<HEADLINE>
NO DOMBROWSKI MEETING _ LASORDA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Interim general manager Tom Lasorda denied reports
Wednesday that the Dodgers already have spoken to Florida GM Dave
Dombrowski, saying the club has not received permission from
Marlins President Don Smiley for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda said he hopes permission is granted within the next two
days when the Dodgers are in Miami to play the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hopeful to get that so we can begin the process of
finding the new GM,,'' Lasorda said. ``We'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski, who did not meet with the Dodgers last weekend when
the Marlins were in Los Angeles, is one of several candidates the
Dodgers have targeted as a possible successor to Lasorda.
</P>
<P>
   The others: Cincinnati GM Jim Bowden, Baltimore assistant GM
Kevin Malone, Mets assistant Omar Minaya, Braves assistant Dean
Taylor and former Yankees GM Bob Watson. Lasorda will interview
Taylor this weekend when the Dodgers are in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski, however, is a favorite of the new owners at Fox. But
like former Dodgers GM Fred Claire, Dombrowski was not part of the
negotiations in the May 15 Mike Piazza trade. Fox chairman Chase
Carey dealt directly with Smiley, who has been trying since the
World Series to put together a group of investors to buy the
Marlins from Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   __ Valdes update: Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes experienced
no discomfort in his strained left-thigh muscle on day after
throwing his first simulated game since going on the disabled list
July 27. With the Dodgers now headed to Florida for two games with
the Marlins, Valdes will pitch Saturday for Class-A Vero Beach in a
rehabilitation assignment.
</P>
<P>
   He then will return to Los Angeles, where doctors will decide
whether he needs another rehab start.
</P>
<P>
   If Valdes rejoins the starting rotation, either Wednesday's
starter Brian Bohanon or tonight's starter Dave Mlicki will head to
the bullpen. Before Wednesday's loss, Bohanon had allowed seven
earned runs in his six previous starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think with the way I've pitched that there is any way
I deserve to be taken out of the starting rotation,'' Bohanon said.
``They already have two lefties (Scott Radinsky and Mark Guthrie)
down there. There isn't room for a third.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick hit: Tracy Woodson, a reserve third baseman on the
Dodgers 1988 World Series championship club, was a visitor to Three
Rivers Stadium. Woodson, who retired in 1996, is in his first year
as manager of the Pirates rookie club in Erie, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two 17-year olds, three 18-year olds and two 19-year
olds in my starting lineup. It's something,'' Woodson said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Woodson met with Lasorda, his former manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him this is a great age to manage, when it is all
new,'' Lasorda said. ``I said I wish I was a mouse in his clubhouse
listening to one of his meetings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
