<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-LOVE-CANAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR TOWNS: IN LOVE CANAL, HIS HOUSE IS STILL A HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOVE CANAL, N.Y. _ All Chester Pysz wants is to live in peace in
the little house in Love Canal he bought 44 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He figures he is not asking for much. Divorced, his three
daughters all grown up, he lives alone here, spending his days
listening to a scanner that summons him to trouble. ``I'm a
volunteer fireman 18 years now,'' he said, standing on the porch
with the screen door ajar so he could monitor fire calls. ``Why,
there are days,'' he said, ``that I'm barely home eight hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people would say that the less time Pysz spends home the
better, since he lives where the government said no one should. His
house is in what the Environmental Protection Agency refers to as
one of Love Canal's ``nonhabitable'' zones.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when the government found that this
neighborhood built around a canal filled with 22,000 tons of liquid
toxic wastes was contaminated and should be evacuated, about 800
families moved. Pysz was one of the ones who stayed put. Ten years
later, when the EPA declared parts of the infamous neighborhood
``habitable,'' and began refurbishing 239 abandoned houses, Pysz
was one of the ones who said told you so. But while his block
stands across the road from a row of freshly rehabilitated,
vinyl-sided houses, it is still considered an unfit place to live.
</P>
<P>
   With almost all the rehabilitated houses sold and the
neighborhood rechristened ``Black Creek Village,'' Pysz's block on
101st Street remains a grim reminder of Love Canal's legacy as one
of the most polluted places on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   His row of 15 houses _ ``there was one next door that got torn
down a couple of months ago'' _ is almost entirely abandoned. One
lonely little Cape Cod after another sits with its windows boarded
and the lawn left to nature and the kids who come around for kicks
after dark. The same goes for the row of houses across the street
from Pysz, and the one behind him, directly in front of the
fenced-in canal. Signs of the life the neighborhood once had _
yellow curtains in a kitchen window, stubborn day lilies reaching
for the sun in a side yard _ only make it look sadder.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Pysz has had one neighbor on his street, an
elderly man a few houses away. Over the weekend, the neighbor, 95
years old, died. Now there's just Pysz, a retired welder going on
71. His last neighbor in this entire nonhabitable zone near the
fenced-in canal lives on 102d Street, another strip of empty
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Pysz's new neighbors across the road, and everywhere else in the
``habitable'' Black Creek Village, believe Pysz and the other 10
holdouts in all of Love Canal's nonhabitable zones should move. The
new people want all reminders of the place that gave birth to
Superfund laws buried like the wastes that still sit in the canal.
</P>
<P>
   The nonhabitable zones raise a troubling question to those who
believe that Love Canal, by any other name, remains a health
hazard. Critics of the new Black Creek Village could point to the
block where Pysz lives, and then across the road, and ask: Why is
one block OK to live in and another 50 yards away not?
</P>
<P>
   That question, said Susan Bloss, director of the Love Canal Area
Revitalization Agency, has been asked time and time again. ``The
EPA's habitability study looked at properties on an area basis,''
she said. ``Because sampling in one spot in an area found
contamination, the whole area was declared nonhabitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to people like Pysz, who believes that Love Canal's
evacuation was a mistake made by politicians fueled by public
panic, if one area is habitable, so is the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people can live there, then I can live here,'' he said,
gesturing across the road. His soil, he added, has come clean in
several tests. He pointed to the perky pink roses growing next to
his front door and a young crimson maple by the curb. ``You can't
kill these things,'' he said. ``I planted that tree two years ago
and it's growing beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bloss said the revitalization agency reserves the right to
condemn Pysz's house if a developer wants it. Over the next several
months, she said, the abandoned houses that have become sorry
reminders of Love Canal will finally be torn down. Then the land
will be sold for light manufacturing or an office park. For those
purposes, the nonhabitable areas are considered habitable.
</P>
<P>
   But Pysz said he'll fight to stay here. He plans to live in his
house forever, he said. ``Then, my daughters get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
