<SLUG> BC-NEUBERGER&AMP;BERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEUBERGER &AMP; BERMAN SET TO SELL 15% STAKE IN A PUBLIC OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Neuberger &AMP; Berman, the investment-management
partnership founded in 1939 by Roy R. Neuberger, the well-known
investor and art benefactor, said Wednesday that it planned to sell
15 percent of its shares in an initial public offering that would
value the company at $1.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which after the offering will be known as Neuberger
Berman Inc., will seek to raise up to $250 million, one-fifth of
which could be used to repay capital to the firm's current
partners. The remainder will be earmarked for general corporate
purposes, including possible acquisitions, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the offering comes as stock prices of
money-management companies have suffered amid the recent market
turmoil. Shares of several mutual fund companies that have recently
sold stock to the public, including Federated Investors Inc. and
Waddell &AMP; Reed Financial Inc., are now trading below their initial
offering prices.
</P>
<P>
   Best known as an adviser to wealthy individuals and
institutional investors, Neuberger &AMP; Berman last year saw its
mutual fund unit take over as its largest business segment. The
growth came even as several of the 35 Neuberger &AMP; Berman funds
lagged behind the market indexes and competing funds.
</P>
<P>
   Neuberger &AMP; Berman generally follows a value style, seeking out
stocks whose prices have been beaten down. That style has fallen
behind as companies with fast-growing earnings have commanded
higher stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of June, the company managed $59.1 billion in assets,
80 percent of which were invested in equities. They include $23.7
billion in mutual funds, $17.8 billion in accounts of
high-net-worth individuals, $16 billion of pension fund and other
institutional assets and $1.6 billion in other accounts.
</P>
<P>
   While Neuberger's mutual fund business has grown rapidly, its
institutional business has been flat since the end of 1995. Chief
administrative officer Jeffrey Lane attributed that lack of growth
to the slowing of the traditional, defined-benefit pension
business, which is being replaced at many companies by
defined-contribution retirement plans like 401(k)'s.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Neuberger's profitability measures up to some of the
best-performing money management companies, according to pro forma
financial statements included in a filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, on a pro forma basis, Neuberger earned pretax profits
of $221.6 million on revenue of $626 million, for a pretax profit
margin of 35.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That compares favorably with the performance of Franklin
Resources, parent of the Franklin Templeton group of mutual funds,
which recorded a pretax profit margin of 28.4 percent in the year
ended Sept. 30, and of T. Rowe Price Associates, whose pretax
margin equaled 35 percent last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
