<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HAVE YOU GONE, TYRONE WHEATLEY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The blueprint for the redesigned Giants backfield
will be unveiled in Thursday night's preseason game with the Jets:
Gary Brown as the starter at halfback, Tiki Barber as the
third-down specialist and Charles Way as the fullback who
frequently switches to a halfback carrying the football.
</P>
<P>
   And where does Tyrone Wheatley fit in?
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Brown, whom the Giants signed as a free agent this past
winter, will have to run well against the Jets to solidify his
position as the principal halfback. An injury to one of the first
three backs could always vault Wheatley back into the mix, and
Barber will never be too far from the picture, getting carries on
first and second downs as well.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing Way's role as a featured back remains a priority.
</P>
<P>
   But conspicuous by his absence in coach Jim Fassel's discussion
of his backfield designs for the Jets game was Wheatley, who was to
get carries only in second-half mop-up time, playing with the
second- and third-string units.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as the Giants broke training camp with a final light
workout, Fassel said he had not decided anything with his backs,
but he did not even mention Wheatley in a broad explanation of what
he is looking for from the Giants' running backs on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Brown will start the game,'' Fassel said, replacing
Barber in the starting lineup for the first time this preseason.
``That doesn't mean Gary Brown is now the starter. But we're going
to have Tiki returning punts and playing in the third-down
packages. We'll get Charles Way in there some carrying the
football. And Tiki will take some regular down stuff, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel went on to mention Greg Comella and Eric Lane, the two
players vying for the backup fullback spot, confirming that they
would see time as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priority is seeing Gary Brown with the first unit,''
Fassel finally said.
</P>
<P>
   Where have you gone, Tyrone Wheatley, the first-round draft pick
of 1995?
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley's shot at winning the starting job apparently came last
week, when he got his only chance of the preseason to play behind
the first-string offensive line. Wheatley had 21 yards on eight
carries in the Giants' dreadful 24-10 loss to Jacksonville.
Wheatley's longest run was 5 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel acknowledged after the game that the offensive line
opened few holes for Wheatley against Jacksonville, but he did not
praise the running back either.
</P>
<P>
   It has probably been Fassel's plan all along to play Brown with
the first team against the Jets in the team's third preseason game,
and the timing is revealing.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every National Football League coach uses the third
exhibition game as the turning point of the preseason. It is the
game when the team's starters play for the longest period and it is
considered to be the closest thing to a true dress rehearsal for
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth and final preseason game, the team's depth chart
is all but decided, and coaches are too worried about injuries to
play their starters for more than a quarter with the regular season
only a week away. It often becomes the sloppiest game of the
preseason, a free-for-all of players auditioning for the last few
spots available on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   That is a game in which Wheatley could see a significant number
of carries. And it is not entirely inconceivable that it could be
Wheatley's last appearance as a Giant.
</P>
<P>
   That remains an unlikely scenario because other than Brown and
Barber, the Giants have no other true halfbacks. But if Way's role
is to be expanded as a featured back, and if Fassel is looking for
a way to keep both Comella and Lane on the team _ or an extra
receiver or linebacker for special teams help _ Wheatley's run with
the Giants could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   So while Wheatley's future, like his entire Giants career, is
still a puzzle, there is little doubt that Brown can secure a place
of prominence in the team's plans with a productive outing against
the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who ran for 945 yards with the San Diego Chargers last
season, has timed his audition well.
</P>
<P>
   Criticized last week for its performance against Jacksonville,
the Giants' offensive line is poised to have a good game. The
team's best offensive lineman, right guard Ron Stone, is returning
to the lineup after missing the Jacksonville game because of an
ankle sprain. As a unit, the line has practiced with renewed
intensity this week, seeming to rally in the face of the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has looked strong running between the tackles in training
camp. He does not have breakaway speed, but at 5 feet 9 inches he
can cleverly pick his way through small openings in the line. And
at 230 pounds, he is a force at the point of attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
