<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORR-VIDEOGAME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTAIN OF ALL-MADDEN VIDEO-GAME TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID EINSTEIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
For Scott Orr more than for most people, life is a game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The game is Madden NFL, which Orr oversees as executive producer
for EA Sports, a division of video-game giant Electronic Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Orr, 42, helped create the game eight years ago and has
developed it into something like a franchise property. Madden NFL _
for computer and all major video-game platforms _ has sold more
than 11 million copies over the years. It was the top-selling
interactive football game last year, according to the NPD Group
research firm, and is EA's most successful title.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, Orr and a team of producers, designers, artists and
programmers craft a new version of Madden NFL, incorporating new
NFL players and teams as well as improvements in technology. Madden
NFL 99, the latest version, is scheduled for release next month to
coincide with the start of football season.
</P>
<P>
   Orr also personally heads up development of several other EA
Sports games _ Nascar Racing, NCAA March Madness Basketball and
NCAA Football. But closest to his heart is the Madden game, which
has earned him the unofficial title of ``father of interactive
football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The genius of the guy is that he has always been able to
satisfy both the sports fan in you and the gamer,'' says Bill
Kunkel, who has known Orr since the video game industry started to
unfold in the early 1980s. ``He gives you realism but also makes
sure that playability is the primary thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr, who grew up in Santa Barbara, started off playing pinball _
mainly because there were no video games. But then along came Pong,
which ushered in a new industry and kindled Orr's passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pong was a revelation to me,'' he says. ``I was always really
into the competitive nature of games, and when Pong and PacMan came
out in arcades, I was all over them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Orr started a small game-publishing company that led to
his first real company, Gamestar, which developed games for the old
Atari and Commodore game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   Kunkel, who now is director of interactive development for
Platinum Studios in Beverly Hills, was one of the first video game
reviewers. He recalls how Orr would show him football and baseball
games he'd created at Gamestar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott would always want to know what was wrong with them,''
Kunkel says. ``He didn't want to hear how great they were. He
wanted to know how to make them better.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr says his chief obstacle back then was manufacturers'
reluctance to produce his sports games. ``They were leery because
they thought video games were for computer geeks who wanted
adventure and role-playing games and not sports games,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Orr sold Gamestar to Activision. He left in 1988 to
work as an independent consultant and began doing work for EA in
1990. In that capacity, he co-designed the first Madden game and
another one, NHL Hockey, both for the Sega Genesis console.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Orr joined EA as a full-time producer and took Madden
NFL under his wing, starting a run that would turn it into one of
the most successful video games.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, he says, ``It took one programmer, maybe one
part-time sound guy and one producer to put a game out. Now it's
much more akin to making a movie or a TV show, and the number of
people involved is extensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. At EA Sports' offices in San Mateo, Orr supervises 15
people involved with designing the Madden game, including producers
and specialists who work with sound, music and TV footage that goes
into the game's PC version.
</P>
<P>
   Once the design is complete, the game is developed by about 35
programmers and graphics specialists at EA's Tiburon Entertainment
unit in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The product then comes back to San Mateo, where some two dozen
testers make sure no bugs have survived.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the technology in Madden NFL has kept pace with
advances in video game consoles and PCs. The action today is
three-dimensional, the players nearly lifelike. And the camera
angles, zoom views and instant replay closely parallel the
experience of watching a real game.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the latest version is more spontaneous, thanks to
artificial intelligence algorithms built into it. ``For example,
with Madden NFL 99, defensive players will adjust their positions
because they know what their teammates are doing,'' Orr says.
``They'll know whether to play man-to-man or stay in a zone.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's going to get even better. Orr says that next year's
game will utilize something called inverse kinematics. When two
players collide, the resulting graphics will be determined by the
actual physics of the collision.
</P>
<P>
   About the only constants throughout the evolution of Madden NFL
have been Orr and the game's namesake, football commentator and
former Raiders coach John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a close relationship with Madden,'' says Orr. ``We see
him four or five times a year, and he makes himself available when
we need him, which is remarkable given his schedule. He really
takes this thing seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   He should. The game has helped turn Madden into a brand name and
has introduced him to new generations of football fans.
</P>
<P>
   Madden's chief contribution, Orr says, is his insight into how
the game is played. ``He stresses realism and the one-on-one nature
of football, which is the essence of his philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, EA Sports has run into serious competition
from other football games. Sony's own NFL Gameday outsold Madden
NFL 98 for the Sony PlayStation, and Acclaim's NFL Quarterback beat
Madden on the Nintendo 64.
</P>
<P>
   But because it spans all the platforms and the others don't,
Madden handily took the overall sales title while generating annual
revenues of $80 million. (EA's total sales were $909 million in
fiscal 1998.)
</P>
<P>
   It also helped EA Sports increase its share of the sports-game
market from 51 to 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That surprised a lot of people,'' Orr says, ``because Sony and
Acclaim were spending money to suggest that EA was losing its
luster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
