<HEADLINE>
BRODERBUND STOCK DROPS 19 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BENNY EVANGELISTA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Shares in Broderbund Software Inc. of Novato fell about 19 percent
yesterday after an analyst questioned the accounting procedures of
the company that is about acquire it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials for both Broderbund and the Learning Co., as well as
other Wall Street analysts, discounted the report as a
``misinterpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless the analyst's report triggered a precipitous slide
in the stock prices of both companies, which led to a subsequent
halt in their trading for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my satisfaction, I've been shown there are no account
irregularities,'' said analyst Stephen S. Fleming of BancAmerica
Robertson Stephens. ``It's a non-issue, a tempest in a teapot.''
</P>
<P>
   The tempest caused stock in Broderbund, the once fiercely
independent educational software-maker, to drop $4 per share to
$16.38 and stock in the Learning Co. to fall $5.13 to $20.63.
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co., a Cambridge, Mass., maker of educational
software, announced in June that it was buying Broderbund for about
$420 million. Directors of both companies are scheduled to vote
separately on the deal August 31.
</P>
<P>
   The report that set off the stock slide came from Pacific Coast
Securities analyst Jeff Goverman, who said the Learning Co. had
underreported its accounts receivable by $25 million in the second
quarter in a recent Securities and Exchange Commission filing.
</P>
<P>
   Goverman claimed that it would take much longer for the company
to collect its outstanding bills than it had previously indicated.
</P>
<P>
   However, officials for the Learning Co. denied any accounting
irregularities yesterday. They said Goverman had failed to consider
the fact that the company had sold some of its accounts receivable
at a discount to third-party debt collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Michael P. Wallace, an analyst with SBC Warburg Dillon Read,
agreed with that assessment. ``The issue has to do with how the
company finances its accounts receivable in the U.S. and
overseas,'' he said in a report. ``We see the sell-off today as
unwarranted and well overdone.''
</P>
<P>
   Goverman did not return a message left yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst privately said Learning Co.'s past reputation for
pushing accounting practices to the limit had created a credibility
problem with investors and caused the market's ``knee-jerk
reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said the Broderbund-Learning Co. deal could have been
jeopardized if the accounting problem had been true and the stock
slide had continued.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expects both stocks to rebound today following the
clarification from Learning Co. officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
