<SLUG> BC-CONVERSION-NAVALBASE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTERED NAVAL BASE SLOWLY FILLING WITH TENANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY DOAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Hangar 39 at the Alameda Naval Air Station used to hold helicopters
and fighter jets. Now it's home to chile peppers the size of Hondas
and a futuristic space port rising 30 feet above the ground.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delphi Productions, which creates these surreal displays for
companies exhibiting at events like Fiesta Texas and the Comdex
high-tech trade show, recently signed a 10-year-lease for space at
the hangar.
</P>
<P>
   The company is one of several lured by the sweet deals and
plentiful space at the former base, which is slowly undergoing the
awkward process of converting from military to commercial use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked everywhere from Richmond to Brisbane, and there was
just no way we could find the kind of clearance and space we needed
anywhere else,'' said Delphi Vice President Anthony Erpelding.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to moving into what has been rechristened Alameda Point,
Delphi occupied 50,000 square feet of warehouse space in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Its new home is twice that size _ 108,000 square feet and 55
feet tall at the highest point. That gives the company plenty of
room to build its exhibits for such clients as Apple, Sony, Nike
and the Oakland Museum of California _ some of which can occupy as
much as 25,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 600 windows and only one column obstructing the
cavernous interior, it was easy for Delphi's designers to envision
how a creation like Novellus' 20-foot-tall ``Metal-morphosis
Chamber'' would appear on an exhibit floor.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber, on display earlier this year at the Semicon West
chip show, highlighted the switch in the chip industry from
aluminum to copper parts by pretending to remove aluminum from
visitors' bodies using steam and flashing lights. One part of the
exhibit featured a huge ``brainwashing'' screen that flashed
messages about copper.
</P>
<P>
   Although the hangar is perfectly suited to the assembly work
Delphi does, it is so huge that the company had to buy seven
bicycles to save employees from trekking across it all day.
</P>
<P>
   So far, nobody seems to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really fun, airy place to work that suits the
theatrical kind of industry we're in,'' said Erpelding. ``I can
look down on the carpentry shop, the painting areas and the storage
areas all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Erpelding said the waterfront location also gives employees
inspiring views of the bay and the reserve ships anchored nearby.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the lease rates were ``very attractive'' and
that much of the $1 million it needed to retrofit the hangar was
covered by federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   Lease rates at the Point start at 25 cents a square foot and
average about 10 percent below market rates for comparable
industrial space in the Bay Area, according to Mike Hampen, manager
of the Alameda Reuse and Redevelopment Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ARRA was set up by the city to attract civilian tenants to the
base, which was built in 1940 and used primarily to repair disabled
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bargain lease rates, it will be some time before the
base is fully occupied.
</P>
<P>
   The land is still owned by the Navy, which is in the final
stages of turning over the base for civilian use by the city of
Alameda and the California Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   While some shoreline property at the base in Alameda may be
protected, &UR;  &LR; more than 4 million square feet of building space has
been approved for a mix of commercial, industrial and residential
use.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the turnover process, or ``reconveyance,'' is likely to
be long and complicated.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how much of the $120 million tab for bringing the
Point up to current building code will be paid by the Navy, said
Kay Miller, executive director of ARRA.
</P>
<P>
   There's clearly a lot of work to do. Some of the bunkers,
aircraft hangars and officers' homes are condemned. Other buildings
are plagued with lead contamination, sewage and electrical
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of bringing it up to code is comparable to that
faced by Vallejo's Mare Island Conversion Center, according to a
consultant who has worked on both projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Mare Island Shipyard closed in 1996, but the terms of the
financing package are still being negotiated, said Jonathan Stern
of Berkeley's Bay Area Economics consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Such conversions are usually financed by a combination of city
funds, federal grants, municipal bonds and lease revenue, but
working out the details is a tortuous process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Hamilton Air Force Base _ it closed in 1970, and the
agreements still aren't final,'' said Hampen. ``We're talking about
a very slow process, no matter how much both sides want things
done.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  It's been more than a year since the Navy officially closed
the base &UR; ,  &LR; in April 1997, and only about 32 percent of the
buildings are leased, according to ARRA's Hampen.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge ARRA faces is evident after a quick walk around
the Point. Many of the usable buildings don't exactly have what
brokers call ``curb appeal'' _ they're low and uninviting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another hurdle, according to ARRA, is that companies with
space requirements like Delphi's are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ARRA is considering partially demolishing or resizing some of
the bunkers to suit small research-and-development and
light-industrial tenants, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One industry that doesn't mind the huge and less-than-glamorous
facilities is Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Several production companies, including George Lucas' Industrial
Light &AMP; Magic and Manex Entertainment, find the size and privacy of
Alameda Point ideal for soundstage work.
</P>
<P>
   Manex recently leased a portion of a hangar to build a studio,
and it has rented other buildings on a short-term basis to shoot
``Flubber,'' a movie starring Robin Williams, and ``The
Rainmaker,'' a movie based on John Grisham's best-selling novel.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Light &AMP; Magic also leases space occasionally to
produce special effects for commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal interest from Hollywood is encouraging, but ARRA is
hoping for long-term occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that ARRA is considering sending out
requests-for-proposal to film studios like Manex that are
interested in permanent studio space.
</P>
<P>
   ARRA is also courting potential tenants in such burgeoning
industries as electric cars.
</P>
<P>
   The tenant list at the Alameda Naval Air Station now includes a
sheet-metal fabricator, a records storage firm, a church and a
swap-meet company.
</P>
<P>
   ARRA says the leases will generate almost $1.7 million in annual
revenues, which covers its $1 million-per-year expenses but doesn't
make much of a dent in the costs of renovation. ARRA's Miller said
the Point probably will not turn a profit until 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long haul ahead, Hampen is optimistic. ``There's a
lot of potential here. You just have to look beyond how things are
set up now to the possibilities for some of these buildings,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampen knows the buildings as well as anyone _ he worked in them
for 13 years as a Navy master chief. He said it hurt to watch the
once-bustling base, which had employed 15,000 people and flew more
than 500 sorties a day, turn into a ghost town.
</P>
<P>
   Even factoring in expected leases, there will be only about
1,200 jobs at the base by the turn of the century. ``But it'll be
exciting to see it gradually brought back to life,'' Hampen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
