<SLUG> BC-DIGITALBAY-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOBE'S HEAD HONCHOS TAKE A TURN IN CORPORATE HOT SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM ABATE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
In the wake of last week's layoffs at Adobe Systems, some in
Silicon Valley are wondering whether the cuts should have started
at the top, with co-founders John Warnock and Chuck Geschke.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Whenever you go through this kind of thing, you ask, `Am I the
problem? Is it time?' '' Warnock said.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe has gone through two executive shakeups in 10 months. Last
fall, Warnock and Geschke, who are co-chairmen, ousted former Chief
Operating Officer Dave Pratt, a nine-year Adobe veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, they forced out three execs hired after Pratt
departed: Chief Financial Officer Jack Bell, marketing czar Robert
Roblin and product manager Ross Bott.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the outside, you could look at multiple executive changes
and conclude the problem was at the top,'' Warnock admitted.
</P>
<P>
   But he says he and Geschke finally have an executive team, with
new CFO Harold Covert and marketer Bruce Chizen, to turn the
graphics-software giant around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand this business as well as anybody on the
planet,'' he said. ``What we've had is an execution problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Adobe's problems began long before the earnings
disappointment that preceded last week's shakeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company whose stock has gone nowhere for two
years,'' said one Silicon Valley insider. ``John and Chuck are nice
guys, but their hanging around just prevents the company from
bringing in someone who can turn the situation around.''
</P>
<P>
   Another critic says that Adobe, though master in print
publishing, has let Microsoft, Sun and Netscape set standards in
Web publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Says a third source in the venture capital community: ``I don't
see John or Chuck at the front of the (industry) parade like they
were 10 or 12 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Warnock disputes each barb. Adobe may yet create a standard
around its Acrobat software for sending documents over the Web.
It's working on new software tools that will let people author
content once and publish it in any medium _ paper, disk or Web.
</P>
<P>
   He says critics will see the first signs of progress in better
financials. ``We'll know within 90 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Warnock counters any suggestion that it's time for
the inventors of desktop publishing software to go out to pasture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck and I understand the publishing market and have defended
it for 15 years,'' he said. ``We're not living in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   _ BANKING BLUES? Like the air shimmering over hot asphalt,
rumors are emanating from the offices of NationsBank Montgomery
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the situation said Montgomery CEO Thom Weisel
and his managing directors have been meeting over the last few days
to discuss whether the ``golden handcuffs'' _ financial inducements
to keep top managers in place after NationsBank acquired Montgomery
last year _ should be loosened to allow execs to depart sooner than
the two or three years they were supposed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   A Montgomery representative declined comment on the rumor that
Jerry Markowitz, a Weisel ally, and another top director might make
an early exit if the cuffs were loosened &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some of Montgomery's 150 research analysts are
venting over other concerns. They used to get paid from a pot of
money, half of which came from investment banking profits, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   Henceforth, word is analysts will only get a 20 percent slice of
that banking fat. Moreover, analysts have supposedly been told to
spend more time covering the stocks of the larger firms in their
industries and less time doting on startups.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Ruth, co-director of research at Montgomery, wouldn't
discuss compensation rumors, but tried to put the coverage question
into context. As Montgomery continues its drive to challenge
top-tier investment banks _ such as Lehman Brothers, Goldman Sachs
and Morgan Stanley _ it wants to make sure its analysts have struck
the proper balance between covering small, fast-growing startups
and larger publicly held firms.
</P>
<P>
   But others in the investment banking world say that as
Montgomery _ and its rival Robertson, Stephens _ become part of
larger banks and step up to challenge New York-based investment
firms, they grow more distant from the Silicon Valley high-tech and
biomedical startups that used to butter their bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent comments from VCs indicate that they are starting to
see signs of these changes and are not happy about it,'' said a
Montgomery rival.
</P>
<P>
   _ FREE WEB SITES: Nonprofit groups should sign up in a hurry for
free Web site hosting, courtesy of Verio Northern California, an
Internet service provider based in Walnut Creek. Get the
application at ncal.verio.net/company/ grant.html.
</P>
<P>
   Verio is a collection of regional ISPs focused on Web hosting
and other net services for commercial firms. Isabel Ehringer, who
runs the Northern California operation, told me about the nonprofit
giveaway during a company briefing. They haven't publicized the
program elsewhere yet, so hurry. It's first-come, first-served.
</P>
<P>
   Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by
phone (650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail
(abate &LR; sfgate.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
