<SLUG> BC-TV-STERN-530&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STERN TALKS TRASH ABOUT `SATURDAY NIGHT LIVE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since Mr. T of ``The A-Team'' promised to poleax the Fonz
have we seen so much competitive scorn heaped on a rival television
show.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the source is Howard Stern, the king of all media
immodesty.
</P>
<P>
   ```Saturday Night Live' should now be called `Saturday Night
Dead,''' Stern crowed on his morning radio program from New York
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the show that ceased being funny when John Belushi's
fat, speedball-filled corpse hit the deck, and you know that. Ever
since then, it's gone downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern, whose syndicated Saturday night TV show debuts this week
on about 70 stations nationally, was also dispensing a sampling of
his celebrated grasp on tasteful entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Grasp? He has good taste by the throat, and he's kicking it in
the behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Howard Stern Radio Show'' is hardly likely to unseat the
top-rated ``SNL.'' But Stern might be the first serious competition
NBC's weekly comedy titan has faced in its 23 years on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my show hits the airwaves this Saturday, and this is a
prediction, people will flock to it like maggots on fresh road kill
on a hot Texas day,'' Stern declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I feel about it. I don't know about anybody else.
So I ask you, should the American public bow to me, accept me,
cater to me? Well, what else can they do? Accept the fact that I am
the greatest entertainer of the millennium, and I will lead the
Tiffany network into the next millennium. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The Tiffany network, or more accurately former Tiffany network,
is CBS. Stern's show was developed mainly for the group of
CBS-owned stations with the full blessing of Mel Karmazin,
president of CBS Corp. But it isn't truly a network show _ probably
to the relief of some traditionalists at the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Howard Stern Radio Show'' is syndicated by CBS' Eyemark
Entertainment wing. The stations that will air it aren't all CBS
affiliates. And it won't be seen at all in a few major TV markets,
notably Dallas and Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Stern is making his customary pledges of class entertainment _
porn queens, nude makeovers, tuneful flatulence. But little of the
Saturday night program will be original. As the title indicates,
it'll be mostly a ``best-of'' compilation videotaped from Stern's
popular radio show.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the hourlong show's content similar to ``Howard
Stern,'' the 30-minute taped version of Stern's radio show that's
on the E! Entertainment cable channel six nights a week.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said the two TV shows would use separate material from the
radio broadcasts. He said he doesn't have time to do an originally
produced TV show as well as his daily radio program. Anyway, said
Stern, the radio show adapts well to the visual medium of
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it,'' he said in his freewheeling on-air radio
press conference Tuesday. ``The radio show is really a television
show in a sense. We have people down here. We're running around the
studio. We have guests. It's not unlike `The Tonight Show' or
something like that in format. It's just that it's better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It's not Stern's first excursion into broadcast television.
WWOR-TV, the Secaucus, N.J., superstation, originated the infamous
Saturday night ``Howard Stern Show'' in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   That show's high points included the use of real prostitutes in
``Hooker Howiewood Squares,'' homeless contestants vying for a
shopping cart on ``Homeless Howiewood Squares,'' and a guest star
who ate live worms.
</P>
<P>
   The period was also notable for Stern's radio attacks on WWOR
management, and for the quick cancellation of the show after a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Stern has had a successful movie and two best-selling books
since then, which adds up to a measure of media respectability.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not entirely domesticated. On the radio, he's been
speaking warmly about his relationship with his longtime backer,
Karmazin, and goading another CBS executive, CBS Television
President Leslie Moonves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you,'' Stern told a few million radio
listeners. ``Leslie is so embarrassed by me, he won't even come on
my (radio) show and promote the show with me hand-in-hand. You
don't see Leslie sitting here. Where is he? Think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he goes, `Well, it's not a CBS show. While many CBS
stations are running it, it's not an official CBS show.' What's the
matter? You afraid to sit on the couch next to me, Leslie?''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves reports to Karmazin. Stern might be the barbarian at
CBS' gate, but he can pick his way through an organizational chart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
