<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LILCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COLLAPSING LILCO PARACHUTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 20:
</P>
<P>
   Golden parachutes for executives are often exorbitant, but they
have a certain logic. By assuring a company's senior officials that
they will be richly compensated if they lose their jobs as a result
of a takeover, golden parachutes encourage them not to resist a
merger that might benefit shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But those who defend such parachutes never contemplated that
they would be used as they were at LILCO, the old Long Island
Lighting Co. Executives there collected millions in parachute
payments, but they also kept their jobs when part of LILCO was
merged into the old Brooklyn Union Gas Co. to form Marketspan Corp.
The rest of LILCO went to the Long Island Power Authority, a state
agency.
</P>
<P>
   The payments created outrage among shareholders and resentment
among executives from the former Brooklyn Union Gas who were not
getting such payouts. Now the top management of Marketspan is
reported to be demanding that some of the executives either give
back the parachute money or bail out of the company.
</P>
<P>
   It is a reasonable request that executives who were not really
severed should give back their severance pay, particularly
considering that they would get to keep other payments they got
under the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this will do nothing about the biggest of the
payments, to former LILCO chairman William Catacosinos, who
collected $42 million, part of it as a golden parachute. Lawsuits
have been filed, by Suffolk County and the LIPA, contending that
those payments were illegal.
</P>
<P>
   But blocking them would have been easier if the state had made
them an issue when the deal was being negotiated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
