<HEADLINE>
ANGELS NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Pitcher Ken Hill's rehab start for single-A
Lake Elsinore in Stockton on Tuesday gave the Anaheim Angels reason
for concern.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was supposed to make 90 pitches and then be activated for
Sunday's game against Toronto. But Hill felt discomfort in his
right elbow starting in the fourth inning and left after making
just 70 pitches in four-plus innings. Hill had arthroscopic elbow
surgery on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Angels manager Terry Collins called it a setback,
Hill would not. Hill, who had X-rays Wednesday that were negative,
blamed it on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine, he said. ``I know what it was. It was just a little
cold, cold weather. The temperature was like 65 degrees. ... I got
70 pitches in. I was supposed to go 90 to 95, that's the only
difference. Other than that, I got some good work in.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he will throw on the side Friday and wouldn't rule out
pitching on Sunday. Collins, though, has already penciled Chuck
Finley's name into Sunday's starting slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty disappointed when we heard what happened,
Collins said. ``But at least Kenny was smart enough to know he had
to back off.
</P>
<P>
   Although team physician Dr. Lewis Yocum was expected to examine
Hill, Hill said he didn't anticipate any more doctor visits: ``For
what? I'm fine.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus was promoted from triple-A Vancouver on July 30 to
take Dave Hollins' spot at third base and is expected to stay there
for years to come. He's been steady in the field (only two errors),
but has been slow to come around at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Wednesday's game, Glaus was hitting .206 with one
homer and 10 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everyone's been waiting for him to hit home runs,
Collins said. ``But he's played in only 80-some games of pro ball.
And all of a sudden, he's playing in a pennant race, playing
against the Yankees, Red Sox, everybody else. We have to realize
he's still young, and he's learning a new position.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus was a shortstop at UCLA when the Angels selected him in
the June 1997 draft with the No. 3 overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins underwent arthroscopic surgery Wednesday at the
Kerlan-Jobe Health Center in Los Angeles. Dr. Yocum performed the
surgery, which requires four to six months of rehabilitation. ...
Pitchers Jeff Juden and Allen Watson went to a hair salon in
Newport Beach Wednesday, and Juden came back a blonde. Watson only
had blonde highlights put in. ... Garret Anderson was not in the
starting lineup Wednesday to get a rest. Reggie Williams started in
his place and batted leadoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
