<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT &LR;      08-20 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RARE NOTE OF IMPERFECTION CREEPS INTO YANKEES' SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Opposing players and managers maintain their
professional mien and say the New York Yankees are a good team but
nothing special, that beating them is nothing special. Then, when
they do conquer the Yankees for a day, as the Minnesota Twins did
Wednesday night, 5-3, they react as if they had won the Little
League World Series.
</P>
<P>
   For Minnesota manager Tom Kelly, a grin is an outburst of
emotion. But as the Twins thumped Andy Pettitte (14-7) for the
third time this year, they escaped a pivotal jam in the seventh and
Kelly hammered the air with his fists in the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The loss snapped the Yankees' three-game winning streak and left
them 92-31 for the season, which is something special in most
books.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were 1 for 13 with runners in scoring position
Wednesday night, and nothing underlined their frustration more than
the seventh inning. Trailing by 5-2, the Yankees loaded the bases
with nobody out and the rest seemed inevitable: Somebody would get
a hit, somebody else would hit a home run and the Yankees would win
again.
</P>
<P>
   But the Minnesota pitcher Mike Trombley briefly interrupted the
Yankees' fantasy season. He struck out Paul O'Neill, who slammed
and broke his bat after his whiff. Trombley then struck out Bernie
Williams. And after falling behind Tino Martinez three balls and no
strikes, Trombley came back to strike out Martinez on some anxious
swings, prompting Kelly's outburst.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did not act or play like themselves in the early
innings. They were just off, like a train 10 minutes late, or a
delivery of a dozen roses that's one short. The Yankees loaded the
bases with nobody out in the second inning against Mike Morgan, the
Twins' starting pitcher, who was making only his second appearance
since June. Then Tim Raines hit into a double play; a run scored,
but the rally was over.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi smacked a double to start the third, but when Chuck
Knoblauch singled to center, Girardi kept glancing over his
shoulder as he ran to third and assumed he would stop. All the
while, the third base coach Willie Randolph windmilled his arm and
waved for Girardi to round the bag. When the next three hitters
made out, Girardi was left at third base.
</P>
<P>
   There were more imperfections: Girardi nearly drilling Pettitte
with his warm-up throw to second base before the fourth inning,
O'Neill making outs in his first four at-bats and extending his
hitless streak to 12 at-bats. No one was more imperfect, however,
than Pettitte, who has been more about finger-painting lately among
a starting rotation of artists.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed eight hits and walked two, repeatedly falling behind
in the count against the Twins, who are among the American League's
worst teams but have given Pettitte major trouble this year.
Minnesota beat Pettitte on May 9, pounding him for nine hits and 7
runs in five and two-thirds innings, and then thrashed him again
six days later, with 12 hits and 7 runs over 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee left-hander struggled to finish off hitters Wednesday
night, to identify a pitch that would place the Twins on the
defensive. Early last month, when Pettitte was at his best, he
would slam his cut fastball in on the hands of opposing
right-handed batters, and once they tried to adjust to this inside
pitch, he would fire his two-seam fastball or his changeup low and
away and they would be completely at his mercy. He often used his
cut fastball against left-handed batters, running it away from them
like a slider.
</P>
<P>
   But a major league scout has noticed that Pettitte has not been
throwing his cut fastball as much as he did before straining a
muscle in his back in late July. Either that or the movement on
this pitch has been reduced dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   David Ortiz's at-bats against Pettitte in the second and third
innings Wednesday night were perfect examples of the Yankee
starter's inability to apply the coup de grace.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz, a left-handed-hitting first baseman, got ahead in the
count three balls and one strike in the second, then swung at
strike two before fouling off two pitches and finally walking on a
curveball low and inside. It was an eight-pitch war with the type
of hitter Pettitte usually dominates.
</P>
<P>
   The next inning, Pettitte once again fell behind 3-1, trying
three times to get Ortiz to chase a breaking ball. Ortiz struck out
on the seventh pitch of the at-bat, but it was too hard, too much
effort for Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees fell behind early after assuming a 1-0 advantage in
the second. The Twins mustered two runs in the bottom of the
inning, on a run-scoring groundout and Pat Meares' run-scoring
single, and never trailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
