u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT &LR;      08-20 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOSHII HANGS TOUGH, AND HIS SUMMER DROUGHT IS OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Masato Yoshii kept waiting for his drought to end and
kept wondering if it ever would. Yoshii was approaching three
months without winning in the major leagues, a startling stretch
considering he has remained in the rotation and the New York Mets
have remained in the skirmish for the wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Wednesday night, Yoshii stopped wondering and stopped
waiting as he guided the Mets to a 2-1 victory over the Colorado
Rockies and won for the first time in 15 starts. It was his first
triumph since May 27, when Mike Piazza was apparently enjoying his
first week with the Mets. And it enabled the Mets (69-55) to leap
ahead of the Chicago Cubs (69-57) by one game in the wild-card
race.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii pitched dependably into the eighth, Piazza smacked a
run-scoring single and was cheered for the second straight night
and Brian McRae's hustle helped the Mets win for the 10th time in
their last 13 games. Mostly, this was Yoshii's night. ``I'm really
proud of how he's endured,'' said manager Bobby Valentine. ``I
thought tonight was as good as he's been.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii (5-6) yielded a homer to Darryl Hamilton on the second
pitch of the game and then danced around the Rockies without being
damaged for another run for the next seven and two-thirds innings.
Even though he gave up nine hits, Yoshii was successful because he
limited the Rockies to no hits in six at-bats with runners in
scoring position while striking out six and walking one with a
powerful fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling that I had to win or need to win was a few levels
higher,'' Yoshii said. ``Maybe that raised the concentration level
to bring the pitching I had today.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mark McGwire, the major league's leading home run hitter
with 49, and the Cardinals invading Shea Stadium for doubleheaders
Thursday and Friday that are expected to attract more than 40,000
fans each night, the Mets improved to 3-0 in this busy week at
home.
</P>
<P>
   They did it with snazzy pitching, stellar relief from Dennis
Cook and John Franco and sturdy defense from shortstop Rey Ordonez,
who snagged a liner and started a crucial double play in the sixth
and robbed Kirt Manwaring of a certain hit with one of his sliding
plays in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Cook replaced Yoshii with Dante Bichette on third and two out in
the eighth and struck out the pinch-hitter Mike Lansing with a 1-2
fastball. Franco, knowing that he had mishandled leads that would
have given Yoshii a victory three different times, worked a 1-2-3
ninth for his 27th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yoshii finally got a win,'' Franco said. ``I've messed it up
for him before so I'm happy to see that. He did an outstanding job.
It's been since May. That's a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii had not won in his previous 14 starts, going 0-5 with a
5.03 earned run average and seemingly placing himself in a perilous
position if the six-man rotation was ever reduced to the customary
five-man rotation. While Yoshii had pitched seven innings or more
and allowed two earned runs or fewer in four different starts, he
had nevertheless not been winning.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had dinner with Yoshii when the Mets were in Colorado
two weeks ago and told him that he still thought he was throwing
well and to not let the streak without a victory bother him. After
Hamilton lined an 0-1 pitch into the Met bullpen in right field in
the first, it looked like another disastrous night. But Yoshii
rebounded after the homer and retired nine of the next 10 batters.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, who has two hits in 36 at-bats this season for an .056
average, looked as if he had won the lottery after Bobby Jones
inexplicably walked him to open the third.
</P>
<P>
   He raced to third on Tony Phillips' ground-rule double. After
Edgardo Alfonzo struck out and John Olerud walked to cram the
bases, Piazza received a partial standing ovation before he even
reached the batter's box. It was the second in two nights for
Piazza, who was also cheered after his three-run, pinch-hit double
that put the Mets ahead in the second game Tuesday night. This
time, Piazza did not empty the bases. But he lined a single to left
to drive in Yoshii and even the score, 1-1, and continued to hear
the cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question this is a big week for us with a lot of
games,'' Piazza said. ``I don't think there's any reason to put
pressure on ourselves. We have to play our game and keep doing what
we've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   McRae's speed and Piazza's body helped score the winning run.
McRae tapped a ground ball to shortstop Neifi Perez, who flipped to
second base. But Piazza barreled into second baseman Kurt Abbot,
whose throw did not beat McRae to first for the double play as
Phillips crossed the plate to make it 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed that way. Yoshii finally won. ''Of course I'm happy to
get the win,'' Yoshii said. ``I'm more happy that we swept
Colorado.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
