<HEADLINE>
NO PLAYOFFS FOR LIBERTY THIS SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ With an opportunity to control its own
post-season destiny Wednesday night, the New York Liberty fell
asleep at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty had held a large lead near the end of the first half
against the Detroit Shock, but it stumbled, then never regained its
form in losing the most important game of the season, 82-68.
</P>
<P>
   A stunned Liberty team returned to its suburban hotel for a
late-night vigil. The Liberty needed help to get into the playoffs.
Washington had let the Liberty down by losing to the Charlotte
Sting, 105-69, so its only hope was with the lowly Sacramento
Monarchs, who were playing a powerful Mercury team in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty, led by Sophia Witherspoon's 26 points, had a chance
to turn around the game late when Rebecca Lobo scored a layup that
tied the score at 62-62. But the Liberty went ice cold, and didn't
score another field goal until less than a minute remained in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Shock, who was led by Sandy Brondello's 24 points, ended its
inaugural season with a 17-13 record. The Liberty, a year after
finishing as runner-up in the Women's National Basketball
Association, ended its regular season at 18-12.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty surrounding the Liberty's post-season chances
was evident in the locker room before the game. The usual
boisterous laughter and spirited conversations between players was
replaced by a quiet apprehension. The players sat alone in their
stalls, lacing up their sneakers, saying little, if anything, to
one another.
</P>
<P>
   But the Liberty went on an 8-0 run early in the first half, and
led by as many as 14 points. For much of the first 20 minutes, it
seemed the Liberty players could do no wrong. Behind-the-back
passes, off-balance shots, everything went the Liberty's way and
the ball eventually seemed to find the net.
</P>
<P>
   But a string of sloppy plays by the Liberty _ including two
straight giveaways, Elisabeth Cebrian dribbling off her foot, a
shot-clock violation and Sophia Witherspoon stepping on the
sideline on successive visits to the offensive end _ began to eat
at the Liberty's lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty, led by 11-point first-half efforts by Vickie
Johnson and Witherspoon, couldn't find its groove again. With three
minutes left in the half, the lead was down to 36-31. The Shock,
led by 39-year-old Lynette Woodard's 12 first-half points, ripped
off 7 straight points to end the half leading by 38-36.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
