</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITYHOOD-PETITION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETITION FOR L.A. SECESSION STUDY WINS EXTENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The state Senate unanimously approved a bill that
would give San Fernando Valley activists three more months to
circulate petitions calling for a secession study.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, written late last week by Assemblyman Robert
Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, passed 37-0 in the Senate and now goes to
the state Assembly, where it could face a vote as soon as Monday. A
two-thirds vote of approval would send the measure to Gov. Pete
Wilson to sign or reject. If signed, it would take effect
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly elated with the Senate vote today,'' said Jeff
Brain, president of Valley Voters Organized Toward Empowerment.
``We anticipate the Assembly will be smooth sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE is gathering petitions in hopes of triggering a
government study of whether the Valley could form its own city
without causing financial damage to the rest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Based on their interpretation of state law, Valley VOTE leaders
believe they have just seven days left to finish collecting the
135,000 valid signatures needed to launch the proposed study. As of
Tuesday, the group had 116,900 names.
</P>
<P>
   In its editorial pages, the Daily News has strongly endorsed
Valley VOTE's drive to trigger a public study of secession that
would determine whether the breakup would be revenue-neutral to the
remaining part of the city and whether the new city would be
economically viable. The newspaper has contributed $60,000 to the
petition-gathering effort.
</P>
<P>
   Should the bill become law before the petition drive's current
deadline of Aug. 27, Valley VOTE would continue collecting
signatures until leaders felt they had enough for a comfortable
margin of success, Brain said. The group estimates it needs about
180,000 signatures to make sure at least 135,000 prove to be valid.
</P>
<P>
   If the bill becomes law after the deadline, Valley VOTE members
said, they will tally their petitions and decide then whether to
restart the drive for signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tight timing, Valley VOTE leaders said they are
cautiously optimistic that the bill could become law before they
hit their deadline next week. Backed by several local lawmakers,
the bill already has received unanimous votes in both the full
Senate and a Senate committee in the first three days of this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a new record for legislation,'' Hertzberg said
after the Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg and Valley VOTE members attributed the bill's swift
movement to the coalition of supportive lawmakers. Backers built
that coalition by pitching the bill as a way to make up for the
blow dealt to the petition drive when Los Angeles city employees
ejected Valley VOTE volunteers from a popular air show at which
they hoped to gather at least 20,000 signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Even secession foe Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles, signed
on as a principal co-author of the bill, citing the air show as a
reason. Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, is
listed as a joint author.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, together with our other coalitions we've put together,
will enhance our chance of passing (in the Assembly),'' Hertzberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   The exact path of the bill is not certain. It could still face a
hearing -- and possibly revision -- in the Assembly local
government committee before reaching the Assembly floor, a step
that could delay it a day, said Hertzberg spokesman Paul Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg will push to have the bill go straight to the Assembly
floor instead, Hefner said.
</P>
<P>
   The assemblyman said he did not anticipate that Wilson would
reject the bill if it reaches his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Sean Walsh said Wilson had not had a chance to review
the language of the bill, but is a strong supporter of
self-determination for the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Legislature considers changing the petition drive's
deadline, Valley VOTE also has suggested that the target number of
signatures needed might change.
</P>
<P>
   The group must collect the signatures of 25 percent of all
registered voters within the Los Angeles city portion of the
Valley. But after noting numerous mistakes on the county's list of
voters, the group's executive board decided Wednesday to contact
Los Angeles County officials and determine exactly how many voters
live in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE estimates there are 526,000 voters registered in the
Valley, a number the group derived by taking the entire list of Los
Angeles voters and adding up those with Valley ZIP codes. Neither
Los Angeles city nor county election officials reached Wednesday
said they knew the exact count of registered Valley voters.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
