r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONAS-TATE-CAM     08-20 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONAS-TATE-CAMP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW KIDS GET YEARLY DOSE OF TEASING FROM ASU VETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP TONTOZONA _ Freshmen, beware.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get one of the kids and tape him to his bed and put
him out on the 50-yard line butt-naked,'' offensive lineman Grey
Ruegamer said. ``Put honey all over him so the bees and bears and
pigs are out there, loving it.''
</P>
<P>
   Camp Tontozona, it's a beautiful thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State football team's annual retreat is an intense
10 days of conditioning and drills in preparation for the season.
But for newcomers, contending with off-the-field follies is nearly
as challenging.
</P>
<P>
   (Aside to freshman defensive lineman Mike Pinkard: That sandal
you were looking for all day yesterday? It's on top of the exit
sign in the freshmen trailer.)
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Sun Devils newcomer, you can count on two things:
You will be victimized by numerous practical jokes; and your living
conditions _ despite the panoramic surroundings _ will be less than
glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean?'' Coach Bruce Snyder asked. ``It's the
Hilton.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh huh. Twenty-five freshmen share a trailer right next to the
football field. Bunk beds take up most of the space, and dirty
clothes are scattered throughout. The smell, well, pick up a gas
mask at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on entering at night. This season's group has
barricaded the entrance by jamming a bunk bed against the door. The
windows are wired shut with coat hangers. It gets a little warm in
there _ the veterans already have disrupted the circuit breaker so
the air-conditioner doesn't work _ but it's worth the trade-off to
fend off a possible late-night seniors raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are brooms and sticks laying around,'' said Darrel
Turner, a fullback from Bellflower, Calif. ``In case they come in,
we'll hear them trip.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The place,'' Brandon Falkner said, ``is a fortress.''
</P>
<P>
   Falkner, a defensive back from Peoria High School, has reason to
be paranoid. He already has been hit in the head by water balloons
thrown from the seniors' cabin that sits on a hill above.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water balloons?'' senior Albrey Battle asked innocently. ``I
don't know nothing about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Falkner, like most of the freshmen, has had his clothes and
towels taken from the outdoor showers. Often, he's been forced to
run naked around the field to find them.
</P>
<P>
   There are full moons at all hours at Camp Tontozona.
</P>
<P>
   The antics have been tamer than last year, when the freshmen
``were a bit more cocky,'' Ruegamer said.
</P>
<P>
   That group got dead fish in its air-conditioning unit. Even the
local wildlife was offended.
</P>
<P>
   Ruegamer admits he's enjoying his senior status. He was the
victim of numerous practical jokes as a freshman, including Tabasco
sauce in his dinner and leftovers in his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Such follies are nothing new. Since 1959, when Coach Frank Kush
brought his team to this remote site that borders the Tonto
National Forest, the newcomers have been tormented.
</P>
<P>
   Former quarterback Jeff Van Raaphorst and several teammates
donned hoods, broke into the freshmen sleeping quarters and threw
several players into a nearby pond.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Jake Plummer and Juan Roque tossed a bat _ as
in the flying creature _ into the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder doesn't mind the mild antics but insists that his players
don't get carried away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a specific policy, but I tell them, `Don't ever
treat your teammate really lousy, or with distaste,' '' he said.
``You don't take someone physically and do something. Never, in 35
years, have I seen how that has helped team morale.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the bark is worse than the bite. Several times over
the past week, veterans have been overheard warning freshmen, ``You
better watch your back. This could be the night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just like to mess with them, give them something to think
about,'' Battle said. ``They don't really know. They're 17-,
18-year-old kids coming here. For some, it's their first time being
away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of fun to tease them a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruegamer already has walked through the freshmen trailer and
looked around, just to make them sweat a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   No one escapes dinner entertainment, when newcomers must sing
the ASU fight song and read their team bio aloud. When accolades
are mentioned _ ``John made the all-academic team'' _ a sarcastic
``oooohhh, aaahhhh'' follows.
</P>
<P>
   And as uncomfortable as the living conditions can be sometimes,
the freshmen admit they enjoy the bonding experience.
</P>
<P>
   This season's group spends its late-night hours recounting the
evening's meetings with position coaches, who often single out
freshmen for rookie mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the funniest newcomers, whose identity will remain
anonymous, does a dead-on impression of running backs coach Cornell
Jackson, who likes to say, ``If you don't KNOW, then you don't
GO!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hilarious,'' another anonymous freshman said.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the newcomers experience, said Snyder, who
believes the trailer is a symbol for introduction to the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says, `As you work your way through the program, things do
get better: playing time, along with other things,' '' Snyder said.
``When you're a freshman, that's just where you are on the
ladder.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
