<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-20 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bell rings down curtain on Phils
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHILADELPHIA _ Astros manager Larry Dierker must have known
something prior to Wednesday night's game when he said it was only
a matter of time before Derek Bell started producing at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually somewhere between three to five days where he
looks like he's all out of whack, and then he just keeps coming
back and getting hot again,'' Dierker said of Bell, who entered the
series finale with the Philadelphia Phillies hitless in his last 14
at-bats. ``If that trend continues, he's about to get hot again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine innings later, Dierker must have felt like a genius. Then
again, with all the comebacks the Astros have staged this season,
he just has to sit back and watch.
</P>
<P>
   Bell delivered a two-run, bases-loaded single with two out in
the ninth inning as the Astros rallied for a 4-3 victory over the
Phillies before a stunned crowd of 21,341 at Veterans Stadium. It
marked the 22nd time this season the Astros have pulled out a
victory in their final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, whose average had slipped to a season-low .308 during the
past week before he came up with a fourth-inning single Wednesday,
said he wasn't thinking about his recent slump. Before his final
at-bat, Bell was hitting .194 this month with nine RBIs in 17
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't matter,'' said Bell, who is batting .478
(11-for-23) against Phillies closer Mark Leiter in his career. ``I
just like being in the thick and thin of things and try to help the
team win. All I have to do is be patient, concentrate and not worry
about hitting the ball out of the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros down 3-2 heading into the ninth, pinch hitters
Dave Clark and Richard Hidalgo singled off Leiter (6-4) to put
runners at first and third with one out. Craig Biggio flied out to
right field, but pinch runner Ricky Gutierrez was forced to hold up
on Bob Abreu's throw to the plate. Leiter hit Bill Spiers on the
left elbow to load the bases, and Bell hit a 3-and-2 fastball up
the middle for the Astros' 38th come-from-behind win this season.
The victory increased their lead in the National League Central to
8{ games over the Chicago Cubs and pulled them within 3{ games of
San Diego for the NL's second-best record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look like he was swinging too good until that last
at-bat,'' Dierker said of Bell. ``I know a guy when he's swinging
good wants to be the guy up there when the game is on the line. But
a guy that is struggling probably would just as soon see somebody
else get the hit. There was no choice, and he really had a great
at-bat. He managed to be patient enough to get the hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Said first baseman Jeff Bagwell: ``He's been a great hitter for
us all year. He's had a great attitude and approach to hitting. It
was just a matter of time for him to get a hit. Luckily for us, it
showed up at a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner pitched the ninth inning, notching his 24th save in
26 opportunities. After allowing singles to Rico Brogna and Abreu,
Wagner got Bobby Estalella on a called third strike to end the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Astros righthander Shane Reynolds (15-8) took a two-hitter into
the seventh inning before the Phillies took the lead on a three-run
homer by Abreu, a former Astro who was left unprotected in the
expansion draft and was picked by Tampa Bay before being traded to
Philadelphia. It was Abreu's 11th home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds allowed five hits and three runs, struck out nine and
walked one for his third victory in his last four decisions. At one
point, Reynolds retired 13 straight batters until Doug Glanville
beat out a high-bouncing infield hit to third base in the sixth
inning. Reynolds is 6-1 with a 2.83 ERA lifetime against the
Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said Reynolds' performance, which pulled him within one
victory of his career-high 16 of 1996, was the best the righthander
has thrown this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good as he's pitched all year,'' Dierker said. ``He
made one bad pitch (to Abreu). I looked up in the ninth, and we had
10 hits, and they had five; they had three runs, and we had two.
One big blow is sometimes the difference in the game. Luckily for
us, we were tenacious enough to get the win anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took a 1-0 lead in the fifth when Biggio hit a
two-out double down the right-field line, scoring Tony Eusebio. The
Astros had another chance to score in the inning but failed when
Biggio was gunned down at the plate by Abreu on Spiers' single to
right. Abreu's assist was his 15th of the season, tops among
major-league outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby's a great player,'' Bagwell said of his former teammate.
``At the time, he didn't fit into our plans right away. Luckily for
Bobby, he got an opportunity to play over here. He's shown that
he's a great player. He has a great arm, and we wish him all the
best in the world. I'm just glad his three-run homer wasn't the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou put the Astros ahead 2-0 in the sixth with a solo
home run to right-center field, giving him 36 on the season. The
victim this time was Philadelphia starter Carlton Loewer, who
allowed eight hits and walked two in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Alou, who has easily shattered his previous career high of 23
home runs set with the Florida Marlins last season, has hit 11 of
this year's homers on the first pitch. He also has 16 home runs
since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Astros take seven of nine meetings between
the teams this season, Philadelphia manager Terry Francona said the
Astros' postseason possibilities are endless.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way you win pennants,'' Francona said. ``That's a
good team over there, and they think they're going deep into the
postseason. I can't argue with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
