<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STOP INDIANS, 3-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers' Aaron Sele represented the
American League during the 1998 All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the 28-year-old right-hander took the mound last night at
The Ballpark in Arlington with a 1-5 record and 7.02 earned-run
average since that selection.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, though, shoveled dirt on his struggles of July and August
by burying the Indians for eight innings in the Rangers' 3-1
victory against the Central Division-leading Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Sele surrendered only one run on five hits and one walk in a
101-pitch appearance Rangers manager Johnny Oates described as
being ``as well as he's pitched all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers began this eight-game home stand by
terminating their three-game losing streak and are 11/2 games
behind the AL West-leading Anaheim Angels, who defeated the Detroit
Tigers last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offense consisted of a three-run sixth inning in
which catcher Ivan Rodriguez delivered a run-scoring infield single
before third baseman Todd Zeile and designated hitter Mike Simms
drew consecutive bases-loaded walks from right-hander Charles Nagy
(10-9).
</P>
<P>
   That would be all Sele would need to record his single-season
best 14th victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story was Aaron Sele,'' Oates said. ``I thought he was in
command the entire ballgame, even in the inning when they scored
their run. That's as well as he's pitched all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele (14-10) pitched well in New York during Friday's 6-4 loss
to the Yankees, but the results did not match the performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at times he's pitched better than his numbers,'' Oates
said. ``I think he's pitched better than 1-5. I think he's pitched
better than some guys who are 5-2 since the All-Star break.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians departed for their hotel with no argument.
</P>
<P>
   Sele threw first-pitch strikes to 17 of 28 batters and induced
12 outs via the ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That indicated that I was throwing the ball better,'' said
Sele, who recorded only his third victory this season when the
Rangers scored five or fewer runs. ``I'm a ground-ball pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagy, who entered the game leading the league with 31 home runs
surrendered, matched Sele early as he cruised through the Rangers'
lineup for five innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offense consisted of an infield single by shortstop
Royce Clayton and a bunt single from second baseman Luis Alicea in
the third inning. Nagy also issued a first-inning walk to left
fielder Rusty Greer and another to Zeile in the second inning, but
no runner advanced as far as third base.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea greeted Nagy with a leadoff single and advanced to third
on the ensuing double to center field by Greer. That brought right
fielder Juan Gonzalez to the plate with no outs, but his well-hit
ground ball found an infielder.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Travis Fryman kept the runners from advancing and
retired Gonzalez. Indians manager Mike Hargrove then opted to walk
first baseman Will Clark intentionally to load the bases and set up
a potential inning-ending, double-play ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez complied with a well-hit one-hopper that Fryman
prevented from leaving the infield with a diving stop, but he
juggled the ball as he returned to his feet and Rodriguez had an
infield single. Nagy then issued consecutive run-scoring walks to
Zeile and Simms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't hit too many balls hard until Luis got the
base hit and Rusty hit the double,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Sele made the three-run inning stand with the scoreless ninth
inning provided from closer John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to maintain my work ethic,'' Sele said. ``That's
how you keep your focus. There are a lot of peaks and valleys in
this game. You never try to get too high when things are going
well, and you don't want to get too low when things aren't going as
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
