<SLUG> BC-FBO-RECRUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPS GET THE SCOOP ON INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ There's no problem finding high school
football recruiting information on the Internet. However, believing
everything you read is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is, if you want to read about recruiting, log on.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Bernard Riley, Los Alamitos' highly-recruited defensive
lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom goes through the Web sites every day,'' said the
6-foot-2, 300-pound Riley. ``She'll have packets of stuff for me to
read. It helps me keep up on my top (seven) schools.''
</P>
<P>
   When in need of depth chart or roster, he can check out a
school's official site. And he can head to online newspaper sites
to find out what's going on in training camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have the ability to know everything about us,'' one
Pac-10 recruiting coordinator said.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan Howry,
</P>
<P>
   Riley's Los Alamitos teammate, is another guy who gets
information on-line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the incoming freshmen and what recruits each
school is looking at,'' Howry said. ``You can also find out what
classes are offered and more about the school. It's helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Howry, a 5-foot-10, 155-pounder, said that Oregon, Washington
State, Washington, Arizona State and UCLA are his favorites right
now. And Arizona State is the leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona State loses four receivers,'' Howry said. ``That would
be a good place to go for a receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, who is California's top defensive line prospect, said
USC, UCLA, Michigan, Florida State, Notre Dame, Arizona State and
Washington still have a shot. And Florida State's recent history of
turning out NFL first-round defensive linemen may not have an
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could easily say no to anybody on my list,'' Riley said.
``Football is only one thing (to consider). Academics are important
and what kids do off the field. I don't see it happening, but it is
easy sometime to get caught up in bad stuff. If I (go on a visit)
and don't like it, I would have no problem saying no.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Arizona linemen Nick Johnson
</P>
<P>
   has dropped UCLA from his list of five. The 6-foot-8, 300-pound
Johnson has added Notre Dame to a list of prospective suitors which
includes Ohio State, Arizona State, Nebraska and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most interesting runs of a recent USC practice was
head coach Paul Hackett's
</P>
<P>
   rush across the field to say good-bye to Hart receiver Jerry
Owens.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 180-pound Owens was headed home after watching the
Trojans' morning practice at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, along with Hart quarterback Kyle Boller
</P>
<P>
   (6-4, 200) and linebacker Scott Hunt
</P>
<P>
   (6-2, 220), also watched the Trojans scrimmage on Wednesday at
the L.A. Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hart head coach Mike Herrington,
</P>
<P>
   Owens has trimmed his wish list to about 10 schools, including
UCLA, USC, Washington, Arizona and Arizona State. UCLA is thought
to be the clear leader.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State's early commitment list grew to four last week
with verbals from a high school receiver and a pair of junior
college players. Culver City receiver Curtis Nettles
</P>
<P>
   (5-7, 170), Sierra College defensive linemen Eric Hodges
</P>
<P>
   (6-3, 248) and Citrus College defensive back Dante Minners
</P>
<P>
   (5-10, 180) are each headed to Pullman. The Cougars' first
commitment was La Canada St. Francis quarterback-defensive back
Kjell Nesen
</P>
<P>
   (6-2, 193).
</P>
<P>
   Oxnard tight end Jacob Rogers has been a frequent visitor to USC
practice over the past 10 days. Rogers, a 6-foot-5, 245-pound tight
end from Oxnard, has already given an oral commitment to the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   USC would love for 6-foot-5, 235-pound tight end Mike Seidman of
Westlake to line up on the other end from Rogers. Seidman's father
is a USC graduate, but the Trojans will have to battle UCLA,
Colorado and Washington for his services.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan linebacker T.J. Duckett, who some proclaim is the
country's best defender, has shown some interest in UCLA. The
6-foot-3, 240-pound Kalamazoo prep will choose among the Bruins,
Michigan, Michigan State, Ohio State and Florida State. His
brother, Tico, is a former standout at Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Another pair of out-of-state guys reportedly looking at UCLA are
Blue Springs, Mo. teammates Jamar Mozee and John Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   Mozee (6-1, 205) is a running back and Garrison (6-6, 250) a
defensive lineman on one of the top prep teams in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Carter defensive back Monti Collier (6-0, 172) became
Mack Brown's 13th early commitment at Texas. Collier is the first
Carter High player to commit, but won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College received a commitment from running back Greg Toal
</P>
<P>
   (5-11, 200) of Franklin Lakes, N.J. Toal, who rushed for 2,002
yards and 31 touchdowns last year, is the high school teammate of
Chris Simms, the country's best prep quarterback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
