<SLUG> BC-LAPD-CHANGES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. POLICE CHIEF HAILS STRIDES MADE SINCE RODNEY KING BEATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Seven years after the Rodney King beating exposed
a wide range of deficiencies in the LAPD, Chief Bernard C. Parks
declared that the department has succeeded in implementing most
Christopher Commission recommendations and changing the culture of
law enforcement in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   From the inner city to the western San Fernando Valley,
community groups lauded the transformation of the Los Angeles
Police Department and acknowledged that there is a new attitude
among officers that represents a commitment to community policing.
</P>
<P>
   In the first report ever made on the steps taken by the LAPD to
comply with the Christopher Commission goals outlined in 1991 after
the King beating, Parks said the department has met 82 of the 102
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report signifies a milestone not just for the Los Angeles
Police Department, but for the people of this city,'' Parks said at
a special Police Commission meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Christopher) Commission's real message was that the
department needed to change its culture dramatically from one which
provided aloof and removed service to one which operated in true
partnership with the people it serves. As we look to the future, we
will never slip back into the isolationist way of dealing with
community problems at the operating level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The men and women of this department would not abandon the
partnerships they have forged. The Police Commission would never
allow it. The City Council and mayor would not allow it and, most
importantly, the public would not stand for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The report comes one year after Parks took over as chief, and
police commissioners credited him with renewing the department's
commitment to reform.
</P>
<P>
   While members of the commission headed by former Secretary of
State Warren Christopher declined direct comment, the Parks report
drew praise from three leading civil rights leaders in the city who
see a change in attitude by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   John Mack of the Urban League, Joe Hicks of the city Human
Relations Commission and Geraldine Washington of the Los Angeles
Chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People said they had seen a dramatic change in police relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You no longer see officers pulling over a teen-ager and
assuming they're a gangbanger,'' Mack said. ``We have had many
battles down here. Over Eulia Love. Over Rodney King. But many
things have changed here, a true change in the institution of the
LAPD.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks agreed and credited Parks for the change. ``Reform of any
any kind takes time, but we are beginning to see the payoff,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Huber of the West Valley Citizens Police Advisory Board
offered her own example of the change in the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think the West Valley is `Leave It to Beaver'
land,'' she said. ``That's not so. We have a lot of new immigrants
living here and they are afraid of the police, so it means a lot to
them when they see a police officer smile and wave at them. That's
the biggest change. Officers smile at people now.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said it was an example of how the department had changed
to become part of the community. ``We want to provide friendly
service,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the American Civil Liberties Union said they
would not comment on the report until they have had additional time
to study it.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher and Gilbert Ray, the two top officials on the
independent commission appointed in the aftermath of the King
beating, said they would not comment directly on the LAPD's status
in adopting its recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone ever expected to see these adopted 100
percent,'' Ray said. ``Besides, issues change and you have to deal
with new circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrick Bobb, who had issued a critical report in 1996 on the
department's slowness in implementing reform, said he was pleased
the LAPD was tracking its progress. However, as a consultant to the
Police Commission, Bobb said he would not comment publicly on the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The major changes made by the department over the years since
the King incident have been a greater emphasis on community
policing as well as radical changes in the department's
use-of-force policy, in tracking problem officers, in dealing with
racism and bias within the department, in improving training, and
in broader recruitment of minorities and gays.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the structure of the department has changed, with the
chief of police limited to two five-year terms, the hiring of an
inspector general and greater authority given to the Police
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Christopher Commission recommendations not implemented,
Parks said all are being pursued and each has a high priority. Two
of the recommendations, however, would require City Charter changes
and are being held off until two charter reform panels complete
their work.
</P>
<P>
   Others involve issues that are under review, such as having
limited tours of duties for officers, and the roles of supervisors
and performance evaluations; or require more money, such as having
in-car video equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Police commissioners were effusive in their praise of Parks and
the progress made over the past two years in implementing reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Police Department you see today is a very different
department than was examined in 1991,'' said commission President
Edith Perez. ``It is a department whose makeup is representative of
the community, a department that is responsible to all the
communities of Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission Vice President Warren Jackson said he was pleased
particularly with the public's response to the changes in the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what we have heard in the community, it is clear that the
Los Angeles Police Department has regained the public's
confidence,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
