r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USCFB-LADN     08-20 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCFB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS HAVE FORMIDABLE FOURSOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The collective egos of the USC receivers,
according to Trojan receiver coach Mike Wilson, must be checked at
the door.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no time to count receptions and it doesn't matter
who scores the touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys know they can't worry about how what they do as
individuals,'' said Wilson, who played on four Super Bowl
championship teams in San Francisco. ``That will work itself out.
Last year, we had three guys with at least 30 catches, which shows
it can be spread around.''
</P>
<P>
   All three of those guys seniors Billy Miller and Mike
Bastianelli and junior R. Jay Soward are back with the Trojans. Add
to the mix senior Larry Parker, who redshirted last season with
foot problems, and San Jose State transfer Windrell Hayes, and the
Trojans should have plenty of guys to catch the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the potential to be one of the best in the country,''
Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Potential, though, is a fickle thing.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's foot is healed, but he has missed a lot of practice
time with a touchy hamstring. Bastianelli appears healthy after
cracking his collarbone in the spring. Soward is sitting out the
opener against Purdue because of some academic deficiencies in the
spring. And Hayes is playing for the first time in more than a
year. Then there's Miller, who had trouble holding on to the ball
as a sophomore, was solid as a junior and has been sensational in
the first 10 days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   After that, though, there is a significant drop in skill level.
Rod Perry was expected to be a key backup, but the former Mater Dei
star, who missed his freshman season after his second knee surgery,
decided to quit football and transferred to Cal State Fullerton to
play baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomores Troy Garner and Stanley Guyness have yet to catch a
collegiate pass and have each been inconsistent in practice. The
other healthy receivers are walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   But, unless injuries strike, the Trojans won't spend much time
going past five deep. And those five are pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps me as a defensive back,'' senior safety Rashard Cook
said. ``Once we get to the game, I'm not facing anybody better than
these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the group could very well be the different
strengths of the individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balance and diversity of this group is something,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soward, one of college football's big-play makers, represents
pure speed. The 5-foot-11, 175-pounder has scored 18 career
touchdowns in 107 touches, which is six points once in every six
times he gets the ball. His touchdowns are from an average of 53
yards, three are longer than 90 yards, and 14 have covered at least
40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to leave the game and be like, `Ooh, did you see
what he did?''' said Soward, who has 66 career catches.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's 92-play scrimmage, Soward caught five passes for
133 yards, including a 47-yard toss from Mike Van Raaphorst. But,
he also dropped a sure touchdown on a perfectly placed bomb from
Carson Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``R. Jay made a couple of great plays,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said. ``But there (also) was his Achilles' heel. One drop could
cost us a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' physical receiver is the 6-foot-4, 220-pound
Miller, who has jostled his way to 76 receptions in three years,
including a team-high 56 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy has been Billy,'' Wilson said. ``He's just such a solid
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was far from solid two years ago, when he had trouble
catching the ball. Miller has made those days feel like a long time
ago with his recent play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball feels comfortable in my hands,'' Miller said. ``(As a
sophomore) it used to ricochet off of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bastianelli, a 6-foot-1, 195-pound senior, who never lost a game
while playing at Concord De La Salle, is a fearless possession
receiver. His only catch as a freshman was a 15-yarder on
third-and-12 to keep a scoring drive alive in a win over Washington
State, and he has 58 career grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Parker, a 6-foot-2, 200-pound senior, is a combination
size-and-speed guy. He played in all 11 games as a true freshman
and started all 12 games and caught 25 passes for the 1995 Rose
Bowl champions. Hamstring and heel problems hampered his junior
year and he redshirted last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be sure Larry is 100percent,'' Hackett said.
``Right now, he's not up to the rigors of two-a-day practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Hayes fits in is yet to be determined. Hayes showed up
four days into the training camp after pleading guilty to a
misdemeanor charge of writing checks with insufficient funds. He
was facing three felony charges for writing bad checks, but a
plea-bargain agreement allowed Hayes to receive three years
probation after paying restitution of nearly $8,500.
</P>
<P>
   The stocky 6-foot, 200-pound Hayes caught 97 passes for 1,383
yards in his two seasons at San Jose State, including four for 40
yards in a 1995 loss to USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``He a young man who's caught (nearly) 100 balls in college,''
Wilson said. ``We're dealing with a polished receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Bastianelli and Miller played with Hayes in the 1995 Shrine
All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I heard he was coming here I told everybody this
guy is awesome,'' Bastianelli said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No telling how good we can be with him with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to jump ahead, but I think we'll be pretty damn
good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
