<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBODY SAID CAMP WOULD BE THIS HARD
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-AZR  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)   By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Camp Tontozona &QL; 
Dear Mom &AMP; Dad:
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's almost over. Camp ends Saturday, and I can't begin to
tell you what a unique summer ex perience this has been.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming. Horseback riding. Canoeing. We haven't done any of
those.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Snyder, the camp coun selor, told freshmen the first night
that if any of us thought we were going to spend the next 10 days
making beaded necklaces and sing ing ``Kum-bah-ya'' around the camp
fire, we read the wrong brochure.
</P>
<P>
   Coach meant business. He was dressed like Tom Hanks in ``Saving
Private Ryan.'' This was boot camp, he barked, his steely eyes
fixed on each of us. He said if we weren't willing to make the
commitment and lay everything on the line for the glory of Arizona
State football, then we should leave camp right now, although Coach
didn't offer his car keys or a map.
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago a walk-on went AWOL. He finally cracked. Maybe it
was the 6:30 a.m. air-horn blasts. Or the practice-field voice of
Coach Cozzetto, our offensive coordinator, demanding that our
linemen _ ``Lemme HEAR you!!'' _ not only block but growl.
</P>
<P>
   After lights out, there were 24 of us in our bunk beds in the
freshman trailer. Next morning, there were 23.
</P>
<P>
   When last seen, the deserter had gone over the hill and was
standing by the highway next to the yellow ``Watch For Animals Next
25 Miles'' sign, his thumb out.
</P>
<P>
   The guy might be home by now.
</P>
<P>
   I'm (sigh) still here. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Day 8 and counting &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the marks on the wall, this is Day 8. Seems like no
more than a month ago we left cam pus and bused 100 miles to camp.
During the ride up, I went over the checklist of items players were
urged to pack to make our stay more enjoyable. A fan. A pillow. A
``better'' blanket. Shampoo. Ear plugs.
</P>
<P>
   Our team motto is ``One at a Time.'' One at a time is how fresh
men use the camp outdoor toilet, property of ``Little Stinker Tink
lers.''
</P>
<P>
   We enjoy several group activities at Camp Tontozona. Twice a day
players run forward, backward and sideways. We dance through
traffic cones. The guards and tackles growl a lot.
</P>
<P>
   After morning practice, lunch. Meetings. A short nap. Then back
to the field which, literally, is right outside our trailer. Mom,
you thought ``my'' room was messy.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, we are cut off from civ ilization. Camp has one
telephone, for emergency use only. No TV.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried to keep up with the news. But here in the pines I
can pick up only two radio stations. One plays country-Western
music. The other broadcasts the voice of a faith healer in Del Rio,
Texas, who last night said the demon spirit must be cast ``owwwt''
if Mr. Clinton hopes to save his presidency. Did his grand jury
testimony not go well? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Staying alive &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I like to think this experience is making a real man out of me,
as op posed to a woman. For five days the freshmen were in what
Coach Sny der called a ``survival mode.'' Grad ually, I've fought
through the pain and fatigue. I endured the hoots of upperclassmen
during my failed at tempt to sing the fight song, which freshmen
are required to memorize and perform in its entirety at dinner. (I
wrote the words on my hand but got sweaty palms, and the ink ran).
</P>
<P>
   There are about 100 of us at camp. Captives, we have done some
serious male bonding. One player sneaked a female into his cabin
but was caught and reprimanded for harboring a pet raccoon.
</P>
<P>
   If only I could have just one night off. Four of us _ my cohorts
shall remain nameless _ have discussed slipping out of camp after
the after noon practice and going into Pay son, where we could do
something sinful, like sample the featured des sert, peanut-butter
pie, at Denny's.
</P>
<P>
   But it's 17 miles. I'm afraid we could spend all night trying to
flag a ride. And even if we did, we would look suspicious walking
around town. Our helmets would give us away.
</P>
<P>
   Bye for now,
</P>
<P>
   Your son &QR; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens &LR; pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
