</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GRACE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK ENJOYING COLLEGE LIFE AS MUCH AS GOLF VICTORIES 
</HEADLINE>
 PARK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phone rings at Grace Park's apartment in Tempe, and almost
immediately after she answers, her laughter begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited,'' said the All-America sophomore, who played a
pivotal role on Arizona State's national championship golf team
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, I haven't been this excited for quite a while. It's
like I'm on a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The tendency would be to think that Park's enthusiasm is
directly related to the U.S. Amateur title she captured last
weekend, when she beat favored Jenny Chuasiriporn in the final, 7
and 6.
</P>
<P>
   It's not. Even though winning the Amateur was Park's biggest
golfing achievement, she has moved on. The Amateur party was the
night before at Grace's place. Been there, done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going shopping tomorrow at Price Club, Target and Kmart,''
she said, giving her caller time to gasp.
</P>
<P>
   Price Club, Target and Kmart?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've got to furnish this place. I don't even have a bed
yet. So that's why I'm so excited. This is my first place away from
home. Now I've got to decorate it. Lots of shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's the little things that count most in a world of
big expectations. Park has known this since she was 12 and made the
bold journey from her homeland in South Korea to America.
Eventually, she learned the English language and became fluent in
golf at Xavier College Prep and at Horizon High, winning three
state championships. Along the way Park was tutored by such noted
instructors as Bill Forrest, Chuck Hogan and Mike LaBauve, her
current teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Soo Nam Park, a wealthy restaurateur from Seoul, was
aware of Grace's athleticism, and he told her simply: ``Go for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Park is the ``second best'' player from South Korea,
trailing the accomplishments of Se Ri Pak at this time, she is
happy with what lies ahead. And, no, the immediate future will not
be in the pro ranks. ASU will do just fine, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lazy when it comes to school,'' she said. ``It's probably
going to take me five years to graduate. But I don't care, because
I'm having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she likes cruising around campus in her green BMW.
Fleeing dormitory life for her own place this year has been a big
plus. The only thing lacking is a boyfriend, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you know any cute guys?'' she asked, laughing heartily
at her slightly bold question.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the 19-year-old Park is busy putting together her
social life now that the golf portion seems as solid as one of her
300-yard drives. It's true: Twice during the U.S. Amateur played at
Barton Hills Country Club in Ann Arbor, Mich., she launched the
ball into an area off the tee that is reserved for guys like Tiger
Woods and John Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm longer than almost every (woman) out there,'' she
said. ``And my short game has gotten so much better. Especially my
wedges from 60 to 100 yards, and my putting. My confidence is so
high, now it's just a matter of practice and developing my own
system.''
</P>
<P>
   She looked like a world beater at the Amateur, where she knocked
off two Curtis Cup team players, the legendary Carol Semple
Thompson and Chuasiriporn, who lost a playoff to Pak earlier this
summer at the U.S. Open. Coupled with victories in the Western and
Trans National amateurs, Park became the first woman since Patty
Berg in 1938 to sweep the major women's amateur events.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that has gone wrong in the past year was a
collapse in the NCAA tournament, where she built a huge lead with
rounds of 65 and 65, then tumbled to third with rounds of 77 and
76. Despite the team's championship, Park broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought it was inappropriate, but I couldn't
help it,'' she said. ``They stuck that camera in my face, and I
wasn't going to cry, but I just did. . . . I'm emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Park's sensitive nature might be the main reason she ends up at
ASU for the full four years. There is no rush to get to Pak, whom
Park used to beat regularly when they were juniors, despite Pak
being 1{ years older.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can wait to be lonely,'' she said of life on the pro tour.
``That's still a little bit scary to me, even though I feel I have
the game. I'm in no hurry. I just want to have my world come
together gradually.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a strategy that's worked pretty well so far. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
