McDOWELL COMES BACK WITH A VENGEANCE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It's no secret that Jack McDowell's elbow is
so fragile that any pitch could be his last. That's why the Anaheim
Angels are happy to get each and every inning McDowell is able to
throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Innings, as many innings as he can give me,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said when asked what he expected from McDowell
Wednesday night in the pitcher's first start since May 31.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell did Collins one better. The former Cy Young Award
winner gave the Angels seven SCORELESS innings in a 2-0 win over
the Detroit Tigers before 21,841 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The win enabled the Angels to maintain a 1{-game lead over Texas
in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell's elbow problems limited him to six starts in 1997 with
the Cleveland Indians and only seven this year with the Angels.
He's been on the disabled list twice this season, the second stint
lasting more than 2{ months. That's why the Angels were cautiously
optimistic about McDowell's return.
</P>
<P>
   With Ken Hill suffering a setback in his attempted return from
elbow surgery, McDowell was a shot in the arm Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He retired the side in order in the first, fourth and seventh
innings. He gave up two hits in the second but got a double play to
help him escape. He gave up a two-out triple to Brian Hunter in the
third inning but stranded him. He also picked Hunter off first in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell (2-2) gave up five hits in seven innings, striking out
two and walking none. He warmed up before the eighth inning, but
Collins took him out before the inning started, replacing him with
Shigetoshi Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa pitched a 1-2-3 eighth inning and Troy Percival _ with
help from first baseman Darin Erstad, who made a spectacular diving
catch _ pitched the ninth for his 34th save.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell made 80 pitches, 59 for strikes, to get his first
victory since April 8, a 2-1 win over Boston. McDowell needed to be
that good considering the way Tigers starter Justin Thompson
(10-10) pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson went eight innings, allowing two runs and nine hits,
but his biggest problem was Reggie Williams. Williams, starting in
place of Garret Anderson, doubled with two out in the third inning
and scored on Erstad's single for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Williams followed Gary DiSarcina's double with an
RBI single to make it 2-0. Williams, who entered this season having
played only 15 major-league games in a 10-year pro career, is
hitting .462 (6 for 13) in six games with the Angels since being
called up Aug. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had a chance to give themselves some breathing room
in the eighth after Randy Velarde walked and Erstad singled Velarde
to second. Velarde stole third, but Tim Salmon struck out. Pinch
hitter Craig Shipley then hit into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
