<HEADLINE>
KINGS CONTACT SUNS ABOUT SKILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the second time this summer, Suns assistant coach Scott
Skiles has emerged as a candidate for a head coaching vacancy in
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   A league source told the ``Arizona Republic'' on Wednesday that
the Sacramento Kings intend to interview Skiles for their coaching
vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings announced Tuesday that Eddie Jordan will not return as
that club's coach.
</P>
<P>
   Suns General Manager Bryan Colangelo confirmed that the Kings
contacted him about Skiles, but he would not elaborate other than
to say that the club expects Skiles' name to pop up in coaching
searches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's considered one of the up-and-coming young coaches in the
league,'' Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, 34, was among four known candidates interviewed by the
Chicago Bulls to replace Phil Jackson, but the Bulls eventually
hired Iowa State Coach Tim Floyd instead.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were 33-64 under Jordan in a little more than one full
season. He replaced Garry St. Jean late in the 1996-97 season and
guided Sacramento to a 27-55 mark last season. Jordan came to the
club as an assistant in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Skiles, league sources said that Los Angeles
Lakers assistant coach Kurt Rambis is expected to be a candidate
for the Sacramento job. Rambis has emerged as a candidate for the
Los Angeles Clippers' opening.
</P>
<P>
   If Skiles lands the Kings job, he'll have his work cut out for
him. The Kings have had five head coaches since the franchise moved
to Northern California from Kansas City in 1985. None has had a
winning season.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Skiles nor his agent, Keith Glass, could be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Glass said earlier in the summer that the Denver Nuggets and
Clippers had inquired about Skiles, although neither club ever
formally asked to interview him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
