<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE SHOULDERS CHALLENGE  
 TIGHT END PUTTING INJURY IN PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he reported to training camp, Cardinals rookie tight end
Terry Hardy knew his dream of earning an NFL career centered on two
factors:
</P>
<P>
   Proving the time bomb he calls a left shoulder can withstand the
pounding of the NFL, and proving he can catch a football _ a
critical element of the West Coast offense.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-round draft pick has answered one of the questions,
but time bombs are what they are until they're defused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've showed everybody on both issues,'' Hardy said.
``I know what I can do. It's just a matter of showing everybody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The rap that probably cost Hardy, an excellent blocker, from
being drafted earlier out of Southern Mississippi concerned the
dislocated shoulder he suffered early in his senior season. The
injury stretched ligaments, tendons and possibly damaged the
rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   But he played through it. Still is, and without a twitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as bad as people think it is,'' said Hardy, who grew
up in Montgomery, Ala., believing basketball was his sport. ``I
haven't done anything special for it, and it hasn't been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as tight as they would like, but I don't even think
about it. If it goes, it goes. I can't control that, so why worry
about things I can't control?''
</P>
<P>
   A coach faced with cutting a roster to 53 players has to worry
about it, and Coach Vince Tobin is no different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you have to think about it,'' Tobin said. ``But
what is encouraging is he hurt it early in the year last year and
played without any repercussions. He's proved he can play with it,
and it was proven strong enough to withstand a season, so that's
encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, because recurrence of the injury is greater if left
unrepaired, it's probable at season's end that Hardy will undergo
what is known as a Bankardt procedure, in which tendons are
transferred to tighten the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the shoulder is damaged again, the 6-foot-4,
266-pound Hardy thinks he has shown enough in camp to have
confidence he won't be tossed away as damaged goods. Tobin will
concur, because Hardy and veteran tight ends Chris Gedney and
Johnny McWilliams figure to give the team a solid rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind I can catch and block at this
level,'' Hardy said. ``I think I've established myself enough to
know I can play in this league. Just being here and going through a
couple of preseason games, which are different from real games, has
allowed my confidence to reach that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have to keep my mind right, not get conceited and work
harder each day and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   In college he was used primarily as a run blocker, catching just
16 passes during his first three seasons and 12 as a senior. He has
quickly dispelled any notions that he suffers from ``dropsy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked him in minicamp when we first saw him,'' Tobin said.
``He's a much better athlete that what we anticipated because he
played on a team that ran the ball a lot. I think he can get deep.
I think all three of our tight ends can get deep. It's a strong
position for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy insists he couldn't have landed in a better situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyday I thank the Lord for the situation he has put me
in,'' he said. ``There are only three of us, so the workload is
greater, but that's a blessing because I get more reps. You learn
more by doing than by watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard how veterans sometimes lead rookies the wrong way
because they're after their job, but Johnny and Chris have really
been helpful.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
