<SLUG> BC-BKW-MERCURY-ROCKERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY'S OPPONENT SUITABLE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Needing a victory for playoff life, the Mercury had to like
having lowly Sacramento at home to get it Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, the Mercury's playoff opponent must make Coach Cheryl
Miller want to hop on the press table and dance. The Mercury went
3-0 against the Rockers, who will come to America West Arena at 5
p.m. Saturday to open the best-of-three semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me nervous because Cleveland is a very good team,''
Miller said of the 3-0 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Better than good of late. The Rockers (20-10), the WNBA's top
shooting team, swiped the Eastern Conference championship with a
four-game winning streak of their own and 10 wins in the last 14
games.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mercury (19-11) tensed up Cleveland's playoff chase by
sweeping the season series, twice in easy fashion before Aug. 10's
double-overtime thriller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We match up really well against them, just like New York
matched up really well with us,'' Mercury guard Michele Timms said.
``Little Umeki Webb does a fantastic job every time she's matched
up with (Cleveland's 6-3 Eva) Nemcova, who is one of the world's
best offensive players.''
</P>
<P>
   Nemcova was held to 11 points combined in the Mercury's first
two victories, a 76-61 July 2 game at Cleveland and a 76-60 home
win on July 10. But Nemcova, the WNBA's top three-point shooter,
did bust out for 19 in the double-overtime game, the only time the
Mercury saw Cleveland fully loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The teams' first meeting was Rockers guard Michelle Edwards'
first game back from injury and center Isabelle Fijalkowski, who
averaged 16.5 points and 8.5 rebounds in two Phoenix games, was out
sick in the second meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to win there on the road the last time,'' Mercury
guard Bridget Pettis said. ``I hope it won't be that close at home
(Saturday) so we can get the momentum and steal one at their
place.''
</P>
<P>
   The one constant for the Mercury in all three Cleveland games
was Jennifer Gillom. She had three of her best four scoring games
of the season against the Rockers, averaging 31 points on 54
percent shooting to go with 8.7 rebounds and 3.7 steals. That
includes a WNBA-season high 36 points in the last game at
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like playing there,'' Gillom said of Gund Arena,
where Cleveland is 11-4. ``I love the lighting. You see the basket
so clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, she does anyway. The rest of the Mercury was 48 for 141
from the field against the Rockers this year. Cleveland, last in
the WNBA in rebounds, also beat the Mercury on the boards, 104-96,
overall. Where the Mercury struggled scoring and rebounding outside
Gillom, it compensated on the other end against the drone-prone
Rockers offense.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland committed 62 turnovers to the Mercury's 37 in the
series. That's especially odd because point guard Suzie McConnell
Serio usually runs its offense with precision. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
