<SLUG> BC-FISHING-DESERT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE SHAD GO, CRAPPIE SOON FOLLOW  
 DEEP WATER BECKONS ON HOT DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
 LAKES-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TONTO BASIN _ It's difficult to deny that the dog days of August
continue to plague fishing on Arizona's lower desert lakes.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to get a large number of accurate reports about
daytime fishing because of the heat. There just aren't that many
anglers willing to brave the humid heat for mediocre bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves nighttime hours, when bass and crappie fishing is
pretty good. But fishing at night this time of year is iffy and can
be dangerous when sudden monsoon storms bring wind, lightning and
heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   Often the storms are of short duration, but their intensity is
scary if you're in a fishing boat.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the monster factor. Some of us sensitive types
always hear monsters, hidden by darkness, crashing around on the
shore. I've never personally seen one, but I know they're out
there. Some climb under my bed at night, too.
</P>
<P>
   But night fishing at this time of year can't be questioned for
its effectiveness. Lakes such as Alamo, Saguaro, Canyon and Apache
have produced some good bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Anglers using floating or submerged lights also have made good
crappie catches at Alamo, Roosevelt and San Carlos lakes.
</P>
<P>
   And in the early morning, there is some top-water fishing at
almost all the lakes, even though the bass often are small.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't mind the heat of day, there are some fish to
be caught _ with some good bass reports from both Bartlett and San
Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Rambo, a crappie guide at Roosevelt Lake, isn't at all fond
of the heat, but since he doesn't like night fishing, either, it's
either heat or stay home. He'll take the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it gets too bad, we put on our life jackets and jump into
the lake,'' he said. Unfortunately, clothes get a little itchy when
the humidity is too high for them to dry quickly.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a particularly good time of year for guides. But
Rambo still accepts some clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I couldn't have been guiding for 10 years if my wife
(Margaret) hadn't gone to work every morning,'' he said. The Rambos
own a realty agency in Tonto Basin.
</P>
<P>
   Rambo has been catching crappie in the daylight hours. Some days
it might be a dozen or so, but others it may be 30 to 60. It
depends on being there when the crappie begin feeding on threadfin
shad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fish are deep,'' he said. ``Their mostly in about 30 feet
of water, and they don't usually move up until about 8:30, 9 in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   He is catching most of his crappie in the Haystack area, which
is across the lake from the marina. It's called Haystack because
barren, clay cliffs along the shoreline look something like
haystacks.
</P>
<P>
   The shoreline also reveals the underwater structure available.
The banks have eroded into steps. A flat shelf drops off to the
next shelf and so on. The crappie are moving from deeper water to
feed on shelves about 30 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   This is not easy fishing. Rambo's success comes from experience.
Deep-water fishing always is difficult for the average angler
because it's more difficult to feel a strike.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, crappie are not the vicious predators that bass
have the reputation of being. Strikes are remarkably light.
Sometimes its just a little movement of the rod tip.
</P>
<P>
   Rambo uses a light rod with extremely light line, usually
4-pound test. The lure is a brown 2-inch Power Grub with a
chartreuse curled tail. He uses an eighth-ounce lead head on the
grub so it will sink faster.
</P>
<P>
   Using a sonar device, he moves slowly along a shelf, looking for
concentrations of shad. Sometimes crappie can be seen with the
shad, sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   When he finds an acceptable number of shad, he drops the lure to
the bottom, retrieves it about a foot from the bottom, then uses
his trolling motor to gently move along the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably have a lot of hits you don't even know about,''
he said. ``You have to watch your rod tip and line all the time. If
you see or feel anything strange at all, set the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, there's a slight jerk of the line that
indicates a crappie, but more likely, it might be a rod tip that
suddenly moves or a line that slackens. There also are small bass
to put up with and a lot of misses. The fish don't hold on. It's
infuriating until you get the hang of it.
</P>
<P>
   There are crappie below, but many of them are scattered. That's
why Rambo continues to move the boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the really good days, you'll find a big school and can just
sit above them and drop down the lure,'' he said. ``That's when you
catch a lot of fish.''
</P>
<P>
   And the heat is always there. A slight breeze or monsoon clouds
make it cooler, but when the wind dies and the clouds clear, body
comfort drops drastically.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, swimming seems more appropriate than fishing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barry Burkhart can be reached at barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2670 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-MONARCHS-MERCURY-     08-20 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-MONARCHS-MERCURY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY DOWNS MONARCHS, AWAITS ROCKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mercury isn't fooling itself.
</P>
<P>
   Its 71-62 WNBA playoff-clinching win over Sacramento on night at
America West Arena wasn't a masterpiece. And its 3-0 edge this
season over semifinal opponent Cleveland is deceptive and doesn't
mean a thing.
</P>
<P>
   But the alternatives _ to have lost and be on the outside of the
postseason like 1997 runner-up New York or to face defending
champion Houston in the semifinals _ are worse for a team
determined to make amends for its 41-point showing (still a league
low) in last year's playoff loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The satisfaction (of making the playoffs) is seeing how we
play against Cleveland,'' Coach Cheryl Miller said. ``We didn't
just play to get in. That's not our approach or mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   The best-of-three semifinal series with Eastern Conference
champion Rockers (20-10) begins here at 5 p.m. Saturday, then
shifts to Gund Arena for games Monday, and if necessary Tuesday.
Phoenix (19-11) goes in on a four-game win streak, equaling its
season high, that includes a playoff-saving double-overtime victory
in Cleveland 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Mercury beat the Rockers by 15 and 16 points, games
when Cleveland was not at full strength. ``That makes me nervous,''
said Miller of the regular-season dominance, a feeling echoed by
center Jennifer Gillom, who is averaging 31 points against the
Rockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' Gillom said. ``You start taking teams for
granted when you beat them three times, and it showed tonight (with
Sacramento). We played like we beat them three times before. We
just took them nonchalantly. We don't want to do that with
Cleveland. We know this playoff time, and those three games don't
matter any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento, which finished 8-22 and tied for last in the West
with Utah, jumped ahead, 10-4 and 18-13, and refused to fold even
after Phoenix took a lead it would never relinquish on back-to-back
layups by Umeki Webb, the second with 5:17 left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs actually pulled even at 25 at 2:21 before
intermission, only to allow eight straight points and almost
another basket as the buzzer sounded on a full-court inbounds pass
from Gillom that left Bridget Pettis too wide-open to convert a
layup.
</P>
<P>
   Despite chilly shooting (33.3 from the field, 18.2 from
three-point), the Mercury slowly built the lead to 10, 59-49, with
8:16 remaining only to see Sacramento still within three, 64-61, on
a layup by Latasha Byears at 1:35.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was the most stressful game New York had lost (to
Detroit before the Mercury tip-off), and it meant we could slip
into third (playoff seed),'' point guard Michele Timms said. ``It
put a little bit more pressure than if New York had of won, and I
felt it more than I had any other game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the veteran, who admits to having a less than stellar
season, responded with a tough running 10-footer at the 4:05 mark
and four free throws in the final 35 seconds, keeping Phoenix
perfect (8-0) vs. the Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   Gillom was 7 for 24 from the field but spun to the baseline past
former teammate Pauline Jordan to score a layup when Sacramento was
within three for the last of her team-high 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with an off shooting night, we needed her,'' Miller said
of her league Most Valuable Player candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Byears had 18 points and Adia Barnes, the Pac-10 Player of the
Year for Arizona, had 18 rebounds and 13 points before fouling out.
Barnes scored her rookie season-high of 24 three days earlier in
the Monarchs' 85-69 loss to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give a lot of credit to Sacramento to come in here and play
the type of game that they did,'' Miller said. ``It's indicative of
what Heidi (VanDerveer) has instilled. They are a very young and
talented team.''
</P>
<P>
   VanDerveer is 13-30 since replacing Mary Murphy as head coach
halfway through the 1997 season and hoping to return next season
when Ruthie Bolton-Holifield will be back from major knee surgery
to team with Ticha Penicheiro at the guard position. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
