<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-EXPOS-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOSHANDCUFF DIAMONDBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't look now, but the Diamondbacks first season is quickly
winding down.
</P>
<P>
   With only 36 games remaining in their inaugural season,
Wednesday afternoon's 8-2 loss to Montreal simply will be logged
away as one of the many losses the club will incur in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal starter Dustin Hermanson basically shoved his
assortment of pitches down the throats of Arizona's batters, who
were nearly unanimous in tipping their cap to one of the Expos'
brightest young players.
</P>
<P>
   While players like Hermanson and the multitalented Vladimir
Guerrero, who hit a monstrous two-run home run in the first inning,
give the Expos reason to point toward the future, the Diamondbacks
are doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   The final five weeks of the season will not only see the
Diamondbacks trying to avoid 100 losses (they must finish 16-20 to
do so), but this will also be a time when Manager Buck Showalter
will audition several of the lesser-used players.
</P>
<P>
   It will be an important time for a few Diamondbacks, notably
players such as Yamil Benitez, David Dellucci and a few minor
leaguers who will be on the big-league roster when it expands Sept.
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some things left to do here,'' Showalter said.
``There are some at-bats and innings I want to give to some people
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   It would not be unusual for Showalter to leave someone like
Benitez in the starting lineup for a two-week stretch. After all,
it is in major league games that clubs learn what a player can
really do.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of winter league games in the Caribbean can simulate
how a player responds to big-league pressure. It's also a safe bet
that several players on the roster will be down to their final days
with the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   One player whose future with the Diamondbacks is unknown is
Wednesday's starter, Amaury Telemaco, whose record dropped to 4-8
while his ERA rose to 3.98 after allowing three runs in six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   While there was some mild praise for Telemaco after the loss,
the reality is that the young right-hander must start to show
significant progress or start to worry about his future in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco has won only once since July 13 and only twice in 11
starts since being inserted into the rotation. He served up a fat
hanging slider to Guerrero in the first that landed about 20 rows
deep down the left field line.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco wound up giving up two more runs, although only one was
earned because of a throwing error by catcher Kelly Stinnett, who
easily could have been charged with another error but was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amaury is capable of better than what he showed today,''
Showalter said. ``He worked through it, though.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point promise must turn into production and even though
it may seem unfair to simply point to the final 36 games as the
end-all, that is one of the propositions facing the Diamondbacks
and several players on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Bernard Gilkey, acquired from the New York Mets on
July 31, finally flexed some muscle and had his first extra-base
hit in 60 at-bats since becoming a Diamondback.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike players such as Dellucci, Benitez and Karim Garcia, who
may see his playing time cut in the near future, Gilkey has the
luxury of being a big-ticket item. The Diamondbacks are on the hook
to pay him nearly $11 million the next two seasons, and he will
probably be a fixture in the outfield at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   These are the dog days of August, but several players better not
take the attitude that they can slough off this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be taking a close look at a lot of things these
last few weeks,'' Showalter said. ``It's a very important time for
us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 0142EDT &QL; 
