<HEADLINE>
JOB OF SAVING GAMES LONELY, HIGH-WIRE ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By definition, their job description says it all: They are in
the game to put out a fire. Little else matters in the life of a
closer.
</P>
<P>
   They are daredevils living on the game's high wire, all eyes
fixed on every pitch. The job of closer is arguably the most
difficult in baseball. At the very least, it's the loneliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we come in, a game is on the line,'' said John
Franco of the New York Mets, one of the best closers ever. ``You
have to be mentally tough to have this job, there's just no way
around that fact. Some make it a tougher job than it really is. You
have to realize it's just a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Mark Wohlers, who until this season was considered one
of the most dominant closers, recently, and inexplicably,
unraveled. He cannot find the strike zone, often throwing pitches
well over the batter's head.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers' numbers have been atrocious as he goes through one of
the worst stretches a big-league pitcher has ever seen. The Braves
were so distrustful of their saves leader of the past three years,
they requested he return to the minor leagues for further
refinement.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers reluctantly accepted his second trip to the minors this
season, but his results at Triple-A Richmond have done little to
bolster the confidence of Atlanta's front office, coaching staff or
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the closer is in a slump, you lose,'' Braves pitching coach
Leo Mazzone told the ``Atlanta Journal-Constitution'' recently.
``If you look around, every closer has been taken out of his job at
one time or another. Mark just has to fight to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Several supporters and teammates have pointed to Wohlers
impending divorce as a possible reason for his slide into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that Wohlers is not the first pitcher to lose his
ability to pitch consistently. The names of Mitch Williams and
Steve Blass spring out. Although Blass was a starter, he suffered
the same experience as Wohlers. He simply could not throw strikes
one season after winning 19 games for Pittsburgh in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, nicknamed the ``Wild Thing'' for obvious reasons, was
never a sure thing. The images of then-Philadelphia Manager Jim
Fregosi and pitcher Curt Schilling shielding their eyes while
Williams did his thing in the 1993 playoffs still stand out.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, few can forget the greatest tragedy a closer has
ever encountered: The suicide of former California Angels reliever
Donnie Moore, who surrendered the home run to Boston's Dave
Henderson that sent the Red Sox onto the 1986 World Series instead
of the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Though the fallout from that one bad pitch haunted Moore for the
rest of his playing career, he also was believed to be battling
personal demons of his own that led to his untimely death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a what-have-you-done-for-me-lately business,''
Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said. ``It's often not the arm
that is the deciding factor in a closer being successful. Not
everybody can do it. They're swashbucklers. They come in and let it
fly, basically saying, `Here it is, hit it if you can.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The life of a closer is the loneliest of any of the 25 players
on a major league roster. While the position players routinely get
four or five at-bats per game and a starting pitcher has as many as
nine innings, a closer is afforded no such luxury.
</P>
<P>
   The closer almost always comes into a game in the ninth inning
with his team leading by three runs or less. There is little margin
for error. One mistake in a one-run game can be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a fragile job,'' said Dennis Eckersley, who many
consider the finest ever. ``The weight of the entire team is on
you. Make a mistake and everyone looks to you as the reason for a
loss. It's a bitch of a way to go through life.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckersley, whose 390 saves rank second on the all-time list,
relies on fear of failure as his motivation. When he was saving
games for those great Oakland clubs, Eckersley was a creature of
habits he followed religiously.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, he would smoke the first of two cigarettes.
In the fifth, he would use the bathroom. In the seventh, he would
finish his second cigarette, and before the start of the eighth, he
would saunter to the bullpen with a cup of steaming coffee in his
pitching hand.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Anaheim's Troy Percival start pacing back and forth
in the bullpen as soon as the eighth inning begins in a close game.
</P>
<P>
   Every closer has his personal nuances and quirks.
</P>
<P>
   Securing the final three outs of a game has always been tough.
That's why the list of the truly great closers remains relatively
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hitter has already had three or four at-bats and has a sense
of his timing down,'' Philadelphia's Ricky Bottalico said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our life revolves around nothing extraordinary happening. If
it does, it means we, personally and as a team, have been beaten.
There is always a sense of urgency when we step into a game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
