<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FANTASY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS SWITCH ING LEAGUES SPELL TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
 BASEBALL-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF CADE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What I could really use is another baseball strike. And I'm not
just speaking for myself . . . oh, all right, I am, too.
</P>
<P>
   But still, there are lots of fantasy owners out there who are
fulfilling their fantasy at this moment by leading their leagues.
</P>
<P>
   And what we all need now is a stoppage in play, starting in 45
minutes. Because if your team is like mine, this lead is not going
to be able to hang on to the ledge much longer.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, strictly hypothetical mind you, say you have a
four-point lead heading into the week. And let's say you lead a
pack of FIVE others in the saves category, only you have lost your
closer, Randy Myers, to the National League, which means all five
of those teams on your heels will now pass you in that category.
</P>
<P>
   This is what's known as a slow death.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for those who lost Randy Johnson. Replacing his
innings with a starter off the scrap pile will introduce your ERA
and WHIP to the world of pain. Unless you really luck out and all
your competition goes into the toilet, your team is going to fade. &QL; 
The dead weight &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same players that get you to the top can also bring you back
down. Pudge Rodriguez of the Rangers is hitting .205 this month. He
could use a few days off, but the AL West race is too tight so he
won't get them.
</P>
<P>
   But at least he's playing. Those counting on Cecil Fielder's
numbers can stop counting, although he'll get a few at-bats with
the Indians now, particularly since David Justice is in such a
slump (29 for 122) and injured Jim Thome is out for another month.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, it helps to have some guys not play. Paul
Sorrento is 6 for 55 with two RBIs in his past 22 games. Blech!
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sele has won once and has a 7.04 ERA since the All-Star
Game.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Mesa has been pretty awful since joining the Giants, but he
has won four games and that's all a fantasy owner cares about.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Hernandez is hitting .171 since the Cubs traded Kevin Orie,
but that's still better than Orie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hot stuff &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ray Lankford is feasting on all the walks Mark McGwire gets.
He's hitting .342 with 11 homers and 42 RBIs in 35 games since the
break. McGwire is hitting just over .200 lately _ no way to catch
Maris.
</P>
<P>
   Brady Anderson is red-hot, belting five homers last week.
Teammate Chris Hoiles is batting higher than .270 and is hitting
grand slams. Mike Simms of Texas slugged three HRs and hit .529
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Smith of Tampa Bay is hitting over .300 and has been
inserted into the 3-hole in the Devil Rays' order.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman has turned himself into a keeper, batting higher
than .300 and more than 30 steals.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter, of 0-for-22 fame, is hitting .364 over the past
two weeks. But he's not going to come close to his 74 steals of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's Mike Maddux hasn't allowed an earned run in a month.
He's the type of sleeper who can help maintain a good ERA and WHIP.
The D-Backs' Willie Banks is pitching almost as well, as are Dan
Miceli and Donne Wall. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nice problem to have &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will try to find a spot in the lineup for Chili
Davis. They tested Darryl Strawberry in left field last week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
See ya Bip &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bip Roberts says he is considering retiring after the season if
the A's don't make an offer. Don't hold your breath, Bip. One of
'98's great lines came from Royals game announcer Josh Lewin when
he said the next time Bip is involved in a brawl, it could be the
first 49-on-1 fight in the history of the game. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
