<SLUG> BC-OUT-STEEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE AIM _ NOW DO IT IN A HURRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PIRU, Calif. _ They practice with pellet guns because the real
things are banned in their country, but the Japanese shooters have
managed top finishes.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel aide to the president of Ecuador will be competing
while his boss is off having surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And the defending champ is an Australian.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for a global smorgasbord of the quickest draws in
the West will be here starting today as the 15th World Speed
Shooting Championships kick off at this tiny citrus outpost in
Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance for someone to see the Michael Jordans of the
shooting world,'' said Cameron Hopkins, editor of American
Handgunner magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the Steel Challenge, the event pits more than 200
shooters against steel targets and the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people from all walks of life _ doctors, lawyers, auto
mechanics, construction workers, dentists,'' said co-organizer Mike
Dalton of Mission Hills. ``And they all have one common bond: They
love speed shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Most competitive shooting is done with paper bull's-eyes and
scoring for accuracy, Dalton said. Some spectators _ if you can
even call shooting a spectator sport _ view those contests as
stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with metal targets, Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can the hear the clang of steel and see the reactive
targets bounce and move and smudge as the bullet makes a smear on
the white paint,'' he explained. ``And there are big electronic
timers to follow the action.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants draw handguns from their holsters and fire at five
metal plates set at distances of 8 to 40 yards. Once all are hit,
the clock stops. The process is repeated several times over seven
stages. By day's end, contestants with the lowest combined time win
in each division, which include open, women's, teen, pre-teen (ages
8 to 12), law enforcement, revolver, cowboy single action and team.
</P>
<P>
   There are no scoring demerits for missing, but, Dalton said,
``You penalize yourself if you miss because you are wasting time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there is no governing body to deem the event the official
world championships, it is recognized as the top competition of its
kind, Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The match's executive directors _ Dalton, a San Fernando Police
officer, and Valencia's Mike Fichman _ founded the Steel Challenge
in 1981 and ran it through 1985 before selling the rights. The
buyers operated the match until 1993 before canceling it because of
low attendance and sponsor support.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton and Fichman bought the tourney back in 1995, and, after a
three-year hiatus, the World Speed Shooting Championships were
resurrected last year in Piru. The founders were fueled by stronger
shooter support and an interested industry that now foots a $90,000
tournament budget, covering everything from tents, targets and
trophies to building materials and construction workers' paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   As a private enterprise, money from entry fees and the shooting
industry goes into a revolving fund to assure the continued health
of the Steel Challenge, said Dalton, who won the event's stock gun
division in 1992 with his duty weapon, a Colt .45.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton said, ``Our main thrust is to generate more interest and
get more people shooting, to expose them to something they may not
have seen before and let them experience what handgun shooting is
all about and see the best shooters in the world doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0044 </DOCNO>
