<P>
   BLIND-GARDENER (Shelter Island, N.Y.) _ Gardening has few
heroes, but William Price, 84, is surely one of them. Blind for
more than 50 years, he does all his gardening by himself, once
someone else turns the soil with a rototiller in the spring.
``Nobody else has set foot in this garden to work in it except
me,'' Price said fiercely, standing in his 45 by 50 foot plot,
which is filled with vegetables and flowers. By Mac Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT6,7) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-SUMMER (Undated) _ Vacationers with a puritanical streak
are drawn to Maine, where stark blue skies and towering evergreens
meet jagged gray rocks and the endless high-low seething of ocean
tides. Here, even leisure activities have an edge, whether it's
knuckling down to sail in a stiff wind or charging up graveled
hills on a bike. Writers like E.B. White and Robert McCloskey have
found Maine rich in material for moral tales of innocence unsettled
by nature's unpredictability. Ralph Lauren and Martha Stewart can
only dream of bottling this essence of virtuous American
simplicity. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   BARD-ARTS-CENTER (Annandale on Hudson, N.Y.) _ Bard College, a
small liberal arts college on 550 acres here, wants to build a
knock-your-socks-off building, a sculptural shell to show off
music, drama and dance. Designed by Frank O. Gehry, an architect
who is basking in the triumph of his Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao,
Spain, the $28-million Bard Performing Arts Center would have some
of the same sweeping, fluttering silvery roofs, some of the same
draftsmen-defying curves as its Spanish sister-under-the-skin _ and
some crinkles thrown in. There is only one problem. A lot of people
think it's in the wrong spot. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT3,4) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   UPS-DESIGN (Undated) _ Recently, Michael Beirut, a graphic
designer and partner at Pentagram, a firm known for nurturing the
eclectic visions of its partners, has been busy examining the
corporate identity of the United Parcel Service. His first instinct
was to introduce a little drama into the life of this nearly
century-old shipping company by changing the color of its trucks.
Maybe UPS trucks could be a lot of different colors, he suggested,
like M&AMP;M candies, with some of the trucks remaining the familiar
deep, chocolate brown. By Karrie Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   NANTUCKET-DUMP (Undated) _ Nantucket Island, off the coast of
Massachusetts, harbor to generations of 19th-century whaling
captains and haven to 20th-century summer residents, rich with
stretches of unspoiled beach and rotten with wooden sailboats and
shingled cottages weathered the gray of a widow's hair, has a local
scene that doesn't show up on the postcards. A popular decorating
and renovation resource, islanders call it the Madaket Mall. What
it is _ is the dump. By Kimberley Stevens.
</P>
