<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ SOON TO JOIN 40-40 CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez is on the verge of becoming the
third player ever to reach 40 home runs and 40 stolen bases in the
same season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who had 36 home runs and 36 stolen bases entering
Wednesday's game, will probably rewrite most every offensive record
every held by a shortstop before he's done playing. Just last week
he became the fourth youngest player to reach 100 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew at the beginning of the year Alex was going to do it,''
said Jose Canseco, who along with Barry Bonds are the only players
to achieve 40-40 in one season. ``In fact, when I first met him, I
told him he was going to do it, get 40-40. Right now, I don't think
either one is going to be tough for Alex. I think he's already
there. I think he'll do it within two weeks, three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's 1998 numbers project to nearly a 50-50 season.
Entering Wednesday's game, the three-time All-Star was on pace to
hit 47 home runs and steal 48 bases. Canseco, who often boasted of
becoming a member of the 50-50 club, now scoffs at anyone being
capable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's impossible,'' Canseco said. ''I just don't see
it happening.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rodriguez, who last year became the first player other than
Cal Ripken to start an All-Star Game at shortstop for the American
League since 1983, hit his 100th home run last week at 23 years 16
days, he passed Johnny Bench (23 years, 161 days) and Hank Aaron
(23, 191). He trails only Mel Ott (22, 132), Tony Conigliaro (22,
197) and Eddie Mathews (22, 292).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a marvelous year,'' Mariners Manager Lou Piniella
said. ``He's a marvelous player. He can do anything that needs to
be done on the baseball field. He seems to be getting better and
better. The young man can play, period.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The two-headed monster &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Myers, who has 347 career saves, insists he will be fine in
his new role for San Diego for the remainder of this season, which
will include being the primary set-up pitcher for Padres closer
Trevor Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with whatever role they put me in,'' Myers
said. ``If I can help get the ball to Trevor or take some of the
workload off him, I will. Basically I'm there to help Trevor and
solidify the bullpen, especially on the left side. I'll do whatever
I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   A potential problem will occur next season if Myers is still
with the Padres. There is little chance Myers and Hoffman could
co-exist for a full season sharing the closing duties, let alone
having Myers return to a role as a set-up pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were going to go out and get a left-handed reliever,
well, we just went out and got the best one we ever could,''
pitching coach Dave Stewart said. ``Overall, our bullpen has been
good all year. But Myers makes us better. He can deal. That's why
he has 300-and-some saves.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's front office feels confident it will be able to
trade Myers, and the $12 million he will be owed the next two
seasons, over the winter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
You, you're fired &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reggie Jackson and George Steinbrenner's often strained
relationship, is on the outs in Yankee-land once again. Jackson
resigned from his post as special assistant to Steinbrenner last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner became furious after reading a quote from Jackson
in a magazine story where Jackson used a vulgarity to describe the
Yankee boss. Whatever happens between these two strong-willed
personalities, Jackson said the two will forever be linked because
of the Yankees tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I don't think it'll be easy to work things out,'' said
Jackson, whose No. 44 is one of the many retired numbers at Yankee
Stadium, ``I think it could be, because I'm a Yankee.''
</P>
<P>
   Several sources within the Yankee organization (no, George
Costanza was not one) say Steinbrenner was furious about the
reference and basically pushed for Jackson to resign. Jackson
countered that he was frustrated with his lack of responsibility
within the front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't work out the way I wanted it to,'' Jackson
said. ``I wished I could've done more. I was frustrated because I
couldn't make a larger contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   This book, no doubt, will have more chapters. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Holding out for more &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jack McKeon, who has helped bring the Cincinnati Reds out of the
funk that previous Manager Ray Knight dragged them into, has been
offered a one-year contract extension that offers him a small
raise.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon, who recently guided the Reds to 15 victories in a
16-game stretch, is holding out for a larger raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stepped into a difficult situation that was a mess, got
things straightened out around here, did a lot of (public
relations) work in the community, kept the team out of all the
controversy that always seems to be here and worked hard with the
media,'' McKeon said. ``That has to be worth something.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon, known for his quick wit, which sometimes offends his
players and other managers, offered up these two gems in the last
10 days:
</P>
<P>
   On why he attends church every day: ``With the way this team
plays, I have to go to church every day.''
</P>
<P>
   And after his Reds beat Milwaukee on consecutive nights by the
scores of 17-0 and 4-0: ``If we shut 'em out, we have a chance to
win.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
