<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS STARTER FEELING AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Montreal right-handed pitcher Dustin Hermanson looked right
at home while striking out eight Diamondbacks in an 8-2 Montreal
victory at Bank One Ballpark on Wednesday, it figures.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Hermanson lives in north Phoenix and says he'd
love to play for Arizona someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful place to play,'' Hermanson said. ``How can
you not like going to a ballpark that closes when it's hot and has
real grass on the field?''
</P>
<P>
   If Hermanson hopes to play his real home games at Bank One
Ballpark, he's making a fair sales pitch. His victory was his third
victory in three starts against Arizona. In those three games he's
yielded only five earned runs in 23 innings _ a 1.96 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is,'' he said. ``I try to pitch the same
against every team. I've pitched better than that without
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermanson said the Diamondbacks are somewhat like the Expos, who
have won only four more games than Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a young, up-and-coming team looking for their talent
to progress and stick together,'' he said. ``You can't have success
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermanson was in complete command, limiting the Diamondbacks to
one hit _ a Karim Garcia bloop single to right _ through 5 innings.
Bernard Gilkey touched him for a solo home run in the sixth and
Matt Williams hit his second home run in as many nights in the
seventh before Hermanson gave way to Shayne Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went after them,'' said Hermanson, who began the season
in the bullpen. ``I had a good slider, and I kept changing speed.
It's like I tell everybody, every inning is a closer-inning . I try
to pitch with a closer's mentality.'' &QL; 
Milestone &QL; 
Montreal Manager Felipe Alou found a bottle of champagne waiting
for him after the victory. It was his 521st victory as manager of
the Expos, moving him past Buck Rodgers (1985-91) and to the top of
the club's all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen champagne since the 1962 playoffs,'' Alou
joked. ``I didn't think they used champagne anymore. I thought they
would buy beer. Champagne's too expensive.'' &QL; 
Oops &QL; 
A security guard stationed next to the bleachers down the
first-base line committed a cardinal sin _ he interfered with a
ball hit by Montreal's Brad Fullmer in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently thought the ball had gone foul, picked it up and
chucked it into the stands. But the ball was fair and in play.
Fullmer was awarded a ground-rule double, which might have been a
break for the Diamondbacks. The ball was headed into the corner and
might have resulted in a triple.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, the security guard was re-assigned to another area
of the ballpark between innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to our guy in charge of security (Sean Maguire) and
told him to just talk to him and let him know he committed a
serious offense,'' club President Rich Dozer said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozer said he did not know the security man's name. &QL;  &QL; 
Snake bites &QL;  &QL; 
The Diamondbacks worked out Dave Licini, an 18-year-old outfielder
from South Bend, Ind., but did not immediately offer him a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Licini a 6-foot-4, 202-pound undrafted free agent has committed
as a walk-on to Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Cory Lidle will undergo ligament-replacement surgery on
his right, throwing, elbow today in Los Angeles. Reknowned
orthopedic surgeon Lewis Yocum will perform the procedure, which is
the same one done on former All-Star Tommy John. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
