<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-HNS &LR;      08-20 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
AL powers put 
Rangers in hole
<TEXT>
<P>
   Softer schedule offers hope
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ARLINGTON _ Johnny Oates whistled on his way to work, strolling
down the tunnel, bounding up the dugout steps and taking the
playing field with purposeful strides.
</P>
<P>
   Whistling by the graveyard? Whistling in the dark?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. Just whistling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those other games, they're over,'' the Rangers' manager said
with a smile. ``Sure, it's been frustrating, but you keep plugging
along.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the idea as the Rangers returned home Wednesday night
after a 2-6 road trip through Cleveland, New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-1 win over the Cleveland Indians behind a combined
five-hitter by Aaron Sele and John Wetteland helped ease the pain
of the road just traveled, but the trek was still a hot topic of
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The good news?
</P>
<P>
   Texas was in every game on the trip. Four of the losses were by
one or two runs. In each of the last three, the Rangers led in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The bad?
</P>
<P>
   Texas lost each of those last three, including both ends of a
drizzly Tuesday doubleheader in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the Rangers scored as many runs (35) as they
gave up on the trip, bunching 16 of them in an 11-run win over the
Yankees wasn't the most efficient way to spread the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Going 1-for-15 with runners in scoring position in the last
three games didn't help much, either.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, what had been a three-game lead over Anaheim in
the American League West has become a one-game deficit. And the
stiff competition hasn't ended for the Rangers, with the Indians in
again tonight and the relentless Yankees due for three over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   So what to make of a close-but-no-cigar run through the AL
gantlet?
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Will Clark opted for the happier spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play bad baseball, but we didn't find a way to win,
and that's what we have to do,'' he said. ``We know we can play
with these guys, but we still have to go out and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With 37 games to go, the Rangers face a challenge if they are to
win their second AL West title in three years.
</P>
<P>
   After this eight-game homestand (Detroit comes in for three
after the Yankees leave), Texas finishes with 19 of its last 30 on
the road, including the last seven (three at Anaheim, four at
Seattle).
</P>
<P>
   For now, Oates hopes to minimize the damage against the top
clubs and still be alive when the Tigers, White Sox and Twins start
coming around again. The next four days figure prominently in that
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a manager, you certainly know it's going to be a tough
period, playing the three best clubs in the American League,'' he
said. ``It'll drive you crazy if the third game into it, you start
thinking about the 13th or 14th.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't prevent fans and media from charting the progress _
or lack of same _ as the Rangers sank slowly in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's bounce-back win, Texas had dropped eight of
10 overall, beginning with the last two games of the previous
homestand. The much-discussed stretch of 17 games in 18 days
(featuring seven with the Yankees, six with Boston and four with
Cleveland) had produced just a 4-8 record as the Rangers stumbled
back from New England.
</P>
<P>
   At the July 31 trade deadline, Texas supposedly fortified itself
for just such a challenge. In deals with the Cardinals and Marlins,
general manager Doug Melvin picked up a front-line starting pitcher
(Todd Stottlemyre) and shortstop (Royce Clayton) from St. Louis for
struggling lefthander Darren Oliver and young third baseman
Fernando Tatis.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin plugged the hole at third by getting Todd Zeile from
Florida for two minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're better equipped than we were three weeks ago,''
Oates said. ``I'm talking about veterans who know how to play the
game, how to handle tight situations.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the impact has been marginal.
</P>
<P>
   In three starts as a Ranger, Stottlemyre is 2-1 but has lasted a
total of just 15 innings, compiling a very Ranger-like 6.89 ERA.
Clayton is hitting .311 with five doubles and eight RBIs. Zeile is
hitting just .232 with six errors in his last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Oates insists his team is better with Stottlemyre
(instead of the disappointing Oliver); Clayton (who replaces the
statue-like Kevin Elster); and Zeile, whose three home runs since
coming to Texas match Tatis' total in 330 at-bats prior to the
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, the manager says, is that the additions can't do it
all themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other people have to keep doing their jobs,'' Oates said.
``Juan (Gonzalez) has to continue to hit; Pudge (Rodriguez) has to
hit. Will has to do his thing at first, and Rusty (Greer) has to do
his thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer (.298) has come on after a slow start but went 0-for-5 in
the doubleheader Tuesday. Rodriguez hit just .258 over a 24-game
stretch. And no one is talking about Hack Wilson's RBI record
anymore after watching Gonzalez (.294, 34 home runs, 120 RBIs)
drive in just 19 runs since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all this, the starting pitching _ never better
than a shaky proposition _ has broken down. Tuesday, for example,
neither John Burkett nor Rick Helling survived the sixth inning,
putting further strain on an overworked bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we need is a break or two, and it can turn the whole
tide,'' Clark said. ``That's what we're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent gloom and doom, the Rangers can see a parting
of the clouds on the horizon. The what-goes-around-comes-around
schedule is about to subject the Angels to a similar test.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday, Texas' next 19 games are against Detroit, the
White Sox, Minnesota, Kansas City and Tampa Bay, teams that were a
combined 94 games under .500 through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim, meanwhile, plays 10 games in New York (five in four
days), Boston (three) and Cleveland (two) beginning next week.
</P>
<P>
   So if the Rangers can get to Sunday without losing too much more
ground, the sun may come out again. ``There's only one barometer,''
Oates said. ``That's where you are at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting there needn't be all fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
