<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2712 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROYALS-BOS     08-20 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROYALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY POWERS RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ So now the Red Sox have another
righthanded-hitting DH screaming to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Jim Leyritz, Mike Stanley didn't have to say a word.
</P>
<P>
   A steady presence since he quietly rejoined the Red Sox in
Anaheim from Toronto on the last day of July, Stanley called
attention to himself here Wednesday night with his bat, driving in
six runs with two two-run homers sandwiched around a two-run single
in an 11-1 win over the Kansas City Royals at Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With 26 home runs, Stanley matched his career high. He also
became the first Sox player to drive in a half-dozen runs in a game
this season. The Sox had 14 hits, including three apiece by John
Valentin and Damon Buford, against ex-Cardinal Brian Barber,
attempting a comeback in the American Legaue with a surgically
repaired elbow, and two relievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came here trying to fit in,'' said Stanley, Dan
Duquette's choice to fill the void left by the trade of the unhappy
Leyritz to San Diego in June. ``It was a nice, easy adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Staked to an 8-0 lead after two innings, knuckleballer Tim
Wakefield went the distance for his second complete game, throwing
a five-hitter for his 15th win of the season, one short of the
career high he set in 1995, the last time the Sox went to the
playoffs. Wakefield, who walked five and did not strike out a
batter, was coming off a game in which he gave up 11 hits and nine
runs (seven earned) in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   The difference Wednesday night? ``I wish I knew,'' Wakefield
said. ``They didn't hit the ball. I don't know. Last (time) was one
of those starts where it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this has been a good year as far as run support. I never
complain about too many runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's win established a high-water mark for the Sox
this season: 24 games over .500 (74-50), their best record since
they ended the '95 season 28 games above the break-even point.
</P>
<P>
   The win kept them seven games in front of Baltimore in the
wild-card race. The Orioles also won Wednesday night and are 30-8
since the All-Star break, a Yankee-like pace they would seem hard
pressed to maintain for the last six weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to try and get as greedy as we can get,'' Stanley
said. ``Every time we look up, Baltimore is still winning. We'd
like to think they can't keep that up, especially where we have six
games with them the last two weeks, including the last four at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to have a five-games-or-better lead in the last four
days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are 12-6 since Stanley reclaimed the place in the
clubhouse he lost when he was traded to the Yankees last August for
two pitchers _ one of whom, Tony Armas Jr., Duquette turned around
and used in the Pedro Martinez deal.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley is batting .317 since his return and has 18 RBIs in 17
games. ``He sat down in front of his locker,'' said Mo Vaughn, who
was aboard for both of Stanley's home runs Wednesday night, ``and
it was like he never left.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley drove center fielder Johnny Damon to the wall in
left-center to catch his drive off lefthander Chris Haney in the
sixth, a ball that carried farther than Stanley thought it would.
He flied out to right in his last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley rejected the notion that he felt pressure to contribute
immediately upon his return to the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt different from last year when I went to New York,
where I felt like I had to prove something,'' he said. ``This year,
coming back here, I was so comfortable. I'd played for Jimy
(Williams) and knew so many guys here, it was easy to slide right
in and contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox arrived here on the heels of the Yankees, who beat
the Royals 10 straight times for the first season series sweep in
the 96-year history of the Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are stacked on top of stacked,'' Royals DH Terry
Pen-dleton said Wednesday. ``They're the best team I've seen in my
15 years in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox haven't been quite as dominant against Kansas City, a
past tormentor, but they've come close. Wednesday night's win made
the Red Sox 8-2 against the Royals, the first time Boston has won
as many as eight games against Kansas City since 1979. This after
their doubleheader sweep Tuesday night against Texas gave the Sox
their first winning record (6-5) against the Rangers in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Sox and Yankees, the Royals are 2-18. Against the
rest of the American League, they're a .500 team (53-53).
</P>
<P>
   House of horrors? The Royals have the worst home record in the
league, 23-42.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming off the last couple of wins, we want to keep things
rolling,'' Stanley said. ``We can't let down. We want to push
hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
