<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
   NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2473 --
August 20, 1998 We are offering the following articles for sale.
Please contact us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl
Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. AVERTING DOOMSDAY What can we Earthlings do if a meteorite
heading directly for our planet is more than just some Hollywood
scriptwriter's idea for the latest blockbuster? Scientists and
engineers have been wrestling with that question and one of them
believes he has the most effective method : using an experimental
rocket engine or ion drive to send a large nuclear payload into
space to deflect the meteorite. By Jeffrey Winters. From Discover
magazine. 750 words + photo. (Story also available in Spanish.) 2.
CELEBRITY ENDORSERS CAN BE RISKY BUSINESS What happens when
celebrities are caught in compromising situations while wearing
designer labels with which they have no commercial association? For
example, Hugh Grant wearing a Tommy Hilfiger cap when arrested for
soliciting a prostitute, or Monica Lewinsky wearing a Donna Karan
beret to a November 1996 photo opportunity with President Bill
Clinton? In this report, company executives discuss the impact of
these unplanned product placements. By Eric Wilson. From Women's
Wear Daily. 1,000 words. 3. WHICH PARENT-KID BATTLES ARE WORTH
FIGHTING? Kids don't come into the world with good judgment, good
manners or even good sense. A large part of the job of parent is
finding ways to get kids to want to do what they should be doing.
Here is a guide to helping them, age by age. By Ava L. Siegler.
From Child magazine. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
MARKETING THE MILLENIUM The host of marketing ideas sparked by the
millennium is reflected in new fashion brands. A look at Year 2000,
01-01-00 and Y2K. By Arthur Friedman. From Women's Wear Daily.
1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   5. CLIMBING THROUGH THE BRAIN The formation of the cortex of the
human brain relies on the mass migration of tens of billions of
nerve cells through the fetal brain. A Parisian doctor presented
with a little boy with ``smooth-brain syndrome,'' a Parisian
researcher who collected and analyzed fetal brains and a Harvard
scientist experimenting with monkey fetuses played critical roles
in our understanding of the mysterious process. By Robert Kunzig.
From Discover magazine. 1,500 words + photos. (Story also available
in Spanish.) 
____________________________________________________________________
____ 6. LANDMARK HEART STUDY TURNS 50 The Framingham Heart Study,
based in New England in the U.S., turns 50 in September, with two
generations now contributing invaluable data on heart disease, diet
and health. One conclusion is that lifestyle changes are proving
hard to make. By Richard A. Marini. 1,400 words + 350-word sidebar.
______________________________________________________________ 7.
HEART TRACING CAN POINT TO HIGH HEART ATTACK RISK Doctors may be
able to tell which patients are at high risk of having a heart
attack simply by looking at their patients' electrocardiograms,
according to a Dutch study. Patients with an abnormal pattern
visible on standard electrocardiograms were nearly four times more
likely to die of a heart attack. By Michael McCarthy. From The
Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
SIGNALLING A NEW TARGET FOR ASTHMA TREATMENT With the steady rise
in the incidence of asthma in the developed countries, more
effective ways of treating this distressing and even
life-threatening disease are continually being sought.
Immunologists are now looking more closely at the biochemical
factors that provoke and maintain the chronic inflammation and help
to develop hyper-responsiveness. By Eleanor Lawrence. From Nature
News Service. 600 words. (N/A France and Spain.)
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
MANY PROSTITUTES SUFFER COMBAT DISORDER, STUDY FINDS The world's
oldest profession may also be among its most traumatizing. A new
study has found that a serious psychiatric illness resulting from
exposure to physical danger is more common among prostitutes than
among troops who have weathered combat duty. By Abigail Zuger. From
The New York Times Science Times. 600 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
From NEW SCIENTIST magazine (N/A Australia, New Zealand, Brazil) A.
The Crying Game : Colic, a condition in which babies cry for hours
on end for no known reason, may be an evolutionary adaptation to
weed out impatient parents. C. The Arbitrary Ape : Our ability to
behave and think randomly may lie at the root of human intelligence
and creativity, setting us apart from other animals.
</P>
