<HEADER>
A3050 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SAFETY-HNS &LR;      08-20 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACADEMY OF SCIENCES RECOMMENDS FOOD SAFETY CZAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To reduce the threat of food-borne illness, the
National Academy of Sciences on Thursday recommended the
appointment of a national food safety czar with the power to manage
federal food safety programs now run by 12 different government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   That person would oversee all federal food safety activities,
including inspection, surveillance, investigation of food-related
illnesses, research and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``This recommendation envisions an identifiable, high-ranking,
presidentially appointed head, who would direct and coordinate
federal activities and speak to the nation, giving federal food
safety efforts a single voice,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Sciences is a private non-profit
research organization that advises the government on scientific and
health issues.
</P>
<P>
   The 194-page report _ entitled ``Ensuring Safe Food From
Production to Consumption'' _ concluded that food safety laws are
outdated and that efforts to rid the food supply of contamination
are hampered by a fragmented federal structure.
</P>
<P>
   The food safety system in the United States ``lacks a central
authority and is hampered by old laws that don't allow flexible
responses to today's threats,'' said John C. Bailar III, chairman
of the Department of Health Studies at the University of Chicago,
who chaired the 13-member scientific panel which wrote the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the challenges to ensuring safe food change and grow more
complex, it is crucial that we rethink how to address the greatest
threats to human health,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report urged Congress to eliminate carcass-by-carcass
inspection of meat and poultry and replace it with scientific
testing for disease-causing germs.
</P>
<P>
   It also recommended a single set of regulations for all foods,
replacing the current patchwork system spread out among a dozen
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Under present practice, for example, the pepperoni line in a
pizza factory is inspected daily by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, while the cheese line is checked once in 10 years by
the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The food industry reacted to the report by lambasting the
recommendation for restructuring the food regulatory system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling for a wholesale reorganization of federal
bureaucracies in Washington will not do anything to ensure the
safety of our food supply,'' said Cal Collier, senior vice
president and general counsel for Kraft Foods, Inc., who chairs a
food industry group called the Food Safety\Independent Food Agency
Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   The report also advised Congress to restrict food imports to
those countries with food safety standards equivalent to those in
the United States. President Clinton has endorsed such an approach
and Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., has introduced the legislation in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., and
Reps. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., and Frank Pallone, D-N.J. have also
sponsored legislation that would combine the 12 government agencies
into a single Food Safety Administration. But that proposal has
faced resistance from the food industry and from the federal
agencies that now oversee food safety.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio hailed the NAS report as ``common-sense recommendations
that will improve our food safety system.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin's spokeswoman Melissa Merz said, ``The message in the
report is clear that American consumers and families will benefit
from a single coordinated approach to food safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Smith DeWaal, director of food safety for the Center
for Science in the Public Interest, a Washington advocacy group,
said a food-safety czar with power over the budgets of food safety
agencies would be a good interim step, but is ``not the final
answer to the food safety problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of the president of the United States, no one is really
in charge of the safety of the U.S. food supply,'' DeWaal said. ``I
don't see how a single person can really run the program unless
there is a single food safety agency.'
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. General Accounting Office has estimated that
contaminated food causes 9,100 deaths a year and as many as 81
million illnesses in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Disease outbreaks from food-borne germs are likely to become
increasingly frequent in the future, according to the Journal of
the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   The $350,000 NAS study was paid for with federal money in the
1998 Department of Agriculture spending bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
