A3054 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-CO     08-20 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Reaching for the old gang
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 23, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The editorial board of the Miami News has not met for
almost 10 years. That's because the newspaper has been out of
business that long. But, after hearing Bill Clinton's brief,
incomplete talk to the nation last Monday, I wished the board was
still around _ to keep me from going off the deep end.
</P>
<P>
   That's the value of newspaper editorial boards. They keep most
editors from being journalistic despots. Often, the editorial board
of the Miami News had a position different from that of the editor,
and the position of the board usually prevailed. Yes, I had a veto
power and used it once but shouldn't have. Overruling the editorial
board can undermine its confidence. Besides, collectively, they
were far wiser than me.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to Clinton's talk, I felt strongly that the man
ought to resign for the good of the country. It wasn't about sex.
It had all to do with him lying to his country, his closest
advisers and, apparently, to his wife and child for seven months _
dragging the nation through a voyeuristic purgatory.
</P>
<P>
   Before I said that in writing, however, I felt a need for the
advice the old editorial board would impart when they saw my knee
begin twitching. So I called them one by one to get their thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   It did not surprise me that I was the only one wanting to seek
Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   I will tell you that I believed this board to be somewhere
between moderate and liberal on the political spectrum but will add
that conservatives in Miami considered it quite left-leaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the arguments against Clinton is on a scale of being
great,'' one responded to my query. ``This isn't Watergate. There's
a lot more going on; there's plenty of wrong on Ken Starr's side.
Hey, Bill Clinton's always been a liar; we re-elected him knowing
that. He's done a good job as president. He stands for what others
in Washington don't stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in him,'' said another former board member.
``He came off as incredibly selfish. But I don't think he ought to
resign and I certainly don't think he ought to be impeached. Every
president comes up against groupies. I feel sorry for the people
around him. He did everybody wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   I pushed back. ``You gave me every reason why he should be gone,
but you concluded, without reason, that he should stay. How do you
justify it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't,'' she answered, ``other than we don't need this at
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   I reserved what I believed would be the last call to our most
outspoken editorial board member. His positions usually were
illustrated with theatrical flair and it is obvious he has not
changed these past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I heard him speak, I wanted him to resign, too,'' he
told me. ``But then I read that smirking editorial in the Wall
Street Journal and, well, I can't have Kenneth Starr winning. Once
they get Clinton out, they'll go after Al Gore. And when they get
him, we're left with Newt. God spare us that!''
</P>
<P>
   There was yet another call to make _ to my publisher, my boss at
the time. While he did not sit on the editorial board, I consulted
often with him, as a publisher ultimately is responsible for the
conduct (and positions) of the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't want Clinton to resign or be impeached either. ``Yes,
Clinton has debased the presidency,'' the former publisher said.
``But our stakes in this world are so large that this country can't
face such an upheaval. We've got to make the best of a very bad
situation. The office of the independent prosecutor has become a
fourth branch of government; it has enormous power _ too much
power. We need to go another route.''
</P>
<P>
   So, this telephone reunion of sorts has left me out in the cold.
My former advisers (and boss) say we need to hang on to Clinton. My
heart tells me to call for his resignation, but the people I trust
journalistically tell me that this is no time to jerk my knee.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we keep the guy around. But to anyone who believes
anything he's got to say, I've got a bridge in Brooklyn I want to
sell you.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
