<HEADER>
A3110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV     08-20 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV08/23 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: JUST HOW LOW CAN WE GO?
 &HT;    For use Sunday, Aug. 23 and thereafter
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON ``The bitch set me up,'' said the mayor of
Washington, right after being caught on videotape smoking crack
cocaine in a downtown hotel room by an FBI sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did have a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky that was not
appropriate,'' said the president of the United States, months
after being caught having sex with a young intern near the Oval
Office by a federal grand jury probe.
</P>
<P>
   If a shamed Bill Clinton stages a comeback, it will be because a
unashamed Marion Barry serves as his de facto political role model.
Such are the wretched depths to which we have sunk in our public
life.
</P>
<P>
   Barry's constituents reelected him in 1994 because they believed
that he had been unjustly treated by the prosecutors and the press.
The Washington jury that had found Barry guilty of a misdemeanor,
thereby limiting his sentence and enabling his subsequent revival,
reflected that constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Constitution, the House Judiciary Committee's 35
members will serve as the president's initial jurors after they get
the independent counsel's report on Clinton's shenanigans. His best
hope of escaping impeachment hearings rests on his poll-driven
belief that the public wants this scandal to go away.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 20 minutes into the networks' analysis of the speech
in which Clinton attacked Ken Starr, his court-appointed nemesis,
ABC switched its viewers back to pre-season Monday Night Football.
Assuming Clinton survives in office, it was a decision worthy of a
gilt-edged State Dinner invitation.
</P>
<P>
   An honest Clinton speech about his lies about his affair could
have borrowed a phrase from Barry, namely: ``The bitches set me
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton believes, not without cause, that he and Monica Lewinsky
were drawn into a sting operation by Linda Tripp and her onetime
literary agent, Lucianne Goldberg, aimed at gathering evidence of a
sexual liaison.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg got Tripp to suggest to Lewinsky that she use a courier
service run by Goldberg's brother to send love letters to Clinton.
Goldberg then told a Newsweek reporter how to get those billing
records.
</P>
<P>
   Next, they arranged for Paula Jones' legal team to get
Lewinsky's name. Then Tripp briefed Starr's team and wore an FBI
wire while eliciting more damning admissions from Lewinsky. That
same Friday evening, she briefed Jones' lawyers on that wire job.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Clinton walked into a perjury trap. While he
knew that Lewinsky was on Jones' witness list, he also knew that
Lewinsky had filed a false affidavit denying an affair. If they
both lied, they could steer safely through their depositions, he
reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   But the precise questioning rattled Clinton. And his lawyers
failed to seek a protective order from the federal judge _ who was
in the room and who would later throw out the Lewinsky line of
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thinks Starr must have been wise to Tripp's Friday
dealings with Jones &AMP; Co. Starr, who could be disbarred for any
such conduct, denies it.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, here are two truths to ponder: The Washington
press corps remains addicted to a sex scandal and most news
consumers could care less about the president's addiction to lying.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
