A3114 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLADE21-COX     08-20 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLADE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Blade'' has some sharp karate moves, little else
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Here's how the producers of ``Blade'' have
chosen to hype the film's title character, pulled from the pages of
a lesser-known comic book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power of an immortal. The soul of a human. The heart of a
hero,'' declares the picture's poster, featuring an armor-suited
Wesley Snipes against a blood-red background.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the makings of another ho-hum summer action
flick.
</P>
<P>
   So far, we've had a lizard that was lifeless (``Godzilla'') and
a meteor shower that was more like a lukewarm bath
(``Armageddon''). Now, we've got vampires who _ guess what? _ come
to suck your blood.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``Blade'' has a better premise than that. And it's
been a few years since vampires have had a decent turn on screen.
This is a film with potential _ and plasma _ to spare.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that somewhere along the line, ``Blade'' loses sight
of its ambitions and accepts being run-of-the-mill. Vampires take a
back seat to karate matches: Think Vincent Price-meets-Bruce Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is a dark, mysterious urban America, where an
ancient order of vampires has run of the city. Unbeknownst to
average citizens, they control the police, the government and _ of
course _ the blood banks. But the new blood (no pun intended) among
these vampires wants to put an end to the underground trafficking
and control the humans openly and outright. Led by the devil-eyed
Deacon Frost (Stephen Dorff), they're the Generation X of
blood-suckers.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Blade (Snipes), a half-human, half-vampire who's
determined to put an end to the cult's reign (chalk it up to his
sentimental Homo sapiens side). Honoring the traditions of the
action genre, he's a lean, mean fighting machine, throwing karate
chops here and there and relying upon no small arsenal of weapons.
Frost tries to persuade him to switch sides. Blade, who enlists the
support of an aging male partner (Kris Kristofferson) and an
attractive female hematologist (N'bushe Wright), is determined to
keep fighting the good fight.
</P>
<P>
   And so the fights, captured with a fair deal of computer
animation, are the meat of ``Blade.'' Directed by Stephen
Norrington, the film maintains a nimble pace _ and it's nice to see
action sequences that don't involve ridiculous car chases or
exploding buildings but honest hand-to-hand combat. Still, it's
nothing you're not going to encounter in any B picture from Hong
Kong. As Gertrude Stein might have put it, a karate chop is a
karate chop is a karate chop.
</P>
<P>
   But with its curious premise, Blade deserves better. Here, the
vampires aren't the ghoulish stuff of bad black-and-white movies
but something more sinister and real: They're ``La Cosa Nostra''
with fangs, a society that can conform to the ways of the modern
world but does so only to support its underground activities.
</P>
<P>
   As for the acting, Snipes is his usual commanding presence, but
he tempers the part with a bit of well-placed humor. As a
co-producer responsible for the fight sequences, he deserves some
of the credit for the film's cunning sense of blood sport but also
some of the blame for its emphasis on action above premise. The
rest of the cast handle their two-dimensional roles with a
good-natured grace but not much else. For their sake, let's hope
those paychecks had lots of zeroes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
