<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROYAL-PALM21-COX     08-20 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROYAL-PALM21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Royal Palm pioneers ready to move on
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROYAL PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jennie Lou Peeples, 47, is about as
Royal Palm Beach as you get. And that holds for the rest of her
kin, 13 of them, all neighbors and all living within blocks of one
another.
</P>
<P>
   And now, says Peeples, the whole family is plotting a mass
exodus from South Florida to the mountains of North Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the very first family to move into Royal Palm Beach,''
Peeples said recently, with a touch of pride, but added a bit
ruefully: ``We never got any recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   I promised the family all the recognition they could stand if
she would explain why in the blue-eyed world the family wants to
swap Paradise for Hicksville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come over to the house for a glass of my Mama's sweet tea, and
we'll talk about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennie Lou and her sister, Ella Jean Field, 52, grew up in the
three-bedroom, one-bath concrete-block house on Dahlia Drive.
There, on a Sunday afternoon, I was greeted by the sisters and
their parents, Lawton and Verna Lee, and Jennie Lou's daughter,
Gretchen Riddle, 26, and daughter-in-law Jennifer Peeples, 25.
</P>
<P>
   How the Lees came to South Florida is a matter of record. How
they became the first to buy a home in Royal Palm Beach is family
legend.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Lawton and Verna moved from their birthplace of Perry
in North Florida to Canal Point when Lawton got a job in road
maintenance for the Department of Transportation. In 1951, the job
took them to Loxahatchee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In March 1960,'' volunteered Gretchen, ``Grandpa and his
drinking buddy, Leon, came out and bought the first two houses the
same day. Then they called their friend, Mr. (R.L.) Williams to
come out, and he bought the third house. They've been neighbors
ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawton, comfortably stretched out on his recliner, watching the
stock-car races, nodded genially at this confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Verna furnished details: ``Now Mr. Williams was a teetotaler, so
he hadn't been drinking, but they all did put $200 down on the
first three houses that Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses are still next door, and Leon's widow lives just
behind the Lees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payments were $78 a month,'' Lawton added. ``The entire house
cost $9,500.''
</P>
<P>
   (The story was fantastic _ that husbands in their right minds
would buy houses without consulting their wives. ``Well, they just
up and did it,'' reflected Verna, recalling an era when men didn't
tell their wives every little bitty thing.)
</P>
<P>
   Life in the Royal Palm Beach of 1960 was certainly countrified
by today's standards. Folks grew vegetables, dropped in on
neighbors, and hunted and fished almost in their back yards.
Southern Boulevard was two lanes, and Royal Palm Beach Boulevard
was years from connecting north to Okeechobee Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you had,'' recalled Verna, ``was a hardware store and a
7-Eleven on Southern. For your groceries, you had to drive to the
Millers at Four Points on Military Trail.''
</P>
<P>
   The sisters, then 13 and 8, remembered growing up in a
neighborhood where everyone was on a first-name basis. And yet
amenities were not entirely absent. On Southern Boulevard, within
walking distance, was a motel with a restaurant and a pool that was
open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy, tell him about the jailhouse band,'' Ella Jean said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton waved a hand, allowing that she might as well tell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days,'' Ella Jean said, ``prisoners worked on the
roads. Well, at the road camp, some of the prisoners had a little
band, and Daddy would bring them over to the motel pool to play at
our dances. Can you imagine that today?''
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully, I could not imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, you went to jail for stealing candy,'' said Jennie
Lou. ``It's not like now.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it is not like now, and here we come to the crux of why the
daughters and their husbands mean to uproot the entire clan and
light out for the Georgia mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving to Georgia because all the mean people are moving
in to South Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Gretchen, seconded by sister-in-law Jennifer. It was
also, I pointed out, a blanket condemnation of the fine people of
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like living here anymore,'' Jennie Lou explained,
``because it's changed so much. Our house has been broken into. A
few years ago, Jeannie and I were mugged at the Target up on Palm
Beach Lakes Boulevard _ a couple of kids ripped off our purses.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister added: ``In the old days, we could trailer our boats
to the ramp at Dreher Park and leave the trailer unattended. Not
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks nowadays don't respect property, the sisters added, citing
a new park in Royal Palm Beach already defaced with graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you can still picnic at DuBois Park, they agreed. Just
send somebody out at 4:30 a.m. to claim a table.
</P>
<P>
   In their travels, family members have scouted a lot of the
country and have fallen in love with the Blairsville, Ga., area,
just south of the North Carolina line. There, a family can wander
the woods without an armed guard. Property is inexpensive, and,
with 10 acres or so, you could have animals, grow some vegetables
and have room for five families.
</P>
<P>
   But is transplanting 13 people a realistic dream? I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our husbands and our son-in-laws are all contractors,'' Ella
Jean said. ``If we can find a piece of property with a couple of
big houses to fix up, we could all go.''
</P>
<P>
   And everybody is up for this?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd leave today, I want to go so bad,'' Gretchen said. ``And
Grandpa would, too. But we're still working on Grandma. She wants
to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really want to go,'' admitted Verna. ``I don't want to
leave my friends, and I don't much care for the cold weather.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, I reminded Verna, she has a history of going along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if my children and grandchildren all moved up to
Georgia, I know I couldn't be satisfied living here without them.
Whether they're ever going to do it or not, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go,'' Lawton reminded her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' Verna said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
