</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3119 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNIPES-INTERVIEW21-CO     08-20 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNIPES-INTERVIEW21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How Wes has won in Hollywood
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the last times Wesley Snipes came through South Florida,
he was in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   A real hurry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the tall, muscular actor was clocked at speeds up to
120 mph driving his motorcycle on Florida's Turnpike, where he was
eventually stopped by state troopers after a 30-mile chase. In
return, he received a reckless driving charge and was sentenced to
80 hours of community service and six months' probation.
</P>
<P>
   It's a far more relaxed Snipes who greeted members of the press
at a swank South Beach club this past weekend. The 36-year-old
movie star, who next to Denzel Washington may be the most bankable
black actor in Hollywood, is in town to promote his latest film,
the vampire-inspired, action-filled ``Blade,'' which opens on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Snipes, a Florida native, to be one of those
self-important actors who sees a need to justify a film that lacks
much in the way of social statement. He handles inquiries about the
movie's meaning the same way he responds to a question about his
driving habits _ with nothing less than total frankness.
</P>
<P>
   On his driving: ``I haven't been riding (recently) in Florida,''
he says with a knowing laugh, freely adding that he's not about to
slow down when he's out of state. ``That's what the bike is
designed for.''
</P>
<P>
   On the movie: ``It's no profound social commentary,'' he says.
Later, he boils it down to this: ``We're not trying to depict real
life, we're trying to tease and titillate the imagination. . . .
You get your money's worth when you see the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on a comic book, ``Blade'' is a tale of modern-day
vampires. They control all facets of society, from the police to
government, but when push comes to shove, they're still interested
in only one thing: sucking human blood. Their nemesis? A half-man,
half-vampire known as Blade, who's determined to destroy this evil
society before it takes over the world _ and before it turns him
into a pure blood-sucker.
</P>
<P>
   For Snipes, who plays the title character, the film may not be
profound, but it is an important step on the career ladder. After
appearing in nearly 20 movies, playing everything from an architect
who commits adultery (``Jungle Fever'') to an urban drug lord
(``New Jack City'') to a drag queen (``To Wong Foo, Thanks for
Everything! Julie Newmar''), he's finally gotten the chance to
double as actor and co-producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, man,'' he says, trying his best to look casual as
he sports the bulky armor vest that's Blade's trademark garb. ``You
get an opportunity to have some control over the final product. As
an actor for hire, your job usually ends when they say, `Wrap,
cut.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes' specific contributions to ``Blade'' were the fight
scenes he helped shape and choreograph. Drawing upon his 20-plus
years of training in a variety of martial arts, he says he tried to
make his character a ``modern-day warrior'' who utilizes everything
from ancient sword-fighting techniques to contemporary kick-boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to bring in all the flavors, even the stuff we
learned on the street,'' he says. ``We had scenes where I was
hitting cats with bottles and garbage cans.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Snipes admits he has much to learn about the movie-making
process. Although he talks with confidence about plot and
character, saying ``Blade'' has ``the elements that good American
cinema used to have,'' he's a little more clueless when it comes to
the financial side.
</P>
<P>
   ``My authority didn't extend that far,'' he says. ``I was the
cat who was like, `What do you mean we have to cut a scene?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade'' also marks an interesting juncture for Snipes as an
actor. Like Sylvester Stallone, he's clearly in a position to cast
himself as a major action star _ and this film only further cements
that status. But he's got a more meaty dramatic side that he can't
ignore. His previous film was the little noticed ``One Night
Stand,'' directed by Mike Figgis (``Leaving Las Vegas''). His role
as a married man who indulges in a dangerous tryst earned him a
best actor award at the Venice Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   How to account for such a diversity of projects?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just my theater training,'' says Snipes, who moved as a
child from Florida to New York, where he went on to study at the
prestigious High School of Performing Arts. Later, he moved to
Orlando, where he joined a bus-and-truck theater company. ``We
built all the sets, we scripted the whole script and we played all
the characters, so I'm very accustomed to doing that. It's just
fortunate I could do it in film.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Snipes doesn't deny it: He does action films because
that's where the money is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The action films . . . translate internationally and that
broadens your base,'' he explains. ``You can pre-sell a movie now
on your foreign appeal. That makes your pockets fat.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does Snipes do with all his money, other than buy
speedy motorcycles?
</P>
<P>
   Well, he maintains residences in Los Angeles and New York. But
his favorite home may be the 7,000-square-foot, multimillion-dollar
mansion he built in a gated community outside Orlando, the city
where much of his family still lives. ``Cafe Wes'' is what Snipes
calls the none-too-simple spread, a place where he can relax with
friends and relatives (he also has an 8-year-old son from a
marriage that ended in divorce).
</P>
<P>
   As for his next project, Snipes remains undecided. He wants to
produce and star in a film about jazz great Miles Davis, an idol of
his. He's also been rumored to be up for the role of Sammy Davis
Jr. in Martin Scorsese's delayed picture about the Rat Pack. And
there's always the possibility of a ``Blade 2,'' since the movie
ends on a somewhat enigmatic note.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, says Snipes, is you can't predict where his
career will take him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to do a musical, that would be another thing that
people would never have expected me to do,'' he concludes. ``The
objective is to keep mixing it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
