<SLUG> BC-BOX-TOPS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Bogus'' Boxtops?
 &HT;    By Pat Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Fla. _ One group labels itself the Boxtops. Another, the
Box Tops.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is anything but subtle to members of the original
1960s music group _ the one with two words in its name _ who have
taken the copycat group to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely bogus act,'' Rick Levy, manager of the
original Box Tops, said recently. ``That group has no members who
were with the original group. Lenny Longo was never in the group,
never performed and never recorded with the original Box Tops.''
</P>
<P>
   Longo's group is scheduled to appear Friday night at the Lyric
Theatre, where managers were surprised to hear the group coming to
Stuart is not the one that recorded such hits as The Letter and Cry
Like a Baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all new to us,'' Lucy Corley, the Lyric's executive
director, said Wednesday. ``We didn't intend to fool anybody and
had we known about it we wouldn't have booked them.''
</P>
<P>
   Longo claims he has the legal right to use the name and has done
so worldwide for years. He said he never intended to mislead
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our name is not even spelled the same as theirs,'' Longo said.
``We don't claim to be the original group. We're an oldies act, a
show with songs from the '50s to the '70s and a little bit of
comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Longo said Wednesday he was dismayed to learn fliers promoting
the Stuart show stated the ``Boxtops'' will be ``Performing their
hit song, The Letter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I've been trying to take that out (of publicity) for
years and it keeps resurfacing. It should not have been worded that
way and no one cleared it with me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The real duel between both groups eventually may be played out
in federal court in Tennessee, where the original group has sued
Longo and his former agent who obtained the group's trademark in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   The original Box Tops bass player, Bill Cunningham, said
founders of the group split up in 1970 and got back together after
he contacted them in 1996. The original group recently finished a
new album that has been released in Europe and should be offered in
this country in a few weeks, their agent Rick Levy of Orlando said.
</P>
<P>
   Another original player, guitarist Gary Talley, said another
group using the group's name also has surfaced in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put these fake Box Tops out of business,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said other groups such as the Coasters, Drifters and
Platters have had other artists using their names over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it all occurs from us not being around for all these
years and people liked the music and stepped in to make money,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham and Talley said their suit, filed in U.S. District
Court in Nashville last year, accuses a Philadelphia agency of
fraudulently obtaining the group's name by falsely stating on the
trademark application they had used the name since 1967.
</P>
<P>
   They also have filed a petition with the U.S. Patent and
Trademark Office asking them to cancel the trademark obtained by
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   But Longo and his agent, Richard Lustig of Orlando, said they
believe the agency obtained the trademark legally since the
original members abandoned it when they disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is Lenny (Longo) legally owns the name,''
Lustig said. ``I've been booking Lenny for 10 years. He puts on an
excellent show. The people will walk away entertained.''
</P>
<P>
   Corley hopes so, but said money would be refunded to disgruntled
ticket buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to get involved in who's who, but I'm not going
to give people money back unless they want it,'' she said. ``We're
going to have a good time. People will be dancing in the aisles.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
