<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sentinel chickens give signs of Florida encephalitis
 &HT;    By Mary Warejcka
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two chickens have tested positive for St. Louis encephalitis in
a preliminary screening _ this year's first signs of the
potentially dangerous virus in Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the two chickens housed west of Boca Raton and West Palm
Beach have the virus won't be known for sure until a second screen
is completed in late August. The chickens are called ``sentinel
chickens'' because they alert people that night-feeding mosquitoes
are spreading the virus, which can sicken and even kill people.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they test positive the second time, two positives
wouldn't be enough to issue warnings, said Jim Jolley,
environmental health administrator for the county Health
Department. Still, it's always a good idea to avoid exposure to
mosquitoes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not be of much concern,'' Jolley said recently.
``We'll just have to wait and see.'' Nearby, Jolley said, Hendry
County has also had one chicken testing positive, but there have
been none in Indian River County _ where birds began showing signs
of the virus in June last year. Statewide, dry weather has helped
cut down on the number of mosquitoes that could spread the disease.
If rain continues, there will be more mosquitoes that could be
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The first positive tests in Palm Beach County come a couple
weeks earlier than they did last year, when an encephalitis scare
led to temporary and unpopular bans on many nighttime activities
such as school football games.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, state health officials declared a 10-week medical
alert that included Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie, Okeechobee and
23 other Florida counties. Nine human cases _ including one in
Belle Glade and a Hillsborough County man who died _ were confirmed
in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
