<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABUTE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tale of infidelities intelligent, disturbing
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Neil LaBute is at it again, stirring up
trouble exploring relations between the sexes, and not finding much
hope for peaceful coexistence. There is a clear link between ``Your
Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' and filmmaker LaBute's debut feature, ``In
the Company of Men.'' Both are unflinching, pessimistic looks at
gender skirmishes, pitch-dark comedies designed to leave an
audience unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   While it was relatively easy to dismiss ``In the Company of
Men'' as a story of the mean-spirited prank of two jerks toying
with the emotions of a hearing-impaired secretary, ``Your Friends &AMP;
Neighbors'' is considerably harder to shake off. This time around,
LaBute wants to broaden his aim, involving and indicting us all.
</P>
<P>
   He focuses on six upwardly mobile thirtysomethings _ longtime
friends, lovers, marriage partners and new acquaintances _ whose
equilibriums are shattered by infidelity. You may not like these
people, but, chances are, you'll find yourself identifying with
some of them. Or being reminded of the equally lost souls of
``Carnal Knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry (Ben Stiller) is a self-absorbed college drama teacher,
the sort you expect to take advantage of some young coed who hangs
on his every word. Instead, after we've heard his longtime live-in
lover Terri (Catherine Keener) rant that he never shuts up,
particularly in bed, Jerry reaches out to her friend Mary (Amy
Brenneman), confessing a long-held desire for an affair with her.
Stuck in an emotionally empty marriage with Barry (Aaron Eckhart,
the prime heel of ``In the Company of Men''), Mary crosses the line
with Jerry with extremely unsatisfying results and repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Cary (Jason Patric), a most unfeeling sexual
predator, whom we first see practicing and refining his bedroom
patter into a tape recorder. And Cheri (Nastassja Kinski), a
flirtatious art gallery manager who takes up with the wounded
Terri. There are further links to this rambunctious sexual daisy
chain, but you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute's script crackles with frank dialogue and observant
little cruelties. Although he clearly has more resources than he
did for the shoestring ``In the Company of Men,'' he continues to
keep his camera in tight, far more interested in his characters
than background atmosphere. Some may find his approach static and
stagy, but the quality of his writing transcends such quibbles.
</P>
<P>
   All of this, of course, could play as soap opera, but the
uniformly razor-sharp and realistic performances of the ensemble
cast keep the movie from slipping into such shallow waters. Patric,
who also co-produced, is unflinching as cold-blooded Cary,
particularly riveting with a monologue recalling a homosexual rape.
Eckhart shows his range, in marked contrast to ``Company of Men,''
expressing the character's dissatisfaction and self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   Keener walks a tightrope, managing to be sympathetically bitchy,
and Brenneman conveys great wells of sorrow in her mournful eyes.
In a clever series of parallel encounters, Kinski controls her art
gallery turf, using her wiles to manipulate all who enter her lair.
</P>
<P>
   Though it will leave some viewers feeling unsatisfied, LaBute
refuses to let them off the hook at the end. This, he is saying, is
the state of relationships in the late '90s. You want a happy
ending? Go see a Disney cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
