<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNCH-BOX21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lunch Box Battle
 &HT;    By Jennifer White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back to school battles are all too common among kids and their
parents. What clothes to buy and which school supplies are
necessary are issues that parent and child generally don't see
eye-to-eye on, but the lunch box battle _ convincing kids to eat
healthy foods when all they want are sweets _ is one of the worst.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George Freeman packs lunches daily for his kids, Michael, 8,
and Magen, 6, and he understands the importance of eating
nutritiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kind of give it to them, it's part of a meal,''
Freeman said about how he and his wife, Heather, encourage their
children to include fruits and vegetables in their lunch boxes.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of 500 parents of elementary-age school children,
conducted by Impulse Research Corp. in June, more than half of
parents (60 percent) disagree with their children over what to pack
in the lunchbox and 70 percent of parents are concerned that their
kids are eating snacks that aren't nutritious.
</P>
<P>
   Michael and Magen, both students at Oakwood, don't have the
option of dining from a school cafeteria, so they bring their lunch
from home. The Freemans are pretty well-rounded eaters, so school
lunches usually consist of sandwiches, fresh fruit and one treat
for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let them make choices at the grocery store so that they're
not surprised with what we pack in their lunch,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Weston, a parenting expert and author, says that kids
appreciate being part of the decision-making process. For example,
when packing a lunch, ask, ``Do you want carrot sticks or celery
sticks?'' and offer snack choices. If kids have a hand in what goes
in the lunch bag, they are more likely to eat those foods _rather
than trade them away.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being good eaters, the Freemans do enjoy their share of
junk food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magen would eat chips and candy all day if we would let her,''
Freeman said. Compromises include packing one treat and choosing
healthier foods for lunches that the kids actually enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both like fresh-sliced meat, so sliced turkey is a source
of protein they eat a great deal of,'' Freeman said. Michael and
Magen also take milk in their thermoses as a source of calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Although some children run in the opposite direction when they
hear the word ``healthy'' attached to a food, Freeman said that
there are nutritious foods available that actually taste good to
kids. He recommends packing left-over foods in kids' lunches,
including pizza, spaghetti and meatloaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's generally a lot better than the things you buy in the
grocery store,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman also encourages parents to continue to pack nutritious
lunches for their kids, despite what they may see other children
eating at school.
</P>
<P>
   Michael has questioned why other kids bring soft drinks for
lunch, but the Freeman's limit such items to weekends and special
occasions so that they don't become a staple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them in order to grow and be healthy, they need to eat
a wide variety of foods,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Setting an example is the hardest thing about getting kids to
eat healthy, Freeman said. ``If your kids see you snack on candy
bars and chips all the time, they're not likely to listen to you
when you say how important it is to eat carrot sticks and
whole-wheat bread.''
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: Nutrition-packed foods to pack
</P>
<P>
   GRAINS: low fat muffins, bagels, whole wheat grain breads and
rolls, pita bread, low fat crackers, bread sticks, cereals
</P>
<P>
   FRUITS: bananas, grapes, apples, cut-up oranges, melons,
peaches, pineapple, kiwi (in small plastic container, already
peeled) ... you may need to limit juice
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLES: carrots, celery sticks, broccoli, cauliflower
flowerets, cuke slices, jicama sticks, lettuce on sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   DAIRY: string cheese, low-fat cheese slices, low-fat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   PROTEIN: nut butters, sunflower seeds, tofu
</P>
<P>
   MIXED: soup, leftover pizza, sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   Source: Kathy Kolasa, a registered dietitian of the Family
Practice Center, East Carolina University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
