<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3126 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENIORS-PETS21-COX     08-20 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-PETS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Best of Friends
 &HT;    By Kim Grizzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ When Sara comes to visit, she's like one of
the family.
</P>
<P>
   Nannie Lee Cox is happy to see her. She smiles sweetly and
extends her hand, touching Sara's face gently and telling her how
lovely she looks.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Sara brings back memories that, for a moment, make her
sad, even homesick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in my life I didn't have a dog or
cat,'' Cox says. ``I had a dog all my life until I come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the Alzheimer's unit of the Carolina House, a Greenville
long-term care facility. Probably the last place you'd expect to
find two pit bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But here they are, lapping up all the attention they're getting.
Sara and Skibo are working the crowd, licking hands and posing for
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me there's something about a cat or dog that's
family,'' Cox says. ``If it won't (against policy), I'd sneak one
in.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sara and Skibo haven't been smuggled in under somebody's
coat. They are guests, invited by Betsy Jones, activities director
at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina House soon plans to have live-in pets like its
sister facility in western North Carolina. More nursing homes and
other facilities are rethinking standard no-pets policies in favor
of an approach that recognizes the potential benefits of human and
animal contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we have more families now who are bringing people's
pets in,'' says Amy Beach, recreation services director at
Greenville Villa, where one aim of animal visits is to give the
facility a more homelike atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a growing trend in that direction, making it (the
facility) as homey as possible,'' says Sandra Triebenbacher, an
assistant professor in the Department of Child Development and
Family Relations at East Carolina University.
</P>
<P>
   Triebenbacher is one of four people in the state certified to
evaluate animals through the Pet Partners Program. The program,
established in 1990 by the Delta Society, has established
guidelines for animals used in therapy and visitation programs.
</P>
<P>
   Drake Parker, owner and head trainer at Top Dog Academy, has had
his American pit bull terriers certified as Pet Partners. Now Sara
and Skibo can accompany him on visits to schools, nursing homes and
day care centers.
</P>
<P>
   The breed, which has been linked with dog fights and other
aggression in the public perception, is not always a welcome sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I do get looks,'' Parker admits. Because he has not
cut his dogs' ears or tails, customary for pit bulls, they look
more like the beloved pooch of ``The Little Rascals'' than the
fighting breed often depicted in the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception is definitely wrong,'' Parker says. ``If you
sit here and watch my dogs for a little while, you might just
change your mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much a breed thing as it is the owner. I've been
around them (pit bulls) since I was a kid, and I know what the
truth is.''
</P>
<P>
   Stereotypes don't seem to mean much at the Carolina House, where
nobody seems to care that they're petting pit bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're beautiful,'' Martha Stang says, admiring Sara and
Skibo. ``They're the kind of dogs you'd be proud to have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Delta Society isn't concerned about breeds either. That is
not taken into consideration during Pet Partners certification.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important things that we are taught as we go
through the evaluator process is that we don't even take breeds
into consideration,'' Triebenbacher says. ``We look at every single
individual animal and their handler.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of his (Parker's) pit bulls are so laid-back and
easy-going. Pit bulls, certainly, and rottweilers have had real bad
raps. Every dog has potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Even strays and mixed-breeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably in this country there are more mixed breeds that are
involved in this type of activity,'' Triebenbacher says.
</P>
<P>
   Triebenbacher's dog, Scruffy, a terrier mix, is a Pet Partner,
as is Suzie, a border collie. She's working to teach a third, Sam,
a lab-chow mix and a stray, so he can join her on visits to schools
and nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   In schools, the dogs are teaching props.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to one preschool classroom, and there was a child who
had some challenges with biting,'' Triebenbacher recalls. ``When he
would get very angry and frustrated, he would bite. Interestingly
enough, of all the things about Suzie (her dog), he was most
intrigued by her teeth. This was a real teachable moment to talk
about what we use our teeth for.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit to preschoolers in the Child Development
Laboratory at East Carolina University, children asked questions
about dogs biting and licking. But mostly, they just wanted to
touch them.
</P>
<P>
   Touching pets and communicating with them has been shown to
lower blood pressure and increase longevity. Additional studies are
exploring a connection between contact with animals and decreased
depression, isolation and loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sometimes) patients ... have decided they're not going to
talk and they're not going to interact with anyone, and all of a
sudden an animal comes into the room and they say 'puppy,' and they
haven't spoken a word in 10 days,'' Triebenbacher says. ``That's an
exciting thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol King, food service director at Greenville Villa, noticed
some pretty remarkable reactions from patients when she started
bringing her Chihuahua, Lucy, to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband found (Lucy). She was abandoned,'' King says. ``We
started pet therapy after that. They ask me all the time since I
work out here, 'When's Lucy coming back?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially the ones with Alzheimer's disease, they perk up.
They definitely want to to touch them and talk to them. Quite a few
of them have surprised me.''
</P>
<P>
   King invited her neighbor, Mary Snow Harriss, to bring her dogs
_ all five of them _ out for visits.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville Villa resident Lonnie Turner seldom misses the chance
to see the dogs, especially Tylullah, a poodle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to see them come,'' she says. ``If I don't come, they
take them to my room.''
</P>
<P>
   Gigi Walter brings her two poodles, Oodi and Tevi, out as well.
Together, the seven or eight dogs stand on a table in the activity
room where residents take turns petting them, holding them and
feeding them doggy treats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love dogs,'' Walter explains, ``and I like sharing my
puppies with someone else who has loved dogs all their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Harriss says her dogs benefit from the experience as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine usually come in for the group,'' she says. ``This is the
highlight of their whole lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Tylullah, there's Darby (a Pomeranian), Bridget (a Shih
Tzu), Charlotte (a Pekingese) and Annie (an English Springer
Spaniel). They range in age from 6 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of my dogs needed homes,'' Harriss says. ``These are dogs
people didn't want.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenville Villa residents find that hard to imagine as they
stroke, brush and hug the dogs Harriss adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are residents of this nursing home who have pictures of
my dog next to pictures of their grandchildren,'' Harriss says.
``They love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
