<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3128 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER21-COX     08-20 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weird weather taking US by storm
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Miami Valley may be enjoying a mild
summer, but some of the odd twists and turns elsewhere have fired
up the debate over global warming. In fact, there have been so many
strange weather events this year that 1998 may go down as the year
of the calamity.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Prudhoe Bay, which lies near the Arctic Circle in Alaska,
recorded a 54 degree day in May, breaking the previous record by 8
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heatwaves of 100 degree-plus temperatures blasted Texas and
Oklahoma for weeks, causing 100 deaths and $1.7 billion in
agricultural losses.
</P>
<P>
   Floods tore through the Midwest in the spring, causing 63
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Wildfires scorched Florida in May and June, as 80 percent of the
state was at a drought level equivalent to a desert.
</P>
<P>
   July's average worldwide temperature was the warmest since
instrumental records have been kept (1880), about one degree
Fahrenheit above the long-term mean.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other oddities were documented by an August report by
the Sierra Club. The environmental group sees such extreme
conditions as a sign that the output from mankind's smokestacks and
automobiles, the so-called greenhouse gases, is increasing the
temperature of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists are telling us that global warming means more
extreme weather,'' said Dan Becker, the Sierra Club's Global
Warming and Energy Program Director. ``The weather is telling us
that global warming has begun.''
</P>
<P>
   It is far from a settled question. The climate of the earth is
so complex, dependent on so many changing factors like heat, air
and moisture, that the most powerful supercomputers can only
approximate its effects using bare-bones models for predictions.
There is widespread consensus among the world's scientists,
however, on the existence of the ``greenhouse effect,'' that rising
carbon dioxide levels create a canopy over the earth, trapping warm
air and raising its temperature. The warmest global temperatures of
the last 600 years have been recorded in the last decade, and some
scientists expect another two- to six-degree rise in the next 100
years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some people argue that global warming is a myth, and that
temperature readings from satellites actually show a slight
cooling. Industry groups have mounted an intense campaign to
Congress against the stricter, potentially expensive environmental
goals set at a conference in Kyoto, Japan, last December. The
conference called on industrialized nations to roll back the
release of fossil fuel-generated greenhouse gases to 1990 levels.
</P>
<P>
   If the earth is warming _ and it would take only one or two
degrees to see drastic shifts in the climate and environment _ the
Dayton area could be altered dramatically. A recent analysis
conducted by the Environmental Defense Fund claims that the Miami
Valley could see two times as many days over 90 degrees in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis placed Dayton 17th on the list of U.S. cities that
would likely experience warmer temperatures. Miami topped the list,
going from an average of 23 days over 90 degrees to 98.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's devastating heat waves in cities across the nation
may provide a picture of a typical summer of the future unless
emissions of greenhouse gases are significantly reduced,'' said
Janine Bloomfield, a scientist with the Environmental Defense Fund,
a New York-based not-for-profit organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dayton averaged only 12 days over 90 degrees per year between
1979 and 1997,'' she said. ``Our analysis shows that without
greenhouse gas controls, 20 to as many as 47 days over 90 degrees
per year can be expected by the year 2100.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis is based on the range of findings of the United
Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. The study used
historical data from the National Center for Atmospheric Research
and ran the averages through a computer model for climate change by
the year 2100.
</P>
<P>
   A warmer Miami Valley wasn't evident this year, however. Summer
temperatures for the most part have hovered at or just below
normal. June and July were below normal, according the the National
Weather Service in Wilmington.
</P>
<P>
   It has been wetter, thanks to the two or three thunderstorms
that swept through the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't really had a big hot spell,'' said Jim Lott, a
meteorologist at the National Weather Service. ``Actually, this
summer pretty much did the opposite of what we thought. We thought
it was going to be hot and dry.''
</P>
<P>
   The more extreme effects of El Nino, the weather-disrupting
current of warm water in the Pacific, generally missed Ohio.
January and February were the warmest in the state since records
started being kept 103 years ago. There was a freaky snowfall in
Cincinnati on Feb. 4 that dropped 12 inches in 24 hours, while
Dayton received a scant 1.5 inches. Lake Erie made it through
February without freezing, according to the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Floods ravaged the Ohio River and central part of the state.
``But that's pretty typical for spring,'' said Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Other areas of the country were hit harder.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California was hit with 21 inches of rain in February.
The wet conditions created a bumper crop of rodents, rattlesnakes
and insects. Texas had over 15 straight days of temperatures over
100 degrees, hitting a record of 113 on July 14. While Florida
suffered a drought, South Carolina had its wettest winter ever,
receiving 36 inches from November 1997 to April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
