   MOVIES (ETA's 1 p.m. unless otherwise noted.)
</P>
<P>
   BLADE _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Here's how the producers of ``Blade''
have chosen to hype the film's title character, pulled from the
pages of a lesser-known comic book. ``The power of an immortal. The
soul of a human. The heart of a hero,'' declares the picture's
poster, featuring an armor-suited Wesley Snipes against a blood-red
background. In other words, the makings of another ho-hum summer
action flick. (Passy, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SNIPES-INTERVIEW _ Don't expect Snipes, a Florida native, to be
one of those self-important actors who sees a need to justify a
film that lacks much in the way of social statement. He handles
inquiries about the movie's meaning the same way he responds to a
question about his driving habits _ with nothing less than total
frankness. (Passy, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LABUTE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Neil LaBute is at it again,
stirring up trouble exploring relations between the sexes, and not
finding much hope for peaceful coexistence. There is a clear link
between ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' and filmmaker LaBute's debut
feature, ``In the Company of Men.'' Both are unflinching,
pessimistic looks at gender skirmishes, pitch-dark comedies
designed to leave an audience unsettled. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
