   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ A letter from a former resident of Macon takes
me to task for referring to Anjette Lyles, ``the Macon murderess'',
in a column last week. She says I ``gleefully'' made the reference
and I assure her there's nothing gleeful about my recollection of
the 1958 murder of two husbands, a mother-in-law and a 10-year-old
daughter by the platnium-haired restaurant operator who is now
dead. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LUNCH-BOX _ Back to school battles are all too common among kids
and their parents. What clothes to buy and which school supplies
are necessary are issues that parent and child generally don't see
eye-to-eye on, but the lunch box battle _ convincing kids to eat
healthy foods when all they want are sweets _ is one of the worst.
(White, Greenville Daily Reflector) MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH SIDEBAR: Nutrition-packed foods to pack.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-PETS _ More nursing homes and other facilities are
rethinking standard no-pets policies in favor of an approach that
recognizes the potential benefits of human and animal contact.
(Grizzard, Greenville Daily Reflector) MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL-PALM _ ROYAL PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jennie Lou Peeples, 47, is
about as Royal Palm Beach as you get. And that holds for the rest
of her kin, 13 of them, all neighbors and all living within blocks
of one another. And now, says Peeples, the whole family is plotting
a mass exodus from South Florida to the mountains of North Georgia.
I promised the family all the recognition they could stand if she
would explain why in the blue-eyed world the family wants to swap
Paradise for Hicksville, Ga. (Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   IMMUNE-FETUSES _ Georgia researchers have solved a 45-year-old
riddle: why mothers are able to carry babies to term. It's an
ability most people never question. Yet it has puzzled scientists
since 1953, when a British immunologist pointed out that fetuses,
being genetically different from their mothers, should be rejected
by their mothers as foreign tissue _ but they aren't. The discovery
has implications for preventing miscarriages, for treating
autoimmune diseases such as arthritis and lupus and perhaps for
AIDS. The research is in Friday's issue of the journal Science.
(Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CDC-TB _ CDC is making special recommendations on TB, pushing
for development of a new and better vaccine. The recommendations
come from the federal Advisory Council for the Elimination of TB,
which generally praises efforts so far but urges stronger action
against the disease. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-ENCEPHALITIS _ Two chickens have tested positive for St.
Louis encephalitis in a preliminary screening _ this year's first
signs of the potentially dangerous virus in Palm Beach County. The
chickens are called ``sentinel chickens'' because they alert people
that night-feeding mosquitoes are spreading the virus, which can
sicken and even kill people. (Warejcka, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The Miami Valley may be
enjoying a mild summer, but some of the odd twists and turns
elsewhere have fired up the debate over global warming. In fact,
there have been so many strange weather events this year that 1998
may go down as the year of the calamity. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
