<HEADER>
A3138 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADELPHIA21-COX     08-20 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADELPHIA21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Adelphia cable lets its fingers do walking into phone service
 &HT;    By Michael Utley and Marguerite M. Plunkett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Adelphia Communications, a local cable
TV company, is planning to offer local phone service at the
burgeoning Abacoa development in Jupiter as early as next month,
making it the first cable operator in Palm Beach County and the
Treasure Coast to challenge BellSouth Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia is testing the service now and expects to make it
available to the entire 2,050-acre Abacoa development, which is
being built north of Donald Ross Road and west of Alternate A1A,
the company's regional manager, Mark Galloway, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where it will start,'' Galloway said. ``We're in the
technical stages of getting it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   An exact launch date and pricing details have not been
determined, he said. Adelphia now offers its customers
long-distance phone service in several package deals with rates
averaging about 10 cents a minute. But Adelphia is reselling
long-distance time it buys in bulk from the major long-distance
companies. Its local service would be routed through the company's
cable lines before tying into the BellSouth network.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia also provides high-speed Internet access for $34.95 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Abacoa development, which has about 130 homes
so far, Adelphia has more than 330,000 cable TV subscribers in Palm
Beach, Martin and St. Lucie counties.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, by far the largest local phone service provider in
Florida, said Wednesday that it welcomes the competition from
Adelphia and others. BellSouth, which has just a few local service
competitors that target business customers, said Adelphia's move
bolsters its argument that the Atlanta-based phone giant should be
allowed to compete for long-distance customers. Regulators have
blocked that request on more than one occasion.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's bid to break into the $70 billion-a-year
long-distance market hit another roadblock Wednesday when the U.S.
Justice Department urged federal regulators to turn down the
company's request.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department lawyers said BellSouth should not be allowed
to provide long-distance service in Louisiana because it has not
sufficiently opened its local phone market to rivals _ a condition
for entering the long-distance business. The Federal Communications
Commission ultimately will decide the matter. The law requires the
FCC to make a decision by Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia's decision to offer local phone service in Jupiter is
``another example of how local facility-based phone competition is
growing in the area,'' said Rob Seitz, a BellSouth spokesman in
West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is healthy for the telecommunications industry and will
result in better prices and services to customers,'' Seitz said.
``It is also an excellent example of BellSouth being singled out in
Florida as the only phone company that cannot provide long-distance
service, and that needs to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Other local cable companies _ including Comcast, Tele-Media and
Time Warner in the Glades _ are expected to offer phone service in
the near future. MediaOne cable company started selling local phone
service on Monday in Broward County, where Comcast also has a
limited service area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in everybody's future plans,'' said Robert Shock, a vice
president in Tele-Media's Boynton Beach office. ``We're doing
feasibility studies on it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress opened local phone service to competition two years ago
with the passage of the 1996 Telecommunications Act, but other
companies have been slow to take on the Baby Bells. Some, like
AT&AMP;T, have found that reselling time bought from the Baby Bells was
a losing proposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
