A3139 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUKE-ENERGY21-COX     08-20 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKE-ENERGY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New plant would sell its energy wholesale
 &HT;    By John Murawski
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Charlotte, N.C.-based Duke Energy is
pushing ahead with a proposal to build a power plant near Daytona
Beach and adjacent to Florida Power &AMP; Light Co.'s service area,
according to a petition filed recently at the Public Service
Commission in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Duke wants to build the state's first merchant plant, which
would sell wholesale low-cost electricity to other utilities in the
state. But the state's major utilities _ FPL, Tampa Electric Co.
and St. Petersburg-based Florida Power Corp. _ oppose Duke's plans.
</P>
<P>
   This is Duke's second application to build the 500 megawatt
gas-powered plant in New Smyrna Beach by 2001. Duke dropped last
year's effort to avoid hearings on its eligibility. This time
around, Duke is asking the PSC to say that growing energy
consumption in the state justifies the construction of a new plant,
a tack that requires fewer hearings. Duke points to this summer's
peak energy demands as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Duke is faced with the predicament of trying to build a power
plant in Florida at a time when there is yet no provision for
deregulation, and utilities such as FPL are citing those rules
against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, to get permission from state regulators to build a
plant, the utility has to justify passing on the construction
expenses to its Florida ratepayers, or customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Duke plant doesn't fit that pattern because it wouldn't
have any ratepayers. It would sell to other utilities. Duke says
it, not customers, is paying the $160 million bill.
</P>
<P>
   FPL says there is nothing in Florida law that allows a company
to build a plant whose primary purpose is to make spare energy as a
wholesale business venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke's proposal circumvents state policy,'' said a statement
from FPL. ``No utility in Florida would be allowed to build this
plant because it exceeds any demonstrated need for electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's proposed 500 megawatt plant would generate enough power
to serve about 150,000 homes. FPL's St. Lucie Nuclear Plant
generates 1,553 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 megawatts of the proposed plant's output would go to
the Utilities Commission of the City of New Smyrna Beach, which has
20,000 retail customers in the area where Duke wants to build. The
other 470 megawatts would be up for grabs to any utility that wants
to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no obligation for anyone to buy the power. But Duke
says it's confident today's critics will become tomorrow's
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be cheaper _ or we won't sell any power,'' said Duke's
energy lawyer in Tallahassee, Scheffel Wright. ``Once the plant is
built and producing power and selling at less than some utilities
are generating from their own older power plants, they'll say, 'I
guess this is the best deal for our ratepayers.' ``
</P>
<P>
   FPL, which has plants around the country that sell energy to
other utilities, says that granting approval would open the
floodgates to similar applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the proposal was approved, speculative power generators
could dot the state, taking up valuable land, consuming state
resources and adding unnecessary pollution,'' FPL said in its
statement.
</P>
<P>
   FPL said it doesn't have any merchant plants in the country. The
Juno Beach-based company's power projects around the country sell
energy to other utilities under long-term contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Merchant plants typically have few or no long-term contracts,
and make money by selling lower than the going daily wholesale
energy rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we do in states elsewhere we're doing under the laws
of that state,'' said FPL spokesman Dale Thomas. ``It's not the
same thing (as Duke's application).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
