<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON-PCBs (Colonie, N.Y.) _ The General Electric Co. says an
Environmental Protection Agency report that found PCBs were
escaping from polluted Hudson River sediment is so flawed that its
conclusions cannot be taken seriously. The company accuses the EPA
of selectively excluding data from its study. By PAUL ZIELBAUER.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-ELECTION (Stockton, Calif.) _ The candidates for governor
are competing fiercely for votes in the fertile corridor of Central
California, a region that has traditionally been less politically
predictable than the state's urban and suburban areas. By ZACHARY
COILE and ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-YORK-ELECTION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Thomas Golisano, head of a
payroll-services company, announces his candidacy for New York
governor, promising a lean state work force and an end to tolls on
the New York Thruway. By JAMES M. ODATA.
</P>
<P>
   TREASURE-ISLAND (San Francisco) _ Mayor Willie Brown, under
pressure to loosen his grip on control of Treasure Island, is ready
to budge and allow the public to visit the former naval base on
weekends. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORIC-BUILDING (San Francisco) _ Preservationists are urging
city officials to halt plans to raze a 97-year-old Municipal
Railway streetcar barn and replace it with a parking lot. The
red-brick building is a local historical landmark and eligible for
listing on the National Register of Historic Places. By ANASTASIA
HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUTTER-HOME (San Francisco) _ Sutter Home, the winery best known
for inventing the fruity white zinfandel, has had a huge impact on
the wine business. The family-owned, $300 million Napa Valley
outfit has quietly become the fourth-largest winery in the United
States. By PAUL FRANSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TIE (San Francisco) _ It's an instant fashion rage, that
tie Monica Lewinsky gave President Clinton. In the chic stores of
San Francisco, there is big demand for the cravat that has become
an issue in the Clinton sex investigation. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-REGENERATION (Undated) _ ``Regeneration'' is a
riveting British film set in a mental hospital designed to cure the
psychological wounds of World War I veterans and send them back
into battle. Directed by Gillies Mackinnon, the film is based on
Pat Barker's prize-winning wartime trilogy. By JUDY STONE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAP-ADVENTURE (Undated) _ Before he penned the first word of
``Treasure Island,'' Robert Louis Stevenson sat down and drew
himself a map. Any traveler who loves maps understands what a
powerful hold they have upon our imagination, how these exquisite
blends of science and art can contain mystery, intrigue and beauty.
By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ From now on, when there is
actual news from or about President Clinton _ say, his wife
actually dumps him _ I will consume and digest it. Everything else
I will view as bad, bad dope, and I will try my level best to leave
it alone. Life is too short for any other approach. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Sorry, Mr. President, I forgot
your birthday on Wednesday. Something came up, like the complete
demoralization of the country. I was going to get you a tie, but
never mind. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
