   &UR; IN OTHER WORDS &LR; . This is the first verse of ``Anacreon in
Heaven,'' the ancient English drinking song that provided the tune
for the United States National Anthem.
</P>
<P>
   To Anacreon in Heav'n, where he sat in full glee,
</P>
<P>
   A few Sons of Harmony sent a petition;
</P>
<P>
   That he their Inspirer and Patron wou'd be;
</P>
<P>
   When this answer arrived from the Jolly Old Grecian;
</P>
<P>
   ``Voice, Fiddle, and Flute,
</P>
<P>
   No longer be mute,
</P>
<P>
   I'll lend you my name and inspire you to boot,
</P>
<P>
   And besides I'll instruct you like me, to intwine,
</P>
<P>
   The Myrtle of Venus with Bacchus's Vine.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEIR AIM IS TRUE &LR; . Dish the dirt with insiders at hundreds of
newspapers by cruising through the Internet presence of the News
Mait Writers' Cooperative (www.newsmait.com). Thanks to a recent
mention in the American Journalism Review, traffic is more than
2,000 hits a day. An example:
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was the only one who worked in a hellhole. Here is
another newspaper that rewards mediocrity; has thugs, liars, sexual
harassers and bullies for upper editorial managers; hires newborns
who don't have a shred of life experience, hence their shallow
reporting; manipulates and denigrates its hardest working people _
I could go on 'til I'm blue in the face. Save yourself some
heartache and stay away from this newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   For broadcast wretches, Mike James and wife are setting up a
similar site, exposing ``overpaid general managers, idiotic news
directors, pompous anchors, stupid reporters, inert photographers,
lazy engineers, dense producers, brain dead viewers, senseless
focus groups, clueless consultants, long hours, low pay....yada
yada yada.'' It's at www.newsblues.com.
</P>
<P>
   James: mikejim(at)ds.net
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YER OUTA HERE &LR; . (See 1st Add below.)
</P>
<P>
   Mike Peterson at the (Plattsburgh, N.Y.) Press-Republican posits
this conversation taking place in the Boston Herald executive
towers, a little yonder from the Boston Globe, about Mike Barnicle:
</P>
<P>
   ``Disgusting. A disgrace. They should have fired him. We coulda
fit an extra desk in right over there ...''
</P>
<P>
   The joke clarifies the predictable mini-controversy over merely
suspending Barnicle for cribbing one-liners, after sacking Globe
columnist Patricia Smith for inventing sources and quotes
wholesale.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the degrees of the two misdemeanors, there is a
marketplace force at work here. Defenders of Smith are free to
publish a newspaper with the motto ``47 clever people quoted in
this paper do not exist'' and defenders of Barnicle can say ``Our
columnists don't tell where they heard their jokes.'' At the end of
the day, the publisher who sells the most papers is the winner.
</P>
<P>
   (Add 1) Thursday. Wow, times change. Barnicle's history, unless
you count maybe a cable TV gig or something similar. Would another
paper leap with an offer? Only without looking. Sorry, Mike, but
you make management look noble and at Boston Globe they are.
</P>
