<HEADLINE>
HUMBLE SUTTER HOME SUBTLY SHAPES AMERICA'S WINE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL FRANSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You won't read much about Sutter Home in snooty
wine magazines, but the winery best known for inventing the fruity
white zinfandel has had a huge impact on the wine business. The
family-owned, $300-million Napa Valley company has quietly become
the fourth-largest winery in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter Home helped make wine accessible to the average consumer
through savvy marketing of varietal wines at affordable prices. Its
sweet pink white zinfandel challenges chardonnay as America's
best-selling varietal wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sutter Home had an immense impact on the industry,'' said Cary
Gott, former senior vice president of production for Seagram
Chateau &AMP; Estates Wine Co.'s California wines (Mumm Napa, Sterling
and Monterey Vineyards), who now runs the Gott Group in Calistoga.
</P>
<P>
   While Sutter Home specializes in inexpensive varietal wines that
sell for $3.49 to $5.99 per bottle, its success has resulted from
marketing innovation as much as from wine. It was the first winery
in Napa Valley to offer free samples to visitors, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a driving force behind making premium varietal wines
popular in the United States,'' notes Jean-Michel Valette, senior
analyst and wine specialist at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, the investment
bank that took both Robert Mondavi Co. and Beringer Wine Estates
public.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Sutter Home's marketing innovations are aimed at
stealing customers from Anheuser-Busch and Coca-Cola, not Mondavi
or Beringer.
</P>
<P>
   It innovated supermarket promotion of wine, placing its
stand-alone displays prominently in the aisles, and was the first
in the United States to package wine in traditional-looking, small
bottles for individual consumption at home. And it has expanded the
market by introducing nonalcoholic and low-alcohol wines.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter also spends about $8 million per year on television
advertising aimed at demystifying wine and encouraging people to
think of wine as part of a healthy meal.
</P>
<P>
   Piedmont, Italy-born John Trinchero, who moved to the Napa
Valley from New York in 1947, bought the abandoned Sutter Home
winery near St. Helena and started the business. His brother,
Mario, soon joined him.
</P>
<P>
   The winery was a modest affair. Bob Trinchero joined the winery
in 1958 after a stint in the Air Force and succeeded his uncle John
as winemaker. He jokes that they sold 52 different wines _ all from
the same two red and white tanks. In 1960, John sold his share to
Mario, who turned the operation over to his children.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, hoping to improve the winery's reputation, Bob
Trinchero decided to focus on zinfandel. The wines received good
reviews, but the winery continued to struggle. That changed when he
accidentally developed white zinfandel in 1972. Originally a
byproduct when Trinchero drained off part of the juice in making
regular zinfandel to concentrate its flavor, the castoff evolved
into today's popular white zin.
</P>
<P>
   The industry ships about 21 million cases of white zinfandel
each year, 4 million from Sutter Home.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Trinchero is now chairman and chief executive, but focuses
on vineyards and production, while Roger Trinchero serves as
president of the winery and drives marketing and sales. Sister Vera
Trinchero Torres is secretary of the corporation.
</P>
<P>
   White zinfandel is the ultimate cash flow wine: It's easy to
produce, requires no aging, and begins generating revenue a few
months after harvest.
</P>
<P>
   The Trincheros have used this cash to build an empire. They own
270 acres in Napa Valley, plus three production facilities. Their
old winery serves as a tasting room.
</P>
<P>
   They also own 6,000 acres of vineyards around the state, much of
it organically farmed. Still, the Trincheros must sometimes feel
the sting of wine snobs. Recently, they hired Derek Holstein, the
respected winemaker from Guenoc Winery in Middletown, Calif., and
introduced a separate high-end brand called M. Trinchero in honor
of their father, Mario. The $30 cabernet and chardonnay have been
getting good reviews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
