<SLUG> BC-TREASURE-ISLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO TO ALLOW SOME ACCESS TO TREASURE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown, under pressure to loosen his
grip on control of Treasure Island, is ready to budge and allow the
public to visit the former naval base on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the policy shift, Annemarie Conroy, Brown's chief
aide for Treasure Island, said, ``People are curious about Treasure
Island. They want to enjoy the beautiful vistas of San Francisco.
We think that is important.''
</P>
<P>
   The new public access plan, which Conroy outlined Wednesday for
the Treasure Island Development Authority, a governing board
appointed by the mayor, is tentative because it must be approved by
the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Though the city manages the base, located in the San Francisco
Bay, Treasure Island Naval Station remains federal property until a
sale to San Francisco is negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Under the public-access proposal, visitors would have weekend
run of the Great Lawn, located on the base's western shore, and
nearby grounds from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. after Labor Day through early
November, weather permitting.
</P>
<P>
   Conroy said the mayor's office is counting on corporate
sponsorship to pay the $30,000 cost of fencing off the visiting
area and for the necessary addition of police, fire and sanitation
services.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings from a Labor Day weekend blues and arts festival at
Treasure Island, an event announced Tuesday by the mayor, also
would be available, Conroy said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the mayor's administration of Treasure Island
applauded Brown's policy shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is great,'' said city Supervisor Tom Ammiano. ``He
is a little late. The train already left the station, but it's good
he's on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the mayor's plan, 160 parking spaces would be provided on
a first-come basis.
</P>
<P>
   Conroy's presentation came a day after Supervisor Michael Yaki
broke ranks with Brown and announced he would introduce legislation
to wrest from the mayor some of his control over the base.
</P>
<P>
   Yaki wants some members of the Board of Supervisors to have
seats on the development authority. The authority directs
conversion of the base to civilian residential, commercial and
recreational uses.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Yaki helped defeat another supervisor's bid
to implement a June ballot measure, passed by city voters, that
called for dissolving the development authority.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Leland Yee, backed by Ammiano, wanted to replace the
Brown-controlled authority with one dominated by supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Both Yee and Ammiano are likely to support Yaki's move to at
least give supervisors a voice in base redevelopment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I will vote for that,'' Yee said. ``It's not exactly
what I wanted, but it's a lot better than what exists now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
