A3187 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-20 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITTING BOTTOM WITH CLINTON BLAH-BLAH-BLAH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Among my pals who are recovering alcoholics or
drug addicts, most can tell of a defining moment when they came
face-to-face with their out-of-control behavior and knew something
had to change.
</P>
<P>
   In Alcoholics Anonymous, it's called hitting bottom.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the moment came courtesy of a drunken-driving arrest
or being fired. For others, the messenger was more subtle: a
glimpse in a brightly-lighted mirror, a crushing remark from a
beloved child, the very last friend who said, ``No, no more
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is, in the moment, the addict got a clean, clear look
at just how much of a mess his life was, just how low she had sunk.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, about 20 minutes after the president's short
mea-sort-of-culpa to the nation, I experienced a similar moment. It
wasn't around the abuse of alcohol or drugs but around another kind
of addiction.
</P>
<P>
   I do not recall which network I was watching or which anchorman
was asking questions. Having exhausted the obvious subjects for
criticism, speculation and prediction, the anchor turned to Clinton
biographer and Washington Post reporter David Maraniss.
</P>
<P>
   Identified as a man who knows the psyche of Bill Clinton inside
out, Maraniss was asked to conjecture about the air between the
president and first lady during their Martha's Vineyard vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Without hesitation, Maraniss stated solemnly that the Clintons
would be ``in different rooms reading different books.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, I hit bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Before me was nauseating proof of just how bad my addiction to
Clinton blah-blah-blah had gotten. I, a mature woman with a good
brain and a college degree _ a woman who is not going to live
forever _ was spending precious moments of my life listening to a
highly paid news anchor bestow omniscience on a newspaperman.
</P>
<P>
   And the newspaperman was accepting it.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Maraniss won a 1993 Pulitzer Prize for his reporting on
Clinton. His biography of the president, ``First In His Class,'' is
considered thorough and respectable. But because of the demand
produced by the nation's addiction to Clinton blah-blah-blah,
because of all the pushers who have gotten in on the game since
Monica Lewinsky was discovered, Maraniss has become more than a
good reporter.
</P>
<P>
   He is now the designated voice of Bill Clinton's inner self.
Further, he is counted upon to see across miles, through walls,
into the future and tell us what will occur between a husband and
wife during their private moments.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how low could I go? Like many addicts, hitting bottom did
not immediately stop me from consuming more poison. Monday night, I
channel-surfed into the late hours, gulping, sniffing and shooting
the theories and opinions of others.
</P>
<P>
   Political pundits. Passengers at Dulles Airport. Former
assistant federal prosecutors. Former White House aides. Former
White House convicted felons. Paula Jones' former image consultant.
Even former Vice President Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning I awoke knowing that I never wanted to feel
that way again.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully, I listened to the news on National Public Radio, then
switched to a classical music station when an ``analysis'' of the
president's speech began. (I saw the speech. Why do I need someone
else to analyze it for me?)
</P>
<P>
   Despite a craving for ``just a few minutes'' of CNN or MSNBC, I
resisted. The last several months have taught me there is no such
thing as a little hit of Clinton blah-blah-blah.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, when there is actual news from or about the
president _ say, his wife actually dumps him _ I will consume and
digest it. Everything else I will view as bad, bad dope, and I will
try my level best to leave it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Life is too short for any other approach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
