<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAP-ADVENTURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETWEEN THE LINES, MAPS HAVE A STORY TO TELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he penned the first word of ``Treasure Island,'' before
he laid out the initial plot line or dreamed up a single character,
Robert Louis Stevenson sat down and drew himself a map.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was elaborately and (I thought) beautifully coloured,'' he
wrote. ``It contained harbors that pleased me like sonnets ...
(and) as I pored over my map of Treasure Island, the future
characters in the book began to appear there visibly among
imaginary woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Any traveler who loves maps understands what a powerful hold
they have upon our imagination, how these exquisite blends of
science and art can contain mystery, intrigue and beauty within
their contour lines.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Theroux, to whom I'm indebted for the Stevenson quote, said
he kept a map of Central America next to his desk during the two
years he spent writing his novel, ``The Mosquito Coast.'' Whenever
he was stuck for an idea, he said, he could find one within the
folds of his map.
</P>
<P>
   For me _ and I suspect I'm joined by other cartophiles in this _
travel is partly a quest to confirm with my own eyes the worlds
maps have conjured up for me.
</P>
<P>
   For years I kept in my study a beautiful, German-made
Alpenvereinskarte 1:25,000-scale map of the Khumbu Himal, the
region around Mount Everest. I unfolded it and studied it so many
times _ tracing the routes of the early Everesters, trying to
deduce where Mallory and Irvine vanished above the North Col,
plotting fantasy journeys of my own _ that it eventually began to
tear along the folds.
</P>
<P>
   I had to buy a new one before I finally booked a real trip to
the Khumbu. And when, toward the end of that trip, I staggered,
gasping for breath, to the top of a 20,000-foot-high mountain, I
risked frostbite to take off my mittens so I could carefully unfold
my map and match its beautiful swirls and squiggles to the actual
peaks, glaciers, valleys and villages below me.
</P>
<P>
   Endlessly beguiling, maps have their own culture and traditions.
Did you know, for instance, that maps routinely contain phony
streets or tributaries so their makers can readily tell when
competitors copy their work? These bogus notations _ called
``bunnies'' _ are surprisingly common. Near Stockton and Lombard
streets on the Carto Graphics map of San Francisco, for instance,
there is a fictitious ``Geek Street'' _ a source of endless
confusion for Fed-Ex deliverymen.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes the notations are not so fictitious. In the 1930s,
a cartographer at Rand McNally unilaterally appended his own name
to a previously nameless mountain in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The unrelenting brouhaha about the Mercator Projection tells you
something about the power maps have over us. As you might recall
from junior high school, Flemish cartographer Geradus Mercator set
out in 1569 to solve what is clearly an unsolvable problem: how to
render a three-dimensional globe accurately on a two-dimensional
piece of paper. On his map, the lines of longitude, instead of
converging at the poles, run parallel to each other.
</P>
<P>
   This created a handy tool for navigation _ it's still used by
ships' captains _ but distorted the size of continents. Land masses
close to the equator are represented fairly accurately, those in
the middle latitudes _ such as North America and Europe _ are
expanded considerably and those close to the poles, such as Alaska
and Greenland, are grossly oversized. On a Mercator projection, for
instance, North America appears larger than Africa, when in reality
the reverse is true.
</P>
<P>
   This has caused a battle in the cartographic community that has
been going on for nearly a century. Some, who feel size does in
fact matter, call Mercator's map ``eurocentric'' and ``the
self-conceit of the white man.'' In 1973 German mapmaker Arno
Peters even came up with an ``egalitarian map'' that shows
continents in the correct size relative to each other. But his map
elongates and distorts the shape of the land masses until they're
all but unrecognizable. And besides, it's ugly and unaesthetic: one
critic likened it to ``wet, ragged, long winter underwear hung out
to dry on the Arctic Circle.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the very reason we're called Americans and not
something else is due almost entirely to some capriciousness on the
part of a mapmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Waldseemuller, a cartographer at a small college in
eastern France in the early 1500s, was working on an update of
Ptolemy's ancient world map and was looking for a name to give to
the recently discovered New World. He heard of a series of letters
circulating in Florence that claimed, with reckless disregard for
the truth, that the discoverer of the New World had been one
Amerigo Vespucci. In fact, Vespucci had merely been a passenger or
lowly officer on ships captained by others.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. In one of those what-the-hell gestures that reshape
world history, Waldseemuller penned Amerigo's name onto his map
(after Latinizing and feminizing it) and the rest is, as they say,
history.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bryson, who dug up this anecdote for his book ``Made in
America,'' follows with a fascinating bit of trivia: Amerigo
Vespucci may not have had much to do with discovering his namesake
continents, but he did have one possible, if marginal, claim to
fame _ he is believed to be the brother of Simonetta Vespucci, the
model for Venus in the Botticelli painting.
</P>
<P>
   We're certainly getting off the subject here, but that's what
happens when you unfold a map and let your imagination wander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
