<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TIE-HNS &LR;      08-20 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLINTON COLLECTION: EVERYONE WANTS THAT NECKTIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ That presidential cravat, tied up in the
controversy over Bill Clinton's White House escapades, is a fashion
rage.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bullock &AMP; Jones store in San Francisco's tony Union
Square, a couple looking for neckties chuckled when they discovered
one that looked remarkably similar to the gold and navy tie Monica
Lewinsky supposedly gave the president for his 50th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady said to me, `He can't get this one because it
represents the `signal tie' _ you know, the one that Clinton wore
when he wanted to get in touch with Monica,''' tie salesman Herman
Storey said.
</P>
<P>
   The tie the woman held was by the same designer _ Ermenegildo
Zegna _ as the president's, but it was not an exact match.
</P>
<P>
   Zegna officials in the Italian designer's New York City offices
reluctantly admitted they had been besieged with calls, but
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Several high-end retailers were swamped Wednesday with calls
about the tie after it was pictured and featured Wednesday in a
story on the front page of The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   According to the newspaper, Clinton was questioned about the tie
during his grand jury testimony Monday on his relationship with
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The president wore the tie in question on Aug. 6, prompting
insinuations from prosecutors that it was used to send some sort of
a secret signal to Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 6 was the same day Lewinsky appeared before a federal
grand, contradicting her earlier testimony in saying she did have
an affair with the president in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have called asking for the tie. We obviously don't have
it because it's two years old,'' said a slightly weary but amused
spokeswoman for Saks Fifth Avenue in New York. ``I don't know why
they want it. Maybe it's just to say, `Hey, I've got the same
tie.'''
</P>
<P>
   The silk tie, a 1996 design with a navy crisscross pattern over
a gold background, retailed for about $110. Lewinsky, now 25,
reportedly gave it to Clinton, who turned 52 on Wednesday, with the
message: ``When I see you wearing this tie, I'll know that I am
close to your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus spokeswoman Alexandra Elliott said Wednesday she
was so busy answering questions about the tie it was difficult to
handle other inquiries. ``It's a strange phenomenon to me,'' she
said from the retail store's Dallas headquarters. ``People just
want to know about that tie.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, Nordstrom shopper Chuck Brauer said he
wouldn't be surprised if knockoffs of the tie started to appear
soon. ``It's the American way to pick up on something like this and
turn it into a marketing opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bill Clinton affair tie _ I don't think I'd want to be
associated with that,'' said another Nordstrom shopper, Brian
Bishop, as he looked for ties. ``It seems pretty absurd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
