<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 12:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3235 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROUGHT-TEXAS-TEX     08-20 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DROUGHT WORST SINCE '50S; MAY WIPE OUT UP TO 25 PERCENT OF
FARMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WORTH WREN JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The drought of '98 has cost state farms and
ranches $2.1 billion, making it the worst weather disaster for
Texas agriculture since the infamous drought of the 1950s,
agricultural economists say.
</P>
<P>
   The new crop loss estimate tops the $2.09 billion lost in the
1996 drought.
</P>
<P>
   And Roland Smith, an economist for the Texas Agricultural
Extension Service, said the broad economic ripple effect will
approach $5.8 billion in losses from 1998 into 2000, up from nearly
$4.95 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to lose some producers, and we're already down to
our frugal and best managers,'' Texas Agriculture Commissioner Rick
Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Sims, president of the Waco-based Texas Farmers Union and a
Sweetwater-area farmer and rancher, estimated that the state could
lose up to 25 percent of its farmers and ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said, ``Prices are also a disaster.'' The drought is not as
widespread as in '96, which means that supplies have not been
reduced as sharply. Prices, in turn, have remained low.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hardest-hit crops are cotton, corn and sorghum.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Anderson, an extension economist and cotton specialist,
called this year's cotton crop one of the worst in Texas history.
</P>
<P>
   The new estimate of cotton losses rose to $704 million, from
last month's estimate of about $500 million, based on last week's
first official government crop forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton, the state's leading cash crop, typically generates $1.3
billion to $1.6 billion annually in gross farm cash receipts.
</P>
<P>
   This year's projected harvest of 3.1 million 480-pound bales
represents an estimated 40 percent plunge from last year's
production. It's 29 percent less than the drought-slashed 1996
crop, and the smallest Texas cotton crop since 2.87 million bales
were harvested in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2 million planted acres won't be harvested, and the
drought damage is expected to run higher before the harvest is
completed this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1950, there have been only 10 other years when Texas
farmers raised smaller cotton crops.
</P>
<P>
   The '50s drought lasted five to seven years and remains the
worst natural disaster to hit Texas agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson said the financial risks in farming and ranching
are far greater today.
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question, he said, of whether the 1996 and 1998
disasters will rival the '50s impact on its mass population shift
from rural to urban centers.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the spotty rains have come too late to soften the
already-incurred losses but are greening up ranch pastures and may
curb further losses on some irrigated corn and cotton in Northwest
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 loss estimates, he said, understate the disaster's
severity when compared with 1996. That's because average cotton
prices are down by about 25 percent, and corn and sorghum prices
are down about 35 percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Losses have also continued to rise on other crops, including
irrigated corn and sorghum, and lenders are warning that 1999
carryover debt will be common and often run into heavy sums for
farmers and ranchers statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson Upton, a cotton, peanut and grain farmer in the
Seminole-Denver City area of Northwest Texas, said that even his
irrigated crops won't stop the drought from pumping red ink onto
his balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Upton's and thousands of other farmers' irrigation wells haven't
been able to keep pace with the water needs of their heat-tortured
crops.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Upton thinks he will have enough land equity for
collateral to obtain refinancing on his 1998 losses and his credit
needs for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so sad about the whole situation is, most of the young
farmers, they don't have any land,'' said Upton, who at age 37 is
still considered young in an aging farming population.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Stallman, president of the Waco-based Texas Farm Bureau and
a coastal rice and cattle farmer, said the drought will put an
uncertain number of farmers out of business and shrink the numbers
of cotton gins, fertilizer suppliers, seed dealers and other
agricultural and rural businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our loss will be determined by what Congress does in
September,'' Sims said. When Congress reconvenes, it will consider
two bills offering financial aid, not loans, and higher crop
price-support loans to boost market prices.
</P>
<P>
   The direct payments could total $500 million or more, and Sims
said the sum could run to $2 billion, with Texas getting the
largest share.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest rural disaster, Perry warned, could come in the
state's Lower Rio Grande Valley, where many farmers have been
forced to carry over debt for five to six years with weather- and
pest-induced losses.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said he's urging commercial lenders, federal banking
regulators, the U.S. Agriculture Department and Congress to pool
their efforts to be more lenient on loans.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
