</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3251 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-ANIMALS-$ADV22     08-20 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ANIMALS-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FANTASY, FOLKLORE AND WOOD CARVINGS ATTRACT TRAVELERS TO OAXACAN
VILLAGE
 &HT;    With MEXICO-RUGS-$ADV22, MEXICO-POTTERY-$ADV22; photos placed in
the International and Travel folders on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    EDs: Arrazola is one of three villages profiled in a three-part
look at the artisan tradition that thrives in Mexico's Oaxaca
state.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories
for use Saturday, Aug. 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARRAZOLA, Mexico _ He's the father of slithering serpents, giant
crabs, a ram with curled horns and sensual, almost human muscles.
</P>
<P>
   All his animals, says Claudio Ojeda, spring from the corners of
his mind and the chunks of wood his hands whittle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's spontaneous,'' the Mexican wood carver and Zapotec Indian
insists.
</P>
<P>
   But Ojeda also admits he finds inspiration in the hallucinogenic
mushrooms some Indians in this southern Mexican state consume for
spiritual and curative purposes.
</P>
<P>
   A beefy, friendly man who is proud of his craft and his
heritage, Ojeda is one of this village's most prosperous and
talented wood carvers.
</P>
<P>
   The village is Arrazola, and the state is Oaxaca (Wah-HA-ka),
where Zapotec and other Mexican Indians still reign when it comes
to culture.
</P>
<P>
   Seven miles southwest of the colonial city of Oaxaca, Arrazola
is home to a beloved Mexican craft: the production of
``animalitos,'' figures carved from the local copal tree and
painted in riotous colors.
</P>
<P>
   Carving is a centuries' old tradition, but in recent years the
artisans of Arrazola have elevated the art to a globally-desired
commodity. Their figures are sought by buyers from Europe, Asia and
all over the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Most are small enough to fit on a shelf, but wild enough to
attract instant attention. Horses sprout wings, as if ready to take
flight. Dogs with florid coats throw back their heads and howl.
Rabbits play congas or blow trumpets.
</P>
<P>
   The animals carved by Ojeda and painted by his wife, Teresa, are
noted for their large size -- some are two feet tall or wide -- and
exquisite detail.
</P>
<P>
   When he began carving in earnest 10 years ago, Ojeda
experimented by fashioning one large animal instead of many small
ones. The piece sold quickly and fetched a high price. Now Ojeda
can show off a thick wad of business cards from international
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father carved, too,'' Ojeda said. ``But he couldn't even
eat from what he sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Ojeda has sold pieces to Disney World in Orlando, galleries in
Chicago and the San Francisco Bay Area, and diplomatic offices in
Texas. He's been asked to exhibit in Hong Kong and his pieces
decorate homes from New York to Paris to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still raise some corn and beans. But we pretty much
dedicate ourselves to artisan work now,'' said Teresa Ojeda. As she
spoke, she was painstakingly decorating a large tortoise with three
frogs poised on its shell.
</P>
<P>
   As you approach Arrazola, you pass carts driven by oxen and
farmers carrying machetes. You begin to see signs in English and
Spanish inviting you into homes where the animals figures are
carved and sold.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a cluster of boys greets you at the edge of town,
offering to accompany you to a favorite carver's house for a few
pesos.
</P>
<P>
   Arrazola's prosperity is striking. The roads are paved, the
houses sturdy, satellite dishes are perched on roofs to pick up
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Claudio Ojeda drives a pick-up and his home is equipped with a
shower and modern bathroom, startling amenities in an Indian
community.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ojedas' workshop remains a traditional family affair. In
a studio behind sliding glass doors, the couple invite customers in
to browse.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike smaller animals, which run under $10, the Ojedas' animals
don't come cheap. Most are the equivalent of $40 and up, sometimes
pushing into the hundreds. But that's a fraction of a U.S. gallery
price, and, by visiting, you get to see the full range of the
couple's creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the studio, a dragon sports a tail that has metamorphosed
into a snake. A crab with bulging eyes seems to scuttle across the
floor, unaware of the reptile perched on its back. Hippopotamuses,
lobsters, and all sorts of other creatures find their way out of
the wood.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Ojeda is from a village where the pre-Hispanic tradition
of hallucinogenic mushrooms is still revered. She and her husband
both say mushrooms have given them visions of animals and colors
leaping and fusing. Neither takes this tradition lightly, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a strong mind,'' Claudio said. ``But it's
something mystical. Scientists can't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO VISIT: In Oaxaca city, hire a taxi, take a city bus or a
tour many hotels offer to Arrazola, where you can browse at the
Ojedas' on Emiliano Zapata Street, or, for smaller animals, at
other families' workshops.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
