<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3265 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BESTMAN-REVIEW-LADN     08-20 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTMAN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE MILLENNIUM AND MARRIAGE MEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Wedding farces are usually played for broad
laughs; everything that can go wrong does go wrong on what's
supposed to be a bride's perfect day, things like that.
</P>
<P>
   Pupi Avati's droll, melancholy ``The Best Man'' goes for
something a little more focused and compelling. While behavioral
humor and surprise reversals play their parts in this handsome
Italian period piece, emotional specificity and a fine sense of a
lost era's attitudes are the film's most engaging qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a rural town on New Year's Eve 1899, the film plays most
amusingly with naive hopes for the future, as represented by both a
strategic, loveless marriage and optimism about the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful Francesca Babini (Spanish actress Ines Sastre), the
daughter of financially overextended, rustic aristocrats, is to wed
this day the unappealing Edgardo (David Cantorelli), an aging
playboy whose family wealth is crucial for the Babinis' survival.
Though told from an early age that romantic love is just a dreamy
fiction, strong-willed Francesca would prefer it to the fate she's
about to be sealed into.
</P>
<P>
   When Edgardo's best man Angelo (Diego Abantantuono) arrives from
America at the last moment, Francesca sees her out. Not only
soulfully attractive and impeccably groomed, the former local
bricklayer has reportedly made a fortune across the sea. It's love
at first sight, as far as she's concerned, but the sad-eyed Angelo
has another agenda. He wants to find his lost first love, driving
the desperate Francesca to increasingly embarrassing outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   Social traditions are flipped upside down as the day turns to
eve and the century runs out. Not only is Francesca behaving in
ways a new bride definitely should not, but guests are getting
drunker. Inevitably, class prejudices _ which will certainly
disappear from the Earth, as will war, in the enlightened 1900s _
shed their genteel couchings. Above all, money and love drive all
considerations, as they have since time began and will no matter
what changes new millennia bring.
</P>
<P>
   Avati, who likes to make films in Italy's northern Emilia
region, where he's lived most of his life, based a lot of the
events in ``The Best Man'' on stories passed down from his
great-grandparents' generation. That rings true. Though ever so
slightly, carefully heightened, the film's characters and events
are so solidly presented and clearly delineated that they transport
you into their unhappily wedded world with almost unnoticed ease.
</P>
<P>
   It's some party, worth attending for the people-watching alone.
There's a slightly addled, virginity-obsessed aunt; a gloriously
in-denial mother of the bride; three young brothers, all priests,
who are thrilled to watch the New Year's ball they dare not
participate in; and many other swiftly, deftly drawn characters
that shine with human veracity even as they waltz through the
monkeyshines of romantic farce. Farce with an exquisitely
well-constructed poker face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
