<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BLADE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bloody `Blade' is strictly O-negative
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only thing that's remotely cutting-edge about ``Blade'' is
the buckets of F/X gore with which it douses its audience.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, this is a distressingly generic comic book movie that
may do a lot for Wesley Snipes' bank account but does nothing to
enhance his fading stature as an actor. Frankly, I miss the Snipes
of ``Mo' Better Blues,'' ``New Jack City'' and ``Rising Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Introduced by Marvel Comics in the early 1970s, Blade (Snipes)
is a superhero with a whopping identity problem. His mother was
bitten by a vampire and died giving birth to him. Half vampire,
half human, Blade can withstand sunlight but also has a taste for
blood.
</P>
<P>
   He's devoted his life to hunting down vampires. He does this
with the help of an impressive arsenal of sci-fi gadgets, a really
cool leather coat and Kris Kristofferson, his mentor-sidekick,
who's like a high-tech Gabby Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Blade's nemesis is a strutting young vampire named Deacon Frost
(Stephen Dorff, reprising his ``City of Angels'' bad-boy act).
Frost wasn't born a vampire; he was ``turned,'' i.e., bitten. But
he has big plans to overthrow the vampire-by-blood aristocracy and
become the leader of a new vampire nation. And those plans include
Blade.
</P>
<P>
   The niftiest thing about the movie is how it honors its comic
book origins. That is, like the best of Marvel, it goes to
considerable trouble to set up the world in which Blade and Frost
exist. The film spells out its complex vampire mythology _ not just
a matter of stakes and mirrors _ and sticks to it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, those same superhero origins prove its downfall.
It's one thing to spend an hour or so following the nonstop slash
'n' gnash exploits of a tormented vampire hunter in a comic book.
It's another to sit through two hours of shock tactics (needles,
veins, trashed throats) that become more repetitive as the movie
goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes has a powerful iconic presence, no question. But the
question is, is a franchise really all he wants? It seems a waste
of a good actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Wesley Snipes and Stephen Dorff. Directed by Stephen
Norrington. Rated R for extreme violence and strong language. 2
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Doesn't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
