<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONDER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATHS CROSS DELIGHTFULLY IN `WONDERLAND'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3{ Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you've ever heard Astrud Gilberto sing
``Corcovado'' with Stan Getz's plaintive, seductive saxophone
whispering in the background, you know the mood writer-director
Brad Anderson is trying to evoke in his feature debut, ``Next Stop
Wonderland.'' Melancholy. Wistful. Meditative. Beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's film is a romance that's as much about being alone as
it is a study on what brings two people together. It features a
terrific lead performance by Hope Davis, who plays Erin, a woman
content with solitude but unable to rid herself of the idea that
her life would be a little better if she shared it with a soulmate.
</P>
<P>
   Across Boston lives Alan (Alan Gelfant), a decent man who would
be perfect for Erin. Their paths frequently cross during the movie,
but Anderson and co-writer Lyn Vaus keep them tantalizingly apart.
The tension slowly builds until ... well, we'll keep that a secret.
Let's just say that, like the rest of this wonderful movie, the
payoff is anything but a Valentine's Day cliche.
</P>
<P>
   When we first meet Erin, she's being dumped by her tree-hugging
boyfriend of several years who thoughtfully _ and hilariously _
leaves a videotape detailing ``Six Points of Why I'm Leaving You.''
Erin is devastated, and her romantically obsessed mother (the
always splendid Holland Taylor) isn't too happy either, although
she could never understand why her beautiful daughter took up with
that ``communist'' in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Mom has placed a personal ad in a Boston newspaper for her
daughter. ``Frisky, cultured, with a zest for life,'' it begins. It
doesn't exactly describe Erin, mired as she is in a funk. But it's
the Erin that Mom remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Erin is embarrassed _ but she's also intrigued. When
she calls her voice mail, she finds 64 men have responded. Still,
Erin isn't exactly floating on air. She's realistic enough to know
that while you always have a choice in dating, it's usually a
pretty weak selection from which to choose. Naturally _ and quite
humorously _ she is proved correct when she begins to meet her slew
of singles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Alan doesn't have much time for romance, as he's
working his way through classes in marine biology and volunteering
at the Boston Aquarium. Alan doesn't want to spend his life being a
plumber, nor does he want to end up like his father, a drunk
gambling away his last 10 bucks at a dog track. So he's trying to
reinvent what seems to be his preordained life.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson weaves these two characters' stories together
seamlessly, sometimes putting them in the same place, sometimes
affording them the same company, but at different times. He has
also populated his movie with a colorful supporting cast that
includes Jose Zuniga as Erin's irresistible Brazilian suitor and
Robert Klein as a tough guy who has criminal designs on the
aquarium's prized puff fish. (Think what happens when a needle hits
a balloon.)
</P>
<P>
   But ``Next Stop Wonderland'' (named after a stop on the Boston
subway line) is a lot more than a sappy ``will-they-or-won't-they''
romance. Anderson has filmed the movie much like a documentary,
using hand-held cameras and minimal lighting that gives his story
an honesty and rawness absent from most romantic comedies.
</P>
<P>
   And the movie's well-developed themes of fate and destiny,
solitude and companionship anchor the film with interesting
dialogue and ideas. Then there's the ever-present soundtrack, songs
like ``Corcovado'' and other lovely bossa nova classics (a lot of
Antonio Carlos Jobim) that nicely underscore the bittersweet action
taking place on the screen. All these aspects _ the writing,
direction, soundtrack and performances _ coalesce into something
quite delightful, a romantic comedy with a brain.
</P>
<P>
   That's the wonder of ``Wonderland.'' And like the cool melodies
of the samba, it proves quite seductive indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
