<HEADER>
A3272 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-DANCE-COX     08-20 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deft `Dance' is light on its feet
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to Hollywood, Jamaica and Cuba are busy cultivating
sensitive men with perfect torsos whose sole purpose in life is to
rejuvenate driven, single American mothers.
</P>
<P>
   That's the familiar plot of ``How Stella Got Her Groove Back'' _
oops, sorry, make that ``Dance With Me.'' As slick a fantasy as the
similarly themed Angela Bassett flick, ``Dance'' has a couple of
major advantages over the Terry McMillan adaptation: Director Randa
Haines (``Children of a Lesser God'') knows her movie is fluff, and
she delivers it with candy-colored flair.
</P>
<P>
   Plus there's the movie's hip-swiveling, Latin-rhythm soundtrack,
which keeps it pulsing despite co-choreographer Daryl Matthews'
brain-dead script.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Bassett a run for Least Likely Single Gal of 1998,
Vanessa L. Williams plays Ruby, a Houston dance instructor. She
hopes to recapture the glory of a Las Vegas competition six years
ago, when she won the title dancing with Julian (Rick Valenzuela),
a jerk who got her pregnant, then ditched her.
</P>
<P>
   Though Williams is top-billed, the movie belongs more to Rafael
(Latin music star Chayanne), a Cuban newcomer to Houston whose
heart is as big as his pecs. He's welcomed into the home of John
Burnett (Kris Kristofferson), owner of the studio where Ruby works
and a dancer who, 30 years ago, worked on the same cruise ship with
Rafael's mom. Hmmmm ...
</P>
<P>
   Rafael putters around the studio, watching Ruby and other
students (including Joan Plowright and ``Ally McBeal's'' Jane
Krakowski) rehearse for the Vegas competition. And we wait a little
too long for the inevitable to begin. We know Ruby and Rafael will
be attracted to each other, fight it, then give in. We already know
the choreography and every single step this kind of movie has in
store. Luckily, for the last 40 minutes, the familiar blueprint
can't spoil the joys of performance, as the characters try out
their moves in Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Haines rarely lets reality weigh things down. She gives us a
Cuba bursting with colorful street life and lusty musicians. Even
Houston's Greyhound bus station, bustling with sailors and cowboys,
could be something out of a '90s ``On the Town.'' This is the sort
of retro guilty pleasure that has a Cuban friend of Rafael's assure
him, ``You never leave Cuba.'' And on spying Ruby practicing a
routine in silence, Rafael asks, ``How do you dance without music?
It comes from the music. I'm sure that's why you look so stiff.''
Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael, you see, is the one who has to teach this by-the-book
professional that real dancing comes from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Original it isn't, but ``Dance'' is great fun. It's the first
film that lets Williams show off her knockout moves; there's a
wonderful scene at a salsa club where she's whirled from partner to
partner in the improvised, communal dance. Meanwhile, in his first
Hollywood flick, Chayanne goes for the summer's heartthrob title.
His Rafael is courtly and charming, and he even manages to pull off
a ``Singin' in the Rain'' homage with its own sweetly comic spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me'' doesn't use dancing as a pointed social
metaphor, like the cartoonish ``Strictly Ballroom'' or the sweet,
melancholy ``Shall We Dance?'' But by the end it presents a lovely,
if fantastic, image of dance as the thing that can set aside all
barriers of age, race or economic differences. The original, better
title was ``Shut Up and Dance.'' When the movie takes that advice
and drops the silly dialogue, it's so light on its feet that you
can't begrudge the helium in its head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Vanessa L. Williams and Chayanne. Directed by Randa
Haines. Rated PG. 2 hours,
</P>
<P>
   6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A guilty, quick-stepping pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
