<HEADER>
A3274 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-FRIENDS-COX     08-20 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FRIENDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A less than friendly group
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you make your feature debut with a film as wickedly
dazzling as last year's ``In the Company of Men,'' a sophomore
slump is almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, that's what's happened to writer-director Neil
LaBute. His second movie, ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' has some
sensational bits and pieces but never completely adds up.
</P>
<P>
   The territory is pretty much the same: sex games people play and
power trips they pull. But this time LaBute widens his net to
include women as well as men. His focus is on six young,
well-educated urbanites. Jerry (Ben Stiller) is a lecherous college
drama teacher, living with tart-tongued Terri (Catherine Keener),
who complains that he talks too much _ especially during sex.
</P>
<P>
   Their good friends Mary (Amy Brenneman) and Barry (Aaron
Eckhart, the cad from ``Men'' with 40 more pounds and a bad
haircut) would seem to have it all. They appear deeply devoted to
each other, have lucrative professional lives and own an apartment
to die for. Yet Barry admits that, as much as he loves Mary, his
best sex is with himself. And Mary is surprisingly open to an
adulterous proposal by Jerry (by now, I hope you've gotten the
rhyming-names joke).
</P>
<P>
   Terri, meanwhile, starts an affair with Cheri (Nastassja
Kinski), a gorgeous art gallery assistant. Finally, there's Cary
(Jason Patric), Barry's best friend. A kind of leftover from the
slash-and-burn ``Men,'' Cary is a doctor who practices pillow talk
into his tape recorder and sends a woman who's made him angry a
false notice that she tested HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute hasn't lost his knack for lacerating dialogue and brutal
black comedy. In one scene, Cary absently tosses a plastic fetus
around like a football. In another, Jerry has a heart-to-heart with
Barry while dressed for a Restoration comedy.
</P>
<P>
   On the chilly side, there's Cary's monologue about the best sex
he ever had: a high school gang rape of a male student. The story
may or may not be true, but it has an acid ring.
</P>
<P>
   But there's something missing here. A sense of cohesiveness or,
perhaps, of cumulative effect. ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' is
smart, funny and cynical. But despite the efforts of its cast
(Patric excluded), it's never as smart, funny or cynical as it
thinks it is. What's lacking is some first-rate Neil LaBute; what's
in its place is some second-rung Woody Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Friends and Neighbors''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Stiller and Jason Patric. Directed by Neil LaBute.
Rated R for sex (intercourse and masturbation) and language. 1
hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: With friends (and neighbors) like these ...
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
