<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PASSION-COX     08-20 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PASSION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A mystical man-and-beast story
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You can't get lost in Egypt,'' says Augustin Robert (Ben
Daniels), a resplendent young captain in Napoleon's army. ``There's
the Nile, and there's the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Famous last words. As we see in ``Passion in the Desert,'' a
striking, strangely lyrical film based on a novella by Honore de
Balzac, the arrogant captain gets very, very lost. Body and soul,
mind and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Augustin is with the French army in Egypt as part of the
emperor's doomed 1798 campaign. A sudden sandstorm separates him
from the rest of the troop. On his own, Augustin is soon going in
circles. Finding refuge in some huge, ancient ruins, he discovers
that he's not alone. From the dark stare a pair of luminous feline
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the movie truly begins. The eyes belong to a
gorgeous and solitary she-leopard. Instead of killing him _
leopards are fully capable of and occasionally inclined to eating
human flesh _ she leads him to a water hole and shares her fresh
kill. Before long, the two are in _ well, there's really no other
word for it _ a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Their bond is undeniably sexualized. Not in the sense of
bestiality, but in the way Augustin becomes immediately jealous
when a male leopard intrudes. Or in the way he paints himself with
clay to look like his leopard love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion'' is the sort of movie you either go along with or you
don't. Those who don't care for animals or can't buy into
Augustin's desert delirium will probably snicker. But others,
especially animal lovers, will be fascinated by the inexplicable
and wondrous connection presented here: how she caresses his cheek
with her sheathed claws, the way he licks her silken shoulder.
First-time director Lavinia Currier isn't afraid of the primitive
mystery at the core of Balzac's story. She embraces it with a
spellbinding visual fluidity that includes long, wordless stretches
reminiscent of the island scenes in ``The Black Stallion.''
</P>
<P>
   With his catlike eyes, lithe, athletic body and leonine mane of
blond hair, British actor Daniels is well-cast as someone just
itching to discover his inner cat-person. Moreover, he's equally
convincing in both his Napoleonic and natural states.
</P>
<P>
   He also deserves some kind of special medal for on-camera
courage. That's really Daniels in all those up-close-and-personal
scenes with the three jungle cats (raised in captivity) that share
his co-star's role. No stunt double here. No digital
special-effects leopard.
</P>
<P>
   A love story as well as a typically Balzacian take on the
shortcomings of so-called civilized man (the French soldiers pass
the time shooting the nose off a sphinx), ``Passion'' is hardly a
costume version of ``That Darn Cat.'' Rather, it's a unique and
daringly original film. And if you have a leopard-skin coat in your
closet, leave it behind. You'll never make it out of the theater
alive. And rightly so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion in the Desert''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Daniels. Directed by Lavinia Currier. Rated PG-13
for violence and nudity. 1 hour, 33 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A desert reverie about the mystical bond between
man and beast.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
