A3276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-REGENERATION-C     08-20 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-REGENERATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A somber and articulate drama that examines the battle scars of
World War I
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The madness of war and how it creates madness in men is the
subject of ``Regeneration,'' a literate and somber Scottish film
that has been smartly positioned to capitalize on the ``Saving
Private Ryan'' overflow.
</P>
<P>
   Working from Pat Barker's reality-based, Booker Prize-winning
novel, director Gillies MacKinnon (``The Playboys'') takes us to
World War I, also known as ``the Great War.'' And though we see
plenty of muddy, torn-up battlefields and bloody, corpse-strewn
trenches, the horror of combat is conveyed less through images than
through the unforgettable words of British soldier-poets Siegfried
Sassoon and Wilfred Owen.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 1917 and the place is a different kind of
battlefront. In a castle-turned-hospital outside Edinburgh,
shellshocked British officers are ministered to by a staff of
military doctors and nurses. Their job is to make these men well,
restoring them to sanity so they can be shipped back to the
insanity of battle.
</P>
<P>
   The movie concentrates on a doctor and three patients. Dr.
Rivers (Jonathan Pryce) is a compassionate psychiatrist. An officer
himself, he's beginning to have doubts about ``regeneration,'' the
army term for efficiently recycling shattered souls.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers' most glamorous patient is Sassoon (James Wilby). A
celebrated poet and war hero, Sassoon has thrown away his medals
and written a very public declaration against the war. In order to
discredit him, the top brass have sent him to Rivers, charging the
doctor not to seek a cure _ Sassoon is obviously sane _ but to make
him recant.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the premises are Owen (Stuart Bunce), a fledgling poet
whose work Sassoon encourages, and Billy Prior (Jonny Lee Miller),
a working-class officer whose muteness says as much about his
background as it does about war.
</P>
<P>
   The movie makes one crucial mistake: It tries to honor all these
characters' stories, thus diffusing its impact. Still,
``Regeneration'' is an often searing and always articulate film,
one graced with excellent acting and an innate respect for the
complex moral dilemmas it presents. If we feel, by the end, that
the picture accomplishes less than it might, it's only because it
sets out to do so much.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's well worth the price of a ticket just to hear some
of the dialogue. For instance, at their initial meeting, Owen tells
Sassoon, ``Sometimes, in the trenches, you get a sense of something
ancient ... as if all the other wars had distilled themselves into
this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg's kinetic camera could hardly put it better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regeneration''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jonathan Pryce, James Wilby and Jonny Lee Miller.
Directed by Gillies MacKinnon. Not rated, but includes nudity,
strong language and violence. At Phipps. 1 hour, 53 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A sober and articulate examination of the battle
scars left by World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
