<HEADER>
A3277 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SKIN-COX     08-20 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SKIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Skin-deep rage fuels a tale of two sisters
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Under the Skin'' made my skin crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was written and directed by a woman and has female
protagonists, it has been heralded as a terrific example of the
female perspective. Now I know how intelligent guys feel when
demographic studies insist they're supposed to get a testos-
</P>
<P>
   terone surge watching ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   Winner of the critics' award at the 1997 Toronto Film Festival,
Carine Adler's movie introduces us to two sisters living in
Liverpool, England. Iris (Samantha Morton) is a headstrong waif
with a Jean Seberg haircut and an enormous capacity for self-pity.
Her older sister, Rose (Claire Rushbrook from ``Secrets and
Lies''), is married and pregnant. When their mother (Rita
Tushingham, a mainstay of early-'60s British cinema) announces that
she's ill with a brain tumor, the pair react characteristically.
Rose worries that her child will never know her grandmother, while
Iris worries that her mom is ``going to die and she hasn't even
noticed me yet.''
</P>
<P>
   How these two deal with their mother and with each other
constitutes the rest of the film. But we spend most of our time
with Iris, who pretty much flips out and, like the protagonist in
``Breaking the Waves,'' seeks some sort of validation or
self-annihilation through a series of casual sexual encounters,
each more dangerous than the last.
</P>
<P>
   Known from her work on British television (``Jane Eyre'' and
``Tom Jones''), Morton delivers a deeply felt if somewhat
incoherent performance. That's less her fault than the script's,
which never makes clear why she does what she does. Rose's
character is similarly opaque. Apparently all we need to know is
that she's pregnant and she's not as cute as her sister.
</P>
<P>
   For all its sexual tough talk _ Iris narrates her quickies as if
she were auditioning for ``The Red Shoe Diaries'' _ ``Under the
Skin'' is just a punked-out variation on the old ``women's movie''
plot in which sister rivals end up weeping in each other's arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Skin''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Starring Samantha Morton. Directed by Carine Adler. Not
</P>
<P>
   rated, but contains strong language, nudity, masturbation and
intercourse. Through Thursday. Cinefest, Georgia State University,
Atlanta. 1 hour, 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Won't get under your skin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
