<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3314 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-POLMONEY-$A     08-20 1462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-POLMONEY-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMPUTER FIRMS SPEND $3 MILLION ON CHAT-NOW, PAY-LATER
POLITICKING
 &HT;    Eds: 800&AMP;adds. With COMPUTERS-DATA
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington) and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For release Saturday, Aug. 22, or thereafter.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON The Sunday after Congress began its August recess,
two senators led eight House members and four House candidates on a
sweep through Silicon Valley and Seattle in search of enlightenment
and cash.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, they sat through intense briefings on economics,
technology and political desires by very rich computer gurus and
venture capitalists from such firms as CNet, Yahoo!, Applied
Materials, Affymetrix, ETrade, Sun, USWeb, NetNoir,
Hewlett-Packard, Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, E-Loan and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this sense that this is the New World, and we want to
learn about it, `` Sen. Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., said in a statement
about the West Coast swing arranged by him and Sen. Jeff Bingaman,
D-N.M.
</P>
<P>
   In between the briefings, they squeezed in social events at
which the briefers and their friends gave $150,000 to the New
Democrat Network, a Washington-based fund-raising group that raises
money for pro-business Democrats in tough races.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the many mechanisms that Democrats and Republicans
alike have used to raise more than $3 million since January 1997
from the nation's 50 most generous computer companies. The
technology leaders, once disparaged by politicians as people ``with
deep pockets and short arms,'' are being courted more than ever
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Rosenberg, who runs the New Democrat Network, said, ``In
many ways we represent what (top computer executives) want:
fiscally responsible fiscal policies and socially tolerant social
policies. ``
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also mine for the computer industry's gold. Senate
Banking Chairman Al D'Amato, R-N.Y., collected 39 contributions
worth $37,500 on a similar visit last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which gave $511,899, topped the list of generous
computer companies compiled by the non-partisan Center for
Responsive Politics in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Others investing at least $100,000 include Electronic Data
Systems of Plano, Texas; Oracle of Redwood Shores, Calif.; Gateway
2000 of North Sioux City, S.D.; Cisco Systems of San Jose; J.D.
Edwards of Denver, and CDB Infotek, a California firm which has
since been acquired by ChoicePoint of Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   On a monthly basis, contributions from the top 50 computer firms
are averaging more than $195,000. That's less than the
record-setting $211,000 monthly average for 1995-96, but a big jump
over other non-presidential election cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, before the global explosion of the World Wide
Web created a new generation of WWWillionaires with a new set of
political concerns, the monthly average for the top 50 was below
$118,000.
</P>
<P>
   The best known political buddies of generous high tech tycoons
are two veteran Democratic schmoozers, President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, who are utterly at home with the industry's
chat-now, pay-later approach.
</P>
<P>
   But the nonpartisan center's studies indicate that Republicans
have gotten about 58 cents out of every political dollar the top 50
companies have handed out since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the GOP is doing better than ever at convincing
computer executives to donate the kind of unregulated ``soft
money'' contributions that would be outlawed under a House-passed
bill pending before the Senate. The Republican share has ballooned
from 33 percent of the $1.3 million given by computer companies in
1995-96 to 54 percent of $1.5 million raised in 1997 and early
1998.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who was briefed in Silicon
Valley in June, is expected back later in August to collect some of
the $20 million he wants the nation's businesses to pony up for the
GOP's fall campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year and a half, an alliance of 150 technology
executives who call their group TechNet has briefed more than 50
members of Congress and raised funds for at least 18 of the
Democrats and 10 of the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to take it for granted that political figures
who didn't grow up in the technology industry understand how
important it is, how fragile it is, how complex,'' said Reed
Hastings, president of TechNet. ``We're bringing them to Palo Alto,
to Seattle, to Boston, to Virginia. A similar effort is being
organized in Austin. High tech is much broader than Silicon Valley,
you know.''
</P>
<P>
   He said they give the office-holders money because ``after you
make an investment of time in having them understand the issues . .
.you want to keep them elected.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every special interest group feels that way,'' said analyst
Jennifer Schechter at the Center for Responsive Politics. ``What
about the people who disagree with (the computer executives) but
can't afford to pay for face time with policy-makers?''
</P>
<P>
   Hastings responded, ``We're not trying to differentiate on the
basis that (because) we give more money, you pay attention to us.
That's a pretty shallow way of viewing the political process.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADDS FOLLOW)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Accountants and trial lawyers and banks and the securities
industry all give tons more money than we do,'' said Wade Randlett,
TechNet's Democratic liaison. ``People come and take part because
it takes a lot of time, words, questions, to discuss the change
from the old economy to the new economy, and (its significance) for
everything from rural development to organ transplants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty sophisticated dialogue, not at all partisan, not
just a one-way lecture,'' said Lezlee Westine, TechNet's GOP
liaison. But she was unable to recall any occasion in which a
public official had changed a high tech executive's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Polese, the CEO of Marimba Inc., a software startup in
Mountain View, Calif., said she finds time for the sessions because
``the high technology industry and our country's future (depend on)
issues such as Internet access for all citizens, individual
privacy, secure communications, and a well-educated,
technology-savvy workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD , WHICH COULD RUN AS A
</ANNOTATION>
SIDEBAR, FOLLOWS)
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In California, technology executives who were appalled by the
state's school system won widespread credit this year for a $3
million effort that resulted in passage of a law that will increase
the number of public charter schools in their state.
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington, the influence of the industry's investment is
harder to measure, mostly because Congress and the Clinton
administration have put off deal-making compromises on many bills
until after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   It looks now as if the industry will win its battles for a law
making it harder for disappointed shareholders to use state courts
to sue companies that issued overly optimistic business
projections. Congress is expected to preserve federal subsidies for
Internet links to schools and libraries, though with a requirement
that the institutions install obscenity-blocking software for
optional use.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the industry's adoption of voluntary
privacy-protection codes has convinced Congress and Clinton to wait
and see whether the policies make it unnecessary to use new laws to
protect children and shoppers from exploitation by Internet-using
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also expected to order some loosening of export
controls on software that uses powerful data-scrambling codes. And
he is expected to compromise with congressional Republicans on
higher immigration quotas for highly skilled professionals.
</P>
<P>
   A two-year or three-year ban on new state or local taxes on
Internet use has better than a 50-50 chance to pass.
</P>
<P>
   But final action this year is less likely on the industry's
proposals for lower capital gains taxes, federal standards on
legally binding digital signatures, a new policy on commercial use
of public data bases, much higher spending on university-based
research, enhanced patent protection laws and extra support for the
International Monetary Fund's efforts to salvage the economies of
the high tech industry's Asian customers.
</P>
<P>
   And the prospects are dimming for passage of anti-spamming laws
to protect Internet users from unwanted e-mail and anti-slamming
laws to protect telephone users from phone-service swindlers. Those
popular proposals are in legislation that is blocked by a dispute
within Congress over whether to use telephone taxes or general
revenues to pay for making the Internet available to students and
library patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
