<HEADLINE>
`GADJO DILO' IS AN ENJOYABLE LOOK AT GYPSY LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title character of Tony Gatlif's latest _ and most enjoyable
_ examination of Gypsy life, ``Gadjo Dilo'' (Crazy Foreigner), is a
determined young Parisian (Romain Duris) who, as the film opens, is
trudging across the frozen outback of Romania on a personal quest.
</P>
<P>
   All his life he's been haunted by the plaintive voice of a
Romanian Gypsy singer named Nora Luca, whose songs his amateur
musicologist father recorded many years before. Now that Eastern
Europe has opened up again, he's out to track her down.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his journey, he can find no one who's even heard of
the singer. But about the time his shoes wear out, he finally
stumbles upon a drunken old Gypsy named Izidor (Isidor Serban), who
has not only heard of Nora Luca, but actually claims to know her
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   The old man takes the young Frenchman to spend the night in a
shanty-town Gypsy community that uneasily exists near a larger
Romanian village. After sobering up, the old man remembers nothing
of the illusive singer, but he decides to adopt the Frenchman.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the movie settles into a light-hearted,
culture-clash comedy as the ``crazy stranger'' lingers in the
village _ gradually overcoming the community's knee-jerk suspicion
of him, becoming virtually accepted into the tribe and falling in
love with a beautiful belly dancer (Rona Hartner).
</P>
<P>
   Like the earlier Gypsy films of the Algerian-born, Spanish-Gypsy
director _ ``Les Princes'' (1982), ``Latcho Drom'' (1993) and
``Mondo'' (1995) _ this one has it both ways. It satirizes the
narrowness of Gypsy culture on the one hand, while wildly
romanticizing it on the other as a bastion of eccentric diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than those earlier movies, however, this one is out to
please its audience with happy incidents and lovable characters.
Star Duris is all wide-eyed Gallic affability, Szerban is as wise
and durable as Zorba the Greek, Hartner is a '40s Hollywood vision
of hot-blooded Gypsy sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   It proves to be a fairly irresistible combination. One shocking
incident of ethnic cleansing aside, ``Gadjo Dilo'' is a happy,
funny, overtly sexy and gloriously life-affirming romp of a movie
that has the distinct smell of a major art-house hit.
</P>
<P>
   Gadjo Dilo. Directed and written by Tony Gatlif. Cast: Romain
Duris, Rona Hartner, Isidor Serban. Lions Gate Films. 97 minutes.
In French, Romanian and Gypsy with English subtitles. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
