<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REGENERATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REGENERATION' IS A SCATTERED FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The setting of Gillies Mackinnon's well-meaning but terminally
dreary period drama, ``Regeneration,'' is a cozy asylum in Scotland
where British military doctors treat shell-shocked World War I
soldiers so they can be sent back to the trenches of France.
</P>
<P>
   The hero is the real-life English war hero and antiwar poet
Siegfried Sassoon (James Wilby), and the story is a fictionalized
account (from a highly acclaimed novel by Pat Barker) of his brief
incarceration there in the wake of his written protest of the war
in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict comes in the form of his doctor, Dr. William Rivers
(Jonathan Pryce), an eminent, fiftyish psychiatrist whose
assignment is less to judge Sassoon's sanity than to bring the
celebrated poet back to his nationalistic senses.
</P>
<P>
   But the conflict turns out to be not much conflict at all. Far
from being a Nurse Ratched, Dr. Rivers is gentle, kindly,
intelligent and a bit shell-shocked himself from dealing with so
many shell-shock cases. He can get angry at Sassoon's haughtiness,
but he likes and sympathizes with the poet.
</P>
<P>
   And the movie seems to lose interest in Sassoon after the first
act to concentrate on the problems of a more authentically
traumatized and equally rebellious patient (Jonny Lee Miller), who
went bonkers after a comrade was blown to bits beside him.
</P>
<P>
   As it progresses, the film gets even more scattered, moving
haphazardly around other cases in the institution, frequently
flashing back on the carnage in France, demonstrating the various
barbaric shock treatments of the time, and showing the impact of
war on a young widow (Tanya Allen).
</P>
<P>
   The film works best as a mood piece. The visuals _ especially
the numerous rainswept shots of the Scottish Moors in winter _ have
a bleak, haunting, end-of-the-world beauty that combine with the
immaculate period detail to give the film an unusual sense of
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   It also effectively dramatizes one of the most touching
relationships in 20th century English literature: the friendship
between Sassoon and Wilfred Owen, an aspiring writer he met in this
institution who would posthumously become the Great War's most
famous poetic chronicler.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, ``Regeneration'' might have been a more memorable
experience had it focused more of its attention on this
relationship, and less on the other, more familiar and (apparently)
fictional storylines that do nothing but batter our senses and
re-enforce what we already know going in _ that war is hell.
</P>
<P>
   Regeneration. Directed by Gillies Mackinnon. Screenplay by Allan
Scott. Cast: Jonathan Pryce, James Wilby, Jonny Lee Miller, Stuart
Bunce. Alliance Films. 95 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3343 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BLADES-SPI &LR;      08-20 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLADES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLADE' PLAYS THE VAMPIRE THRILLER AS EPIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vampire thriller is, of course, the most completely
overworked movie genre of the American cinema. It's been played and
replayed so often for comedy, burlesque, exoticism and horror that
it's become, for the most part, a cliche and a bore.
</P>
<P>
   But this week's edition, ``Blade,'' gives the formula some new
life by playing it as epic _ in fact, as apocalyptic epic. In this
film, it's the vampires that run the world, and the underdog humans
who have to try and take it back.
</P>
<P>
   The result is mesmerizing and often a lot of grisly fun. Horror
fans should eat it up, though a more mainstream audience will be
put off by the film's focus on torture, dismemberment and
blood-bathing, as well as teasing references to incest and
pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Marvel comic book, it's the story a stalwart
vampire hunter named Blade (Wesley Snipes) who stalks the noir
urban landscape dispensing justice to the uppity Undead _ via
silver sword, a gun that shoots silver bullets and canisters of
garlic mace.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big job because the vampires are institutionalized. They
have a secret treaty with the U.S. government, they run the LAPD,
and they have billions in offshore bank accounts. They make the
Mafia look like a neighborhood street gang.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, it turns out that Blade himself is a
semi-vampire, a ``daywalker'' _ a man with the strength of a
vampire but none of its weaknesses. So he has to keep taking a
special serum or he's likely to ``turn.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the additional problem of a Gen X renegade vampire
named Deacon (Stephen Dorff) who, by studying the ancient vampire
scriptures, has found a way take control from the vampire
establishment and make himself ruler of the Earth _ if he can find
the blood of a ``daywalker'' to use as part of his ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the premise of the film _ its complicated vampire
mythology, and conventions of what the creatures can and cannot do
_ never really adds up to anything that makes any sense, even by
the liberal standards we apply to vampire fantasies. Try to analyze
this thing and you'll go nuts.
</P>
<P>
   The film also suffers from the casting of Dorff as the vampire
anti-Christ. He's a good actor and he makes a clear visual contrast
to hero Snipes, but his WASPish pretty-boy, boy-next-door presence
makes him altogether about as menacing as Mickey Rooney playing
Andy Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film is carried by the sweep of its style. Director
Stephen Norrington and his crew create a marvelously paranoid and
incorrigibly morbid comic-book world. The action sequences seem
remarkably original, surreal and exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the rest of the casting works. Kris Kristofferson is just
right as Blade's folksy mentor; N'Bushe Wright (``Zebrahead'')
projects just the proper blend of vulnerability and spunk as
Blade's imperiled love interest; and Snipes makes a volatile,
soaringly resolute, splendidly mythic Savior of Mankind.
</P>
<P>
   Blade. Directed by Stephen Norington. Written by David S. Goyer.
Cast: Wesley Snipes, Stephen Dorff, Kris Kristofferson, N'Bushe
Wright. New Line Cinema. 120 minutes. Rated R for violence and
sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3344 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FRIENDS-SPI &LR;      08-20 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FRIENDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`YOUR FRIENDS AND NEIGHBORS' WILL INFURIATE, FASCINATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neil LaBute's second feature, ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' is
sure to both infuriate (at the preview screening, three people
walked out proclaiming, ``These people are losers!'') and
fascinate.
</P>
<P>
   His ``immorality tale'' about friendship, art, marriage,
relationships and, especially, truth packs a wallop equal to his
first black comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thought LaBute would soften after searingly exploring
sexual politics and ethics within the corporate hierarchy in his
controversial ``In The Company Of Men,'' is sorely mistaken. If
anything he's gone a step further in risking alienation of the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' is dark, entangled, nasty and
altogether possible.
</P>
<P>
   And that's a nod to LaBute's strength as a writer. Purposely
staged as a bawdy Restoration comedy, with a wide lens capturing
all the immoral details between six people who are old
acquaintances and friends, the film rings with emotional resonance
the further away we get in time.
</P>
<P>
   Mary (Amy Brenneman) and Barry (Aaron Eckhart, who gained 40
pounds to play the role) are married and living in their beautiful
new house. Their friends, the couple Terri (Catherine Keener) and
Jerry (Ben Stiller), pay a social call. What appears to be an
innocent visit soon becomes embroiled with darker subtexts.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry makes a pass at Mary and the perfect veneer is stripped
from the facade of both a happy marriage and Jerry and Terri's
romance, revealing the miserable cracks and gouges beneath. Jerry
pursues Mary. Terri becomes involved with a beautiful art gallery
assistant named Cheri (Nastassja Kinski).
</P>
<P>
   Using Jerry and Barry's best friend, Cary (Jason Patric), as the
``purveyor of truth'' and gauge of moral conscience, LaBute has
created a guide through the action who is adept at eviscerating his
friends by tapping into their deepest secrets. He's a solitary
perfectionist, bitingly smart and smugly content in his solitude,
maybe even a little sociopathic. Everyone wants what Cary has and
he thus sets the rhythm for his friend's covetous desires.
</P>
<P>
   It's tricky to ask an audience to like such difficult, abrasive
characters. But, surprisingly, LaBute makes us see the
vulnerability beneath the brittleness. And he's written long, talky
scenes that allow the cast to chew up the scenery and gives the
film a live theater feel. That intimacy, juxtaposed against the
word warfare in which the characters routinely engage, makes ``Your
Friends and Neighbors'' an unusual, difficult, thought-provoking
adventure into modern urban survival.
</P>
<P>
   In making a film that is better than his first movie, LaBute
created a unique and claustrophobic cinema of cruelty and social
commentary that we find riveting, no matter how painful the price.
</P>
<P>
   Your Friends and Neighbors. Directed and written by Neil LaBute.
Cast: Amy Brenneman, Aaron Eckhart, Catherine Keener, Nastassja
Kinski, Jason Patric, Ben Stiller. Gramercy Pictures. 100 minutes.
Rated R for nudity, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3346 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DANCE-SPI &LR;      08-20 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DANCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE STORY AT HEART OF `DANCE WITH ME' IS A DUD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A story of hearts in motion'' reads the tag line for ``Dance
With Me,'' and indeed, ``motion'' is the best thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   While the film is a mix of ``Dirty Dancing'' and ``Strictly
Ballroom,'' with a little ``Lambada'' and ``Staying Alive'' tossed
in, its dance sequences are terrific and crackle with energy and
style.
</P>
<P>
   But the love story at its heart is a resounding dud and the
script is addled with howler lines like, ``How do you dance without
music? It has to come from the music.''
</P>
<P>
   The film seems, at first, an odd choice for director Randa
Haines (``Children Of A Lesser God,'' ``The Doctor''), but then we
recall she also directed the flop ``Wrestling Ernest Hemingway,''
which featured a similar hot, humid atmosphere and a subplot
revolving around a character's obsession with ballroom dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Infante (Chayanne) has left Santiago de Cuba and come to
Houston in search of the man who may be his father. His mother has
just died, leaving Rafael with the address of a man, John Burnett
(Kris Kristofferson), who was the love of her life and with whom
she had a torrid romance two decades earlier.
</P>
<P>
   John owns a rundown dance studio and welcomes Rafael _ though he
doesn't know he's possibly his son _ with open arms. He gives the
young man a job as handyman and Rafael makes a big impression on
the regulars who frequent the Excelsior dance studio.
</P>
<P>
   But one woman, teacher Ruby (Vanessa L. Williams), isn't so
easily won. She is intent upon regaining her standing as the top
International Latin Ballroom dancer at the month-away competition
in Las Vegas and, as a single mom, has little time for flirtation
with a handsome stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael gently breaks down her defenses and teaches her how to
feel the music and loosen up her rigid, disciplined technique. The
two slowly get closer and closer. But in the end, Ruby pulls away,
fearing the feelings she's succumbed to. How can Rafael prove he's
as serious about Ruby as he is about dancing?
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a stranger rolling into town and changing the lives
of everyone in the vicinity is a common cinematic staple.
Unfortunately, ``Dance With Me'' doesn't work on this elemental
level. The intended lovers have little chemistry and the usually
exquisite Vanessa L. Williams is shot so badly that she often looks
scary.
</P>
<P>
   During the climactic scene at the competition in Las Vegas,
we're distracted from enjoying Williams' dancing prowess because
her face looks frighteningly distorted and full of physical pain.
It's like a bad opera. And newcomer Chayanne smiles through the
entire film, utilizing a grin as his main charismatic weapon. In
fact, he smiles more than he dances.
</P>
<P>
   Other supporting characters are equally hammy. English actress
Joan Plowright is on hand as comic relief but her big scene is both
implausible and embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me'' works best when it relies on the understated
appeal of Kris Kristofferson and on the dancing itself.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, all that fancy footwork doesn't begin until an
hour into the film. But when it finally does, the payoff makes up
for the clich &UR; gfacute &LR; e of a story. The final dance competition is
great fun, and full of whip-cracking verve and stylish
choreography. Still, it only makes what's missing all the more
glaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me'' looks great and is full of colorful climate,
but when the dancers aren't on screen, the love story trips all
over its big feet.
</P>
<P>
   Dance with Me. Directed by Randa Haines. Written by Daryl
Matthews. Cast: Vanessa L. Williams, Chayanne, Kris Kristofferson.
Columbia Pictures. 126 minutes. Rated PG for sexual situations,
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
