<HEADLINE>
`DEAD MAN ON CAMPUS' IS MOROSE AND CRASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Tom Everett Scott. After an impressive debut in the Tom
Hanks movie, ``That Thing You Do,'' the actor has slowly seen his
career take a downward spiral. First it was ``An American Werewolf
In Paris,'' now this odious and tasteless trifle.
</P>
<P>
   Even the opening credits are morose and crass in ``Dead Man On
Campus,'' with various methods of suicide integrated into the cast
and crew's names.
</P>
<P>
   The story is based on the urban legend that a ``dead man's
clause'' exists on college campuses that says a student will be
awarded a 4.0 grade point average if his or her college roommate
dies by murder, accidental death, violent death or slow death
within the room itself. Different variations on the theme survive,
but suicide is the method of choice in ``Dead Man On Campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Josh (Everett Scott) is a medical student from Indiana who is
putting himself through school on a scholarship. His roommate,
Cooper (Mark-Paul Gosselaar, who is does his best to impersonate
Jim Carrey in ``The Cable Guy'' here), is a rich party boy who
never goes to class and has eked by on his charms.
</P>
<P>
   Josh has to maintain a B+ average to keep his financial aid, but
after a few months with Cooper as his dorm mate, Josh's grades have
slid into the toilet. The pair embark on a scheme to take on a
third roommate _ one who is actively suicidal _ so they can claim
the ``dead man's clause.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair scout for potential candidates, finding three guys who
appear likely to fall off the edge. Cliff (Lochlyn Munro) is a John
Belushi-esque nutcase, Buckley (Randy Pearlstein) is a computer
nerd who wants to assassinate Bill Gates, and Matt (Corey Page) is
a black-hearted musician who sings songs of death.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``Dead Man On Campus'' drones on and on with its
one-note premise and the jokes fall flat and become tiresome after
awhile. Plus, it's offensive and inane at the same time. Who wants
to watch a bunch of losers try to off themselves? Even the movie's
protagonists turn out to be a couple of schmucks who find no
redemption and learn no lesson from their schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, Everett Scott will have better luck with his next
film, the Meryl Streep-starrer, ``One True Thing,'' because ``Dead
Man On Campus'' is so unfunny and pointless that it deserves to die
a fast death at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Dead Man on Campus. Directed by Alan Cohn. Written by Michael
Traeger, Mike White. Cast: Tom Everett Scott, Mark-Paul Gosselaar.
Paramount Pictures. 96 minutes. Rated R for sexual content,
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
