<SLUG> BC-FILM-HANDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING `HANDS ON A HARD BODY' IS WORTH VIEWERS' TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The documentary ``Hands on a Hard Body'' deals with such an
obscure subject _ a contest sponsored by a smalltown Texas
auto-dealer _ that it's probably going to have a hard time
gathering a great deal of initial audience interest.
</P>
<P>
   But those who venture into the the film are destined to be
richly rewarded: it's an often brilliant, always totally engrossing
competition movie of the first order, and the best documentary to
appear in a Seattle theater so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it's a movie that digs deep into a milieu that's
usually treated with considerable contempt by films _ the lower
middle-class South _ and presents an ensemble of characters who
prove to be considerably more noble and resourceful than their
stereotypes. In this respect, the film is strangely reminiscent of
``The Apostle.''
</P>
<P>
   The contest is an endurance test involving some 24 contestants
who are picked at random by a Longview, Texas, Nissan dealer from a
barrage of applicants. The contestants stand around a brand new
Nissan truck, keeping one hand on its body at all times. The last
hand remaining on the truck gets to drive it home.
</P>
<P>
   The contestants get a five-minute break every hour, and a
15-minute break every six hours. They can talk among themselves,
read, sing, listen to a Walkman, be interviewed by the local radio
station or by filmmaker S.R. Bindler. But the moment more than one
hand leaves the body of the vehicle, they're disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   The contestants are white, black and Hispanic, old and young,
mostly under-educated. As pre-event interviews are cut into the
narrative, we get to know their aspirations, their training for the
event or lack thereof, their strengths and limitations. Most are in
it for the money, others just want to own the ultimate Texas status
symbol.
</P>
<P>
   There's Benny, the returning champion whose running
philosophical observations are so funny and down-home perceptive
that he deserves his own talk show. And Norma, who's propelled by
the ``joy of the Lord'' and has a 200-person prayer network rooting
for her. And Kelly, a sweet kid who wants to win the truck so she
can sell it and stop waiting tables for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The hours drag on. Ten, 15, 20 hours. A few of the less
determined contestants begin to drop off. Then 30, 40, 50, 60
hours. Bodies get numb. Some contestants become delirious, others
hear voices and break into uncontrollable laughter. More fall away
_ especially the younger ones. ``Age and maturity will win this
thing,'' Benny tells us early on.
</P>
<P>
   As the contest goes on for 70, then 80 and toward 90 hours, the
movie puts us right on the edge of our seats. It uncannily
communicates the camaraderie the participants develop for one
another, the excruciating pain and sadness of dropping out after
such a punishing investment, the unusual reservoir of character
that dwells in the psyche of each of the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hands On a Hard Body'' is finally just one terrific
competition movie. It's all here: the thrill of victory, the agony
of defeat, even the heart-pounding, neck-and-neck finish that leads
to the surprise outcome. It may have been shot with home video
cameras on a total budget of under $10, but this little movie
delivers more excitement and drama than any of the summer's $100
million blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   Hands on a Hard Body. Directed and edited by S.R. Bindler.
Produced by Bindler, Kevin Morris and Chaplin John Wilson.
Documentary. Legacy Releasing. 97 minutes. Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
