<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-REGENERATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REGENERATION' BLASTS ANY NOTION OF GLORIOUS COMBAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY STONE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It is sweet and fitting to die for one's country,'' wrote the
Roman poet Horace, but that sentiment takes its lumps in
``Regeneration,'' a riveting British film set in a mental hospital
designed to cure the psychological wounds of World War I veterans
and send them back into battle.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the director nor the star agrees with that lavish
patriotic expression which is nailed as an ``old lie'' in the film,
based on Pat Barker's prize-winning wartime trilogy. Her novel is a
fictionalized account of the real relationships experienced by Dr.
William Rivers, the head neurologist (Jonathan Pryce), Siegfried
Sassoon, a decorated war hero turned passionate anti-war polemicist
(James Wilby), and poet Wilfred Owen (Stuart Bunce), who switched
from romantic verse to blistering evocations of battlefield
horrors.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, Scottish director Gillies Mackinnon, who has
always been haunted by the murderous devastation of the first great
war, said he didn't think of his production as an ``anti-war''
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who see this don't need to be converted,'' he
commented at the Toronto International Film Festival last year. ``I
assume they already feel the First World War was a horrible,
horrible event and should be unrepeatable, but of course it isn't
unrepeatable. After all that carnage, there was the carnage of 1944
and now more carnage in Yugoslavia. It seems that human beings
haven't learned a lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Pryce, interviewed last week by telephone from his vacation home
on Cape Cod, thought it was particularly appropriate that
``Regeneration'' is opening in the United States almost
simultaneously with ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which deals with the
Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the first 20 minutes of `Ryan' seriously demystifies
war. You can feel the trauma and agony the soldiers endured and the
lack of comprehension on their faces when they see the deaths
around them. After that, it turns into a very American movie with
the kind of wartime heroism shown in many American films.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither man, both 50, took a strictly pacifist position.
They agreed with Sassoon, who said he did not believe that no war
is ever justified. He was known as ``Mad Jack'' because he took so
many dangerous risks, but two years on the battlefield convinced
him that the war was ``being deliberately prolonged by those who
have the power to end it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sassoon wanted to be court-martialed for the publicity it would
bring to his declaration to end the war. Instead, pressured by
Sassoon's friend, writer Robert Graves, a medical board figured the
protest could be more effectively silenced by incarcerating him at
the Craiglockart War Hospital in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Mackinnon noted that Sassoon's eloquent statement is the
backbone of the story. The director of ``Playboys'' and ``Small
Faces'' couldn't quite account for his very early identification
with World War I veterans. His grandfather, a veteran, would never
talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole generation was paralyzed in some way. Wounded
inside,'' Mackinnon observed. ``This was a different kind of war.
You can understand the appalling reasons for World War II. This
wasn't like the Holocaust. There wasn't even a crazy philosophy
like Hitler's. This was like you didn't understand why millions of
men had to walk into machine guns. Everybody went there to be
destroyed. I had a sense of guilt that I should have been there _
or maybe,'' he added obliquely, ``I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Glasgow, his home town, he used to meet World War I veterans
who had survived bloody battles fought in France's Somme valley.
One veteran told him, ``I was brought up a Catholic and all my life
I believed in God. Then I went to the Somme and I couldn't believe
in God anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   That remark made a lasting impression on Mackinnon. ``He was a
simple man and the one thing he had was a belief in God.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackinnon, who was educated at the Glasgow School of Art, added
softly, ``I believe in art, I suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   His art training stood him in good stead when it came to
incorporating poetry _ Sassoon's and Owen's _ in the film. ``We
introduced poems that were not in the book, but we needed them for
our story. (For instance: Owen's ``red lips are not so red as the
stained stones kissed by the English dead.'') As soon as you use
poetry in a film it becomes something different because poems are
not supposed to have visual images. As soon as you put visual
images with them it changes them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rivers, who empathizes with his patients and learns from
them, had his own misgivings about repairing them to fight again,
but he also felt that Sassoon's proclamation would accomplish
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wonderful to play a man who is learning about his
profession,'' Pryce said, ``while I'm going through the same
process learning to be Rivers. It was not a pro-active role but a
listening role. If you put it into another context, the Gulf War
soldiers were complaining about the same sort of neuroses as the
men in `Regeneration.' I think the film is very important because
it shows how to vocalize one's objections to war.''
</P>
<P>
   Pryce, who portrayed the pacifist Lytton Strachey in
``Carrington,'' said his closest exposure to a battleground was
observing the violence in Northern Ireland from his home in London.
``War is an obscenity and the necessity to fight is a tragedy. I've
asked myself if I would ever go and fight, but it's always been
hypothetical. There was a real possibility that I might be called
up at the time of the Falklands, but that seemed more like two
rival football teams rather than a war between England and
Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, he later went to Argentina to play Peron in
``Evita'' and got another view that, in a sense, corroborated his
own feelings. ``That war,'' Pryce said, referring to the 1982
conflict, ``was a political piece of maneuvering, not favored by
people in Britain although they rallied to support the soldiers.
The only ones who profited were the politicians of both countries.
In Buenos Aires, I learned that most Argentinians were happy they
lost because it enabled them to overthrow the generals ruling the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   When Pryce looks back at the Falklands era, he said, ``A great
part of me thinks I would not have gone to fight in that war.'' As
with ``Regeneration,'' ``My sympathies are very much with Sassoon
and Dr. Rivers, who sympathizes with the men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
