<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-READING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST FAMILY'S BOOKS FOR HUNKERING DOWN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ It is as predictable as the tourist traffic
and the county fair: the annual sending of the books, a healthy
competition between the only two bookstores on Martha's Vineyard,
which send a selection of summer reading for the first family.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, nothing is quite the same.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's books were chosen well in advance of any
presidential testimony to a grand jury, or any talk of tension
between Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton. But with so many reporters
searching for news, there is plenty of reading between the lines.
</P>
<P>
   So book sellers and authors are being asked such questions as
whether their books are about family dysfunction, or whether a
title like ``Fall From Grace'' was a way of sending a literary hint
to the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too bad,'' said Boston-based novelist Elizabeth Berg.
``It felt to me as though the line of questioning may have been
manipulative,'' said Berg, refering to a TV interview in which she
was questioned about the significance of her book ``What We Keep''
arriving at the Clintons' summer doorstep, courtesy of the
Bickerton &AMP; Ripley bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The novel is about intergenerational turmoil, healing, and
forgiviness, but it definitely was not written with the Clintons in
mind, Berg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news is supposed to be about independent book sellers and
the service they perform,'' Berg said. ``It is of the highest
order.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners of both bookstores _ The Bunch of Grapes in Vineyard
Haven and Bickerton &AMP; Ripley Books in Edgartown _ say they chose
the books for content and quality, and not for any subtle messages.
But Berg was among the many people who have been victim of a press
corps whose annual vacation coverage has been acompanied by the
strange context of the controvesy surrounding Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly two weeks to spend here, White House aides say the
Clintons will probably take in the attractions of the island. Until
then, they can always enjoy their basket of books.
</P>
<P>
   Because Clinton last summer enjoyed ``Sacred'' by Dorchester's
Dennis Lehane, Bickerton &AMP; Ripley Books sent Lehane's newest work
of fiction, ``Gone, Baby, Gone.'' The only duplication on the two
stores' gift lists was a mystery by island author Philip Craig, ``A
Shoot on Martha's Vineyard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they read, and we are so thankful that in all the
competitiveness that exists today we have a first family that
reads,'' said Bunch of Grapes manager Ann Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Bickerton &AMP; Ripley co-owner Marilyn R. Scheerbaum said Bill
Bryson's ``A Walk in the Woods'' was the one she selected as a
``family'' read.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a complete list of the books sent to the summer WHite
House:
</P>
<P>
   From Bunch of Grapes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ships of Gold in the Deep Blue Sea'' by Gary Kinder; ``Havana
Dreams'' by Wendy Gimbel; ``The Last Apocalypse'' by James Reston
Jr.; ``Titan'' by Ron Chernow; ``Summer Sisters'' by Judy Bloom;
``The Book Shop'' by Penelope Fitzgerald; ``The Untouchables'' by
John Banville; ``A Shoot on Martha's Vineyard'' by Philip Craig.
</P>
<P>
   From Bickerton &AMP; Ripley:
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone, Baby, Gone'' by Dennis Lehane; ``Fall from Grace'' by
Clyde Phillips; ``What We Keep'' by Elizabeth Berg; ``A Walk in the
Woods'' by Bill Bryson; ``Hullabaloo in the Guava Orchard'' by
Kiran Desai; ``A Shoot on Martha's Vineyard'' by Philip Craig.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-3RD &LR;  &UR; TA     08-20 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... has been limited.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The summer-blooming butterfly bush has several near-blue
varieties, including Nanho Blue. It dies down to the ground each
winter in colder areas, but the plant doesn't die and instead
sprouts long gawky spikes of color in August that draw butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   The Bluebird variety of rose-of-Sharon has welcome near-blue
trumpets in profusion in late July, each with a red heart and
lasting only a day. This is a large, coarse, messy plant, as it has
all those spent blossoms to shed, but it can be cut back hard each
winter to keep it smaller than the 10 feet it aspires to.
</P>
<P>
   Caryopteris has everything going for it _ it's small, doesn't
need pruning, and produces bluish flowers in late summer and early
autumn. The new variety Worcester Gold even sports chartreuse
foliage that keeps its color all season and combines well with its
soft-blue flowers.
</P>
<P>
   There are many blue-flowered tropical vines, the best loved
being morning glory Heavenly Blue. These one-day trumpets are
truest blue and well named. They really do invite a feeling of
exultation, especially since you have waited so long for them to
bloom. The tissue-thin trumpets lack substance but are as
transparent to light as stained-glass windows. They are easy to
start from seed if planted in May where you want them to grow;
otherwise they are hard to transplant. The flowers won't appear
until September and don't stay open all day. Still, they're
infinitely easier to grow than the legendary blue Himalayan poppy,
which can't stand our hot summers. And no blue flower is more
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Another well worth trying is poisonous solanum. The Glasnevin
selection from Dublin has the most exquisite pale-blue flowers.
</P>
<P>
   There are many near-blue clematis. The bluest climber, according
to expert Sue Austin of the Completely Clematis Specialty Nursery
in Ipswich, is H.F. Young. Herbaceous clematis, which scramble on
the ground rather than climb, also come in some good blue tones,
especially Clematis x durandii. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Blue annuals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most annuals are really just perennials from warmer climates
that aren't hardy here. They're a great source of blues, especially
if you have a conservatory for wintering them over. For the rest of
us, well, they're annuals.
</P>
<P>
   Evolvulus Blue Daze is a morning glory relative that's quicker
to bloom than its cousin. Grow it in hanging planters.
</P>
<P>
   Other worthy tropicals include the blue sky vine (Thunbergia
grandiflora); Clerodendrum ugadense, a shrub for potting; and
Iochroma cyaneum, a relative of the angel trumpet.
</P>
<P>
   Oxypetalum is the turqouise milkweed, hardly worth the trouble
some would say unless you have a greenhouse. The second year, it's
great.
</P>
<P>
   Tender salvias have better blues than perennial salvias. But
don't just stick with boring old Victoria. Try 4-foot-tall cobalt
S. guaranitica, or 3-foot-tall S. patens, which has huge flowers.
The Cambridge variety is light blue. S. thymoides is sky blue and a
foot tall. S. tiliifolia is electric blue. S. uliginosa has
sky-blue flowers that look great in a large terra-cotta pot. S.
sinaloensis is a knockout in containers because it has maroon
leaves to contrast with cobalt flowers. Destined for stardom!
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to search out most of these rarities at specialists
like Blue Meadow Farm.
</P>
<P>
   But garden centers also carry some good, common blue annuals.
You can ask them to order the bluest varieties for you. These
plants will sell themselves and the owners may thank you for the
tip.
</P>
<P>
   Ask for Blue Blazer, the bluest annual ageratum; Blue Boy
bachelor's buttons; and felicia _ the bluest annual daisy.
</P>
<P>
   Phacelia is a California wildflower that doesn't like our hot
summers, so it wins no awards for performance, but people love the
cobalt color, and it's suddenly widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Plumbago should be more available with its ice-blue, phloxlike
flowers. You can winter it over in a cool but sunny window.
</P>
<P>
   Cynoglossum amabile Firmament is close to sky blue, and
conveniently self-seeds. It's an overlooked garden workhorse that
blooms all summer without watering.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget petunias. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Blue flower sources
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are no nurseries that specialize in blue flowers. The best
places to find blue flowers are nurseries run by people who know
their stock and can describe it accurately. If you're very
particular about shades of blue, it's preferable to see a plant in
bloom before you buy it, as individuals perceive color differently.
</P>
<P>
   Plant catalogs, especially the cheaper sort, have a history of
notoriously misrepresenting purple-blue flowers as blue. There are
no roses, dahlias, or tulips that come close to being blue. They're
not even in the ballpark. So beware of any source that claims they
sell these. Photographs can also be misleading, as blue is
difficult to photograph accurately and many photographers use blue
filters on their cameras to enhance color.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's not misrepresentation to describe as ``blue'' a
flower that has red or purple undertones, such as campanula, but
that is widely regarded as blue.
</P>
<P>
   The following sources offer a wide selection, accurately
described:
</P>
<P>
   _Avant Gardens, 710 High Hill Road, North Dartmouth, MA 02748;
508-998-8819.
</P>
<P>
   _Blue Meadow Farm, 184 Meadow Road, Montague Center, MA 01351;
413-367-2394. A large selection of perennials and the region's best
source of rare annuals. Open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. this weekend and
Aug. 29 and 30 before closing for the season. A special open
gardens day with refreshments will be held Sunday. Catalog $3.50.
</P>
<P>
   _Completely Clematis Specialty Nursery, 217 Argilla Road,
Ipswich, MA 10938-2617. Catalog $3. Open Monday through Friday, 8
a.m. to 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _Geraneacea, 122 Hillcrest Ave., Kentfield, CA 94904, carries
the latest and bluest in hardy geranium selections.
</P>
<P>
   _Wayside Gardens, 1 Garden Lane, Hodges, SC 29695-0001;
800-845-1124, or www.waysidegardens.com. Beautiful, free color
catalog of many well-chosen new varieties of herbaceous and woody
plants.
</P>
<P>
   _White Flower Farm, Box 50, Litchfield, CT 06759-0050;
800-503-9624. Free color catalog. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Blue books
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Color in Garden Design,'' by Sandra Austin (Taunton Press,
1998, $35). This Harvard Graduate School of Design alumna provides
a basic vocabulary for thinking about color so it can be used
effectively in any garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garden Artistry: Secrets of Designing and Planting a Small
Garden; Advice on Space, Design and Color Combined for the First
Time,'' by Helen Dillon (Macmillan USA, 1995, $40). A celebrated
Dublin gardener outlines steps for developing harmonious order in
even the smallest garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color Echoes: Harmonizing Color in the Garden,'' by Pamela J.
Harper (Macmillan, 1994, $35) tells how to repeat different tints
of one color throughout a garden to achieve overall unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Color Garden (Blue),'' by Elvin McDonald (Collins
Publishers San Francisco, 1995, $20) discusses blue flowers and
ways to design with them. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``L'heure bleu''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blue is in the eye of the beholder. Actually, it's in the minute
rods and cones in our eyes that register light. The cones perceive
primary colors. The rods see black and white.
</P>
<P>
   During that 40 minutes or so between when the sun has set and
darkness occurs, all colors go through changes as we gradually lose
our ability to perceive any color at all. When darkness has fallen,
our night vision becomes black and white. After dark we can
perceive only white flowers.
</P>
<P>
   The first color we lose as the light fades is red. Then we lose
green. Blue is the last color wave frequency that our eyes
distinguish before the cones give up.
</P>
<P>
   But just before then, we can see the blue frequencies that are
present in most things but masked by other colors. For those few
minutes, most flowers, except the white ones, look blue. Almost
everything looks blue. It's the most romantic time of the day. In
English, it's sometimes called ``the magic hour.'' In French it's
called ``l'heure bleu.''
</P>
<P>
   The blue hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
