<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
_OF CANCER AND DRUGS: BEWARE POT, COCAINE   
 _A CHANGE OF HEART ON CARDIAC RESCUES   
 _CROUP MEDICINE FOUND USEFUL FOR MILD CASES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Of cancer and drugs: Beware pot, cocaine
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smoking marijuana and cocaine may cause lung cancer the same way
that smoking cigarettes does.
</P>
<P>
   That is the conclusion of a first-of-its-kind study that
examined mucous samples from the bronchial passages of 104 healthy
volunteers, 28 of whom were nonsmokers while the rest smoked
cigarettes, marijuana, cocaine, or a mix of the three substances.
The samples were scoured for biological and chemical markers known
to signal an increased risk of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The results, published in the current Journal of the National
Cancer Institute, were dramatic: Smokers of any of the three
substances had substantially more markers of cancer than
nonsmokers, up to six times more. The evidence of precancerous
growths was most pronounced in subjects who smoked both marijuana
and tobacco, or cocaine and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings from the UCLA School of Medicine are especially
troubling given recent trends of increased use of marijuana by US
youth, and continued use of crack cocaine. And ongoing campaigns to
discourage young people from smoking cigarettes ``may have the
unintended consequence that teenage smokers will replace tobacco
with marijuana,'' warned the authors of an editorial in the same
issue of the NCI journal.
</P>
<P>
   But the editorial writers, who work at the MD Anderson Cancer
Center in Houston, said they worry that finding definitive proof
that marijuana and cocaine cause cancer will be tougher than it was
for cigarettes. That, they explain, is ``because of the difficulty
in obtaining reliable information and follow-up from users of
illicit drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A change of heart on cardiac rescues
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of every four patients with severe cardiac troubles does not
want to be resuscitated if the patient's heart stops beating, a new
survey suggests.
</P>
<P>
   However, among patients who could be tracked down two months
after they left the hospital, 40 percent who had initially rejected
resuscitation had changed their minds. The reason, authors of the
study said, is that congestive heart failure patients who feel
terrible shortly after an attack often feel much better later on,
which distinguishes them from people suffering from terminal AIDS
or cancer, who often feel progressively worse.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, published in the American Heart Association journal
Circulation, also found that physicians are not especially good in
monitoring their heart patients' preferences. Researchers
interviewed the doctors of two-thirds of the 936 heart patients who
participated in the survey, and found that one in four doctors
incorrectly perceived their patient's preference regarding
resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about just being in touch with your patient, listening to
them, and understanding where they're coming from,'' said Dr.
Harlan M. Krumholz, a cardiologist at Yale University School of
Medicine and lead author of the article. ``If they are severely
depressed, you may want to encourage them to hold off on deciding
against resuscitation. But if they're of sound mind, and
appropriately depressed after weighing their options, you have to
respect what they say.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Croup medicine found useful for mild cases
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The barking cough and hoarse voice that come with croup are all
too familiar to most parents of young children.
</P>
<P>
   But there's evidence that dexamethasone, an oral medication used
for extreme cases of the illness, can be equally effective with the
more common milder forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason why many of us did not provide dexamethasone for
croup was that many children with mild or moderate symptoms get
better without specific treatment, but it takes longer that way and
a larger proportion end up in the hospital,'' said Dr. David M.
Jaffe, director of emergency medicine at St. Louis Children's
Hospital and author of an editorial accompanying the croup study in
the current New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving dexamethasone can shorten the duration, making it
milder quicker, and reduce the proportion of children who end up
being hospitalized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
