<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG DAY FOR THE BIG EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not unusual for any given week to be crucial for a team's
hopes of success. But it is rare indeed when a week's round of
games is vital to a conference.
</P>
<P>
   That is the scenario looming for the Big East Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Boston College at Georgia Tech; Ohio State at West
Virginia; Tennessee at Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   With two prime-time games plus a major intersectional battle for
Boston College, this is a showcase weekend for a conference that
has had very few such attractions.
</P>
<P>
   How important is the first week of the season? ``Huge,'' says
Big East commissioner Mike Tranghese, who has argued (successfully,
it appears) that his teams play some quality opponents in
nonconference games. ``Winning those games will put our teams right
into the national picture and give a tremendous boost to our
league.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Tranghese about scheduling in general and how the Big East
can get better and his answer is blunt: ``Go out and play some
people. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple and difficult. West Virginia and Syracuse each has a
chance to beat a quality opponent. A West Virginia victory over an
Ohio State team ranked No. 1 in both preseason polls would
certainly boost the Mountaineers into the Top 10 and perhaps into
the Top 5.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse, which has what seems a suicidal schedule, plays
Tennessee and travels to Michigan the following week. A 2-0 start
would put the Orangemen in the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   More important, it would put the Big East, a league desperate
for some positive developments, into the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   The downside, of course, is that the Big East could be
eliminated from consideration as a competitive conference after one
week of play. Blowouts by Tennessee and Ohio State would further
tarnish a conference that can ill afford any more negative
perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Big East football is at a crossroads this season. The talk about
the Big Ten expanding has some people worried that Syracuse is on
that conference's wish list. It is, but only after Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese says he has never felt better about his conference.
And that is the way he should feel. In two weeks, the Big East at
least will have a chance to gain some respect as well as
respectability.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ND will wait and see
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word out of Notre Dame is that the Irish will wait at least
until the first of the year before making a decision on whether to
get serious in their dealings with the Big Ten or break them off.
Although the Big Ten was pushing for a quick decision on whether
Notre Dame would become the 12th member of the conference, that
doesn't appear to be the scenario. Notre Dame athletic director
Mike Wadsworth said last week that there is simply too much
information to absorb and discuss for the Irish to quickly decide
whether to even continue talking with the Big Ten ... Ohio State
officials are worried that All-America linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer
might not be eligible for the season after a shaky summer of
classes. Odds are that Katzenmoyer, who has openly expressed
disdain for the academic side of collegiate life, will make it
through, but don't count on him remaining in Columbus much past the
Buckeyes' last game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BC unfairly hounded
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word has it that some BC fans are unhappy with the Eagles'
decision to drop Southern Methodist in favor of Northeastern. Give
me a break. First of all, it's a better opportunity for the Eagles
to get a win _ one that will count toward the required minimum of
six for bowl eligibility. Secondly, just how big a rivalry does
anyone think SMU-BC is? Northeastern is a better draw in this area,
and it's a better game for college football in New England ...
What's going on at Virginia? It's only August and coach George
Welsh has made his team off limits to the media all week ... Being
No. 1 creates added pressure for an Ohio State program that seems
to be surrounded by it. But according to coach John Cooper, it's no
big deal. ``There's pressure, sure,'' Cooper told the Ohio State
media last week in Columbus. ``But not any more than there's been
the past few years. We were a good team last year, and the nucleus
of that team is back.'' ... Going into the season, Nebraska has the
longest winning streak in Division 1-A with 14. Michigan (12), UCLA
(10), and Colorado State (9) are next ... The Western Athletic
Conference has an unusual situation. Every team in the league has
at least 10 starters back. Nevada-Las Vegas has 20 ... Iowa State
has changed its recruiting tactics. The Cyclones have 18 former
junior college players on their roster.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and national college football sources was used in
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
