<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CULDESAC-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIZE SUBURBAN IDEAL OFFERS PRIVACY OVER NEIGHBORLINESS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEEDHAM, Mass. _ Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   That was the word that came to Christine Battat's mind when she
laid eyes on Burr Drive nearly 18 months ago during a house-hunting
tour. After all, the 5,300-square-foot, nearly completed colonial
she was considering had the kind of turnkey comfort she and
husband, Randy, wanted for themselves and their two children when
they moved from Chicago. And just look at Burr Drive itself: a
slightly bowed cul-de-sac carved in the early 1990s from a small
forest of northeastern pine, a safe haven of eight large and
meticulous homes that display well-tended lawns by day and subdued
lighting by night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Christine Battat remembers thinking, ``is it.
</P>
<P>
   Motor through Boston's suburbs and you'll see that such
subdivisions are also it for many other familes who can pay the
price. As land suitable for development dwindles, particularly in
the inner suburban ring, old estates and former farms are
transformed into short, dead-end ``lollipops.'' But the new houses
that line many of these instant neighborhoods are hardly the
shoeboxes upon which suburbia was founded after World War II, nor
even the relatively modest manses of a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all that is different. Wednesday's sprawling suburbs
offered accessibility and togetherness, a vision of block parties,
barbecues, and over-the-back-fence intimacy that knit the
neighborhood together. Today's cul-de-sac is almost
antineighborhood by contrast, existing unto itself while providing
cocooned residents with the security, privacy, and exclusivity of a
gated community. Except without the gates.
</P>
<P>
   This quiet new street, where house lots have sold for as much as
$305,000, is typical of a new upsized American Dream being found in
suburbs from Boxford to Natick to Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   But if square footage has lured these baby boomers to Burr
Drive, so has the notion of cul-de-sac living. Schmooze with the
families who live here and soon they'll be extolling the virtues of
privacy and security. They like the fact that while Sunday drivers
may turn into the short street to ogle the homes, the only
nonresident pedestrians are the occasional joggers who bound onto
the road from busy South Street. ``This is a very closed
environment,'' Thomas says, adding that the nearest parallel
street, a cul-de-sac 200 yards away, is ``another community,
really.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Burr Drive is a kind of island, a place from which kids
_ five of the families have children age 12 and under _ are ferried
by car to their activities. Meanwhile, non-islanders are permitted
but their presence is noted. ``We watch each other's houses,''
points out Karon Cohen, who moved onto the street three years ago
with her husband, Lewis. ``We watch each other's comings and
goings. We're very protective of the street, and we're very aware
of `foreign' cars when they come down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Their concern about traffic is such that residents recently rose
up at a public hearing to express their opposition to a plan that
would link Burr Drive to a proposed subdivision. ``We bought on a
cul-de-sac for a reason,'' Battat explains. ``We don't want traffic
going through here.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't necessarily the kind of place where these folks grew
up. Paula Vanderhorst and John Thomas are 39-year-old management
consultants who moved here three years ago with their three kids
and a live-in nanny. Vanderhorst was raised in a small town in New
York State, cavorting in a neighborhood where kids roamed from
street to street after school. There were green fields to play in
too. Now her children spend much of their playtime right here on
Burr Drive with their closest neighbors, where they are well
watched and well contained. That's the way Vanderhorst likes it.
``I wouldn't let my children disappear for half an hour,'' she
declares. ``With all the weird stuff going on today, you just can't
be too careful.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like a movie set
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drive down Burr Drive on a non-summer weekday morning and it
looks like a movie set during lunchbreak. The silence is broken
only by the occasional high chirping of birds or the low hum of
mowers being pointed to and fro by lawn-care workers. The action
picks up when the kids hit the 40-foot-wide pavement to bike or
play street hockey, but the mood is hardly raucous. ``One of the
reasons we moved here is that we wouldn't be bombarded with
children,'' says Karon Cohen, who has two grown children and one
grown stepchild. The street definitely has a subdued feeling,
though its serenity is not for everyone. John Bruno, whose Walpole
construction company built the Battats' house on speculation, says
he lost more than one prospective buyer for the home because
several people wanted to live in a larger neighbrhood with more
kids around.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the adults' social life is, as Vanderhorst puts it,
``still evolving.'' But it's aided in no small measure by the fact
that Burr Drive is almost exclusively populated by educated
professionals who range in age from their late 30s to early 50s.
It's a group that comfortably shares personal values and swaps
business war stories when gathering at Christmas or Thanksgiving,
or at, say, Lew Cohen's 50th birthday party. They jokingly critique
one another's lawns and gladly fetch coffee for each other at
Starbucks, miles away. Yet they do all this with the same sense of
privacy and retreat that brought them here in the first place.
``Everyone knows everyone, but they don't know everyone's
business,'' is the way Karon Cohen puts it.
</P>
<P>
   All of them are the very first owners of their respected homes.
That means are there no ancient and honorable cliques on their
little road, no old guard eager to declare that things have been
done a certain way for years. And the street _ which doesn't even
appear on many recent maps _ is so new none of its initial
residents has yet moved away. ``I think if you had second- and
third-generation owners, people wouldn't socialize as much,'' Lew
Cohen declares. ``Older neighborhoods tend to be more stratified.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
