<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JOHNSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' JOHNSON SET TO CASH IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots and linebacker Ted Johnson have
reached agreement on a five-year contract extension worth in the
vicinity of $25 million, which should be made official sometime
today.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his agent, Jack Mills of Colorado, have been
negotiating for several weeks. The talks stalled for a while
because Johnson was seeking Levon Kirkland-type money _ five years,
$28 million. But Mills backed off and the parties came to an
agreement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have said privately that they would not have been
able to put together such a deal for Johnson if they had matched
the six-year, $36 million package the Jets gave Curtis Martin when
he left New England as a restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a fourth-year veteran, could have become an
unrestricted free agent after the season, but the Patriots probably
would have designated him their franchise player, thus retaining
him, anyway. But the team didn't want to create bad feelings and
decided to do a deal immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's $403,000 salary for 1998 probably will be upgraded,
and he'll also receive a sizable signing bonus, though perhaps not
as big as Willie McGinest's $8 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-3-inch, 240-pounder from the University of Colorado,
Johnson immediately began to establish himself as an NFL presence
after the Patriots selected him in the second round, 57th overall,
in the 1995 draft. In his debut season, Johnson started the 12
games in which he appeared and earned a berth on the NFL All-Rookie
Team.
</P>
<P>
   He emerged as the club's leading tackler with 115 _ 87 solo _
during the Super Bowl season of 1996 and was selected first-team
All-Pro by USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Johnson set career highs with 127 tackles (95 solo),
again leading the team, and four sacks. He was picked as a Pro Bowl
alternate.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's considered on the cusp of becoming a Pro Bowl
perennial, and retaining him was regarded as a top Patriots
priority.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiating parameters were roughly set when Kirkland signed
his blockbuster deal during the spring, virtually guaranteeing
Johnson an astronomical raise as he approached the end of his
present three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations intensified when the Patriots opened the exhibition
season in San Francisco Aug. 2 as Mills and club vice president
Andy Wasynczuk spent most of the game discussing the pact. Both
sides termed the talks encouraging and proceeded from there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3376 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-CULDESAC-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-20 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CULDESAC-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEEDHAM, Mass. ... more stratified.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But if folks on Burr Drive are bound together by their
similarities, so are they kept apart by their work styles. When
Randy Battat eases his Cadillac out of the garage at 5:30 a.m.,
bound for a swim before he takes on his job as a vice president of
Motorla, he may have been beaten off the mark by as much as two
hours by Lew Cohen in his Mercedes. ``You can't leave for work at
7:30 or 8 o'clock and expect to pay for these houses,'' says Cohen,
who owns a company that manufactures adhesive tape.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of couples here have two incomes, and most don't
work fixed hours. In the sunlit kitchen of John Thomas's house,
where he earns a star on the family calendar when he arrives home
from work by 7 p.m., he smiles wryly as he wife reviews his recent
success. ``One, two, three, four, five,'' Vanderhorst announces as
she counts the stars. ``That's five in May. And in April, he had
two.'' Thomas shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in the likes of jogging, squash, and tennis, not to mention
what Vanderhorst calls those ``yuppie workout areas,'' and it's not
surprising these people aren't buying fixer-upper homes and
spending their Saturdays atop ladders. ``The most precious
commodity for people like this is time,'' says Bill Kiley,
president of Hunneman Coldwell Banker, who points to a recent study
that found that 87.8 percent of all married buyers of homes in
Massachusetts are two-income families. ``Married couples used to
tend to buy older houses, fix them up, and then move on. That went
away with the dual-income buyer. No one's around the house to deal
with contractors anymore. So they choose new construction.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 rooms and a Jacuzzi
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The average Burr Drive home _ most sit on an acre of land _ is a
2 1/2-story, columned colonial valued for tax purposes by the town
of Needham at $665,450 and consisting of 4,815 square feet of
finished living space, a 2,341-square-foot basement, 10 rooms, 4
1/2 bedrooms, three bathrooms, one lavatory, central air
conditioning, a deck, and a Jacuzzi. Three-car garages are
required, as spelled out by the design standards of the developer.
Artificial siding is banned, and so are TV satellite dishes.
Clotheslines must be out of sight, sheds are limited in size, and
only cedar fences are permitted. There's one swimming pool on the
street, four sport-utility vehicles, two dogs, one cat, and the
occasional white-tailed deer.
</P>
<P>
   Francis and Cathy Fung, who with their two children became the
second family to set up housekeeping on Burr Drive, moved here from
a more modest Needham neighborhood in 1994. Their previous house
was half the size of the stately 4,000-square-foot colonial that
Francis Fung, an engineer, designed himself. The Fungs initially
worried a bit about who their new neighbors might be, but today
they're happy living among the other baby boomers who've chosen to
reside on Burr Drive. Yet they know that their previous
neighborhood is separated from their current one by more than a few
miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw more of our neighbors in the old neighborhood,''
Francis Fung explains as he relaxes in his oversize living room.
``The houses were closer together, and you'd see them when you went
out. Here, the people travel a lot on business. And they seem to
spend a lot of time inside their houses. They're not outside mowing
their lawns, so they don't see each other and say, `Hey, come on
over for a beer.'
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have very busy schedules. So when they do get
together, there's a lot of talk about e-mail and airports.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Old family estate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like most similar new neighborhoods, Burr Drive sprouted on a
patch of land that once belonged to a single family. The wooded
property was owned for much of this century by Leslie Cutler, the
first female senator in Massachusetts. In 1973, it was purchased,
in two parcels totaling about 40 acres, by Dr. Fredrick Cunliffe
and his wife, Donna, along with another family member, A.G.
Hartman. The total price of $227,500, which included Leslie
Cutler's large and still-standing stone house built in 1913, was
less than the cost of a typical 1-acre Burr Drive lot of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   The Cunliffes now spend much of their time in Maine and Florida,
so Donna Cunliffe and Hartman began drawing up plans for Burr Drive
in 1990. They retained one of the eight house lots for themselves,
building a massive, 7,500-square-foot home where Hartman now lives.
Four additional large new houses are planned for the remaining
acreage beyond the end of the street, homes that are expected to
fetch well over $1 million apiece and will overlook the nearby
Charles River. This means that the development will finally be able
to live up to its seldom-used name: Waterview Estates. ``This is
not an Ozzie and Harriet neighborhood,'' muses Hartman, who is in
his 70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some beautiful old trees here,'' Donna Cunliffe
says of the woods that Burr Dive has replaced. ``But someone was
eventually going to do it (develop the land) if we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they are doing it only a half-mile east of Burr Drive,
as the estate once owned by Thomas Dudley Cabot becomes 20-acre
Stonefield Estates, a lollipop of 16 new homes being marketed for
$1.2 to $1.3 million each. Three houses are already in place, and
the residents have held a cookout. Their other neighbors will move
in during the months ahead, seeking out the tranquility and privacy
found in other such grand cul-de-sacs of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' they will likely say. ``Perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
