<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
  
 DOES M's BRASS HAVE WILL, SKILL TO FIX THINGS?  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Lou Piniella's shoes were covered in dust, which might
have been a good metaphor for a Mariner season covered in the
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But it was dust from something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was over at the new ballpark today,'' Piniella said
Wednesday, removing one of his shoes and wiping down the black
leather with care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, it's nice. The people of Seattle have something they can
be really proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not something the Mariners' skipper could exactly say
about his team's results in the standings or in the court of public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   By now, all citizens of Marinerville understand that the
remainder of '98 will mean not much more than Alex Rodriguez's run
at 40-40; Ken Griffey Jr.'s usual amassing of hits, RBIs,
over-the-back catches and homers; and the development of the
youngsters soon to be called up from Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   And this is really strange.
</P>
<P>
   Here it is mid-August and the home team is dead. One trip down
to the Kingdome these days is all it takes to understand the depths
of this lost season.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Gate D, there used to hang a giant poster that featured
every one of the Mariner stars and starters. Jay Buhner. Edgar
Martinez. Ken Griffey. Alex Rodriguez. Jeff Fassero. David Segui.
Russ Davis. Randy Johnson. Joey Cora.
</P>
<P>
   Well, wouldn't you know it. Someone has gone and taken it down.
It's like the end of an era. The little star-studded Northwest team
that helped bring baseball back to life is gone.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left out there on the Kingdome exterior are big block
letters that say ``Gate D.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly the sort of alluring displaythat would attract
walk-up ticket buyers into the Kingdome, where expectations for
meaningful Augusts and Septembers were born in 1995, '96 (where the
M's were still in the AL West hunt until the final weekend) and
'97.
</P>
<P>
   But it makes sense that the poster has been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is gone, finally, about eight months too late,
considering the best deal and the best way to have rid the team of
this problem would have been to trade Johnson last January.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Cora and Davis are either out of Seattle or on the trading
block, which means the M's must now search for a lead-off hitter,
second baseman, third baseman, and, yes, a No. 1 starter and a
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Cora gives you some clue, though, about the downtrodden
emotional status of the Mariner team, which has been left frayed
and deflated by months of indecision and lack of trades to try and
improvement the team _ all culminating in the botched Johnson
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Fallout continued even after the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a meeting after Randy was traded and they didn't even
ask some of us to come,'' Cora said Wednesday, still extremely
disappointed and hurt by the way things unraveled this season.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, only the core group of Mariners (Rodriguez, Segui,
Buhner, Dan Wilson, Fassero, Moyer and Griffey) was involved in the
post-trade meeting in which Mariner vice president of baseball
operations Woody Woodward tried to diffuse anger over the Johnson
trade _ which brought no major leaguers from the Astros and had
players seriously thinking the M's were about to dismantle this
one-time contending team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm out of here, but that really hurt,'' Cora said. ``I
mean, I'm still out there busting my butt every day. But it's so
obvious I'm out of the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   There is still no clear indication that the chain of command
from ownership down to the front office will soon be put into
working order.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mariners to make any real improvements, something must
be done. One might guess that ownership is considering the notion
that someone, or some people, might have to pay for what went wrong
with the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   But ownership has some responsibility, too. It needs to make
known its priorities.
</P>
<P>
   No one will ever know what might have happened if ownership had
let Woodward and Chuck Armstrong offer Johnson the Roger
Clemens-type money ($8 million a year) they thought was
appropriate, even if Johnson's agents were demanding Greg Maddux
money ($11 million) or a trade.
</P>
<P>
   And after that did not happen, no one knows how much brighter
and happier 1998 would have been if Woodward had gone ahead and
pulled the trigger on an off-season Johnson deal. The Yankees,
Indians and Blue Jays all were ready to make a good deal, although
Woodward obviously thought he wasn't getting enough for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   And no one is exactly explaining why ownership has decided to
meddle in the affairs of their baseball people _ unless, of course,
there is division or mistrust between ownership and the baseball
people.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Cora said, maybe none of the faceless 16 owners care.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got their ballpark,'' Cora said.
</P>
<P>
   But we can tell you this: It's August in Seattle and the home
team is out of contention. What happens between now and spring
training will tell the good citizens of Marinerville everything
they need to know about whether they should be proud or peeved.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
