<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3397 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-ART-BOS &LR;      08-20 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT A STONE HOUSE _ BUILT BY HAND  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It all started in 1987, when Ralph Weaver built a stone house,
literally by hand.
</P>
<P>
   He thought it a good idea to tell somebody about it; after all,
stone houses are not built by hand every day. So he sent the
Globe's handyman a picture of the house and a letter wondering if
the handyman would be interested. The handyman replied fairly
quickly, by letter, having failed to find Weaver in the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the handyman wrote, that looks and sounds like a good
idea, so let's set a date. The handyman promptly forgot about the
letter.
</P>
<P>
   So did Weaver. (itals)Nine years later(unitals), he found the
handyman's letter while rummaging through some house documents.
Unopened.
</P>
<P>
   From then on things moved at lightning speed. Weaver wrote the
handyman, with some chagrin, enclosing the letter and another
suggestion for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   This time he enclosed his number, which the handyman promptly
called to make a date. Weaver could not explain how the letter was
never opened and then put away, but did say that he has another
stone project in mind, and bought equipment to handle the stones.
``This is necessary, because for some unknown reason, the stones
that they have today are much heavier than the ones I used in
1987.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the stone house in Carver, Mass. is not Weaver's first
project. He built a 24- by 24-foot stone garage, ``to see if I
could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, a retired policeman who will turn 50 next November,
found that he could do it _ the garage went up in one summer _ so
he tackled the much bigger house with confidence. Confidence he
needed; the house is 36 by 42 feet.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Joanne, and two children, who live with him in Newton,
Mass., are tolerant supporters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but why stone? ``I bought the land in 1982, then I read a
book about stone walls, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver admits knowing zero about stone, but he wasn't afraid to
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mason told me about the old stone houses in New England that
are much admired today. They were built by farmers who knew nothing
when they started.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So, why not me?'' he said. He started the right way, building
a huge foundation to hold the great weight of the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver used slip-form construction as described in the first of
several books he read. And here is how it works. For one thing, it
allows walls to be built by two men. ``Me and another guy,'' Weaver
said.
</P>
<P>
   He built forms, similar to those used in pouring concrete, but
only four feet high. The forms were set on a cement-and-slurry coat
on the foundation and the first course of stones put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the stones have at least one flat face, said Weaver,
and set this face on the outside wall of the form, so when the form
is removed, the flat faces of the stones will show.
</P>
<P>
   Then add concrete on top of the first course and behind it and
between the stones. This concrete is the mortar, holding everything
in place. The concrete fills the form toward the inside, so that
the inside surface looks like a regular poured concrete foundation,
more or less. It's not very neat, but a framed, insulated wall
covers that inside of the stone wall.
</P>
<P>
   As the form is filled, the concrete is allowed to set overnight;
then the form is raised and secured and the procedure starts all
over again to complete the wall.
</P>
<P>
   It took Weaver and ``the other guy'' six months to complete the
four sides.
</P>
<P>
   One problem that Weaver ran into was how to handle the concrete.
He couldn't order ready-mixed concrete, because the wall work was
slow, and some of the ready-mix would set before it was used.
</P>
<P>
   So Weaver mixed his own, a classic 1:2:3 mix, 1 part Portland
cement, 2 parts sand, and 3 parts crushed stone. He bought a mixer
for $75 from used goods magazine and put an electric motor on it.
It worked out well.
</P>
<P>
   From then on it was easy: framing and finishing.
</P>
<P>
   The wall comes out like a riprap conglomerate wall, which is
exactly what it is. The joints are deep and somewhat crude, but
that wall is going nowhere for several hundred years. No, a
thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   And just think, no painting, staining, sealing, or any other
treatments, even repointing, for a thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye toward his new project, he bought a bigger mixer, a
Seabee surplus machine from the Yankee Swapper in Rhode Island. He
also bought a big logging claw, designed to wrestle logs around,
but, he says, ``I'll use it to haul all those heavier stones
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver isn't quite sure what his next project will be, but you
can bet it will be with stone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
