<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3406 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-SURVIVOR-AR     08-20 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-SURVIVOR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLOCAUST, LOST CHILDHOOD DRIVE CABBIE'S SEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ACTON, Mass. _ Tatiana Benharbone strains forward in the
driver's seat of her taxi, gesturing with one hand flying off the
wheel, sometimes two. The Volkswagen van glides down Route 2,
slipping into Boston at dusk.
</P>
<P>
   It is an hour when, in the glare of headlights and under the
dark canopy of sky, fairy tales seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I'm not really from this planet,'' says
Benharbone. ``That's what saves me.''
</P>
<P>
   Benharbone's home planet would be a world where gypsy dancers
spin to the beat of Spanish guitars, where horses leap through
fields of pastel fog. A land where a person can live many lives.
</P>
<P>
   Benharbone has wandered from life to life, continent to
continent. She has crossed European borders hidden in a covered
wagon, peered from windows of Jerusalem buses, always searching,
reaching out for some elusive comfort.
</P>
<P>
   A Jew born in Poland in 1937, Benharbone was raised Catholic by
a family who, by taking her in, spared her from the Treblinka death
camp where her parents and grandmother died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I was from anyplace,'' says Benharbone. ``I
didn't know who I was or where I was going. I felt like a displaced
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving a cab has become the latest vehicle for Benharbone's
wanderlust. Today, she speeds down Boston-area highways, acting out
her rootlessness. Her unsettled nature, common to many Holocaust
survivors, is a product of the World War II era when she and
millions of other Jews were forced to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   A half-century later, 891 Holocaust survivors live in
Massachusetts, according to the registry of the Holocaust Museum in
Washington. Most are elderly. Benharbone is one of the few who
remain in the working world.
</P>
<P>
   Benharbone's postwar journey began on the doorstep of an
orphanage, where she was left clutching a rosary and New Testament,
with no idea what it meant to be Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   The little Polish girl grew into a flamenco dancer who twirled
her way through New York, California, Spain, and Israel, commanding
attention on stage with the thump-thump of her high heels, with her
dark beauty and wild hair.
</P>
<P>
   That gypsy dancer became an artist whose political cartoons and
whimsical animal dreamscapes were snatched up on the streets of
Toulouse, France.
</P>
<P>
   After she had saturated the Toulouse art market, Benharbone
landed back in America, because the $200 plane fare to New York was
the same price as a bus ticket to Nice. Now the
orphan-turned-dancer-turned-painter is the owner of ABC Taxi, a
one-woman cab company she has run out of her Acton home since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Once widowed, once divorced, living far from two adult children,
Benharbone is still searching, still running. She continues to play
hide and seek with the loneliness that has shadowed her from
childhood. At age 60, she is more comfortable in motion than at
rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I wake up in the morning and everything hurts,'' she
says. ``But as soon as I get going on a cab job, I'll start talking
to the customer and, it's neat, I feel a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in my house, sometimes it feels really strange, kind of
lonesome and empty. Acton isn't home. I don't think anyplace is
home.''
</P>
<P>
   She left her first home as a toddler. Her parents had already
disappeared into the chaos of wartorn Warsaw, ultimately bound for
the death camps. Her grandmother woke her one night, she remembers,
and took her to a family in Krakow.
</P>
<P>
   That night exists as a series of snapshots in her mind _ a
bundle of blankets, a team of horses, staring despairingly into a
bowl of noodle soup in her strange new home.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandmother promised to come back. She never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting with my grandmother, every time I formed an
attachment with someone, they disappeared,'' Benharbone told
historians from the Holocaust Museum.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, she was given up by the family that hid her, and
wound up in the care of Lena Kuchler, a Polish Jew who, like
Benharbone, passed as Catholic to survive the war. Kuchler gathered
Jewish orphans under her wing, later recording her story in a book,
``My Hundred Children.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that postwar violence against Jews in Poland threatened
the children's lives, Kuchler snuck her brood into France and
eventually took the group to Israel. Benharbone, one of the
youngest, was adopted from France by an American family, perhaps
because she was ``too frail and dreamy for life on a kibbutz,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Benharbone does not like to talk directly about the
Holocaust, which she calls a tired subject. She does acknowledge,
however, that a disrupted childhood has shaped her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this terrible hole inside you,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Benharbone's days of running did not end when she came to the
United States. Too raw and troubled for her adopted family, she
says, she moved in and out of their Cambridge home and, after
graduating from Simmons College in Boston, ran off to dance in New
York in 1961. There she met her first husband, flamenco dancer and
choreographer Roberto Iglesias.
</P>
<P>
   The two dancers performed together throughout Europe and Israel.
After Iglesias died of a heart attack in 1972, Benharbone started
her own dance company in Israel. The Jerusalem Post wrote of ``the
astonishing Spanish dancer Tatiana ... whose flying heels, toes,
knees and other appendages have to be seen to be believed.''
</P>
<P>
   Flamenco spoke to Benharbone, who identified more as a gypsy
than as a Jew. ``The soul of flamenco deals with pain, it comes
from an oppressed people,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Benharbone remarried and settled in France with her two children
from her first marriage. An overzealous doctor, whom she now
curses, told her a bad hip made dancing too risky. She turned to
painting to express her restlessness, her love of movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to create things that are beautiful, that don't
really exist,'' she explained in the interview with Holocaust
Museum historians. ``I never wanted to deal with the anger and the
pain. Inside me there's this tremendous rage. Sometimes I feel it
and it scares me.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the Boston area was a disappointment to Benharbone,
and it strained her marriage to the breaking point. With no way to
make a living as an artist, she founded ABC Taxi. With the
exception of a short break to dance in California, the taxi has
been her life work ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started with ABC I was lonely and divorced, and
it was great for me,'' she says. ``The phone would ring and I would
get to go on a ride somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Benharbone has struggled with boredom, and with the back and
neck pain that come from driving all day. But she tries to find
purpose in her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business has kept me alive and paid my bills,'' she says.
``It also helps people by getting them where they need to go. It's
not painting, it's not dancing or poetry or creating beauty, but it
does a practical good.''
</P>
<P>
   And it keeps her moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on a spiritual search now,'' says Benharbone. ``I write
songs, I write poetry. Words just come to me and I record them when
I'm walking my dog in the woods or driving the cab early in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, she adds, ``I have a dream to get myself in an RV and
just go, just drive out to the Grand Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the journey to Logan and back suffices. She
jokes with her customers, but she rarely tells them personal
stories, saying, ``My own life is not that interesting.'' She takes
her dog, Kitty, along on most trips, and gives her cars names like
``the flying phroomph.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you always look forward to new adventures, new exciting
things, new learning experience,'' she says, ``then it's OK. You
can get through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
