<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-MAC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING PERSONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUG BAILEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't really believe I'm smarter than the average Macintosh
loyalist, but I remember being at MacWorld several years ago when
Apple introduced the Newton Personal Digital Assistant and thinking
that all the enthusiastic attendees shelling out hundreds of
dollars for the little device were wasting their money.
</P>
<P>
   I never caught the Newton bug. It was a great idea but the thing
was too big, too dim, and the handwriting recognition program left
much to be desired. I first picked one up at a 1990 Apple
conference in San Jose and wrote ``hello'' on the screen in
longhand, which the computer translated as ``little.'' Beyond the
fun of some comically erotic translations of my scrawl, I could
find no practical use for the Newton. And when Apple folded the
Newton experiment last year, I resisted the temptation to say I
told you so and forgot about PDAs all together.
</P>
<P>
   Even when my brother showed up one day with a PalmPilot by 3Com,
I scoffed. ``What do you do with it?'' I asked. Mostly it seemed to
be an electronic Rolodex that also played Space Invaders. I need
this? And when he told a story of being in a recent meeting when
seven people around the table all suddenly pulled out their
PalmPilots, I roared. How geeky can you get?
</P>
<P>
   Then a few weeks ago a friend of mine who works at Lotus
Development Corp. was seriously extolling the virtues of the
PalmPilot, and this time I listened. Her husband said he was
getting one too. Some quick research and I realized I was way
behind the PalmPilot curve. And, of course, I can't have that.
</P>
<P>
   3Com has sold more than 1 million PalmPilots in the last two
years, making it the most successful pocket-sized computer on the
market. Casio, Hewlett-Packard, Phillips, and even Microsoft all
sell handhelds or will soon, but clearly the business belongs to
3Com at moment. It holds about a 65 percent market share.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking I had perhaps underestimated the device's attraction, I
recently bought a PalmIII, 3Com's third generation Pilot that was
released earlier this year. I can't say that owning one has been a
life-changing experience, but I am a convert. The PalmIII now holds
my contacts, phone numbers, appointments, memos, e-mail, and
miscellaneous scrawlings.
</P>
<P>
   With the optional modem, I can send and receive e-mail and even
surf the Web when I'm away from the office or home.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmPilot's best feature is the ability to instantly
synchronize data between your home and office computer. In fact,
it's easier to input data to your desktop and transfer it to the
PalmPilot with a push of a button. It supports Lotus Notes and
desktop organizers. 3Com also intends to make the PalmIII double as
a pager, a feature already available in earlier PalmPilot models.
</P>
<P>
   The best news for Mac users is that the PalmPilot is about to
become more compatible with their home and office machines. Later
this summer 3Com plans to release a new MacPac system to improve
connections between the PalmPilots and Macs as well as a version of
Claris Organizer software. 3Com bought Claris Organizer from Apple
last year. The program integrates calendar, contacts, tasks, notes,
and intelligent features such as drag-and-drop scheduling, custom
views, and printing options in one application.
</P>
<P>
   All current Macintosh users of the Palm III, like me, who bought
the original MacPac version 1.0, will qualify for a free upgrade to
the new Palm MacPac software. The free upgrade can be downloaded
from the company's We bsite for 60 days after the product is
released, at http://www.palm.com.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to support. Unlike the Newton, which was
virtually orphaned by software developers _ and eventually by Apple
itself _ the PalmPilot benefits from scads of support, not just
from 3Com but from third-party producers, shareware developers, and
other sources. The best sites can be found at the palm.com site.
One of the new sites is Ziff-Davis's at
http://www.hotfiles.com/pilotsoftware.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Addendum: I've heard all the news stories about Apple's new
iMac being a likely hit, but now I'm sure of it. My 68 year-old
mother bought one Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Doug Bailey can be reached at dbaile(at)mediaone.net
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
