<HEADLINE>
WEST WAS A VOICE FOR BLACK MIDDLE CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  She opened the door wearing pink slippers and a flowered
house robe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Dorothy West was a tiny, brown lady, but after two decades of
silence, she had become an important literary figure, once more.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago on the Fourth of July, I walked through a dark,
wooded area in the Oak Bluffs section of Martha's Vineyard, looking
for her home. As I found and entered her cluttered cottage, there
was a picture on her wall of a much younger West, a photo often
used in a poster of the Harlem Renaissance writers.
</P>
<P>
   West, who died Sunday at age 91, was the last living member of
that 1920s group, in which black writers made their marks on the
literary scene. She was the youngest of the stars, who included
Langston Hughes, Countee Cullen, Richard Wright, and Zora Neale
Hurston.
</P>
<P>
   It was an era that brought the black literary voice to the
forefront. The young, strong voices like that of West spoke
lyrically about the stench of racism and the sweetness and
bitterness of love. The authors wove together folksy tales of the
black experience.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, writing at a time when racism was arguably at its
worst, they were not ostracized, but hailed as the voice of the
time, West said. Over the years, the writers' circle faded, some
authors no longer in vogue, many eventually dying off, but quietly
West lived on, nestled in the Oak Bluffs home she summered in as a
child.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, though, West was only a distancing study in
African-American literature. She had published her first
book, &UR;  &LR; ``The Living Is Easy,'' in 1947, but for decades her life
seemed uneventful. That is, until 1995, when her smash book, ``The
Wedding,'' was published.
</P>
<P>
   Both books, though decades apart, explored a black middle-class
family in New England, ``The Living Is Easy'' in Boston, ``The
Wedding'' on Martha's Vineyard. Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis urged
her to write the second book. Sometimes, West recalled during an
earlier interview, the former first lady-turned-book editor would
come to her little cottage, sit on the floor, and the two women
would talk about life and the progress of the book. She dedicated
the book to Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   Like the themes of most of her work, ``The Wedding'' dealt with
a web of issues involving the black middle class, including race,
the issue of skin tones among blacks, and interracial love.
</P>
<P>
   Although her stories were set decades ago, the topics are still
not easy for many African-Americans to swallow. Even now, in book
clubs throughout the country, her stories spur heated discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The issues that she wrote about sprang from her own life: West
was the daughter of an emancipated slave who became a successful
merchant; her mother was light-skinned. Her cousins, who shared her
four-story home in Boston, were very light-skinned _ so it was the
darker West who felt the brunt of nasty comments.
</P>
<P>
   But West always said it was the universal issue of class that
really interested her. She became one of the few black writers who
looked under the rugs of black middle-class lifestyles. Her
characters struggled with issues of love, ambition, and self-doubt,
and were not very different from whites.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is why she was beloved by so many readers, regardless
of race and nationality.
</P>
<P>
   Until her death, fans continued to knock on her door, despite
signs that read, ``Please, no unexpected visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   She allowed these visitors to come in, and talked for hours with
them about the days of the Harlem Renaissance, about race and
class. She was like a walking literary anthology, happily
discussing her friendships with major figures such as Hughes and
Hurston. Two years ago, West said she was planning to write a book
about the black middle class in Oak Bluffs _ something she knew
well.
</P>
<P>
   She said she loved talking to young writers, since her time was
almost up. She said she wanted to spend whatever time she had left
enjoying life, writing, and busying herself with new ventures.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was enjoying her return to fame, but said sadly
that nothing could duplicate those great days of the past _ when
the black literary voice was king.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be a period like that again,'' she said.
``Never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
