<HEADLINE>
CHANGES HERALD A TABLOID WITH SOFTER EDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JUKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Come Monday, the Boston Herald's stark gray pages, short
screaming headlines, and harder tabloid edges may become a thing of
the past, replaced by a kinder, gentler, and more
lifestyle-oriented model.
</P>
<P>
   That is the day when the paper unveils an expensive redesign
that according to managing editor Kevin R. Convey is ``not just a
redesign'' but a ``rethink.'' The operative question is whether a
tabloid can successfully change its stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Two years in the making, the facelift will include: the use of
color, most prominently on the front and back pages; a new
front-page logo and a new Page 1 index to stories; 10 additional
pages including four more local pages and two additional world and
national pages; more frequent use of graphics; new and separate
fronts for the lifestyle and arts sections; a new body typeface and
a smaller headline typeface that will lead to more double-deck
headlines and fewer traditionally tabloid one- and two-word
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   According to editor Andrew F. Costello Jr., the format will
restructure pages 2 and 3 so that the former is more
consumer-oriented and the latter provides a ``more thematic'' look
at the day's news.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of the changes is to modernize and soften the look of
the Herald and bring more attention to areas like business, arts,
and features that have not been considered the paper's strong
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to broaden our reach and our scope,'' said
Costello, characterizing the new Herald as ``more contemporary ...
more in pace with the time.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the paper's editors, the redesign's costs included
about $4-$5 million to retrofit the presses with color equipment.
This has also coincided with the hiring of about 10 staffers from
graphic designers to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   One potential area of concern is Herald deadlines, which have
been moved up roughly one hour to accommodate the redesign. Another
is the impact of the changes on the paper's unions, which have
battled management over wages and health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teasingly say we're very happy to see this great leap into
the '80s,'' said Tom Mashberg, chairman of the editorial bargaining
unit for the Newspaper Guild. ``We definitely feel the paper needs
to project a more serious appearance. ... Where we have a problem
on the labor side (is) a lot of people here ... are very
dissatisfied with our level of compensation and we have very poor
(health) benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Mashberg and Lesley Phillips, the president of the
Newspaper Guild Local 3102, say the investment and worker sweat
poured into the redesign will strengthen the union's resolve to
push for stronger contracts. (This one expires in November 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   ``People are concerned about being compensated and getting the
recognition from the employer who they have worked very hard for,''
said Phillips. ``We're going to say, `Hey, share the wealth.'''
</P>
<P>
   The paper's top editors said that the paper's unions had pulled
together to work on the redesign. ``There's been a lot of give and
take throughout this process,'' said Convey. ``It calls for a
dramatic change in the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufdots &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Herald columnist and WRKO-AM (680) talkmaster Howie Carr's
dust-up with Don Imus is getting serious. After Carr poked fun at
Imus's age, the New York-based syndicated talk-radio host
retaliated by suggesting repeated carnal encounters between Carr's
wife and former heavyweight champion Riddick Bowe. Upping the ante,
Carr's wife, Kathy, has hired legal gunslinger Alan Dershowitz to
handle her suit against Imus. Presumably, she is the one suing
because it is easier to win such a battle when the plaintiff is not
a public figure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Monica mania: Capitalizing on the interest in President
Clinton's testimony Monday, Time magazine is rushing out an issue
that will appear on newsstands in 25 major markets today rather
than early next week. ``Our aim was not to be part of some rush to
judgment,'' insisted managing editor Walter Isaacson. ``We want to
give our readers solid information while they are making up their
minds about the week's events.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the public forgives Bill Clinton for the Monica Lewinsky
scandal is an open question. But citizens seems less likely to let
bygones be bygones when it comes to the media.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point was CNN's Sunday night three-hour ``national
town meeting'' to examine the Clinton crisis. Keenly aware of the
vociferous criticism of the media's coverage, host Jeff Greenfield
opened the show by solemnly intoning that ``in the spirit of the
late Joe Friday,'' the program would deal with ``just the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Within moments of that statement, Greenfield then turned to
several reporters and pundits who stated that Hillary Rodham
Clinton was participating in the final strategy sessions; the
president would acknowledge an inappropriate relationship with
Lewinsky and probably speak to the country; White House staffers
were feeling betrayed; and Clinton's political advisers were
leaking stories.
</P>
<P>
   With that breathless barrage out of the way, Greenfield took his
first phone call from an ordinary American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think you're jumping the gun,'' she charged angrily.
``You (in the media) don't see yourself the way people in the real
world see you. It's disgusting.'' Click.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
