<HEADLINE>
THANK GOODNESS WE HAVE SO MUCH TO FORGET TODAY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Americans can't remember anymore. We have a national epidemic of
memory loss. We're over the hill and over-scheduled. We're too old
and too busy to remember. What's wrong with me? I can't believe I
forgot her name. Have we been here before? What did I come here
for? What meeting?
</P>
<P>
   All this forgetting is a little strange in a nation that has so
many defining moments. Every time you turn on the TV there's
another defining moment. How do you forget a defining moment? Maybe
that's why we seem to have so many. We keep forgetting them.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible we need to forget. Who could fault us for not
wanting to remember a lot of what's been going on lately? But if we
fail to remember, we never learn from our mistakes. What mistakes?
Have we made mistakes?
</P>
<P>
   Forgetting comes in handy. I forgot to pick up the dry cleaning.
You forgot your dentist's appointment. If we try hard enough, most
of us can forget that certain person we once swore we'd never
forget. And, as we've seen recently, forgetting can be a good
career move. Did I do something wrong? I don't remember.
</P>
<P>
   With so much forgetting, memory improvement is big business.
Search the Internet, look in any bookstore and you'll find all the
help you'll ever need to improve your memory, and then some.
Schemes, cures, enhancers, systems, all of which seem to boil down
to the same thing: use it or lose it. Exercise your memory as if it
were a muscle. Keep your memory on its toes with puzzles,
challenges, games.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to my idea for a board game for people who can't
remember anything. I thought of a good name for it the other day,
but I forget what it was. A sample follows.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Who is Kathleen Willey?
</P>
<P>
   a) Teenager who came between Bruce and Demi.
</P>
<P>
   b) Woman on ``Seinfeld' whose name Jerry can't recall, although
he thinks it rhymes with a part of the male anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   c) Star forward on the WBNA's New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   d) Winner of the Frozen Potato Products Institute's Martha
Stewart Cook-Alike Contest.
</P>
<P>
   e) None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Question 2: Who said, ``I misled people.''?
</P>
<P>
   a) Lawrence Welk.
</P>
<P>
   b) James Thomas Brudnell, 7th Earl of Cardigan.
</P>
<P>
   c) Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   d) Bill Jurges.
</P>
<P>
   e) None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Question 3. Who said, ``Yes ... once.''? Under what
circumstances did they say it?
</P>
<P>
   a) Jocelyn Wildenstein, when asked, ``Have you ever had cosmetic
surgery?''
</P>
<P>
   b) Donald Trump, when asked, ``Have you ever experienced a
moment of self-doubt?''
</P>
<P>
   c) Martha Stewart, when asked ``Have you ever had a hair out of
place?''
</P>
<P>
   d) My mother, when asked, ``Have you ever been wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   e) None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to all three questions is e), not that it matters.
Answers don't count in this game. Points are scored on the
following basis:
</P>
<P>
   One point for remembering to show up for the game.
</P>
<P>
   One point each for remembering the names of the other players.
</P>
<P>
   Three points for remembering the question.
</P>
<P>
   Two points if you need to have the question repeated only once.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
