<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BLADES-SPI &LR;      08-20 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLADES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLADE' PLAYS THE VAMPIRE THRILLER AS EPIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vampire thriller is, of course, the most completely
overworked movie genre of the American cinema. It's been played and
replayed so often for comedy, burlesque, exoticism and horror that
it's become, for the most part, a cliche and a bore.
</P>
<P>
   But this week's edition, ``Blade,'' gives the formula some new
life by playing it as epic _ in fact, as apocalyptic epic. In this
film, it's the vampires that run the world, and the underdog humans
who have to try and take it back.
</P>
<P>
   The result is mesmerizing and often a lot of grisly fun. Horror
fans should eat it up, though a more mainstream audience will be
put off by the film's focus on torture, dismemberment and
blood-bathing, as well as teasing references to incest and
pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Marvel comic book, it's the story a stalwart
vampire hunter named Blade (Wesley Snipes) who stalks the noir
urban landscape dispensing justice to the uppity Undead _ via
silver sword, a gun that shoots silver bullets and canisters of
garlic mace.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big job because the vampires are institutionalized. They
have a secret treaty with the U.S. government, they run the LAPD,
and they have billions in offshore bank accounts. They make the
Mafia look like a neighborhood street gang.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, it turns out that Blade himself is a
semi-vampire, a ``daywalker'' _ a man with the strength of a
vampire but none of its weaknesses. So he has to keep taking a
special serum or he's likely to ``turn.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the additional problem of a Gen X renegade vampire
named Deacon (Stephen Dorff) who, by studying the ancient vampire
scriptures, has found a way take control from the vampire
establishment and make himself ruler of the Earth _ if he can find
the blood of a ``daywalker'' to use as part of his ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the premise of the film _ its complicated vampire
mythology, and conventions of what the creatures can and cannot do
_ never really adds up to anything that makes any sense, even by
the liberal standards we apply to vampire fantasies. Try to analyze
this thing and you'll go nuts.
</P>
<P>
   The film also suffers from the casting of Dorff as the vampire
anti-Christ. He's a good actor and he makes a clear visual contrast
to hero Snipes, but his WASPish pretty-boy, boy-next-door presence
makes him altogether about as menacing as Mickey Rooney playing
Andy Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film is carried by the sweep of its style. Director
Stephen Norrington and his crew create a marvelously paranoid and
incorrigibly morbid comic-book world. The action sequences seem
remarkably original, surreal and exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the rest of the casting works. Kris Kristofferson is just
right as Blade's folksy mentor; N'Bushe Wright (``Zebrahead'')
projects just the proper blend of vulnerability and spunk as
Blade's imperiled love interest; and Snipes makes a volatile,
soaringly resolute, splendidly mythic Savior of Mankind.
</P>
<P>
   Blade. Directed by Stephen Norington. Written by David S. Goyer.
Cast: Wesley Snipes, Stephen Dorff, Kris Kristofferson, N'Bushe
Wright. New Line Cinema. 120 minutes. Rated R for violence and
sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
