<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE ECONOMY SHOWING SOME CRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts's unemployment is a mere 3.4 percent. Job growth
continues to outpace the nation. Home sales last quarter were
stronger than any time since the last housing boom in 1987. The
cost of occupying one of Boston's fanciest office towers has spiked
more than 20 percent this year. State tax revenues came in almost
$1 billion more than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the broad indicators tell a tale of a booming local
economy. But many of the mechanics who spend their days with their
heads stuck down in the grimy engine that powers the state's
economy see something else too: trouble ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the rosy scenario that is easily plotted on charts, the
evidence of a softening is mostly anecdotal. Corporate turnaround
specialists, brought into troubled situations, report business is
booming here. Bankruptcies aren't moving up yet, but law firms are
hiring bankruptcy attorneys in anticipation of brisk times just
ahead. The Boston Globe's help-wanted advertising, always a good
barometer of the job market, is turning down, particularly among
high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clearly going to be an increase in underperforming
businesses in the next year to 18 months,'' says Marti Kopacz, who
works with distressed companies out of the Boston office of
PricewaterhouseCoopers, &UR;  &LR; the accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Edward I. Shifman Jr., senior vice president of Congress
Financial Corp., which lends to higher-risk companies: ``We're
seeing companies beginning to lose money that haven't lost money in
years.''
</P>
<P>
   These people who make their living monitoring the economy's
underbelly cite a number of problems, most prominently the collapse
in Asia, which has choked off sales and stiffened competition for
New England companies. The strong dollar is hurting local exports
and Asian competitors are so desperate for work they will do it at
almost any price, executives say.
</P>
<P>
   Another often-cited issue: excess capital that has made it all
too easy for weak firms to get cheap money and has eroded
underwriting standards at lenders. ``There is a lot of money
chasing a lot of deals, which means there are a lot of bad deals
being written,'' says David Ferrari, president of Argus Management
Corp., a South Natick firm that helps companies restructure their
debts. ``These companies are going to become very troubled, very
quickly.'' Peter Pelletier, who runs a similar firm in Braintree,
says money is so plentiful that troubled firms he counsels can now
get new financing in three months rather than the 18 months it
would have taken in the past. He says lenders are easing terms and
controls on loans to win the business. ``Problems are being masked
by borrowed money,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both the Federal Reserve and the Comptroller of the
Currency, two agencies that regulate banks, have recently expressed
concern that the competition for lending has led to looser loan
standards, particularly in commercial loans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, New England's big banks, like most banks nationwide, were
taught some harsh lessons in the last recession and currently have
strong reserves to cushion against bad loans and a low percentage
of nonperforming loans. Leo Breitman, president of the
Massachusetts operations for Fleet Financial Group Inc., the
region's largest bank, is anything but alarmed by what he sees:
``Our current asset quality numbers have never been better in our
commerical loan portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists say the New England economy is still healthy and
growing. Payroll employment in Masachusetts grew 3 percent over the
year ending in June, compared with a gain of 2.6 percent
nationwide, according to the US Labor Department. New Hampshire was
the weak sister of the region over the last year, growing at just
0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But economists say, too, that the best of the expansion may be
behind us. A recent BankBoston survey found New England's volume of
manufacturing orders was deteriorating severely, a product of the
problems in Asia, and is starting to have a noticeable effect on
employment. Initial unemployment claims in Massachusetts are no
longer declining.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good as it gets,'' says Fred Breimyer, chief
economist for State Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Perna, Fleet's chief economist, thinks that if there is a
slowdown ahead, the region is much better prepared this time
around. In the 1989-92 recession, New England was hit with a
double-whammy, the collapse of the minicomputer business and the
defense industry build-down. In addition, overbuilding in the real
estate industry was rampant.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Massachusetts lost 11 percent of its jobs to the
recession while the country lost just 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another recession, says Perna, ``wouldn't be fun, but there is
no reason for us to get hit disproportionately as hard as we did
last time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, personal bankruptcy filings continue to rise,
but corporate filings actually fell 21 percent last year and
another 33 percent in the first six months of this year. But a
number of law firms, including Hale and Dorr, Goodwin Procter &AMP;
Hoar, and Mintz Levin, all report they are looking to add
bankruptcy attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely an underside that has developed that
didn't exist a couple of years ago,'' says Richard Mikels, head of
Mintz Levin's bankruptcy practice.
</P>
<P>
   There's an old saw in the real estate business that says there's
no need to worry until you see the cranes in the air. Have you
looked up lately?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
