<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer pnans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, Aug. 21, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GADJO (Undated) The title character of Tony Gatlif's latest
_ and most enjoyable _ examination of Gypsy life, ``Gadjo Dilo''
(Crazy Foreigner), is a determined young Parisian (Romain Duris)
who, as the film opens, is trudging across the frozen outback of
Romania on a personal quest.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REGENERATION (Undated) The setting of Gillies Mackinnon's
well-meaning but terminally dreary period drama, ``Regeneration,''
is a cozy asylum in Scotland where British military doctors treat
shell-shocked World War I soldiers so they can be sent back to the
trenches of France.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HANDS (Undated) The documentary ``Hands on a Hard Body''
deals with such an obscure subject _ a contest sponsored by a
smalltown Texas auto-dealer _ that it's probably going to have a
hard time gathering a great deal of initial audience interest.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BLADE (Undated) ``Blade,'' gives the vampire thriller
formula some new life by playing it as epic _ in fact, as
apocalyptic epic. In this film, it's the vampires that run the
world, and the underdog humans who have to try and take it back.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FRIENDS (Undated) Neil LaBute's second feature, ``Your
Friends and Neighbors,'' is sure to both infuriate (at the preview
screening, three people walked out proclaiming, ``These people are
losers!'') and fascinate.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STRIKE (Undated) ``Strike!'' brings to mind the 1966 film,
``The Trouble With Angels,'' which featured rebellious convent
school students, played by Hayley Mills and June Harding, pitted
against Rosalind Russell's stern but kindly Mother Superior.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DANCE (Undated) ``A story of hearts in motion'' reads the
tag line for ``Dance With Me,'' and indeed, ``motion'' is the best
thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DEAD (Undated) Poor Tom Everett Scott. After an impressive
debut in the Tom Hanks movie, ``That Thing You Do,'' the actor has
slowly seen his career take a downward spiral. First it was ``An
American Werewolf In Paris,'' now this odious and tasteless trifle.
Even the opening credits are morose and crass in ``Dead Man On
Campus,'' with various methods of suicide integrated into the cast
and crew's names.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FALL-FOX (Undated) The fall season begins Sunday with the
premieres of two new Fox comedies, ``Holding the Baby'' and ``That
'70s Show.''
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (story will move in the ``e'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
