<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACK-TO-SCHOOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION-CONSCIOUS KIDS CREATE BACK-TO-SCHOOL CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A generation ago, when the Crayola box held only six colors and
a kid's one and only pair of sneakers were Keds, back-to-school
shopping was as elementary as a Dick-and-Jane reader.
</P>
<P>
   If your child was a boy, you got him a haircut, new shoes, and a
Zorro lunch box and _ Voila! _ a freshly spruced-up young scholar
was ready for the demanding rigors of third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping for college was only slightly more complicated. Fill a
steamer trunk with sweaters and skirts, buy a bean-bag chair for
the dorm room, and a young woman was all set.
</P>
<P>
   But in an era when some nine-year-olds know more about Calvin
Klein than Calvin Coolidge, it's not so simple anymore. Nowadays a
lot of back-to-school shopping is about high fashion and high tech,
and that's changed both the way parents shop and the way retailers
make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was small, it seemed all a kid needed was a new lunch
box,'' said vice president John Konarski of the International
Council of Shopping Centers. ``Now you need calculators,
minicomputers, and floppy disks.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result, Staples Inc. can claim that ``August is our
Christmas,'' said Christina Erridge, a spokeswoman for the
Westborough-based chain of office supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   Between tony togs and floppy disks, the American Express Retail
Index estimates that $408 will be spent on back-to-school
merchandise and clothing this year for each grade-school and
high-school kid in the United States, up 3 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   All these changes have shifted shopping patterns.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a decade ago, many mothers liked to hit the
stores early and do all their back-to-school shopping in one fell
swoop, said Raschel Gray, owner of two Raschel's children's
clothing and shoe stores in Foxborough and Westborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``By July 15, the lines were out the door and down the block,''
said Gray, adding, ``Customers would pick up everything at once _
they just wanted to get it all done.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Woods still shops that way.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the birth of her first child 15 years ago, a nurse
in her pediatrician's office tipped her off about Raschel's, and
she's been making an annual back-to-school pilgrimage ever since, a
50-minute drive each way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to go early when all the sizes are available, and
there aren't too many people,'' said Woods as she helped her
6-year-old daughter Brittany pick out a school wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   While some mothers still reduce back-to-school to a single big
shopping expedition, many others now make several small shopping
trips over several weeks instead, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   One shopper adopting this strategy is Tracy Bailey-Gates, a
Rhode Island mother of three young sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make several trips,'' she said as sons Brian,
Christopher, and Michael checked out baseball caps and football
sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   A retailer in her 25th back-to-school season, Gray offered
several theories to explain this change in shopping habits.
</P>
<P>
   Parents in two-income households are more pressed for time. So
are single mothers, who can't set aside a full day to buy kids'
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be another reason why, in many cases, a single big
shopping spree has been replaced by several smaller trips.
</P>
<P>
   Once, most kids wore what their mothers told them to wear
(though not always cheerfully). But some of today's 8-year-olds are
not only more fashion conscious than kids of yore; they also have
more influence on parents' purchasing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   While many third-graders still dress like little girls, some
underage clotheshorses want to wear the same styles of '70s retro
outfits, striped ensembles, and flaired slacks as their teenage
sisters, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether third grader or high-school sophomore, these students
don't want to commit too soon to the wrong wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to go back to school first and see what the other
kids are wearing,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of buying a full complement of clothing in mid
summer, some families are buying just one or two outfits, then
returning to the store in September to round out the school
wardrobe, Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Retail Federation has a military sounding name for
the phenomenon of students ``checking out what new styles are hot
during the first few weeks of school.''
</P>
<P>
   The federation calls it ``peer recon and review.''
</P>
<P>
   If fashion is king, Stride Rite Corp. could earn high marks from
students engaging in peer recon and review this fall. In recent
years, the Lexington, Mass. shoe company has signed licensing
agreements with top designers. Along with its well-known line of
children's shoes, Stride Rite now also offers shoe lines for some
students under such brand names as Tommy Hilfiger and Nine West.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-school shopping period may be more important to
Stride Rite than ever. Once the company could count on seasonal
sales boosts in both the spring and the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But trends toward casual dress have ``reduced the importance of
Easter'' as a selling season, said John M. Kelliher, Stride Rite's
chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Brand-name fall fashion is also the focal point of a new
five-week marketing campaign the Filene's department store chain is
aiming at customers between 12 and 20 years of age.
</P>
<P>
   Showing photos of young people wearing clothes by Tommy
Hilfiger, Polo Jeans, Levi's, XOXO, and Calvin Klein, the goal of a
campaign with the slogan of ``Think it, be it'' is to persuade
young students that Filene's should be the ``first-stop
headquarters for back-to-school,'' said Paul Cavalli, Filene's
senior vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   While apparel stores are seeing a stretching out of the
back-to-school season, stores that sell school supplies and
computers can still see concentrated bursts of spending in August.
</P>
<P>
   Staples is one beneficiary of an August bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the year, Staples primarily serves small business
owners and people who work at home. But in August, store traffic
can swell from kids and parents loading up on school supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy Co., a Midwestern retailer about to open stores in the
Boston market, reports a similar phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``August is our biggest month for computer sales,'' said Best
Buy spokeswoman Laurie Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   All these changes are rearranging the retail calendar. Once
retailers could plan on big upward spikes in sales at Easter,
back-to-school, and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Now consumers seem more likely to spend steadily all through the
year, buying items when they need them and not waiting until August
and December.
</P>
<P>
   The peaks and valleys of spending aren't ``as sharp as they used
to be,'' says John Macht of the Macht Group, a retail consulting
firm in Boston. ``But retailers can still make money if they plan
carefully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
