<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS' STATUS IS STILL IFFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If No. 1 draft pick Robert Edwards had
missed this much time with a preseason injury under the previous
Patriots regime, the coach might have publicly questioned his
gender.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Parcells referred to the wide receiver as ``she''
because he had missed much of his first training camp with a
hamstring injury in 1996, Glenn was able to shed the label only by
catching 90 passes during the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the kinder and gentler atmosphere that surrounds the Pete
Carroll Patriots, Edwards will not have to deal with such
treatment. The 18th player taken in the draft, the running back
from Georgia has a history of injury problems, and his latest _ a
groin pull _ is legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm injured and I can't go out there and run the way I want
to,'' said Edwards. ``It's been a little frustrating, but I can't
rush the injury. I have to go out and let it heal completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday before practice, in which he participated, there was
concern about whether Edwards would be able to play Saturday's
exhibition in Washington. Despite Sedrick Shaw's 50-yard
performance against the Dallas Cowboys Monday night, it doesn't
take tarot cards to reveal that the Patriots want Edwards to emerge
as their new Curtis Martin. His emergence would vindicate the
Patriots for letting Martin go to Parcells's Jets as a free agent.
In fact, it would be a bonus, because Edwards was taken with one of
the compensation picks the Patriots received for losing Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards received a five-year, $5.75 million contract with a $2.7
million signing bonus. He's a big-ticket item. And as much as any
organization says, ``May the best man win,'' normally, it's the
highest-paid player who wins.
</P>
<P>
   While the Patriots say nice things about Shaw, they feel deep
down that Edwards is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Robert is able to play, he's gonna start the game and get
the reps to make up for the lost time,'' said Carroll. ``I thought
he would be ready for this game, but after talking to the trainer,
it's not set. It's very questionable right now.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Shaw, ``Sedrick continues to do solid things,'' said
Carroll. ``He's running very tough. He blocked well again. He's in
the process of learning what we need for him to learn. If Robert is
not available for a couple of weeks, we'll take on the course we've
been on. Harold (Shaw) is pounding the ball and Derrick (Cullors)
continues to make big plays. I'm feeling good about the situation.
I just wish Robert could get out there. But if we're starting the
season right now, Sedrick would start.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he isn't afraid to test Edwards despite limited
camp time. He believes it might take two good games in a row during
the regular season to judge whether Edwards can handle the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not a big mystery, either,'' said Carroll. ``We know
what he can do. We know he's gonna run tough and catch the ball
well. I don't know if he's going to be dominant and take the job,
but we know what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a quiet man, has tried to avoid the spotlight until
he's ready to play. But even after Shaw's strong performance, the
spotlight seems to linger on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I'm behind, but mentally, I'm in the game,'' said
Edwards. ``I see a play and I think to myself what I would do in a
certain situation. I don't think I'm going to have any problems
picking up the offense. The problem is trying to stay in shape.
Once I do get in there, I might have to come out just to get some
air. So the main thing is to keep in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who has suffered foot and knee injuries in the past, is
dealing with a groin injury for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the recovery time) has been slower than I expected,''
said Edwards. ``I haven't had one before. I did it in practice and
then reinjured it in San Francisco. I was able to start jogging
last week, but what you do on the football field is totally
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, starting out this way is not what Edwards envisioned.
If anything, he wanted to silence the critics who considered him
injury-prone and questioned why the Patriots would take him with
the 18th pick. Instead, Edwards, who gained 20 yards on six carries
at San Francisco in the exhibition opener before reinjuring the
groin, has only raised more doubts about his durability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen and you have to adjust,'' he said. ``This week
I'll take it to a higher level and see if it holds up. I'll take my
time because it's important that once it's healed, I can put it
behind me. Physically, I'm prepared, but my body might tell me
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll talks about accelerating Edwards's education. He will
give him the ball quite a bit during the next two days. He
dismissed any notion that Edwards would not be able to start the
season, indicating he should have plenty of time to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards realizes that everything he does or doesn't do is open
to scrutiny because of his status as the top pick. While there is
no longer a coach who would question why he's not on the field,
there are those who wonder what Edwards is all about and whether
they should begin to panic about the Patriots' running game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
