<HEADLINE>
TRADE TO REVOLUTION SURPRISES VETERAN DAMIAN ALVAREZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ For the last two years, Damian Alvarez's
loyalty has been split between two teams, two leagues, two
countries. But things have become even more complicated in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   First Damian was sent from Las Chivas de Guadalajara to Club
America in Mexico City, where he will play after the Major League
Soccer season ends.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Saturday, he was traded from the Dallas Burn to the
Revolution, where he will perform for at least the next seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a change I didn't expect,'' Damian said Wednesday.
``It was a big surprise. One day, you go to sleep and you are with
Dallas. The next day, you wake up and you are playing with the
Revolution. Only in the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Such late-season movements are very rare outside the United
States, though offseason dealings are numerous. Once the season
begins, there is little change, which is to be highly recommended
in a sport that requires time for a foundation to be established
and for a team to evolve properly.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the trade of Colombian midfielder Oscar Pareja to
Dallas for Damian seems a desperation move for both teams. Pareja
did not make a strong impact with the Revolution, who have MLS's
worst record as they prepare for Saturday's game against the Los
Angeles Galaxy. Damian scored only four goals before injuring the
medial collateral ligament in his left knee for Dallas, which is
near the bottom of the Western Conference this year.
</P>
<P>
   Though Damian is among the league's most explosive players, he
is not expected to save the Revolution, who have struggled
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chances for the playoffs are not great but they still
exist,'' Damian said. ``And I am here to play and contribute
whatever this team needs. That is all I am interested in now _ to
make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Damian was not at full speed during indoor training Tuesday
morning. He was encouraged by the reduced swelling in his knee and
was examined by Dr. Bert Zarins after the Revolution met the
Worcester Wildfire in a scrimmage at Babson College Tuesday night.
He kept his perspective and sense of humor while being treated by
masseur Adam Parret and trainer Mike Fritz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a left-footed player,'' Damian said. ``I have only one
leg, and it is injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Though defenders know Damian definitely favors the left side, he
is effective because of his athleticism, skill, and speed. Damian
credits genetics for much of his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was the same; we play the same position,'' Damian
said. ``He also played for Chivas and for the Mexico national
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Damian was born in 1973 in Vera Cruz, where his father, Pedro,
was playing, but soon moved to Guadalajara. He performed for Atlas
and for Mexico's under-21 national team against the US in CONCACAF
qualifying. Damian also played eight times for Mexico's national
team under Bora Milutinovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never been injured, so he is not sure how hard to push
it,'' Revolution coach Thomas Rongen said. ``It feels good after
playing in tight spaces indoors, so that is a good sign. He is not
game-fit yet. What he needs is a good practice, with contact, to
get his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played in big games before 100,000 people, so he can
handle the pressure. But if he isn't ready, I don't want to do him
or the team a disservice by playing him. I don't want him to fail
in his first game, though this is a big game for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
