<HEADER>
A3444 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     08-20 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE NEVER GOT RICH, BUT SHE HAD A ROYAL TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was 80 and got two new knees and a new husband.
</P>
<P>
   That was 10 years ago, and Midge Whiting is now generously
reconciled to the fact that she won't dethrone Martina Hingis at
Flushing Meadow to claim the US tennis title that narrowly eluded
her 68 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   She won't mind it at all if Hingis remains queen. ``I like
Martina's manner, that she can smile out there, even when things
don't go her way,'' Midge says.
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Adele ``Midge'' Morrill Painter Whiting is a charming
90-year-old leftover from a time when an important tennis strategy
was learning how to play the king.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't beat him, but you didn't make it obvious, either,''
Midge laughs. ``Everybody went along. The king was a nice fellow.
Enthusiastic, but not much of a player.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1929. Tennis players didn't make any money but they
traveled in the same circles as the wealthy and titled on the
French Riviera. Competing in tournaments to amuse patrons of the
best resorts, they got first-class room, board, and mingling
rights, and had to pack evening gowns or tuxedos in their steamer
trunks.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the deal was playing in handicap mixed doubles events
with such nabobs as 70-year-old King Gustav V of Sweden. Called
just plain Mr. G. by partners and opponents, he was a slim,
distinguished figure in white mustache and straw hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of his victims,'' Midge recalls, her eyes hazel and
jovial. ``I played with some Austrian, and the king had a German,
Cilly Aussem, who won Wimbledon a couple years later, as his
protector. She covered most of the court, and we kept it close.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, though the players are rich, elegance isn't on their
calendar, and most of them think the king of Sweden is named Volvo
or Saab, maybe Borg.
</P>
<P>
   As Midge Morrill, a Winsor School kid, she came out of Dedham,
Mass. to become one of the world's better players _ five times in
the US Top 10 between 1928 and 1934 _ and finds herself the last of
her crowd. The January death at 92 of her friend Helen Wills Moody
(a woman neither she nor anybody else could beat) leaves Midge as
the elder among the female Top 10 gang. ``I never got more than a
couple of games off Helen.''
</P>
<P>
   She was in good company. Moody rang up 27 titles (17 majors) and
a 158-match streak over a 14-year span before losing the 1933 US
singles final to Helen Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   Midge is sitting on the porch at Longwood Cricket Club in
Brookline, Mass. with her kid sister, Polly Sands, looking in two
directions. Backward and forward. At an interrogator's request, she
peers into the seldom-visited past, talking about the ``almost''
year, 1930, although the quote is from a New York Times story, not
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Twice widowed, she nevertheless prefers the good new to the good
old days, and ``the wonderful life I have with three children, 11
grandchildren, and 22 great-grandchildren. I wish today's players
the same kind of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   An immediate thought is of the MFS Pro tourney next week at
Longwood and ``the hope I can get seats close to the ground so I
won't have much climbing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   She was applauded on that ground, then a grassy plot, many
times. The MFS is to be staged in the same arena, an enlarged
version, where Midge and the dark-haired Pat Rafterian male god of
the 1930s, Frank Shields, lost a US mixed doubles final to Edith
Cross and Wilmer Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Teaming with the dashing Shields (Brooke Shields's grandfather)
in 1930, ``I was the envy of every woman in Boston. Frank was mad
when we won the semis because the final cut in on a weekend he had
planned with a girl in Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Another matinee idol by her side to the US semifinals of 1928
was the French boulevardier and two-time Wimbledon champ, Jean
Borotra. ``He wore a beret and was a great hand kisser.''
</P>
<P>
   A US singles quarterfinalist in 1927 and '32, Midge was a
sturdy, broad-shouldered 5 feet 8 inches in knee-length white dress
and brightly hued bandeau holding brunette tresses in place. She
might have hit the jackpot in '30 as she ``slugged'' her way to the
semis on the Forest Hills lawn with the ``demoralizing fury of a
withering forehand'' _ the words of the Times' Allison Danzig. She
rescued two set points in winning the first set, 8-6, and led
England's Betty Nuthall, 4-2, in the second.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sluggers' August like our own. Five men were ahead of
Babe Ruth's 1927 record pace of 60 homers: Ruth, who wound up with
49; teammate Lou Gehrig (41); Jimmie Foxx (37) of the
pennant-winning Philadelphia Athletics, Chuck Klein (40) of the
Phillies; and Hack Wilson (56) of the Cubs. Midge may have had as
much punch as Our Olde Towne Team's best, Earl Webb, who hit 16 for
the last-place Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember much about that match,'' she says, ``but I
think Betty got me with drop shots.'' Midge ``lost coordination in
a surprising lull so near to victory,'' Danzig wrote, losing, 6-8,
6-4, 6-2. Nuthall then dispatched Valerie Harper in 36 minutes to
win the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never given it much thought,'' says Midge. ``We just had
so much fun. Helen obviously took it very seriously. But most of us
didn't. We didn't train or practice much, just played. The stakes
weren't as high as today.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Miss Morrill ranked No. 2 behind Moody, who declined to
make the train trip from San Francisco to New York for the US
showdown, saying she'd traveled enough in winning the French and
Wimbledon. Winning five of 12 tournaments, Midge had the kind of
season that would be worth about a million present-day bucks, the
sum earned in 1997 by the current American No. 2, Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. I'm not sure I'd want to have worked that hard.
We were amateurs with no financial aspirations, just looking for
fun. I fell in love with Whit Painter, the father of my three kids,
and that was the end of the tour for me. I stopped playing at 80
when the knees gave out, had a brief, happy marriage with John
Whiting.''
</P>
<P>
   She has outlasted a world in which she fit so well. Nobody
travels by ocean liner anymore, equipped with ballroom dresses and
rackets. A bygone haunt, Longwood's prime courts, are paved harder
than Kenneth Starr's heart. The grass and Riviera circuits that
meant so much are pressed into scrapbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stretching?'' She shakes her head in merriment. ``Didn't know
about that stuff, but we played, anyway.'' They prided themselves
on stretching a 1930 dollar into dinner, carfare, and a movie at a
time when you could stay on Atlantic City's then fashionable
Boardwalk in a seaside hotel room with three meals for $6.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the engaging Midge, who cast her first presidential ballot
for Franklin Roosevelt's New Deal, has stretched into her 10th
decade very nicely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
