<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-QUIGLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIGLEY IS PASSING SENIOR TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just a year ago Dana Quigley won for the first time on the
Senior PGA Tour, beating Jay Sigel in a playoff on the third extra
hole at the Northville Long Island Classic. It was an afternoon in
which he experienced the full range of life's emotions. It was a
win that gave him a year's exemption, but when he was walking to
the interview tent he received a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd take it later but was told he should talk to his
brother Paul immediately. The news was that their father, Wally,
had died of cancer that afternoon. ``I was told, `Your brother
wants to talk to you.''' Quigley recalled Wednesday on the eve of
his defense at Meadow Brook CC in Jericho, N.Y. ``I said, ```Tell
him I'll call him back. I'm going to talk to the press.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy said, `You'd better talk to him now.' Never once that
day did I think my father had died. I collapsed to the ground. I
just lay there for 10 or 15 minutes. Then I had to go to the press
room. No one knew about it. The first thing I said was about my
father dying. I was crying. The next half hour was tough. Everybody
was crying. It was so emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley, who grew up in Barrington, R.I., went to the University
of Rhode Island and had dominated New England PGA sectional play,
had turned 50 on April 14, 1997. He couldn't go to the Senior Tour
qualifying school until that fall so the only avenue to play was in
Monday qualifiers, something he did during the decade he played on
the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   The catch to playing the Senior Tour is you're only as good as
your last victory unless you enjoy the success of players such as
Tom Weiskopf, George Archer, Bruce Crampton, and Chi Chi Rodriguez
who are eligible for tournaments based on the career money list.
Quigley has played in 39 straight tournaments since the BankBoston
Classic a year ago at Nashawtuc CC when he received a sponsor's
exemption and finished tied for sixth. He still had to qualify
Monday in Jericho, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he hasn't missed an event and is 13th on the money
list with $620,00. This virtually guarantees him a free ride next
season , since the top 31 are exempt. ``It's been absolutely
fabulous,'' said Quigley, who will be in next week's BankBoston
Classic and doesn't plan to take any time off from the tour. ``It
beats the hell out of the Cummaquid pro-am. Who would have thunk
it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't so sure I'd be able to stay mentally positive. It's
more golf than I wanted to play, but more than the physical it's
the mental. I think that's the whole key. Certainly playing week
after week can get tiring, but it's the mind. You have to put the
`I can't' words out of your mind. I've played every one, 39 in a
row going into this week. I haven't even come close to taking a
week off. If I take a week off, I can drop down on the money
list.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, after winning the Wogan Award as the
NEPGA's top player for the seventh time in 12 years, Quigley
decided to test the Senior Tour waters. He knew it was a gamble,
but he felt it might be worth the risk if he somehow could make the
top 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just went over $1 million,'' Quigley said. ``For a guy like
me to make that type of money is something I'd never have expected.
If I make good, then I may take some time off but I still have a
little way to go before I make enough to be exempt. I'm physically
fit, so if I'm mentaly sharp I'll just keep playing for as long as
I can. I'm just having too much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley, who had been director of golf at Crestwood CC in
Rehoboth, said his old NEPGA sidekick Paul Parajeckas, the pro at
Woburn CC, will be his caddie at Nashawtuc. ``He told me he was
going to go out and walk the course tomorrow,'' said Quigley. ``I
said, `For What?' I had my 11th top 10 last week. I'm playing
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley will be the guest of honor at a dinner tonight in
Jericho, N.Y. ``We've got 35 people coming down,'' Quigley said.
The group will include his mother Dot. He said a victory next week
in Concord would be a special treat, but the Long Island Classic
will always have special meaning. ``I just shot a 69 in the
pro-am,'' Quigley said, ``and maybe the emotion of my father's
memory might carry me through it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
