<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-CLINTON-RESIGN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT IS TIME FOR CLINTON TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or
fax her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WASHINGTON -- It is time for the American people to tell
President Clinton: ''Go. Resign or be impeached.''
 &HT;    Americans are asking hard questions now that Clinton has
acknowledged that he ''had a relationship with Miss Lewinsky that
was not appropriate.'' Only seven months ago, he defiantly told us,
''I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
 &HT;    Do we want to have as our president an incorrigible sexaholic?
He has been accused of making passes or carrying on full-fledged
affairs by Gennifer Flowers, Paula Jones, Kathleen Willey, Monica
Lewinsky and others allegedly preparing their own law suits.
 &HT;    Do we want a chronic liar as president? This week Clinton
belatedly acknowledged that his ''public comments and my silence
about this matter gave a false impression. I misled people,
including even my wife.''
 &HT;    Indeed, in his very confession, he patently lied to us over and
over again.
 &HT;    Were his answers in a deposition in the Jones suit ''legally
accurate'' as he now claims, when he said in January, ''I have
never had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky?''
 &HT;    Why did she visit him 37 times in the White House after she was
transferred to the Pentagon? She was not a member of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
 &HT;    He has acknowledged to the grand jury that he had oral sex with
her. But, his lawyers assert that does not meet the definition of
sexual relations established by the judge of knowingly having
''contact with the genitals, anus, groin, breast inner thigh, or
buttocks of any person with an intent to arouse or gratify the
sexual desire of any person.''
 &HT;    Oral sex clearly meets that definition.
 &HT;    He lied when he said, ''I was also very concerned about
protecting my family ... I intend to reclaim my family life for my
family.''
 &HT;    In a ''Wall Street Journal'' column, William Bennett writes:
''Let's be blunt. If Mr. Clinton genuinely cared about 'the two
people I love most -- my wife and our daughter,' he would not be
chronically unfaithful to them.
 &HT;    ''He would not have had oral sex with an intern barely older
than his daughter ... He would not betray his family's trust time
after time. He would not have sent forth his wife to defend him
with preposterous claims of a 'vast right-wing conspiracy.' Mr.
Clinton's real message is: I will betray my wife and daughter when
it's convenient and I will hide behind them when it's necessary.
And then I will do it all over again.''
 &HT;    The author of a powerful new book, ''The Death of Outrage: Bill
Clinton and the Assault on American Ideals,'' Bennett called the
president's four-minute address to the American people ''the most
deceptive, shameless and self-pitying speech ever delivered by an
American president.''
 &HT;    Clinton outrageously attacked Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr's
investigation as having ''gone on too long, cost too much and hurt
too many people.''
 &HT;    This is transparently deceitful.
 &HT;    If the president had made Monday night's speech last January, he
would have shortened the investigation by seven months. It was
Clinton who refused to testify to the grand jury six times until he
was sent a subpoena.
 &HT;    It was Clinton who claimed a non-existent ''executive
privilege'' to keep the Secret Service and aides from testifying,
and took their case to the Supreme Court.
 &HT;    It was Clinton who forced his staff to spend hundreds of
thousands of their own dollars in legal fees to defend his
scabrous, sickening sexual obsession before the grand jury.
 &HT;    Do we want as president, the nation's highest law enforcement
officer, a man who committed perjury and who apparently encouraged
Lewinsky to lie? She says he helped her develop ''cover stories''
to disguise their affair, and suggested hypothetical ways to avoid
turning over presidential gifts to Jones' lawyers. If so, he
committed the crime of suborning perjury.
 &HT;    Do we want as president a man who offers bribes to silence a
witness? Clinton even asked then U.N. Ambassador Bill Richardson to
hire Monica Lewinsky, and the job was offered.
 &HT;    Do we want as president a man whose message to young people is
commit adultery on Saturday night and wave a Bible as you walk to
church holding hands with your wife on Sunday.
 &HT;    The president tells us it is time ''to turn away from the
spectacle of the past seven months, to repair the fabric of our
national disgrace.''
 &HT;    Sadly, only he has the power to do that by resigning.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
