<P>
   CLINTON-MAIN _ WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky went back to the
federal courthouse Thursday for more testimony amid indications
independent counsel Kenneth Starr plans to ask others to return.
Meanwhile, prosecutors collected samples of President Clinton's
DNA. Nearby in the Justice Department, Attorney General Janet Reno
was facing new pressure from Republicans to name an independent
counsel to investigate whether Vice President Gore violated federal
campaign fund-raising laws. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MONICABEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Among those Americans who aren't so
anxious for independent counsel Kenneth Starr to wind up his
investigation of President Clinton are the residents of Monica
Beach _ the photographers and TV technicians who have camped
outside the E. Everett Prettyman U.S. Courthouse since January
(Dart, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-SENATE _ From President Clinton's home state of Arkansas
to the Republican bastion of South Carolina, the South is serving
up some of the most competitive Senate contests in the country in
the 1998 mid-term elections. The parties are vying for open seats
in Arkansas and Kentucky and struggling to defend incumbents in
North Carolina (Republican Sen. Lauch Faircloth) and South Carolina
(Democrat Ernest Hollings). Relatively strong Democratic turnout in
the Georgia primary could also make things interesting for Sen.
Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) in the peach state. (Foskett, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-CAROLINA -- Can a freshman Republican who has made
District of Columbia's leadership woes his most visible legacy use
the issue to win re-election in North Carolina? Sen. Lauch
Faircloth (R-N.C.), running against millionaire John Edwards,
thinks so. (Foskett, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PAIN _ WASHINGTON _ A bill pending in Congress that would
prohibit dispensing large doses of pain medication should be
defeated, a panel of health care specialiosts announced Thursday.
(Shook, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FT-HOOD-BOSNIA -- Live coverage of the first wave of Fort Hood
soldiers to head for Bosnia. (Perkes, Austin Americna-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BEER-CLASS _ ATHENS, Ga. _ ``Beer wasn't made simply to drink.
It was made to speak to you.'' So says Dr. Beer, aka Brian Nummer,
who owns the Athens Brewing Company and holds a Ph.D. in food
microbiology. Nummer will be teaching a course this fall at the
University of Georgia called ``the art, science, &AMP; history of
beer,'' and he expects students to learn enough in the class to
open their own brewpubs, or, at the very least, to better
appreciate a fine draw of homemade beer. (McCarthy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KENYA-TOURISM _ A look at the impact of the embassy bombings on
tourism in Kenya. Kenyans, who suffered by far the most casualites
in an attack aimed at the United States, are now feeling the bomb's
financial shock waves, too. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS AND LOCATOR MAP.
</P>
