<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-STRIKE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRIKE!' TRIES TO PACK IN TOO MUCH IN ONE MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Strike!'' brings to mind the 1966 film, ``The Trouble With
Angels,'' which featured rebellious convent school students, played
by Hayley Mills and June Harding, pitted against Rosalind Russell's
stern but kindly Mother Superior.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it's Miss Godard's Prep School for Girls and there
are five fiery young women _ not just two _ struggling with the
perils of coming-of-age in an idealistic 1963.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new era and women's roles are changing. Miss Godard's,
for all its convention, is teaching its pupils to be
forward-thinking and brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Odie (Gaby Hoffmann) is the story's narrator. She's smart,
offbeat and pushing hard to lose her virginity. Verena (Kirsten
Dunst) has the Hayley Mills role and is an outspoken prankster who
retains a fierce loyalty to the school. Tinka (Monica Keena) is a
flirty seductress, while Tweety (Heather Matarazzo) suffers from an
eating disorder. Momo (Merritt Wever) is the scientific genius who
launches the ultimate plan to keep the school from being forced to
go coed because of impending financial disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over this wayward brood of girls with authority and
fondness is the eccentric, individualistic headmistress, Miss
McVane (Lynn Redgrave). She is distraught over the merger, worried
her girls' interests will be pushed aside and they'll become second
class citizens once boys arrive on campus. Leave it to Verena and
Odie to plan a radical revolt that might just keep the school safe
from male dominance and give the girls a newfound sense of self
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Writer and director Sarah Kernochan drew her characters directly
from her own New England boarding school experiences. The result is
a wildly uneven movie that suffers from mood swings and
insufferably precious lines like, ``Up your ziggy with a wah-wah
brush.'' Obviously, Kernochan had difficulty keeping an objective
point-of-view about her personal memories, which are really only
adorable to her and don't necessarily make good movie material.
</P>
<P>
   While it's an intriguing idea to focus on adolescent girls in a
comedic way after recent movies like ``Whatever'' and ``All Over
Me'' emphasized the scary, serious side of teenage life,
``Strike!'' bites off more than it can chew.
</P>
<P>
   It wants to be funny, fervent, feminist and socially savvy about
girl's problems with self-image, boys, breasts, sex and parents,
and there's a subplot about anorexia and bulemia tossed in for good
measure. But while it has lots of energy, there's enough stuff in
the script for two movies. By the time the film winds down, it
feels much longer than its 96 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Strike! Directed and written by Sarah Kernochan. Cast: Kirsten
Dunst, Gaby Hoffmann, Monica Keena, Lynn Redgrave. Miramax Films.
96 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual themes and partial nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
