<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3495 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARCIA-MARQUEZ-JOURNA     08-20 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-MARQUEZ-JOURNALISM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GABRIEL GARCIA MARQUEZ LIKES A GOOD STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By SILVANA PATERNOSTRO  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   A few months ago, a horde of Colombian journalists from radio,
print and television were at the bedside of Liliana Caceres, a
19-year-old girl who was to give birth to sextuplets in the coastal
Caribbean city of Barranquilla.
</P>
<P>
   They had followed her pregnancy _ publishing an array of stories
about the size of her belly, her boyfriend's reaction, even medical
explanations from her doctors.
</P>
<P>
   What no journalist discovered, after weeks of being around her,
was that her tummy was huge not because she was about to produce
six babies but because she had tied pounds of rags around her. She
wanted her boyfriend to propose marriage.
</P>
<P>
   When the story broke, Nobel-laureate Gabriel Garcia Marquez,
novelist and journalist, was there teaching a workshop on reportage
_ part of the Foundation for New Iberoamerican Journalism, ``a
school without walls'' he fathered in 1995 out of his preoccupation
with the state of journalism in the region.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the computer era, the tape recorder and the lack of
rapport between reporter and editor has turned journalists into
cold communicators and simple transmitters of press releases and
transcribers of taped interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Journalism, which Garcia Marquez calls ``the best profession in
the world,'' is ailing. He is so concerned that we journalists have
forgotten how to tell a good story that he is willing to spend time
teaching us how he writes them.
</P>
<P>
   In the workshops, he admonishes those who prefer getting the
breaking story rather than preparing a good story, those who are
more concerned about reaching the halls of power and not the hearts
of readers. As much as Liliana's smart tactics made for an amusing
anecdote, her ability to deceive the nation's media prove Garcia
Marquez right: We are not doing our job.
</P>
<P>
   It also served him as a great teaching tool. Recognizing that
the story had all the elements of a great piece of reportage, the
maestro invited the prankster to class and asked the dozen
participants, young professional journalists, to interview her.
</P>
<P>
   Their assignment was to write Liliana's story _ not just by
pulling quotes from the infamous, ever-present tape recorder _ but
by following the principle that print journalism is a literary
form.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is not in itself a revelation, Garcia Marquez's
commitment to bring such a belief back to the newsroom is a
difficult and commendable effort. Because he is convinced that
there are no theories to be learned in journalism _ that the best
way to teach is to gather cub reporters and have them listen to the
experience of the veterans _ the Foundation brings them together in
an informal setting of workshops and seminars.
</P>
<P>
   It is based in Cartagena, Colombia, because that is the home of
El Universal, the first newspaper that Garcia Marquez wrote for;
and it is also the home of Clemente Manuel Zavala, the man whose
red pencil scratched and scribbled over his first articles _ the
type of editor, he believes, Latin American newspapers lack. Garcia
Marquez wants to bring his old editor back to life so much that, at
the Foundation's headquarters, one of the conference rooms is named
after him.
</P>
<P>
   Because its Nobel founder believes in Bolivar's dream of Latin
American unity, the Foundation organizes events throughout the
region. People have been taught not only in Cartagena but in other
Colombian cities and in Madrid, Mexico, Buenos Aires, Quito,
Guayaquil and Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, 600 journalists have been able to discuss
narrative techniques, current events and questions of professional
ethics face to face with the best Spanish-speaking non-fiction
writers of today. To have Garcia Marquez, Tomas Eloy Martinez or
Alma Guillermo Prieto give tips about how to write a piece of
reportage is like getting Keith Richards to show a starting
musician chords on his guitar.
</P>
<P>
   At one of the workshops Garcia Marquez taught in Cartagena _ he
has conducted 10 of the 50 events _ he acted as newsroom editor and
took on a real investigation about a young Italian tourist who had
died after having being arrested by the police. At another one in
Mexico, to teach students how to write description, he took the
class to sit in while a sketcher for the Mexican police was given
the details of the suspected criminal. Based on what they heard,
students had to write a profile.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Anderson has spoken about reporting under fire. Colombian
priest-turned-reporter Javier Dario Restrepo talks about the
difficulties of being a journalist in a country at war. Horacio
Verbitsky and Pulitzer Prize-winner Tim Golden taught investigative
journalism. Carlos Monsivais, Mexico's leading opinion journalist,
will discuss his columns while Sergio Munoz, a member of The Los
Angeles Times' editorial board, will explain how to write
straightforward op-ed pieces, devoid of the obscure and complicated
phrasing that characterizes Latin America's editorial writers.
</P>
<P>
   For photojournalists, Magnum photographer Susan Meiselas shares
her slides from the civil wars of Central America, showing how
photographers are also storytellers _ not just the appendage of the
writer. Free-lance photojournalist Stephen Ferry, who applauds
Garcia Marquez's concern that most journalism is being done in
press conferences and not on the street, sees the Foundation as his
chance to do subversive work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want photographers to rebel against their editors,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers come in asking him technical questions such as how
to prevent a flash from bouncing off a speakers's face. He answers
by telling them to leave the press conference _ press conferences
don't tell stories.
</P>
<P>
   With the Foundation's efforts and the team of professionals
involved in teaching Spanish-speaking reporters, the future of
journalism in the region is promising. Hopefully, episodes like
Liliana's will not create an embarrassing moment for the entire
media of a region but an opportunity to write the fantastic story
her imagination deserved.
</P>
<P>
   _________ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SILVANA PATERNOSTRO, a Colombian-born journalist, is the
author of ``In the Land of God and Man: Confronting Our Sexual
Culture,'' to be published by Dutton in November. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Her article on contemporary life in Cuba is forthcoming in The
New York Times Magazine.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Paternostro has recently reported on Pope John Paul's historic
visit to Cuba, Gabriel Garcia Marquez's efforts to rejuvenate Latin
American journalism, New York City's Latino community and Mexico's
``narco-democracy.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (She is a proud winner of the Center for Documentary Studies'
Dorothea Lange-Paul Taylor Prize for her prior journalism on Cuba;
and has also written for The Paris Review, Spin, The Nation, The
Miami Herald and The New York Daily News. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Paternostro holds a master's degree from Columbia University's
School of International and Public Affairs and is currently a
senior fellow at the World Policy Institute in Manhattan.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
