<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3569 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTY-FOOD-WSIDEBAR-L     08-20 2923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-FOOD-WSIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKING AUTHOR EMBRACES LIGHT-STYLE DINING
</HEADLINE>
 (NOTE: A photograph is available from NYTimes. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When guests come to Laurie Burrows Grad's house
these days, she doesn't load them up on fat and calories. Instead
she opts for cooking light _ and easy _ which has become a way of
life for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's healthful and keeps me slim,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those killer recipes that we've all served company over the
years have vanished from her repertoire. ``You don't have to use
butter and cream to create beautiful parties,'' emphasized Grad.
</P>
<P>
   Now she relies on tempting creations that use lower-fat and
lower-calorie alternatives and take advantage of fat-reducing
cooking methods when she entertains. And she says her company is
grateful.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find the particulars of how she does it in her latest
cookbook, ``Entertaining Light &AMP; Easy, Lower-Fat Recipes for
Festive Meals'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster; $25), including recipes for a
variety of occasions _ from festive brunches and holiday parties to
elegant dinners and casual feasts. ``The book is all about dining
pleasurably _ entertaining with a conscience and eating without
fear,'' said Grad, adding that moderation is the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light does not mean eating diet food or fat-free cakes _ or
depriving yourself of flavor,'' she noted recently at her Los
Angeles home. But light does mean taking advantage of the
California lifestyle. And that means using lots of fresh seasonal
produce, grilling outdoors (her husband, Peter, a screenwriter, is
the expert here) or indoors, steaming vegetables and poaching foods
without added fats. She also uses fruit and vegetable salsas rather
than heavy, rich sauces on meats, poultry and fish. In addition,
she relies on the natural taste of herbs, produce, meat, fish and
poultry to enhance a dish without added fat. Asian condiments and
flavorings _ items like chili paste with garlic, hoisin sauce,
sesame oil and Cinkiang rice vinegar _ are favored in Grad's
cooking (in marinades, salad dressings and noodle dishes, for
instance) because they add intense flavor without a lot of fat.
</P>
<P>
   To keep fit, she prefers eating fresh food that is generally
lower in fat than processed foods. Fresh salads, light sandwiches
or grilled meals have become her regular choices, replacing
fat-laden options, she noted. But Grad also believes in exercising
_ and she walks 3 1/2 miles daily with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Grad, who was born in Los Angeles, but grew up in New York,
hails from a family of good cooks. ``Both of my parents were very
good cooks and my mother entertained at large parties. She was very
creative _ curry dishes and bouillabaise were among her
favorites.'' Her father, the late playwright/director Abe Burrows,
cooked when he was in writer's block, she noted.
</P>
<P>
   So cooking came naturally for Grad, who has written three other
cookbooks as well as hosted a cable television cooking show.
</P>
<P>
   Grad believes that regardless of the reduction of fat and
calories, the end results must taste good _ in fact so good that
guests won't notice or can't believe the dishes are low-fat.
Appealing presentation is important, too, she added, suggesting you
garnish and decorate finished creations with a slice of citrus
fruit, a few sprigs of a fresh herb, a cherry tomato or an edible
flower _ all the while paying attention to color.
</P>
<P>
   Setting a beautiful table is key as well. ``It doesn't have to
be complicated to be a knockout,'' noted Grad, who admits to not
being great with flowers. ``Use some colorful ribbon to tie up
napkins. Buy some inexpensive bud vases, fill each with tulips or
whatever is in season and baby's breath and place one at each
setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Grad prefers inviting eight to 10 people to her dinner parties _
and 20 for a barbecue. Her rationale is simple: ``I don't like to
kill myself for four people,'' she said. ``It's the same amount of
work for four or 10.''
</P>
<P>
   In summer, when she entertains a couple of times or more per
month, she likes to serve crudites such as baby carrots and cherry
tomatoes, smoked salmon tartare, Sweet Pea Guacamole, grilled tuna,
chicken fajitas or butterflied leg of lamb, roasted corn and cold
soups like Cucumber Yogurt Soup with Fresh Mint or a cold zucchini
soup. Other times, she might pair a cold soup with chicken salad
and fruit and cookies for dessert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also love to do salsas on grilled fish or chicken or grilled
fish with Roasted Garlic Sauce,'' she continued. The garlic sauce _
made with baked garlic, nonfat yogurt, reduced fat mayonnaise and
grainy Dijon mustard _ can be prepared a day or two in advance of
serving and kept refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Grad also likes to put together salads that are seasonal and
fresh.
</P>
<P>
   If there's no time to make an appetizer, pick up flavored smoked
salmon and serve with a quick sauce mixed up with yogurt, dill,
lemon juice and mustard accompanied with pumpernickel rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Because the book touts light-style dining, it's a bit surprising
that the recipes don't include calorie or fat counts or any other
nutritional analysis. Grad asks cooks to trust that the recipes are
low in fat, low in calories and low in sodium, but that may not
appease cooks and diners who are interested in specific figures or
are on special or restricted diets.
</P>
<P>
   Grad believes that this, her fourth cookbook, is the freshest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in cookbook burnout for five years,'' she noted, ``and
then I decided I wanted to share a battery of new recipes.'' This
new volume is the outgrowth of that.
</P>
<P>
   Grad has designed a summer luncheon party that would be ideal
for a bridal or baby shower or other occasions with ideas from her
book. It's easy to orchestrate the production if you plan and do
most of the cooking in advance (recipes in the book include
do-ahead prep tips). Dress up the recipes with a lovely
presentation _ either on beautiful dishes or with festive garnishes
and get ready for the kudos. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Luncheon Menu &QC; 
Sweet Pea Guacamole  &QC; 
Roasted Vegetable Spread &QC; 
Chinese Chicken Salad &QC; 
Chilled Sesame Noodles With Vegetables &QC; 
Light Orange Poppy Seed Pound Cake &QC; 
Summer Fruit Compote &QC; 
Strawberry Lemonade &QC; 
 &QC; 
 &QL; 
SWEET PEA GUACAMOLE
</P>
<P>
   Michael Roberts, former chef at Trumps in Los Angeles,
popularized the concept of using peas in guacamole. He suggests
using the frozen peas because the color is more vibrant and the
sugarin the peas has not been allowed to turn to starch.
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (10 ounces EACH) frozen peas, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1/4 medium ripe avocado, peeled, pitted and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons defatted chicken OR vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons low-fat mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons roughly chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons jalapeno chile, seeded and roughly chopped (see
Note)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground chile powder
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons EACH chopped tomatoes and green onions for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Baked tortilla chips OR low-fat tortilla chips
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor or blender, combine all ingredients except
tomatoes, green onions and chips, and process until just smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Place in a serving bowl, garnish with tomatoes and green onions.
Serve accompanied with tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is avocado in dip, which tends to discolor, it is
best to serve immediately, but can be kept a few hours in
refrigerator. Makes 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: About 89 percent of a chile's fire is contained in the
ribs. If these ribs and attached seeds are cut off and discarded,
the heat is diminished. In handling chiles, it is a good idea to
wear thin rubber gloves; if you do touch a chile with your bare
hands, be sure not to touch your eyes or mouth until you have
washed your hands with soap and water and allowed a few hours to
elapse.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATION: For a lower-fat version, avocado can be omitted. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ROASTED VEGETABLE SPREAD
</P>
<P>
   Other vegetables can be substituted or added to this spread such
as red or yellow bell peppers, shallots, zucchini and for added
spice a jalapeno chile. The spread can also be tossed with linguine
or spaghetti for a delicious pasta dish or spread on pizza crust
and baked until hot and bubbly.
</P>
<P>
   1 medium eggplant (about 1 pound), quartered lengthwise (see
Note)
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, thickly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds tomatoes, sliced horizontally and squeezed of seeds
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh basil plus additional fresh basil
leaves for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Toasted thin sliced bread
</P>
<P>
   Lightly coat a roasting pan with olive oil nonstick cooking
spray.
</P>
<P>
   Place eggplant, skin side down, in pan; add onion, tomatoes and
garlic. Spray vegetables lightly with oil.
</P>
<P>
   Roast in preheated 425-degree oven 45 to 50 minutes or until
vegetables are softened and browned. Allow to cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Place eggplant, onion and tomatoes (not garlic) in a food
processor or blender and process until just smooth. Squeeze garlic
puree out of skin into food processor, add chopped basil, vinegar
and salt and pepper. Continue to puree until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Serve spread hot, at room temperature or even cold on toasted
thin-sliced bread garnished with basil leaves. Spread may be
prepared up to 3 days in advance and chilled until ready to serve.
Makes 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The younger the eggplant, the fewer seeds and the less
bitter the flesh. To select a young vegetable, choose an eggplant
that is rich purple in color with a firm flesh. Medium-sized
eggplants are preferred since larger ones tend to have more seeds.
The cap should look fresh and green and avoid any eggplants with
dark brown spots, a sure sign of decay.
</P>
<P>
   It is not necessary to peel eggplant or tomato since skins will
soften considerably. If desired, remove skins easily after roasting
and before pureeing spread.
</P>
<P>
   One pound of Japanese eggplants can be substituted for 1 medium
eggplant. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHINESE CHICKEN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   This lightened version dispenses with fried noodles and oily
dressing but yields delicious results.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN SALAD:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups shredded cooked chicken
</P>
<P>
   3 cups shredded iceberg lettuce
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   DRESSING:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Chinese OR Japanese rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Asian-style sesame seed oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   TOPPING:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons preserved red ginger, diced
</P>
<P>
   For Salad, in a large bowl, place chicken, lettuce and green
onions.
</P>
<P>
   For Dressing, whisk all dressing ingredients together. Toss with
chicken and lettuce mixture to combine.
</P>
<P>
   Top with remaining ingredients and serve immediately. Makes 4 to
6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATIONS: Toasted almonds can be substituted for pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Sliced OR chopped water chestnuts OR blanched snow pea pods OR
baby bok choy can be added to salad. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRILLED SESAME NOODLES WITH VEGETABLES
</P>
<P>
   Cold noodles with spicy peanut sauce are a great lunch dish or
can be served as part of a summer buffet.
</P>
<P>
   NOODLE MIXTURE:
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large zucchini, shredded (about 1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   3 radishes, trimmed and shredded
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, green parts only
</P>
<P>
   DRESSING:
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Asian-style sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili paste with garlic OR to taste
</P>
<P>
   GARNISH:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   Green onions
</P>
<P>
   For Noodle Mixture, drop spaghetti into boiling water and cook
until al dente, drain well. Toss with 1/2 teaspoon sesame oil.
</P>
<P>
   In a serving bowl, place cooked spaghetti and top with zucchini,
radishes and green onions.
</P>
<P>
   For Dressing, in a small food processor, chop ginger and garlic
until just minced. Add all remaining dressing ingredients and
process until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour dressing over spaghetti and vegetables. Top with sesame
seeds and toss. Serve immediately garnished with green onions.
Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATIONS: Hot chili oil can be substituted for chili paste.
</P>
<P>
   Other shredded seasonal vegetables can be added to taste.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT ORANGE POPPY SEED POUNDCAKE
</P>
<P>
   You will need a nonstick 10-inch tube pan to make this cake.
It's a sort of angel food/poundcake combo made moist by nonfat sour
cream, lightened by beaten whites, but with the texture of a rich
poundcake. It is not a complicated recipe but does require a lot of
bowls and dishes to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   CAKE:
</P>
<P>
   6 egg whites, at room temperature for 15 minutes before using
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 carton (16 ounces) nonfat sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup frozen orange juice concentrate
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup poppy seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 whole eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   GLAZE:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   Nonfat OR low-fat vanilla OR lemon frozen yogurt OR low-fat
vanilla ice cream for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Generously coat a nonstick 10-inch tube pan with nonstick
cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   For Cake, in a large bowl, beat egg whites on high with an
electric mixer until just frothy. Gradually add 1/2 cup granulated
sugar, beating until soft peaks form.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine sour cream with orange juice
concentrate, poppy seeds, orange peel and vanilla. Whisk until
mixture is smooth.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate medium bowl, beat remaining 1 1/2 cups granulated
sugar with oil until lightly combined. Add whole eggs and beat
until well mixed. Add sour cream mixture and continue to beat until
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine cake flour, baking powder, baking soda
and salt. Add to sour cream mixture and continue beating until
smooth. Fold in a small amount of egg whites by hand and when
combined, add remaining egg whites, folding until well mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into prepared pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake on middle shelf in preheated 300-degree oven about 1 hour
and 5 minutes or until cake springs back to touch. Remove from
oven. Allow to cool in pan about 10 minutes. Then turn out onto a
rack to cool thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   While cake is cooling, prepare Glaze by mixing powdered sugar
with orange juice and peel and continue beating until smooth. When
cake is slightly cooled, prick holes lightly with a fork and pour
glaze over cake.
</P>
<P>
   Allow cake to cool slightly, slice and serve warm or at room
temperature, topped with a dollop of nonfat or low-fat vanilla or
lemon frozen yogurt or low-fat vanilla ice cream. Makes 1 large
cake, about 16 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUMMER FRUIT COMPOTE
</P>
<P>
   This easy and refreshing dessert is particularly useful when you
have an overabundance of ripe fruit.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   4 apricots, pitted and quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 plums, pitted and quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 nectarines, pitted and quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 cantaloupe, cut into balls
</P>
<P>
   1 pint raspberries
</P>
<P>
   Nonfat OR low-fat vanilla yogurt OR low-fat sour cream and
sprigs of mint for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Bring sugar, water, honey and vanilla bean to a boil. Reduce
heat and simmer, uncovered, 6 to 7 minutes, stirring occasionally,
until sugar has dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   Add apricots, plums and nectarines. Bring to a boil, reduce heat
and simmer 6 to 7 minutes or until tender. Add cantaloupe and
raspberries and cook 2 to 3 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   Remove vanilla bean, allow to dry and rewrap it to be used
again. Place fruit in a covered container and refrigerate until
ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Serve compote chilled, garnished with a dollop of nonfat or
low-fat vanilla yogurt or low-fat sour cream and sprigs of mint.
Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATIONS: Any variety of seasonal fruits can be substituted.
</P>
<P>
   If time permits, apricots, plums and nectarines can be peeled. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
STRAWBERRY LEMONADE
</P>
<P>
   Tired of chemical-laden fizzy diet drinks? Try this alternative
cooling beverage form the chefs at The Four Seasons Hotel chain.
This strawberry lemonade and variations are easy to prepare and
provide a perfect light accompaniment to a summertime lunch or
supper.
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, rinsed and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 cups freshly squeezed lemon juice (about 10 to 12 ripe and
juicy lemons)
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups cold water
</P>
<P>
   Place strawberries and sugar in a food processor or blender and
puree until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Strain mixture into a pitcher. Add lemon juice and cold water;
stir well. Pour into ice-filled glasses or chill until ready to
serve. Makes 4 serving.
</P>
<P>
   VARIATIONS
</P>
<P>
   For RASPBERRY LEMONADE, use 2 pints raspberries, 1 cup sugar, 2
cups lemon juice and 4 cups cold water.
</P>
<P>
   For PINEAPPLE LEMONADE, use 1 peeled, cored and sliced
pineapple, 1/2 cup sugar, 2 cups lemon juice and 2 1/2 cups cold
water.
</P>
<P>
   For PEACH LEMONADE, use 6 very ripe peeled and sliced peaches,
3/4 cup sugar, 2 cups lemon juice and 3 cups cold water.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: To get most juice from a lemon, always squeeze lemons at
room temperature and roll on a counter with palm of your hand
before juicing. If lemons are stored in refrigerator, microwave 10
to 20 seconds or leave in hot water several minutes before
juicing. &QL; 
END
</P>
</TEXT>
