<SLUG> BC-PARTY-SIDEBAR-FOOD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING IT LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Following are some of cookbook author Laurie
Burrows Grad's additional tricks for cooking light and easy
anytime.
</P>
<P>
   _Use fresh lemon juice instead of bottled. Squeeze fresh lemons
when plentiful and keep a supply of juice in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   _Limit the amount of oil used. Fill spray pumps with olive or
canola oil and use to spray pans. You'll save money. Keep in mind
that light olive oil is not lower in fat _ it just has some of the
oil's flavor and color removed.
</P>
<P>
   _Slowly roasted garlic is an excellent fat-free ``butter''
alternative that can be used as a spread on bread or to flavor
sauces or mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   _Use canned broths, refrigerated prepared salsas, canned
tomatoes, store-bought peeled garlic and curry powder as
timesavers.
</P>
<P>
   _Use heavy, nonstick pans. Grad's personal choice is All-Clad,
LTD. A less expensive alternative is Farberware Millennium pans,
she notes.
</P>
<P>
   _Yogurt cheese is a good base for dips and salad dressings in
place of mayonnaise or sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   _Dip meats, fish or poultry into butter or egg white rather than
whole egg when coating with crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   _Lean ground turkey is a good substitute for ground beef in
meatloaves, burgers, chilis and other dishes.
</P>
<P>
   _Cooked and pureed vegetables are good natural thickeners in
place of butter, flour and cream in soups and sauces.
</P>
<P>
   _Grill meats (to remove fat) rather than sauteing before putting
in stews and braised dishes, advised Grad. In osso buco, for
instance, she grills the veal before braising to eliminate fat.
</P>
<P>
   _To intensify flavor, toast nuts and seeds; they'll add more
flavor to finished dishes than plain ones, so you'll end up using
less.
</P>
<P>
   _Cook in paper or foil packets; added fats are not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   _Use nonfat or 1 percent low-fat milk _ which are lower in
saturated fat, cholesterol and calories than whole milk. You can
give nonfat milk more body by adding a spoonful of powdered milk.
</P>
<P>
   _Use low-fat or reduced-fat cheeses. Avoid nonfat cheeses, which
are rubbery. Also avoid nonfat cream cheese, which is gross, noted
Grad.
</P>
<P>
   _Mustard, especially the grainy variety, is good for adding
thickness to dressings and sauces without added fat.
</P>
<P>
   _Discard fat on chicken after cooking and before eating.
</P>
<P>
   _To reduce fat in recipes, substitute egg whites for whole eggs
_ 1 1/2 to 2 egg whites for each yolk.
</P>
<P>
   _Keep in mind you'll need a little bit of fat in baked goods for
taste and texture. Although Grad advocates using low-fat rather
than nonfat sour cream in most cases, she makes an exception and
uses nonfat sour cream in cakes for moistness.
</P>
<P>
   _When a recipe calls for cream or milk, use chicken or vegetable
broth and a few cooked, pureed potatoes or rice for thickening.
</P>
<P>
   _Use small amounts of prosciutto or Canadian bacon to add smoky
flavor to dishes.
</P>
<P>
   _Use a gravy or fat strainer to separate fats and oils from
soups, sauces and stews when there is no time for overnight
chilling. This is one of Grad's favorite light gadgets. She also
likes a yogurt cheese maker.
</P>
<P>
   _Top fruit desserts, cakes, etc., with a dollop of nonfat
vanilla yogurt or frozen yogurt rather than whipped cream or ice
cream. &QL; 
END &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
