<HEADLINE>
GE SAYS EPA REPORT ON HUDSON RIVER POLLUTION IS FLAWED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ An Environmental Protection Agency report that
found PCBs were escaping from polluted Hudson River sediment is so
flawed that its conclusions cannot be taken seriously, the General
Electric Co. has charged.
</P>
<P>
   GE accused the environmental agency of selectively excluding
data, bumbling key statistics and jumping to rash conclusions about
the amount and location of PCBs leaving the Hudson's sediment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report contains errors so serious and so fundamental that
GE believes the conclusions invalid,'' Mel Schweiger, manager of
GE's Hudson River PCB assessment team, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The contradictory claims from GE and the federal government
center on the EPA's conclusion last month that silt-bound PCBs were
not staying buried by layers of clean sediment. Rather, the federal
agency's report said the industrial chemicals were escaping into
the water from patches of sediment where they are highly
concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA report, based on samples taken in 1984 and 1994,
contradicted GE's long-standing claim that PCBs were being buried
deep enough to seal them off from marine life or were naturally
breaking down into harmless substances.
</P>
<P>
   GE used PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls, for about three
decades as an insulator in electric capacitors. The company legally
discharged more than one million pounds of the chemicals from
factories in two New York towns, Hudson Falls and Fort Edward, into
the river before the chemicals were banned in 1976. GE says it has
spent $150 million to remove some of PCBs it discharged and could
be forced to pay the potentially huge cost of dredging them from
the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has set a June 2001 date for making a final decision
about what to do about the PCB pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government considers PCBs toxic to humans. In April,
GE Chairman Jack Welch told stockholders that PCBs have no adverse
health effects.
</P>
<P>
   GE's dismissal of the EPA's study, announced at a news
conference Wednesday, is based on the company's own study of cores
of Hudson River sediment, completed in June. The report picked
apart the EPA's main conclusion and offered GE's own explanations
of where the agency went wrong. For example, GE criticized as
invalid EPA's reliance on only 60 sediment samples to estimate PCB
releases for the entire six-mile stretch of the Thompson Island
Pool, a ``hot spot,'' or known area of high PCB concentration,
south of Fort Edward.
</P>
<P>
   GE also said the EPA's analysis of Hudson River core samples was
far too crude to offer conclusions about how encased the
sediment-bound PCBs are.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just isn't enough data to analyze anything with any
accuracy,'' said John Connolly, a GE consultant and president of
Quantitative Environmental Analysis of Montvale, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Presented with the accusations in General Electric's report, EPA
spokesman Dick Stapleton said, ``We stand by our findings. PCBs are
not being covered by clean sediments and there have been
significant releases from hot spots into the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about GE's dismantling of the EPA methodology, he said,
``We have good scientists.''
</P>
<P>
   GE's detailed riposte to each new EPA finding highlights the
high-stakes battle in which neither side will acknowledge the
other's scientific findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``So high are the stakes on the Hudson River that the science
that supports EPA's conclusions must be of impeccable quality,''
Schweiger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
