<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BLADE-TEX     08-20 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONFIDENT WESLEY SNIPES CUTS LIKE A KNIFE IN `BLADE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although it's about 20 minutes too long, the action-horror movie
``Blade'' is a rousing tease _ it's smarter than it has a right to
be. It opens with the birth of its title character 31 years ago,
and then jumps into the present.
</P>
<P>
   An unsuspecting human is dragged by a beautiful girl into a
bumping club hidden beneath a meat locker. When the music at the
joint hits its climax, the shower spigots open and spray the room
with blood. It's full of vampires, and the hapless human is bounced
around like a meal in Levis.
</P>
<P>
   Blade (Wesley Snipes) appears, and a lurid, amped battle is
joined _ he spins through the crowd of bloodsuckers with his
samurai sword and automatic weapons loaded with
silver-garlic-tipped hollow-points.
</P>
<P>
   This spectacularly insane scene is just the antidote for horror
movie fans who are tired of seeing beautiful 15-year-olds stalked
by knife-wielding maniacs. When it works, ``Blade'' has a baroque,
wicked wit. The opening sequence sets a high-water mark, if you'll
pardon the pun.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes drops his voice an octave into an action-hero baritone,
although this tactic doesn't entirely rob him of expressiveness. He
is capable of being shocked, and he retains his sense of humor so
he can play the shocks for laughs _ an asset that eludes most
superstuds embroidered with muscles. He moves well, spinning and
kicking like a savior who has spent much time worshipping at the
shrine of Hong Kong avatars Jackie Chan and Jet Li. (It helps that
the vampires are as dim-witted as the villains in the Hong Kong
action stuff. Here, they mostly attack the hero one at a time _ if
these guys ever learn gang warfare, civilization as we know it is
over.)
</P>
<P>
   Blade's pregnant mother was bitten by a vamp before he was born,
and his mission is to take his elm-tree-sized Afro and bandoleer
loaded with wooden blades to do in the creature that bit her.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his unique status, Blade can go out into daylight and
has a vampire's strength, but he also needs blood. Whistler (Kris
Kristofferson), Blade's mentor and weapons master, has an even more
gravel-ridden voice than his protege. The anti-vampire team gets a
new partner, Karen (N'Bushe Wright), a hematologist who was bitten
and is trying to fight off vampirism.
</P>
<P>
   Director Stephen Norrington fashions a tense, moody ambience,
and the script piles on alert, genre cleverness. The problems come
because the movie doesn't exactly follow its own logic. When Frost
discovers a set of symbols that could turn the entire world into
vampires, it doesn't seem to occur to him that there will be no
food left if he succeeds. ``Blade'' doesn't have the low-camp
soap-opera zest of the WB's ``Buffy,'' although the kung-fu grip
battle scenes are definitely reminiscent. It's often genuinely
creepy, which gives it a gruesome resonance missing from most of
the new wave of horror movies.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Blade'' didn't drag on so long, it would be a great
B-movie. Instead, Snipes carries a lot of ``Blade'' on his
muscular, broad back. He's one of the few action stars with a
personality, and he can act. Recently, he has gone through a slew
of bad movies, and you can almost hear the audience sigh with
relief that he has chosen a worthwhile project. Ironically, he had
to do a vampire movie to show some taste.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Blade''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Wesley Snipes, Stephen Dorff
</P>
<P>
   Director: Stephen Norrington
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and bloody scenes of violence
</P>
<P>
   Length: 120 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
