<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DANCEWITHME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DANCE WITH ME' HAS TWO LEFT FEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not at all light on its feet, ``Dance With Me'' stumbles
clumsily onto the cinema dance floor, one already crowded with
hackneyed hoofer pictures.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear some studio pitch-monkey saying, ``Hey,
Latin dancing is hot now, right? Why not make a movie about a poor
Cuban Pete who cha-chas his way into the hearts of America? It'll
be like a salsa-style `Strictly Ballroom.' '' Yeah, except without
all the entertainment value.
</P>
<P>
   It's puzzling why studios even bother cranking out dance
pictures anymore. When they work, as did ``Ballroom, Shall We
Dance?'' and ``Dirty Dancing,'' success can be moderate to decent.
But when they misstep _ ``The Forbidden Dance, Staying Alive'' or
``Breakin' 2: Electric Boogaloo'' _ the fallout usually has the
half-life of uranium 238. Kevin Bacon is still trying to shake off
``Footloose'' jokes, and that was a successful dance picture.
</P>
<P>
   Latin American singing sensation Chayanne hopes to Swayze his
way to screen success as Rafael, a young Cuban dreamer who comes to
Texas in search of the love of his late mother's, er, life. Kris
Kristofferson is a grizzled Houston dance studio manager who feels
for the boy enough to let him live over his garage and squeegee the
mirrors at the studio. You know, of course, that the studio manager
and Rafael share a big secret. Never mind that you figured it out
in the first 10 minutes _ this story is about as by-the-numbers as
a set of painted footprints on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Kristofferson's studio is populated by a handful of bored
neighborhood locals, as well as Vanessa L. Williams, the former
Miss America whose ravishing beauty seems ridiculously out of place
in this Dolly Dinkle dance dive. She left her life as a champion
dancer because her husband/partner is an egomaniacal jerk. Now she
does the dance teacher-by-day/single mother-by-night gig when she's
not beguiling the lovestruck Rafael, who manages to reignite her
passion for dance. (Think ``Stella Gets Her Mambo Back.)''
</P>
<P>
   There's not much point in summing up any more. Suffice it to say
there's a bitter breakup, a father/son scrap, a seemingly endless
Vegas dance contest, a touching reunion and the triumph of true
love in the end. Cliche, party of ... oh, too many to count.
</P>
<P>
   The film is not completely without charm. Chayanne is engaging,
with a smile that will melt hearts and a body that will wag
tongues. Williams proves herself to be quite a dancer, particularly
in the contest scenes. And the film gets an extra star just for not
having Kristofferson strut his stuff.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Dance With Me''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Randa Haines
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Vanessa L. Williams, Chayanne, Kris Kristofferson
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ profanity, adult situations and subject matter and
steamy love scenes
</P>
<P>
   Length: 126 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is a film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
