A3624 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-YOURFRIENDS-TEX     08-20 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-YOURFRIENDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET US PREY, BUT DON'T LET US ENJOY IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most audacious thing about writer-director Neil LaBute's new
movie, ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' isn't its subject _ couples
bouncing around in sexual roundelays _ or even a scene featuring
the most heartless of them, Jason Patric, drop-kicking a plastic
infant he's just plucked from a model of a womb. There's no
messiness for LaBute, just conquerors and victims, which is the way
he lets audiences off the hook; there's a self-congratulatory
quality to his cruelty, like that of documentary filmmaker Michael
Moore. So his newest film is about as close to the edge as a Yes
album; ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' is like ``Carnal Knowledge''
starring the Muppets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends'' follows a married couple (Amy Brenneman and Aaron
Eckhart), a cohabiting couple (Catherine Keener and Ben Stiller), a
carnivorous bachelor (Patric) and a needy lesbian (Nastassja
Kinski). It feels like a play, with everyone giving in to his
constant impulse to explain exactly what he's going through at all
times. There is no possible misinterpretation of anyone's actions;
there are no real surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller is a college drama professor with a beard that gives his
face a rodentlike cast. His girlfriend, Keener, just wants him to
shut up during sex. When she begins an affair with Kinski, Keener
blurts out the same thing. Apparently, she should just have sex
with herself.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhart seems to prefer that; he says his favorite sex partner
is himself, turning the old Woody Allen joke about masturbation _
``It's sex with someone I love'' _ a little too seriously. Eckhart
has softened considerably since playing the heartless womanizer in
``In the Company of Men,'' LaBute's impressively staged first
feature. Now Eckhart is as doughy as a puff pastry, and with the
extra weight, he has made himself physically uninteresting. As his
wife, Brenneman, who has continually beseeching doe eyes, is
intense and nervous; of all the archetypes, she's most sympathetic.
But like everyone else, she's too one-note.
</P>
<P>
   Patric will probably score best with his portrayal of the cold,
forthright stud _ basically, the same guy whom Eckhart played in
``In the Company of Men.'' Insanely self-obsessed, he preens like a
forest animal. Even his conversations with his friends feel like
date rape. He gives a showstopper of a speech to Stiller and
Eckhart, which makes explicit what most psychiatrists say about Don
Juanism. (In a case of cheesy irony, he's a gynecologist.)
</P>
<P>
   La Bute distanced himself from the characters, so we can all
look down our noses at them _ he has turned contempt into a type of
dramatization, creating a shallow superiority that cheapens the
material. In another of the chocolate-covered ironies that LaBute
deals in, none of his characters gets any pleasure from sex. Maybe
his most impressive feat is that he passes that lack of pleasure on
to the audience. He makes you feel dirty for laughing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Your Friends and Neighbors''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jason Patric, Ben Stiller, Nastassja Kinski, Amy
Brenneman
</P>
<P>
   Director: Neil La Bute
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ Extremely frank sexual dialogue, including a
monologue about a rape
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1447EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3631 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-DEADMAN-TEX     08-20 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DEADMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIP THIS CLASSLESS COLLEGE COMEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few movies are more irritating than the ones that don't have the
courage of their own bad taste. ``Dead Man on Campus'' is one of
'em: a slob movie that denies its slobdom, a dark comedy that
resists its darkness. As a result, it's just dim.
</P>
<P>
   One expected a dumb movie, but not this dumb; its dumbness would
be forgivable if the movie had any momentum, but it never gets out
of second gear. It takes forever to get to its title premise,
wasting time on a lengthy set-up in which serious-minded premedical
freshman Josh (Tom Everett Scott) is corrupted by his carefree
roommate Cooper (Mark-Paul Gosselaar of TV's ``Saved by the
Bell).''
</P>
<P>
   Josh's grades suffer. Cooper, whose favorite subject is his
bong, doesn't study at all. They both need an out, and they find it
in the college's ``suicide rule'' _ if a dorm student commits
suicide, his or her roommate is given straight A's as consolation.
</P>
<P>
   Having ditched their lecherous, ill-tempered real roommate, Josh
and Cooper set out trying to find a campus basket case in the hopes
that he'll off himself while sharing their digs. This sets up a
series of one-joke sketches involving a loony frat boy (Lochlyn
Munro, who almost breathes life into the movie), a paranoiac with a
Bill Gates fixation (Randy Pearlstein) and a depressed British
musician (Corey Page).
</P>
<P>
   For a movie bearing the MTV Films imprint, the film is unhip.
It's hard for it to maintain credibility when it name-drops Marilyn
Manson to refer to a character who looks and acts like Adam Ant, or
when it has the only computer-driven nutcase in the world who
doesn't have Internet access. The whole film seems to have been
made in another decade, and its actors are like dilutions of their
predecessors. Scott and Gosselaar are likable, but they coast on
personality more than they act, with Scott playing ``Bachelor
Party''-era Tom Hanks and Gosselaar stepping into Bill Murray's
``Stripes'' shoes (Munro takes the John Belushi part).
</P>
<P>
   The film has the further misfortune of coming out after
``There's Something About Mary,'' and face it _ no matter what you
thought about ``Mary,'' it raised the stakes for this genre. ``Dead
Man'' just isn't outrageous enough _ it's too ``nice'' for a movie
about two guys trying to get someone else to turn out his lights.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Dead Man on Campus''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Alan Cohn
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Tom Everett Scott, Mark-Paul Gosselaar
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, drug use and questionable content
</P>
<P>
   Length: 98 minutes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1448EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
