<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3644 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-YORK-ELECTION-HNS     08-20 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-YORK-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESSMAN RUNS AGAIN FOR NEW YORK GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATA  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Thomas Golisano, head of a payroll-services
company, has launched his candidacy for governor of New York,
criticizing state borrowing and promising an end to tolls on the
New York Thruway.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in blue pinstripes, Golisano, 56, said Wednesday he
would govern like he directs the 5,000-employee Paychex, the
company he created from scratch. He painted a picture of New York,
under his leadership, as a place where the Thruway is toll-free,
where teachers earn tenure, where debt and spending are in balance,
and where the state work force is lean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am in this thing to win,'' the Rochester multimillionaire
pledged. Golisano is running under the Independence Party banner,
the alternative line he created in 1993 as part of his unsuccessful
bid for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Golisano was compensated to the tune of $695,250 from Paychex
last year and is listed by Forbes magazine as among the 400 richest
Americans. He said he would refuse special-interest money and
donations from political action committees and spend $10 million of
his own money on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is joining the race months after the other
candidates, his infusion of personal wealth immediately ranks him
second only to Gov. George Pataki in available campaign funds.
Pataki, a Republican, has raised about $17 million and has $12.2
million on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Golisano's ante solidly placed him in the race for governor,
although he is considered a long shot, political experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's viable, but whether he has a chance to win, I
don't know if anyone at this point has a really good chance at
beating Pataki,'' said Sarah Liebschutz, state government and
political science professor at the State University College at
Brockport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got a good issue on the debt. He's a very
successful CEO of a business, and he has credibility in terms of
growing a business and not being indebted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that he can put this kind of money in a campaign
makes him a serious candidate because he can buy TV; he can get out
there similarly to (Ross) Perot,'' said Rachel Leon of Common
Cause. ``The sad thing is: You either have to be a millionaire or
friends of millionaire to run for governor in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   After launching an attack on Pataki's penchant for state
borrowing, Golisano previewed a series of television and radio ads
that will cost about $9.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials blast ``borrow and spend Pataki'' for adding $20
billion to New York's debt since 1994, 90 percent of which is the
``back-door'' variety that comes without voter approval.
</P>
<P>
   The spots also claim New York wastes money on toll collectors
and inconveniences motorists with tolls. Golisano would get rid of
both, finding cheaper ways to fund highway maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Using several themes employed by Democrats seeking to challenge
Pataki, Golisano said job growth in New York is well behind the
national level.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is in the lowest 5 percent; that's not acceptable,''
he said. He described Pataki's economic development program as
``corporate welfare'' and said New York gives too much money to
companies that really don't add jobs. And he said pay raises for
union employees should be at the inflation rate with considerations
for productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Laureen A. Oliver, 45, a tax accountant, is running with
Golisano as lieutenant governor. Four years ago, Golisano garnered
4 percent of the vote, spending more than $6.5 million of his own
funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1453EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
