<HEADER>
A3810 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPICEGIRL-AZR &LR;      08-20 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPICEGIRL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING'S NICE. OR IS IT? A CHAT WITH CHEERFUL GIRL MEL B. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Thanks to the burly British accent, the voice on the
other end of the line is hard to understand. Still, the words are
unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello! This is Mel B. from the Spice Girls! How are you doing
today?''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, it suddenly kicks in: Millions of 9-year-old
girls around the world would trade places with me in an instant.
It's a heady feeling, actually.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the reality of it is that I'm on the phone with Melanie
Brown, better known in Spice World as Scary Spice. And it's kind
of, well, scary.
</P>
<P>
   Seems the Girls' publicist wants the biggest female group of the
decade to do all their interviews months before their first
American tour starts. So we're speaking in May, a good 12 weeks
before the fab five _ er, four _ are scheduled to play at
Blockbuster Desert Sky Pavilion in Phoenix..
</P>
<P>
   And because the women haven't toured the States yet, Scary
doesn't have a lot to say that's terribly interesting. In fact,
everything she says sounds mechanically cheerful, like she's been
through this oh so many times. Call her Stepford Spice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've already been in every city in every state doing
radio spots,'' says Scary, the world traveler. ``But I can't wait
for this tour. It's our chance to give back to the fans who have
supported us for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   She's calling from Oslo, Norway, on the eve of the group's last
European show. Forget talk about a backlash, she insists, the
response from crowds has been phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just mad about us,'' she says. ``They scream, they
shout, they cry. They've all been so supportive of us from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   But European and American audiences are somewhat different. Here
in the States, for instance, the Girls' following seems to be
getting progressively prepubescent.
</P>
<P>
   It's hurt them in radio. ``Stop,'' a bubbly Motown pastiche, was
the group's last single, and it stopped short of the Top 10.
Programmers resisted the disc because the Girls' core audience is
now the under-10-year-old set _ not exactly a hugely desirable
market for most radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Young American girls go from Barney to Baby Spice in rapid
succession. But it doesn't bother Scary _ the least popular Spice,
if the online voting at http://c3.vmg.co.uk/spicegirls/spiceworld
is to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really flattered by the response in America,'' Scary
insists. ``We're singing our own songs, writing our own songs,
bringing positivity to fans. It's really important for them to
understand where we're coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   But, it's been suggested, the Spice Girls probably aren't the
best role models for today's youngsters. There are the tattoos and
the body piercings and the skimpy costumes.
</P>
<P>
   And the music? Shirley Partridge never would have let Keith and
Laurie sing some of the stuff the Spices perform. When Baby croons,
``Be a little bit wiser baby; put it on, put it on,'' in ``2 Become
1,'' she's not talking about funky music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you don't wake up in the morning and go, `Oh, I'm a role
model,' Scary says, apparently in a Charles Barkley frame of mind.
``You just get on with what you have to do. It's always in the back
of my mind. I mean, I know we do have a responsibility because
people do see us as role models. But it's not an overpowering
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk drifts over to accents. She doesn't understand why
Americans have a hard time understanding Brits, because she has no
problem with Stateside vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love American accents,'' she coos. ``They're quite
sexy, especially American male accents. In fact, yours I quite
fancy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that Scary is no baby when it comes to handling the
media. She knows what she wants and how she's going to say it. Her
conversation is about as well-rehearsed as a Broadway show _
something to which the Spices' slick live act often has been
compared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're writing the third album. So we're with each
other a lot, but it's great. It's not like I have one friend with
the Spice Girls. I've got four best friends; it is literally like
that. It's always nice to know I have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Scary rattled on about her best friends, Geri
Halliwell, a k a Ginger Spice, exited the quintet. Internet gossip
said Scary used to reduce Ginger to tears during limo rides with
her teasing and berating. Apparently, there's a reason she's not
called Benign Spice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fame doesn't really change the person you are,'' Scary
continues. ``If anything, you grow up a little bit more. You mature
a bit faster than normally. You get to kind of see people for what
they really are. You get alert. You're more spiritually aware of
things that happen. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of spirituality, it seems the interview is being
conducted on Scary's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 23 today!'' she declares, which is one of those statements
you don't challenge but wonder about. ``It's going to be really
wicked after the show. You wouldn't believe some of the stuff we've
planned.''
</P>
<P>
   She talks some more. She's big on figures. She says that 98
percent of the American tour is sold out. Americans may carp about
a backlash, but the '96 debut ``Spice'' has sold 6 million copies
here; the follow-up ``Spiceworld'' has headed past 3 million.
Figures seem to comfort her, if the critics don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started, we had so many barriers that we had to
break down as women in the music industry. Nobody wanted to
interview us then _ `Girls don't sell magazines,' we were told. But
at the end of the day, we've got two listings in the ``Guinness
Book of World Records.'' Every single we've released in England has
gone to Number 1. What we've done is absolutely amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people and papers start repeating incorrect information,
it's complete crap. Our fans are still there. Our fans are always
there. Our records are still selling like mad. The press will build
you up and knock you down, but our fans will always be there.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-MONICABEACH-0821     08-20 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-MONICABEACH-0821 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONICA BEACH REGULARS DON'T WANT 'GRAVY TRAIN' TO END
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among those Americans who aren't so anxious for
independent counsel Kenneth Starr to wind up his investigation of
President Clinton are the residents of Monica Beach _ the
photographers and TV technicians who have camped outside the E.
Everett Prettyman U.S. Courthouse since January.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a citizen, I guess I am glad to see it ending, but jobwise
_ no,'' said a network cameraman. ``This has been a gravy train.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed feelings,'' echoed Linda Boyle, a make-up artist
for NBC News. ``I'm tired of the saga going on and on. But it has
employed a lot of people in the TV industry.''
</P>
<P>
   With Monica Lewinsky making her second visit before the federal
grand jury on Thursday and Clinton having testified in the White
House earlier this week, the end is clearly in sight for Starr's
investigation into whether the president illegally covered up a
sexual affair with a young intern.
</P>
<P>
   Since the story broke in January, a media village of sorts has
arisen outside the courthouse where the grand jury meets. The
workers number in the hundreds. There are canopies and drink
coolers and lawn chairs galore. Several satellite trucks have been
parked by the curb for months. Others come and go according who the
day's witness will be. On Lewinsky's second visit, there were about
20 trucks plus three ``cherry pickers'' lifting cameramen high
above the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Monica Beach's photographers and technicians are
freelancers _ hired to augment Washington news bureau staffers and
to cover the four entrances to the courthouse. For an eight-hour
shift, they are paid a ``day rate'' of from $200 to $500, depending
on the job and skill level. They get time and a half for overtime,
plus catered meals. The scandal has provided a bonanza for many.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best comparison is the O.J. trial,'' said Charlie Slie, an
independent sound technician.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a windfall for us all _ a great summer job,'' said
Jim Norris, a freelance cameraman working for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, August is traditionally a slow month in the nation's
capital _ with Congress and the Supreme Court in recess and the
president often on vacation. But not this year.
</P>
<P>
   The story ``is getting good,'' said CNN correspondent Bob
Franken. ``Obviously we're coming to the end of the first act. But
now it's going to the Hill (for congressional consideration). Even
with all its unsavory aspects, it's a hugely significant story.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he will follow the story to Congress, Franken said his
wife is going on a trip to France without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had told her there was no way in the world that I can take
any vacation this year. Well, she said 'I can','' he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of 'comp time' is a fiction in this business,'' he
said, gesturing toward the canopies that shade correspondents doing
``stand-up'' reports. ``This is what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Linda Boyle does is keep some of the stars of Monica
Beach looking cool and competent for the camera when all around
them are sweating bullets in the noontime heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, its easier outside than in the studio where the
lights are hotter,'' said the NBC make-up artist after deftly
applying powder to accent the cheekbones of legal analyst Cynthia
Alksne.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no real prima donnas,'' she said of the NBC
courthouse correspondents. ``They treat me well because they know I
have to treat them well.''
</P>
<P>
   Located within walking distance of the Capitol and across the
street from the National Gallery of Art, the media village has
become a tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you need a Disneyland pass to get in here?'' joked Al
Johnson, a visiting history teacher from Orange County, Calif.,
With the advent of 24-hour news channels like Court TV and MSNBC to
compete with CNN, he said, ``I guess there is a need for news.
Everybody says they want it over but the ratings are good. I'm no
better. I'm standing here watching, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny and Barbara Jump had stopped on their way to the Capitol
after hearing that Lewinsky was testifying. The couple from
Springfield, Mo., said the media operation was considerably more
complex than they'd observed from watching the coverage on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty wild,'' said Danny Jump.
</P>
<P>
   Well, ``wild'' is not the description given by Robert Giroux, a
freelance photographer working for several magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed emotions,'' he said. Without Monica Beach, ``I
wouldn't be doing as well financially, but I might be a little more
interested in what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven months of shooting witnesses entering and leaving the
courthouse has become a bit ``mind numbing,'' he said. ``But the
money is good. It's job security.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice now that we have sunny weather,'' said Johnie (CQ)
Roth, a freelance TV cameraman. All around, technicians were
lounging in lawn chairs. ``But it wasn't very glamorous when we
were waiting in the cold and rain last winter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fireman-type job,'' he said. ``You sit a lot. But then
that car comes up and out steps Monica and you'd better be on your
toes.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
