<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBLE-DATA-$ADV23-COX     08-20 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBLE-DATA-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE BAD NEWS GETS WORSE FOR RUSSIA'S ECONOMY
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-RUBLE-$ADV23; RUSSIA-STOCKS-$ADV23.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories for use Sunday, Aug. 23 and thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Some facts and figures about Russia's problem-plagued
economy:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  THE SHRINKING RUBLE ....
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the week, a Russian ruble was worth about 16
U.S. cents (trading at 6.2 to the dollar). The de facto devaluation
means its worth can slide on currency markets to about 11 cents
(9.5 to the dollar), or 34 percent. Consumer prices have started to
rise to reflect the weakened ruble.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A SMALL ECONOMY GETTING SMALLER ....
</P>
<P>
   Still a nuclear superpower, Russia is far from being an economic
giant. In terms of gross domestic product (GDP), the country's
total output of goods and services, Russia does not make the list
of the world's top 20 economies. Oil is the leading export, but
flat world prices mean less-than-expected revenues. Projections for
1998 show Russia's gross domestic product at just 5.5 percent of
the U.S. GDP, according to Moody's.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WILL THE LAST INVESTOR IN RUSSIA PLEASE TURN OFF THE LIGHTS
...?
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Russia had one of the most robust emerging stock
markets in the world, with gains of 200 percent and more in some
issues. This year, it is the world's worst. Total capital invested
in the Russian market has fallen to below $18 billion this month,
compared with $128 billion at the end of last year. In the past few
weeks, only about a half-dozen stocks listed on the exchange have
seen any significant trading, out of 87 companies on the board,
according to the Russian Trading System.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SAVINGS WIPEOUT FOR RUSSIANS ...?
</P>
<P>
   Only 30 of an estimated 1,500 banks in Russia will survive
currency devaluation, Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov has
predicted. But the impact may not be great on average Russians for
two reasons: Most Russians have no savings. And most of those who
do keep their money in U.S. dollars under the mattress, not in a
bank.
</P>
<P>
   According to government estimates, 77 percent of Russian
households have zero potential for savings. Of the rest, those with
savings of $10,000 or less keep only about 7 percent of their money
in the form of rubles. And the richest, those with savings of more
than $10,000, keep virtually none of their money in the national
currency.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AMERICA AT RISK ...?
</P>
<P>
   The political stakes are huge should Russia's fiscal woes force
President Boris Yeltsin from office or derail the country's
attempts at economic and democratic reforms. But economically,
Russia simply does not matter much to American producers. U.S.
exports to Russia in 1997 amounted to $3.4 billion, only about 0.5
percent of total U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BOUND FOR BANKRUPTCY ...?
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Russia announced a 90-day moratorium on its debt
payments. Russian officials insist the country and its major banks
will not default on loans. If it were to, here's who would lose
....
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Largest Lenders:
</P>
<P>
   German banks ..... $30.5 billion
</P>
<P>
   U.S. banks ................ $7.1 billion
</P>
<P>
   French banks .......... $7.0 billion
</P>
<P>
   Italian banks .......... $4.3 billion
</P>
<P>
   Austrian banks ...... $3.6 billion
</P>
<P>
   Swiss banks ........... $1.5 billion
</P>
<P>
   British banks ......... $1.0 billion
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks ..... $1.0 billion
</P>
<P>
   Source: Bank for International Settlements, as of December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
