<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-STOCKS-$ADV23-     08-20 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-STOCKS-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S STOCK MARKET: A SMALL BEAR WITH A BIG BITE
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-RUBLE-$ADV23.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories for use Sunday, Aug. 23 and thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES AND JULIA SHARGORODSKA 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ ``The potential is certainly enormous,'' Institutional
Investor magazine, the bible of international finance, wrote last
summer of Russia's young and vigorous stock market.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the publication was referring to the potential for
profits, not the catastrophic declines the market would suffer in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian stock market is minuscule by Western standards and
has little impact in the lives of most ordinary Russians. Yet it is
an important barometer of foreign investors' confidence -- in
recent months, a badly withered faith -- in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In two bullish years, the Russian Trading System (RTS), the
country's main stock market, rose 110 percent in 1996, and again in
1997. This year, the market has slumped 78 percent. The 21st
largest market in the world at the end of 1997, it now ranks in the
bottom, similar in size to such minor stock exchanges as Egypt,
Columbia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years after the collapse of the Soviet Union, the majority
of Russians simply lack the money -- the average monthly salary in
Russia is only about $200 -- and the familiarity with free markets
to invest.
</P>
<P>
   The major players are Russian banks, investment companies
representing the wealthy minority in Russia and foreigners, who
must participate through Russian-registered brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian financial crisis has driven foreign investors out of
emerging markets in Russia and elsewhere. The declining world price
of oil, Russia's biggest export earner, has contributed to the
problems, as oil and energy related stocks dominate the Moscow
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The world's worst performing market this year, its declines and
Russia's ballooning foreign debt contributed to the International
Monetary Fund's decision to assemble a $22.6 billion bailout
package for Russia last month.
</P>
<P>
   That loan package was intended to restore confidence in Russia.
It didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Last week alone, the market lost nearly $3 billion and trading
virtually ceased to exist. As of August 18, the market's
capitalization was $18 billion, compared with $128 billion at the
end of 1997. (By comparison, capital in the U.S. market, the
world's largest, at the end of 1997 was $11.3 trillion).
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Trading System (RTS), which handles more than half
of all issues on Russia's stock market, began operating in the fall
of 1995 and currently trades in 87 companies. Russia's other major
stock markets, the Moscow Stock Exchange and the Moscow Interbank
Currency Exchange (MICEX) began trading shares in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The most actively traded stocks are Russia's electricity
monopoly Unified Energy System (UES), Russia's largest oil company,
Lukoil, and the main long-distance telecommunications provider,
Rostelecom.
</P>
<P>
   With prices low, will the market rebound soon?
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe a substantial upswing to profit levels seen in
1996 and 1997 will not come until after the scheduled Russian
presidential elections in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market isn't growing now because the situation is not
stable,'' said Nikolai Gusev, a trader at Regent European
Securities. ``Nobody knows what's going to happen tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
