<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARY POPPINS WAS RIGHT ABOUT SUGAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coffee to get rid of headaches; ginger and chile peppers to ease
arthritis; rice to soothe digestion; and sugar to help us sleep?
</P>
<P>
   Although sugar is by no means a health food, it can help us
sleep because it triggers the production of serotonin in the brain
to help suppress pain and depression and ease us into restful
slumber, says a pioneer in the healing power of good nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal Barnard recommends a cookie and some fruit juice about
an hour before bedtime. Milk, he says, causes digestive problems
for too many people and lots of aches and pains that we would never
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   It took us a long time to come around to the fact that a very
low-fat, mostly vegetarian diet can not only prevent but also
reverse heart disease in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Barnard has put together a lot of evidence to suggest that
such a diet can also prevent as well as cure back pain, migraines,
arthritis, menstrual pain, kidney stones and insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard is president of the Physicians' Committee for
Responsible Medicine, a nonprofit professional organization that
promotes vegetarian eating and is known for rating airport food and
school lunch programs. He was in Dallas recently to promote his
newest book, ``Foods That Fight Pain'' (Harmony Books, $25).
</P>
<P>
   He says that we are just starting to recognize the power that
food has.
</P>
<P>
   To many people, using foods to fight pain, such as that of
arthritis or migraine headaches, is a foreign idea.
</P>
<P>
   Certain foods can trigger pain while others ease pain, Barnard
says.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pain-reduction benefit of foods comes from opening
arteries and promoting good blood flow throughout the body, but
some foods seem to provide an analgesic to nerves and work within
the brain to reduce sensitivity, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a very low-fat diet, he recommends three major
strategies for nutritional control of pain: Determine which foods
trigger pain for you; find which foods soothe your pain; and use
herbal supplements when necessary to increase the effectiveness of
dietary changes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many people with arthritis are sensitive to one or
more of the following foods: dairy products, corn, meats, wheat,
oats and rye, eggs, citrus fruits, potatoes, tomatoes, nuts and
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Barnard says arthritics should first avoid all those foods for
two weeks to cool the joints, then begin adding them back one at a
time, every two days. If the addition does not cause pain, he said,
that food is safe to add back to the diet.
</P>
<P>
   To boost the effects of dietary changes, he recommends
gingerroot in a tea or added to vegetables _ about one-half to one
teaspoon per day, fresh from the grocery produce department or
powdered from a health food store.
</P>
<P>
   The ginger stops white blood cells from making the chemicals
that cause inflammation, he says, and the effect can be boosted by
adding some fatty acids such as flax seed oil or evening primrose.
</P>
<P>
   For migraines, his recommendations are similar except that the
most common triggers seem to be dairy products, chocolate, eggs,
citrus fruits, meat, wheat, nuts and peanuts, tomatoes, onions,
corn, apples and bananas.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7687. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
