A3837 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-20 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT TIME TO WRAP THIS ALL UP?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No, Yogi, it isn't over yet.
</P>
<P>
   Despite President Clinton's testimony to a federal grand jury
and his televised ``mea culpa'' to the American people Monday
night, there is no discernible end yet to the sickening tragicomedy
of concupiscence, prevarication and taped telephone conversations
that has been tormenting the American soul for more than seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   Some political prognosticators have speculated that special
prosecutor Kenneth Starr soon will wind up his
Whitewater-turned-adultery-in-the-White House scandal now that he
has had his shot at the president under oath.
</P>
<P>
   That looks increasingly like wishful thinking. Starr is intent
upon calling more witnesses and recalling some previously
questioned. Then he has to pore over the president's testimony and
somehow weave it into the massive fabric of half-truths and
fragmentary evidence he has spent years and more than $40 million
spinning.
</P>
<P>
   While he is assembling his report, Starr is likely to have his
operatives leak parts of the president's testimony in daily
dribbles to those elements of the news media that he has been
playing like a ukulele.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the realization, during his grand jury
interrogation, that Starr intended to continue to drag the matter
out that persuaded the president to alter the tone of his remarks
to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   It has been reported that the president had prepared a decidedly
more penitent statement and that what he ultimately said made some
of his advisers and supporters uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Had he believed that doing a presidential equivalent of a teary,
sin-soaked televangelist begging forgiveness would end the sordid
business, Clinton might have waxed more histrionically repentant.
But if he knew Starr would not relent, such excessive
self-flagellation was pointless.
</P>
<P>
   The fact of the matter is that Starr has to try to justify his
extravagant expense account. With that in mind, and given the
amount of rope he has been handed, Starr is likely to persist until
he thinks he can hang the president.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, then, Clinton did the appropriate thing
by admitting his wrongdoing, taking responsibility for it, and
still holding his head high and making it clear that he intends to
stand his ground against the special prosecutor. That may be the
best way to bring this painful ordeal for the nation to a quicker
end.
</P>
<P>
   By attaching his criticism of the special prosecutor to his
apology to the American people, the president appeared to be
signalling to Starr that he will not be intimidated into resigning,
which appears to be Starr's objective.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, Starr _ if he has a shred of concern left
about the damage done by his protracted effort to salvage something
resembling success from his failed Whitewater witch hunt _ should
expeditiously wrap up his investigation and submit his report.
</P>
<P>
   If he does not now have sufficient evidence to justify a call
for the president's impeachment, he will never have it.
</P>
<P>
   And the odds are that Republican Party leaders, who have enjoyed
immensely this government-paralyzing fiasco, would not risk pushing
for impeachment because they know that such an effort could
backfire on them politically.
</P>
<P>
   They sense the mood of the public, and they understand that a
majority of the American people consider the Lewinsky affair a
trivial matter that is distracting the government's attention from
much more important domestic and foreign issues.
</P>
<P>
   It's still the economy that matters most to them. The last thing
that most Americans want is a governmental cataclysm that might
propel the surging national economy into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   As the minutes ticked down toward Clinton's moment of truth with
a federal grand jury Monday, a daunting question hovered over the
American political landscape: Could the American people handle the
truth?
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, depended upon what the president offered as the
truth to the public, after giving his testimony via closed-circuit
television to the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   A few _ very few _ held out hope that the president would
somehow provide a convincing declaration of his absolute innocence.
Most Americans expected the president to admit that he had a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky. But they believed he would make that
admission in a way that would not provide grounds for perjury
charges to be brought against him.
</P>
<P>
   That is what he did. And, judging by the polls, most Americans
can handle that version of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Yogi, it's time for it to be over.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
