<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS HOPE TO SAVE OLD SAN FRANCISCO STREETCAR BARN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Preservationists are urging the city to save a
97-year-old Municipal Railway building that is a recognized
historic landmark, but which the transit agency wants to raze to
make way for streetcar and auto parking.
</P>
<P>
   The red-brick Geneva Car Barn at the corner of San Jose and
Geneva avenues was declared San Francisco's 180th historical
landmark in 1985 and is eligible for listing on the national
Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so little to start with, that to think we'll lose this
is something that really upsets me,'' said Carol Ann Taylor,
founder of Neighbors of the Excelsior. ``This building is
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and other preservation activists say they are busily
contacting city supervisors and the mayor's office in an effort to
save the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son remembers going there to buy his (street) car tickets
all the time,'' said Tony Sacco, president of the New Mission
Terrace Association. ``To tear it down for what they plan to do is
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   If the plans are carried out, the Geneva Car Barn would be the
first designated landmark in San Francisco to be razed.
</P>
<P>
   Once used as office space and storage for antique streetcars,
the two-story structure has been vacant since the 1989 Loma Prieta
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The Municipal Railway, or Muni, says it cannot afford the
estimated $4 million it would take to repair and seismically
retrofit the building, which is rife with cracked bricks, moldy
stairways, broken windows, peeling paint and the accumulation of
pigeon droppings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely had looked at that (restoration) early on, but
had made a determination it wasn't fiscally feasible in the next 10
to 20 years, and we had more immediate needs for parking for the
old cars,'' said Nancy Whelan, Muni's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Muni officials asked the Planning Department to begin an
environmental review process, which is a necessity anytime changes
are proposed for a landmark. The process has been under way since
September 1997, and a draft report is expected to be released
sometime n
</P>
