<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE FILM NEEDS MORE DANCING, OF ALL THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - ``Strictly Ballroom'' captured the passion and humor
of the ballroom dance craze. ``The Tango Lesson'' explored the
erotic tension of intimate dancing. And the Gap khakis ads
demonstrated how cool it looks if you can swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me'' misses the beat entirely, making a double
left-footed mistake for a movie about dancers: not enough dancing.
</P>
<P>
   They could have called this one ``Emote With Me.'' Or ``Sit
Around and Get Bored With Me.'' But if you're going to make a movie
called ``Dance With Me,'' let them dance.
</P>
<P>
   Director Randa Haines and her sorry-we'll-sit-this-one-out
scriptwriters go an hour into this movie before they really hit the
dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   What were they thinking? Or were they?
</P>
<P>
   Haines (``The Doctor``) takes long breaks between the dance
numbers for a story about Rafael (Chayanne), a young Cuban who
comes to Texas to work as a janitor at a dance studio owned by John
(Kris Kristofferson), the world's grumpiest dance teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael brings his vibrant Latin rhythms with him. Should have
brought an alarm clock, too _ to wake up the director.
</P>
<P>
   While we're waiting for someone to hit the floor, Rafael falls
for Ruby (Vanessa L. Williams), a teacher who is nervously
preparing to enter the big Latin dance contest for professionals
only. As a pro, she has no time for an amateur like Rafael, who
only dances because the music moves him.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like me or anyone else who has seen a movie in the
past decade, you'll guess that eventually Rafael will sweep Ruby
onto her feet and teach her that real dancing comes from the heart,
not the choreography.
</P>
<P>
   But the director doesn't get her own message and spends most of
the movie working out the problems between Rafael and John.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to a dance movie in which there's more fishing than
dancing, more Kristofferson than Williams.
</P>
<P>
   What were they thinking? I don't think they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me'' contains one fantastic dance scene in a Latino
club, where the infectious exuberance of the dancing screams that
this is what the movie should be about.
</P>
<P>
   Although she doesn't hear her own screams, Haines does recognize
the movie's other two strengths: the beauty of Williams and the
charisma of Chayanne.
</P>
<P>
   The singer and actor will make some young hearts in the audience
find that dancing beat. He has enough screen presence to deserve a
shot in a good movie. This isn't it.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't care for what dancing there is, the movie offers
two Hollywood oddities:
</P>
<P>
   _Kristofferson has two movies opening on the same day _ ``Dance
With Me'' and ``Blade _'' which is at least one too many.
</P>
<P>
   _The dance movie ``The Tango Lesson'' featured a takeoff on Gene
Kelly's famous dancing-in-the-rain number. So does ``Dance With
Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG, ``Dance With Me'' contains minor profanity and the
unchildlike sensuality of the dancing. 2 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
