<SLUG> BC-HISTORIC-BUILDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS HOPE TO SAVE OLD SAN FRANCISCO STREETCAR BARN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Refiling to eliminate garble)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Preservationists are urging the city to save a
97-year-old Municipal Railway building that is a recognized
historic landmark, but which the transit agency wants to raze to
make way for streetcar and auto parking.
</P>
<P>
   The red-brick Geneva Car Barn at the corner of San Jose and
Geneva avenues was declared San Francisco's 180th historical
landmark in 1985 and is eligible for listing on the national
Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so little to start with, that to think we'll lose this
is something that really upsets me,'' said Carol Ann Taylor,
founder of Neighbors of the Excelsior. ``This building is
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and other preservation activists say they are busily
contacting city supervisors and the mayor's office in an effort to
save the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son remembers going there to buy his (street) car tickets
all the time,'' said Tony Sacco, president of the New Mission
Terrace Association. ``To tear it down for what they plan to do is
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   If the plans are carried out, the Geneva Car Barn would be the
first designated landmark in San Francisco to be razed.
</P>
<P>
   Once used as office space and storage for antique streetcars,
the two-story structure has been vacant since the 1989 Loma Prieta
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The Municipal Railway, or Muni, says it cannot afford the
estimated $4 million it would take to repair and seismically
retrofit the building, which is rife with cracked bricks, moldy
stairways, broken windows, peeling paint and the accumulation of
pigeon droppings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely had looked at that (restoration) early on, but
had made a determination it wasn't fiscally feasible in the next 10
to 20 years, and we had more immediate needs for parking for the
old cars,'' said Nancy Whelan, Muni's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Muni officials asked the Planning Department to begin an
environmental review process, which is a necessity anytime changes
are proposed for a landmark. The process has been under way since
September 1997, and a draft report is expected to be released
sometime next month.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a hearing on the draft report and another when it
is finalized. Planning Department staffers will then offer a
recommendation to the Planning Commission, as will the Landmarks
Preservation Advisory Board. A final decision on the fate of the
last physical reminder of San Francisco's first electric railway
company will be made by the commissioners after those hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The office building and powerhouse that still stand on the
property were built by sugar magnate John D. Spreckels in 1901,
after he took over the fledgling railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Its Romanesque design boasted elegantly arched entrances and
windows, slanted wooden bays and a rounded Queen Anne turret on one
side. Shiny, solid wood paneling lined the hallways. When it was
built, fields of cabbage patches surrounded the building, and no
paved streets were anywhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   David Bahlman, executive director of the Foundation for San
Francisco's Architectural Heritage, said the building is in as bad
a shape as it is today because Muni allowed it to deteriorate for
years before the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called demolition by neglect,'' he said. Decayed, rusted
drainage gutters resulted in water damage that cracked many of the
walls, and aging beams and masonry were never repaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's been done here in the last 30 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency found in 1996 that the
unreinforced masonry building ``retains exceptional integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahlman hired an architect and engineer to visit the site for an
independent assessment a few weeks ago, and the assessment was
similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not beyond repair,'' Bahlman said. ``The foundations are
very, very solid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3894 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOCOLATE-VACATION-AR     08-20 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-VACATION-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRUE CHOCOLATE FIX DIPPED IN NOSTALGIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (JT)  
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERSHEY, Pa. _ A girlfriend once sent me a greeting card with
the message, ``I love you almost as much as chocolate itself.''
After some pondering _ and a handful of chocolate chips _ I
resolved to take it positively.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate, after all, is life's deepest, most addictive, gooiest
pleasure: chocolate bunnies on Easter morning, miniature bars in a
Halloween bag, a chocolate malt on a sizzling summer day, hot cocoa
after skiing. Whenever, wherever that sinfully fattening brown
nectar oozes over one's taste buds, life is good. Complete. Yes,
rich.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine my consternation several months ago when I read a
news account about the world's impending chocolate shortage. In
equatorial zones across the globe, it seems that fungal and viral
diseases and icky little insects are attacking cacao trees, whose
beans are the raw material from which chocolate is made. The crunch
may hit as soon as five years.
</P>
<P>
   Uncharacteristically, I was moved by more than self-pity. I have
two sons, Roy, 10, and Guy, 8, whose happiest moments are marked by
chocolate syrup smeared on their faces. So it was with a heavy
heart that I convened a family conference around our kitchen table
to tell them they faced an empty life. Just at the point I was
venturing the suggestion that cigarettes might eventually fill the
void, my wife, Suzanne, jumped into the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   She said the world would never let chocolate disappear.
Moreover, she said chocolate is a state of mind, like Christmas.
She knew this, she said, because in her peripatetic Army brat
youth, she had once lived near the capital of chocolate, Hershey,
Pa. She said the street lights there are Hershey Kisses, the main
intersection is at Chocolate and Cocoa Avenues, and the air itself
smells of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Yes! We sent for tourist literature, and almost before a certain
substance might melt in your mouth, we struck out. We were headed
for a destination the literature called ``the sweetest place on
earth.''
</P>
<P>
   As carless New Yorkers committed to the notion that someone else
can do the driving, we took the subway to Penn Station and the
train to Harrisburg. There, we were picked up by a van from Hershey
Lodge, where we had reservations. The service is included in a
two-day package that includes admission to Hersheypark, the
amusement park that chocolate built; the Hershey Museum, and the
Hershey Gardens. There is also a free shuttle bus to the
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Our very first impression that night was profoundly
disappointing: the air did not smell of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   But things picked up. Upon registering, Hershey Lodge gave each
of us a candy bar _ the classic milk chocolate slab _ with our room
key. The parking lot stop signs had Hershey Kisses on them, as did
each door. There was cocoa butter soap in the bathroom. On the
television was a channel devoted to the subject of our quest. The
first program was a history of chocolate, the next told about the
amusement park and its six roller coasters, while the third
conveyed the amazing tale of the Chocolate King, Milton Snavely
Hershey. In these magical environs, the founder's spirit rules, as
does his story.
</P>
<P>
   It Started With Caramel
</P>
<P>
   Hershey, as he is still called hereabouts a half century after
his death, landed a job in an ice cream parlor in nearby Lancaster
when he was 15, and found a home in the candy kitchen. Four years
later, he headed for Philadelphia to start a candy shop and failed.
He failed again in New York. This ability to bounce back was an
object lesson that I tried to point out to the boys.
</P>
<P>
   His creativity was another lesson, though cunning might be the
better word. Hershey returned to Pennsylvania and began to make
caramels. He did very, very well. In 1900, he sold his Lancaster
Caramel Company for $1 million but shrewdly reserved the right to
continue to sell chocolate. He had made the important observation
that children licked the chocolate off chocolate-covered caramels
and threw away the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stake everything on chocolate,'' he pronounced.
``Caramels are a fad. The chocolate market will be a permanent
one.''
</P>
<P>
   And he matter-of-factly proceeded to learn how to make milk
chocolate, then a luxury good produced in Switzerland. In no time
at all, he had built a factory, named the town Hershey and built a
trolley system to bring milk and workers to the factory. A
byproduct was a mass-transit system that stretched for miles.
</P>
<P>
   The factory churned out tons of chocolate at prices the average
Joe could afford. Success piled upon success. Kisses began to be
made in 1907, and Hershey's soon became the world's largest buyer
of almonds, for its Almond Joy bar.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hershey was bound and determined to make the town
itself a model of benevolence for company towns. Houses were not
made in cookie-cutter molds and were priced so workers could afford
them. Hershey Park (it didn't become Hersheypark until 1971) was
established in 1907 as a picnic ground for workers. There were free
band concerts, vaudeville and before long, a carousel. Other rides
were added almost every year.
</P>
<P>
   But almost from the beginning, the park was a tourist
destination. Hershey persuaded the Philadelphia &AMP; Reading Railroad
to build a spur to bring excursions there. And in the sort of mix
of business and recreation that has become the touchstone of
today's society, the cute little town with the Hershey smokestacks
became an advertising tool.
</P>
<P>
   For years, each candy bar contained postcards of Hershey. (Candy
bars were bigger once.) Moreover, the company offered window
displays of its namesake town to store owners all over the country
as a promotional device.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the big man busily created his own legends.
When he walked through Hershey Park, he would pick up even the
tiniest piece of litter _ unless, of course, it was a Hershey candy
bar wrapper. Those, he would turn over so the label could be read.
</P>
<P>
   When he built an elegant Mediterranean-inspired hotel, he made
the dining room circular, so nobody would have a corner table. He
had noticed that people who tipped modestly ended up in such
gastronomic ghettos.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hershey's mansion was not remote; it was across the street from
the chocolate factory. At the suggestion of his wife, Kitty, the
childless couple devoted almost all their personal fortune to
caring for orphans on farms surrounding Hershey, an initiative that
the family's foundation continues, although today's beneficiaries
are not necessarily parentless.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast and Dessert
</P>
<P>
   The infomercials ended. It was bedtime, particularly as the only
feasible alternative was clearly the Cartoon Network. It was then
we experienced our second disappointment: no York Peppermint Patty
on the pillow. I had sort of expected it.
</P>
<P>
   Upon waking up, we were thus especially eager to get to
breakfast in the lodge's Lebbie Lebkicher's Eatery and Pub, named
for a man who lent Hershey some money after one of his failures. It
is decorated with old posters for nickel-and-dime candy bars. The
waitress asked the boys whether they wanted chocolate milk or hot
chocolate. She gave them crayons in a tin candy container.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to eat more chocolate than you've ever eaten in
your life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I had coffee and four succulent chocolate muffins, but the
children ate healthily. To be sure, the waitress had point-blank
refused Guy's request to give them plates of whipped cream. A
Reese's Peanut Butter Cup, with a human inside, came by. Guy said,
``It's fun shaking your favorite candy's hand, right, Dad?''
</P>
<P>
   After grabbing a handful of free Hershey Kisses for the road, we
waited in front of Hershey Lodge for Suzanne's flute teacher, who
lives nearby and with whom she has kept up all these years. The
hotel is oriented to families and conventions, and had seemed more
our kind of place than the hilltop Hotel Hershey across town. This
was not just because it is cheaper, but because it also had
miniature golf, several swimming pools and a video arcade.
</P>
<P>
   A friendly crowd. There were lots of people in Nascar and
motorcycle T-shirts; a huge woman wearing an ``I'm a chocoholic''
tank top; a couple with triplet babies in a single stroller, and
people carrying five-foot-high stuffed animals they had obviously
won at the amusement park. Pointing to the prizes, Roy gasped,
``Those kids are talented, Mom.'' (He believed this deeply, it was
to emerge in tearful moments later on.)
</P>
<P>
   Youthful Memories
</P>
<P>
   But before visiting Hersheypark, we went for a ride with
Suzanne's teacher, Bish, and her husband, Karl. Suzanne's four
years in a nearby town, Cleona, seven miles down the road from
Hershey, was the longest she lived anywhere as a child. We saw her
high school and other required sights We also went to places to
sample fresh-made soft pretzels and Lebanon bologna.
</P>
<P>
   Most compellingly, we marveled at the chocolate factory, with
the giant logo Hershey Cocoa spelled out in shrubbery, as well as
the towering silos full of cocoa beans. We saw Hershey Hotel, with
the magnificent fountains and stone lions in the lobby, and the
stunning gardens outside. Reverently, we paused at the intersection
of Chocolate and Cocoa and whiffed the air wafting over from the
factory. Yes, Virginia, it smelled divinely of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   What was once the centerpiece of a Hershey visit, a factory
tour, has not been offered for years. Suzanne remembered seeing
huge vats of bubbling chocolate and savoring a chocolate milk on
factory tours of her youth. By the early 1970s, the tour was
drawing a million people a year, ultimately making it too crowded
for the workers.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was Hershey's Chocolate World, a Disney-like tour
of chocolate, with visitors riding automated cars. The attraction
has just been spruced up in honor of its 25th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   For the brief ride, about 10 or 12 minutes, one sees the world
from the perspective of a cocoa bean. From being cut with a machete
in an unidentified rain forest, you are shipped in containers to
the Pennsylvania promised land for roasting, milling, refining and
any number of other things. A Donald Duck-sounding voice provides
commentary. The cars never stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``So cool, man,'' Roy intoned as we went through the roaster
oven where the enveloping odor was you-know-what. The Hershey's
Kiss machine would have been anti-climactic, had it not been so
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   The final message, from an eminently sincere recorded voice,
was: ``No matter where you go, no matter how far, you're always
near a Hershey's Bar.'' As if to prove it, you are then given a
free candy bar before exiting into a really big gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, you pass an expansive wall plaque with a lot of
names on little gold sheets. It is labeled the Hall of Fame of the
National Confectionary Salesmen's Association. That seemed
intriguing. Who were these men prowling the highways and byways of
America to bring chocolate to those in need? I'll never know,
because Roy and Guy had made a beeline for the gift shop. We raced
to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the shop was the giant made-to-order candy bars
they were selling that you could put any message on: ``Thanks for
watching the house,'' was the suggested one. I briefly thought of
provocative inscriptions I might have written to that long-ago
girlfriend, when my attention was suddenly seized by a toddler
stumbling by in a daze. ``Chocolaty, chocolaty,'' he kept
repeating.
</P>
<P>
   The Early Factory Days
</P>
<P>
   We each had a hot fudge sundae at an ice cream stand near the
gift shop. Then it was a short walk on to Hershey Museum, mostly an
eclectic collection of things Hershey picked up here and there _ an
American Indian section, Pennsylvania Dutch furniture, artifacts of
Victorian America and lots on the history of the Hershey family,
town and business. The Hershey stuff was best.
</P>
<P>
   Roy loved the re-creation of the factory locker room, where he
put on the chocolate-brown uniform of a worker and punched a time
clock. In the Discovery Room, the boys time-traveled to the 1800s
and pretended to buy things at a general store and cook on a wood
stove. What they liked best was playing checkers, a game that has
not changed. Parents sit on chairs at the edge of the room as
spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Intriguingly, a small exhibition hinted that things were not
always simple and easy, even in the world's sweetest town. In 1937,
there was a pretty brutal sitdown strike, the result of workers'
discontent with wages and an organizing campaign by the Council of
Industrial Organizations. The strikers shut down the plant and
barricaded themselves inside. Workers loyal to Hershey, local dairy
farmers and the American Legion fought with the strikers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, neither the Council nor a company union got
bargaining rights. Hershey promised not to discriminate against any
participants. Chocolate town returned to cozy comfort.
</P>
<P>
   One wondered, though. One object in the display case, with no
accompanying explanation, riveted my attention: a wooden club with
a leather strap. And according to another exhibition at the museum,
life on the world's sweetest assembly line was relentlessly
demanding piecework. Payment on the ``Kiss line'' was a dime for 20
dozen Kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Shake-ups
</P>
<P>
   The time for Hersheypark had come. Suzanne and I have kind of an
ambivalent feeling about amusement parks. It might be because
neither of us much likes spinning out of control at high altitudes.
Or it might be an aversion to seeing the rubes, particularly
ourselves, fleeced on the Midway. What we like about amusement
parks is the atmosphere, somehow nostalgic and challenging at the
same time. We like Coney Island. Sometimes we think we should take
the boys to Disneyworld, but we've never quite gotten around to it.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering, we were measured to determine which rides we
could handle. Roy was tall enough to be a ``Twizzler,'' a Hershey's
candy that, alarmingly, contains no chocolate. That meant he could
ride almost anything. Guy was a Hershey Bar, which barred him from
a ride or two. Suzanne was ``Cookies `N' Creme.'' At 6 feet 3
inches, I was waved through.
</P>
<P>
   We began bravely enough by marching straight to the Comet, the
biggest roller coaster in the United States when it opened in 1946.
We waited in line for about 45 minutes, which is standard for most
of the big rides on the weekend. I rode with Roy. We screamed and
complained and promised to ride each of the park's other five
coasters, then somehow forgot to get around to it.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne and Guy found the experience sinister. She made Guy
close his eyes throughout the ride. She feared she was going to fly
out of the car, and sank so deeply into her seat her knees and back
hurt. She said it was awful. Guy let it be known that his teddy
bear (and alter ego), who had just been named Teddy Fudge in honor
of our expedition, would ride no more roller coasters. That meant
Guy wouldn't either.
</P>
<P>
   We soon found ourselves absorbed in the fantasy world of the
park. We drank big lemonades, lots of them, and ate popcorn and
cotton candy and funnel cake. Roy and I did a really great water
slide, Pistol Pete's Plunge, and also Tidal Force, a ride in which
you slowly climb a 100-foot hill in a 20-passenger boat, then shoot
down at a 43-degree angle to hit the water with an enormous splash.
The boys and I loved yet a third water ride, Canyon River Rapids,
which gives the experience of white-water rafting. But on a hot
afternoon, we had to wait for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne and Guy tackled the Rodeo, an innocuous enough looking
ride compared with all the killer coasters _ particularly the new
Great Bear, on which riders sit in ski chairs with their feet
dangling down through 60-mile-an-hour corkscrew turns and
360-degree loops. But she was white as a sheet after revolving and
rotating, at the same time, on the Rodeo. Roy studied the map and
said, ``I've got a good ride for Mom _ the bathroom or the
telephone booth.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went, through two sunny days and one neon-seared night.
Fear, laughter and time moving at a little different speed. A
spectacular antique carousel went round and round and round. The
boys cried bitterly after unsuccessful tries at tossing balls in
milk cans and other Midway games, but were thrilled to win stuffed
animals when a barker could not guess either of their weights.
</P>
<P>
   They frolicked in the misting sprinklers the park has placed at
strategic locations. They laughed a little too loudly when a
toddler threw up his Twizzlers. At ZooAmerica, which began with
Hershey's personal animal collection and is included with admission
to the park, we walked on a bridge to a quieter, wooded world. The
animals are exclusively North American. We liked the bears.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what to think? The experience is wholly commercial,
with every feature linked to promoting the Hershey image, or
occasionally other corporate sponsors who have rented space. What
is known as ``the sweetest parade on earth'' consists of 14
characters, each a trademarked Hershey's product, marching
triumphantly through the park shortly before dark. Having your
picture taken with one or another candy bar is one of everyone's
favorite activities.
</P>
<P>
   Well, why not? For better or worse, Hershey in this very place
made chocolate accessible to the masses. By definition, chocolate
is happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we ate too much chocolate,'' Guy mumbled as we were
leaving, a Hershey's Kiss firmly in his mouth. ``But this  &UR; is &LR;  a
special chocolate place.''
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEY LODGE, West Chocolate Avenue and University Drive, (800)
533-3131. Open year round. Nightly rates start at $89 a person for
adults, based on double occupancy, during the summer season. Room
rates vary significantly according to season and specific package.
Call for details and reservations.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL HERSHEY, Hotel Road, (800) 533-3131. Open year round.
Nightly rates start at $129 a person for adults, based on double
occupancy during the summer season. Room rates vary significantly
according to season and specific package. Call for details and
reservations. Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   LEBBIE LEBKICHER'S EATERY AND PUB, at Hershey Lodge, West
Chocolate Avenue and University Drive, (717) 533-3311. Open daily:
7 to 11 a.m. for breakfast, 11:30 a.m. to 11 p.m. for lunch and
dinner. All major credit cards accepted. Attractions
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEYPARK, (800) 437-7439. Hours: through Sunday, 10 a.m. to
11 p.m.; Monday through Labor Day, Mondays through Thursdays 10
a.m. to 8 p.m., Fridays through Sundays 10 a.m. to 10 p.m.; Sept. 8
to 20, open Saturdays 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. and Sundays 10 a.m. to 8
p.m.. Park closed after Sept. 20 until the spring of 1999.
Admission: $29.95, ages 9 to 54; $16.95. ages 3 to 8 or 55 and
older; $18.95 for consecutive day (keep previous day's ticket
stub); $15.95 late-day admission (call for specific hours); free
for children 2 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEY'S CHOCOLATE WORLD, Park Boulevard, (717) 534-4900.
Hours: 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. daily; 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. on Labor Day; after
Labor Day, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. usually, but hours can vary and
visitors should call. Free.
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEY MUSEUM, 170 West Hersheypark Drive, (717) 534-3439.
Hours: 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily through Labor Day; after Labor Day,
10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $5; $4.50 for the elderly; $2.50 for
ages 3 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEY GARDENS, Hotel Road (across from Hotel Hershey), (717)
534-3492. Hours: 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily; to 8 p.m. on Fridays and
Saturdays before Labor Day. Admission: $5; $4.25 for those 62 and
over; $2.50 for ages 3 to 15; members and children under 3, free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
