<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OUTDOOR-SCULPTURE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ART, TOO, A SUMMER IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No one can say that New York is outdoor
sculpture-challenged. If you travel around the city in summer, in
addition to the time-honored monuments that appear at every turn,
you will find many a newish work or works ensconced on temporarily
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The run this year is from celebrated talents like Auguste Rodin
and Tony Smith to a single quirky placement by the English sculptor
Rachel Whiteread in SoHo; from a playful show in the courtyard of
PS 1 in Queens to a more conventional convocation at Long Island
University's Brooklyn campus.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some suggestions of what to look for:
</P>
<P>
   One of the hardiest of the perennial outdoor shows flourishes at
Socrates Sculpture Park, a foolproof location on the East River in
Long Island City, Queens, where younger, less-established artists
are given room and support to flex their talents. ``Escape
Velocity'' is the title of the current offering, with 13 new works
planted around the park's refreshingly unmanicured four and a half
acres.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most site-responsive is Alissa Neglia's ``Lace,'' a
huge, ragged screen made from thousands of steel washers suspended
between two posts. Through it you get a dreamy glimpse of the
Manhattan skyline as if seen through a wall of frothy water.
</P>
<P>
   Also aimed at the opposite shore is Robert Hickman's ``Roosevelt
Island Shuttle,'' a frisky parody of the East River funicular. A
plain old wooden chair, mounted on an inclined rail supported by a
wooden trestle equipped with a dummy propulsion lever, it could
theoretically zoom its rider clear across the river (fortunately,
the lever is permanently braked).
</P>
<P>
   Other attention-getters include Bob Seng's ``Lost Hills,'' a
festive mounding of the fence around the park with streams and
rivers of multicolored materials; Wendy Klemperer's ``Fallen
Horse,'' a big steel skeleton of an upended steed, looming
vertically like a tower; Christopher Lesnewski's ``Bootleg,'' a
sardonic air-traffic control center ingeniously wrought of junk
parts, and Christine Koch's ``Cosmic Bosom,'' an open geometric
structure 30 feet high from whose apex dangles a cluster of bosomy,
phallic shapes unexpectedly fashioned of marble.
</P>
<P>
   An even more dramatic river site than Socrates is the
Empire-Fulton Ferry State Park, a hospitable patch of lawn and
trees strikingly situated on the Brooklyn waterfront between the
Brooklyn and Manhattan Bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The show, ``Between the Bridges,'' sponsored annually since 1981
by the New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic
Preservation, is organized by the Brooklyn Artists Waterfront
Coalition, a loose-knit group that invites participation from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The startling closeness of the bridges and the riveting skyline
have had their effects on several pieces in this hodgepodge of a
show. Among them are Daniel Bergman's ``East River,'' a tensile
structure of wood posts braced by steel pipes and strung with a
geometric web of cables that echoes the complex rigging of the
Brooklyn Bridge, and Wendy Carroll's delicate ``Energy River
Harvest,'' a long line of reedy-looking rods plugged vertically
into the riverfront bulkhead.
</P>
<P>
   The parklike aspects of the site are picked up by Lorraine
Walsh's ``Driver Ants,'' a steel picnic table whose zinc surface is
etched with images of marching ants, and Andi Kovel's ``Where Never
Is Heard a Discouraging Word,'' four topiary toadstool shapes
covered with grass.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth regarding are Sandra Salisbury's ``Dead City 3-D,'' a
cluster of small wooden houses translated from several paintings by
Egon Schiele; Matt Burke's ``Anger and Food,'' an interactive
complexity of three giant wooden spools that, when cranked, slowly
rotate to produce written messages, and Henner Kuckkuck's ``Gate,''
a powerful vertical composition of closely nested abstract steel
elements painted black. The site enhances all. Long Island
University
</P>
<P>
   A smaller show in a much more formal setting is the seventh
annual outdoor display organized by the Sculpture Center, a
nonprofit alternative gallery, at the Brooklyn campus of Long
Island University. Works by six artists are deployed around a
pleasant quadrangle near the main gate, cloistered from the clatter
of traffic on flanking Flatbush Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting idea here, although not the best executed,
is Heidi Schlatter's ``Interior No. 1, 2, 3, 4,'' four huge
blow-ups of tacky motel innards, each installed at ground-floor
level in an exterior niche of a prosaic brick building.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed from a middle distance, the images seem part of the
building's structure, creating the illusion that you are looking
into actual rooms. But they are skewed, perspectively and
otherwise, in relation to the building's dull facade.
</P>
<P>
   A more conventional but well-wrought sculpture is Arthur Weyhe's
``Untitled,'' a tall structure that suggests a skeletal wigwam
turned upside down. Five wooden spokes angle outward around a
vertical center pole, all painted bright red, all braced by steel
cables at the top and steel clamps at the bottom. The work has a
tidy, industrial look that doesn't belie its whimsicality.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Emily Feinstein's ``Gathering,'' an assemblage of mini-size,
Minimal-looking benches of raw wood, seems to imply a Shaker
meeting in which the benches themselves are the congregation, and
Jan Baracz's ``Shelter,'' a spare cubicle of yellow-painted wood
that is both a room and a passageway, nicely plays against the
glass and steel formality of the institutional edifices.
</P>
<P>
   Rising above the generation gap, Gelatin, a frolicsome group of
four Vienna-based performance artists, has turned the new ``outdoor
galleries'' (really an extended courtyard) of PS 1 Contemporary Art
Center into a loony romp-for-everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions include a 25-foot walk-up tower made of discarded
furniture parts, a giant blue inflated teddy bear in perpetual
motion that looks like a refugee from the Macy's Thanksgiving Day
parade, and a ``refrigerator room'' of old iceboxes that makes a
summer day into an Arctic experience.
</P>
<P>
   Among other pleasures, you can also bask on a multilevel,
Mylar-covered sunbathing platform, disport in a sprinklered pool
with lots of inflatable toys, or take a sauna in a ``heating room''
made of corrugated tin.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Gelatin environment _ which also serves as a
setting for ``Warm Up,'' PS 1's disk jockey fests on summer
Saturday afternoons _ is more of a play than a sculptural
experience, the group should not be regarded too lightly.
Collectively, it has animation, city planning and stage design
credentials, and is apparently beloved in its native Austria. Take
the kiddies.
</P>
<P>
   It looks almost as playful as Gelatin's environment, but ``Under
the Sun: An Outdoor Exhibition of Light'' at the Cooper-Hewitt
National Design Museum has a somewhat more scientific motive: to
show the potential of solar energy.
</P>
<P>
   Several quirky-looking structures, each especially designed to
draw its working power from the sun, occupy the museum's handsome
garden. The most sculptural is the ``Solar Powered Tensile
Pavilion,'' a translucent tarpaulin 32 feet high and rigged like a
tent. Its fabric is bonded with thin devices that collect enough
solar output to power the mast lights. Easily taken apart, rolled
and relocated, the pavilion is designed as a movable shelter.
</P>
<P>
   But its taut, soaring presence is beautiful in itself; and
what's more, the structure acts as a sundial, casting a revolving
shadow that shows the time of day by pointing to markers on the
lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Another kind of sundial is made by a circle of 12 odd-looking
but quite sittable garden chairs, set in a circle on the lawn. They
are fitted out with solar-powered lights that signal seconds,
minutes and hours, and overhead canopies that can provide night
illumination.
</P>
<P>
   A third work is also a pavilion, a more modest-looking structure
of three eight-foot glass cubes. From solar energy, the cubes
generate electricity to run their own ventilation and lighting
systems. The works were designed by the architects Nicholas
Goldsmith and Gregory Kiss. Children might like this one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Small outdoor shows of two past masters, one of the 19th
century, the other of the 20th, are both projects of the Public Art
Fund, and appropriately, they've been given prime public spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Stroll along Rockefeller Center's Channel Gardens, the
flower-and-fountain lined promenade from Fifth Avenue to the
Skating Rink, and you'll encounter eight works by Auguste Rodin
(1840-1917).
</P>
<P>
   The formal site fits. Such familiars as ``The Thinker'' (1880)
and ``The Three Shades'' (1880), both deriving from Rodin's
unfinished monumental door ``The Gate of Hell,'' are here, along
with head and figure studies for ``The Burghers of
Calais''(1884-88).
</P>
<P>
   But there are others less well known, including the armless,
almost Cubistically distorted woman's figure, ``Meditation''
(1884-85), part of a monument to Victor Hugo, and _ in honor of the
painter James McNeill Whistler _ ``Whistler's Muse'' (1906),
portraying not his mother but an athletic nude Venus climbing the
mountain of fame.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptures were lent by the Iris and B. Gerald Cantor
Foundation, and they give a touch of class to the promenade, facing
as they do Paul Manship's stylized rendition of Prometheus covered
with glitzy gold leaf that serves as backdrop for the skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   The emotive realism of Rodin is a long way from the cool
Minimalist geometrics of Tony Smith (1912-1980), whose work is
fully explored in ``Tony Smith: Architect, Painter, Sculptor,'' a
current show at the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern's garden has been emptied and restocked with Smiths
for the show's duration. The museum has also collaborated with the
Public Art Fund in placing three large-scale sculptures elsewhere
in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light-Up!'' (1971), at the Seagram Plaza, is a big polyhedron
painted bright yellow _ one of Smith's few chromatic sculptures.
Like most of his work, it reveals its complexities as you make your
way around it, but can never quite be seen as a whole. Vaguely
suggestive of a striding man, it has an open center that can be
walked through, in effect making a sportive entranceway to the prim
Seagram building.
</P>
<P>
   On the Doris C. Freedman Plaza, at the 60th Street entrance to
Central Park, sits ``Cigarette'' (1961), a sprawlier polyhedron
that also has a gateway effect, framing the archway that is the
``Scholar's Gate'' entrance to the park.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Quite different from these is ``Smug'' (1973), a ground-hugging
open-work structure of painted black steel whose mini-polyhedrons
are arranged in a repetitive overall pattern. Hunkered down on the
stair landing of the Avenue of the Americas entrance to Bryant
Park, behind the New York Public Library, it suggests a giant
tarantula waiting to spring.
</P>
<P>
   You have to look up to see Rachel Whiteread's ``Water Tower,''
perched on a SoHo roof. Cast in translucent resin from the interior
of an actual wooden water tank, it stands on its own steel frame
between two functional tanks, a ghostly maverick among them and the
thousands of other tanks that are a classic part of New York's
skyline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water Tower'' _ best seen from the southwest corner of West
Broadway and Grand _ can be distinguished by its refined, glowing
whiteness against the coarse brown exteriors of its siblings. Its
monolithic form, with three-inch walls, owes its shape to a
sacrificed East Side water tank.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Whiteread, a native of England, is noted for exploring the
sculptural possibilities of everyday objects. At first she did
mattresses, chairs, tables; then, in 1993, she made a cast of an
entire East London row house.
</P>
<P>
   The resin water tower, done as a commission from the Public Art
Fund, occurred to her on one of many walks around the city
searching for a sculptural motif. What a challenge the Chrysler
Building would be!
</P>
<P>
   A pair of engagement rings, three stories high with lighted
``diamonds,'' is Dennis Oppenheim's contribution to the city's
sculpture-scape. Right across from the Flatiron Building in
Manhattan, he has set up two skinny steel hoops embedded in
concrete, each precariously topped by a glass cabin whose -steepled
roof mimics the facets of a diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Each cabin is supported by a fragile galvanized steel structure
meant to evoke a Tiffany setting. Lighted up at night, they
simulate the glow and twinkle of high-carat stones.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheim, a Conceptual artist known recently for his jokey
installations on architectural and body themes _ among others _
achieved a larger balancing act last year with ``Device to Root Out
Evil,'' a mammoth work shown at the Venice Biennale.
</P>
<P>
   In it, red Venetian glass formed the roof shingles of an upended
country church, its steeple stuck at an ominous angle into the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Whiteread, he seems to enjoy milking familiar forms for
sculptural possibilities. The solid old Flatiron Building should
give him a few new ideas. Robert Moses Garden
</P>
<P>
   One of the least-known mini-parks in Manhattan, the well-kempt
Robert Moses Sculpture Garden lies a flight above street level
right across from the southern end of Lincoln Center. A fine spot
to read and relax, its serenity has often been disturbed by
horrific sculpture shows.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to report, then, that David Boyajian's current
exhibition of 10 large-scale pieces, based on plant forms, rises
well above the usual dross.
</P>
<P>
   Made of mild steel whose skin forms a mellow rust, his
semi-abstract seed and bud shapes rest on columnar stems, the whole
expressing a stage of plant growth. The most impressive work is
``The Peach,'' a balancing act of volumetric half- and
quarter-circle forms perched atop a triangular shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative is the word for these works, but they are real
sculptures, a welcome change.
</P>
<P>
   Walking in TriBeCa, you may suddenly come across Bill Barrett's
nine-foot-tall bronze sculpture ``Abstract Memories,'' which sits
quietly on a traffic island. A gestural work related to Abstract
Expressionism, its twisted, curving forms, part linear, part
fleshily biomorphic, suggesting both plant shapes and parts of the
human body, play happily off each other.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Nardin Gallery, Barrett's dealer, it is kind of
an old-fashioned notion to encounter on a TriBeCa street, but in
Barrett's hands, nostalgia works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     08-20 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALSA'S WOULD-BE SABADO NIGHT FEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randa Haines' likable mess of a movie ``Dance With Me'' wants so
desperately to be the ``Saturday Night Fever'' of salsa that you
can feel it huffing and puffing and straining its Achilles tendons
to try to detonate the same mixture of sex, alienation and
terpsichorean transcendence as the 1977 blockbuster that launched
John Travolta into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   But despite plenty of smoke and fire, the big liftoff never
arrives, and the climactic dance-contest sequence is a botched
fizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Aspiring to fill the shoes of the young John Travolta is
Chayanne, a handsome, charismatic Puerto Rican pop singer and soap
opera star who is the epitome of a tenderhearted, smoldering-eyed
Latin American hunk.
</P>
<P>
   Chayanne plays Rafael Infante, an ambitious young Cuban who
moves to Houston after the death of his mother to work as a
handyman at a dance studio owned by an American named John Burnett
(Kris Kristofferson).
</P>
<P>
   John was a friend of Rafael's mother from the days when they
danced together on a cruise ship. A gruff, cynical loner who is
considering selling his studio and spending the rest of his life
fishing in the Gulf of Mexico, John may or may not be Rafael's
biological father.
</P>
<P>
   The question of paternity and the ambivalent bond between the
two men is one of several themes the movie bungles terribly in its
rush to cover too many dramatic bases too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The film's happiest surprise is the uninhibited performance of
Vanessa L. Williams as Ruby, a dance studio teacher and single
mother with whom Chayanne becomes instantly smitten. Ms. Williams,
who usually appears bland and buttoned-up in her films, explodes
joyously to life in the scenes in which Chayanne and Ruby tear up
the floor at a local salsa club.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams happens to be a superb dancer who consistently
eclipses her co-star in versatility, grace and joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   Chayanne is good at hoisting partners over his head, but as a
less balletic ballroom dancer he seems terminally earthbound. He
lacks the airy hauteur and kineticism of a human missile about to
take off that performers as diverse as Fred Astaire, Michael
Jackson, John Travolta and Patrick Swayze have brought to their
dancing roles.
</P>
<P>
   The movie insists that Rafael's untutored salsa dancing is
superior to Ruby's more elegant studio technique because it is more
``authentic,'' but the visual evidence suggests the opposite. Ruby
proves to be a much bigger influence on Rafael than he on her.
</P>
<P>
   And in the final dance contest sequence, set in Las Vegas, so
many different Latin dance styles are thrown together in such rapid
succession that any point the movie wanted to make about the rising
importance of salsa is dissipated in a confusingly edited,
suspense-free jumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance With Me'' lacks the fluent, aloft-on-tiptoes momentum
that a dance-oriented movie must have in order to sustain a mood of
airy dreaminess. The dance sequences are awkwardly shoehorned into
personal stories that are too tentative and lackadaisically
developed to accumulate much weight.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby and Rafael are both adrift in the world. She is an Army
brat bringing up a young son who, like Rafael, is illegitimate.
While Ruby is agonizing over whether or not to reunite with an
abusive former partner with whom she stands a chance of winning
championship dance contests. Rafael is brooding about his
paternity, his future and whether or not he should return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The movie isn't helped by a wooden performance from
Kristofferson who squints so much he seems barely to be making eye
contact with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Dance With Me'' disappoints on almost every level, it
still leaves you mildly elated, and its rich, percolating
soundtrack touches on a wide range of Latin American pop styles,
with Ruben Blades' song ``Patria'' a particular high point.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   DANCE WITH ME
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Dance With Me'' is rated PG (Parental guidance
suggested). It has sexual situations and strong language.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Randa Haines; written by Daryl Matthews; director of
photography, Fred Murphy; edited by Lisa Fruchtman; music by
Michael Convertino; choreography by Matthews and Liz Curtis;
production designer, Waldemar Kalinowski; produced by Lauren C.
Weissman, Shinya Egawa and Ms. Haines; released by Columbia
Pictures Running time: 126 minutes. This film is rated PG.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Vanessa Williams (Ruby), Chayanne (Rafael), Kris
Kristofferson (John) and Joan Plowright (Bea).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
