<HEADER>
A3947 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAFILMS-SAVANNAH-COX     08-20 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAFILMS-SAVANNAH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savannah savoring its box of chocolates
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. Folks in neighboring South Carolina love to point
out that 85 percent of ``Forrest Gump'' was filmed in their state,
vs. only one really key scene here.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Because it's that Savannah scene, where Forrest (Tom
Hanks) watches the world go by from a park bench, that everyone
really remembers.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes in this coastal city so memorably dripping with
Spanish moss, cobblestoned squares and quirky characters that
filmmakers almost seem incapable of staying away. The credit list
here includes such mid-'70s schlock thrillers as ``Gator'' and
``Squirm,'' but the real glory days of Savannah moviemaking began
around 1989, when _ what else? _ the Oscar-winning ``Glory'' was
filmed in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, two big-studio features, ``The Gingerbread Man'' and
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' were shot here. This
summer, two more _ ``The General's Daughter'' and ``Forces of
Nature'' _ are filming in the city at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes things a bit crowded in a place with 136,000
people and a layout that has to be considered unfriendly to
wide-turning movie production trucks. Many industry observers say
Savannah's stardom is largely attributable to its unique look _ as
compared with, say, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Savannah Film Office says that's true _ but
only to a certain extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be a lot of different things,'' said Jay Self, pointing
out that ``The Gingerbread Man'' was originally set in Memphis,
which looks quite different from Savannah. ``In `Wild America,' we
played Texas, Louisiana and Arkansas, and in `Forces of Nature,'
we're being any number of places between New York and Savannah.''
</P>
<P>
   But much like Forrest's box of chocolates, you never quite know
what you're going to get when a movie sets up shop in your small,
self-absorbed city. The success of ``Forrest Gump'' was a
double-edged sword for Savannah, said Self, with one faction of
residents thrilled by the economic impact it created via crew
spending and increased tourism, and another unhappy with the way
the film company seemed to ``roll over people in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of arguing about it ad nauseam, Savannah in 1995 used
$100,000 from the city's general fund to open the one-staffer film
office.
</P>
<P>
   Both Self and Georgia Film &AMP; Videotape Office director Greg
Torre say their offices have an excellent working relationship _
even exhibiting together at some large industry trade shows.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's hard to argue with the success of a small city
that has its own film commission and which estimates that its 1998
moviemaking take will be $18 million to $20 million (compared with
$17 million in 1997 and $10 million in 1996.)
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves one to wonder: Can they ever make too many movies
in Savannah?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much pushed to our limit with two movies in town
now,'' Self admitted. ``We couldn't handle a third.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGIA-FILMS-COX     08-20 1891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-FILMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Film industry's team spirit helps revive glory days
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Savannah, Georgia, John Travolta and Ben Affleck are deep
into filming competing big-budget flicks for equally big-name
(Paramount, DreamWorks) studios. The feature film ``False River''
recently completed principal photography everywhere from Conyers to
Porterdale, and another TV movie, this one for TNT, has just signed
on to film in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, production is about to begin on a Disney
made-for-TV movie about the civil rights march on Selma, Ala.
Cicely Tyson, Blair Underwood and Queen Latifah are already filming
``Mama Flora's Family,'' a CBS mini-
</P>
<P>
   series based on the book by Alex Haley (``Roots'').
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, good times are here again for Georgia's film industry,
which flourished in the early '90s, then slumped for a number of
reasons _ some of them self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Now, says an older and wiser Georgia film community, it knows
what has to be done to restore the state as one of the primary
places for moviemaking outside Los Angeles or New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had some growing pains,'' admitted Greg Torre, director
of the Georgia Film &AMP; Videotape Office. ``People were coming to us
for the longest time. Now, the whole thing is about us becoming
more proactive.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of urgency has almost nothing to do with a desire to
gawk at the likes of the white-hot Travolta. It has nearly
everything to do with cold, hard cash. Since 1973, the state
Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism calculates that feature
movie and TV production has brought nearly $2.5 billion into
Georgia _ an estimated $247 million in 1997 alone.
</P>
<P>
   And just up Interstate 85, movies, TV and commercials pumped an
eye-popping $329 million into North Carolina's coffers last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was not a really good year for us,'' said Bill
Arnold, director of the North Carolina Film Office. ``In 1996, we
made 53 films here and $440 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia cannot afford to sit back and wait to field offers from
studios. Not when Canada's weakened dollar buys so much more for
Hollywood productions that set up shop there, or when North
Carolina goes to the Cannes Film Festival to sell the idea of using
its moving picture-perfect settings and experienced crew base. And
not when you consider how South Carolina whipped into action a few
years ago when it was learned that Barbra Streisand was seriously
considering shooting ``The Prince of Tides'' _ a book set in and
written by South Carolina resident Pat Conroy _ in, of all places,
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Streisand needed three sound stages, so Beaufort-area leaders
decided to empty out all the surplus goods stored in a county
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local technical college made its gymnasium available,''
recalled state film office manager Isabel Hill, who also helped
facilitate Streisand's request to meet with Conroy. ``Then we went
to the National Guard and they agreed to reroute their weekend
training (to another facility) elsewhere in South Carolina through
the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was back in the early 1990s, when many of the
approximately 350 film commissions now vying for projects worldwide
didn't yet exist. The message hasn't been lost of late on Georgia's
film industry, where signs abound that they mean business when it
comes to increasing the state's film business.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Atlanta Production Partnership: Formed some 18 months
ago, this loose coalition of some 30 Georgia filmmaking entities
ranging from casting agents to lighting experts, meets monthly to
share information and strategize about bringing more projects to
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that Georgia had had a competitive advantage that
was being eroded by other states developing their own equipment,
crew and production bases,'' said Partnership founder Steve Mensch,
who runs the Atlanta office of Feature Systems, a movie equipment
rental company. ``Let's say we hear a production is coming here to
scout (as a possible filming site). We can pull together a
Partnership meeting and build a consensus that we'll do a job and
make it happen. As far as I know, that's unique to us here.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Go West: For a long time, the movie business found Georgia.
Now with neighboring states, and places as far away as Canada,
proving much stiffer competition, Torre said, ``We're asking
ourselves, `What are ways that we can better market ourselves?'''
</P>
<P>
   One major response: The state film office recently awarded a
one-year consulting contract to Shay Bentley-Griffin, who'll
promote Georgia filmmaking directly to the decisionmakers in such
industry epicenters as Los Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``This truly was a brainchild of the (Atlanta Production
Partnership),'' said Bentley-Griffin, whose contacts in the
filmmaking industry go back to 1980, when she started out
representing performers. ``The group began to say, `We as an
industry have to find a way to come up with something that really
comes up with selling our strengths. And we also have to have a
body to get on plane and go to L.A. and talk at people!''
</P>
<P>
   -- Go Web: For years, the state film office has attended
festivals and trade shows _ ranging from the humongous ShowBiz Expo
West in L.A. to smaller events, like South-by-Southwest, which
Torre says provide ``a chance to meet up-and-coming directors and
producers'' who might film in Georgia someday.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop, cyberspace. South Carolina's film office has a
Website _ indeed, a mere click of the mouse calls up everything
from photos of suitable-for-filming Charleston slave cabins to the
time of sunset in Sumter in September _ so why not Georgia? While
the film office already has an Internet presence _ on the Industry,
Trade and Tourism department site (www.georgia.org) and a group
site for all Southern states (www.telefilm-south.com), Torre says
work is under way on developing a dedicated site capable of
transmitting location photos and information worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   -- What union problems?: Even the mere hint of union activity
can scare away some movie production companies, a message much of
Georgia's film community seems to have heard loud and clear. Both
Hilary Henkin, who represents the IATSE Local 479 of studio
mechanics here, and International Brotherhood of Teamsters' Local
728 secretary-treasurer Richard Black attend Production Partnership
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   And the spirit of cooperation hardly ends there. IATSE's
Southern locals recently developed a contract that allows
low-budget ($750,000 to $3 million), independent features to keep
upfront costs down in return for ``backend'' deals, Henkin said.
Meanwhile, a recent innovation allowing movie production
coordinators to decide which Teamsters will work on their sets
appears to be working out to everyone's benefit, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our (members) are looking for every opportunity to please the
coordinators so they'll work again,'' said Black, who also attended
Location Expo and ShowBiz West. ``I met a lot of producers there
who said they were hearing better things about the situation
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for such intensive soul-searching and strategizing
scarcely would have been imaginable back in the early 1990s, when
Georgia's film industry was literally laughing all the way to the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many movies being made here that a little joke
got started _ `I'd hate to be the fourth film shooting in
Atlanta,''' recalled Dawn Fields, an independent producer and
publisher of ``Back to One,'' a local film magazine. ``There were
only so much crew and resources to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   Now flash forward to the middle of this decade and an industry
that had been stagnant _ if not in actual decline _ for several
years. The half-dozen major feature films shot here in 1997
(``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' ``Scream 2,'' ``The
Gingerbread Man''), while an encouraging development, did little to
ease the minds of a film community haunted by memories of 1995 and
'96, when a total of three features were filmed in Georgia. And it
only began to approach the glory days of the early '90s _ in 1990,
seven TV movies and eight features were shot in Georgia, while 1991
saw a whopping 10 TV movies, four TV series and six features filmed
around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Observers point to myriad reasons for the drop-off in
moviemaking here, not the least of them being the more favorable
exchange rate and tax incentives available in Canada. Closer to
home, they say, North Carolina offers highly competitive prices and
a large studio complex built in Wilmington in the early 1980s by
producer Dino DeLaurentiis.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was the situation helped by a perception of union activity
here several years ago _ a perception many admit had some basis in
reality, although they say the situation was never as bad as
Hollywood feared.
</P>
<P>
   And what's a state to do when its looks seemingly go out of
style?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trendy for awhile,'' said Henkin, who points to a
spate of ``rural Southern movies'' from ``Driving Miss Daisy''
(1989) to ``Fried Green Tomatoes'' (1991) filmed here. ``To a
certain extent, that group of film fell out of trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet many here place the blame at least partially on Georgia's
film industry itself, for not noticing warning signs of decline
soon enough _ or coming up with a coordinated plan for combating
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of us in our own special areas marketed ourselves, which
we should have done,'' said Bentley-Griffin, the longtime
Atlanta-based casting agent who's worked on Georgia productions
ranging from ``Glory'' and ``Fried Green Tomatoes'' to ``Forces of
Nature'' and ``The General's Daughter,'' currently filming in
Savannah. ``As we got better, we didn't do much as a community.''
</P>
<P>
   But all that is changing now. Besides forming coalitions such as
the Production Partnership, the state's various film entities have
begun making a show of strength _ together _ at some of the
industry's largest events. For instance, the state film office has
long sent representatives to Location Expo, a mammoth trade show
that _ as the name suggests _ helps production companies big and
small learn about potential shooting sites. Yet for the first time
this year, their booth was flanked on either side by
representatives of the Savannah Film Office and the Atlanta
Production Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would talk to us about specific (Atlanta) locations, but
if there was something else they needed, I could steer them to the
Georgia booth or Savannah's,'' explained Henkin, who was in the
Production Partnership's booth. ``It sounds kind of trite, but when
the work comes in here, everyone wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. In the sort of ironically happy ending that usually only
happens in movies, Torre a few weeks ago revealed that Georgia was
very close to landing yet another major TV film.
</P>
<P>
   And what, exactly, had kept the producers from signing on the
dotted line so far?
</P>
<P>
   ``Their concern is, is there enough crew base here to service
them, what with all the other projects we've got going on,'' Torre
said, the grin on his face suggesting that this was the sort of
problem he liked dealing with. ``We're trying to convince them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
