(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
DANCE-MOVIE (Los Angeles) _ ``Dance With Me'' may be another movie
about dancing all your troubles away. But there's a lot at stake
for its principle talents. It's the first movie to showcase Vanessa
L. Williams' considerable dancing ability. Her co-star, Puerto
Rican singing sensation Chayanne, makes his English-speaking debut
in the film. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
ANIFEST-FILM (Los Angeles) _ The low-down on Anifest '98, a
colorful, hands-on exhibition of the animation industry that is as
individual as the people who draw and create the characters. By Bob
McCarthy. 
. 
BLADE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Blade, the title hero of Wesley
Snipes' gory new action movie, is a more living than dead member of
the living dead. His mother was bitten and infected by a vampire
shortly before giving him birth, and he's devoted his superpowered
existence to ridding the Earth of the bloodsucking scum. By Bob
Strauss. 
. 
WONDER-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ `Next Stop Wonderland'' is as much
about being alone as it is a study on what brings two people
together. Together the elements coalesce into something quite
delightful, a romantic comedy with a brain. By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
DANCE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Enchanting music and sometimes-great
choreography can't dance around the fact that the storytelling in
``Dance With Me'' is all left feet. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
BESTMAN-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Wedding farces are usually played
for broad laughs; everything that can go wrong does go wrong on
what's supposed to be a bride's perfect day, things like that. Pupi
Avati's droll, melancholy ``The Best Man'' goes for something a
little more focused and compelling. While behavioral humor and
surprise reversals play their parts in this handsome Italian period
piece, emotional specificity and a fine sense of a lost era's
attitudes are the film's most engaging qualities. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
ERNEST-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ We talk with pioneering Jamaican jazz
guitarist Ernest Ranglin, whose career has straddled several
continents. His latest release, ``In Search of the Lost Riddim''
pairs him with Afro-pop star Baaba Maal. It's a natural bridge for
an artist whose session work with Bob Marley, Prince Buster, Lee
Perry and Millie Small in the 1970s helped define reggae/ska. By
Fred Shuster. 
. 
POP-BEAT (Los Angeles) _ Dr. John can't recall having had more
arguments while cutting an album in his entire 30 years in the biz.
``We fought about everything, but I think the record turned out
pretty good in the end,'' the New Orleans-bred pianist and singer
says about his ``Anutha Zone'' LP. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Korn is the Rodney Dangerfield of
noxious hard rock _ they get no respect. Not that these nitwits
deserve any. The Huntington Beach quintet creates the sort of
repulsive one-dimensional noise that makes a gasoline-powered leaf
blower sound like a string quartet. By Fred Shuster. 
. 
KUNDUN-VIDEO (LoS Angeles) _ Not long into ``Kundun,'' a film about
the early life of the 14th Dalai Lama, you begin to wonder if
Martin Scorsese made the movie as form of atonement. Or maybe the
director of such gut-wretching, violent films such as ``Mean
Streets'' (1973), ``Taxi Driver'' (1977), ``Goodfellas'' (1990) and
``Casino'' (1995) choose to tell the story of the nonviolent,
spiritual leader of the Tibetan people as a way of assuring that he
wouldn't be reincarnated as, say, a rock. By Rob Lowman. 
. 
RATPACK-TV (Los Angeles) _ Ray Liotta likes to joke that playing
Frank Sinatra in HBO's ``The Rat Pack,'' which premieres at 9 p.m.
Saturday, was cake. ``I have blue eyes. I'm from New Jersey. Close
enough,'' he says. But playing Francis Albert, 'Ol Blue Eyes, the
Chairman of the Board, was a daunting task for Liotta. By Keith
Marder. 
. 

