<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAFILMS-TORRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cult classic gave Torre his start; now he sells filmmakers on
state
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's got the corner office now, the one with the James Dean
photograph on one wall and the nice view of Peachtree Center 10
floors below.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Greg Torre confessed recently, the job's not all perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days I miss the ability to run away from problems,''
Torre said with a smile. ``Yo
</P>
<P>
   u know ... just heading out to different locations.''
</P>
<P>
   That's mostly celluloid fantasy now that Torre is six months
into his job as director of the Georgia Film &AMP; Videotape Office.
Charged with promoting the entire state as an on-location filming
site, the 40-year-old Toco Hills resident's tasks include
everything from nurturing Hollywood creative types to running a
five-person office that answers to state government (it falls under
the jurisdiction of the Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism).
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the onetime movie set location manager (``The Mosquito
Coast,'' ``Stars and Bars'') still gets to spend plenty of time
scouting potential movie locations in his current position.
</P>
<P>
   The demands of his job may have grown. But so have the potential
payoffs for Georgia's movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Paramount recently couldn't secure Department
of Defense permission to shoot the John Travolta thriller ``The
General's Daughter'' on an operating military base, the Film &AMP;
Videotape Office swung into action. Torre and company had already
spent nearly a year working on bringing the film to Georgia _ now
they tried to find just the right base ``stand-in.''
</P>
<P>
   Photos were sent out and the filmmakers were brought in to look
at, among other places, North Georgia College &AMP; State University in
Dahlonega, Spelman and Morehouse colleges in Atlanta and Central
State Hospital in Milledgeville. Torre even arranged a research
visit to Fort Benning near Columbus for the filmmakers, who later
went on to scout in the Savannah area. The upshot? Travolta and
crew have spent much of the summer filming on the campus of
Savannah State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of time, (filmmakers) don't know exactly what they have
in mind,'' Torre explained with a slight grin.
</P>
<P>
   And to think it all started with an innocent trip to the local
laundry. That's where the University of South Carolina graduate
found himself in the early 1980s, armed with a load of dirty
clothes and a B.A. in journalism, with an advertising/public
relations concentration. There, he met an art director on ``Swamp
Thing,'' and instead of going on to graduate school in public
health, Torre got his first film job as a set dresser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent two months in the swamps,'' Torre said of his stint on
the Wes ``Scream'' Craven cult favorite. ``We made it look extra
swampy.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``best time I ever had on a movie'' turned into a career
choice for Torre. He spent the next six years serving as everything
from famed producer Ray Stark's assistant on ``The Slugger's Wife''
(``I went to New York as his driver. I had never driven in New
York. That's when I started losing my hair.'' ) to third assistant
director on ``The Lords of Discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, a field representative's job opened up in Georgia's
Film &AMP; Videotape Office, and Torre applied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see what it was like to have a life,'' explained
Torre, who gradually worked his way up through the ranks to
assistant director of the office. ``You know _ pets, stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet stable doesn't exactly describe Georgia's film industry of
late _ a fact about which Torre is refreshingly candid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had several very slow years,'' he acknowledged. ``We
realize L.A. doesn't have to come here (to film) anymore. We have
to make them see very clearly the benefits of coming.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can do it, many in Georgia's film industry believe,
it's Torre. Indeed, when longtime film office director Norman
Bielowicz resigned, the Atlanta Production Partnership circulated a
petition supporting Torre for the top job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hard-working, personable; he has so many contacts, and
he's able to explain to them (film industry representatives) about
all the changes we're making here,'' Richard Black,
secretary-treasurer of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters
Local 728, said of the man he's seen in action in meetings and at
trade shows. ``One of the most instrumental reasons for the
industry growing here again is Greg Torre.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
