<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen idols still make 'em swoon
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 30 years ago, 19-year-old Peter Noone (Herman of
Herman's Hermits) wrote this open letter published in the March
1967 issue of 16 Magazine:
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere in this wide, wide world there is a girl waiting
just for me. I believe this with all my heart _ because, you see, I
too am waiting ... waiting for her. So far, I haven't even laid
eyes on her, but I know exactly what she looks like. And I know
exactly what she is like _ because this is the girl I love; this is
my bird.''
</P>
<P>
   To millions of preteens, there was no doubt: The baby-faced
British pop star was looking for them. When he sang ``There's a
Kind of Hush,'' it was a personal message about ``just the two of
us, and nobody else.'' That wink into the camera on ``The Ed
Sullivan Show'' meant Noone was dreaming of a simple, ordinary girl
_ just like the ones who had his picture on their bedroom walls,
ate sandwiches out of his lunchbox and scribbled his name on their
school notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Noone's ``bird'' is pushing 50 now, but she apparently
hasn't forgotten Noone. Or Davy. Or Bobby. This summer, Noone,
along with Davy Jones of the Monkees and fellow late-'60s pop
heartthrob Bobby Sherman, is packing midsize music halls with
middle-aged fans (and their children) who still squeal, giggle and
grab for autographs at the Teen Idols Tour, which rolls into
Peachtree City on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Calling from the coffee shop of the AmeriSuites Hotel in Grand
Rapids, Mich., Noone makes a confession:
</P>
<P>
   ``I never wanted to be a teen idol,'' he says. ``I wanted to be
a rock 'n' roll singer. Teen idols were cute guys like Fabian, who
was walking down the street when some record producer drove by and
said, `You'd make a great rock star.' I had sold 20 million records
before anyone ever saw a picture of me.''
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to magazines like 16, Noone, Jones and Sherman became
icons to little girls throughout America, their good looks soon
eclipsing their music. And Noone says today that he's come to an
epiphany: That's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really want to stop being Herman,'' he says. ``I
explain that to Davy all the time. Think of it this way. When you
think of Yul Brynner, what do you think of? `The King and I,' of
course. Sure, he did other stuff. But that was his hit record. I
knew it wouldn't last; I knew that back when I was 16. You become
the flavor of the month. But, you know, we did some good work. We
have an obligation to give the people what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Noone, Jones and Sherman (who hasn't toured in 20 years) roll
out the hits in a free-form show that changes from night to night.
Noone, the headliner, says that often it's Sherman who gets the
biggest audience reaction. For the past decade, the one-time star
of television's ``Here Come the Brides'' has been out of the
limelight, working as an emergency medical technician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grown women scream,'' Noone says. ``They're relieved when
Bobby comes out because he still looks like Bobby. If he came out
drunk and fat and said four-letter words, it would completely
destroy the energy stored in their vault of memories as to what he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Noone believes that the massive teen-idol phenomenon of the '60s
would be hard to duplicate in today's multimedia age.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch somebody in a video 100 times, you move on.
Remember, back then, TV appearances and records were events,'' he
says, adding that the immediacy and control provided by VCRs,
videotape and dozens of cable TV channels today have put once
nearly unattainable artists ``in your lap.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Noone and daughter Natalie, 10, recently caught a
Herman's Hermits performance on an old segment of ``The Ed Sullivan
Show'' on VH1.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought it was fantastic,'' he says, ``but it also
embarrassed her a bit _ it was in black and white.''
</P>
<P>
   (For more information on the Teen Idols Tour, fans might want to
check out Noone's popular World Wide Web site at
http://www.peternoone.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
