</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODSTEWART-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker Rod Stewart remains master showman after all these years
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let us now praise the Lad Eternal.
</P>
<P>
   A rock 'n' roll archetype from the days when they still minted
originals, Rod Stewart is, and ever was, a primary role model for
every strutting bad boy who followed in his footsteps. He even
anticipated Robert Plant, if you can believe that now, when Stewart
fronted guitar god Jeff Beck's group in the late 1960s, wallowing
in those dirty, amped-up blues. The former gravedigger and semi-pro
soccer player rose to prominence shortly after, making his name at
the advent of the '70s, the same era as Neil Young, David Bowie,
Bryan Ferry (Roxy Music) and Elton John. But he quickly established
himself as a far, far rowdier rooster. Bowie and Ferry flaunted a
slicker, more sophisticated and sexually ambiguous appeal, one
draped in designer silks and fin de siecle ennui. Young was a
hippie cowhand who stomped like a renegade, far too earthy to
aspire to rock idol worship. John was a peacock who let his
costumes do the talking.
</P>
<P>
   Rod was Mod.
</P>
<P>
   And he was more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stewart, even in front of tens of thousands, projects an
ex-athlete's warmth, sets up towel-snapping camaraderie among the
players, and somehow manages to embody both the extrovert,
one-of-the-boys hi-jinks of the macho carouser and the introvert,
aw-she'd-probably-never-notice-me-anyway self-consciousness of the
shyest kid on the block. Even as we envy his outgoing, big-winner's
style, we revel in the knowledge he provides via self-mockery that
he can lose as often and as badly as we do.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Paul Nelson writing in 1976, in the first edition of
the ``Rolling Stone Illustrated History of Rock &AMP; Roll,'' which,
when I was 18, possessed an almost Talmudic authority over all
things amplified. Twenty years go by, and you begin to get wistful
for such complexities of performance, for someone who could sing
the line ``Combed my hair a thousand different ways / Standin' in
front of the mirror'' and make of the words a perfectly observed
moment, an instance of exposure glimpsed and then gone.
</P>
<P>
   The memory of that is compensatory. If we have to blame Stewart
for visiting the likes of Black Crowes vocalist Chris Robinson upon
us, for paving the way for every skin-and-bone rawk dude to gyrate
and hip shake, gripped by that peculiar strain of Saint Vitus'
dance that works only if the victim wears leather pants, well, then
we have to blame him. He can take it. He'll take it as a tribute.
He'll take it because every time he does, he knows that it means
rock 'n' roll would never have been the same without him.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute. Rod's not dead yet. I mean, he's 50 _ or is
he 53? He's at that peculiar time in life when we begin to ask of
our rock stars: Can they still rock? Septuagenarian blues guys with
missing teeth and a bum left leg never get asked that question. The
older they get, the more they rock. Jazz? Same thing. I bet when he
was onstage a mere month ago, nobody was asking Benny Waters, the
alto saxophonist who just died at 96, if he could still swing.
Bluegrass fiddlers don't take that guff.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that those forms are all based on traditions that
thrive on mastery, not novelty. Rock absorbs those traditions in
various ways, but is, as a form, obsessed with youth culture, with
new blood. Which is why, although Mick Jagger continues to make
records and tour and appears to be as athletic as ever, new kids on
the block like, say, Oasis seem somehow more startlingly relevant
to life and how we live it.
</P>
<P>
   OK. Not terribly relevant. You get the idea, though. The Rolling
Stones are history. Oasis is a headline. The object, once you've
become the former, is to also continue to be the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Young, wild-eyed galoot that he is, pulls it off _ even
though Beck seems to have inherited his mutton-chop sideburns.
Bowie? If wishing made it so. At least he's brave enough to make
albums no one wants to listen to.
</P>
<P>
   Rod doesn't have that problem: His latest CD, ``When We Were the
New Boys'' (Warner Bros.), is about to crack the Top 100 on
Billboard's album chart. Lo and behold, he's covering songs by ...
Oasis! The fans are out there, tuned in to VH1, no doubt, and not
overly concerned that Stewart hasn't made any music as revelatory
as his very best since, oh, the turn of the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   That pivot in his career is easily marked by his descent from
the emotional complexities of the epic ``Every Picture Tells a
Story'' to the cheesy sleaze of ``Do Ya Think I'm Sexy?'' It's the
difference between being a young Turk and singing ``Young Turks,''
while a real young Turk _ Paul Westerberg of '80s indie-rock
vagabonds the Replacements _ picks up on the wayward truths of your
most honest songwriting. (``Sixteen Blue,'' on the Replacements'
``Let It Be'' album, may be the greatest Rod Stewart song Stewart
never wrote.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Those first four or five albums were phenomenal, phenomenal,
and then he kind of went into the shtick,'' says Mark Kemp, former
music editor of Rolling Stone magazine and now vice president of
music development for MTV. ``Where he got lost was where he
continued to try and be hip or got bad advice from people who
didn't know what made him tick. There was a desperate attempt to
keep up with the Stones, then he kind of floundered. Not
commercially; his fans loved him, people went to hear the old songs
and he got off on that. He's a star, I mean a real star, in the
old-fashioned sense, (for) that generation that felt their stars
would never turn into Frank Sinatras, the kind of star that
continues doing those songs. You know, `Thank you, thank you very
much. I wrote this one in 1957. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   No sin, that, after all. ``He's a master showman, man, and he
still lives up to that standard,'' says Z-93 radio personality
Willard. ``You can't argue with a man who just set the highest
ticket price ever at the Hollywood Bowl: $150 a ticket!''
</P>
<P>
   That's champagne payback for a guy who started life on a beer
budget. Stewart's concerts are swoonfests for the females, rousing
pub crawls for the guys, rife with sing-along medleys and old video
clips and songs that emphasize the performer's strongest suit. The
old rasp in his throat is holding up pretty well, and makes Stewart
a still viable white soul-stirrer. He can evoke the spirit of Sam
Cooke with real panache, and, occasionally, even the echo of
himself, combing his hair a thousand different ways.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: sdollar(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
