<SLUG> BC-SOUL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Years fade away as bands become soul mates
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems that getting older as a rhythm-and-blues performer is a
lot harder than if you spent your best years playing rock 'n' roll.
Long after the Rolling Stones had a really big hit, they still sell
out the 70,000-capacity Georgia Dome. R&AMP;B artists of comparable
stature do well to fill the 6,000-to-8,000-seat spaces.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it seems that things are changing. Classic soul formats,
such as the one on Atlanta radio station WAMJ-FM (107.5), are
gaining momentum across the country. Which indicates that there is
still a sizable audience for old Motown and soul music of that era.
Even the acts themselves are making adjustments, including those on
Sunday's bill at Chastain Park Amphitheatre:
</P>
<P>
   -- Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire has asked rapper and producer Wyclef Jean
of the Fugees to work on its upcoming album. ``I think it's a
perfect match, because I come from a musical sense that I think
would have been better appreciated in the time they were making
songs like `That's the Way of the World' and `Reasons,''' says
Jean. ``But since I wasn't fortunate enough to be born in their
era, I hope I can make people feel why they are still relevant in
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of a voluminous catalog of classics
(``Reasons,'' ``Devotion,'' ``Keep Your Head to the Sky''), the
28-year-old EW&AMP;F continues to sell out amphitheaters every time it
tours. This is true even though co-lead singer/founder Maurice
White hasn't performed with the band in the United States in recent
years. And it's true even though EW&AMP;F hasn't had a really
big-selling album of new work since ``I Am'' (``Boogie
Wonderland,'' ``After the Love Is Gone'') in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Isley Brothers, particularly lead singer Ron Isley, are
making winning alliances with such urban contemporary acts as R.
Kelly (``Down Low''), Babyface (``Tears'') and newcomer Kelly Price
(``Friend of Mine''). In fact, Kelly refers to Ron Isley as ``Mr.
Big.'' It's a persona that Isley played up on his act's last album,
``Mission to Please,'' the first million-seller the current trio
has had in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't hurt either that our songs like `Between the Sheets'
and `Footsteps in the Dark' have been sampled by Biggie Smalls
(`Big Poppa'), Da Brat (`Funkdafied'), Ice Cube (`It Was a Good
Day') and all these rap folks,'' added guitarist Ernie Isley of the
25-year-old act. ``Then for R. Kelly to have Ron in his videos, on
his records, it's like a stamp of approval to the younger kids.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The O'Jays have had less success in terms of recent tours and
album sales. But samples from their 26-year catalog still propel
hip-hop (Big Pun, Queen Latifah) and R&AMP;B records. ``And when I did
the album with my son (Gerald), people responded incredibly well,''
says O'Jays founder Eddie Levert. ``They love to see and hear the
generations of singers. It didn't go platinum, or whatever the kids
say. But we know it meant something. So we're working with him to
write the kinds of songs that will hopefully speak to his
generation while still meaning something to mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
