<SLUG> BC-ANIFEST-FILM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANIMATION FESTIVAL AT MEDIA CITY CENTER MALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Anifest '98 runs through Sunday in Burbank,
offering a behind-the-scenes look at how animators combine artistic
talent and technology to produce visual entertainment that's as
individual as its creators.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar characters the Angry Beavers, Arnold, Bad Dog, Bobby,
Candy, Eek the Cat and Robocop will be there in costume, along with
the Scooby Doo Mystery Van. This event should appeal to working
animators, people wanting to break into the industry and the rest
of us who just plain enjoy watching cartoonish high jinks.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of Anifest '98, being held at the Media City Center
mall, are:
</P>
<P>
   _``Dexter's Laboratory'': Creator Gendy Tartakovsky presents a
never-before-seen episode and other animated stuff in the works. 7
to 8:30 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   _Nancy Cartwright, the voice of Bart Simpson, takes questions
from 11 a.m. to noon Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _Voice-over stage show, 2 and 2:30 p.m. Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _``The Making of Mulan'': Original artwork, a video presentation
and discussion with a team of Disney feature animators, 3 to 4 p.m.
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _Create your own animated film: Full-day session starts at 10
a.m. Sunday. Fee and registration required. Call (818) 566-8556.
</P>
<P>
   _A ``How Do They Do That?'' display area where studios and
artists reveal the process of making key animation elements.
</P>
<P>
   The Media City Center is at 210 E. Magnolia Blvd., Burbank. For
festival information or a schedule of events, call (818) 566-8556.
</P>
<P>
   MGM, DreamWorks, Nickelodeon, Saban Entertainment, Sony
Pictures, the Walt Disney Co., Warner Bros., Hanna-Barbera, Film
Roman and the University of Southern California are among the
participants. Anifest '98 is sponsored by ASIFA Hollywood, a
chapter of the international association of film animation founded
in France in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   GOODBYE FOR NOW: ``American Cinematheque's Greatest Hits,
1993-1998'' enters its final weekend at the Raleigh Studios theater
before the lights go down for a four-month hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:15 tonight, the last remaining 35mm print of ``Twitch of
the Death Nerve'' (1971) has been secured. A mansion is the setting
for murder as 13 occupants turn on each other in this 90-minute
film by Italian frightmaster Mario Bava. At 9:15, director Robert
Wise's ``The Set-Up'' (1949, RKO), about a washed-up fighter in his
last bout, will be followed by Vincent Sherman's ``The Hard Way''
(1942), starring Ida Lupino as the overbearing sister who insists
to everyone that her sister is a movie star. Discussions with the
directors, both of whom will attend, take place between screenings.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, ``The Last Big Thing'' will be shown again at 7:15
p.m. Writer/director Dan Zukovic stars in this scathing 1996 satire
that takes aim at super-hyped modern media that's given us music
videos, supermodels and the sudden cultural affection for the '70s.
The director will attend and discuss his film. Four episodes of
Lela Lee's animated ``Angry Little Asian Girl'' (six minutes total)
will also follow.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:15, ``Sword of Doom'' (1966), from Japanese director
Kihachi Okamoto, and the spaghetti western ``Cemetery Without
Crosses from 1968 will close. ``Cemetery'' is actor/director Robert
Hossein's western about a killer drawn into a kidnap/murder plot by
love. Strangely, the story has little dialogue and is mostly
achieved through visuals.
</P>
<P>
   For program information, call (323) 466-3456. The Cinematheque
will reopen in early December at the Egyptian Theatre in Hollywood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
