<SLUG> BC-BLADE-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEVER A DULL MOMENT IN SHINY `BLADE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN SCHOFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Then there was the sound of rattling chains and the clanking
of massive bolts . . . and the great door swung back. Within stood
a tall old man, clean-shaven save for a long white mustache, and
clad in black from head to foot, without a single speck of colour
about him anywhere. `` - Bram Stoker (``Dracula``) &QL; 
 &QL; 
UNDATED - A time-lapse sun plunges on the New York City horizon.
Full night follows as a beautiful girl leads a young man into a
trendy dance club behind a slaughterhouse. As the techno-pop
grooves resonate and the dancers reach a frenzy, the ceiling
sprinklers shower them with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to a postmodern world of vampires that would give Bram
Stoker nightmares. It is a world in which vampires operate in a
secret nocturnal organization, sinking their claws and fangs into
every part of society: finance, real estate, law enforcement. They
roam the streets, hunting. They are everywhere. And they must be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Blade, a daywalker: half-human, half-vampire. He wages a
virtual one-man war on the vampires in a stylish new thriller based
on the Marvel Comic.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Snipes plays Blade, the cool hero who speaks little and
packs plenty of weaponry. The days of a stake through the heart and
holy water are over. Blade eliminates vampires with everything from
an old-fashioned Samurai sword to an Uzi loaded with silver
bullets. Granted, silver bullets are usually associated with
werewolves, but the vampires of Blade have as much in common with
Bram Stoker's ``Dracula'' as the Oxford English Dictionary has with
a Speak-N-Spell. Gothic horror has given way to MTV.
</P>
<P>
   The story of ``Blade'' concerns a human-turned-vampire named
Frost (icily played by Stephen Dorff), who seeks to awaken the
vampire god and take over the human world. To achieve his goals, he
needs Blade's blood because it contains properties that would allow
Frost to move freely in daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Aiding Blade in the fight against Frost is Whistler (Kris
Kristofferson), a grizzled vampire-slayer who makes the weapons
Blade uses, and Karen (N'Bushe Wright), a hematologist bitten by a
vampire but saved from becoming one because of a serum that
suppresses the thirst for blood.
</P>
<P>
   The plot, however, serves merely as an excuse for the action and
is filled with about as many holes as one of Blade's victims. For
instance, about halfway through the movie we see Frost outside in
full daylight. How can a vampire do this? Why, with sunscreen, of
course. Yet the movie never explains how he is able to cover
(apparently) his entire body with enough sunscreen to keep from
burning to death.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the reason the vampires have become so powerful is due to
their ability to blend in. But in the same scene, Frost tosses a
child hundreds of feet through the air and onto a crowded street,
yet no one seems to notice. Nor is the child injured in any way.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Blade drives around in a souped-up jet-black 1968
Dodge Charger and dresses like Arnold Schwarzenegger in
``Terminator 2.'' This is blending?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the plot and gaps in logic seem unimportant to the
filmmakers (the movie ``is'' based on a comic book, after all).
Blade is about wasting ammunition, kung fu fighting, and racking up
dead bodies (enough to put Buffy to shame). Blade is style over
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Director Stephen Norrington to some extent used the movie to
test different film speeds. There's the time-lapse, which
compresses a day into minutes. There's slow motion. There's fast
motion (allowing the characters to run and jump and fight at high
speed). There's rapid-fire cutting. And all sorts of gruesome
special effects and makeup.
</P>
<P>
   The film never lapses into campiness and has the feel of a comic
book: ultra-violent, ultra-stylish and ultra-cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade'' is rated R for excessive violence, strong language and
sexual situations. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
