<HEADLINE>
DR. JOHN'S FIGHTIN' WORDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Things got a bit contentious during the making of
Dr. John's latest record featuring members of some of Britain's top
bands.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans-bred pianist and singer, whose real name is Mac
Rebennack, says he can't recall having had more arguments while
cutting an album in his entire 30 years in the biz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd fight about the groove and if it was slippin' or not,''
Rebennack drawled. ``Finally, we put the song to a click track and
saw we was slippin' way downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album, ``Anutha Zone'' (Pointblank), includes
contributions from Paul Weller and Jools Holland, plus members of
Spiritualized, Supergrass, Portishead, Primal Scream and Ocean
Colour Scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought about everything, but I think the record turned out
pretty good in the end,'' Rebennack, 57, said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Some tracks such as ``John Gris'' and ``Voices in My Head''
re-create the swampy hoodoo feel of such classic Dr. John discs as
``Dr. John the Night Tripper,'' the 1968 album that established
Rebennack's ghostly alter-ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I liked about working with the London guys
was they weren't tryin' to do my thing, and I wasn't tryin' to do
their thing,'' Rebennack said. ``That's the only way this sort of
thing can work.''
</P>
<P>
   `TORN' NOTORIETY: Although she's fronted local rockers Ednaswap
for years, Anne Preven has found notoriety courtesy of an ex-soap
star from the Land Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   Preven's ``Torn,'' penned with songwriting partner and bandmate
Scott Cutler, was a worldwide smash for Aussie singer and TV
actress Natalie Imbruglia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That song had been covered a few times before,'' Preven said.
``The version before Natalie's was identical but didn't do well for
some reason. We have no control. Once a song has been recorded,
anyone that wants to can cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other tunes by Preven and Cutler have been recorded by Madonna
and Irish chanteuse Mary Black, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Ednaswap celebrates the release of its third album, ``Wonderland
Park'' (Island), with a free show at 10 tonight at Tower Sunset in
West Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Preven says ``Torn'' hasn't provided a financial windfall _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't received a dime, but we expect the royalties
sometime next year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, look out!
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDTRACK SCENE: The soundtrack to the film ``Permanent
Midnight'' boasts cuts from Crystal Method, Moby, Morcheeba, Girls
Against Boys, Prodigy, Spiritualized, Black Lab and a solo Art
Alexakis. The disc is due Sept. 15 from DGC/Critical Failure
Records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
