A3996 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RATPACK-REVIEW-NYT     08-20 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATPACK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE RAT PACK': EXTREMES WITH IMPOSSIBLE SCHEMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he is about to walk onstage, an aging Frank Sinatra stops to
light a cigarette, or more precisely to have one lighted for him.
``Match me,'' he tells a male lackey, only to have an off-camera
woman with a sugary voice give him a light instead. ``Thanks,
doll,'' he tells her, walking on.
</P>
<P>
   You can hoot at this style as irredeemably tacky, or view it as
the essence of retro cool. You can even see it as both. Those
possibilities suggest the breadth of appeal behind the HBO film
``The Rat Pack,'' which recreates a dizzyingly energetic,
near-mythic phase of American culture.
</P>
<P>
   As anthropology or as sheer fun, a project called ``The Rat
Pack'' offers immense promise. Even a misguided ``Rat Pack,'' like
this one, holds some fascination.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the film is Sinatra's flashback to the late 1950s and
early '60s, when he seemed to rule show biz. In Las Vegas, he
cavorts onstage and through casinos, surrounded by the genuine
talents of Dean Martin and Sammy Davis Jr. and the lesser lights of
Peter Lawford and Joey Bishop (the only surviving Rat Pack member).
He plays host to them at his Palm Springs estate where he serves
pasta for breakfast and keeps everyone supplied with booze and
broads. They were bad boys who offered vicarious hope to every
suburban couple: the men who envied their freedom and the women who
dreamed of their sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
   America turned away from the Rat Pack's martini-and-cigarette
chic in the mid-'60s, but the style has made a tongue-in-cheek
return in the '90s. The film ``Swingers'' and the forthcoming CBS
show ``Buddy Faro,'' about a onetime crony of the Rat Packers, are
two conspicuous examples of the era's recycled allure.
</P>
<P>
   That enticing aura is the crucial element missing from HBO's
disappointing film. Despite some high moments, it desperately lacks
the charismatic charge that would have explained it all. Viewers
can fill in the gaps in this pedestrian movie, but they really
shouldn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   The dark side of the Rat Pack myth was uncovered long ago, and
the film focuses on those elements: the callous treatment of women
and even of one another; Sinatra's friendships with both the mob
boss Sam Giancana and John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Liotta's problematic performance as Sinatra leaves a void in
the center of the film. The Rat Pack was built on his magnificent
voice and popularity; without that charisma, the group itself seems
a collection of louses and Sinatra merely a bully. Liotta can be
magnetic (as he was in films like ``Goodfellas''), but his appeal
is a cool, insinuating one. Nowhere is this more obvious than in
the difference between Liotta's icy blue eyes and those warmer ones
that caused Sinatra to be nicknamed ``Ol' Blue Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The script offers Liotta no help. His Sinatra is already the Rat
Pack's Chairman of the Board, though there is no hint why anyone
would listen to him. Well, there is the fact that his pal Momo, as
Giancana is always called here, is usually hovering around; but
we're meant to believe that Sinatra's power comes from more than
that.
</P>
<P>
   The film telegraphs scenes rather than developing them. Marilyn
Monroe wafts through. So does Ava Gardner, divorced from Sinatra,
who still pines for her. In one scene, a pretty brunette walks into
a club and introduces herself: ``Judy Campbell, I'm here to see
Frank.'' Sinatra quickly passes the woman (now better known as
Judith Campbell Exner) along to both Giancana and Kennedy. ``Well,
chickie baby, its just you, me and the Girl Scouts,'' Sinatra tells
Kennedy when offering a choice between Campbell and another woman.
Though this straight-faced film has few campy impulses, it is hard
to beat the high camp of that line.
</P>
<P>
   As Peter Lawford, the actor and Kennedy brother-in-law, Angus
Macfadyen offers little more than a hard-to-place British accent.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mantegna is convincing but seriously underused as Dean
Martin, who drinks apple juice onstage and stays sober while acting
thoroughly drunk. His self-protective detachment is intriguingly
hinted at.
</P>
<P>
   Don Cheadle has the most dynamic role as Davis. In a performance
that is not mimicry but a reimagining of a character in lifelike
terms, Cheadle captures the big grin and exaggerated laugh,
especially loud when Davis is the butt of the joke.
</P>
<P>
   In an explosive fantasy scene, Davis imagines singing and
dancing for a mob of Nazis in front of a neon sign with a racial
slur. This scene of self-debasement, anger and defiance powerfully
encapsulates the film's interpretation of Davis as a man who
endures racist jokes to break barriers and carve a path for future
black entertainers. (He even says that, far too literally.) This
startling, first-rate scene seems out of place; it is the only
reminder that the script was written by Kario Salem, who also wrote
the far more trenchant HBO film ``Don King: Only in America.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's exuberant moments is a re-creation of the Rat
Pack at a fund-raiser for Kennedy's presidential campaign, singing
the special lyrics Sammy Cahn had written for the Sinatra hit
``High Hopes.'' (``Everyone wants to back Jack/Jack is on the right
track.'')
</P>
<P>
   More typical is a scene that maps out everything. The camera
travels into several rooms and beds in the Sands Hotel: there is
JFK with Campbell; Sinatra with two women at once; Martin, the
family man, alone watching television.
</P>
<P>
   The film is nearly saved by William Petersen as Kennedy, who
displays all the charisma this Sinatra lacks. Kennedy lives
comfortably in his skin, exuding the sense that power, grace and
invincibility are his birthright. Sinatra, who scrapped his way up,
is desperate for this friendship and camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   He comes through when Joseph P. Kennedy asks him to use his mob
connections to help JFK win the West Virginia primary. But Sinatra
never understands that the pimping and the gangster connections
that make him valuable in some ways also mean the Kennedys will
never truly embrace him.
</P>
<P>
   Martin sees that Robert F. Kennedy's determination to take on
the Mafia will make a blood brothership between JFK and Sinatra
impossible. Martin sardonically says: ``Brother Bobby made attorney
general. Nice to hear that a choirboy with a passion for sin will
be watchin' out for us.'' His statement heralds the end of Rat Pack
power.
</P>
<P>
   One major problem is the film's minimal use of music. The actors
lip-sync to snatches of songs performed by uninspired imitators.
The music is telling. Like its soundtrack, ``The Rat Pack'' offers
a tinny echo of the era and its stars.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE RAT PACK'
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Saturday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Cohen; written by Kario Salem; music by Mark
Adler; Savion Glover, choreographer; Neal H. Moritz, executive
producer; Fred Caruso, producer.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Ray Liotta (Frank Sinatra), Joe Mantegna (Dean Martin),
Don Cheadle (Sammy Davis Jr.), Angus Macfadyen (Peter Lawford),
William Petersen (John F. Kennedy) and Bobby Slayton (Joey Bishop).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
