<HEADER>
A4000 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RATPACK-TEX     08-20 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATPACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RAT PACK' LEAVES NO RUMOR UNEXPLORED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month, when Ray Liotta turned up to promote ``The Rat
Pack,'' he was clearly irritated by the constant assertions that he
didn't look a thing like Frank Sinatra, even in a dimly lit room.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, it turns out. ``The Rat Pack,'' the story of the
glorious and glamorous alliance of Sinatra, Dean Martin and Sammy
Davis Jr., isn't about imitation as much as imagination.
</P>
<P>
   There's so much stuffed into this HBO film, airing at 8 p.m.
Sunday, that you have to wonder whether there is any
unsubstantiated rumor or tale the creators didn't cram in. The one
where a mobster says he can't whack Sinatra because it means never
again hearing him croon ``Chicago'' is a favorite, as is a scene in
which presidential candidate John F. Kennedy has a hotel
assignation with a mysteriously creepy brunette bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Kennedys, not the angry Sinatra family, ought to be
the ones crying foul about this film treatment, because John
Kennedy is portrayed as a lusty loverboy. (Having watched ``The Rat
Pack'' shortly before seeing President Clinton's live address about
his own lustful union was enough to bring on a patriotic
depression.)
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, ``The Rat Pack'' is quite a fun ride, partly
because screenwriter Kario Salem (''Don King: Only in America'')
and director Rob Cohen have made a spirited film, focusing on a
very specific time, the late '50s and early '60s, when the Pack was
at the height of its power and panache.
</P>
<P>
   This was a time when the three, along with Joey Bishop (Bobby
Slayton) and Peter Lawford (Angus Macfadyen) appeared somewhat
bored with their stage accomplishments and sought higher ground, or
at least different footing.
</P>
<P>
   Martin (Joe Mantegna) readily embraces the hard-drinking,
hard-partying lifestyle while maintaining equilibrium with the wife
and family he rarely sees. The Dino here never seems all that happy
in either place.
</P>
<P>
   Davis (Don Cheadle) must stay in his place, a spot reserved for
a talented man wanting the perks of his white colleagues at a time
when it simply wasn't possible in a racially divided America.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra, meanwhile, wanted power, and that extended to the
nation's highest office. His relationship with President Kennedy in
this movie borders on worship; did Sinatra really go mad, busting
up an under-construction wing of his house after learning that
Kennedy wouldn't stay there during a California visit?
</P>
<P>
   Bishop is barely noticeable, and Lawford, then married to Pat
Kennedy, is written as a whining messenger boy scuttling between
the president and Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   Screaming ``Damn Kennedys!'' is the extent of his contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra's life fuels ``The Rat Pack,'' but the more prickly,
engaging scenes occur with Martin and Davis, two people who seem to
be tortured souls hiding behind public personas.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Martin takes the stage with not booze but apple
juice. And during one fine scene in which the camera pans past
different windows of the Sands Hotel, we see Davis, Kennedy and
Sinatra going at it with women, while Martin sits stoically downing
a glass of milk, watching television.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Mantegna tries hard but never connects with
Martin's slow, suave baritone when he speaks. The portrayal of Dino
as a man more often alone than cruising was an intriguing sight.
</P>
<P>
   While watching white supremacists rally outside his hotel
window, upset over his engagement to a white Swedish actress, Davis
dreams up a sequence in which he walks out in front of the mob and
bursts into ``I've Got You Under My Skin.'' It's a fabulous
segment, with Cheadle tapping up a storm _ apparently the crash
course with Tony-winning tapdancer Savion Glover paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, I have the most questions about Davis; how, for
instance, he was able to hang with the Rat Pack with race staring
him in the face. During one poignant performance scene, he's shown
laughing at a racist joke from Sinatra, turning away from the
audience, then grimacing.
</P>
<P>
   He later explains to his fiancee, ``So I get a little dirt on my
uniform sometimes. But I'm circling the bases, baby. And the fellas
who come up behind me are gonna have it easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Martin and Davis stand out because Sinatra, pop-culture
figure, has been done to death, including that weak-kneed CBS
miniseries orchestrated by his daughter, Tina, in 1992. By the end
of ``The Rat Pack,'' I could only say, ``Wow, I never knew Frank
had a thing for toy trains.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
