<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-EEL-NYT &LR;      08-20 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-EEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PASSIONS THAT SEETHE UNDER THE ORDERLY SURFACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the dead of night, a husband, inflamed by suspicion, returns
home early from a fishing outing. In the bedroom, his beautiful
wife, who sent him off with a neatly wrapped snack and wished him
good luck, moans naked and ecstatic against the body of another
man.
</P>
<P>
   The husband enters the house, seizes a gleaming knife, makes his
way to the bedroom, stabs her lover and plunges the long blade
repeatedly into his wife as she stares into his face. When life has
drained from her, he gently covers her body, mounts his bicycle and
pedals blood-drenched to the police station to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   So begins ``The Eel,'' the riveting, wrenching film by Shohei
Imamura that won the Palme d'Or at the 1997 Cannes International
Film Festival. Adapted by the director from ``Sparkles in the
Darkness,'' a novel by Akira Yoshima, ``The Eel'' swims with grace,
insight and vast compassion along the ineradicable fault line that
separates flawed mankind from the elusive realization of heavenly
perfection.
</P>
<P>
   In telling his story, Imamura, the Japanese filmmaker who also
won the Palme d'Or in 1983 for ``The Ballad of Narayama,'' marshals
a small cast of vivid characters that enable him not only to bare
the passions that seethe beneath the orderly surface and apparent
conformity of Japanese life but also to ponder emotions and issues
that know no nationality.
</P>
<P>
   Among these may be counted jealousy, rage, crime, punishment,
remorse, the onerous baggage of ghosts and guilt and, most of all,
the possibilities of redemption, the persistence of hope, the
achievement of love and the miracles of rebirth and survival.
</P>
<P>
   The murderous husband, Takuro Yamashita (played by Koji Yakusho
of ``Shall We Dance?''), is Imamura's Everyman. At the outset of
``The Eel,'' Yamashita is one of those people the Japanese call a
salaryman _ a blue-suited, white-shirted, stripe-tied corporate
drone commuting between home and skyscraper office.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, swinging his arms and lifting his knees in
the automaton's march of an obedient prisoner, he is ushered into
the office of the warden, warned not to be drawn into trouble of
any kind and paroled into the custody of a Buddhist priest.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the warden's caution, Yamashita takes with him his pet
eel. ``He listens to what I say,'' Yamashita explains to those who
ask. And the eel doesn't say what he doesn't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Along a bleak stretch of coast, Yamashita begins his new life. A
prison-trained hair cutter, he sets about restoring a ramshackle
barbershop. Grim, repressed, uncommunicative, he keeps mostly to
himself, except for an occasional nocturnal eel-fishing expedition
with one of the townsmen, an authority on their life cycle.
</P>
<P>
   But one day, through the window of his shop, Yamashita spies a
woman who bears an uncanny resemblance to his wife. Not long
afterward, while on a solitary outing to net food for his pet from
an inlet, he finds the woman unconscious in the grass. His impulse
is to flee, but soon he returns. The life of the woman, who had
attempted suicide, is saved.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Keiko Hattori (Misa Shimizu of ``Okoge''), who
explains, ``I fell in love with the wrong man.'' The wrong man will
eventually reappear.
</P>
<P>
   Keiko, too, is in the care of the priest and his wife, and
because Keiko does not want to return to Tokyo but is eager to
work, Yamashita is asked to accept her as a helper.
</P>
<P>
   Yamashita is not pleased, but soon business is booming. Despite
his blunt indifference, Keiko improves the premises; she prepares
and serves tidbits for waiting customers like Masaki Saito (Ken
Kobayashi), the young man who plans to borrow the barber pole for a
site he is preparing in hope of attracting a UFO and befriending
aliens from outer space.
</P>
<P>
   What he and Yamashita share is a fear of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had my fill of women,'' Yamashita tells Keiko.
</P>
<P>
   As time passes, though, she warms to him. But Imamura, though
not without a sense of humor, scarcely intends to deliver a
conventional resolution in which Yamashita comes to terms with his
past and returns from the living dead.
</P>
<P>
   Both Yamashita and Keiko are plagued by nightmares, figurative
and literal, from their past: Yamashita by a former fellow
prisoner, a drunken, rapacious lout working as a garbage man who
taunts him for his lack of overt remorse and reveals his history to
Keiko; and Keiko by her insane mother, Fumie, and Dojima, her
vengeful former lover and business associate who has a claim on
Fumie's fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Given the bloody opening, the film is suffused with tension.
Having once revealed his capacity for murderous rage, Yamashita
remains throughout a potentially volcanic figure, and harking back
to the beginning of ``The Eel,'' Imamura imbues the stropping of a
razor with high tension.
</P>
<P>
   The barber's rejection of the lunches Keiko dangles from a
bridge on his early morning returns from fishing resonate with the
mournful, crippling stubbornness of those whose experience of
betrayal and pain makes them erect a shield against love.
</P>
<P>
   Yakusho and Ms. Shimizu deliver unerring performances in a
splendid film that harvests hope from a bleak landscape. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE EEL
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Shohei Imamura; written (in Japanese, with English
subtitles) by Motofumi Tomikawa, Daisuke Tengan and Imamura, based
on the novel ``Sparkles in the Darkness'' by Akira Yoshimura;
director of photography, Shigeru Komatsubara; edited by Hajime
Okayasu; music by Shinichiro Ikebe; produced by Hisa Iino; released
by New Yorker Films. Running time: 117 minutes. This film is not
rated. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Koji Yakusho (Takuro Yamashita), Misa Shimizu (Keiko
Hattori), Fujio Tsuneta (Jiro Nakajima), Mitsuko Baisho (Misako
Nakajima), Ken Kobayashi (Masaki Saito) and Akira Emoto (Tamotsu
Takasaki). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
