by the Roman Catholic Church to have reached the ``age of reason''
and is entitled to receive communion. Some evangelical churches
hold that a child of 7 can make an independent spiritual choice. In
Judaism and Islam, a boy of 7 is expected to begin his religious
studies and participate, to some degree, in adult rituals like
fasting and praying. But is a child of such tender years a
responsible being, capable of telling right from wrong and
accountable, not just legally but morally, for his actions? By
Susan Sachs.
</P>
