<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKE     08-20 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES COLUMN: SEEING BEAUTY IN THE BUG ON THE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J., Del., Conn.)   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Salvador Dali used to take live beetles to lunch with him at the
St. Regis. He kept them in a clear plastic box on the table and
watched, riveted, as they navigated mounds of sand. He found them
more interesting than his companions. Vladimir Nabokov loved
butterflies and was expert at catching them; he gave them names
like Karner Blue and Satyr I and II. He may have taken his cue from
the surrealist Andre Breton, who mounted boxes of butterflies on
the walls of his Paris apartment in the 1920s. Victorians, like the
British aristocrat in the film ``Angels and Insects,'' invited
young men who had scoured the globe for natural specimens to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The fascination for nature in a box persists. One exhibition
this summer is a new take on an old subject. With ``Etre Nature,''
at the Cartier Foundation for Contemporary Art in Paris through
Sept. 20, the curator, Herve Chandes, said he wanted to explore
``the role of the artist when faced with Creation with a capital
C.'' He asked 20 international artists to investigate ``the
reciprocity between a work of art and nature.'' One of them,
Jacques Kerchache, does not make art: he collects odd bug
specimens. ``I look at an insect as the work of a fully fledged
artist,'' he said. His exquisitely mounted boxes of large black
beetles look like shining jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Kerchache quoted the French structuralist Claude Levi-Strauss:
``A bird, a beetle, a butterfly call for the same rapt
contemplation that we reserve for a Tintoretto or a Rembrandt.''
The point, Chandes said, is that ``these beetles are not in a
nature museum; they are in an art show.''
</P>
<P>
   Other artists displayed bronzes of snakes and turtles in cases
with the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 16th century, Europeans were assembling natural
history specimens in ``wonder rooms.'' As Victoria Newhouse writes
in her new book, ``Towards a New Museum'' (Monacelli Press), ``The
cabinet of curiosities, or Wunderkammer, was a room whose walls and
ceilings, cupboards and drawers, housed collections that included a
bizarre spectrum of natural curiosities as well as art objects.''
The natural objects could include anything from bits of coral to
crystals to flies, and they were mounted right next to the
antiquities and paintings.
</P>
<P>
   In her effort to distinguish these domestic spaces from what
later would become museums for fine art, Ms. Newhouse notes: ``In
contrast with the devotional and didactic purposes of religious
collections, these cabinets were intended primarily to `entertain
and amuse' and only secondarily to instruct or uplift.'' The
Hapsburg Emperor Rudolf II (1552-1612) was deeply interested in
science, and he imported artists, botanists, astronomers and
philosophers to his court in Prague. When one artist, Joris
Hoefnagel, created a lavishly illustrated manuscript of natural
life, he was not afraid to mix his art with examples from real
life. He glued dragonfly wings onto the bodies of the insects he
painted.
</P>
<P>
   In the 17th century, the Dutch and Flemish showed ``trophies''
from nature, found in the age of exploration, in their own ``wonder
rooms.'' These were recorded in paintings by artists like Jan
Bruegel the Elder and Adriaen van Stalbemt, including those on
display now through Nov. 1, at the National Gallery of Art in
Washington in ``A Collector's Cabinet.'' These collectors, said
Earl A. Powell 3d, the director of the National Gallery, were
``armed with the belief that God had placed man at the center of
the world and had provided him with the means to achieve unlimited
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   As Powell writes in the catalog: ``Their collections contained
both unusual natural phenomena, or naturalia, such as shells or
coral, and remarkable human creations, or artificialia, such as
paintings, sculpture or graphic arts.''
</P>
<P>
   The French followed suit. Who can forget Louis XV's rhinoceros,
said to be the first ever that was stuffed and mounted, which
arrived in France in 1770? The Encyclopedists cataloged natural
specimens, and their efforts are still on display at the National
Museum of Natural History in Paris. Its Gallery of Entomology, for
example, has some 1,500 specimens, including the rarest
butterflies, stored in elegant wooden drawers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A person does not have to be an entomologist, however, to be
attracted to the gorgeous display of bugs. Even the squeamish have
no trouble displaying somebody else's collection, especially when
the antique case is curly maple and the copper plate lettering in
Latin is a beautiful script.
</P>
<P>
   The dealer Michael Trapp, of West Cornwall, Conn., is selling
several glass cases from the late 19th and early 20th centuries
that display artfully mounted butterflies, African crickets,
rhinoceros beetles and praying mantises. ``Controlled nature is
like controlled fantasy,'' Trapp said. ``It makes you think about
the mind behind it _ the collector who had the time to go around
the world, who had the money, the leisure and interest. I think the
appeal may be not so much the love of nature as love of
possession.'' His cases range from $225 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Marotta, a Manhattan antiques dealer, recently sold 15 cases
of butterflies and moths from the 1870s. ``Anything dealing with
the garden appeals to people today,'' he said. ``It's nature
without killing anything. People want to bring the outside in, year
round. It's also very decorative. Interior designers use these
collections as sculptures.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Taylor, the proprietor of Praiseworthy Antiques, a
by-appointment Manhattan gallery, just sold a set of 20 Riker Mount
boxes displaying butterflies collected in the 1950s and 1960s by a
man who had been in the military. Each insect was numbered; in a
corresponding book was its name and where it was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were bought by a woman who had boys aged 7, 4 and 3,''
Taylor recalled. ``She said, `This is what I want my kids to look
at as they grow up.' She bought them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said a good bug box costs $50 to $500. ``Bugs are so
flamboyant; they appeal to everyone,'' he said. ``They also skip
the language barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   John Malchione, a dealer in sporting collectibles in
Centerville, Del., is selling old fishing lures in Booth No. 1107
at the Irene Stella's Antiques Weekend in Somerset, N.J., tomorrow
and Sunday. One of his old glass cases boasts 80 hand-tied trout
and salmon flies, each housed in its own red velvet square, and
costs $450. ``The beautiful colors of the flies and the hand-forged
hooks make for a wonderful display,'' Malchione said. ``The people
who tied flies before the second world war were true masters of the
art.'' His cases cost $150 to $1,200, and he said his best
customers were women.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, bugs are fashionable. ``There's this real fascination
with the natural sciences now,'' Taylor said. ``They were always
interesting to collectors, but now it's the masses.''
</P>
<P>
   He might be right. The new advertisement for Absolut Citron
features exquisite yellow butterflies hovering on top of the vodka
bottle. The teen-agers who avidly collect Absolut print
advertisements today are obviously too young to drink, but this one
is directed toward collectors of all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
