<SLUG> BC-HEPATITISBOX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACTS ABOUT HEPATITIS C 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like hepatitis A and B, hepatitis C is a chronic inflammation of
the liver caused by a virus. In advanced stages, it can cause
cirrhosis, or scarring, of the liver. It also can lead to liver
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   2. Who is at risk for hepatitis C?
</P>
<P>
   People who have been intravenous drug users, undergone body
piercing, had tattoos, engaged in unsafe promiscuous sex, had a
blood transfusion before 1992 or work in the health care field and
are subject to accidental needle sticks may have contracted the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   3. How long does hepatitis C take to develop?
</P>
<P>
   Signs of the disease may not show up for as long as 20 years
after infection.
</P>
<P>
   4. Who should be tested for hepatitis C?
</P>
<P>
   Those identified as being in high risk groups should have a
blood test to determine liver enzyme levels. If levels are high,
they should be tested specifically for hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   5. What are the symptoms of hepatitis C?
</P>
<P>
   There may be few or no symptoms. Or the patient could suffer
fatigue, muscle pain, jaundice, flulike symptoms, weakness. More
serious signs include fluid retention in the ankles and abdomen,
confusion, increased risk of bleeding, intestinal bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   6. Where can I find more information about hepatitis C and other
liver diseases?
</P>
<P>
   The American Liver Foundation at 800-GO-LIVER (800-465-4837); or
www.liverfoundation.org on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Hepatitis C Foundation at www.hepcfoundation.org/index.html
on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The hepatitis home page of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention at www.cdc.gov/ncidod/diseases/hepatitis. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
