<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA CANDIDATES ZERO IN ON FERTILE CENTRAL VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE and ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ California's Central Valley is a region of
fertile farms and unpredictable politics. And in this year's
gubernatorial race, it has become an unusual battleground for the
Democratic and Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the region, a major supplier of fruits and
vegetables, have often complained that politicians neglect it in
favor of the vote-rich urban and suburban areas. Their party
allegiances are more malleable than in San Francisco and Los
Angeles County, which are largely Democratic strongholds, or in
Orange County, San Diego and far northern California, which favor
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Valley is the place where the next governor is going to
be elected,'' Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, the Democratic candidate for
governor, told a crowd of 200 supporters at a park next to the
Stockton City Hall. ``I am going to spend so much time here you're
going to get tired of seeing me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the middle and they're fighting for the middle,''
said Allen Sawyer, a deputy district attorney for San Joaquin
County. ``I think we could be convinced by either party if they
show concern for our issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis made his pitch Wednesday, taking a bus tour through
Fresno, Modesto and Stockton. The tour followed a debate in Fresno
with his Republican opponent, Attorney General Dan Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   Lungren staged his own Central Valley bus tour last week,
touting his endorsement by the California Farm Bureau Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates claim they would do more for the area as
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do my level best to make sure the Valley is a
full partner in decisions we make in Sacramento,'' said Davis, who
had shed his customary suit and tie for cowboy boots, khaki pants
and an Oxford shirt. ``You're not going to take a back seat to
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he would appoint Valley representatives to state
agencies and commissions, and deliver more funding for education
and other programs. Lungren has said he will work to settle
long-ignored disputes over water and suburban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates support the creation of a 10th University of
California campus, at Merced. Davis has said the campus could help
attract high-tech jobs to diversify the area's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Valley largely has been left out of the state's
booming economy. Many cities there have double-digit unemployment,
high crime rates and higher-than-average illiteracy and teen-age
pregnancy rates.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists believe Lungren has an edge in the
Central Valley, where GOP registration has risen from one-third of
voters two decades ago to 42 percent today. Democrats make up 44
percent of registered voters, but the party traditionally has a
lower turnout.
</P>
<P>
   The past two Democratic nominees, Kathleen Brown and Dianne
Feinstein, fared poorly in the Valley. But Davis' advisers note
that he has won in the Central Valley in three previous statewide
races _ twice for controller, once for lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis campaign manager, Garry South, said Davis' pro-death
penalty, tough-on-crime positions and support of veterans rights
appeal to some conservatives. Democratic Party strategist Bob
Mulholland said Davis also could be helped by the Valley's growing
population of Hispanics, who traditionally favor Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But Brent Paris, executive director for the Stanislaus County
Hispanic Chamber of Commerce, said: ``Assuming the Hispanic
electorate will go for the Democrats 100 percent is incorrect. ...
They're making choices based on what they think will be best for
their families and for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
