<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILLER THEATER FOR PRIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1969, Richard Zanuck was trying hard to sign up Charlton
Heston for a sequel being made by 20th Century Fox, which was run
by Zanuck. A year earlier, Heston had starred as the astronaut
Taylor in Fox's highly successful ``Planet of the Apes.'' Now his
services were badly needed for ``Beneath the Planet of the Apes,''
the second installment of what would become a five-film series.
</P>
<P>
   Heston, however, felt that for him another ape movie would be
one too many. Or at least another complete ape movie. ``I owed Dick
one on this,'' he said in an interview this week. ``So I told him,
`I'll be in the first scene, then you kill me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Zanuck agreed, with one adjustment. ``Dick came back with, `How
about you disappear in the first scene, then we kill you in the
last scene?' '' Heston said.
</P>
<P>
   This week Fox issued ``Planet of the Apes'' in a
30th-anniversary edition, along with its four sequels and a fine
two-hour documentary about the making of all of them called
``Behind the Planet of the Apes.'' As for Heston's Taylor in
``Beneath the Planet of the Apes'' (1970), he was vaporized on cue
at the finale by a doomsday device that Taylor, perhaps taking no
chances, detonated himself.
</P>
<P>
   Later the eons-long battle for control between man and the
lesser (or was it superior?) primates would rage on without him in
``Escape From the Planet of the Apes'' (1971), ``Conquest of the
Planet of the Apes'' (1972) and `'Battle for the Planet of the
Apes'' (1973).
</P>
<P>
   Like most sequels, none of them ranked with the original.
Adapted from the novel by Pierre Boulle and tirelessly promoted by
the producer Arthur P. Jacobs, ``Planet of the Apes'' was to prove
a tour de force for its time. At first, though, Hollywood ran the
other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Arthur went around peddling the film, he got laughed out
of every studio office in town,'' Heston said. ``They called it a
Saturday morning serial; said it was ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics attributed the film's success to its premise (that a
breed of advanced apes had taken control of primitive humans, who
in turn once had been superior to the apes), the flexible and
lifelike prosthetic masks worn by the apes, Franklin Schaffner's
exacting direction and to the larger-than-life presence of Heston.
</P>
<P>
   During production the worry had been that audiences would laugh
at the apes. But the call of the ram's horn (just one of the
distinctive devices in Jerry Goldsmith's famous score) still sends
chills as the gorilla cavalry, fearsome creatures in black leather,
swoop down on their human quarry.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was Zanuck who took a chance on the film, which
cost $6 million to make. ``There's high risk in any project,'' he
said this week. ``The apes made it entertaining. That really was
lessening the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years after ``Planet of the Apes,'' Zanuck produced
``Jaws.'' No one was entirely sure what the reaction would be there
either. ``Until we saw it in front of an audience, we were scared
to death the audience would laugh at the shark,'' he said. ``You
never know how people are going to respond.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Apostle
</P>
<P>
   Robert Duvall's performance as the evangelist preacher Euliss
(Sonny) Dewey neatly sidesteps standard depictions of such
characters. Sonny is no angel, but when marital problems prompt him
to whack his wife's lover with a baseball bat, he flees to a tiny
town in Louisiana and settles down to hard work and joyful
preaching.
</P>
<P>
   As the film's director, Duvall stays in pace with leisurely
small-town Southern life, but, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York
Times, the accomplishment here is ``a full, fiery, warts-and-all
portrait of Sonny without reducing him to any kind of
stereotype.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)1997. Universal. $107.37. 148 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Men With Guns
</P>
<P>
   Set in a nameless Latin American country, John Sayles' film
explores the facelessness of a civil war that could be taking place
anywhere. At an advanced point in his career, Dr. Humberto Fuentes
(Federico Luppi) journeys into rural areas to learn what became of
the young doctors he trained for duty there.
</P>
<P>
   The quest leads to combatants in a struggle for causes they are
asked to commit atrocities for but ultimately know little about. To
stress the depth of misunderstanding, Sayles directs the film in a
half-dozen languages, but his story is told ``so exactingly that
there is no true language barrier at all'' (Janet Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)1997. Columbia Tri-Star. 126 minutes. R. Spanish with
English subtitles. Release date: Tuesday.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Leading Man
</P>
<P>
   The British playwright Felix Webb (Lambert Wilson) has a comely
young mistress (Thandie Newton) and a lovely wife (Anna Galiena)
distressed enough with him to cut up his belongings with a gleaming
pair of scissors. But then Felix entertains a proposal from Robin
Grange (Jon Bon Jovi), the rakish leading man of his new
production.
</P>
<P>
   In return for financial and professional considerations, Robin
will seduce Felix's wife, setting the grounds for a future divorce.
Unfortunately, despite fine London settings and performances by
accomplished supporting players, the result is only ``watchable
without being gripping'' (Lawrence Van Gelder). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)1996. BMG. $97.99. 99 minutes. R. Release date:
Tuesday.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Alan Smithee Film: Burn Hollywood Burn
</P>
<P>
   Having always flouted the Hollywood power elite, the
screenwriter Joe Eszterhas shoots his own brand of humor in the
foot with an idea that is decidedly unfunny. A pseudonym used by
filmmakers who want their names off the credits, Smithee in this
case is a real director (Eric Idle) who, attended by a pack of
slick studio jackals, deliberately destroys his own blockbuster
when he sees it running amok.
</P>
<P>
   Stray jokes and jabs at the film industry lead to a hopelessly
flat comedy that ``has itself been given the Alan Smithee treatment
and it's not hard to see why'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)1997. Hollywood. $104.16. 86 minutes. Closed captioned.
R.(end italics)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Other new titles of interest, some of which may have
had a theater release at one time or appeared on television.(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE CLOCKMAKER (1973, 105 minutes) and A SUNDAY IN THE COUNTRY
(1984, 94 minutes). In the first of two films by Bertrand
Tavernier, based on a novel by Georges Simenon, the orderly life of
a widowed watchmaker (Philippe Noiret) in Lyons is turned upside
down when his son (Sylvain Rougerie) is arrested for murder.
</P>
<P>
   To his distress, the father discovers that he really doesn't
know his son at all, which starts a process of regeneration and the
re-establishment of a strong relationship between the two.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Sunday in the Country,'' it is 1912 and Monsieur Ladmiral
(Louis Ducreux), an elderly French painter, contemplates spending a
lazy day at his country estate preparing a grand dinner and
swapping observations about art with his son and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Then up drives Ladmiral's spirited daughter (Sabine Azema) to
take him for a ride in her new car and inject fresh spirit in his
life before dashing off as quickly as she had come.
</P>
<P>
   Both films are reissued by Kino. $24.95 each. Letterboxed.
French with English subtitles. No ratings. Information: (800)
562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   DETECTIVE (1985, 95 minutes) and PASSION (1982, 88 minutes). Two
Jean-Luc Godard films come to video for the first time. In
``Detective,'' a standard if convoluted murder case is an occasion
for ruminations on subjects from boxing to love, film making,
language and pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion'' joins a Polish director (Jerzy Radziwilowicz) in the
midst of making a film of that name while starting affairs with two
women (Hanna Schygulla and Isabelle Huppert) at the same time. Fox
Lorber. $49.98 each. French with English subtitles. No ratings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
