<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PHYSICIAN SUICIDE BILL COULD HARM PATIENTS, PANEL WARNS
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill intended to prevent physician-assisted
suicides by prohibiting the dispensing of large doses of pain
medication would instead harm patients who need strong pain relief,
a panel of health care specialists said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation introduced by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and Sen.
Don Nickles, R-Okla., would authorize the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration to investigate whenever a physician is alleged to
have prescribed a controlled drug _ such as morphine _ with the
``intent'' of assisting a suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The DEA also would have the power to revoke physicians' DEA
registration, impose large fines, and arrest them.
</P>
<P>
   The medical community is so afraid of the mere hint of a DEA
investigation that physicians and pharmacists would avoid
prescribing strong pain medication to avoid the cost, time, stigma
and adverse publicity stemming from such a probe, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason why a patient should have to wait for pain
medication, but many do,'' said Skip Baker, president of the
American Society for Action on Pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this bill passes, it will become difficult for me and
millions of others to get adequate pain medication. For some, it
will become impossible,'' said Baker, who takes a daily pain
medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a severe pain sufferer can't get the medication they
need, many commit suicide, die of heart attacks or strokes, or
suffer inhuman, unbearable pain that you can't even imagine unless
you've been there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Bennett, president of the American Society of Pain
Management Nurses, said she has seen the ``physical and mental
relief'' from pain medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a great job to tell America 'just say no,' but
there are times when you have to 'just say yes,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
