<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RUBLE-$ADV23-C     08-20 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RUBLE-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER BAILOUTS AND NOW DEVALUATION, THE TASK REMAINS: FIX
RUSSIA'S ECONOMY
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-STOCKS-$ADV23; RUBLE-DATA-$ADV23.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia is running out of options as it seeks to claw
its way out of an ever-widening financial swamp.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid bankruptcy, the government devalued the national
currency last Monday(Aug.17), allowing the ruble to decline against
the dollar by as much as 34 percent. It also announced a 90-day
moratorium on Russian commercial firms and banks repaying their
debts to banks abroad.
</P>
<P>
   It is a risky gamble intended to give President Boris Yeltsin's
government the cash and the time to tackle a gloomy array of
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's sapped financial markets virtually have ceased to
exist, its banking system is near collapse, its public debt on
borrowing from foreign banks is out of control and unpaid wages to
millions of workers is growing.
</P>
<P>
   To find a lasting fix, analysts said, Yeltsin's government, led
by Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, must fundamentally transform
the economy from the unpredictable hybrid of Soviet-era
centralization and profiteering capitalism it has become.
</P>
<P>
   It means a radical overhaul to improve tax collections, reduce
government spending and somehow win back the confidence of foreign
investors. At stake is the future of Russia and Yeltsin's now
time-worn promise when the Soviet Union collapsed seven years ago
that his people would enjoy the fruits of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the critical list. There is no more waiting,'' said
Sergei Kolmakov, a Russian political and economic analyst. ``Russia
cannot cut itself off from the world markets, but it has
demonstrated that (under the current system) it cannot keep up with
them either.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Kremlin has bounded in pinball fashion from
crisis to crisis, unable or unwilling to focus on the basic
reforms, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a $22.6 billion bailout package forged by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) was intended to see that Russia
enacted long-overdue reforms to improve tax collections and lower
its budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials also intended it to avert a devaluation,
allowing them to maintain virtually the only economic boast Yeltsin
could claim: a stable ruble and low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But the first IMF installment, $4.8 billion in July, didn't go
far. Russia had to keep spending from its hard-currency reserves to
make its debt payments, and could have soon gone bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   After a rebuff last weekend from the IMF, the United States and
other Western governments for more aid, Russian officials chose to
seek a measured devaluation, allowing the currency to float on the
market from its previous high of 6.2 rubles to the dollar to as
high as 9.5 rubles to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the deficit is vital, analysts said. The huge
government shortfalls that force Russia to borrow from foreign
banks at high interest rates produce an accumulated debt that
demands $1 billion a week in payments.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit also has meant Russia is unable to pay full wages
and pensions to millions of its citizens, triggering strikes by
miners and other laborers throughout the nation this summer. Unpaid
wages grew to $11 billion at the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Billions of dollars in taxes go uncollected every year. And as
part of the strings attached to the IMF loans, Yeltsin's government
agreed to pursue an austerity program designed to produce another
$16 billion in revenue next year.
</P>
<P>
   But tackling Russia's deeper problems has been troublesome given
the political opposition of the Communist-dominated parliament, and
the economic interests of a small group of powerful Russian
business magnates who oppose more state control over big business.
</P>
<P>
   In emergency session in July, the Duma, parliament's lower
house, rejected 11 of 25 government-sponsored bills aimed at
raising more tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma, which convened again Friday(Aug. 21) in emergency
session, expressed concern over the new troubles, but showed little
inclination to go along with Yeltsin's plans.
</P>
<P>
   But the tax problem is not merely a matter of raising rates or
of finding the cheats. It requires a basic change in the way most
Russians conduct their daily business.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the tax authority estimated that up to 58
percent of retail transactions occur in cash and barter, a shadow
economy almost impossible for tax collectors to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated $1 billion a year alone in uncollected tax revenues
is lost in the illegal sale of alcohol, primarily vodka smuggled
from abroad or produced by homemade distillers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more troubling long-term problems, according to Anders
Aslund, a former adviser to the Russian government who now works
for the Carnegie Endowment in Washington, is a weak banking system
and punishing tax rate that fails to promote small businesses and
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   With most of the country's wealth in the hands of a relatively
few powerful men, Russia has been unable to diversify its economy.
</P>
<P>
   It depends heavily on oil and natural gas exports, which have
been hit by flat prices on the world market, hovering at
10-year-lows. The government said the value of oil exports in the
first half of 1998 decreased 46 percent from 1997, compounding the
country's financial woes.
</P>
<P>
   Devaluation could give the Yeltsin government the time and the
momentum it needs to pursue its reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But the alternative result of devaluation could be chaos, a
Indonesian-style free-fall that results in social unrest and
political pressure on the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this year, as financial markets in Russia fell, the
problems were confined to the government and the elite world of
banking and finance. Now all Russians have a stake in recovery with
the devaluation of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of relative stability and low inflation,
Russians are nervously watching their rubles slide in value as
prices rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government plan will most likely solve the short-term
fiscal problem, but will open the country to the risk of
self-perpetuating inflation with all its social and political
consequences,'' said Radoslav Petkov of the Institute for East/West
Studies, a think thank.
</P>
<P>
   If devaluation doesn't work, Russia has nowhere else to turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't rush to buy dollars. If you and me and everyone rushes
to swap national currency for foreign we really will destroy the
ruble,'' the newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda urged its readers the
day after devaluation was announced. ``There will be no one but us
to blame.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
