<HEADER>
A4053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      08-20 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD BARGAIN: BUYING A BABY, SELLING A SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stockard Channing does not look at home in a Louisiana trailer
park. Which is a point ``The Baby Dance'' wants to make. There she
is, as Rachel Luckman, a well-dressed Hollywood executive, making
her way through the trash-strewn yards, fending off barking dogs,
avoiding the stares of half-naked men who are working on a car.
</P>
<P>
   Finally she reaches the trailer of Al LeFauve (Richard
Lineback), an unemployed pipe fitter, and his wife, Wanda (Laura
Dern), who is very pregnant with their fifth child. Rachel is there
to buy their baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Baby Dance,'' which has its premiere on Showtime on Sunday
night, shows us just what an agonizing, invasive and ultimately
soul-destroying process that kind of transaction can be. The film,
written and directed by Jane Anderson, based on her 1989 play, is
alternately funny and poignant.
</P>
<P>
   As Hollywood white collar and Shreveport blue collar eye each
other with polite words barely disguising mutual horror, the story
teeters constantly on the brink of the ridiculous. But thanks to
Ms. Anderson's restrained directing style and to strong, sure
performances by this cast (including Peter Riegert as Rachel's
husband, Richard), the film hangs onto its dignity.
</P>
<P>
   And the final scenes are as heart-wrenching as screen
storytelling can be, made all the more powerful by the comic
encounters that preceded them.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel and Richard have come to Shreveport for a first meeting
with Wanda and Al, who answered their ``baby wanted'' ad and have
contracted to give up their child for adoption by the Luckmans.
</P>
<P>
   The two women start out politely. Rachel brings flowers to Wanda
and says, ``Isn't this lovely?'' as she enters the cramped, hot
trailer. Wanda brings out a cold-cut plate with white bread for
lunch. But the trouble has already begun.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel and Richard had sent the LeFauves $500 to buy an
air-conditioner, but the money has been spent elsewhere. Wanda is
smoking, drinking coffee and not taking the prenatal vitamins that
Rachel had recommended. And Rachel's question about whether Wanda
might have ever considered an abortion prompts a rather basic
discussion of religion.
</P>
<P>
   Wanda just wants to be sure that the Luckmans do ``go to
church.'' The next thing you know, Rachel, who is Jewish, is
promising to celebrate Christmas with the child and in the spring
to observe Easter as well as Passover.
</P>
<P>
   As Rachel is waxing poetic about the universality of the seder
as a celebration of freedom, Wanda interrupts her with ``Well, will
you still have chocolate bunnies and jelly beans and all?''
</P>
<P>
   If Laura Dern plays one more white-trash Southerner this
effectively (``Rambling Rose,'' ``Citizen Ruth''), her fans are
going to forget she grew up privileged in Hollywood. And although
Ms. Channing is in ``Six Degrees of Separation'' mode as a
sophisticate of good will who enjoys her own clever remarks, she is
heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   The scene in which Rachel rests her head on Wanda's stomach to
listen to her future daughter's heartbeat and whisper the name she
has chosen could have been maudlin, but Ms. Channing turns it
around.
</P>
<P>
   The scene in which Ms. Channing spies Wanda's 12-year-old
daughter in the backyard _ long, silky, golden hair flowing and
catching the sunlight as she does cartwheels _ could easily have
come across like Humbert Humbert's first glimpse of Lolita.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Channing makes it pure. And when Ms. Dern then remarks,
``Now you know what the girls look like,'' her voice conveys all
the bitterness and the loss of the pact she has made with the
Devil.
</P>
<P>
   The film is far from perfect. There are a few truly terrible
lines like Riegert's to Lineback in the hospital just before the
baby's birth: ``You always have the advantage over me, my friend.
You have the ability to make life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the production designer, Brent Thomas, has a real eye for
rural squalor. And if the joke is on the poor couple _ ridiculing
their home, their language, their taste _ the Luckmans are
eventually shown to have numerous flaws of their own. One very
significant flaw, in fact, reveals itself at the end.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BABY DANCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, Sunday night at 9 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jane Anderson, writer and director; Meg LeFauve and Vicky
Herman, producers; Jodie Foster, Robert Halmi Jr., Tony Allard and
Matthew O'Connor, executive producers; Jan Kiesser, director of
photography; Brent Thomas, production designer; Norman Buckley,
editor; music by Terry Allen; costumes by Gregory Mah.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Stockard Channing (Rachel Luckman), Laura Dern (Wanda
LeFauve), Richard Lineback (Al LeFauve) and Peter Riegert (Richard
Luckman). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
