<HEADER>
A4080 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SAFETY-1STLD-WRI     08-20 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SAFETY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL ACADEMY OF SCIENCES RECOMMENDS FOOD SAFETY CZAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: MAKES minor changes in lede, alters material in 7th graf,
adds new 8th and 9th grafs.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To reduce the threat of food-borne illness, the
National Academy of Sciences on Thursday recommended the
appointment of an official with the power to manage federal
food-safety programs now run by 12 government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The new food czar would preside over such federal food-safety
activities as inspection, surveillance, investigation of
food-related illnesses, research and education.
</P>
<P>
   ``This recommendation envisions an identifiable, high-ranking,
presidentially appointed head who would direct and coordinate
federal activities and speak to the nation, giving federal
food-safety efforts a single voice,'' the academy said in a
194-page report.
</P>
<P>
   The organization is a private, non-profit research group here
that advises the government on scientific and health issues.
</P>
<P>
   Its report _ ``Ensuring Safe Food From Production to
Consumption'' _ concluded that food-safety laws are outdated and
that efforts to rid the food supply of contamination are hampered
by a fragmented federal structure.
</P>
<P>
   But the academy did not recommend merging the 12 agencies that
oversee food-safety programs. The responsibilities of those
agencies are spelled out in 35 federal laws.
</P>
<P>
   The food-safety system in the United States ``stands out as a
patchwork quilt rather than a seamless network,'' said John C.
Bailar III, chairman of the Department of Health Studies at the
University of Chicago, who headed the 13-member scientific panel
that wrote the report.
</P>
<P>
   Bailar, who spoke at a news conference Thursday, said the
``fragmentation and outdated safety laws that are still in effect
are barriers to improving the safety of the food supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailar said Congress should grant the person in charge of ``an
intergrated federal system'' the ``authority, responsibility and
resources'' to do the job. He added that this person should rank
above heads of the other agencies such as the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, the Food and Drug Administration and the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The report urged Congress to eliminate carcass-by-carcass
inspection of meat and poultry and replace it with scientific
testing for disease-causing germs.
</P>
<P>
   It also recommended a single set of regulations for all foods,
replacing the current patchwork of rules.
</P>
<P>
   Under present practice, for example, the pepperoni line in a
pizza factory is inspected daily by the Agriculture Department
while the cheese line is checked once in 10 years by the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Bailor said ``one of several possibilities'' for improving food
safety would be creating a single food-safety agency.
</P>
<P>
   The food industry reacted to the report by lambasting any
recommendation for restructuring the food regulatory system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling for a wholesale reorganization of federal
bureaucracies in Washington will not do anything to ensure the
safety of our food supply,'' said Cal Collier, senior vice
president and general counsel for Kraft Foods Inc., who chairs a
food industry group called the Food Safety-Independent Food Agency
Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   The report also urged Congress to allow food imports only from
those countries with safety standards equaling those in the United
States. President Clinton has endorsed the proposal, and Sen.
Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., has introduced legislation requiring such
a rule.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., and Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J.,
and Reps. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., and Frank Pallone, D-N.J., have also
sponsored legislation that would combine the 12 government agencies
into a single Food Safety Administration. But that proposal has
faced resistance from the food industry and from the federal
agencies that now oversee food safety.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio hailed the academy's report as ``common-sense
recommendations that will improve our food safety system.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin's spokeswoman, Melissa Merz, said, ``The message in the
report is clear that American consumers and families will benefit
from a single, coordinated approach to food safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Smith DeWaal, director of food safety for the Center
for Science in the Public Interest, a Washington advocacy group,
said a food-safety czar with power over the budgets of food safety
agencies would be a good interim step, but is ``not the final
answer to the food safety problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Short of the president of the United States, no one is really
in charge of the safety of the U.S. food supply,'' DeWaal said. ``I
don't see how a single person can really run the program unless
there is a single food safety agency.'
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office, the key investigative arm of
Congress, has estimated that contaminated food causes 9,100 deaths
and as many as 81 million illnesses a year in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal of the American Medical Association has predicted
that disease outbreaks from food-borne germs are likely to increase
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The $350,000 NAS study was financed with funds in the 1998
Department of Agriculture spending bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1659EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4086 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-HONORS-1STLD-     08-20 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-HONORS-1STLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY CENTER NAMES 6 PERFORMANCE HONOREES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please use this version)  
 (af)  
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shirley Temple, the little girl who saved a movie
studio from failure during the Depression, and Willie Nelson, who
helped reinvent country music, were among six people named Thursday
to receive the Kennedy Center's annual honors in the performning
arts.
</P>
<P>
   The others are the actor-comedian Bill Cosby, the Broadway
song-writing team of John Kander and Fred Ebb, and Andre Previn,
the composer, conductor and pianist, whose first opera, ``A
Streetcar Named Desire,'' will have its premiere at the San
Francisco Opera on Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   They will be honored at a gala at the Kennedy Center on Dec. 6,
which will be shown on CBS later that month.
</P>
<P>
   Because the award is for lifetime achievement, the recipients
are in their 60s and 70s. But although she is 70, Shirley Temple
Black is permanently engraved in the American memory as the little
moppet whose smiling optimism helped the nation through the weary
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   That memory is caused partly by her retirement from the movies
after appearing in ``A Kiss for Corliss'' when she was 21. She
appeared in 40 movies in the 1930s, before she was 12, including
``Little Miss Marker'' in 1934, the same year that she sang ``On
the Good Ship Lollipop'' in ``Bright Eyes.'' Darryl F. Zanuck said
that her movies saved his studio, 20th Century-Fox, from
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   She is remembered as well for sparkling tap dancing scenes with
Bill ``Bojangles'' Robinson, the great black dancer, at a time when
the movies did not allow close contacts between whites and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know about that until I was 7 years old,'' Mrs. Black
said Thursday from her California home, discussing the country's
race relations problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I got a cold, the studio would send me to Palm
Springs, where I stayed at the Desert Inn,'' she said, with Bill
Robinson joining her to teach her dance steps for their next movie.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Which cottage are you in?' I asked him,'' she said, ``and he
answered, `You don't need to know, darling.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When she pressed him, she recalled, he answered: ``I am in the
chauffeur's cottage over the garage. But don't you worry about it.
I'm there with (italics)my(end italics) chauffeur.''
</P>
<P>
   Kander, the music writing half of Kander and Ebb, is 71 and has
been the professional partner of Ebb, 63, for half his life _ since
1962, a year otherwise notable for his Broadway debut as the
composer for ``A Family Affair,'' which flopped.
</P>
<P>
   Every New Yorker hums their ``New York, New York,'' and most
people everywhere are familiar with their other hits, like
``Cabaret,'' ``How Lucky Can You Get,'' ``Maybe This Time'' and
``All That Jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   Their shows include ``Cabaret'' and ``Chicago,'' both of which
are now enjoying successful revivals; ``Kiss of the Spider Woman''
and, for those with long memories, ``Flora, the Red Menace,'' in
which the teen-aged Liza Minnelli made her Broadway debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like people to think of me as a good carpenter,'' Kander
said from his home in Manhattan Thursday. ``Being a good craftsman
means more to me than anything else. I take that very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to name other such craftsmen, he replied: ``Like
Stravinsky, like Gershwin, like Steve Sondheim, Jerome Kern, Jerry
Bock.'' It is very unglamorous, to be wonderful at your craft.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosby, who is 61, has been an influential performer for many
reasons, not the least being his role as co-star, with Robert Culp,
in the 1060s television series ``I Spy,'' in which he became the
first black actor to play the lead role in a weekly series.
</P>
<P>
   He achieved even greater success in the highly rated ``Cosby
Show'' and is known as well for his stand-up comedy, his comedy
records and his best-selling books.
</P>
<P>
   Previn, 69, has ranged from jazz to classical music, with
Hollywood film scores in between. He was born in Berlin and fled
from the Nazis with his family to the United States in 1939. He was
working as an orchestrator for M-G-M while still in high school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
