<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4098 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-WILLIE     08-20 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-WILLIE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WILLIE NELSON SELECTED FOR KENNEDY CENTER HONOR
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyles
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Completing a long and winding career journey from
outlaw Texas troubadour to mainstream cultural icon, Willie Nelson
was named Thursday as a winner of the 1998 Kennedy Center Honors _
the nation's highest award for lifetime achievement in the
performing arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 65-year-old singer, songwriter, guitarist, and actor
remains a restlessly creative soul,'' declared James A. Johnson,
chairman of the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Nelson, recipients to be honored at the Kennedy
Center's 21st annual national celebration of the arts are Bill
Cosby, Shirley Temple Black, composer and conductor Andre Previn
and the Broadway composer and lyricist team of John Kander and Fred
Ebb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' said Nelson, reached on the road again. He
spoke by phone from his tour bus in Boulder, Colo., where he is
promoting a new album. ``I'm really in there with a nice group of
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his legal scrapes over marijuana and taxes as well as
for his unmistakable voice and classic compositions, Nelson was
asked if he ever thought his career would be capped by such a tony
award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's recipients included Lauren Bacall, Charlton Heston
and Boy Dylan. Earlier Kennedy Center Awards have gone to Bob Hope,
Lucille Ball, Johnny Carson, Frank Sinatra, Cary Grant, Ray
Charles, Katherine Hepburn, Paul Newman and Aretha Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said this year's recipients are equally as deserving.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the unique and invaluable contribution they have made to
the cultural life of our nation,'' said Johnson, ``we honor a comic
genius who has touched millions, two men who together make up the
longest-running partnership in Broadway musical history, a man who
gave a restless new power to country music, a complete musician
whose gifts to us have ranged from chamber music and opera to the
best of jazz and film scores and an actress, who as a child star,
defined an era with her warmth and vitality.''
</P>
<P>
   The honorees will be saluted by their peers at a gala
performance on Dec. 6, which will be attended by President Clinton
and Hillary Rodham Clinton as well as artists from around the
country. The program will be broadcast on CBS television shortly
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a good show,'' said Nelson. ``I'm looking forward
to going there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two-hour telecast has received the Emmy award five
times. The Kennedy Center Honors recipients are recognized for
lifetime contributions to American culture through the performing
arts.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing its 1998 honors, the Kennedy Center called Nelson
``one of contemporary music's rare genuine icons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His music helps us to know what we are as Americans and where
we came from,'' the Center announced.
</P>
<P>
   Born on April 30, 1933, in Abbott, Texas, Nelson got his first
guitar at the age of six and grew up on the music of fellow Texans
Bob Wills and Ernest Tubbs. Four decades ago, he made his initial
impact on country music as a Nashville songwriter of such classics
as ``Crazy,'' ``Night Life'' and ``Funny How Time Slips Away.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Nelson headed home to Texas and led the ``outlaw''
movement of rollicking, honky-tonk music, recording hit albums
including ``Shotgun Willie,'' ``The Red-Haired Stranger'' and
``Wanted: The Outlaws.'' At the end of the decade, though, he
abruptly changed directions with the the album ``Stardust'' _ a
collection of pop standards.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Nelson embarked on an acting career _ appearing in movies
``Thief,'' ``The Electric Horseman,'' ``Honeysuckle Rose'' and,
most recently, ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, he has toured almost constantly _ sending fans
to their feet with the opening chords of ``Whiskey River.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Nelson helped reinvent country music,'' proclaimed the
Kennedy Center announcement. ``Throughout his career, he has not
only entertained, but he has given us part of our heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
