<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-FLYTOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fly right: Hire a plane to take in McKinley
 &HT;    By James D. Smith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALKEETNA, Alaska _The drone of single-engine airplanes taking
off from Talkeetna State Airport sounds like the hungry buzzing of
an Alaska-sized army of mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   For days the pilots have been restricted because of poor flying
conditions in the area around Mount McKinley, North America's
highest peak. Now that the clouds are lifting, they're eager to get
back in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Located 100 miles north of Anchorage and 135 miles south of the
entrance to Denali National Park, the airport in this small
community of mom-and-pop shops and eateries has become a center for
McKinley sightseeing and mountaineering activities. Alaskans call
it ``flightseeing,'' and given the rugged vastness of the state's
terrain, it's a smart way to cover a lot of territory in a short
time.
</P>
<P>
   You can take your pick from several services, all of which offer
several options, based on length of flight and whether a glacier
landing is included. Prices, according to brochures that can be
picked up at the Talkeetna Ranger Station, run from $75 for a
one-hour round trip that gives you a closer aerial view of the
mountain to $185 for a two-hour trip around the top of 20,320-foot
McKinley. My wife and I chose a 2 1/2-hour flight that circled
McKinley at a ``mere'' 12,000-feet but included a landing on the
Ruth Glacier, costing us $175 each.
</P>
<P>
   The grandeur of hundreds of square miles of green forest
interspersed with meadows, lakes and muskegs _ the Alaskan swamp or
bog, a favorite haunt for moose, bears and other wildlife _ spreads
out beneath you at liftoff. In the distance, 50 miles to the north,
loom the soaring peaks of the Alaska Range and, towering above them
all, Mount McKinley.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to you on headsets, which also cut down on cabin noise,
your pilot provides a running commentary and answers questions.
You'll also be able to listen to other air traffic as pilots call
in their positions and chat with each other.
</P>
<P>
   On the longer flights, you'll eventually be surrounded by jagged
peaks as your small plane darts in and out of the folds of the
mountains, bringing you face to face with McKinley before
catapulting you around to the other side of the mountain. During
summer, it's likely at some point that you'll see a thin black line
of mountaineers snaking their way along a ridge as they head to the
mountain's summit.
</P>
<P>
   Because conditions around McKinley can change rapidly _ the
mountain creates its own weather _ it's the pilot's call on whether
to attempt a glacier landing.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining a favorable report on conditions, our pilot set us
down. Manually lowering our plane's skis into position (after
warning us not to be alarmed by the noise they make), he glided us
down to a smooth landing.
</P>
<P>
   It's exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping onto the glacial ice, we were thrust into a snow-white
world lined with jagged peaks, stabbing the deep-blue sky like the
spines of a giant dragon's tail. After 30 minutes or so of photo
taking and ``gee-whizzing,'' we reluctantly clambered back into the
plane for the return trip.
</P>
<P>
   Booking a flightseeing trip is easy enough. Many services have
toll-free numbers and Web sites. There's also a commercial visitor
information center at the junction of the Parks Highway and the
Talkeetna Spur Road, the only road leading into Talkeetna.
</P>
<P>
   While reservations are recommended, my wife and I simply showed
up and put our name on a waiting list at K2 Aviation, the second
air service we visited (the first was too backlogged trying to get
climbers down off the mountain to deal with a couple of walk-ups),
and checked back several hours later as instructed after having
lunch and touring the town's gift and souvenir shops.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information:
</P>
<P>
   K2 Aviation, Box 545-B, Talkeetna, AK 99676; 1-800-764-2291;
http://www
</P>
<P>
   .alaska.net/(tilde)flyk2.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Geeting Aviation, Box 42, Talkeetna, AK 99676;
1-800-770-2366; http://www.alaskan.com/airtours
</P>
<P>
   /tour.html.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson Air Service, Box 648, Talkeetna, AK 99676; 907-733-2321;
http://www
</P>
<P>
   .alaskan.com/hudsonair.
</P>
<P>
   Talkeetna Air Taxi, Box 73, Talkeetna, AK 88676; 1-800-533-2219;
http://www
</P>
<P>
   .alaska.net/(tilde)flytat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
