<HEADER>
A4156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALASKA-HIKING-COX     08-20 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-HIKING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intrepid hikers forge through a glacier-strewn, glorious summer
landscape
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska_There were nine of us, all strangers who would
become close friends _ possibly for life _ in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   We slogged through shoulder-high foliage to get to Ptarmigan
Lake near Moose Pass, Alaska, 100 miles south of Anchorage. We
switchbacked up rocky slopes so steep we had to hug the ground to
keep from sliding hundreds of feet to the base of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   There were days when a brisk and sometimes abrupt and biting
July wind threatened to slam us to the ground as we navigated
strenuous, and often treacherous, hikes through snow and along ice
fields. Layer upon layer of clothing warmed us.
</P>
<P>
   That's summer hiking in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Two guides from Timberline Adventures, a Denver outfitter,
waited for us in the lobby of an Anchorage hotel for the start of a
lodge-to-lodge trip that would take us via van 130 miles south to
Seward through towns with names such as Moose Pass and Aleyeska, on
hikes along the Iditarod Trail to Crows Pass and for a boat trip on
the Gulf of Alaska past blue-tinted glaciers that thundered when
sections broke away.
</P>
<P>
   The water was battleship-gray. The flowers, in fields edged with
ice fields, were in bloom. The Alaskan king crab legs awaiting us
at dinner were huge.
</P>
<P>
   The tourist season is short, usually June through August. Often,
space is scarce; a trip halfway around the Northern Hemisphere
should be booked several months in advance, so fall is the best
time to plan.
</P>
<P>
   But once you make plane reservations and book a date with an
outfitter (there are several that lead hikers and bikers through
Alaska), all you have to do is show up; the outfitters make all the
arrangements for meals, hotels or camp sites and transportation. In
addition to hiking and biking, some outfitters schedule at least a
day of rafting or kayaking, boating to a glacier or taking a ride
on the Alaska Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Our first hike was along the Coastal Trail, within the city
limits of Anchorage but seemingly in a wilderness. Aside from the
bald eagle sightings _ and the breathtaking scenery of a place
where everything seemed larger that anywhere else in the United
States _ the easy walk along Cook Inlet bore little resemblance to
the more demanding hikes we would take over the next five days.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the week, the routine was to put together our
own lunches using the supply of sandwich makings the guides
provided, hike three or four hours, eat our sandwiches, cookies,
trail mix and chips at the end of the trail, then retrace our
steps.
</P>
<P>
   Like the first walk, the second day's 15-mile trek started out
with our being surrounded by grass and flowers. Our hike began at
the Glenn Alps trail head in Chugach State Park and headed up
Powerline Pass just outside Anchorage. The temperature was in the
mid-60s. The trail was relatively flat until we reached a
10-foot-wide stream, almost knee deep, that we had to ford
barefoot.
</P>
<P>
   That was where things changed abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   Green turned to brown. Wind gusts threatened to blow us over.
And the spongy path lined with ice and snow seemed to head straight
up.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us made it to the top and to the edge of Ship Lake for a
view of the Chugach range, while a few chose to huddle behind
boulders, away from the cold wind.
</P>
<P>
   Day three found us on the Iditarod Trail, heading toward Crows
Pass. Many started in T-shirts and shorts only to have added layers
of sweaters and fleece by the time we'd reached a Forestry Service
hostel halfway up the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The trail took us across three steams that started with water
from melting glaciers, past the remnants of an abandoned gold mine,
across snow bridges tipped perilously at 45-degree angles and a
switchback of rock and dirt that was so narrow it barely allowed
room for one person to pass. But once at the top of Crows Pass,
from a snowy bluff tinted red with algae, we could look down on
Raven Glacier, a mountain of ice covering thousands of acres far
below.
</P>
<P>
   Our fourth full day of hiking took us to Ptarmigan Lake, part of
Chugach National Forest, which abuts the state park. We had no snow
or steep climbs. No wind either, but an almost constant drizzle.
And instead of making our way across rock, we bushwhacked through
shoulder-high grass and ferns.
</P>
<P>
   One by one we skirted a swift stream, passing prickly bushes we
were warned not to touch. The guides didn't know the name of the
shrubs, which have a bite that's sharp and often infectious. Three
hours later, our clothes wet and our boots filled with water, we
reached quiet and isolated Ptarmigan Lake, gray from mountain
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The last hike, at Kenai Fjords National Park, was the most
difficult but by far the most spectacular _ hiking from the base of
Exit Glacier to the edge of the Harding ice field, named for
President Warren G. Harding, who died in Alaska after eating
tainted seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the trail was nothing more than rocks stacked one atop
the other and moraines, narrow ledges that mark various natural
boundaries formed as the glacier receded over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Marmots darted in and out of the boulders along the path, afraid
to get too close but curious about the traffic through their world.
Mountain sheep chewed on flowers and grass uphill from a path lined
with snow.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,100 feet from where we started was an ocean of ice 35
miles long and 20 miles wide surrounded by mountains that literally
appeared purple.
</P>
<P>
   The hugeness of everything made whispering seem more appropriate
if it was absolutely necessary to speak.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: A number of outfitters lead hikes through
Alaska. The cost varies with the amenities offered. The charge for
the Timberline Adventures hike was at the low end, at $1,395 for
six days and five nights. For a similar trip that is a day longer,
Backroads charges $2,198. Among the outfitters to consider:
</P>
<P>
   Timberline Adventures, 1-800-417-2453.
http//www.timbertours.com/tours./
</P>
<P>
   Backroads Active Travel, 1-800 462-2848.
http//www.backroads.com.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain Travel Sobek, 1-888 687-6235. http//www.mtsobek.com.
</P>
<P>
   North Star, 1-800-258-8434. http//www.adventuretrip.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALASKA-MAIN-COX     08-20 2495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tourists, at long last, observe science in action at Seward
research station
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEWARD, Alaska _It's breakfast time in this northern hamlet of
mountain and ocean, time for a bucket of herring between buddies.
Dennis Christen carries the salty morning morsels _ served over ice
_ through a labyrinth of laboratory hallways until he reaches the
shores of the Alaska SeaLife Center. Two slick-brown flippers
emerge from a concrete pool, followed by the 580-pound bulk of
Woody the sea lion, who sniffs the air for the familiar fishy
scent.
</P>
<P>
   Like a daily exchange between teacher and favorite student,
Christen calls out a few friendly salutations before beginning the
feeding/training session. With wide eyes and whiskered chin
pointing skyward, Woody intently watches Christen's hand gestures
and obeys, barring his teeth for a brushing, then lying down on a
rope to have girth and blubber density measured. Christen wings a
few herring Woody's way, along with a soothing chorus of ``Good
boy, Woody, that's a g-ooo-ooo-d boy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alaska SeaLife center, which opened in May, was created to
help endangered sea creatures like Woody. It took one of mankind's
worst affronts to the ocean to spur the building of a
state-of-the-science facility for rehabilitating and researching
marine mammals. Penalties of $37.5 million paid by Exxon Corp.
after it spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil into Alaskan
waters nine years ago provided the bulk of construction money for
the $52 million, 115,000-square-foot SeaLife Center.
</P>
<P>
   Blackening 1,600 miles of Alaska's south-central coast and
islands and contaminating and killing thousands of birds and
animals, the Exxon Valdez oil spill was precisely what many
residents had predicted if a tanker ever ran aground in Prince
William Sound: disaster.
</P>
<P>
   While the black muck did not foul the beaches of Seward, the
town got deeply involved _ fashioning one of many makeshift
stations for cleaning slicked and sick sea otters and birds.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for this unique blend of mammal research and
rehabilitation center had been discussed in the state for three
decades, long before the 1989 disaster that confirmed the need for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Seward lobbied hard for the facility for many reasons. It
already had a small oceanography research center operated by the
University of Alaska at Fairbanks that had outgrown its tanks and
labs. It also wanted a big draw to encourage cruise ships to dock
awhile longer, and for tourists to drive from Anchorage, about 125
miles north. Geology gave Seward an edge. Although surrounded by
glaciers and mountains, its deep harbor is always ice-free,
allowing for year-round research in and out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Seward, a town of 3,000, approved $17 million in
revenue bonds for construction costs, and residents raised $6
million in private donations. It was a classic grass-roots effort:
$1 million alone came from perpetual bake sales and relentless
door-to-door campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The SeaLife Center's $6.25 million annual operating budget is
almost entirely dependent on gate receipts and gift shop sales. The
center's 250,000 yearly visitation projections _ considered wishful
thinking by some _ appear to be on track. Only 10 weeks after
opening day, the center's 100,000th visitor tipped the turnstyle.
Tourism throughout Alaska is strongest mid-May to mid-September,
when coastal towns such as Seward swarm with day-trippers from
cruise ships.
</P>
<P>
   But playing the odds comes naturally to Alaska towns,
particularly those that have survived earthquakes (Seward was
rocked by North America's worst in 1964), tidal waves, golddiggers,
get-rich dreamers, gamblers, thieves _ and oil spills. Such is the
history of Seward, founded by Russian Alexander Baranov, who sailed
into the bay out of a storm on Easter Sunday 1781. The beautiful
blue-green harbor came to be known as Resurrection Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Research first, then tourism
</P>
<P>
   Tucked between ocean and mountains, glaciers and gold rush
trails, the SeaLife Center gives visitors a window to the sea. It
is designed to be two parts research and animal rehabilitation and
one part tourist attraction. But it's tourism without any tricks.
There are no hourly shows featuring jumping seals or swirling sea
lions. No little fish for sale to feed the big critters. The
emphasis is on education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're merging the outside with the inside,'' executive
director Kim Sundberg says. ``You see a king crab exhibit and
you're sitting right on the edge of the water where they fish for
them. You take a tour boat and see the sea lions in the wild and
then come back to the SeaLife Center and you're looking that sea
lion in the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   On exhibit now are three Steller sea lions, eight harbor seals,
15 river otters and dozens of seabirds. More injured or sick
smaller animals may be rehabilitated here, but no additional large
marine mammals are expected as permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
   The facility is two stories high, with the first-floor
laboratories closed to the public but open for viewing from large
windows on the second floor. From this perch, visitors can peer
down into large stalls where various animals may be getting poked
and prodded for measurements, blood specimens or for other
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scientists are on display just like the animals,'' jokes
research director Michael Castellini, one of 60 full-time
employees. ``That was an important aspect of the design of the
SeaLife Center. The permits we have for these animals are
exclusively research permits, not aquarium permits.''
</P>
<P>
   Data of every conceivable kind are recorded, computed and
categorized. Blubber density. Tooth and beak growth. Fur thickness.
Stool counts.
</P>
<P>
   Two wet labs feature rows of ceiling showerheads that could
shoot gallons of salt water on animals slicked by oil or other
contaminants. There are also four dry labs, an autopsy room and
areas devoted to fish genetics. Staff and visiting researchers take
on as many as 15 simultaneous animal studies.
</P>
<P>
   Steller sea lions are a special focus. Since the 1970s,
scientists have been baffled by the animals' dramatic population
decline in Alaskan waters, the primary habitat in the world for
these massive, energetic mammals that are often dubbed bears of the
sea. Declared endangered, the population of Steller sea lions in
Seward's Kenai Peninsula region has fallen from 150,000 to 25,000.
Theories about the decline abound: a drop in food supply; ecosystem
changes; habitat intrusion. But there has been no easy way to
research these animals since few are in captivity and those in the
wild are too aggressive and unwieldy to study _ although that
hasn't deterred a determined league of marine biologists from
trying.
</P>
<P>
   Since transferring Woody and two other Stellers in March from
Vancouver Aquarium in British Columbia, where they'd been raised as
pups, Christen is making progress on this uncharted man-mammal
bond. Christen, 25, relocated from the Vancouver Aquarium to stay
with the mammals he met as part of a high school science honors
program. That launched his career in marine mammal training.
</P>
<P>
   ``In nature, these animals are very aggressive,'' Castellini
says. ``The fact that Dennis can have them trained for research
protocols is extremely impressive. He can ask them to get in a
cage: Give a hand signal, and they do it. Nowhere else in the world
is that done.''
</P>
<P>
   One study alters diets of the sea lions to look for differences
between them and their wild counterparts. Scientists theorize
ecosystem changes have forced Steller sea lions to switch from once
abundant and healthy herring to a steady diet of pollock, fish that
Castellini considers ``junk food of the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Steller sea lions can grow to 1,500 pounds and 9 feet in length.
Since March, Woody has gained 200 pounds, more than the females
Sugarloaf and Kiska. (Woody, for now, must be separated from the
girls because of stirring teenage hormones _ researchers don't want
to deal with pregnant animals just yet.)
</P>
<P>
   Stellers are not California sea lions, a smaller, more docile
animal and the ones trained to balance balls on their snouts in
aquarium performances. ``California sea lions are the border
collies,'' Christen says, ``while Stellers are the bull mastiffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Taming and training them not only takes buckets of
positive-reinforcement herring but a positive approach, Christen
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm of a very firm belief that if you're positive and upbeat
when dealing with them, they'll respond. You have to be able to
motivate them to cooperate. A lot of this research stuff is boring
to them, so you need to be happy and upbeat. If you're having a bad
day, you have to put that aside when working with them because they
can read you very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Close to nature
</P>
<P>
   Wraparound windows on the ocean accent the slate-gray stone
building located at the end of Seward's main commercial street,
Fourth Avenue. Jagged peaks of the Chugach Mountains rise behind
the center, and sailboats and sea otters play in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping inside the glass entrance, visitors first see a
dangling Dall's porpoise. These black and white carvings, the work
of local artist Jim Ramsdell, hang from the ceiling, in pursuit of
smaller fish. And inside them is a bit of local history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote a poem for the porpoise,'' Seward sixth-grader Sean
Chase says. ``It's a time capsule, and our school put pictures,
poems and letters inside the mom porpoise's belly.'' Then, like the
rest of the local kids touring their world-class backyard
attraction, the 12-year-old scampers off for yet another ride up
the first escalator in this part of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor's tour is predetermined at the SeaLife Center,
beginning with a progression of exhibits encountered as you step
off the escalator on the second floor (providing, of course, the
first-floor gift shop is saved for last).
</P>
<P>
   An optional short video on sea mammals leads to the first
hallway of exhibits _ small displays of jellyfish and kelp, and an
explanation of the life cycle of Coho salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Next comes a separate room devoted entirely to explaining the
Valdez oil spill, its cleanup and long-term damage to wildlife and
the shoreline. Lifesize cutouts of people affected by the spill,
and those participating in the cleanup _ such as fishermen (and
women) and Alaskan natives _ explain the consequences of that
fateful night in large text displays. Extensive photographs and
maps line the walls. Simple, concise descriptions of the day-by-day
spreading of the spill provide an easy-to-understand synopsis of a
complex situation.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only place Exxon is mentioned at the facility, even
though $37.5 million in oil company settlements helped build the
center. For some, this exhibit may seem packed with images already
seen and known the world over: pitiful sea otters, sad-eyed seals,
blackened birds. But it also leaves a lasting impression on many,
especially school and youth groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the oil spill, even though I was only 7 years old
at the time,'' says Quincy Opdycke, a 16-year-old from Fairbanks'
Frontier High School. ``If they're going to make a mistake that
big, they need to make an even bigger contribution to fix it and to
prevent it from ever happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Dustin Farnum, owner of an Anchorage communications
company, ``This exhibit is pretty upfront about the whole oil
spill. It tells you exactly what is known and unknown ... even what
Exxon doesn't want you to know.''
</P>
<P>
   After the reality check of the oil spill display comes the
center's ``Please Do Touch'' exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Intertidal creatures _ sea stars, sea urchins and other
invertebrates _ hang out in an open tank called the Discovery Zone.
Here, visitors dip their hands in the salt water and examine the
bright undersides of the ``stars of the sea,'' such as sunflower
star, true star, vermillion star and leather star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, this one isn't spiny. It's kind of hairy,'' one boy tells
his less-enthralled mom upon picking up a snail-like creature
called a hairy triton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, are these good to eat?'' another curious kid asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' volunteer Lani Lockwood patiently replies.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the Discovery Zone is another discovery zone of sorts,
the viewing windows into the research labs below and to backyard
tanks and concrete pools where the seals and sea lions are
sometimes kept when being studied.
</P>
<P>
   The tour then moves to the large habitats of the sea lions,
seals and sea birds. The animals are free to romp in and out of
their tanks and around rocks sculpted to resemble Resurrection
Bay's coastline. Nearby, puffins, murres and other birds flutter
around the burrows in their screened-in quarters. At the sea lion
and seal habitats are several indoor and outdoor observation
points; the birds can be seen from afar along the edge of their
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   From here, visitors descend into the exhibit ``Denizens of the
Deep,'' which is the underwater view of the second-story sea lion
and seal habitats. From this vantage point, animals and humans
enjoy the view of each other through laminated glass encasing the
100,000-gallon tank.
</P>
<P>
   The area outside the tanks allows ample elbow room for excitable
kids and baby-strolling parents. Here, children could spend hours
communing with the noses and faces of chocolate-brown seals and sea
lions.
</P>
<P>
   That was the scene in May when Seward residents got a sneak
preview. Kids and their parents couldn't seem to tear themselves
away from watching Woody and his two sea lion gal pals, Kiska and
Sugarloaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful for the kids, '' said Debbie Darakas,
who was touring with her son and his friends while on a break from
her nearby Greek restaurant, Apollo. ``We've been waiting for this
all to come together for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some local residents are concerned tourists will travel
to this far-flung Alaska town only to be disappointed by the
center's style _ which is long on lessons but short on souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Sea World,'' says Barbara Fleming, one of the
center's 100 volunteers. ``I think that will be the biggest
misperception to overcome. Visitors look at the (EKG heart) patches
on the seals and wonder why we're doing that to them. ... The
animals just happen to be cute.''
</P>
<P>
   Seward Mayor Bob Satin, who also doubles as a ranger at nearby
Kenai Fjords National Park, believes those tourists will ``get
educated despite their preconceived notions.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a typical Last Frontier lunch of reindeer sausage, hold the
mustard, Satin says, ``You know, this is an amazing effort for this
size community. I think there are still some people who believe
we'll fall flat on our face. But this is Alaska. Here, we make big
things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
