<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-FOX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX TAKES EARLY AIM AT FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By TV's strange system of reckoning, fall begins Sunday. True,
most of the networks' prime-time shows will be premiering nearer
the week of Sept. 21 _ the official start of fall for ratings
purposes. Fox, however, hopes to hook viewers with an early look at
its revised Sunday lineup.
</P>
<P>
   For those not paying attention, Fox is moving its popular
animated comedy, ``King of the Hill,'' to Tuesdays in a bid to
jump-start a loser night. Fox is also trimming ``The World's
Funniest . . . '' to a half-hour, maybe less, depending on how long
Sunday football runs.
</P>
<P>
   Taking up the slack are two new comedies that will bookend ``The
Simpsons.'' On one end, at 7:30, is ``Holding the Baby,'' an
American treatment of a British sitcom. After ``The Simpsons'' (and
before ``The X-Files'') comes ``That '70s Show,'' a puckish paean
to a mellower time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '70s Show'' is from the creators of ``3rd Rock from the
Sun,'' and it has the same roguish sense of fun without as much
over-the-top silliness. It focuses on a superbly cast ensemble of
actors who play six teenagers in the safely suburban enclave of
Point Place, Wis. Five of them are locals, the sixth an exchange
student from, well, no one is quite sure. Neither social outcasts
nor A-list regulars, they fall neatly into that big in-between
where most teens dread to be seen. Their hangout is the basement of
Eric Forman's house, where they spend most of their time doing _ or
thinking about doing _ whatever their parents told them not to do.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking, drugs and disobedience pop up in episode one, to the
dismay of some fun-busters who've questioned the wisdom of
highlighting bad behavior without including repercussions. The
producers say that won't always be the case, but let's hope they
don't lose sight of that eerie disconnect that encompassed the
'70s. From snips of the Captain &AMP; Tennille to reminders on the
versatility of Vienna sausages, ``That '70s Show'' is unbelievably
believable.
</P>
<P>
   Topher Grace, a newcomer to TV, plays Eric Forman with such ease
that it's hard to believe he's acting. And Laura Prepon, another TV
newbie, is a star in the making as Eric's best friend, Donna
Pinciotti. Though they're only a month apart in age, Donna is
physically and intellectually more mature, leading to wonderfully
awkward moments between the two.
</P>
<P>
   They and their friends _ dim bulb Michael (Ashton Kutcher),
annoying Jackie (Mila Kunis), suspicious Steve (Danny Masterson)
and wide-eyed Fez (Wilmer Valderrama) _ are a gourmet assortment of
mixed nuts who put a smiley face on some well-written,
well-directed material.
</P>
<P>
   The single-parent gambit, meanwhile, is played for the zillionth
time in ``Holding the Baby,'' but it does have a certain charm.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Patrick Walker plays newly single dad Gordon Stiles with an
American sort of Hugh Grant dash. Jennifer Westfeldt plays Kelly
O'Malley, a graduate student who'd like to work at Stiles' office,
but Stiles is more in need of a nanny because his wife has decided
to abandon him and their baby in a quest for inner peace with her
new lover in the Himalayas. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen all the situations before, but Walker, Westfeldt and
Eddie McClintock (as irresponsible brother Jimmy Stiles) seem
capable of delivering with flair. It's incumbent on the writers,
then, not to drop the baby.
</P>
<P>
   _ Holding the Baby. Half-hour comedy about a workaholic who gets
a crash course in parenting when his wife walks out. Premieres
Sunday. Check local listigs. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _ That '70s Show. Half-hour comedy about six teens coming of age
in the mid-'70s. Premieres Sunday. Check local listings. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send an e-mail
message to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
