<HEADER>
A4161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALASKA-IFYOUGO-COX     08-20 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKA-IFYOUGO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If you go. .to Alaska
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    BY Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEALIFE CENTER
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: $12.50 adults; $10 ages 4-16; under 4 free.
Summer hours: 9 a.m.-9:30 p.m. daily. Sept. 21-Oct. 18: 10 a.m.-7
p.m. daily. Winter hours: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Wednesday-Sunday (closed
Monday-Tuesday). 1-800-224-2525 or http://www.alaskasealife.org.
</P>
<P>
   SEWARD DETAILS
</P>
<P>
   -- Welcoming tourists: A downtown trolley ($1) shuttles visitors
to hotels, restaurants, the harbor and campgrounds. An information
center in a historic railroad car offers plenty of free tourist
guidebooks. With the arrival of the SeaLife Center, hotels are
expanding, restaurants are opening and locals are converting extra
rooms to bed-and-breakfast inns.
</P>
<P>
   -- Outdoor activities: The so-called ``Alpine village by the
sea'' is an outdoor enthusiasts' paradise. Lakes and lush forests
make for great camping and exploring _ whether roughshod on
mountain bikes or in wide-load Winnebagos. The town is on
Resurrection Bay, entry to some of the most stunning coastal Alaska
scenery. Whales, sea otters, dolphins, seals and other marine
animals are easily seen year-round from all types of guided tour
boats or from kayaks, sailboats or fishing vessels, available to
rent. Call Sunny Cove Sea Kayaking Co., 907-345-5339; Sea Lion
Sports Boat Rentals, 907-224-7171; Kenai Fjords Tours,
1-800-468-8068.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking, skiing and glacier exploring are also popular (Trails
North, 907-224-3587; groups only). So is ``flightseeing,''
sightseeing by small plane and helicopter (Alaska Aerial Tours,
1-888-248-6898; Bear Lake Air &AMP; Guide Service, 1-800-224-5985).
</P>
<P>
   Also, many outfitters rent equipment and offer guide services.
Or you could let the dogs do the work. Check out dog-sled
demonstrations and rides (even when there's no snow, it's done on
wheeled sleds) at IditaRide Sled Dog Tours on Old Exit Glacier Road
(907-224-8607).
</P>
<P>
   -- Lodging (higher prices are summer rates):
</P>
<P>
   Harborview Inn: New rooms feature lovely carved wood furniture,
native art and massive stone fireplaces. Great views of Mount
Marathon. $49-$109. 1-888-324-3217.
</P>
<P>
   Best Western Hotel Seward: Large rooms, bay windows. Located
downtown, one block from the SeaLife Center, with bay and mountain
views. $69-$203. Also, two-story, luxurious log cabin on a cliff
overlooking harbor features deck and hot tub. $125 (winter); $329
(summer). 907-224-2378.
</P>
<P>
   Bell-in-the-Woods B&AMP;B: Country style, serving full breakfast.
$80-$150. 907-224-7271.
</P>
<P>
   VanGilder Hotel: Creaky but charming. On the National Register
of Historic Places. $95 double, $165 suite. 907-224-3525.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: Seward Chamber of Commerce, Box 749, Seward, AK
99664. 907-224-8051.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   -- Car: From Anchorage, take the 125-mile Seward Highway (Alaska
1/9). The SeaLife Center is at mile 0. Spectacular views of
mountains, ice fields, forests and maybe a moose or two make this
drive a show-stopper. It's the only highway where I've ever been
stopped for driving too slow. The excuse, ``Well, I've never been
to Alaska and it's so beautiful. Guess that's why I'm driving so
slow,'' doesn't fly. The speed limit varies from 55 to 65 mph;
minimum is 45 mph but not recommended because you'll be slowing
traffic on the two-lane.
</P>
<P>
   -- Train: The Alaska Railroad runs a small train from Anchorage
to Seward daily in summer only; $40 one way. 1-800-544-0552.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ferry: Seward is on the route known as the Alaska Marine
Highway, which takes visitors by ferry along the southeastern coast
and the Kodiak and Aleutian Islands. 1-800-642-0066.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bus, fly: Seward Bus Lines runs several buses from Anchorage
daily (907-563-0800). Several one-way 45-minute flights also leave
daily (summer only) on F.S. Air (907-224-5920) and Era Aviation
(1-800-866-8394).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
