<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   EDITORS: Amen Ra Films (Afrakhan Minds Engaged N Royal Affairs) is
correct.  
 (smw)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; How Fox Got Its Groove Back  &LR;  HOLLYWOOD _ A black flag wasn't
quite fluttering at 20th Century Fox last summer, but the mood at
the studio was decidedly bleak. ``Speed 2: Cruise Control,'' the
adventure-action sequel to ``Speed,'' was the biggest disaster of
the summer. And the studio had sunk more than $140 million into
``Titanic,'' whose cost had run amok. The word was that Rupert
Murdoch, who owns the studio, would chop off a head or two.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Like many studios in town, which go through tough times one year
and bounce back the next, Fox has returned to almost dominate the
summer season with a series of hits that were not entirely
expected, like ``There's Something About Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   William Mechanic, chairman of Fox Filmed Entertainment, said
that seven of eight films released by the studio in recent months
would turn a profit, the lone exception Warren Beatty's
``Bulworth,'' a political comedy that was critically acclaimed but
failed to stir much enthusiasm at the box office. The most
successful film is ``There's Something About Mary,'' the dumb but
very funny comedy that cost about $25 million and has already
grossed nearly $92 million. The film has made Cameron Diaz a star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear we couldn't keep spending the kind of money we
were spending on movies,'' Mechanic said. ``We had to make some
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is that relatively inexpensive Fox films like ``Hope
Floats,'' ``Ever After'' and perhaps such newcomers as ``How Stella
Got Her Groove Back'' and ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' seem headed
for success. Costly movies like ``Dr. Dolittle'' and perhaps ``The
X-Files'' will also turn a profit. In the meantime, ``Titanic,''
which was also financed by Paramount, has grossed nearly $600
million in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have we learned this summer?'' Mechanic said. ``The
audience generally is seeking something else, something new. Look
at the success of `Saving Private Ryan.' It's clearly cutting
against the grain and is an action picture with a brain and a
voice. The success of that is positive for the whole business.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dergarabedian, president of the Exhibitor Relations
Company, which monitors the box office, said that the lesson so far
was that summer is no longer a season when studios unload only
their big action films plus family movies, saving their more
serious films for the fall, when moviegoers are not on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Saving Private Ryan' belied that _ it's not your typical
summer action popcorn movie,'' Dergarabedian said. ``People have
now learned you can release any kind of film in the summer as long
as it's good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which was made by Dreamworks and
Paramount, cost about $65 million. Executives at both studios
privately thought at first that the Steven Spielberg World War II
drama was so intense and so long (2 hours and 40 minutes) that
audiences would shy away from it and turn to more escapist fare.
</P>
<P>
   But the film, buoyed by dazzling critical reviews, has been No.
1 at the box office for the last three weeks, is expected to gross
as much as $190 million and is probably the biggest hit of the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Snipes Does `Blade'  &LR;  Wesley Snipes says he has seen too many
of his films come and go, mostly go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk down the street and someone says, `Hey man, I like you
as an actor, but I see some of the films you're in and you are
wacked,' '' Snipes said. ``And I say: `Hey man, I agree with you.
These weren't the films I wanted to make.'''
</P>
<P>
   So Snipes took matters into his own hands. His company, Amen Ra
Films (Afrakhan Minds Engaged N Royal Affairs), decided to produce
``Blade,'' a futuristic thriller about a vampire hunter, played by
Snipes. The action hero Blade was introduced to comic book fans in
1973 as a supporting character in Marvel Comics' ``Tomb of
Dracula,'' and over the years has become a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Blade was a comic book superhero who had special appeal for
Snipes. ``You rarely see African-American superheroes in movies,''
he said. ``That has positive social ramifications.''
</P>
<P>
   But what especially appealed to Snipes was the degree of control
he had over the film, which is being released on Friday by New
Line. ``As an actor for hire, your job and influence are finished
once you leave the set,'' said Snipes, whose action films include
``Passenger 57,'' ``Demolition Man,'' ``Money Train,'' ``U.S.
Marshals,'' ``The Fan'' and ``Drop Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be disheartening, putting in four months, five months,
and then it comes out and you're not satisfied with it,'' he said.
``For this one, I wanted to have my hands on it, my spirit in it.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, Snipes said, that he was involved with the
screenplay (written by David S. Goyer) as well as the casting,
production and action sequences. ``This is the way to go for me,''
said Snipes, whose production company also made ``Down in the
Delta,'' a modest drama that marked Maya Angelou's directorial
debut and had its premiere at the recent Urbanworld Film Festival
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes acknowledged that it's sometimes frustrating to be known
as an action star, when so much of his career has rested on serious
or at least nonaction films. He starred in such dramas as
``Waterdance'' and ``One Night Stand,'' as well as Spike Lee's
``Mo' Better Blues'' and ``Jungle Fever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I play a lot of average guys; I like to play average guys, but
the trouble is people don't remember those parts,'' Snipes said.
``People are aware of the action parts because of the publicity
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes said he was uncertain about his next project. But he was
quite sure of one thing: ``It won't be an action film.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR; A Crocodile in Maine  &LR;  When Steve Miner directs a horror film
like ``Halloween: H20'' he hears movie music in his head. ``I watch
a scene unfold, and I try to play in my mind an old Bernard
Herrmann score to feel the suspense,'' said Miner, whose new film
stars Jamie Lee Curtis in the role that started her career 20 years
ago in John Carpenter's landmark original ``Halloween.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I make a horror film, I think of myself as sitting in the
audience and what would scare me,'' Miner said. ``The audience is a
partner in horror movies. The audience wants a roller-coaster ride.
You try to give it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the film's box office receipts dropped sharply in its
second week _ horror-film fans are often teen-agers who show up
over the first weekend _ the movie had already grossed more than
$40 million, making it a success for Miramax's Dimension Films.
``I'm just gratified at the reaction: we were only a blip on the
radar screen in May compared to all the big summer blockbusters,''
said Miner, 50.
</P>
<P>
   Miner spoke on the phone from Vancouver, where he is directing
``Lake Placid,'' a comedy written by David E. Kelley, one of
television's top writers, in which Bridget Fonda, Bill Pullman and
Oliver Platt deal with a 30-foot-long man-eating crocodile that
turns up in Maine. ``I guess there's one word to describe it _
quirky,''' said Miner, who has directed episodes of two of Kelley's
series, ``Chicago Hope'' and ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Quirky can also describe Miner's career. A film buff since his
childhood in Westport, Conn., with a passion for Alfred Hitchcock,
Miner worked as a production assistant on industrial films in New
York and then joined a boyhood friend, Sean Cunningham, in helping
to make a low-budget horror film, ``Last House on the Left''
(1973). The movie was the directing debut of the horror master Wes
Craven.
</P>
<P>
   Miner and Cunningham went on to produce several other films,
notably ``Friday the 13th.'' Miner made his directing debut in
``Friday the 13th Part 2.'' Later, he moved into television,
directing the pilot for ``The Wonder Years,'' as well as the WB
series ``Dawson's Creek.'' His films include the romantic drama
``Forever Young'' (1992), starring Mel Gibson and Ms. Curtis. He
has also directed television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did everything backwards,'' Miner said with a laugh. ``I
went from features to television to commercials. I'll do student
films next.''
</P>
<P>
   Miner, who is divorced and has two children, said that directing
``Halloween: H20,'' as well as ``Dawson's Creek,'' had been of
enormous benefit to his relationship with his 14-year-old daughter,
Nina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, my daughter thinks I'm cool,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
