<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy showers, gusty winds and bands of thunderstorms will
surround a disturbance Friday as it moves toward the Texas coast.
Torrential rain to will bring local flooding to parts of
southeastern Texas. Meanwhile, high pressure will keep areas from
northern Texas to the central plains hot with ample sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Limited sunshine will alternate with heavy showers and
thunderstorms over much of Florida as a weak tropical disturbance
drifts over the state. The heaviest rain is expected over central
and southern sections. Gusty onshore winds are expected along the
eastern coast. Elsewhere in the Southeast, it will be hot and
rather humid with plenty of sun, although afternoon thunderstorms
will erupt near the Gulf coast.
</P>
<P>
   A band of clouds and a few light showers will accompany a warm
front as it moves through eastern New England early Friday. A
mixture of clouds and sun will follow the front during midday,
however scattered showers will develop near the Canadian border
Friday afternoon. Most of the Northeast will be partly cloudy and a
bit more humid than recent days.
</P>
<P>
   A front from the northern Rockies to the southern Great Lakes
will be the focus for areas of showers and some thunderstorms.
Persistent clouds and a few heavy showers are expected near a jet
stream disturbance over eastern Nebraska and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the interior West will be very warm. Afternoon
thunderstorms will form over many peaks in the central and southern
Rockies. Cool air at high-levels will promote scattered showers
over the mountains of the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Born in Africa
</P>
<P>
   The disturbance that became Tropical Storm Bonnie north of the
Windward Islands on Thursday began its life in Africa. In the late
summer, dozens of clusters of thunderstorms form in the strongly
heated air near the Sahel. They travel westward in the belt of
easterly trade winds which girdle the globe within 1,500 miles of
the equator. The chilly waters near Africa's west coast are
inhospitable territory for the disturbances struggling to
strengthen. But, when the high-level winds are favorable, the
African disturbances can reach the warmer waters to the west where
hurricanes take shape. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
