<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4203 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-20 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSCURE REPUBLICAN FROM MISSOURI GOES ON THE ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Monica Mess rolls on, we may be witnessing
more than the destruction of an incumbent president.
</P>
<P>
   We may be watching the making of another presidency, or at least
the making of a serious candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Sen. John Ashcroft, an obscure Republican with
presidential ambitions, has been out front day after day claiming
the moral high road, criticizing President Clinton and calling for
his resignation. Ashcroft has been interviewed so often that he is
becoming a familiar figure, not yet a household name but
considerably more recognizable than before the Monica Lewinsky
issue erupted in January.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, of course, has nothing to lose by attacking Clinton
and potentially a great deal to gain politically. He was the first
elected Republican to declare that if Clinton was sexually involved
with a young intern, the president should resign.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the president's partial confession of a sexual
relationship, many Republican officials have remained silent to
avoid creating an appearance of too much partisan glee. House
Speaker Newt Gingrich warned fellow GOP lawmakers not to publicly
prejudge the president until Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
submits his report on possible impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft has been joined, however, by another Republican with
presidential ambitions, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, in
pounding Clinton for reprehensible behavior. Alexander echoes
Ashcroft's call for Clinton's resignation while conceding that
removing the president would not be ``the best thing'' for the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has been having difficulty being heard above the
political din, mostly because no one takes his candidacy seriously.
So far he is just an asterisk on the political calendar.
</P>
<P>
   But Ashcroft has evolved over recent months into a substantive
attack dog with a consistent, hard-hitting message that goes beyond
the marginal right-wing ideological issues that were his original
themes. He has found his central issue, and it is Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft has crafted criticism that portrays Clinton as an
ineffective president because he has ``lost his moral authority to
govern.'' In Ashcroft's view, Clinton is clinging to office ``at
the expense of the nation's domestic and international
responsibilities and opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The country cannot and should not be forced to engage issues
with a discredited president who cannot be completely trusted,''
Ashcroft thunders.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ashcroft may be more prescient than he could have
realized.
</P>
<P>
   In a military exercise reminiscent of ``Wag the Dog,'' a movie
in which a president invents a fake international crisis to
distract attention from a domestic scandal, Clinton has just put
our trust to an important test. On Thursday _ the very day that
Lewinsky was testifying for a second time before Starr's grand jury
_ Clinton abruptly struck suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan
and Sudan and returned to Washington from his Martha's Vineyard
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   His timing seemed more than coincidental. Dramatically leaving
the Vineyard also had overtones of fleeing Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   The president was retaliating for the recent bombings at two
U.S. embassies, exercising his authority as commander-in-chief to
protect U.S. interests abroad. But public support for this sudden
warlike act will ultimately depend upon confidence in the sincerity
of his motives.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, there will be widespread skepticism that the
president was as eager to create a diversion as he was to smack
terrorists. It is a measure of the damage he has done to the
presidency and himself that such doubts about his credibility are
even raised on an issue as crucial as fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   It is Ashcroft's position that only by leaving the White House
can President Clinton put those doubts to rest. So long as Clinton
wields power, his motives will always be suspect. The only question
is whether such suspicions will be so debilitating that the
president cannot function, leaving us with two years of a political
vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft also has called for the president's impeachment, ``if
he has subverted the truth, if there are serious crimes of
perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft is a member of the Judiciary Committee and could play a
crucial role in any impeachment trial, should it come to that. (If
the House votes to recommend a trial in the Senate, tradition
indicates that a specially-appointed Senate committee would first
study the issue before sending it to the full Senate body for a
vote. That committee is likely to include Judiciary Committee
members.)
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, 56, is extraordinarily ambitious for a first-term
senator, although he was seasoned by serving for two terms as
governor of Missouri. He has made a strong run at the religious
right, espousing its favorite issues, from school prayer to a ban
on abortion and elimination of the National Endowment for the Arts.
He has made some headway at winning the support of cultural
conservatives like Pat Robertson, although rivals are clamoring for
that support, too.
</P>
<P>
   One thing his ``family values'' platform can't do is snub
working women. His wife Janet is a lawyer like Hillary Clinton; she
teaches business law at Howard University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft might have a chance if the GOP presidential field
remains as crowded as it now seems. He will have to elbow his way
past the apparent front-runner, Texas Gov. George Bush, but since
neither Bush nor Ashcroft has been tested on the national stage,
what might happen is anybody's guess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
