<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RATPACK-COX     08-20 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATPACK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Rat Pack'' can't take you back, but you'll feel like you were
there
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They put the biz in show business. Their public lives cooked
with a pre-ironic, pre-retro gas; they were cool before it was
``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rat Pack _ Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, Sammy Davis, Jr. and
anybody else who torched a cigarette in their oxygen _ was the
Vegas version of the Kennedys' Camelot, a lifestyle that defined
its times (late '50s, early '60s) and was envied and aped right up
until ... it's time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world is drunk and we're just the cocktail of the
moment, pal,'' says Martin (Joe Mantegna), the Pack's commissioner
of existential realism, in HBO's darkly mesmerizing, exquisitely
flawed resurrection that premieres Saturday night. ``One day
everybody's gonna wake up with a heck of a hangover, down two
aspirin with a glass of tomato juice and wonder what the hell all
the fuss was about.''
</P>
<P>
   You're drawn into HBO's ``The Rat Pack'' even as you notice the
nips and tucks it needed to look young again. As Sinatra, Ray
Liotta (``Goodfellas'') is a kind of early draft that hints at the
right things: the no-neck head turns, the captain-of-the-tree-fort
way he both cuts up and stays in charge of his buds. But the shadow
Liotta's Sinatra throws doesn't cover the whole room, and his thin
voice is closer to whiney than fearsome. He's more punk than thug.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly that doesn't matter. While Frank was the Chairman, the
Rat Pack was a true ensemble, and their dizzying, non-stop whirl
here keeps you from sweating the details.
</P>
<P>
   The movie compresses the Pack's ``Ocean's 11,'' Kennedy
presidential campaign heyday, and it's to this movie's credit that
the hangover Martin talks about always feels just one stiff drink
away.
</P>
<P>
   As a crew, they're on top of the world. By themselves, they
grope in the dark. Davis (Don Cheadle) is the Pack's consumate
entertainer and most convenient prop; his eternal smile is exposed
as a fierce grimmace when he marries a Swedish woman and suffers
thecultural consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Martin seems always to be wagging his head at the success of the
threesome's shallowness. He bolts parties early, sleeps alone in
his hotel bed, even as an opposite image of him expands. ``In order
to share intimate feelings you have to have intimate feelings,'' he
tells his frustrated wife.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra, meanwhile, is obsessed with Jack Kennedy, eager to work
the biggest stage of them all, as if he'll one day install the Rat
Pack in the White House as a kind of hep cat cabinet. With Kennedy
in-law Peter Lawford (Angus Macfadyen) serving as both pimp and
go-between, it's a doomed notion that the Kennedy's deftly exploit.
</P>
<P>
   All this over-reaching looks small and sad now. But ``The Rat
Pack'' also lets you know why we still remember these guys, why
they remain a kind of standard of cool we keep handy for whenever
we need a reminder of where we are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it when you sing,'' Frank is told by ex-wife actress
Ava Gardner, the lost love he never got over. ``You're honest when
you sing. Why don't you just sing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rat Pack''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. EDT Saturday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
