<P>
   DROUGHT-TEXAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The drought of '98 has cost state farms and
ranches $2.1 billion, making it the worst weather disaster for
Texas agriculture since the infamous drought of the 1950s,
agricultural economists say. The new crop loss estimate tops the
$2.09 billion lost in the 1996 drought. By WORTH WREN JR. Story has
moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-RAT PACK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Last month, when Ray Liotta turned up to promote ``The
Rat Pack,'' he was clearly irritated by the constant assertions
that he didn't look a thing like Frank Sinatra, even in a dimly lit
room. No matter, it turns out. ``The Rat Pack,'' the story of the
glorious and glamorous alliance of Sinatra, Dean Martin and Sammy
Davis Jr., isn't about imitation as much as imagination. There's so
much stuffed into this HBO film, airing at 8 p.m. Sunday, that you
have to wonder whether there is any unsubstantiated rumor or tale
the creators didn't cram in. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved
in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-YOUR FRIENDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Neil LaBute's new movie, ``Your Friends and
Neighbors,'' is about as close to the edge as a Yes album; it's
like ``Carnal Knowledge'' starring the Muppets. By ELVIS MITCHELL.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DEAD MAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Few movies are more irritating than the ones that
don't have the courage of their own bad taste. ``Dead Man on
Campus'' is one of 'em: a slob movie that denies its slobdom, a
dark comedy that resists its darkness. As a result, it's just dim.
One expected a dumb movie, but not this dumb. By ROBERT PHILPOT.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DANCE WITH ME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Not at all light on its feet, ``Dance With Me''
stumbles clumsily onto the cinema dance floor, one already crowded
with hackneyed hoofer pictures. You can almost hear some studio
pitch-monkey saying, ``Hey, Latin dancing is hot now, right? Why
not make a movie about a poor Cuban Pete who cha-chas his way into
the hearts of America? It'll be like a salsa-style `Strictly
Ballroom.''' Yeah, except without all the entertainment value. By
TODD CAMP. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BLADE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Although it's about 20 minutes too long, the
action-horror movie ``Blade'' is a rousing tease _ it's smarter
than it has a right to be. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ One of the nation's often-overlooked minorities is
getting ready to flex its economic muscles in the marketplace.
Hispanics are ``where the action is,'' according to author and
speaker Juan Roberto Job, author of ``Just Because I'm Latin
Doesn't Mean I Mambo: A Success Guide for Hispanic Americans.'' By
TERESA McUSIC. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Coffee to get rid of headaches; ginger and chile
peppers to ease arthritis; rice to soothe digestion; and sugar to
help us sleep? Although sugar is by no means a ``health food,'' it
can help us sleep because it triggers the production of serotonin
in the brain to help suppress pain and depression and ease us into
restful slumber, says a pioneer in the healing power of good
nutrition. By CAROLYN POIROT. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOHNSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ No, Yogi, it isn't over yet. Despite President
Clinton's testimony to a federal grand jury and his televised ``mea
culpa'' to the American people Monday night, there is no
discernible end yet to the sickening tragicomedy of concupiscence,
prevarication and taped telephone conversations that has been
tormenting the American soul for more than seven months. By CECIL
JOHNSON. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
