<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4314 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSISTED-SUICIDE-HNS &LR;      08-20 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSISTED-SUICIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP SAYS BILL TO CURB DOCTOR-ASSISTED SUICIDE HURTS PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill aimed at curbing physician-assisted suicide
by trying to limit the amount of pain medication a doctor can
prescribe would leave more chronically ill people in pain and
possibly cause more suicides, several medical care groups said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the groups _ including the American College of
Physicians-American Society of Internal Medicine, the American
Pharmaceutical Association and the National Hospice Organization _
said at a news conference that the bill could scare doctors away
from prescribing adequate pain medication.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would require the government to revoke physicians'
licenses if the Drug Enforcement Agency finds that they have
``intentionally dispensed or distributed a (drug) with a purpose of
causing, or assisting in causing, the suicide or euthanasia of any
individual.'' A federal board would hold hearings at which doctors
would have to defend their anti-pain prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to vote on the bill next month. A similar
measure in the Senate is pending in the Judiciary Committee and may
go to a vote before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crux of good medical care is between a patient, the
doctor, and the family,'' said Robert Copeland, a physician in
LaGrange, Ga. But he warned that ``adding a gumshoe,'' or making
doctors answer to federal investigators, would complicate the task
of providing a patient with adequate medication.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland, who chairs the Philadelphia-based American College of
Physicians-American Society of Internal Medicine, praised the goal
of preventing physician-assisted suicide. But he said the bill
would make doctors fearful of damaging their reputation and of
being penalized for prescribing large doses of pain medication,
which he said are often necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland said doctors sometimes need to prescribe more than 10
times the Food and Drug Administration-recommended dosage for
medications to adequately relieve severe pain.
</P>
<P>
   Samira Beckwith, director of Hope Hospice and Palliative Care in
Ft. Myers, Fla., said the bill would have the opposite effect of
what legislators expect. Prescriptions for pain medication would
decrease and suffering would increase, and as a result, more
elderly people in chronic pain would seek assisted suicide, she
warned.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith recalled a 50-year-old man with terminal cancer who
``asked our staff and ... many people in the community about how he
could commit suicide.'' She said the man wanted to call Michigan to
search for Dr. Jack Kevorkian, the leading advocate of
physician-assisted suicide, when her staff began giving him
medication.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after his treatment started, he was up and talking
with his family, she said, and later died peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Bennett, president of the American Society of Pain
Management Nurses, a Pensacola, Fla.,-based group, said there are
no ``normal doses'' of medication for seriously ill patients.
</P>
<P>
   One 15-year-old cancer patient, Bennett said, received 4,600
micrograms of a pain medication, Fentanyl, every hour, which is 46
times the FDA-recommended maximum dose.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was awake, alert, talking to her parents and joking with
her nurses,'' Bennett said. ``This dosage was needed to control her
pain at that point in her disease. ... She died pain-free in the
arms of her parents as a result of her cancer, not because of her
medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said such a large dose would catch the attention of the
special board proposed in the bill, and a physician might not be
willing to give that amount for fear of federal reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Pain care is already inadequate, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study in the Journal of the American Medical
Association, 26 percent of elderly patients with daily pain who
live in nursing homes receive no medication for pain.
</P>
<P>
   Only Oregon has a law that allows physicians to prescribe a
deadly dose of drugs to terminally ill patients, or people with a
life expectancy of six months or less. The doctors may not
administer the medicine, but the patients may. Forty-six states and
Washington, D.C. have state statutes or laws prohibiting
physician-assisted suicide. North Carolina, Utah and Wyoming do not
have laws on doctor-assisted suicides.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Skip Baker, president of the American Society for Action on
Pain, a Williamsburg, Va.-based patient advocacy group, said he
takes 500 milligrams of morphine a day, as prescribed by his doctor
for his debilitating joint disease that causes him chronic pain.
</P>
<P>
   For 14 months he could not get enough medication and suffered
great weight loss because he often was in too much pain to eat, he
said. Now his doctor gives him adequate pain relief, but he said he
fears that the proposed legislation would put him back in
unmanageable pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this bill passes, at some point down the road, it is going
to cause my suicide,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
