<HEADLINE>
TOWN HONORS SOLDIER KILLED IN BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   (LAMAR, Mo. )_ No town seems less likely
to feel the effects of a terrorist bomb than this one, where flags
hang from every pole on the square and a Statue of Liberty replica
sits on a corner.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet on Wednesday, an Army honor guard in pressed green uniforms
and bright white gloves draped an American flag over the polished
wood coffin of Staff Sgt. Kenneth Hobson II. Hobson was killed by a
terrorist bomb Aug. 7 at his post in the American embassy in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   And on this sweltering afternoon, hundreds of the slain
soldier's family, friends, soldiers and other well-wishers streamed
into the town's Thiebaud Auditorium to say goodbye to a man they
referred to as a hero, a good father and a brave soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among those saying goodbye was his young widow,
Deborah, who accepted two meritorious conduct medals and a purple
heart for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she handed their infant daughter, Meghan, to a relative
and walked with tight steps onto the stage. Surrounded by dozens of
floral arrangements, she stood near her 27-year-old husband's
coffin. Before reading a farewell poem, she said: ``He's still in
my heart. I just can't bring myself to say goodbye yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then with her voice breaking, and her words chopped to stifle
sobs, she read from the poem, ``Live your life to its fullest, and
when you need me, just whisper my name.'' She ended by turning and
hurrying off the stage and back to her family.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, relatives took turns carrying Meghan, 2, up
and down the aisle. She alternately called out, ``Ma-ma'' and
``Da-da'' and held tight a single yellow flower.
</P>
<P>
   Army Major General Robert Flowers paid a soldier's tribute to
Hobson, saying, ``If, God forbid, my four sons ever have to go to
war, I would want them serving with or under a soldier like Staff
Sgt. Kenneth Hobson II.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Congressman Roy Blunt spoke of the cowardly act that had
killed Hobson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no greater love than to lay down your life for
another,'' he said. ``And that's what Sgt. Hobson did. And he did
it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hobson was remembered through the day as an artist and a student
who loved a good debate. He graduated in 1989 from high school and
joined the Army. He served through the Gulf War, clearing out enemy
bunkers in the Iraqi desert. He married in 1994 and had a daughter
two years ago. He trained to be a linguist and five months ago
transferred to the American Embassy in Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I was in Vietnam with his father, and his father was
my hero,'' Ronald Meyer, who came from Wisconsin for the funeral,
said softly.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, Kenneth Hobson II's father saved Meyer's life
in Vietnam, fighting off the enemy after a bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There we were, in wartime and surrounded by the threat of
death, and we survived,'' Meyers said. ``It doesn't seem fair that
his son should die now, 30 years later during peacetime. It just
doesn't seem fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
