<HEADER>
A4324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKE     08-20 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   ``ARMAGEDDON,'' starring Bruce Willis, Ben Affleck and Liv
Tyler. Directed by Michael Bay (PG-13, 144 minutes). This big,
showy, spirit-crushing summer extravaganza includes not a single
heartfelt moment, unless you count its sequence set in a strip
club. Imminent doom (courtesy of an approaching asteroid) becomes
the excuse for rampant flag-waving, gung-ho patriotism and a notion
of heroism that has nothing whatever to do with real courage.
Willis gets the film's noblest lines for the same reason that he
probably got the set's biggest trailer. Affleck tries gamely to
seem mad about Ms. Tyler, who serves as window dressing at NASA
headquarters. Totally predictable elements _ loud noises, frequent
explosions and bright computer screen colors _ seem as inevitable
and deadly as the asteroid while they create the illusion of
escapist fun (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE AVENGERS,'' starring Uma Thurman and Ralph Fiennes.
Directed by Jeremiah Chechik (PG, 100 minutes). Sometimes major
movie studios should be afraid to screen expensive fiascos for the
press, but they go ahead anyway. ``The Avengers'' is Warner
Brothers' would-be blockbuster that actually had its light hidden
beneath a bushel until opening day, and no wonder. With
pseudo-suave repartee that would make Austin Powers blush and with
so many shades of ``Howard the Duck'' that one scene depicts
man-size pastel teddy bears sitting around a conference table, it's
a film to gall fans of the old television series and perplex anyone
else. I can't remember another Friday morning show where I heard
actual cries of ``Ugh!'' on the way out the door (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE CHAMBERMAID ON THE TITANIC,'' starring Olivier Martinez,
Aitana Sanchez Gijon and Romane Bohringer. Directed by Bigas Luna
(not rated; 96 minutes). A delightful, sexy period fable, adapted
from a novel by Didier Decoin. ``Chambermaid'' wittily illustrates
the basic human need to consume and spin heroic stories of passion
and loss (whether or not they're true). When Horty ( Martinez), a
poor French foundry worker, wins a contest that sends him to
Southhampton, England, to watch the Titanic depart on its maiden
voyage, he takes to his hotel room a woman who claims to be a
chambermaid on the ship and has no lodging. After the ship sinks,
his co-workers press him about the details, and his fabricated
story of an ultimate one-night stand becomes a local myth that
eventually catapults him into a show business career telling the
same (increasingly embellished) tale over and over. The movie has
profound things to say about gossip, storytelling and the primal
urge to mythicize personal experience (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``EVER AFTER: A CINDERELLA STORY,'' starring Drew Barrymore,
Anjelica Huston and Dougray Scott. Directed by Andy Tennant (PG-13,
120 minutes). The clever notion of reinventing Cinderella as a
self-motivated powerhouse who doesn't need a fairy godmother to get
ahead has been reduced into a bland mishmash of comedy and soap
opera. Drew Barrymore is appealing as Danielle, a plucky,
resourceful, slightly tomboyish 16th-century French girl who knows
how to stand up for herself. But her wimpish prince ( Scott) isn't
much of a prize to crow over. And why is Leonardo da Vinci (Patrick
Godfrey) traipsing around France with the ``Mona Lisa'' under his
arm, giving advice to the lovelorn? The most orthodox refugee from
the standard fairy tale is Ms. Huston's haughty stepmother
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``EVEREST,'' directed by David Brashears with Greg MacGillivray
(not rated; 45 minutes). If life in New York City doesn't provide
enough in the way of thrills, those in search of a vicarious
near-death experience can make their way to the Sony Imax Theater
at Lincoln Square (1998 Broadway, at 68th Street) for a go at
``Everest.'' There, images of the world's highest mountain _ 29,028
feet _ find a frame worthy of the peak's spectacular, lethal
beauty: the eight-story-high, 100-foot-wide screen. This account
focuses mainly on the efforts of three people to scale the peak in
1996 despite yawning chasms of ever-shifting ice and sudden,
blinding storms. While this expedition was on the mountain, other
teams made their way into the so-called death zone, at 25,000 feet,
where a violent storm overtook them. Eight people perished in the
worst single disaster on the mountain. ``Everest'' makes it
possible for armchair adventurers to share the risks and glory of
the team's climb toward heaven (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GOVERNESS,'' starring Minnie Driver and Tom Wilkinson.
Directed by Sandra Goldbacher (R, 114 minutes). It is the early
1840s, and Rosina (Minnie Driver), a headstrong young Sephardic
Jewish woman living in London, poses as a gentile to get a job as a
governess for the Cavendish family on a remote Scottish island.
Falling in love with the skittish, devoutly Christian head of the
household (Tom Wilkinson), a gentleman inventor with whom she has a
stormy affair, she becomes his collaborator in the invention of
photography. The ravishingly handsome film works on several levels:
as a proto-feminist fable, a meditation on still photography and
its relation to real life, and a portrait of lovers whose religious
difference becomes an unbridgeable emotional gap. Ms. Driver holds
the picture with a solid performance that falls short of great
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``HOW STELLA GOT HER GROOVE BACK,'' starring Angela Bassett,
Taye Diggs and Whoopi Goldberg. Directed by Kevin Rodney Sullivan.
(R, 99 minutes). This silly soft-core fantasy in which 40-year-old
Stella (Ms. Bassett) meets and falls in love with 20-year-old
Winston ( Diggs) while on vacation in Jamaica is part Caribbean
travel brochure (fly to Jamaica and meet the hunk of your dreams)
and part diluted Chippendales strip show floated on a bathtub full
of suds with some light comedy thrown in. Ms. Bassett brings real
fire to the role of a beautiful divorced-with-one-son San Francisco
stockbroker whose resistance to romance is broken down in the
tropics. But Diggs' nearly perfect boyfriend is a vapid
romance-novel fabrication. Ms. Goldberg shamelessly stirs up the
suds as Stella's raunchy best friend, who is secretly dying of
liver cancer (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
