<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4326 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-20 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASKED TO RESIGN? DO IT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   Mike Barnicle's employer asked him to
resign. Barnicle refused. Barnicle kept his job _ for awhile,
anyway.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should you use Barnicle's tactic if you get a similar demand?
Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   If your work relationship is so tainted that your boss wants you
gone, it's probably best for everyone that you go. On Wednesday,
Barnicle finally admitted the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody asked me for my resignation, I would probably give
it,'' said Nancy Day, a human resources professor at the University
of Missouri-Kansas City. ``If their need for me has ended, it
wouldn't be a great place for me to fulfill my career objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, a columnist at /{The Boston Globe/}, was asked to
resign after jokes from a George Carlin book appeared in his column
without credit to Carlin. Barnicle said a friend gave him the jokes
and he hadn't read the book. But, others noted, Barnicle had
recommended the book on a TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was _ plagiarism or lying _ it led editors to seek
Barnicle's resignation. But advertisers and readers were Barnicle
boosters. Editors reconsidered. He got a two-month, unpaid
suspension. Then another problem column was revealed, and Barnicle
resigned, agreeing it was best for all.
</P>
<P>
   If a client walked into Robert L. Dameron's law offices in
Kansas City, Kan., and said, ``I've been asked to resign. Should I
say no?'' Dameron, a labor law specialist, said he'd ask at least
three questions:
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a good chance of getting another job quickly?
</P>
<P>
   Are you being fired ``for cause'' _ because of misconduct or
lack of performance according to your employer's reasonable
expectations?
</P>
<P>
   Is your employer willing to give you a good reference letter in
exchange for your resignation?
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, Kansas and many other states have ``at will'' labor
laws. That means a job relationship can be ended for any reason or
for no reason, absent an individual employment contract or
collective bargaining agreement. There are other exceptions, too,
if the worker is protected by federal or state statutes or public
policy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you believed you were asked to resign because
you were _ pick one _ disabled, involved in a worker's compensation
claim, or the victim of race, sex or age discrimination, you might
refuse to resign and seek job protection under the relevant laws.
</P>
<P>
   If none of those protections applies, though, you probably have
this choice: Do I resign or get fired?
</P>
<P>
   If you don't expect to find another job quickly, you might note
that _ usually _ resigning from a job will cause a greater delay in
getting unemployment benefits than getting fired. But if you were
fired ``for cause'' you may get no unemployment benefits anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It's wisest to dwell on Dameron's third question: Can you get a
good reference letter?
</P>
<P>
   Missouri (but not Kansas) law, grants you the right to obtain a
service letter that lists your dates of employment. In any state,
though, it's much easier to get a new job with fuller, nicer
letters of recommendation. It's also easier to explain a
resignation ``because of opinion differences'' than to explain a
firing.
</P>
<P>
   A final tip: If you negotiate a reference letter, it's safer to
have it in hand /{before/} you sign your resignation papers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     08-20 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: cancer (Holden). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``THE LAST DAYS OF DISCO,'' starring Kate Beckinsale and Chloe
Sevigny. Directed by Whit Stillman (R, 112 minutes). Stillman's
smart, fretful, patrician characters turn up midway between
``Metropolitan'' and ``Barcelona'' in a film that charmingly mixes
postcollege career worries with improbable discomania. A delightful
cast engages in nonstop flirtation and hair-splitting debate,
rendered with Stillman's usual acuity and humor. Ms. Beckinsale, an
English actress with a flawless American accent here and diffidence
that's just as perfect, holds court beguilingly at the center of a
bright and amusing crowd. The ideal film for anyone willing to
entertain the notion that the spread of environmentalism was
sparked by the revival of ``Bambi'' during the disco generation's
formative years (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``LETHAL WEAPON 4,'' starring Mel Gibson, Danny Glover and Rene
Russo. Directed by Richard Donner (R, 125 minutes). In the full
perspective-warping heat of the summer movie season, this turns out
to be one of the nicer blow-'em-ups around. The characters are
funny and likable, and they all live on earth. The formula still
has some zip. The stars, with the welcome new addition of Chris
Rock as a young detective who has literally married into the
``Lethal Weapon'' family, play their roles with breezy finesse. And
the story, about slave smuggling and Chinese gangsters, is a
flamboyant, fight-filled adventure fueled by kidding camaraderie
and constant forward motion. Bear in mind that this is still a film
whose idea of high drama is watching a car getting pushed in front
of an oncoming train (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``MAFIA!,'' starring Jay Mohr, Lloyd Bridges and Christina
Applegate. Directed by Jim Abrahams (PG-13, 86 minutes). This
sendup makes an offer you could probably refuse, but its
Mad-magazine-style hit-or-miss humor works well enough to be
reasonably bright. It's true, though, that a Mafia movie satire
without a single horse's head in a bed and without anyone who
sounds like Joe Pesci has left a few stones unturned. Concentrating
mostly on the ``Godfather'' films and ``Casino,'' Abrahams throws
in anything from canned meatballs by Spalding to vomit gags. Lloyd
Bridges, to whose memory the film is dedicated, has the role of a
dapper don and shows one last time how sporting and debonair he
could be (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE MASK OF ZORRO,'' starring Antonio Banderas, Anthony
Hopkins and Catherine Zeta-Jones. Directed by Martin Campbell
(PG-13, 130 minutes). Travel back to the days when swashbuckling
was serious business, when boyish adventure films still had their
innocence and when the bravado of thrilling stunt work was all a
movie needed in the way of special effects. Hopkins is marvelously
game as the film's dashing senior Zorro. Banderas was born to play
the aging hero's jokey, hotblooded protege. And he meets his match
in the story's heroine, whose beauty is inevitably described as
``beyond compare.'' This robust old-fashioned adventure should
appeal to older children, but beware of a few needlessly grisly
touches (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE NEGOTIATOR,'' starring Samuel L. Jackson and Kevin Spacey.
Directed by F. Gary Gray (R, 115 minutes). In a twist on the
Hitchcockian maxim, this thriller takes two extraordinary actors
and places them in surprisingly ordinary circumstances. In a film
whose title should have been plural, both stars play seasoned
hostage negotiators who are caught up in a by-the-numbers battle of
wits. Amazingly, both these shrewd, maverick actors are cast as
nice guys, team players and clean-cut family men. The movie's
brisk, familiar look of a police story, heavy with close-ups, that
escalates to a paramilitary operation will look right at home when
it comes to the video screen (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``NIGHTS OF CABIRIA,'' starring Giulietta Masina. Directed by
Federico Fellini (not rated, 117 minutes). Anyone dismayed by the
hyperkinetic emptiness of summertime film spectacles will find the
antidote in this 1957 Fellini masterpiece. It has been refurbished
and revived by the same team that brought back ``Contempt'' last
year, and they display the same acumen in reissuing a film of
special prescience; though it was shot in black and white amid the
poverty of postwar Italy, neither the style nor the searching of
``Cabiria' has grown dated at all. In a heartbreaking performance,
the star plays a scrappy Roman streetwalker who drifts almost
magically among the film's astonishingly varied realms. There is
more grace and courage in the famous image of Masina smiling
through her tears than in all the fire-breathing blockbusters
Hollywood has to offer (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE OPPOSITE OF SEX,'' starring Christina Ricci, Martin
Donovan, Lisa Kudrow and Lyle Lovett. Directed by Don Roos (R, 100
minutes). Wicked, foulmouthed and very funny, this gleefully
acerbic comedy finds that Ms. Ricci has morphed enchantingly from
nasty little Wednesday of ``The Addams Family'' into Lolita's evil
twin. Voluptuous and scheming, her poisonous Dedee narrates this
film and announces immediately that she won't be developing a heart
of gold. Which is, of course, mostly a lie. The film brutally
skewers preconceptions about gay and straight life, then lets its
characters intermingle in sweetly unexpected ways. Donovan and Ms.
Kudrow, as unlikely comrades brought together by Dedee's treachery,
deliver the zingers from Roos' screenplay with deadpan panache
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE PARENT TRAP,'' starring Lindsay Lohan, Natasha Richardson
and Dennis Quaid. Directed by Nancy Meyers and written by David
Swift, Ms. Meyers and Charles Shyer (PG, 128 minutes). A super-cute
remake of the old Hayley Mills hit, this time given a privileged
shelter-magazine gloss by the ``Father of the Bride'' team of Ms.
Meyers and Shyer. Ms. Richardson and Quaid beam appealingly as
parents who somehow managed to separate their twins at birth
without a twinge of guilt and who seem to have spent all of the
intervening 11 1/2 years shopping. In her dual role as English and
American sisters (one lives in a grand London town house, the other
on a big Napa Valley vineyard; nobody lives in a coal mine), the
spirited Ms. Lohan commandeers the movie as if she had been taking
shrinking-violet lessons from Sharon Stone (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
