<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-KAYAK-ART-2TAKES-N     08-20 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KAYAK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHTTIME PADDLE AROUND MANHATTAN: TIME, TIDE AND TIRED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JED STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sure, the waters of Baja are beautiful. So are those
of Alaska, the Pacific Northwest and dozens of other world-renowned
paddling destinations attracting thousands of avid kayakers each
year. But the waters of Manhattan, with its lights and contrasts,
might be the most beautiful of all.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, they were paddled by just a few, those who would
brave the dirt and the chemicals. Even finding a place to launch a
boat was almost impossible. In the last few years, though, the
water quality has improved. Now, almost anyone can get out on the
water, and kayaking has blossomed.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I completed a dream I'd had for several years: a
nighttime, solo circumnavigation of Manhattan. The last two summers
I've led kayak tours on most Saturday mornings from the Downtown
Boathouse in Tribeca to the Statue of Liberty and back. So I'd had
a little experience in Lower Manhattan waters. I'd even been on two
daylight round-Manhattan trips and remembered a bit of the route
and its problems.
</P>
<P>
   But a night journey promised to be something special. New York
aglow, seen from a kayak, could be an exhilarating experience.
</P>
<P>
   Shackled to the moon, the three rivers of Manhattan have lives
of their own. Two, the Harlem and the East, aren't rivers at all
but channels that suck and push water to and from the Hudson and
Long Island Sound. The only river worthy of its name is the Hudson,
and that, too, changes direction every six and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   The East River has treacherous tidal currents nearly impossible
to paddle if you choose to fight them. The Harlem, too, can push a
boat backward or forward, depending on the time of day.
</P>
<P>
   The trick with all three is to read the tidal charts correctly,
as tides change with the position of the moon, ignoring clocks and
timetables. You must catch the tide at the Battery at just the
right moment so that the East River's rising waters, sweeping into
Long Island Sound, will pull you northward to the Harlem and later
to the Hudson, whose changing tide drags you southward. Miss that
window and you face near-constant paddling.
</P>
<P>
   As I left the Downtown Boathouse at 5:30 p.m. on a recent
Friday, the main current of the Hudson began carrying me south
toward the Battery. I only had to use the paddle to keep the bow of
my 15-foot kayak pointed southward; the river did the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Once I rounded Battery Point, I came upon a Staten Island ferry
berthed at her dock, boarding her rush-hour passengers. I could
hear the low thrum of her idling engines, the squeak of pilings
rustling in the waves, the throb of police boats. This was becoming
a very noisy trip.
</P>
<P>
   Turning toward the East River, I found the currents were against
me and began paddling as fast as I could to get around the ferry
before she backed out of the dock. There's a lot of that in
negotiating Manhattan by kayak: spurts of fast paddling.
</P>
<P>
   But quiet times usually come right afterward, offering moments
to laze in the eddies and the still waters between piers. South
Street provides a lot of those eddies, with piers for helicopters,
clipper ships and even tennis.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of time to dawdle, since the tide wouldn't turn
for another hour or two, so I wandered in and out and underneath
the piers, concentrating on the sounds of the shoreline at
twilight.
</P>
<P>
   New York sounds so different on the water. Because the shoreline
is protected by seawalls that rise several feet or more above you,
much of the sound gets channeled overhead. So even during the
evening rush hour, one can be cloistered in near silence while
several feet from heavy traffic. Then the quiet is broken by an
arriving helicopter, a passing jet skier or, at one pier, by a
bagpiper practicing a Gaelic-tinged ``America, the Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Paddling diagonally across the East River to the River Cafe in
Brooklyn, I felt myself pushed backward by the current, losing
headway but gaining a great view of the Brooklyn Bridge overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Heading for the Manhattan Bridge, I was forced to dodge two tugs
pushing their barges upriver. In a kind of nautical jaywalk, I had
to paddle behind one before the other arrived. Like crossing
midtown streets, it's a situation in which one should move with all
deliberate speed. As I cleared the path of one oncoming tug, I
rushed into the waves of another that had just passed.
</P>
<P>
   Like all other boats, tugs move forward by displacing water
behind them, a lot of water. Suddenly, I was in the middle of a
mini-maelstrom, being pushed violently southward amid wild eddies
one might find on a white-water river. The danger lies not in the
eddy itself but in exiting one clockwise eddy and being caught by
another turning counterclockwise. The bow of the boat alters
direction dramatically and can easily be tipped over by the sudden
change. I leaned forward and tried to anticipate when one eddy
would pass me to the next and that one to the quieter water near
shore.
</P>
<P>
   As I eluded the lines of fishermen trying their luck under the
Williamsburg Bridge, people leaned over to talk to me. ``Where are
you going?'' ``Doesn't your boat tip over?'' ``How can I do that?''
</P>
<P>
   When I got closer to Roosevelt Island, the tide slackened, the
current relented, and I started to speed up.
</P>
<P>
   Passing the United Nations building around 7:30, I was lucky to
catch a breathtaking phenomenon. I could see the setting sun
reflected in its eastern windows. I was puzzled because I could
also see the sun setting behind it. Weird. A glorious sunset
reflected from the Citibank building in Long Island City, Queens,
solved the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Then the river's mysteries became more mundane. The desolation
of the Williamsburg and Greenpoint shores lined with crumbling
buildings and salvage yards was so different from the Manhattan
side. It was difficult to reconcile the two. Between the shores, a
small island south of Roosevelt held two types of tenants:
cormorants nesting in the penthouses of the trees and sea gulls in
the cheaper habitats on the ground below. Geese flew over me, and
ducks, startled into flight, quacked rapidly out of my path.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A solo circumnavigation of Manhattan can be a dangerous thing,
especially at night. For those who do not have extensive
experience, several organizations provide stimulating, guided and
safe daytime tours.
</P>
<P>
   MANHATTAN KAYAK COMPANY, Pier 60 at the Sports Center at Chelsea
Piers, 23rd Street and the Hudson River, (212) 336-6068. Classes in
paddle basics, daily short tours to Battery Park, and the Intrepid,
longer tours to the Statue of Liberty every two to three weeks and
a monthly Manhattan circumnavigation (the next one will be on Sept.
20). Prices range from $35 for a short trip ($25 for members of the
Sports Center) to $230 for the circumnavigation ($155 for members).
</P>
<P>
   THE DOWNTOWN BOATHOUSE, between Hubert Street and North Moore
Street on the Hudson River, Tribeca, (212) 966-1852. Lends kayaks
free on a first-come basis. After a ``30-second lesson'' paddlers
can experience the river by paddling in the large protected
embayment north of the boathouse. The volunteer-run boathouse also
offers free three-hour supervised tours to Liberty Island or to the
Intrepid, docked at 43rd Street. The tours leave at 9 a.m. on
Saturday and Sunday and are restricted to about 20 paddlers with
some prior experience, either at the boathouse or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTIC KAYAK TOURS, Saugerties, N.Y., (914) 246-2187, has
full-day tours with boats and equipment provided including some
basic paddling lessons. The tours are offered at points along the
Hudson River from New York Harbor to the Catskill region, on Long
Island Sound along the Connecticut shoreline, in New York Harbor to
Liberty Island and a circumnavigation of Manhattan scheduled for
advanced paddlers on Sunday; a circumnavigation for beginning
paddlers is on Sept. 6. Cost: $80 for a full day.
</P>
<P>
   THE SMALL BOAT SHOP, Rex Marina, on Water Street, Norwalk,
Conn., (203) 854-5223, leads guided tours to the Norwalk Islands
lasting about six hours. The $80 fee covers some instruction; boats
and equipment are provided.
</P>
</TEXT>
