<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWELFTHNIGHT-MUSIC-AR     08-20 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWELFTHNIGHT-MUSIC-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LINCOLN CENTER'S `TWELFTH NIGHT,' MUSIC BOTH EXOTIC AND
UNAMPLIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Early in the process of composing incidental music
and songs for Lincoln Center Theater's current production of
Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night,'' Jeanine Tesori went to a downtown
percussion store with her orchestrator, Rick Bassett, and made an
unusual request. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, `Show me all the instruments that nobody else
ever rents, the more exotic the better,' '' she explained recently.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proprietor disappeared into the storage room and came back
with metallic Tibetan temple bowls that are played by rubbing a
wooden stick around the rim, much like the trick people play at
dinner parties by rubbing a wet finger on the rim of a wine glass
to produce a ringing sound. Except that the unearthly, soft,
ringing sounds these simple Tibetan bowls make are more hauntingly
beautiful than anything produced by a state-of-the-art synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all Ms. Tesori and Bassett walked away with that
day. The instruments used in this eclectic original score include
many of ancient ancestry, like gongs, wood blocks, chimes and bells
as well as unorthodox newer creations like the daxophone, a
German-made instrument of bowed wood with a convex finger board
that is used for a wide range of sound effects, like bird calls and
ocean waves. To these are added guitars, a banjo, cello, violin,
piano, harmonium and woodwinds. All these instruments are played by
just six versatile musicians, who collectively create an
unbelievably rich range of sound colors.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of keeping the music for ``Twelfth Night'' natural,
exotic and, most important, unamplified came from its British
director, Nicholas Hytner. ``Rick told me he wanted no microphones,
no electronic instruments,'' Ms. Tesori said. ``And that was fine
by me. When you introduce amplification into a band or orchestra
for a show, the musicians lose their ability to project because
they are being amplified and have to be careful. So more
amplification is added, and it goes on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tesori, who has done a considerable amount of conducting in
the theater, believes that the ability to balance an orchestra is
something that many conductors are not really taught. ``Instead,
there is a sound man at a control board determining that, say, more
oboe is needed, and turning up the microphone on the oboe,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music for this show is a little subversive,'' said Mark
Stewart, one of the pivotal musicians, who plays guitar, strings,
daxophone, bowls, and sundry percussion instruments, and also
contributes vocals. ``We are taking control back from the sound
board, which is quite lovely.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, the score chastises the typical blaring Broadway band,
souped up with amplification and rigidly presided over. ``Within
the confines of Jeanine's ideas, we are free,'' said Kimberly
Grigsby, the conductor of ``Twelfth Night,'' adding: ``The score is
so fluid, in a way, all I have to do is say, here we go, then trust
everybody, and keep my ears attuned to balances.''
</P>
<P>
   Hytner's stipulation about natural sound came not just from an
antipathy to amplification but also from his take on this
particular play. ``Twelfth Night'' is set in a sort of never-never
land called Illyria ruled by a handsome young duke, Orsino (played
by Paul Rudd), who is courting a recalcitrant countess, Olivia
(Kyra Sedgwick), and is attended by a loyal valet, actually Viola
(Helen Hunt), a young woman who has just survived a shipwreck and
pines for the duke but serves him disguised as a man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Hytner and Ms. Tesori, the fantasy elements of the story, the
timelessness of the locale and the gender-bending confusions of the
characters called for music that was equally ambiguous: elemental
yet mystical, familiar yet exotic, simple yet ethereal. Moreover,
much of the action takes place on a nearby coast, and the water
imagery that runs through the text is depicted in designer Bob
Crowley's remarkable set, on which real rain falls and which
contains real ponds and pools that the characters slosh through.
This too called for specifically evocative music.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, Viola says of the duke, `I can sing and speak to
him in many sorts of music,''' Ms. Tesori said. ``So that's what I
have tried to provide. And, Rick Bassett, our orchestrator, brought
his incredible knowledge of world music to the job, which was very
appropriate for this play.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is just a bit of amplified music in the score,
but involving only the electric guitar, and the daxophone, which
must be played through speakers. Otherwise, all the acoustic
instruments are played without amplification, making the Vivian
Beaumont Theater, right now, the rare Broadway theater where you
can hear the sounds of a piano, a cello, an Indian drum or
whatever, with no electronic enhancement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When the audience enters the theater, it is greeted by all six
musicians playing on Tibetan bowls tuned to different pitches, a
collected sound both eerie and strangely comforting. This segues
into music with gentle accompanimental patterns for guitar, the
soft tapping of Indian tabla, mournful string lines and a wisp of a
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tesori has set the many song texts in the play,
Shakespeare's equivalent of verbal ditties, as moody poplike
minstrel songs for Feste, a jester in Olivia's court, played by
David Patrick Kelly, who strums the lute and sings in a plaintive
low tenor. There are dance sequences with fractured meters that
interrupt the action, and shimmering sustained harmonic passages
that underscore it. Several of the musicians also sing, including
Marshall Coid, a countertenor whose voice Ms. Tesori feels vividly
evokes the androgynous elements of the play. The result is a
skillful mixture of ethnic music, modal folk songs, driving dances
segments that might be from Morocco, Broadway riffs, pop licks,
chamber music and coloristic sound effects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the theater has been what Ms. Tesori, a Port
Washington, N.Y., native, now 36, has wanted to do ever since she
switched her major from pre-med to music while a student at
Barnard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I conducted shows and worked in theater during school, but
never really studied composition,'' she said. ``I just listened a
lot, and went to as much as I could in the city.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She has worked in Broadway extensively as an arranger and
conductor, most recently doing dance and incidental sequences for
the revivals of ``How to Succeed in Business Without Really
Trying'' and ``The Sound of Music,'' the latter of which her
husband, Michael Rafter, conducts.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the work that has meant most to her so far is her own
musical, ``Violet,'' about a disfigured woman from rural North
Carolina who travels to Tulsa to be healed by a television
evangelist. Ms. Tesori gave up a well-paying job, as associate
conductor of ``The Who's `Tommy,' '' for the sake of ``Violet,''
which became a workshop production at Playwrights Horizons in 1997.
The musical developed an almost cult-like following among segments
of the audience, but received mixed reviews and did not make it to
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done a lot of helping other people with their work,'' she
said. ``But I would love, honestly, to have a show produced for
which I wrote the score, and that is hard to achieve these days,
when production costs are so high and producers are so afraid of
risk. But I surround myself with people who believe in the theater
the way it was: that is, if you tell a great story, audiences will
come, and if you make music that comes out of your heart, people
will listen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she is gratified by the response to her music
for ``Twelfth Night,'' which runs through Aug. 30 at Lincoln
Center, and the chance it provided to work so creatively with
stimulating musicians.
</P>
<P>
   It has been equally involving for the musicians. Before
composing a note, Ms. Tesori spent a long time with each player to
find out just what instruments they could play, whether they could
sing, what their special musical gifts were. That is an experience
far removed from the typical Broadway gig, where a musician plays
his part night after night deep in a pit while an unseen engineer
controls the projection, volume and balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once my work was done, I realized that I didn't need to come
by the theater very often,'' Ms. Tesori said. ``I didn't have to
worry about a sound man tampering with the score. And the piece
breathes musically, so it will be a little different every night.
That's what I wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
