<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMER-ART-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-20 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMER-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: TWO NEW ENGLAND SHOWS NATIVE SON WINSLOW HOMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Maine)   (bl)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given his life _ born in Boston, died in Prouts Neck, Maine _
and rugged themes, from deep woods to open sea, it's small wonder
that Winslow Homer (1836-1910) is a New England institution.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't even surprising that two museums of the region are
currently staging shows of his work. The Norman Rockwell Museum in
Stockbridge, Mass., is presenting ``Winslow Homer: Artist and
Illustrator,'' while the Portland Museum of Art in Maine has come
up with an ambitious but more familiar survey, ``Winslow Homer
Facing Nature.''
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, the smaller show at the Rockwell museum,
built to honor the corny but cherished American illustrator,
focuses on the magazine and newspaper side of Homer's art. The show
in Portland celebrates the 15th anniversary of the Charles Shipman
Payson building, put up in recognition of Payson's gift of 17
Homers, and it covers the full range of the artist's career. Still,
the exhibitions complement each other nicely and in some areas even
overlap.
</P>
<P>
   Apprenticed to a lithographer at 19, Homer soon graduated to
freelance drawing for Ballou's Pictorial and, beginning in 1859,
Harper's Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   He did appealing genre scenes: bustling streets, college life,
country festivals, cotillions, seashore vignettes. But his career
took off with the Civil War, which Harper's sent him to cover.
</P>
<P>
   By then, he knew how to draw for woodblock reproduction,
producing strong, simple designs in shallow perspective, a
technique that was to affect his later painting style. From the
front, he dispatched illustrations regularly, in the process honing
a gift for pictorial narrative that carried through his career.
</P>
<P>
   There are examples in both exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland show has ``The War for the Union 1862 _ A Cavalry
Charge,'' done for Harper's Weekly, an old-fashioned European-style
battle scene of flailing sabers and fallen horses. In the Rockwell
show, ``Our Women and the War,'' also done for Harper's in 1862,
depicts several touching but very Victorian vignettes of women
knitting, sewing and tending wounded men.
</P>
<P>
   But an even more poignant scene, ``Our Watering Places: The
Empty Sleeve at Newport,'' that appeared in Harper's in 1865, shows
a maturing style.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp, close-cropped and focused on two individuals, it depicts
a young belle driving a gig, while beside her sits a somber veteran
with an empty sleeve pinned to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the war, Homer had become one of the most popular
illustrators in the best magazines of the time. When it was over,
he resumed his attractive renditions of everyday life, particularly
Americans at play, but the work was clearer and more cleverly
thought out.
</P>
<P>
   A vivid ice-skating scene, done for Frank Leslie's Illustrated
Newspaper in 1866, has a carefully off-balance composition, closing
in on three dashing skaters in the left foreground, their backs to
the viewer. The scene may reflect Homer's awareness of the
sophisticated Japanese prints known to artists of the time, but he
had also learned draftsmanship and composition from the technicians
he worked with.
</P>
<P>
   The real interest of the Rockwell show is its focus on the play
back and forth between Homer's paintings _ during the war, he had
begun to work in oils _ and his illustrations. He mined the former
for magazine material, and sometimes vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   His famous painting of schoolboys at play, ``Snap the Whip''
(1872) _ shown here, alas, in reproduction _ also appears as an
illustration in Harper's in 1873, with more clarity and detail than
the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seesaw,'' a watercolor of 1873, depicts four boys playing
on a seesaw balanced on rocks. But in a Harper's illustration the
next year, three girls playing cat's cradle have been added to the
same scene, taken from a different 1873 watercolor in which they
were playing with a lobster.
</P>
<P>
   A similar juxtaposition is made in the show at the Portland
Museum, where Homer's famous Civil War painting ``Sharpshooter''
(1863), portraying a rifleman taking aim while perched in a tree,
is paired with ``The Army of the Potomac _ A Sharpshooter on Picket
Duty,'' from an 1862 issue of Harper's. In this case, however, the
painting, tightened up in its composition, appears to have been
made after the illustration.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland show, with some 50 paintings, drawings and
engravings, essentially addresses the prevailing theme of nature in
Homer's work, from pastoral views to scenes of trapping and fishing
in the Adirondacks to encounters with the ocean, like
``Weatherbeaten'' (1894), a magnificent rendition of the sea as it
writhed and thrashed against rocks near his Prouts Neck studio.
</P>
<P>
   Included, too, are a number of works done in Cullercoats, the
English fishing village on the North Sea where Homer went in 1881
to renew himself and his subject matter. He not only recorded the
ravenous ocean, hungry for sailors and ships, he also focused on
the women of the village, strongly built ``fishergirls'' very
different from the playful American princesses he had once
delighted in.
</P>
<P>
   For the splendid ``Windy Day, Cullercoats'' (1881), he used a
combination of graphite and gouache on brown paper to draw one of
these stalwarts, standing on the shore, a basket on her muscular
arm, as the wind whips the sail of a boat behind her and makes a
sail of the apron she wears over her dress.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, so taken was Homer with the fisherwomen that he later
portrayed them as types in Maine settings, for example in ``Down
the Cliff'' (1883), a watercolor made near his studio that shows a
lone woman standing against the sky, her dress blowing, a basket on
her arm.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, the show includes a tiny pair of artist's
mannequins dressed by Homer in fisherwomen's garb, which he
apparently used as an aid once back from England.
</P>
<P>
   For those who know Homer's work, these two shows will provide a
productive revisit. For those who think they don't, the rewards are
great.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
