<HEADER>
A4361 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-DAUGHTERS-COX     08-20 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-DAUGHTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Daughters' chronicles U.S. women's often-turbulent battle to
become airborne
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Carolyn Nizzi Warmbold
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Hillary Rodham Clinton announced in March that Air Force
Lt. Col. Eileen Collins would be the first woman to command an
American space flight, the first lady declared the assignment ``one
big step forward for women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amelia Earhart's Daughters'' documents how giant a leap it
was. Academics Leslie Hayns-
</P>
<P>
   worth and David Toomey chronicle the histories of two groups:
the women aviators who ferried aircraft during World War II, and 13
women pilots who hoped to be astronauts in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   The authors' method of telling the story woman by woman makes
for a readable, though patchy history. By the last page, one craves
some analysis and wishes that race and class issues had been as
directly addressed as gender discrimination. Still, this book fills
in gaps in the past and is vital to women's studies and aviation
history.
</P>
<P>
   Two names especially emerge from World War II annals: Jackie
Cochran, director of the Women's Airforce Service Pilots (WASP)
training program, and Nancy Harkness Love, founder of the Women's
Auxiliary Ferrying Squadron (WAFS).
</P>
<P>
   The WASP secretly trained to ferry aircraft in Houston and
Sweetwater, Texas, with the volunteers passing themselves off as a
women's basketball team. Ignoring a directive to avoid flying
during menstrual cycles, the WAFS went on to ferry troublesome
planes such as the P-39, while the WASP trained in craft including
the B-26, so tricky it was known as ``The Widowmaker.'' Gen. Hap
Arnold found that the women were willing to take on dangerous
assignments feared even by accomplished male pilots.
</P>
<P>
   By 1944, he was so pleased that he urged armed service
recognition for the WASP (the military did not even pay for the
women's burials). But, the authors write, some male civilian pilots
and veterans groups protested, and the women did not receive the
same benefits accorded the WAC and WAVES. When the Air Force cut
back at the end of the year, the WASP was disbanded. Congress did
not approve their veteran status until 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,074 women who trained at Sweetwater flew more than 60
million miles in every Air Force craft. Thirty-eight died, some in
training, some on duty. The women returned to their families or
other war efforts. Some were offered jobs from commercial airlines
_ as stewardesses.
</P>
<P>
   Between the war and the space age, it was almost impossible for
women to receive jet training. Cochran managed to train privately
with Chuck Yeager and became the first woman to break the sound
barrier in 1953. But women, such as aviation executive Jerrie Cobb
of Oklahoma City, were proficient civilian instructors or test
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb met Randolph Lovelace, director of the Albuquerque, N.M.,
astronaut medical testing clinic, at a 1959 conference. When Cobb's
boss suggested that she be considered for the space program,
Lovelace listened. He knew the Russians were planning to use women
cosmonauts.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, Cobb, who had been appointed a NASA
consultant, and 25 other women _ including Myrtle Cagle of Macon _
went through the relentless medical and stress tests at the
Lovelace Clinic. The 13 who passed were ordered to report to
Pensacola, Fla., for flight testing, but just before their
departure the secret program was abruptly canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Dietrich, one of the 13, wrote about their experience for
McCall's magazine. The aviators received hate mail _ some from
women _ telling them to go home and take care of their kids.
Congressional hearings into the fitness of women as astronauts went
nowhere partly because they had not been trained as jet pilots.
</P>
<P>
   On June 13, 1963, Valentina Tereshkova of Russia became the
first woman in space. She was greeted with cheers and flowers in
Moscow. Khrushchev departed from his prepared text, looked at
Tereshkova, grinned, shook his finger at the crowd and said, ``Here
is your weaker
</P>
<P>
   sex. ...''
</P>
<P>
   That was almost two decades before Sally Ride's historic flight,
and more than three decades before Feb. 3, 1995, when Collins
became the first woman to pilot a U.S. spacecraft. Watching from
the VIP stands in Cape Canaveral, Fla., were her special guests:
former members of the WASP and seven of the original women tested
for the astronaut program.
</P>
<P>
   Amelia Earhart's Daughters: The Wild and Glorious Story of
American Women Aviators from World War II to the Dawn of the Space
Age. By Leslie Haynsworth and David Toomey. Morrow. $24. 322 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An important, if incomplete chapter of history.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
