<HEADER>
A4362 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE23-COX     08-20 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another `best' list, but this history took some thought
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL AUGUST 23: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you thought you'd heard the end of it, just when the
howls of hilarity and cries of indignation had died to subdued
chuckles and mutterings, it's back. Another List of 100 Books
Better Than All Others _ and James Joyce's ``Ulysses'' didn't make
it.
</P>
<P>
   This one is called ``The 100 Most Influential Books Ever
Written: The History of Thought From Ancient Times to Today''
(Citadel Press, $34.95), and it beats the socks off Modern
Library's best 20th-century novels in English.
</P>
<P>
   That list, you'll recall, prompted so much high dudgeon you
might have thought an official inquiry were in order. Only last
week, in the pages of The New Yorker, William Styron, a member of
the Modern Library jury that hasn't forgotten ``The Magnificent
Ambersons,'' tried to distance himself from the verdict. Styron
explained, plausibly enough, how ballots by mail led to a system of
tallying whose results were, well, weird. ``When I saw the final
roster,'' Styron writes, ``I was a little shocked at what the 10 of
us had wrought, not only in respect to the list's glaring omissions
(no Toni Morrison, no Patrick White, only eight women in the lot)
but in respect to its generally oppressive stodginess.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Martin Seymour-Smith, a jury of one, pronouncing with
confident assurance that a different set of books stands above all
others. These are not just books in English, not just books written
in this century, not just novels; Seymour-Smith means, so to speak,
the entire library, from ``The I Ching'' to ``The Feminine
Mystique.'' Unlike the Modern Library jury, though, he doesn't set
himself the trap of ranking 1 through 100. (To do so ``would have
been too frivolous and would have begged far too many questions.'')
Instead he chose 100 that ``have exercised, if sometimes in devious
and very subterranean ways, the most decisive influence upon the
course of human thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Author a respected biographer, critic
</P>
<P>
   It's necessary to speak of Seymour-Smith in both the present and
the past tense. He is in every sense another Dead White Male _ he
died July 1 at his home in England. More important, he was a
distinguished biographer and critic who unleashed his opinions with
a wit and relish that might have saved the Modern Library jury from
charges of superannuation and senility.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour-Smith is not afraid to assert or to judge. John Locke
was ``the shifty and emotionally indecisive, but gifted, English
philosopher ... to whose thinking America owes its constitution.''
(A bit overstated on all counts?) Betty Friedan, in ``The Feminine
Mystique,'' ``could not possibly (have anticipated) that within 25
years male-controlled magazines, nominally edited by women, would
be publishing psychologically unconvincing and merely fashionable
tales of `liberated' women. It would have been fatal for her to
have seen that feminism would soon turn into pseudofeminism.'' (But
what of the reaction against feminism by females themselves?)
</P>
<P>
   A task like Seymour-Smith's is undertaken boldly or it is not
undertaken at all. When bets are hedged and punches pulled, the
entire enterprise collapses from dullness. Implicit in ``The 100
Most Influential Books Ever Written'' is the assumption that
readers will agree here, disagree there. Seymour-Smith pays them
the compliment of having minds of their own. He comes to converse
more than to canonize.
</P>
<P>
   Some masterpieces missing
</P>
<P>
   How different this is from the Modern Library jurors, who merely
checked off titles supplied them by Random House. Consider that a
single book made both lists: George Orwell's ``Nineteen
Eighty-Four.'' Orwell's novel, ``as well as satirizing Stalinist
`purity' and deceit ... anticipates the almost exactly parallel
development of the equally drab and tyrannical `political
correctness' of our own times.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing from Seymour-Smith's list are any number of masterpieces
_ not only ``Ulysses'' (No. 1 in the Modern Library rankings) but
also Scott Fitzgerald's ``The Great Gatsby'' (No. 2), the entire
corpus of Hemingway, Faulkner and Toni Morrison (nothing like being
denied twice). The point is not literary merit, but influence over
the way we think and act.
</P>
<P>
   To that Seymour-Smith would add, ``for better or worse.'' Thus,
the Old Testament and New Testament, the Koran, Thomas Paine's
``Common Sense,'' Freud's ``The Interpretation of Dreams,'' Franz
Kafka's ``The Trial,'' Darwin's ``The Origin of Species'' and
90-some others.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, they add up to what the historian Arthur Lovejoy
called ``The Great Chain of Being.'' The mathematician Norbert
Wiener, selected for his 1948 book ``Cybernetics,'' put it more
nicely still: ``We are swimming upstream against a great torrent of
disorganization. ... It is the greatest possible victory to be, to
continue to be, and to have been. ... No defeat can deprive us of
the success of having existed for some moment in time in a universe
that seems indifferent to us.''
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
