<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN21-COX     08-20 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: It's not in glee that I recalled Macon killer
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A letter from a former resident of Macon, Georgia takes me to
task for referring to Anjette Lyles, ``the Macon murderess,'' in a
column last week.
</P>
<P>
   She says I ``gleefully'' made the reference, and I assure her
there's nothing gleeful about my recollection of the 1958 murder of
two husbands, a mother-in-law and a 10-year-old daughter by the
platinum-haired restaurant operator, who is now dead.
</P>
<P>
   Their suffering from arsenic, which she was convicted of feeding
them, was so hideous, it is painful now _ 40 years later _ to think
of it. As I recall, I had the case on my mind because I had just
talked to a young woman who has written a book about the Lyles
murders and trial.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Jaclyn White; the book, still untitled as far as I
know, is to be published by Mercer University Press. It is so
voluminous and brilliantly researched that if family members of
Anjette Lyles are sensitive to my one-line reference to her, they
may want to get out of the country before this book comes out.
</P>
<P>
   The former Macon resident who wrote to me detailed her family's
friendship with the Donovan and Lyles families, Anjette's own
relatives and her in-laws. She wrote, ``Putting ourselves in their
places, imagine the ordeal that family went through. ... They
struggled through it, managing to keep living normal lives and
conducting themselves with the grace and dignity that we should all
hope to emulate should such an event be thrust upon our own
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   As one who has covered a number of murder trials and become
fairly well acquainted with some murderers, I know that almost
always the murderer's family suffers unabated grief and
humiliation. I didn't realize Anjette had so many relatives left
after the slaying of two husbands, a mother-in-law and a daughter.
I assumed that her younger daughter, Carla, who would be about 47,
is alive and well, but I don't know where. She was taken from
Anjette and may have grown up protected from details of the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   My correspondent tells of one family member who emphatically was
not protected: Anjette's brother. He died a few months ago after
reading in The Macon Telegraph a story on the infamous criminals in
the city's history, featuring Anjette's case. He had a heart attack
and died the day after that article was published, my correspondent
wrote, adding, ``Coincidence? Cause and effect? We will never know.
He was, after all, in his 70s and had a heart condition anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, I am sorry for his suffering and for any I may have
caused anybody. I do resent the letter writer's belief that there
was a ``media frenzy'' surrounding that case.
</P>
<P>
   I covered the Lyles story for the Constitution; Margaret
Shannon, since retired, covered it for the Journal; Hugh Schute
covered it for The Associated Press. Different staff members
covered it for the Macon papers, coming and going as the trial
progressed, and by no means frenziedly.
</P>
<P>
   There was no thundering herd act, no yelling questions at
Anjette, no pushing and crowding for a view of her. We were
assigned seats in the courtroom balcony, and we listened quietly,
nauseated and horrified as the details of the crimes were related
from the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   Anjette died of heart failure Dec. 4, 1977, at the state
hospital in Milledgeville. She was 52. She is buried in the
churchyard at Coleman's Chapel in Wadley, in Jefferson County,
beside her first husband, ``Little Ben'' Lyles, and daughter
Marcia, both victims of the arsenic-heavy Terra Ant Bane.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
