<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMUNE-FETUSES-life-C     08-20 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMUNE-FETUSES-life-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why isn't a pregnant woman's immune system attacking and
destroying fetuses?
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia researchers have solved a 45-year-old riddle: Why
mothers are able to carry babies to term.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ability most people never question. Yet it has puzzled
scientists since 1953, when a British immunologist pointed out that
fetuses, being genetically different from their mothers, should be
rejected by their mothers as foreign tissue _ but they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Medical College of Georgia and the
University of Georgia have discovered the mechanism that keeps the
mother's immune system from attacking and destroying fetuses. The
findings appear in today's issue of the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery someday could lead to new treatments for
auto-immune diseases such as juvenile diabetes, rheumatoid
arthritis and multiple sclerosis. It also might help scientists
better understand how to prevent miscarriages or rejection of organ
transplants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a rather surprising mechanism, which no one had
previously guessed at,'' said study co-author Andrew Mellor, a
molecular geneticist and immunologist at MCG in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, a body's immune system attacks any foreign cells that
enter it. Foreign, in this case, could mean anything from
disease-causing bacteria to a life-saving transplanted organ.
</P>
<P>
   But no one considered that fetuses might also fall into this
category until 1953, when Sir Peter B. Medawar spotlighted the
apparent contradiction that mammalian fetuses survive in utero,
despite differing genetically from their mothers. Mammalian
offspring inherit genes from both parents.
</P>
<P>
   Medawar later won a Nobel Prize in medicine, but his paradox has
remained unsolved until now.
</P>
<P>
   The key lies in an enzyme, called IDO, that is created by cells
in the placenta, the membrane through which the mother delivers
nourishment to and removes wastes from the fetus. The placenta is
the barrier as well as the interface between mother and child.
</P>
<P>
   IDO acts as a sort of local anesthetic, by suppressing the
mother's immune system within the placenta. It does this by
breaking down tryptophan, an essential amino acid required by
T-cells, which orchestrate the body's immune system responses.
</P>
<P>
   Mellor and his colleagues tested their barrier mechanism theory
in mice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reasoned that when we block that mechanism, the mother
would now see the fetus as foreign tissue and reject it,'' Mellor
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the researchers inhibited the mechanism in pregnant mice,
they all miscarried.
</P>
<P>
   In another set of experiments, scientists confirmed that the
genetic differences between the mother and its fetus are
responsible for incurring rejection when the barrier mechanism
fails or is inhibited.
</P>
<P>
   To prove this, the research team used strains of mice specially
inbred to be genetically identical. They mated mice who were
essentially twins. The female mice, therefore, conceived fetuses
who also were their genetic duplicates.
</P>
<P>
   When the researchers blocked the barrier mechanism in the
pregnant mice, nothing happened. The mice carried their pregnancies
to term _ because their bodies didn't recognize the pups as
foreign.
</P>
<P>
   A final confirmation of the theory was the observation that mice
that lack immune systems were able to carry and deliver genetically
different pups. No barrier mechanism was needed in these mice,
because no immune system existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely, I think, do you find such clear-cut results that
absolutely agree with the hypothesis like this,'' said Emory
immunologist Judith Kapp. ``It's the kind of study we all dream
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Much more research must be done, though, to understand
specifically how the barrier mechanism works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just at the infancy stage of doing these experiments,''
said Dr. David Munn, a pediatric oncologist at MCG who also
co-authored the study. ``We're just so floored at having found this
mechanism to investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are now studying whether the barrier mechanism in
the placenta occurs elsewhere in the human body. But new treatments
based on the research are years away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
