<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``That '70's Show'' is true to form with a little innocence
mixed in
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox dribbles out the new TV season at 8:30 p.m. EDT Sunday with
``That '70s Show,'' an amusingly slight sitcom that follows a group
of Wisconsin high school friends in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   With this creation of Bonnie and Terry Turner (``3rd Rock from
the Sun''), Fox finally finds a smartly subversive family that
isn't animated. Think ``Happy Days'' meets ``Dazed and Confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Ground zero here is the basement rec room of Eric Foreman
(Topher Grace), a likeable, clean-cut kid eager to earn his
teen-rebel stripes. The spacious basement is where the teens hatch
plots to pocket beers from their parents' upstairs disco party;
watch ``The Brady Bunch'' without the sound; smoke a little pot _
all with a '70s nonchalance that looks almost staggering today.
</P>
<P>
   Eric is aided and encouraged in his pursuits by a teen
menagerie. Donna (Laura Prepon) is a neighbor since childhood whom
Eric now awkwardly realizes has grown up gorgeous. Kelso (Ashton
Kutcher) is an accidental Romeo always ready to dump his girlfriend
Jackie (Mila Kunis) even as he gets more involved with her. Hyde
(Danny Masterson) is a bright kid capable of spotting a corporate
conspiracy where none appears to be. And foreign exchange student
Fez (Wilmer Valderrama) seems to absorb American culture just to
mangle it.
</P>
<P>
   They're not bad kids; they just want a taste of being bad. Their
parents get that, and the two sides exist with a knowing, even
loving distrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonder where they're going?'' Eric's mother (Debra Jo Rupp)
asks her husband when she hears Eric and his friends getting into
the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of town,'' Eric's father (Kurtwood Smith) answers
off-handedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sure?'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he answers. ``I told them not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby'' lacks common sense
</P>
<P>
   Babies are always pooping, fathers are inept, and women, even
one you just met a few minutes ago, are perfectly suited caregivers
for your infant, right?
</P>
<P>
   That's the inane setup for Fox's other new fall sitcom ``Holding
The Baby'' (7:30 p.m. EDT Sunday), that's also the network's latest
assault on parenthood and common sense.
</P>
<P>
   John Patrick Walker stars as Gordon, a corporate-climbing ad
exec who neglects his family and drives his wife to attend ``a
stupid woman's retreat'' from which she _ understandbly _never
returns. Ill-equipped to care for their 6-month-old son, Gordon
enlists the help of his brother Jimmy, an unemployed playboy, and
Kelly, a grad student who is conveniently applying for a job at the
firm when his life falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   Silly and tasteless, the show depends on baby Dan's prodigous
bodily functions for most of its jokes. But in the end, ``Holding
the Baby'' is nothing more than a soggy diaper that reeks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _Lyle V. Harris, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Rock a surrvivor of the late-night battles
</P>
<P>
   While others battle for the ``The King of Late Night'' title,
comedian Chris Rock is content being the undisputed clown prince of
cable.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's self-titled late-night talker starts its third season
tonight on HBO (11:30 p.m.EDT) with celebrity guests Johnnie
Cochran and British hip-hop sensation Tricky.
</P>
<P>
   While Rock has spent most of his career in obscurity, the last
two years have seen him become a Nike pitchman, a Grammy-winning
comic, a movie star, and a survivor of the late-night talk show
battles that have claimed other well-intentioned hosts such as
Keenen Ivory Wayans, Sinbad and ex-basketball star Earvin ``Magic''
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Rock says his show has been successful because it's only on once
a week, and even though he's on a cable network, the
commercial-free environment gives him the creative freedom to say
whatever he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in the mass business and I didn't get into show
business to work every day,'' Rock said during a telephone
interview. ``I'd rather play 5,000 seats than 105,000 seats as long
as people get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rock said he has sympathy for the other talk show hosts
who became late night casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to judge those guys, Magic was supposed to fail.
I don't mean that in a bad way. If I played guard for the Lakers,
I'd probably fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock said even if he got a chance to host a broadcast network
show and play to larger audiences, he'd avoid making the same fatal
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason they give talk shows to comedian,'' he said.
``You gotta really be focused on comedy _ not on guest wars and the
muscial guests. You have to give people good comedy. They don't
want a sexy or hip show, they just want to laugh. The funniest guy
is the hippest guy. The funniest guy is the sexiest guy. I'm not
really criticizing those shows, but they tried to outhip each other
instead of trying to out-funny each other.''
</P>
<P>
   _Lyle V. Harris, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
