<SLUG> BC-BC-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET THAT LAPTOP OFF YOUR SHOULDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laptop vendors are not in the business of selling carrying cases
for their products, except as a courtesy. Most will offer a decent
case, but it usually has just enough room to carry the laptop, the
power supply and little else.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are cases that offer plenty of space and are easy
to transport -- because they're on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   When I did a roundup of laptop carrying cases a year ago, the
premise was that many people spend a lot of money for a computer
and then dump it in a cheesy, cheap bag that offers little
protection for their investment. That situation hasn't changed
much. But the latest rolling cases offer enough advantages that
business travelers might want to consider upgrading.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who travel for a living have to carry much more that
just a laptop. We still need a briefcase for all the paper that is
generated in this so-called paperless society. And we need
something to protect all the other electronic devices we lug
around: computer peripherals, cellular phones, pagers and so on.
Not to mention telephone cords, batteries and various other bits of
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   A good bag should also protect more than just the computer -- it
needs to protect your health. Several vendors have finally decided
that a rolling case is useful for many travelers because it can
handle all the extras while getting all that weight off your
shoulders and keeping your knuckles from dragging on the floor in
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Port has a new case called the EasyRoller. The folks at Port
make first-rate bags, but the marketing department should do better
research. The advertisements claim that the EasyRoller is the first
computer briefcase on wheels. Lodis might be a little surprised by
that claim -- I've owned one of their rolling computer briefcases
for nearly a year. And at last year's Comdex computer show, I found
several roller bags.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing gaffe aside, the EasyRoller is a nicely designed
unit. The telescoping pistol-grip handle seems very sturdy, and I
like the fact that the release button is on the handle. I've never
been fond of the ones that force you to bend over before you can
make the handle retract.
</P>
<P>
   The EasyRoller has a large compartment in the rear that provides
a fair amount of flexibility through the use of what Port calls
``System 2000'' modules. One module lets you carry a second laptop.
Another module lets you carry a portable printer and a Zip drive
with accessories. A third module is a file folder, and the final
module is for extra clothes and a toiletries bag. The EasyRoller
retails for $149, and each of the modules is $29. While Port is
taking orders, it won't ship the EasyRoller until late August or
early September.
</P>
<P>
   Targus' Pilot Case is one of two rolling units in its product
line. It is a hard-side case and has space for both a laptop and a
printer, or even a second laptop. The two outside pockets can hold
a cell phone and a personal digital assistant. The laptop
compartments are loaded from the top, but there is a side
compartment that holds all your office supplies and drops down as a
portable desk. The Pilot has a street price of $190.
</P>
<P>
   The other rolling case of interest is from Anvil Cases. It is
called the Speedster and has a retractable handle. The case is
designed to withstand the rigors of airline baggage handlers. It is
custom-made to your specifications so you can have all the
compartments you want, but there's a price to pay -- around $500
depending on the options you choose.
</P>
<P>
   While the other bags are first-rate, they still lag behind the
Lodis Exec-on-the-Go. As far as I'm concerned, this case set the
standard. I've carted it everywhere and in all kinds of conditions.
It has held up through a daily commute on the New York City subway
system, and it still looks brand new. The only problem I've had is
a cracked ring on one of the handles, but I'm not eager to be
without the bag for the time it would take to ship it back for
repair. It's a problem that I can live with until the ring actually
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Port: port.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ Targus Pilot: targus.com/products/cpo2.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ Anvil Cases: anvilcase.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ Lodis: lodis.com/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen C. Miller is assistant to the technology editor at The
New York Times.)
</P>
