<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-ARTS-AT-LARGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSICAL CDS WITH THE SCORE AND MORE
</HEADLINE>
  By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And now it's time to sing along with Maurizio.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of following the bouncing ball, keep your eye on the
computer monitor. As Maurizio Pollini tickles the ivories on three
little numbers we like to call the Beethoven piano sonatas Opus 22,
26 and 53, the sheet music scrolls past and a vertical stripe of
color highlights the onscreen notes as they are played.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the pianist's flying fingers outpace the computer,
especially in the speedy presto passages. For the most part,
though, the sound that streams from the speakers is synchronized
with the marker as it glides over the page.
</P>
<P>
   Pollini is one of the leading pianists of our time. These
splendid performances, live recordings made in 1997, have been
preserved on a standard -- and standard-priced -- audio compact
disk released in the United States in April by Deutsche Grammophon.
</P>
<P>
   But the disk is also the first in a series of ``CD-pluscore''
titles developed by the venerable German music publisher Schott. An
indirect descendant of the Voyager Company's line of classical
music CD-ROMs, it is essentially an enhanced CD, except that the
multimedia material supplementing the audio content is richer than
the usual jumble of video clips and interactive games that
characterizes the ECD format. As a bonus, the scores for the
``Waldstein'' sonata (Op. 53) and the two earlier works can be
printed out in their entirety.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pollini's pianistic pyrotechnics would probably prevent
any kind of sing-along session or keyboard karaoke, Deutsche
Grammophon and Schott deserve a chorus of hosannas for allowing the
complete scores to be tracked with precision while the disk spins
in the CD-ROM drive of a PC-compatible computer.
</P>
<P>
   Staring into the screen, one can easily imagine sitting at
Pollini's side during a concert and serving as his page-turner --
except that the computer flips the pages at just the right moment.
Even those who cannot read music are likely to enjoy following the
rise and fall of the notes and ``seeing'' the silence whenever
musical rests occur.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, the scores have been cross-linked with a
musicological analysis, penned by the Beethoven expert Barry
Cooper, that pops up in an adjacent window. The text describing
each movement is divided into sections like ``exposition'' and
``recapitulation,'' and it is further cross-linked with a glossary
defining ``arpeggio'' and other relevant terms.
</P>
<P>
   This analysis can be read while the audio disk plays from start
to finish, but the speaker icons that introduce each section of the
text call up the relevant musical passages, enabling listeners to
hear how Beethoven constructed the sonatas.
</P>
<P>
   Thoughtful touches abound. A timer can be set to track minutes
or count bars, making it easier to find the related commentary in
the adjacent text. Cooper has also provided a Beethoven chronology
and some brief biographical essays. The sheet music can be printed
as-is, or with user-supplied marks for fingerings, tempo and
dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   The software on the disk, including the score, takes up less
space than 50 seconds of audio data, according to Katya Kratzer,
manager of Schott's multimedia division.
</P>
<P>
   Kratzer explained that the score was synchronized to the
performance by hand, bar by bar. She acknowledged that the vertical
marker that tracks the score will sometimes appear to pause,
showing the points where Pollini is taking the subtle liberties
with rhythm that help to personalize a musical interpretation.
``It's been done on purpose to show the rubato a little bit, to
show where he's 'improvising,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Did the pianist, who is known for his formidable technique, ever
cause problems by departing from the score?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not Pollini,'' Kratzer said with a laugh. ``He never misses
notes. There are other artists who do, but it is really amazing how
exactly you can synchronize Pollini's playing to the score.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Deutsche Grammophon recently issued the next two
titles in the CD-pluscore series: a collection of easy piano pieces
played by diverse performers, and ``Cellissimo,'' a set of newly
published arrangements for the cellist Mischa Maisky. The disks
have yet to be released in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Although no more Pollini disks are planned for the series, a
string-quartet project is in the works, as is a 4-CD box of the
complete Beethoven violin sonatas played by Anne-Sophie Mutter.
Kratzer said the CD-pluscore system could also be applied to
orchestral recordings, but that their large-format sheet music
makes them impractical for display on the small-screen monitors
that dominate the European computer market.
</P>
<P>
   Some future releases will contain MIDI (musical instrument
digital interface) files so that, for example, an amateur pianist
could accompany a computer-generated version of Mutter playing the
``Kreutzer'' sonata, altering the tempo to suit his or her skill
level. Pollini vetoed this feature on his disk, Kratzer said,
``because he did not want his music to be changed by the user.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, IDG Books and the EMI record label teamed to produce
the Classical Music for Dummies series of enhanced CDs. The disks
</P>
<P>
   contained essays written in a cutesy style and interactive
features that were not well-executed, including scrolling scores
for short works accompanied by computer-generated beeps and some
bland descriptive text.
</P>
<P>
   With CD-pluscore disk, Deutsche Grammophon and Schott have
realized a brighter idea. This is classical music for smarties, and
anyone can play.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   _ Pollini's recording of the Beethoven Piano Sonatas Opus 22, 26
and 53: dgclassics.com/news/newsff05.htm
</P>
<P>
