<HEADER>
A4369 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERTIMES-EDUCATION-     08-20 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERTIMES-EDUCATION-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL DISTRICT ACCUSED OF SOFTWARE PIRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  By PAMELA MENDELS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials in the Los Angeles Unified School District have
learned the hard way that software -- like textbooks, desks and
other school supplies -- is not free.
</P>
<P>
   The district faces the possibility of paying almost $5 million
to settle accusations of software piracy brought by the Business
Software Alliance, a coalition of software publishers, including
Microsoft Corp., based in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles's difficulties began two years ago when coalition
officials, acting on a tip to their anti-piracy phone line, began
investigating whether the West Valley Occupational Center, an adult
vocational school under district jurisdiction, had pirated software
running on its computers.
</P>
<P>
   The group said it found 1,400 copies of unlicensed software in
use, including Microsoft Word and Adobe Photoshop.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Software Alliance is asking, among other things,
that the school district pay $300,000 -- the approximate value of
the copies -- to the group's anti-piracy fund. But the big ticket
items in the proposal are requirements stipulating that any
unlicensed software running in other Los Angeles schools be
replaced with licensed copies and that the district establish a
team to train staff members in copyright do's and don'ts -- efforts
that district officials say would cost about $4.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Los Angeles Unified School District declined
to comment, saying the accusations were the subject of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   However, David N. Tokofsky, one of the seven members of the
district school board, said that while he does not condone software
piracy, he is unhappy with how the Business Software Alliance has
acted, likening the anti-piracy phone line to the use of moles. He
also said that with the millions of dollars software companies
spend on advertising touting the educational value of their
products, he felt they could afford to help a poor urban school
district like Los Angeles train staff members in copyright
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have said, 'We don't want the $300,000,''' Tokofsky
said, and instead given ``an offer of training, reconciliation and
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Kruger, vice president of enforcement for the Business
Software Alliance, rebutted the criticism, pointing out that
tipsters to the phone line are not rewarded and that software
makers often help school districts by offering them discounted
prices for software. Furthermore, he said, the proposed settlement
is less an effort to collect money than it is an effort to
encourage the school district ``to eliminate reliance on pirated
software.''
</P>
<P>
   Software makers hope the financial rap on the knuckles will
serve as a warning to other schools around the country to make sure
that programs running on school computers are licensed copies.
``Could this serve as an example to other school systems?'' Kruger
asked. ``I would hope so. Not just because there are financial
interests attached, but because it points to the right thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruger said that unauthorized use of software is widespread by
both individuals and companies, estimating that for every four
pieces of software in American hands, one is a pirated copy. He
acknowledged that it was impossible to ascertain whether that
proportion applies to schools, too.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jamieson A. McKenzie, a former school superintendent
who advises schools on how to use technology and publishes an
online journal on the subject, believes, based on anecdotes, that
the problem in schools is widespread. ``In many places, people
think 'the software is for kids; it's for a good cause and there's
nothing illegal about it,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But another education expert indicated that the Los Angeles
example was unusual. For one thing, said E. Joseph Schneider,
deputy executive director of the American Association of School
Administrators, ``there is not a school district in the country
that would not have a fairly well-spelled-out policy about
authorized software use on the books.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, it is standard procedure in most school
districts to have computer technicians regularly run software
programs that tell them what other software is running on the
computers under their care. If unauthorized copies are found, they
are purged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is not just the desire of school officials to comply
with copyright laws, added Schneider, whose organization represents
about 16,000 school superintendents. Computer viruses often begin
with a piece of what he called ``refugee'' software. And school
officials want to swiftly eliminate any potentially problematic --
or controversial -- programs that may be introduced to school
computer systems by mischievous youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   For Sarah B. Alexander, a spokeswoman for Microsoft, there is
another issue: Too often, she said, people who would not dream of
stealing, say, a book, believe it is legitimate to use software
without paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do they justify it?'' she asked. ``Just because it's
easier to make a copy of software than a desk or a book?''
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Business Software Alliance: bsa.org/
</P>
<P>
   _McKenzie's technology journal: fromnowon.org/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Pamela Mendels, a Manhattan-based writer, covers education,
government, censorship and civil rights issues for CyberTimes.)
</P>
