<TEXT>
<P>
   The following articles constitute this week's transmission of
The New York Times Syndicate's CyberTimes package. All have been
sent to category codes ``l'' lifestyle news or ``f'' business news.
</P>
<P>
   1. ``TRAVEL LOG: GET THAT LAPTOP OFF YOUR SHOULDERS''
</P>
<P>
   Laptop vendors may give you a decent case with your computer,
but it usually has just enough room to carry the laptop, the power
supply and little else. However, there are cases that offer plenty
of space and are easy to transport -- because they're on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-COLUMN-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   2. ``ARTS(AT)LARGE: CLASSICAL CDS WITH THE SCORE AND MORE''
</P>
<P>
   An enhanced CD lets users follow along in the score and read
background essays as Maurizio Pollini plays three Beethoven piano
sonatas. Similar CDs of several classical works are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-CYBERTIMES-ARTS-AT-LARGE-NYTSF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   3. ``EDUCATION: SCHOOL DISTRICT ACCUSED OF SOFTWARE PIRACY''
</P>
<P>
   School officials in the Los Angeles Unified School District have
learned the hard way that software -- like textbooks, desks and
other school supplies -- is not free. The district faces the
possibility of paying almost $5 million to settle accusations of
software piracy brought by the Business Software Alliance, a
coalition of software publishers.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-CYBERTIMES-EDUCATION-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   4. ``CYBERLAW JOURNAL: FILMMAKER SUES OVER TERMINATION OF
E-MAIL''
</P>
<P>
   A filmmaker is suing Earthlink, an Internet service provider,
for more than $7 million, claiming that the company wrongly
terminated his e-mail service at a crucial time. The novel case
could help establish ground rules for ISPs who want to shut down
e-mail accounts they believe have been misused.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-CYBERTIMES-LAW-JOURNAL-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   5. ``EUROBYTES: GERMAN STUDENTS BUILD A NEXT-GENERATION
'SHOPBOT'''
</P>
<P>
   Two young German students have taken a big step in the
development of ``smart'' shopping agents. Their engine searches
many sites and displays prices that include shipping and handling
calculated according to the location of the customer, and delivery
time is factored in.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-CYBERTIMES-EUROBYTES-NYTSF
</P>
