<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALZBURG-FESTIVAL-2TA     08-20 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALZBURG-FESTIVAL-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING THE OTHER STAGE AT SALZBURG  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Anne Midgette writes frequently on international art, music and
theater  
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALZBURG, Austria _ In the opinion of Joseph F. Troy, who heads
the board of the American Friends of Salzburg, ``Critics and
audiences alike have long acclaimed the Salzburg Festival as the
leading music festival in the world.'' To Alberto Vilar, the
organization's president, it is ``the premier summer classical
music festival.''
</P>
<P>
   Most international music lovers would agree. To them, the name
Salzburg Festival evokes the musical legacy of the conductor
Herbert von Karajan, who from the 1960s until his death in 1989
dominated the Austrian festival with concerts and traditional
productions of star-studded operas.
</P>
<P>
   But to German speakers, who make up some 80 percent of the
festival's audience, Troy and Vilar's definitions are strikingly
incomplete. After all, it was a theater director and a playwright,
as well as a composer, who founded the festival in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo von Hofmannsthal, the playwright, poet and opera librettist
(``Der Rosenkavalier'') summed up the goals he shared with his
co-founders, the stage director Max Reinhardt and the composer
Richard Strauss: a festival devoted to ``opera and drama
together.'' Traditionally, then, the Salzburg Festival has always
been a festival not only of music, but also of spoken theater.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the festival's first-ever production was a
spoken-theater piece. ``Jedermann'' (``Everyman''), Hofmannsthal's
adaptation of a medieval English morality play, which Reinhardt
staged on the square in front of Salzburg's cathedral, is still
presented every year. For German speakers, this play _ more than
Karajan, more than Mozart _ is the quintessential symbol of the
Salzburg Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is more spoken theater at Salzburg than ever
before, from the theater guru Robert Wilson's new staging of Georg
Buchner's play ``Dantons Tod'' (``Danton's Death'') to the
``Troilus and Cressida'' of Stefan Bachmann, 31, the incoming
director of the Basel playhouse, to the filmmaker Hal Hartley's
first-ever work of theater, ``Soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that theater at the festival hasn't had some setbacks since
the days when Reinhardt's grandiose productions of Goethe's
``Faust'' and ``Jedermann'' were mainstays of the program. When
Germany annexed Austria in 1938, the Nazis quickly removed from the
festival all traces of Reinhardt and Hofmannsthal, who were part
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of the cold war, the composer Gottfried von
Einem, the festival's progressive new artistic director, tried to
engage an equally progressive theater director, the playwright
Bertolt Brecht: but Brecht, a Communist, was denied the post, and
the flap over the would-be appointment forced von Einem to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has always been theater at the Salzburg Festival,
even under Karajan. In the early 1970s, Giorgio Strehler, the late
Italian avant-garde director, flirted with the post of theater
director, but abandoned the idea after his less-than-successful
productions of ``Das Spiel der Machtigen'' (``The Game of the
Powerful,'' based on Shakespeare's ``Henry VI'') and ``Die
Zauberflote.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the directors Claus Peymann and Dieter Dorn, leading
lights of the German theater, staged works by the Austrian
playwright Thomas Bernhard.
</P>
<P>
   But it took Gerard Mortier, a Belgian from the world of opera,
to put the spotlight back on theater in Salzburg. In 1991, Mortier
took over as the festival's artistic director and introduced a
whole new program focusing on avant-garde stagings, 20th-century
opera and contemporary music _ and lots of spoken theater.
</P>
<P>
   Mortier signaled theater's ascendancy by boosting the festival's
theater budget and appointing Peter Stein, one of the most highly
regarded stage directors in the German-speaking world, as theater
director. Dubbed ``the Callas of directors'' by one German critic,
tein invoked Reinhardt's spirit by mounting large-scale productions
of Shakespeare plays and Greek tragedies in the Felsenreitschule, a
huge performance space in what had been a riding arena hewn from
Salzburg's cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   Critical response was mixed, but theater attendance figures
soared. Stein's 1992 ``Julius Caesar,'' which traveled to the
Edinburgh Festival in 1993, may have been a comfort to those
patrons scared off by ``Saint Francois d'Assise,'' an opera by
Messaien, presented at Salzburg in a video-studded staging by the
American director Peter Sellars. Stein, says Mortier, ``put theater
in Salzburg back on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stein also represented some things Mortier didn't like. His
monumental productions of classic works seemed, critics said,
increasingly ``tired out,'' and he left little room on the program
for talent other than his own. To Mortier, who is almost blindly
devoted to cultivating new talent, Stein represented an old guard,
albeit an old avant-garde.
</P>
<P>
   What Stein wanted to do was ``Faust'' in the Felsenreitschule _
again following Reinhardt _ but he ultimately decided that it
wasn't possible on his budget. Citing ``frightful battles'' at
Salzburg, he left willingly when his contract ran out in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Stein's departure, Mortier, newly confident after
having extended his own contract until 2001, announced his plan to
run every aspect of the festival's artistic program himself.
Theater was to be placed largely in the hands of four stage
directors _ Sellars; the then-unknown Bachmann; Deborah Warner,
from the nonprofit English stage, and the eccentric Swiss director
Christoph Marthaler _ to be supervised by a ``Konsulent,'' a kind
of administrative consultant in a part-time job.
</P>
<P>
   But things worked out a little differently in practice. For all
of Mortier's desire to control the artistic program himself, a
theater director, whatever the title, is a necessary part of his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a theater director because I can't cast plays alone,''
Mortier says. ``I'm an opera man. I can cast operas with no
problem, but I need someone for German theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Only an individual with an insider's knowledge of the
German-language theater scene can assemble the leading actors who
bring Salzburg's theater onto a qualitative par with its music,
such as the excellent company in ``Dantons Tod,'' which gave new
animation to Robert Wilson's esthetically pleasing but increasingly
repetitive theatrical language.
</P>
<P>
   And for all of Mortier's internationalism, the hottest pure
theater at the Salzburg Festival is still in German. In addition to
``Jedermann,'' the sellout productions this year were ``Dantons
Tod'' and ``er nicht als er'' (``he not as himself''), a play by
the Austrian writer Elfriede Jelinek, who is the 1998 festival's
author in residence.
</P>
<P>
   Staging this piece's world premiere was the Swiss director Jossi
Wieler, who won the German theater critics' production of the year
award in 1994 for his last Jelinek staging, ``Wolken. Heim''
(``Cloud. Home'') at the Deutsches Schauspielhaus in Hamburg. His
strikingly creative interpretation of ``er nicht als er,'' in which
he converted a block of text written without characters or stage
direction into a face-off between Jelinek and the late Swiss poet
Robert Walser, could well come up for the same honor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
