<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK MANAGERS FILE BIAS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amtrak managers filed a class-action lawsuit
Thursday alleging that the company discriminated against
African-Americans in management and other white-collar positions.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 plaintiffs _ who also include former managers, job
applicants, and one white former employee _ said Amtrak has paid
black managers and professionals less than whites, has not promoted
or hired blacks fairly, has condoned the use of racial epithets,
and has retaliated against those who have filed complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is the second discrimination charge against Amtrak
this year in US District Court in Washington. Black track-laying
and repair workers in the Northeast filed a class-action suit in
April, also charging unfair treatment of blacks and likening Amtrak
to a ``plantation.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' lawyers said they want Amtrak to change its
employment and disciplinary practices, and they are seeking damages
for back pay and mental anguish. Lawyers said they could seek more
than $100 million to represent two groups _ one of about 700 black
managers and former managers and one including about 2,500 black
applicants who the company rejected.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the allegations, Amtrak officials said Thursday
the company works to prevent discrimination. ``Amtrak has a
zero-tolerance policy for discriminatory practices in hiring or in
any aspect of the workplace,'' said George D. Warrington, Amtrak's
acting president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always worked hard to ensure that our hiring,
promotion, and employment practices do not discriminate and that
all employment opportunities are open to people of all races,
religions, and ethnic origins, without regard to gender or
disabilities that can be reasonably accommodated.''
</P>
<P>
   Four attorneys' groups are representing the plaintiffs in both
lawsuits, including the Washington law firm of Sprenger &AMP; Lang, the
Washington Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights and Urban Affairs,
the Boston Bar Association's Lawyer's Committee for Civil Rights
Under Law, and the Boston firm of Shapiro, Haber &AMP; Urmy.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier lawsuit, which included two Amtrak workers from
Massachusetts, opened the door for the second suit, lawyers said.
They hinted that more suits may be in store.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we filed that complaint, we received a flood of calls
from Amtrak employees that led us to believe that the extent of
racial discrimination is much broader than the first lawsuit,''
said Michael Leider, a lawyer representing the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, plaintiffs detailed instances in
which they said they were victims of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Perry, a former manager at Amtrak in Philadelphia,
complained that she was not allowed to advance at the company, and
she said the company did little to stop co-workers who use racial
epithets, even after she filed complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The white female plaintiff, Leslie Dunning of Fairfax Station,
Va., said Amtrak demoted her in retaliation for helping a black
manager prepare a report that detailed discrimination within the
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALZBURG-FESTIVAL-2ND     08-20 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALZBURG-FESTIVAL-2NDTAKE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SALZBURG, Austria: same honor.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While ``it's good to have the big foreign companies come in,''
Mortier says, ``the Salzburg Festival needs its own productions as
well.'' Only by generating new work can the festival remain more
than just another stop on the international circuit, presenting
fashionable productions already seen in New York or Avignon,
Edinburgh or the Wiener Festwochen (Vienna Festival).
</P>
<P>
   And as a leader of the German-language performing arts, the
festival is more or less obliged to present most of its own theater
productions in German. The theater network in Germany, Austria and
Switzerland is virtually unparalleled; its symbol is the Berlin
Theatertreffen (Theater Meeting), which showcases the year's best
German-language productions. Salzburg, of course, wants a piece of
that action, particularly as the Wiener Festwochen is also
dedicated to funky new-wave theater.
</P>
<P>
   Mortier has been keenly aware of Vienna, at the very least since
Luc Bondy, who had done several stagings for Mortier's festival,
became the Festwochen's theater director and said he would not
return to Salzburg. Sellars and Marthaler, both loyal, also have
presented or will present work in Vienna. The powers that be on
Vienna's theater scene ``attack me,'' says Mortier, ``but then they
hire my directors.''
</P>
<P>
   As a proponent of ``the new,'' Mortier _ who sees himself as
someone who presents new talent and points it in new directions
(commissioning the filmmaker Hartley to do theater, for example) _
comes in for his share of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   He is profaning the festival's tradition by overwhelming it with
new work, says one faction; he is a mere slick packager in search
of the latest trends, says another.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for theater at the festival to remain
predominantly German-language is that the festival wants to tap
into the German theater world's financial resources. Salzburg
receives relatively little state financing for a European cultural
institution: 74 percent of its budget comes from ticket sales and
private sources.
</P>
<P>
   As opera is far more expensive than theater to produce, the
theater budget is but a slice of Salzburg's financial pie, pared
down after Stein's departure to cover only the theater program's
fixed operating costs. Salzburg's theater has to come up with all
the money for artistic expenditure itself.
</P>
<P>
   Co-productions with other theaters have taken on new importance:
German theaters can afford to help pay for productions that, while
they originate in Salzburg, will also bring them prestige. All of
this year's new theater productions except ``Soon'' will travel to
other German-speaking houses.
</P>
<P>
   Given this background, it is not surprising that once the
appointed Konsulent _ the critic and theater administrator Ivan
Nagel _ had proved himself congenial to Mortier, he was designated
``theater director,'' after all, on this year's program.
</P>
<P>
   Nagel's choice of productions is, Mortier says, ``closer to my
own wishes than Stein's: smaller productions, more contemporary.''
In assembling this year's program, Nagel was given a more or less
free hand. ``I make suggestions,'' Mortier says, ``but the final
decision is his.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Nagel's decisions was to play down the role of Mortier's
group of directors: only Bachmann was represented on the 1998
theater program. In practice, rule by committee was less useful to
the festival than a single, decisive man of German theater.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the inner workings of Salzburg have proven as rocky for
Nagel as for his predecessors, and, one year into his three-year
contract, he has already resigned. Nagel took the deliberately
provocative step of inviting Elfriede Jelinek to organize the
literary readings that have traditionally been a part of the
festival.
</P>
<P>
   This would be tantamount to inviting the American performance
artist Karen Finley to stage the Inauguration. Ms. Jelinek is an
abrasive, controversial figure who attacks the Austrian
establishment and the social status quo, particularly with regard
to the role of women, in difficult, confrontational texts.
Salzburg's board of directors, whose president is a woman, was not
amused.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Jelinek program was ultimately approved (and has
been extremely successful with audiences), Nagel was so
disillusioned by what he called Salzburg's behind-the-scenes
``intrigues,'' that, pleading ill health, he will be leaving at the
end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than viewing this as another opportunity to step in, take
charge and mount more international productions, Mortier
immediately sought out another German-theater administrator.
Nagel's all-but-official successor is his own protege, Frank
Baumbauer, currently director of the Deutsches Schauspielhaus,
which he has led three times to the German theater critics' award
for theater of the year.
</P>
<P>
   One sure thing on next year's theater program is, of course,
``Jedermann.'' No one quite knows what to do with it. Originally,
Reinhardt's staging was hailed as an example of the director's
brilliance: playing the action off the statues on the cathedral's
Baroque facade, he incorporated the lengthening shadows of evening
as lighting effects, so that the steeple of St. Peter's Church
casts its shadow over centerstage at the moment Death appears to
claim Everyman.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the production has deteriorated into something
of a costume pageant. The role of Everyman is traditionally taken
by the leading actor of the day, from Will Quadflieg in the 1950s
through Klaus Maria Brandauer in the 70s to Gerd Voss today.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Sellars, the current staging involves ``what
people expect of theater: their favorite actors standing up there
talking very, very loud.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Mortier dared to lay hands on this sacred cow at the
beginning of his tenure, his departure from Salzburg might have
been precipitous. Today, with a stronger support base and less to
lose, he has a few ideas of his own about how to incorporate the
new and hip into this rather dated piece _ and make international
audiences aware of Salzburg's spoken theater, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should turn it into a musical,'' he says, with a twinkle in
his eye, ``and cast it with Arnold Schwarzenegger and Madonna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another option: every year there's a big debate in the press
about who will play the paramour, the girl. I want to cast it with
Leonardo DiCaprio. That should make everybody happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
