s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACKLEY-ART-2TAKES-$AD     08-20 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACKLEY-ART-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURATOR'S PERSONAL MONTAGE OF AGE SOAKED IN IMAGES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Deborah Weisgall recently wrote in this section about the Wyeth
galleries in Maine.  
 By DEBORAH WEISGALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Clifford Ackley, the curator of prints, drawings and
photographs at the Museum of Fine Arts, was walking through his
exhibition ``PhotoImage: Printmaking '60s to '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped in front of ``License,'' a lithograph by Robert
Rauschenberg dating from 1962. Quick strokes of black are brushed
over a montage of pictures: a stalking Siamese cat, a car race, a
phalanx of horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are images of speed, photographs taken from The New York
Times,'' said Ackley, a soft-spoken man in pale horn-rimmed glasses
and a dark plaid shirt. ``When I came to the museum 32 years ago,
`License' was my first acquisition. My field was 17th-century
Northern European prints.'' He smiled. ``I still love the 17th
century. Can you imagine a world where one was not surrounded by
photographic images?''
</P>
<P>
   For ``PhotoImage,'' at the museum through Sept. 27, Ackley has
turned his galleries into an eloquent montage of images that all
make use, in various ways, of photographs. Luscious lipsticked
lips; a grid of glass eyes; a face printed so delicately that it
almost disappears; hazy stills from the Zapruder film: they are
disparate images, often ugly or banal or frightening, transformed
into art.
</P>
<P>
   ``PhotoImage'' explores that process of transformation; it is
Ackley's summation, his ordering of the outrageousness, violence
and irony _ and beauty _ of the art of the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
   It is also very personal. ``This is an autobiographical show; it
covers the same decades that I cover,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many works in the show come from the department's collection,
acknowledged to be one of the finest in the world. In the '60s and
'70s, the museum's shows of Durer, Rembrandt and Goya, to which
Ackley contributed, set a standard of scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Now he does the same for contemporary prints. The exhibition
includes 120 images by 72 artists, some of whom were not born when
Rauschenberg and Andy Warhol first began experimenting in 1962.
Most are represented by one or two works.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I emphasize four artists,'' said Ackley. ``Rauschenberg,
Warhol, the British artist Richard Hamilton, and the German artist
Gerhard Richter.'' Their innovations have entered our visual
vocabulary, and their recurring presence gives the exhibition its
narrative thread.
</P>
<P>
   ``This show is dense,'' Ackley observed. It is also didactic in
the great tradition of MFA print shows. The sheer wealth of
material allows Ackley to suggest visually complex ideas. ``I have
arranged it by theme, not chronologically. Portraits, words and
images, a section concerned with seeing, landscapes.'' He pointed
to a mysterious hovering cloud by Gerhard Richter. ``He's always on
the verge of becoming a 19th-century romantic painter.''
</P>
<P>
   Beside the Richter hangs a small picture of water by Vija
Celmins, a square of waves that proves not to be a photograph at
all but a finely detailed woodcut.
</P>
<P>
   Ackley's labels describe how each print was made: for instance,
how a photograph was altered, what the artist added mechanically or
by hand, the source of the photographs. For Ackley, meaning and
process are intertwined. Two small seascapes by Roy Lichtenstein
layer photographs of water and sand with horizons of Ben Day dots
and skies of luminous patterned plastic.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, such cheap commercial materials were provocative enough
almost to obscure the print's strong connection to the tradition of
landscape. ``With photography, there's always the high-art, low-art
dialogue,'' said Ackley. ``But is there really any difference?''
</P>
<P>
   Farther along the wall, confrontational works from the '70s _
close-ups of a handgun, or Chinese, Soviet and American flags
blended by their blood-red color _ contrast with edgy images from
the '90s hanging across the room: intensely colored ink-jet prints
of bondage scenes from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's my political corner,'' Ackley says. ``Some things are
correct, some incorrect.'' Their troubling beauty lies in the
elegant way ugly objects are presented, in the patterns of the
guns, the sensuous red of the flags, the velvety, seductive blues,
purples and oranges of women wearing bits in their mouths.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition doubles back on itself and suddenly two images
hanging far apart connect with each other. Along one wall, Ackley
has hung a string of Mao portraits: a cross-dressing clown Mao by
Jim Dine, a soft-focus man-in-the-moon Mao by Gerhard Richter and,
by Warhol, a strung-out, neon Mao.
</P>
<P>
   Everything resonates; an overly exposed image becomes fresh. The
Chinese dictator represents a contest between the power of history
and art. Across from them hangs a block of 24 frames composing
Christian Boltanski's portfolio ``Gymnasium Chases.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The work shows members of the graduating class of 1931 from a
Jewish high school of that name in Vienna, enlarged from a small
group photograph. Grainy and hollow-eyed, each face has been so
enlarged that it seems ready to explode. They prefigure their own
fates in the Holocaust; almost anonymous victims of history stare
across at the icon Mao.
</P>
<P>
   ``PhotoImage'' is full of tensions like this, between
recognizable images and those that have been pushed to the edge of
recognition, changed into something else, perhaps even into a lie.
</P>
<P>
   The invention of photography propelled painting toward
abstraction; ``PhotoImage'' shows how photographs have bullied and
coaxed art back to the real world. ``Photography still has an
edge,'' Ackley said, and everywhere he plays with the pull between
our response to the content of an image, its subject, and our
response to what it looks like, its esthetic qualities.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall next to the grid of ``Gymnasium Chases'' hang a
Rauschenberg with three oblong photographs arranged vertically, a
Celmins in which three pictures of space line up side by side, and
two images by John Baldessari containing small, mysterious, printed
oblongs. Ackley considered the wall. ``Fun with squares and
rectangles,'' he mused.
</P>
<P>
   Ackley has his own fun with squares and rectangles in the
exhibition catalogue. Operating like the artists in ``PhotoImage,''
he manipulates photographs of the works in the show and juxtaposes
them, often differently from the way they hang on the walls; he
blows up details, to clarify how they are made and also because
they look good big.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful in itself, the catalogue documents this exhibition in
the same way that some of the most haunting prints in
``PhotoImage'' document temporary installations and performances.
</P>
<P>
   The catalogue's cover is a cropped Warhol ``Marilyn,'' garish
and gorgeous in teal, silver and Day-Glo pink. Warhol, especially,
exploited the issues of lies and low art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Boston in general, I held back on Warhol,'' Ackley said
as he stood in front of four ``Marilyns'' at the entrance to the
exhibition. ``The show is going to Des Moines next year. Halston
left his Warhols to the Art Center there; he was from Des Moines.
The heartland. That's where I come from, too. I was raised in
dairy-farming country in Oregon.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any autobiography, the show reflects on time passing. Much
of the art of the '60s and '70s deals with conflict: between public
and private, between cheap images and high art, between abstraction
and representation. Dieter Roth's ``Six Piccadillies'' is six
versions of a tourist postcard. In one Piccadilly, the busy London
hub blossoms into psychedelic color; in another, a train of three
infrared double-decker buses trundles through a black night. Three
decades ago, they might have seemed out of control; now they
dazzle.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade outrage has mellowed; it is once again
permissible to be decorative, to beguile. Richter, in ``Candle I,''
squeegeed black paint calligraphically over a photograph of a
burning candle and achieved a golden Dutch interior viewed through
centuries of soot.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Schatten'' (``Shadows'') by the Swiss artist Markus Raetz,
shapes bent from a single piece of wire drift like puffs of smoke
above a Magritte-like pipe twisted from the same wire. The six
images seem to have been captured in an instant, but the artist has
painstakingly fashioned the inert materials and exposed them on
photographic paper. It is very beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   All the works in ``PhotoImage'' are beautiful. The show, by
making connections among method, color, form and subject, reveals
the beauty in a hermaphrodite dancing in front of credit cards, in
the ghostly vanitas of an X-rayed skeleton, in a purple snapshot of
Joseph Beuys crouching before a shimmering silver horse.
</P>
<P>
   Ackley finds subtle beauty in charged, blatant images that snag
the eye, a core of delight in images that lie. He locates beauty in
an age that mistrusts it and works to deny it: beauty, almost
despite itself.
</P>
<P>
   Ackley smiled wryly. ``I am a romantic,'' he said. ``So I always
end up with something beautiful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
