<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT RULES QUEBEC HAS RIGHT TO SECEDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Weighing in for the first time on the emotional
political issue that has clouded Canadaian politics for decades,
the nation's highest court ruled Thursday that Quebec cannot
unilaterally break away from the 131-year-old confederation.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a historic opinion that appeared to undercut the
federal government's claim that Canada is indivisible, the Supreme
Court also declared that Quebec has a right to secede in an
orderly, democratic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's nine high court justices ruled unanimously that Quebec
has no legal right to unilaterally split from Canada on the basis
of a simple majority ``Yes'' vote in a province-wide referendum, as
it came within a hair's breadth of doing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of the unequivocal legal ruling against secession
that the federal government had sought, the high court declared
that if Quebecers one day opt for independence in a fair vote,
Canada has a ``constitutional duty'' to negotiate terms of
separation in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice Antonio Lamer, himself a Quebecer, described the
case as the most important ever to come before the Canadian high
court. The opinion spelled out in a 78-page ruling effectively
marked the first official acknowledgement by Canada that Quebec has
a right to secede, if only under structured terms. In that sense,
the ruling backfired on Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst seemed caught off-guard by the ruling, and suggested
that it might deepen the rift between the nation's ``two
solitudes'' _ French Quebec and English Canada _ since it gives the
appearance of federal meddling in Quebec politics while failing to
legally define the rules of national breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a surprise, and certainly not what the federal
government wanted or expected,'' said Ghislain Otis, a professor of
law at Quebec's Laval University. ``Instead of simply saying Quebec
has no right to secede, as Ottawa hoped, the justices have said
that Canada has an obligation to negotiate terms of secession if
Quebecers clearly choose this path.''
</P>
<P>
   Quebec's secessionist leaders shrugged off the ruling, saying it
was irrelevant and that Quebec will determine its own political
future without reference to English Canada. The province had
boycotted the high court hearings that led to Thursday's landmark
ruling, refusing to argue its case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position remains that Quebecers have always had, and will
continue to have, the inalienable right to pursue our national
destiny,'' said Jacques Brassard, Quebec minister for
intergovernmental affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came as Quebec heads for provincial elections, likely
to be called in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard, an ardent separatist, has
pledged to hold yet another referendum on secession, perhaps as
early as next year, if his Parti Quebecois government is
re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   Bouchard maintains that Canadian constitutional law has no legal
sway over Quebec, and that Quebec will pursue political
``sovereignty'' regardless of Supreme Court rulings or threats from
Ottawa. ``It is not up to the Supreme Court to determine the
legitimacy of Quebecers' right to decide their own future,''
Bouchard said.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that Quebec has a right to pick its political path
without reference to the rest of Canada is an article of passionate
faith among French-speaking Quebecers, even those who favor
remaining within the confederation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the ruling put federalist champion Jean Charest, head of
Quebec's Liberal Party and Bouchard's only serious challenger for
the premiership, in the bizarre position of arguing that Quebec
must remain a part of Canada -- but that the Supreme Court has no
legal authority to keep Quebec in the fold.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial Supreme Court ruling comes three years after
Quebec stunned observers by bringing Canada to the brink of
dissolution.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 provincial referendum on independence, the separatist
side won 49.4 percent of the vote, sending a political shock wave
that reverbrated not only across Canada but in Washington and other
foreign capitals. Quebec's leaders planned to issue an immediate
``unilateral'' declaration of independence had the referendum been
won by even just a single ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The near-miss caused the federal government to ask the Supreme
Court to rule on three legal questions: Can Quebec secede
unilaterally -- that is, on its own accord -- under Canadian law?
Can it secede unilaterally under international law? If there is a
conflict, which law prevails?
</P>
<P>
   In the only portions of their opinion that seemed unequivocal,
the justices ruled that neither the Canadian constitution nor
international law gives Quebec the right to unilateral secession.
</P>
<P>
   However, for the first time, the Supreme Court ruled that Quebec
has a right to negotiate a departure if its people give
``unambiguous expression...that they no longer wish to remain in
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   In the view of some analysts, the Canadian government opened a
Pandora's box by going to the high court instead of sticking to the
political arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking this issue to the Supreme Court is one of the most
foolish decisions ever made by the federal government in the
history of this country,'' former British Columbia Premier Dave
Barrett told the CBC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
