<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: The price of forfeiting privacy
 &HT;    (EDS: Embargoed until Saturday, Aug. 22, 1998.)
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do journalists have dilemmas about revealing scandalous matters
relating to politicians' personal lives? Do they ever think about
the pain and hurt such revelations will cause spouses and children?
The answer is yes _ even in today's voyeuristic culture.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, I can tell about a story I didn't write. No need
for reservations now because it's public knowledge. It relates to
the chairman of the Democratic National Committee, Colorado Gov.
Roy Romer, married with seven children.
</P>
<P>
   Romer's in the uncomfortable position of being called on to
comment in national forums about the Clinton-Lewinsky matter.
Uncomfortable because a short time ago, an anonymous political
enemy released a video of him in a long embrace with his former
chief of staff, B.J. Thornberry, in a car at a Washington airport
and later at her home.
</P>
<P>
   I ran into Romer and Thornberry in a most unusual setting three
years ago, one that raised questions that I might have pursued or
tipped off some Colorado media friends to pursue. I didn't, mainly
because I couldn't find any public-interest reason to do so, though
I knew from living in Colorado (and serving in the Colorado Senate
for eight years) of rumors about the two.
</P>
<P>
   My 25-year-old son, John, and I were backpacking on the
Appalachian Trail in May 1995 _ Memorial Day weekend, a rainy,
nasty one for hiking or sight-seeing in Virginia's Thomas Jefferson
National Forest. Near the end of our 80-mile adventure, John and I
crossed the Skyline Drive near Rockfish Gap, one of the vistas that
Jefferson called America's most magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   As we bemoaned civilization's interference with the trail, a car
pulled up to the stop sign where we stood. To my astonishment, the
driver was Romer. I waved my red rain jacket, and he rolled down
the window. John and I greeted him excitedly. The governor seemed
less excited to see us. In the car with him was a woman, not his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remember B.J.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed I did. I remembered too the rumors about the governor's
relationship with Thornberry, which circulated primarily in the
underground press and were only picked up by the mainstream media
prior to Romer's first re-election campaign in 1992. At that time
Romer nipped the rumor in the bud in his straightforward, farm-boy
style. At a state Democratic convention, with Thornberry on one
side and his wife on the other, he praised Thornberry's service to
the state and said ``how dare you'' to the media for insulting her.
The scenario elicited a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   But on that May morning in Virginia, the governor was less
artful. He looked through the thick fog that shrouded his car and
us, and explained that he just been showing Thornberry ``this
beautiful Skyline Drive.'' He went on to add that he'd come to
Virginia to check out some of the John Deere stores he owns.
</P>
<P>
   Two years went by before the Romer-Thornberry relationship
surfaced again in the media. When the dirty-tricks video was
released, Romer, again with his wife beside him, held one news
conference, saying that he had ``an affectionate relationship''
with Thornberry and that his family was well aware of it. He made
no apologies, and he never answered another question about it.
</P>
<P>
   There was a short-lived flurry of stories in the Colorado media
that barely made the news wires elsewhere, even though Romer, by
that time, was the national Democratic Party chairman. Though his
``affectionate'' line makes little sense to anyone, he used it
again last week when Jeff Greenfield asked him about the
relationship on a national CNN ``town meeting.'' It was,
ironically, a session in which various leaders discussed whether
politicians should be held to higher moral standards than others.
</P>
<P>
   I watched, uncomfortable that the man I had met on Skyline Drive
chose to comment on the Clinton situation. The conflict gnawed
then. It does still.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a governor who had been a good one. Here was a family
with a loving wife and mother and seven nice children. Should all
privacy be forfeited and his family pay the price? I didn't think
so then, and I don't now.Martha Ezzard is a member of the Atlanta
Journal editorial board. Her column appears Saturdays and Mondays.
E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
