<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FRINGE-FESTIVAL-3T     08-20 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FRINGE-FESTIVAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK CITY, TRAWLING THE FRINGE'S WILD TERRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hugh Hysell was determined to crack this fringe
thing. Having been wait-listed by the organizers of the New York
International Fringe Festival with a not-very-novel idea, a revival
of ``The Night Larry Kramer Kissed Me,'' the aspiring Manhattan
director racked his brain for a project that might be more in tune
with the festival's ebullient spirit, its mandate to, above all
else, make it new.
</P>
<P>
   With the submission deadline looming, it came to him: why not,
in the classic-twisting age of ``Shakespeare's R &AMP; J,'' create an
all-male version of ``The Importance of Being Earnest''? Half-Moon
Street could become Chelsea; Woolton, the Hamptons. Cecily could be
morphed into Kurt, Gwendolyn into Gerald and Miss Prism
de-feminized with a simple''
</P>
<P>
   ``I downloaded the play off the Internet, made a number of cuts,
and it all made sense: the pretensions in the gay culture, the
cattiness,'' Hysell said. ``I wrote my proposal, said, `How about
an alternative to my alternative?' and they said, `OK, you're in
the festival.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Voila! Another New York theater adventure typed out and played
out under deadline. The results of this and many other such
backstage dramas _ 143 others, to be exact _ are yours for the
sampling in the funky, flexible, artistically free-form spaces of
the Lower East Side, where the sophomore year of the New York
International Fringe Festival is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Operating virtually around-the-clock through Aug. 30, the
festival, which began on Wednesday, has with uncanny swiftness put
its stamp on late-summer theatergoing in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering little-known theater companies from around the world
for 12 days, the event is evolving into a kind of Olympics of
performance art, an oasis invigorated by the boundless energy of an
eclectic band of writers and actors in the normally parched weeks
before Labor Day, when the theater season just begins to rev up.
</P>
<P>
   The festival could be the season's jumper cables. And there may
be no more appropriate way to absorb the electric optimism of a
season on the brink than spending a day or two with the players who
hope to represent the art form's future.
</P>
<P>
   The event is come-as-you-are and see-what-you-want. At any given
time, the curtain may be rising simultaneously on seven or eight
shows in the festival's more than a dozen spaces (not including the
free outdoor shows of the adjunct Fringe Al Fresco).
</P>
<P>
   Consult the festival's indispensable 40-page program and map out
a strategy: Let's see, there's ``Tales of a Bugged-Out Black
Chick'' at noon, ``Women of James Bond'' at 2, ``Alice's Evidence''
at 7, ``Lola Montez in Bavaria'' at 9:30 ... and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Hang out at what is called Fringe Central, the Theatorium on
Stanton Street, and trade playgoing tips with the young people
sipping coffee at the entrance, or wander over to the Kraine
Theater on East Fourth, Surf Reality on Allen or the House of
Candles on Stanton and poll departing theatergoers.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can stop by the Allen Street Mall, where Michael
Krynski's hallucinatory sculptures of giant twigs protruding from
pairs of slacks are on display throughout the festival.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to roam, bring a water bottle, but leave your lofty
expectations at home. Be prepared to sit on unpadded seats,
perspire or freeze a bit _ the air-conditioning in these spaces is
spotty _ and fill in the dramaturgical blanks because a lot of what
you'll see is embryonic, performed on minuscule budgets with
minimal scenery, the gotta-run sort that folds up into suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 30 minutes between shows, and the show before you
has 15 minutes to get out when they're done,'' Hysell said of the
round-robin performance schedule, a typical show running six or
seven times during the festival. ``We have seven minutes to load
in, but it's pretty simple: four wooden folding chairs, a table,
four picture frames and a piece of purple fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   Hysell, who worked as associate manager of the Off Broadway show
``Tap Dogs'' and will serve in a similar capacity with a revival of
``The Mystery of Irma Vep'' beginning in September at the Westside
Theater, is not enduring the rigors of the Theater of Masking Tape
as a creative way to kill time.
</P>
<P>
   He has a fantasy that some influential audience member, some
agent or producer, might make his show a star. The template for his
fancy was set down by the success of ``Gross Indecency,'' however
unlikely that may be. The hit play about the libel and lewdness
trials of Oscar Wilde has run for more than a year, and is soon to
close, at the Minetta Lane Theater in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Though this well-constructed play was not part of the festival,
its Off Off Broadway origins, which share roots with many of the
fringe's offerings, have made its triumph an exemplar. ``The cool
thing to have happen,'' Hysell said, ``would be a transfer like
`Gross Indecency,' or even to get published.''
</P>
<P>
   Short of discovery, the pleasure for the participants is the
total immersion. ``For 12 days the theater is an ideal environment;
it's like theater camp,'' said Diane Paulus who, with Aaron Beall
and John Clancy, is a co-artistic director for the festival. ``It's
a community-based, no-frills, risk-taking venture.''
</P>
<P>
   Beall, the artistic director of Todo Con Nada, a mini-empire of
spaces on Ludlow and Stanton Streets, said the fringe is intended
as a mere slice of downtown's teeming theatrical life. ``It's a
Polaroid of what goes on all year round,'' he explained. ``And it's
a celebration of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The second New York Fringe Festival is a slightly pared-down
version of the first, which organizers say drew about 25,000
playgoers and presented 175 plays and performance pieces. The event
can expand or contract, they say, based on the quality and
diversity of the projects they review.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the members of the triumvirate each pored over 450
submissions _ the proposal letter being the most important document
they evaluated _ and whittled the list to the chosen 144.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the NFL draft,'' Beall said.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, a particularly New York refashioning of the
fringe concept, pioneered by the granddaddy of the fringe
festivals, in Edinburgh, and largely duplicated in a string of
popular fringe festivals across Canada, from Edmonton to Toronto to
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the main event, there are fringelets in
``FringeJR,'' an assortment of children's arts and crafts workshops
and other daily events at the Connelly Theater on East Fourth
Street, and in Fringe Al Fresco, which includes ``Frozen Fringe,''
an outdoor ice show in Seward Park, at the corner of Essex Street
and East Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another major New York departure from the older fringes is the
selectivity. Nancy Webster, the producer of the Toronto Fringe, one
of Canada's best-known festivals, said the local participants, who
make up 75 percent of the Toronto offerings, are selected by
lottery, a process which she says insures that the event is
accessible to anyone who wants to produce a show.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Webster explained that the Canadian Association of Fringe
Festivals considered the nonjuried aspect such a vital ingredient,
along with a tradition of giving all box-office receipts to the
participants, that it had politely suggested to the New York
festival that it not label itself as ``fringe.''
</P>
<P>
   (The New York Fringe Festival, its organizers say, returns $7 of
every $11 ticket to the individual shows; $3 goes into the coffers
for the next year's festival and $1 into a pool for the theater
spaces.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wonderful about the fringe in Canada is that somebody
straight out of school, they'll do this, and they have this
audience that will see them,'' Ms. Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   The differences are of a philosophical, rather than overtly
confrontational, variety. The New York organizers contended that
because of the greater volume of theater produced at every level
here than anywhere else, it was essential to impose some
restrictions, however loose, on what is to be offered. ``New York
City is 365 days a year of unadjudicated fringe festival,'' Ms.
Paulus argued. What need is there, she added, for more of that?
</P>
<P>
   Reading the guide to the New York festival, it's extremely
difficult to divine any sense of limit, what with shows with titles
like ``So, I Killed a Few People'' by the Annoyance Theater of
Chicago, or ``Something Something Uber Alles'' by the Purgatorio
Ink Theater of New York. In fact, judging from the experience last
August, the fringe program is anything but a scientific how-to
manual for the best of the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to predict which shows will be worth your time.
The joy of the festival is that it is all a matter of individual
initiative. This year's fringe looks to be knee-deep in the
classics reclassified, a indication of how many of the participants
are fresh out of acting programs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the shows: ``Three Sisters in Search of a Cherry
Orchard,'' ``Antigone Through Time,'' a 24-hour version of ``The
Bald Soprano,'' ``Medeamaterial,'' ``Lizzie Borden's `Tempest'''
and ``The Prometheus Excerpts.'' One-man (and woman) stands like
``Once Vaudeville,'' Kevin Augustine's adult puppet show;
improvisation groups, and even a conventional play or two are among
the offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Some attractions will be draws on the strength of favorable
reputation, like the plays honoring the centennial of Brecht's
birth, or by dint of outrageousness: ``Synchronized Swimming _ The
Dry Version,'' from Switzerland, just sounds too wild to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation of watching gymnastic imaginations giving their
craziest notions a total workout is what can make a fringe festival
something to look forward to. The fearlessness of these endeavors
brings to mind an intrepid expedition of climbers setting off even
when they hear the distant rumbling of an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fringe would be the only place where I could explore
something like this, at the level I'm at now,'' said Linda Key, one
of the directors of ``Clowning the Bard,'' a 75-minute, new
vaudeville-style show that rejiggers every play (plus a sonnet) by
Shakespeare for a 16-member clown troupe. Audiences will be asked
to try to figure out which piece is based on which play.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was so ambitious that Ms. Key, the artistic director of
Six Figures Theater Company, was in rehearsal with the production
before she realized that one of the plays had been forgotten.
Appropriately enough, it was ``Love's Labor's Lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the order right has been a bear, but we're ready,''
Ms. Key said. ``It's what the fringe is about: the only place in
New York where they give you a theater and let you do something
like this.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Second New York International Fringe Festival will run
through Aug. 30 at various venues around the city. The festival
also features programs for children and families under the title
``Fringe Jr,'' and free outdoor events referred to as ``Fringe
Alfresco.'' Festival brochures can be picked up at performances
venues, as well as at many Barnes and Noble bookstores throughout
the city and at businesses in lower Manhattan. Admission to most
events is $11 ($7 for children at the Fringe Junior shows); outdoor
events are free. Information: (212) 420-8877. There is also a
website for the festival, http://www.fringenyc.org. Here is a
schedule for shows mentioned in the accompanying article and a
sampling of festival events:
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
