<HEADLINE>
JOURNAL REPORTER WHO COVERED BARNICLE STORY   LEAVES PAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Mike Barnicle saga _ and the heightened
journalistic scrutiny and self-examination in this summer of media
mea culpas _ may have claimed another victim. James S. Hirsch, a
three-year veteran of The Wall Street Journal's Boston bureau, left
the newspaper this week after a problem surfaced in his Aug. 12
story on the previous day's decision by The Boston Globe to suspend
Barnicle for two months rather than terminate him.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Barnicle resigned from the Globe after new
questions about his credibility arose and he was unable to verify
the reporting behind an Oct. 8, 1995, column.
</P>
<P>
   In his Aug. 12 story, Hirsch wrote that the Globe's owner, The
New York Times Co., ``declined to comment'' on the decision to
suspend Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   But the Journal subsequently published a correction stating that
``the Times had not been called for comment on the article.'' The
Times' official position was: ``We support the Globe's right to
make its own decision.'' After the Aug. 12 story, the Times pointed
out the error in a letter to the Journal's managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hirsch knowingly printed an untruth, which we take very
seriously,'' said Journal spokeswoman Karen Miller Pensiero. ``It
violated our compact with our readers. We considered all of the
circumstances and the reporter was disciplined.'' The company also
confirmed that Hirsch no longer worked at the Journal, but would
not comment on the particulars of his leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch also declined to comment on the circumstances of his
departure.
</P>
<P>
   In his nine-year career at the Journal, Hirsch built a
reputation as a sharp and solid newsman among his peers. Besides
covering the Barnicle travails, he wrote a notable front-page story
in late May detailing the financial problems besetting Fidelity
Investments' Community Newspaper Company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONDA-EARNINGS-315&AMP;AD     08-20 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDA-EARNINGS-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDA, EXPANDING GLOBALLY, CITES 26 PERCENT RISE IN PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Honda Motor Co. is benefiting more than ever from its
global reach, a distinction once ridiculed by domestically focused
competitors in Japan's automotive industry.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the domestic market shrinking rapidly, Japan's No. 3
automaker (behind Toyota and Nissan) reported a 26 percent profit
gain Thursday for the latest quarter, largely because of sales in
Europe and in Honda's largest market, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended June 30, Honda reported net income of a
record 78.22 billion yen, or $547 million, on a 17.4 percent sales
increase of 1.6 trillion yen, or $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas sales once earned Honda criticism, much the same way
that Sony's vast international sales once led industry titans here
to dismiss it as ``not really a Japanese company.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, with almost every Japanese business executive
praising the benefits of globalization, Honda's pioneering spirit
is admired.
</P>
<P>
   Its new president, Hiroyuki Yoshino, says he believes the reach
that Honda has already established will protect it from the forces
of consolidation sweeping the global automobile business.
</P>
<P>
   With Daimler buying Chrysler, Volkswagen buying Rolls Royce and
BMW clearly looking to expand, the Japanese automakers seem like
attractive potential partners with their dominance of Japan's huge
car market and deep penetration in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoshino says he is convinced the Japanese automakers can
hold their own. ``The way I look at Daimler and Chrysler is:
Chrysler is really only in North America, Benz has only a small
presence there,'' he said in an interview earlier this month.
``They didn't have a global strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Honda makes more than 100 products in 40 countries. ``Honda's
global strategy has been established, and I think it is top rate,''
Yoshino said. ``We build our cars in North America, Asia and Europe
_ we're already there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yoshino also has a novel way of looking at Honda's spot in the
global hierarchy of car manufacturers. Annually, Honda sells about
5 million motorcycles and 3 million pieces of power equipment, he
points out, in addition to 2.3 million cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even GM sells only 9 million units a year, and Toyota sells
only 5 million,'' he said, only half in jest. ``If you look at it
on a unit basis, we're outselling them.''
</P>
<P>
   That may sound arrogant. But Honda has needed a strong sense of
itself just to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Honda is not a member of a kei-retsu, the powerful business
agglomerations built around banks that have until recently provided
endless amounts of credit regardless of borrower quality.
</P>
<P>
   Honda has been more reliant on shareholders and the capital
markets for financing, and it has done a good job of making them
happy. ``It's one of the most transparent companies in Japan,''
said Noriaki Hirakata, an automotive analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   An example of the company's honest appraisal of its performance
came a few months ago when Honda reported a small increase in June
domestic sales. Rather than portraying the increase as a sign of
strength, Yoshino explained that it was largely because of a change
in the way that Accord station wagons were counted. Domestically
sold Accord wagons produced elsewhere _ and thus not counted in the
1997 numbers _ were now produced in Japan and counted in the 1998
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give too much of an impression of success,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hirakata at Morgan Stanley and others have some concerns about
Honda. One is whether the automaker may run out of production
capacity for cars. Another is whether it can continue to make money
pursuing the ``small is smart'' strategy it has pursued in the
domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   Honda, like other auto manufacturers, has had more luck selling
mini-cars in the Japanese market, where the specter of rising
unemployment, a shaky financial system and a virtually nonexistent
social safety net are among the worries keeping consumers from
showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the company will start selling newly designed
mini-cars, and Yoshino said he was confident they would help
Honda's second-half performance. He said Honda must rely on smaller
cars to sustain its performance in Japan, since an economic
turnaround was unlikely any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller cars, however, typically provide smaller profit margins.
Yoshino said he was not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made profit on the mini-cars that we've been selling so
far, and profits from the ones we start selling in October should
be higher,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for capacity constraints, Yoshino said he could understand
the worries. But he was uneasy about the United States market,
where Honda will introduce a redesigned Acura later this year, and
said he was reluctant to commit more capital to production lines at
this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that concern in the back of my head, what we'll do is
stick to our current production capacity,'' he said, adding that
the company could compensate for some capacity limitations by
purchasing employees' paid vacation time so they could keep
working.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshino also noted that Honda had a second North American line
opening in Canada, where it would produce mini-vans.
</P>
<P>
   On the home front, Honda's nemesis, Toyota Motor Corp., has also
thrown down a challenge. Toyota, Japan's largest automaker, is
worried about the unpopularity of its cars among younger people and
has vowed to woo that demographic group, which is Honda's main
customer base.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshino conceded that Toyota was a threat, but said he was not
intimidated. ``One reason we attract younger people is the
motorcycle business and our reputation in it,'' he said. ``We also
are back in Formula One racing, which helps, too.''
</P>
<P>
   His predecessor, Nobuhiko Kawamoto, took Honda out of that
business in 1992 but put it back in this spring, announcing plans
to return to Formula One racing in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshino conceded that Toyota's stodgy image had been helped by
its hybrid ``clean'' car, Prius, which uses an electric battery and
gasoline engine and is far lower in emissions than a regular car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am gritting my teeth a bit,'' Yoshino said of the flood of
good press Toyota has enjoyed from Prius. ``But I'd say their
technical expertise with that car is not so great.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his opinion about Toyota's technical expertise, he's
not repeating Kawamoto's bold suggestion that Honda, which produces
fewer than half the cars Toyota does, could overtake Toyota as
Japan's No. 1 car maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger is not always better,'' he said. ``If everything else
stays the same, then bigger is better. But things rarely stay the
same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
