<HEADLINE>
SHORT-SALES OPEN POSITIONS ON BIG BOARD DOWN SLIGHTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open positions of short sales on the New York Stock
Exchange declined slightly last month, to 4.1 billion shares last
Friday, the exchange reported Thursday. The decrease of 28.7
million shares in open short positions, less than 1 percent, was
the first monthly decline since January.
</P>
<P>
   The latest short-interest figure was equal to 1 percent of all
shares listed on the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   On the smaller American Stock Exchange, short interest rose 3.2
percent last month, to 200.5 million shares, a new monthly record.
</P>
<P>
   A short position is created when an investor sells shares that
have been borrowed. If the share price falls, the investor can
profit by buying shares at a lower price to replace the borrowed
ones.
</P>
<P>
   An increase in the short position in a company's shares may
indicate a rise in bearish sentiments among investors toward that
company. But a short position in a company's shares can also
increase because of complex trading strategies, especially those
related to arbitrage in takeover deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
