<HEADLINE>
(ATTENTION: TEXAS EDITORS)  
 TEXAS LAWMAKERS RALLY BEHIND CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas lawmakers rallied behind President Clinton's
decision Thursday to bomb suspected terrorist camps in Afghanistan
and a chemical plant in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has an absolute duty to attack terrorism
where it lives and breeds, in order to prevent future attacks on
American citizens around the world,'' said House Majority Leader
Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people stand united in the face of terrorism. The
men and women who undertook this mission deserve our praise and
prayers,'' Armey added.
</P>
<P>
   The military strikes came nearly three days after President
Clinton testified before a federal grand jury here and later
publicly acknowledged a relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky that he said was ``not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William ``Mac'' Thornberry, R-Texas, asked about the timing
of the attack, said he would like to see more evidence about why it
was launched Thursday. ``I think a lot of us are interested in
knowing more about the evidence,'' Thornberry said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added: ``I've got to assume that any president would
only risk the lives of U.S. soldiers for the right reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornberry said that ``it is very important for the United
States to speak with one voice against terrorism... I do think that
once we know who committed a terrorist attack, we've got to strike
hard against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas, said he was ``highly supportive of our
military strikes today in Afghanistan and Sudan.'' He added, ``If
we have credible information that these are the responsible
parties, which it seems our intelligence agencies have provided,
these bombings are absolutely justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nicholas V. Lampson, D-Texas, also supported the
president's action. He said he was ``proud that the United States
acted swiftly, decisively, and appropriately in response to recent
acts of senseless terrorism in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine looking into the eyes of a mother of one of
the 12 Americans who were sent home in caskets last week and
telling her that no response is necessary,'' Lampson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lampson said he hopes the bombing ``will send a clear message to
terrorists in Afghanistan, Sudan and other parts of the world that
the United States will not be blackmailed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
