<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROVIDES A SURREAL AFTERNOON ON THE VINEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ The dozens of journalists eager for a sight
of President Clinton on his summer vacation got their chance
Thursday afternoon, when the president strode into the makeshift
press center at Edgartown Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   There, he announced to the world that the US had launched
strikes against Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Just as quickly, he was gone, his motorcade rushing off to
Martha's Vineyard Airport for an Air Force One flight back to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been keeping a low profile since arriving here
Tuesday, a day after he acknowledged a relationship that was ``not
appropriate'' with a former White House intern in grand jury
testimony and nationally televised address.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, Clinton had only been seen once. Photographers
captured him walking his chocolate Labrador retriever, Buddy, on
Boston businessman Richard Friedman's Edgartown estate, where
Clinton, First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and their daughter
Chelsea are staying.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's entrance into the press center was a dramatic moment
in an afternoon that was surreal. Before he arrived, so-called pool
reporters _ assigned to follow the president's moves and report
back to other journalists _ lounged under a tent on the grounds of
the estate. The speculation was whether Clinton might play golf on
such a perfect day.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, they were watching a videotape of the movie ``Wag
the Dog,'' about a president who creates a foreign policy crisis to
distract attention from a sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at the press center, McCurry began his daily
briefing with reporters hungry for news. ``What meager scraps would
you like to start with first?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he offered some details about a small birthday party held
Wednesday night for Clinton, who turned 52, at the rented Chilmark
farm home of his longtime friend, Washington power broker Vernon E.
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a very quiet, simple dinner with Vernon, his family,
Vernon's daughter and her family came for dessert,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it was very low-key. They had coconut cake from a local
bakery here. They had barbecued chicken raised on that very farm
and island corn,'' he said. He then added, ``They did candles on
the cake and sang to the president, `Happy Birthday.' Isn't that
sweet?''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said dinner guest collectively gave Clinton a wool
sweater made from a sheep on the farm that Jordan is renting.
</P>
<P>
   As he was being peppered with questions about Lewinsky's second
appearance Thursday before a grand jury, McCurry was handed a note
that interrupted the questions. ``I need to do a very important
piece of business,'' he said. ``In about 10 minutes, the president
will be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
