<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CONG-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SPECTER, SANTORUM QUESTION TIMING OF ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 20 -- Within minutes of President Clinton's
announcement of the attacks against terrorists, U.S. Sen Arlen
Specter openly questioned the president's motive for launching the
bombings, becoming one of the first lawmakers to raise the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those questions will be raised around the world,'' Specter,
R-Pa., said at a hastily arranged press conference in Philadelphia,
broadcast around the world on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he wanted the White House and Pentagon to explain
``especially the reason for doing it now,'' alluding to the
president's swirling controversy regarding his admission of an
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Johnstown, the top Democrat on the House
defense appropriations subcommittee, was returning Thursday from a
fact-finding trip in Saudi Arabia, which sits across the Red Sea
from Sudan, the site of one of the two bombings on alleged
terrorist compounds. Murtha, however, could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa., in prepared remarks, did not raise
the Lewinsky issue. But once Specter and Sen. Daniel Coats, R-Ind.,
a close friend of Santorum's, raised the issue, he also admitted he
had questions about the timing of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to give the benefit of the doubt to this
president,'' said Robert Traynham, Santorum's spokesman, but he
added, ``The senator has a raised eyebrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats and many other Republicans, however, rallied
around the president's decision, including House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, who said, ``It was the right thing to do at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not assume any other reason (for the strikes) unless I
have evidence,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a senior member of
the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to respond to the recent terrorist attacks
and to prevent additional attacks upon American interests,'' said
House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   But Specter said there was an issue of whether ``any
diversionary motive was involved'' in the bombing. He noted the
past U.S. responses to attacks like the ones on American embassies
in East Africa were much different.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, President Reagan ordered a bombing run in Tripoli
because of Libyan support for the bombing of a German dance club in
which U.S. soldiers died, but that came after a months-long
investigation, Specter said. And in June 1996, 19 Air Force
soldiers died in a terrorist bombing at their base in Saudi Arabia.
Two years later, no U.S. action has been taken.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, less than two weeks after the bombings in Kenya
and Tanzania killed a dozen Americans and at least 245 Africans,
the Clinton administration said it had sufficient evidence to
launch the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to respond forcefully to terrorism, but we
ought to have evidentiary basis for doing so,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, however, said there was ample
evidence that those compounds were involved in the embassy
bombings, and that they were planning further attacks against
American sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was done in self defense,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright told reporters in the White House briefing room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
