<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-CLASS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Class at university tackles question: Which came first _ bread
or beer?
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Bread or beer? Barley v. grapes? Nutrition or
libation? These are some of the questions that University of
Georgia students will be discussing this fall in Food Science 2020,
``The Art, Science and History of Beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Taught and designed by Brian Nummer, a brewpub owner and an
adjunct assistant professor in the Department of Food Science, the
one-credit course will introduce students to the role beer and
fermentation have played in world history, culture and religion,
moving from ancient Sumeria, to Europe in the Middle Ages, to
modern microbreweries.
</P>
<P>
   Just as food touches almost every aspect of our lives, so
Nummer's course touches on history, anthropology, agriculture,
transportation, microbiology, sociology and business. It's not
designed for the swill-at-will crowd _ the only tasting will be
imaginary, and one lecture is devoted to the ethics of beer and
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some debate in cultural anthropology as to whether,
when the hunter-gatherers settled down and began cultivating crops,
they first made beer or bread out of barley,'' said Nummer, who
holds a Ph.D. in microbiology from Clemson University. ``I would
say they probably made beer _ home brew is so yeasty that it's full
of vitamins and very nutritious.''
</P>
<P>
   Nummer, 36, has been a student and connoisseur of fermented
froth since he was an undergraduate at Iowa State, where he made
beer _ ``some good, some terrible,'' he confesses _ in his dorm
room. Later, as a graduate student, he trekked through Europe,
stopping in the wine-producing Mozell River town in Germany where
his father's family is from, and realizing ``that if things had
been different, that could have been me there, making wine.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, he worked for a few years in a food testing lab in
Chicago, where he looked for microbial indicators of food quality.
He left Chicago for Clemson, then came to Athens to work in for the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. When funding for his
particular laboratory work was cut, Nummer moved to Germany and
spent six months brewing beer, then taught at Tennessee Tech for a
few years.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1995, he moved back to Athens. A year later, he opened
the Athens Brewing Company in a two-story cavernous building on
Washington Street. He has been worrying over his wort _ a
nonfermented stage of beer _ ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Six on-site brews _ with names like Oliver Hardy Bitter Ale, for
North Georgia's famous comedian, and Pulitizer Pale Ale, in honor
of prize-winning author Ed Larson, one of Nummer's investors _ are
usually available both in the pub upstairs and the restaurant
downstairs, along with countless other beers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course offers me a way to keep my hand in teaching, which
I really enjoy,'' said Nummer. ``I made the switch from academics
to business, but there's no guarantee of success, given the
competition. Besides, this lets me make a contribution to the
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
