<HEADLINE>
JOURNAL REPORTER WHO COVERED BARNICLE STORY   LEAVES PAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Mike Barnicle saga _ and the heightened
journalistic scrutiny and self-examination in this summer of media
mea culpas _ may have claimed another victim. James S. Hirsch, a
three-year veteran of The Wall Street Journal's Boston bureau, left
the newspaper this week after a problem surfaced in his Aug. 12
story on the previous day's decision by The Boston Globe to suspend
Barnicle for two months rather than terminate him.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Barnicle resigned from the Globe after new
questions about his credibility arose and he was unable to verify
the reporting behind an Oct. 8, 1995, column.
</P>
<P>
   In his Aug. 12 story, Hirsch wrote that the Globe's owner, The
New York Times Co., ``declined to comment'' on the decision to
suspend Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   But the Journal subsequently published a correction stating that
``the Times had not been called for comment on the article.'' The
Times' official position was: ``We support the Globe's right to
make its own decision.'' After the Aug. 12 story, the Times pointed
out the error in a letter to the Journal's managing editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hirsch knowingly printed an untruth, which we take very
seriously,'' said Journal spokeswoman Karen Miller Pensiero. ``It
violated our compact with our readers. We considered all of the
circumstances and the reporter was disciplined.'' The company also
confirmed that Hirsch no longer worked at the Journal, but would
not comment on the particulars of his leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch also declined to comment on the circumstances of his
departure.
</P>
<P>
   In his nine-year career at the Journal, Hirsch built a
reputation as a sharp and solid newsman among his peers. Besides
covering the Barnicle travails, he wrote a notable front-page story
in late May detailing the financial problems besetting Fidelity
Investments' Community Newspaper Company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
