A4442 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUDAN-FAMINE-COX     08-20 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-FAMINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No end in sight for Sudanese famine without peace, diplomat
warns
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ A United Nations official said Thursday that,
despite a relief effort on a scale seldom seen before, famine in
Sudan will end only when that country's warring factions make
peace.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat, speaking to reporters here after concluding a
10-day tour of Sudan, said the situation continues to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suffering which one sees surpasses one's worst
nightmares,'' said Tom Vraalsen, the U.N. secretary general's
special envoy for humanitarian affairs in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Vraalsen spoke before the U.S. attack on a plant in the Sudan
suspected of making agents for use in chemical weapons. Late last
year, however, a Sudanese opposition group claimed that the
government was making chemical weapons and using them in its war
against southern rebels. The war has been blamed by many for
creating the country's famine conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In the southwestern town of Wau, Vraalsen said, 70 people are
dying every day. CARE, the Atlanta-based relief organization, is in
the process of setting up feeding stations in Wau right now.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan, Africa's largest country, has been wracked for 15 years
by a civil war between the Islamic government of the north, where
the population is largely Arab, and rebels in the south, where the
population is predominantly black.
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers say that both sides have pushed people off their
land, looting their cattle and preventing them from growing crops.
The famine has been exacerbated by drought.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of lives lost and people displaced, the war in Sudan is
currently the most costly conflict in the world, Vraalsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five relief organizations, operating under a U.N.
umbrella organization called Operation Lifeline Sudan, are running
what Vraalsen said was the largest airlift ever run in Africa. The
operation, based in northwestern Kenya, flies 14 planes, including
six C-130 cargo planes, that ferry food and supplies into feeding
stations in Sudan and air drop supplies to areas that are otherwise
inaccessible.
</P>
<P>
   But Vraalsen said that is still not enough to meet current needs
or forestall future famines _ a point he said he raised with
leaders from both the government and the rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my talks, I made the point that relief, in itself, is
no solution,'' Vraalsen said. ''And I emphasized that a solution
must be found. The international community cannot sustain
indefinitely this humanitarian operation at this level. It is
simply not do-able.''
</P>
<P>
   The envoy called for an extension of the current cease fire, due
to expire in six weeks, and its expansion to more areas of the
country where people are in need.
</P>
<P>
   He said the international community should press the warring
factions to reach a permanent agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no prospect of early peace,'' he acknowledged. ``But
we cannot give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
