</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-RUIZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANKIE RUIZ WAS SALSA'S SHOOTING STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I guess it's no surprise to me that salsa singer Frankie Ruiz
died last week at the age of 40, of liver cirrhosis. Anyone who
followed Ruiz's career _ his stints in jail, his fistfights with
flight attendants, his record company's publicity campaign about
his supposed drug and alcohol rehabilitation _ could have seen it
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this was going to happen,'' said Carrie Sanchez, who
had been Mr. Ruiz's booking agent for the past eight years, in a
phone interview from her New York office this week. ``He'd been
sick on and off for a year and eight months.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm remembering the one time I ended up backstage at a concert
of Mr. Ruiz's, at Vincent's nightclub in Randolph in 1995. I'd been
left breathless by his performance, and yet there he was,
staggering and reeking of alcohol after the show. He rolled his
sleeve up and excused himself _ and a syringe _ to the bathroom for
10 minutes before the interview could happen. He reappeared, moist
and clammy, and kept repeating himself. He looked like a little
boy: guilty and innocent all at once, trying to act professional,
unable to, pulled down by the layers of gold jewelry he wore around
his neck as surely as if they were made of lead. He was thinner
than he was in pictures I'd seen before. Most of all, I am
remembering the sad, faraway, decidedly drugged look in his eyes,
and my thoughts at the time: He can't go on like this. No one
could.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Ruiz was a rare talent. His voice may not have been the
strongest or most versatile in salsa, but it was passionate, part
of the reason it became the cornerstone of the salsa romantica
movement of the 1980s. His was a harsh tenor in some ways younger
than its owner, a voice almost adolescent in the sharp ways it
pulled unexpected notes out of scales and then hung them out where
we could see. When he performed, he meant it. No mild walking about
the stage for Mr. Ruiz. Rather, he bent into his notes, strained
for them, and the music became a person he danced with up there. It
was dazzling to watch, and heartbreaking to hear. The lyrics were
love poems. And yet, even then he was dying, before our eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Born Jose Antonio Terresola Ruiz in Patterson, N.J., on March
10, 1958, Mr. Ruiz began singing professionally, with the stage
name of Frankie Ruiz, as an adolescent, in  &UR; gfspanish &LR; Mayaguez,
Puerto Rico, where he had moved at the age of 7. At 15, his mother
took him to the Maricao nightclub, and proceeded to beg Roberto
Rivera, the leader of a band called La Solucion, to let her son
sing a tune or two.
</P>
<P>
   What Rivera did not expect was that the young Mr. Ruiz would
floor him. Soon after that night, the band had a new teenage singer
named Frankie. A couple of years later, he left the group to join
the Tommy Olivencia orchestra. Mr. Ruiz performed with the group
until 1980, when as a 22-year-old he decided to pursue a solo
career.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to release seven solo records, including the three
most recent ones: ``Mi Historia'' (1997), ``En Vivo'' (1996), and
``Tranquilo'' (1996). He had numerous hit songs, including ``La
Rueda,'' ``La Cura,'' ``Desnudate Mujer,'' and ``Mi Libertad.'' As
are most salsa singers, he was known for a sung signature phrase;
in Mr. Ruiz's case, it was ``Vaya, mi China!'' (roughly, ``Go,
baby!''). Even as the tawdry dramas of his personal life unfolded
in the Spanish tabloids, Mr. Ruiz was embraced by his fans.
</P>
<P>
   He was awarded many prizes in Latin America over the years, and
just last year won his first mainstream trophy in the United
States, in Billboard's Latin Music Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to Billboard magazine recently, Ralph Mercado,
president of RMM Records, for whichMr. Ruiz once recorded,
summarized the singer's tragedy: ``He had a brilliant career, but
he never took time to try and get cured.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Ruiz did not want to die in that room at University Hospital
in Newark, N.J., on Aug. 9, 1998, at 11:40 p.m., and he had said as
much. His father, girlfriend, ex-wife, and cousins were there,
watching helplessly. He'd been hospitalized before, and always he
managed to pull through. In fact, he had told friends he wanted God
to cure him this time, so that he could finish the album he had
been working on, a tribute to his favorite salsa singer of all
time, Hector Lavoe. According to the The Record (Bergen County,
N.J.), Mr. Ruiz told his father on his deathbed, ``When I die, play
my music.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Ruiz was buried in Fairlawn, N.J., near his most recent home
town of Union City. Memorial services have been held for him at the
Ortiz funeral home in the Bronx, and at City Hall in Mayaguez,
where the mayor called for three days of mourning for the town's
most famous musician. Mr. Ruiz leaves his father, Frank Terresola,
and three children: Cristina, Yaritza, and Frankie Jr. Hundreds of
Internet postings in makeshift mourning sites testify to the
singer's loyal following worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Ruiz's record company, Rodven/Polygram Latino, plans to
release the songs he had been working on at the time of his death,
in a disc called, appropriately, ``Nacimientos Y Recuerdos (Births
and Memories).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
