<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4450 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVISIBLE-WINGS-DANCE     08-20 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVISIBLE-WINGS-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING THE STORIES THAT BUILDINGS HAVE TO TELL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (AtTN: Calif., Mass.)  (af) 
 Rita Felciano is the dance critic for the San Francisco Bay
Guardian.  
 By RITA FELCIANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The aboriginal people of Australia believe that
the natural features of the land are the traces of ancestors who
dreamed the earth into being.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco choreographer Joanna Haigood would understand.
Her mythic landscapes include historic cemeteries, old warehouses,
abandoned gyms and rotting piers. For Ms. Haigood, architecture
harbors ancestral memories; buildings and spaces have stories to
tell, and she means to find out what they are.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest and largest investigation is titled ``Invisible
Wings,'' a work inspired by a building on the rambling grounds of
the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival in Becket, Mass. Now housing a
bookstore, the structure served as a safe house for slaves fleeing
along the Underground Railroad before the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haigood and her company, the Zaccho Dance Theater, will
present the dance at the festival beginning Tuesday through
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Four years in the making and involving some 50 collaborators,
``Wings'' incorporates African-American storytelling by Diane
Ferlatte and original music by Lauren Weinger as well as
19th-century slave songs collected by Linda Tillery, all in the
cause of evoking slave culture.
</P>
<P>
   At the dance's premiere in July, at the historic Fort Point in
San Francisco, audiences were met outside the walls by a Mother
Africa figure, then ushered inside through a tunnel in which a
dancer recreated the trans-Atlantic Middle Passage.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtyard, as the wind howled and traffic rumbled across
the Golden Gate Bridge above, performers enacted scenes of
plantation life, both in the slave quarters and in the master's Big
House, and of people escaping from it. (The dance has been
reconceived for the Jacob's Pillow performance. Audiences there
will assemble in a wooded area for an opening scene involving the
capture of an escaped slave, then move indoors.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I make dances for places,'' said Ms. Haigood, 41, who won a
Guggenheim Fellowship in 1997 and, this year, a Cal Arts/Alpert
Award in Arts grant, for $50,000, given to artists in
``early-midcareer.'' For her, places are not only physical
environments but also locations of collective human memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``History is in evidence everywhere in our environment,'' she
said recently in her light-flooded studio in a former mattress
factory in San Francisco. ``But we have pretty much learned to
ignore it. Every scar in this room, every dip in the concrete,
every change of color has a story. What fascinates me is to go to
that one spot there'' _ she points to a nick on the white-washed
wall _ ``and bring my largest magnifying glasses to it; that is,
all of my senses and my intellect. To draw some of the information
forward and share it with people.''
</P>
<P>
   She has done this for 15 years with metaphors of movement:
performers climbing walls, walking on ceilings, floating in water
tanks, balancing on industrial cranes, swinging from trapezes and
dropping themselves off 30-foot ladders.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Ms. Haigood creates her own physical environments in
the hope that ``people will shift their perspective, or just
broaden their relationship with the place they inhabit.''
</P>
<P>
   In one work, ``The Inside Room,'' she mounted a sofa on a wall
eight feet above the ground and had a chair swing from a rope. In
``The Voyager,'' a half-dozen dancers stayed airborne within an
elaborate framework of eight ladders. For a recent solo, ``Dance in
a Bed on a Wall,'' Ms. Haigood attached a queen-size bed at a
slight angle some 20 feet above the floor and performed on, under,
over and alongside it.
</P>
<P>
   She is probably best known for an early piece, ``Yal,'' for
which she used a trapeze that alternately expanded and restricted
her possibilities for movement.
</P>
<P>
   Though performers in the Zaccho Dance Theater (the name comes
from the segment of a Greek column that anchors it to the ground)
move above the floor as often as on it, there is nothing circuslike
or athletically spectacular to the choreography. The language is
sparse, concentrated and stripped down. Most notable is how Ms.
Haigood paces her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I move toward slowing things down,'' she explained. ``It takes
people a long time to absorb something deeply because we are so
constantly bombarded with sensations. So I know if I slow things
down or give them several things to look at at the same time, they
can start the process of wandering through an atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Another striking aspect of her pieces is their dreamlike,
sometimes quasi-ritualistic quality. ``Dreams are important to
me,'' she said. ``They are the place where I can listen to my
intuitions in a deeper way. It's also the place where great
fantasies are born.'' Sometimes with surprising results.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haigood once unsettled an audience of 400 at the end of a
solo work created for and performed at a Roman cemetery in Arles,
France. She closed the piece, ``Journey From Elysian Fields,'' by
climbing out of a tomb and slowly ascending the outside of a tower
before disappearing into a beam of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had decided not to come back for a bow,'' she recalled,
laughing. ``It just didn't seem appropriate. People apparently just
freaked out because they couldn't figure out what had happened to
me.'' She finally relented and returned for a bow.
</P>
<P>
   One of her earliest architecture-specific pieces is ``Building
T952,'' which called forth ghosts of its own. Set in and inspired
by an abandoned army gymnasium at Fort Barry, across the Golden
Gate Bridge in Marin County, the dance brought eerily to life a
time when the fort was a place from which GI's were shipped to the
Pacific during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asking'' the wood-frame structure to release its secrets, Ms.
Haigood had dark-clad figures spill from a rear balcony; another
dropped from the ceiling through a hatch door. Still other dancers
crawled along support beams and radiators or called up a
long-forgotten game of basketball. One young couple waltzed, the
woman's head nestled against the man's neck.
</P>
<P>
   None of her research has been as arduous or as personally moving
as that for ``Invisible Wings,'' a work commissioned by Jacob's
Pillow. ``I did lots of reading and traveled to libraries,'' she
said. ``I interviewed people in Georgia and South Carolina, where
my father is from and where there still is evidence of slave
culture. People were very generous in sharing the information.''
</P>
<P>
   She remembers the sadness in the voice of an old man in Sea
Island, Ga., who walked with her through fields that had been
deeded to his family by slave owners after Emancipation, fields now
threatened by developers who had made his neighbors offers they
couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   She listened to the voices of slaves recorded in the early 1930s
by Zora Neale Hurston and Alan Lomax, and she looked at hundreds of
faces in archival photographs and documentary films like ``Roots of
Resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   She also read slave accounts, like one about Margaret Garner,
whose story was the inspiration for Toni Morrison's novel
``Beloved.'' Garner killed one of her infants rather than let him
grow up in slavery and ``rejoiced'' when another drowned in a
boating accident after they were caught escaping.
</P>
<P>
   Another account was of a kindly soul who found an escaped slave
he was going to help hanging from a tree, still wearing an iron
neck brace with bells attached. ``His body,'' said Ms. Haigood,
``was perfectly intact. The bells had kept the birds away.''
</P>
<P>
   The more she researched this material, ``the more I realized how
enormous it was,'' she said, ``and how much we are still in
denial.'' She used her findings not to recreate specific incidents
but to construct a vast landscape out of which she fashioned
``Invisible Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haigood even drew up a genealogy of the Carter family, who
in the 19th century homesteaded the farm that is now Jacob's
Pillow. One Carter descendant was born on the property and will
attend the Pillow performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me all of these family pictures but didn't know how
the people were related to each other,'' she recalled of their
first meeting. ``So I pulled out this sheet of paper, and we were
able to put names and relationships to the faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Park Service is considering sponsoring a tour in
which ``Invisible Wings'' would be performed at other Underground
Railroad sites around the country.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Haigood, she is deep in preparation for her next
site-specific work, a commission by Dancing in the Streets for the
Red Hook section of Brooklyn. There, a dilapidated 19th-century
grain terminal has caught her fancy. ``The building is really
beautiful, even though now it's mostly a symbol of the area's
collapse,'' she said. ``But grain,'' she added, smiling, ``is the
seed of life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1847EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4454 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FLU-1918-ART-2TAK     08-20 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FLU-1918-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCTIC GRAVES MAY YIELD CLUES ON 1918 EPIDEMIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGYEARBYEN, Norway _ Five gravediggers from London were
scheduled to started digging here Friday morning. Actually, much of
the time they will be hammering through ice.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the islands of Spitsbergen in the high Arctic between
mainland Norway and Greenland, the ground three feet down is always
frozen in permafrost. At six feet, they should find the bodies, in
the mass grave encased in a tomb of ice.
</P>
<P>
   It is the time of the midnight sun. A white fox slinks up the
steep hill overlooking this small mining town, its camouflage coat
useless now against the bare rock and dark moss. The seed-fluff
from the arctic cottongrass floats on the breeze among the rows of
white wooden crosses.
</P>
<P>
   Over the mass grave, a tent with a special air lock has been
stretched and inflated. The tent is for privacy in this somber
enterprise and protection against anything possibly dangerous
escaping into the outside air. Inside, the diggers, with medical
scientists at their side, will go about their business of opening
the resting place of seven young men who were buried here 80 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   This is a critical moment in one of the most ambitious efforts
yet to solve an intractable medical mystery: What caused the
influenza pandemic of 1918 and early 1919? Why was this particular
contagion so virulent that it killed an estimated 20 million to 40
million people worldwide?
</P>
<P>
   The secret of one of the most lethal viruses the world has ever
known may dwell in the lungs of these seven victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years' work culminates in the next few weeks,'' Dr.
Kirsty Duncan, who is directing the project, said as final
preparations were under way. She specializes in medical geography
and teaches at the universities of Windsor and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by reading ``America's Forgotten Pandemic: The
Influenza Of 1918,'' (Cambridge University Press) by Alfred W.
Crosby of the University of Texas, she began the search for flu
victims whose bodies might be preserved in ice. The research led
scientists to the mass grave in the cemetery here.
</P>
<P>
   In a diary kept by the coal mining company here, Dr. Duncan
found the names of the seven men, 18 to 29 years old, farmers and
fishermen who had just arrived here to earn extra money at winter
jobs in the mine. But they had contracted flu on the boat trip from
the mainland and died in the first week of October 1918.
</P>
<P>
   The sight of their names on the six crosses and one headstone at
the back of the cemetery moved Dr. Duncan to tears: Johan Bjerk,
William Henry Richardsen, Ole Kristofferson, Magnus Gabrielson,
Tormod Albrigtsen, Hans Hansen and Kristian Hansen.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Duncan impressed Norwegian authorities with the importance
of the project of isolating and describing at last the unknown 1918
virus. She emphasized the safety precautions that would be taken.
The authorities then obtained permissions from the families to
exhume and examine six of the seven bodies (all but
Kristofferson's).
</P>
<P>
   By the time the permissions came through, Dr. Duncan had
gathered an international group of pathologists, virologists,
molecular biologists, geologists and medical archeologists for the
work.
</P>
<P>
   A survey with ground-penetrating radar established that the
bodies, side by side, were indeed in permanent permafrost and thus
should be well preserved for medical study. A team of experienced
gravediggers from Necropolis Co. in London was hired.
</P>
<P>
   After the topsoil is removed by spade and the permafrost is
penetrated with electric jack hammer, Dr. Charles R. Smith, a
pathologist from the Hospital for Sick Children at the University
of Toronto, plans to remove samples of tissues from the victims'
lungs, intestines and other organs. The bodies, which were not
embalmed, will not be thawed or taken from the grave, both out of
respect and as a precaution against the spread of any infectious
material.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists seriously doubt that any of the flu virus will
still be alive, but just in case, they will be wearing modified
space suits with self-contained breathing apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   Once the tissues are extracted, portions of each sample will be
sealed in separate vials and shipped to laboratories in Norway,
Canada, Britain and the United States. The most sensitive
investigations will be conducted at the U.S. Army's infectious
disease research laboratory in Fort Detrick, Md. and the National
Institute of Medical Research in London, which are equipped to
maintain the highest levels of biological containment of unknown
organisms.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Bergan of the University of Oslo, a virologist on the
team, said the tissue samples would not be touched until they
arrived at the laboratories. ``Our first obligation is safety
requirements against the risk of contamination,'' Bergan said. ``We
want to make sure there is no viable virus in the sample and, if
there is, protect against its escape into the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergan said the research might help determine the composition,
genetic structure and nature of the 1918 virus, in particular its
exterior surfaces, where the virus attaches itself to the lining of
the lungs and the upper respiratory tract. Such knowledge could
lead to the development of a vaccine against this acute form of
influenza and tests and modifications of current or new anti-viral
drugs for treating the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The pandemic occurred near the close of World War I, when
doctors had yet to learn that influenza is caused by a virus and
they had no antibiotics to treat bacterial infections like
pneumonia that often attacked the weakened bodies and contributed
to death.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Scientists in the project said it might take several months,
maybe a year, of analysis before they would be ready to publish
their findings.
</P>
<P>
   Their undertaking comes at a time when the search for the 1918
virus has gained momentum on several fronts. Last year, Dr. Jeffrey
K. Taubenberger, a biologist at the Armed Forces Institute of
Pathology in Washington, reported finding viral fragments in
preserved lung tissue of two U.S. soldiers who died of flu in World
War I. The specimens were in a collection of autopsy tissue, soaked
in formaldehyde and encased in paraffin, that the Army has kept
since the Civil War. The analysis of the material has enabled the
scientists to map at least one of the virus' protein-making genes.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Johan Hultin, a retired pathologist who lives in San
Francisco, went to the tundra of Alaska last year and exhumed the
well preserved body of an Eskimo woman who died of the 1918 flu. He
sent lung tissue samples to Taubenberger, who was able to isolate
more viral traces.
</P>
<P>
   These findings encouraged Dr. Duncan's team in the belief that
it would also find traces of flu viruses in permafrost burials. But
for a time, Dr. Duncan wondered if there was any point in
continuing in light of the Taubenberger successes. At a meeting
with officials at the federal Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta, she was persuaded to press on.
</P>
<P>
   The project is supported by a $150,000 grant from the National
Institutes of Health in the United States and about $194,000 from
Hoffmann-La Roche, the pharmaceutical company.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Duncan emphasized the need for still more samples from other
parts of the world, especially material that has not been preserved
and possibly altered in formaldehyde.
</P>
<P>
   So head gravedigger Roger Webber is ready. He has been exhuming
bodies for 33 years, but has never worked in permafrost. It cannot
be harder than the many times he has dealt with layers of solid
chalk or limestone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Using a technique known as needle biopsy, the pathologist,
Smith, will take bore samples of tissue from the lungs of the six
bodies. Then he will try to probe the hearts, where he may be able
to extract frozen blood. This is a long shot, but any blood could
yield samples of serum and any antibodies produced in the acute
phases of the disease. The intestines could hold bacteria, possible
clues to other complicating infections. An attempt will also be
made to get samples from the livers and spleens.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Smith said, ``You don't know what you are going to find
until you look.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for the 1918 influenza virus has apparently created
little stir in Spitsbergen. The 1,300 residents of Longyearbyen,
the island's principal community, are used to visitors with
peculiar goals in mind. Explorers like Richard E. Byrd and Roald
Amundsen set out from here in 1929 for the North Pole, about 700
miles away, and more recently, scientists have been operating bases
for studies in geophysics, climatology and polar life in the
Svalbard Archipelago, which includes Spitsbergen.
</P>
<P>
   Ann-Kristin Olsen, governor of the Svalbard Archipelago, said
that community meetings have been held to inform people of the
exhumations, and they had seemed to accept the reassurances that
the work posed no health hazard. Hallvard Holm, headmaster of the
local school, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard of a single soul who has been afraid,'' Holm
said. ``I know there have been jokes, nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the people of Spitsbergen and the tourists have more
familiar dangers on their minds. Each day hikers head off for the
rugged hills and glaciers with packs on their backs and rifles
slung over their shoulders. People are advised to carry a firearm
whenever they roam beyond town, in case they should meet up with a
hungry polar bear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-BOMBING-700&AMP;     08-20 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-BOMBING-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MORE VICTIMS ARE BURIED, SOME SEE OMAGH BLAST AS WATERSHED
TOWARD PEACE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES F. CLARITY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ As Northern Ireland buried eight
more victims of a terrorist bombing on Saturday, a guilty hope
began to emerge Thursday among officials, analysts and some
ordinary people that some good may come of the atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   The blast, which killed 28 people and injured 220 in the town of
Omagh, 60 miles to the west, was the deadliest attack in 29 years
of sectarian violence in this predominantly Protestant British
province.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are almost afraid to think it, but this tragedy may be
another watershed toward real peace,'' said Margaret Arthur, a
local painter and printmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Paul Arthur, a professor of political science at
Ulster University here, added that he had been told in recent days
by a senior American official that the blast and the public outrage
it stimulated meant that ``the war's over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That bomb has destroyed whole the movement against the peace
agreement,'' he said, referring to the accord approved in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur added of the Real IRA, the group that claimed
responsibility for the bombing: ``They don't have the water to swim
in anymore _ no public support.''
</P>
<P>
   David McKittrick, author of several standard reference books on
Northern Ireland, wrote in Thursday's London Independent that
``while these are the worst of times for the people of Omagh, they
must also appear to the be the worst of times for the small but
shockingly dangerous splinter groups intent on bringing down'' the
new peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is thus possible,'' he added, ``to hope that the political
and moral illiterates are, one by one, realizing that war has had
its day and to hope that Ireland is still moving in the direction
of eventual peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Wood, a political consultant and former British information
director here, said the Catholic Republican guerrilla groups are
now likely to end their attacks and spend much of their time trying
to elude the police and intelligence officers of Britain and the
Irish Republic to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, who was a government insider for 10 years until last year,
said the ``draconian'' security and legal measures advanced on
Wednesday by the Irish government would put more pressure on the
dissident paramilitary groups to abandon violence. But the bombing
may also lead, he said, to ``internecine blood-letting'' between
the Real IRA and the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA, with about 100 dissidents, some of whom are
skilled bomb-makers, broke away from the IRA after the IRA called a
cease-fire 13 months ago that helped lead to the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA, and its political wing, Sinn Fein, are embarrassed by
terrorist attacks by other, smaller, republican groups. ``And who
in Omagh, or anywhere is going to care if a couple of these guys
are murdered?,'' Wood added.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Parliament, under Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, is to
meet in two weeks to consider, and probably approve, a series of
measures that Ahern said were ``draconian'' to combat terrorism. In
part, the proposals, which could have been made any time during the
decades of violence, are to show an angry public that the
government is acting decisively. Whether the new measures would
actually result in the capture of more terrorists is impossible to
predict.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Royal Ulster Constabulary said Thursday that
three people being questioned about the Omagh bombing had been
released from police custody without being charged, Agence
France-Presse reported. The two others, arrested in and around the
Omagh area, on Monday, were still being held.)
</P>
<P>
   One provision being considered by the Irish government would
make it easier to imprison someone accused of membership in a
terrorist organization. Another would double, to four days, the
time a terrorist suspect could be held without being charged with a
crime. But, significantly, Ahern said the government was not
planning to revive ``internment,'' or preventive detention without
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Internment, used by the British here in the early 1970's, kept
hundreds of terrorist suspects out of action, but allowed them to
win international recognition with highly publicized hunger
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The British government of Prime Minister Tony Blair killed
internment last year. That means that if Ireland used internment,
but Britain did not, fugitives in the south, where many of the
splinter group guerrillas are based, would flee to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, on vacation in France, issued a statement Thursday saying
that he and Ahern had agreed that the Real IRA ``will be dealt with
and taken off the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The measures announced by the Irish government indicate they
are being true to their word, he added. ``There is unprecedented
cooperation between our two governments as we take our plans.''
Blair did not elaborate on the specifics of the new steps.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the prime minister at Downing Street said that
Blair is not at the moment contemplating new legislation because
many of the measures can be taken by stretching the application of
existing British laws. He noted, however, that if new laws were
required, ``we will do whatever is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood, the consultant, warned against reviving internment in
dealing with terrorists. ``The thing is,'' Wood said, ``that you do
not at all costs make them martyrs.''
</P>
<P>
   Internment, he added, would force Republicans such as Sinn Fein
into hard-line political positions, hindering the operation of the
new Northern Ireland Assembly that is to revise the political
structure of the north to give minority Catholics more power and to
give the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic more influence in
northern affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Lislianeghan, outside Omagh, Samantha McFarland,
17, a Catholic, was buried as Protestants and Catholics looked on
glumly. She had been working on Saturday afternoon in an OXFAM
shop, was evacuated by the police after they received a misleading
bomb warning from the Real IRA. Instead of away from the bomb, she
was led close to it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Derek Quinn said, ``How cruel and ironic it is that it
was because of her very desire to help those afflicted by poverty,
injustice and oppression that she herself and her best friend would
be evacuated from that shop only to walk into the path of the bomb
that was to rob them of their very lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
