A4474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEDEPOT-GROWTH-COX     08-20 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-GROWTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot to open more stores in South America
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot has announced plans to step up its pace of
international expansion, adding more stores in Chile and moving
into Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   As previously announced, Atlanta-based Home Depot will open a
store next week in Santiago, with another planned later in fiscal
1998. On Thursday, the company announced it would open three more
stores in Chile the following year, in addition to a store in
Buenos Aires, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Argentina is the next step to continue growing our South
American business, and it will complement and leverage our Chilean
store operations,'' said Arthur M. Blank, president and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Although Home Depot has been the world's largest home
improvement retailer for nearly a decade, the Santiago store marks
its first international venture outside its Canadian division. Its
cautious global growth plan has been strikingly different from its
breakneck domestic pace, which has seen the company opening stores
at an average of 100 each year over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Chile was chosen for the first Home Depot store outside North
America because of its stable economy and government, and a growing
middle class. Home Depot had looked at expansion in Mexico, but
shelved plans in 1995 because of the peso's devaluation.
</P>
<P>
   The Chile stores will be called Home Depot, complete with orange
aprons and the trademark logo, but the merchandise will be markedly
different from the U.S. selection. For example, the lumber
department has been scaled back to suit Chilean homes, which use
more bricks, concrete blocks and steel. The stores will be
predominantly stocked by local vendors, but Home Depot is using
U.S. suppliers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's main competition is Sodimac, Chile's largest home
improvement company, with revenue of $681 million and 47 stores.
(Home Depot had 1997 revenue of $24.2 billion.) Sodimac is Chile's
version of Home Depot, with stores that range in size from 80,000
to 100,000 square feet and drive-through lumberyards.
</P>
<P>
   Sodimac has recently increased its U.S. involvement, including a
new alliance with Ace Hardware, which supplies stores in Chile and
Colombia. Sodimac also just opened its first U.S. office at the
Paper Mill Office Park in Marietta to coordinate the sourcing of
international products.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot also announced Thursday management changes related to
its South American division. Bill Pena, who has been with Home
Depot since 1994, was named regional president for Argentina and
Chile, a newly created position. Pena was vice president of
international development and will continue as chairman of Home
Depot's joint venture with Falabella, Chile's largest retailer.
Pena will be based in Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting to him will be Julio Campos, a former executive of
Sodimac and general manager of Chile, and Nelson Tirado, who was
named regional vice president of operations for Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
