<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLAN-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      08-20 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLAN-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-KLANSMAN QUIZZED IN BOWERS FIREBOMBNG TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ Devours Nix, a one-time Klansman, took the
stand Thursday on behalf of his friend, Sam Bowers, the imperial
wizard of the White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan, to call Bowers a
``real, real nice man'' and to describe the Klan as a
``benevolent'' organization that handed out fruit baskets at
Christmastime.
</P>
<P>
   Nix's testimony, on the fourth day of Bowers' trial for murder
in the 1966 firebombing of Hattiesburg NAACP president Vernon
Dahmer, provoked snickers of disbelief in the crowded courtroom.
His credibility was shredded further during cross-examination when
he denied owning Klan paraphenalia and the prosecution produced an
old photo of Nix dressed in a hooded robe and carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Nix was originally arrested with Bowers and a dozen other
Klansmen 32 years ago, but he has never been tried. He was
rearrested with Bowers and a third defendant last spring after new
evidence prompted the state to revive the case.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-year-old Nix, now awaiting trial for arson in the Dahmer
case, spoke from a wheelchair, his hands trembling from a reaction
to medication, he said, and with tubes inserted in his nostrils to
supply oxygen. He was released on his own recognizance because of
health reasons following his arrest, but called back to court weeks
later after a photographer for a Jackson newspaper captured him
playing golf. The same day the photo was published, Nix was
arrested again and required to post a $50,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   After the prosecution rested its case, the defense took the
initiative. But the trial was briefly disrupted when Richard
Barrett, a white supremacist with a minuscule following in the
state, began passing out leaflets describing ``The crimes of Vernon
Dahmer'' and predicting that Mississippi would ``whip the NAACP.''
</P>
<P>
   When Circuit Judge Richard McKenzie ordered Barrett arrested for
contempt of court, many spectators burst into applause.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers' attorney, Travis Buckley, appealed for a mistrial, but
since the incident took place out of sight of the jury the motion
was denied.
</P>
<P>
   After Buckley led Nix through two hours of testimony in which
the witness contradicted himself several times, prosecuting
attorney Robert Helfrich opened the cross-examination by asking:
``Mr. Nix, do you know what perjury is?''
</P>
<P>
   Although Nix had said earlier that he did not know whether
Bowers belonged to the Klan, Helfrich reported that Nix had once
identified Bowers as the ``imperial wizard'' during a hearing in
Federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember that,'' Nix said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked the color of his Klan robe, Nix said: ``I didn't have
no robe.''
</P>
<P>
   Helfrich then presented Nix with a copy of a photo seized at
Nix's house during a search by authorities two months after
Dahmer's death.
</P>
<P>
   Helfrich: ``What does this person have on?''
</P>
<P>
   Nix: ``It looks like it might be a robe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With a hood?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmm-hmm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Holding a gun?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's you, is it not?''
</P>
<P>
   When Nix replied, ``No sir, that's not me,'' laughter swept the
courtroom again.
</P>
<P>
   Helfrich said authorities noted in 1966 that Nix's wife
complained to her husband after the raid on their house: ``They
found that crazy, silly picture of you with a pointed hood on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Nix operated John's Restaurant in nearby Laurel,
described in earlier testimony as a Klan hang-out where a jug
rested on the counter to collect funds for the defense of those
arrested in the Dahmer murder case.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecution witness, Bob Stringer, testified Wednesday that he
overheard a conversation between Bowers, Nix and another Klansman,
Henry deBoxtel, in the restaurant a few days before the raid on
Dahmer's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I overheard Bowers make a statement,'' Stringer said, ``that
the Forrest County boys were not doing their job, and that
something needs to be done about that nigger down south.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer lived in Forrest County, where the local Klan was deemed
ineffective during the turbulent civil rights movement three
decades ago. According to testimony here, Bowers controlled the
White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan from Laurel, a Jones County city
35 miles north of here, and a Jones County Klan unit was the one
tapped by Bowers to destroy Dahmer.
</P>
<P>
   Stringer testified that he heard deBoxtel, who has since died,
tell Bowers: ``We ought to put a `4' on him and shut him up.'' Code
4, in Klan parlance, called for death.
</P>
<P>
   Nix said he was not acquainted with Stringer, and denied ever
hearing Bowers issue a racial slur.
</P>
<P>
   Although another witness placed Nix at a Klan gathering where
Bowers called for Dahmer's elimination, Nix denied attending any
meeting where violence was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   He also denied that Klan literature was distributed at his
restaurant, though Helfrich said during cross-examination that a
1966 search of the cafe found Klan pamphlets.
</P>
<P>
   After saying he did not know whether Bowers belonged to the
Klan, Nix testified that Bowers told him Nix had been elected an
``investigator'' for the Klan. Later, he corrected himself again
and said someone other than Bowers informed him.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Nix said he learned of Dahmer's death ``on the way
to Washington'' to appear before the House Unamerican Activities
Committee. Later, he said he heard the news after he had returned
to Laurel.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was persuaded to join the Klan after learning of its
benevolent activities. Asked if he remembered the Klan oath, Nix
said, ``The only thing I recall is that you had to believe in
God.'' Asked about other parts of the oath, he paused and said,
``I'm at a loss for words.''
</P>
<P>
   Helfrich closed his cross-examination by asking Nix if he had
ever delivered any baskets of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never delivered any,'' Nix said glumly, and he was wheeled
out of the courtroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
