<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. ATTACKS TERRORIST BASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning a four-page package of stories on
the U.S. military strikes against terrorist bases in Afghanistan
and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   We commend to your attention Tim Weiner's ATTACK-BINLADEN, a
profile in preparation prior to today's developments.
</P>
<P>
   The ledeall, with a 4-col. hed, will move by  &UR; 9 p.m. Eastern
time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S. (Washington) _ Ledeall on the attacks: President
Clinton returns to Washington, announces the attacks on the
terrorist bases. How and when the decision was made. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   With satellite photos.
</P>
<P>
   With maps showing attack targets.
</P>
<P>
   With timeline graphic.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move by  &UR; 8:00 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-BINLADEN (Washington) _ How Osama bin Laden, the youngest
son of a construction magnate from Yemen, became the world's most
feared sponsor of terrorism. The religious and ideological roots of
his rage lie in the 1980s, when he worked side by side with the CIA
backing the Afghan rebels. When that battle was over, he and his
fellow holy warriors, past and present _ having defeated the
British in the 19th century and the Soviets in the 20th _ went to
work on the United States. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   With locator map.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The most cherished axiom of
American diplomacy is that politics stops at the water's edge,
meaning that the opposition party supports the president when
missiles are flying. Today it worked, more or less. The bulk of
congressional leaders, from Speaker Newt Gingrich to such reliable
Clinton critics as Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina, rallied
around the commander-in-chief, with Gingrich declaring: ``I think
based on what I know that it was the right thing to do at the right
time.'' But in the surreal and cinematic atmosphere that suffused
Washington this week, a handful of voices on Capitol Hill cried
foul. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SECURITY (Washington) _ A look at the security of U.S.
cities as well as U.S. embassies and military bases abroad. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ Arrests in Albania show links to the
African embassy bombings: In a series of lightning raids with the
Albanian secret police this summer, American intelligence agents
appear to have thwarted a bomb plot against the American Embassy
here. They also seem to have broken up a ring of Egyptian Islamic
terrorists using this nation's anarchy to set up a base. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT (Jerusalem) _ Reactions from the Middle
East and other governments. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN (Nairobi, Kenya) _ The U.S.'s troubled relationship
with Sudan. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With locator map.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MEDIA (Undated) _ How the all-news TV stations handled
the sudden change in content. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-GAS (Undated) _ An explainer on deadly VX gas. By Judy
Miller
</P>
<P>
   With graphic explainer on chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move by  &UR; 9:00 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ The evidence the administration
had for attacking the Sudan facility and bin Laden's base in
Afghanistan. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MILITARY (Washington) _ Details of the attack; the role
of Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs; the impact
on tactics of lessons learned in earlier operations. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ASSESS (Undated) _ A news analysis on the efficacy of
military strikes against terrorist organizations. By Serge
Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-WAG (New York) _ Reaction from the street: ``Wag the
Dog'' quips and other reaction. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
