<SLUG> BC-PROMISEKEEPERS-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW TO PROTEST PROMISE KEEPERS RALLY IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RAD SALLEE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Texas president of the National Organization for
Women joined some local clergy members and others Thursday in
criticizing the Promise Keepers organization, which is starting a
conference Friday night in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   NOW and others will protest the event at 5 p.m., CDT, Saturday,
said Houston attorney Jeanne Sommerfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Promise Keepers, a ``Christian outreach for men,'' was founded
by former University of Colorado football coach Bill McCartney. Its
emotional rallies fill sports stadiums nationwide, featuring men of
all races praying together, confessing their failings, and
promising to be better husbands and fathers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that, said Sommerfeld and the pastors, is that
the aims are promoted through an intolerant fundamentalism that
subordinates women, oppresses homosexuals and promotes right-wing
political aims.
</P>
<P>
   Promise Keepers, a Denver-based group, urges men to make seven
promises, including ``practicing spiritual, moral, ethical and
sexual purity'' and ``building strong marriages and families
through love, protection and biblical values.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sommerfeld challenged the organization to answer seven
questions, including explaining its alleged disrespect toward
women, political agenda, anti-gay stance and funding sources.
</P>
<P>
   Promise Keepers literature says the group is politically
neutral, but Sommerfeld cited McCartney's vows to ``take back the
nation for Christ'' and to ``contend for the truth'' in ``schools
and the legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   A NOW handout said McCartney also worked for a Colorado
referendum to deny gays and lesbians protection from
discrimination. The resulting amendment was ruled unconstitutional
by the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Promise Keepers' official statements say homosexual behavior is
a sin but that gays are welcome to attend the group's events and
seek God's forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   While Sommerfeld acknowledged that Promise Keepers does not
condone wife abuse or seek to deprive women of legal rights, she
said these results could be a ``logical consequence'' of a
subordinate role.
</P>
<P>
   While Promise Keepers promotes apostle Paul's teaching that
women should ``submit'' to their husbands, the group also exhorts
husbands to cherish and protect their wives.
</P>
<P>
   The organization reported that its rallies at 22 stadiums in
1996 drew 1.1 million men. In 1997 it had a staff of 452 and a
budget of about $117 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Others speaking against the rally included ministers Bob
Schaibly of First Unitarian Universalist Church, where the press
conference was held, Bruce Prescott of Easthaven Baptist Church and
Carolyn Mobley of Metropolitan Community Church of Resurrection,
and former ministers Don Sinclair and Wes Seeliger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
