A4503 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEACONESS-CONSENSUS-B     08-20 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEACONESS-CONSENSUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL LICENSES DRUG-DEVELOPMENT PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center has licensed a new
drug development process to Consensus Pharmaceuticals Inc., a
Boston &UR;  &LR; company formed this week to market the technology.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Consensus, which is backed by venture capital
financing of $4 million to $7 million, marks the first time the
hospital has taken an equity stake in a spinoff company involving
BI-Deaconess research.
</P>
<P>
   The new company's shareholders include the hospital, Interwest
Partners of Menlo Park, Calif., and Axiom Venture Partners, based
in Hartford, Conn. Interwest holds the biggest stake.
</P>
<P>
   Consensus plans to hire about 30 employees in its first year,
according to managing director Arnold L. Oronsky.
</P>
<P>
   Consensus will contract with drug companies to screen hundreds
of millions of molecules for possible reaction with a protein, gene
or cell, allowing manufacturers to develop new drugs in far less
time than traditional drug-screening methods require, investors
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeared to me that it literally cut years off the
process,'' said Dr. Linda D. Sonntag, an Axiom general partner, of
Consensus's technology.
</P>
<P>
   BI-Deaconess researcher Dr. Lewis Cantley, who developed the
process, will serve on the company's scientific advisory board and
work as a consultant for Consensus. The company's management will
be made up of outside businesspeople rather than people affiliated
with the hospital , according to Mark Chalek, director of corporate
research at BI-Deaconess.
</P>
<P>
   Consensus hopes to line up several contracts with pharmaceutical
companies over the next few months, Chalek said. In addition to
contract work for drug companies, Consensus will also develop its
own drugs using its technology, Oronsky said.
</P>
<P>
   After a merger created BI-Deaconess 18 months ago, the hospital
hired Chalek to investigate ways to spin off the hospital's
research through startup companies or licenses to existing firms,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   While hospitals in other regions often take equity positions in
companies formed to market their research, Boston-area medical
centers are only beginning to do so, Chalek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston tends to somewhat of a more conservative community,''
he said. ``As more and more of these have been done over the years
and institutions have realized it's a beneficial way to transfer
technology, it's becoming more usual.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
