<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4507 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USSTRIKES-AFGHANISTAN     08-20 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USSTRIKES-AFGHANISTAN-0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFGHANISTAN: WHERE IT IS, WHAT IT'S LIKE
 &HT;    With USSTRIKES-MAIN-0821.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not many people in Afghanistan's capital will be
able to see the effects of the U.S. attack on facilities in their
country on television.
</P>
<P>
   After a warning period expired, Islamic morality squads from the
Taliban movement, which controls most of the country, that controls
most of Afghanistan began this month to move through the streets,
stores and workplaces of Kabul smashing all the TV sets they could
find.
</P>
<P>
   ``These means of corruption were in some places even thrown out
of the windows of high buildings to smash on the streets below,'' a
local newspaper reported. The Taliban announced on radio (which is
still legal) that it will supply the morality squads with uniforms
and armbands, so that people will be able to tell them from the
country's many bands of unauthorized freelance thugs.
</P>
<P>
   Afghanistan is a poor, mountainous, landlocked country with the
bad luck to be right in the middle of the best land route between
Europe and Asia. The target of more powerful nations for centuries,
its many tribes and political factions joined together to throw out
the latest occupation force, which came from the Soviet Union, in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   The civil war that broke out among the Afghan victors continues,
despite recent efforts by Americans and other outsiders to work out
a peace agreement. The Taliban, a fundamentalist Islamist movement,
has controlled Kabul and the southern two-thirds of Afghanistan for
nearly 23 months -- but by no means controls everything that goes
on within that part.
</P>
<P>
   Taliban's generals frequently announce victories against other
Afghans in the north, but the civil war never seems to end.
</P>
<P>
   The International Red Cross fed more than 3,700 families last
week in Kabul, where the Taliban won't let women take paying jobs
outside their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other things to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Government: At the top of Taliban, the closest thing
Afghanistan has to a government, is the president, Lt. Gen. Omar
Hassan Ahmed al-Bashir. There is no legislative branch and
religious courts handle judicial activity.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Neighbors: Afghanistan is surrounded by Pakistan to the east
and south, Iran to the west and China and three former Soviet
republics -- Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan and Tajikistan -- to its
North.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Size: 647,500 square kilometers , slightly smaller than Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Population: Around 28 million, twice Florida's.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ethnic groups: Pashtun 38 percent; Tajik 25 percent; Hazara 19
percent; Uzbek 6 percent; plus others.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Languages: Many Afghanis are bilingual. The first language for
about half is an Afghan version of Persian, the language of
neighboring Iran. Most of the rest speak Uzbek, Turkmen or another
Turkic language.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Life expectancy: The average woman has a life expectancy of 47
years; the average man lives 46 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Religion: Virtually everybody is a Muslim, with about 85
percent Sunni and the rest Shi'ite.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
