<SLUG> BC-SURVEY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: RISING TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The relationship between agencies and advertisers is
deteriorating, according to an annual survey, after two years of
results that had begun to narrow a yawning chasm between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had seen some real improvements, but this year the
advertisers and agencies are starting to fall out again,'' said
Nancy Salz, president of Nancy L. Salz Consulting in New York, who
offered a preview of the findings of the 1998 Salz Survey of
Advertiser-Agency Relations.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys for 1996 and 1997 had brought surprisingly better
responses from executives at agencies and client companies when
asked about the nature of their relations. But that era of good
feelings proved brief, much to Ms. Salz's dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't expecting that,'' Ms. Salz said, referring to the
conclusions of the 1998 survey.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which has been conducted for the last 13 years, is
significant because what advertisers and agencies think and feel
about each other strongly influences their ability to work
together. That in turn can profoundly affect the quality and
effectiveness of the campaigns that are aimed at consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to stay focused on the advertising,'' Ms. Salz
said, ``but it's very, very easy to lose that focus.'' Indeed,
advertisers responding to the survey said that if they could
consistently obtain the best work from their agencies, their sales
would increase by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Half the agency executives who replied to the survey said that
there was increased tension in the relationship with their major
clients. That figure was at its highest level since 1994. At the
same time, 30 percent of the executives at client companies said
that there was increased tension in the relationship with their
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Both agencies and advertisers also told of frustrations with the
process by which ads are produced. Asked if in the last year there
were more or fewer hassles (to use the wording of the question)
than previously, 45 percent of agencies, and 25 percent of
advertisers, answered by saying there were more.
</P>
<P>
   And there were sharp differences in the responses to a question
about whether there was more or less teamwork in the agency-client
relationship. Sixty-four percent of advertisers said that there was
more teamwork, a record figure for that response. Five percent said
that there was less teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   When agencies were asked the same question, only 36 percent said
that there was more teamwork. Thirty-two percent said that there
was less teamwork, a record figure for that response.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for the reversal of fortune in the survey,
Ms. Salz said, was ``the extraordinary pressure on advertisers to
increase earnings to justify stock value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As the bull market goes on, those pressures are even
greater,'' she added. ``So what clients demand of their agencies
causes the tensions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both advertisers and agencies agree that the agencies have
responded well to the pressure,'' Ms. Salz said, ``and are more
focused on their clients' needs. However, they do not agree how
well their relationship is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Ms. Salz said, survey responses from advertisers were
more optimistic than those from their agencies. That's an
interesting twist to the widespread perception that Madison Avenue
is replete with preternatural Pollyannas.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salz said she did not believe that the continuing turmoil in
agency account assignments, as marketers frenetically hire and fire
shops, contributed to the souring of client-agency relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's an issue any more so than in the past,''
she said, citing the fact that account turnover had been
particularly pronounced in 1996 and 1997 as the relationship
between advertisers and agencies was deemed to be improving.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what clients and agencies can do, Ms. Salz suggested that
they ``set the highest possible standards and insist up front on
only the best,'' because they ``agree that's the most important
thing you can do to create or get terrific work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easier said than done,'' Ms. Salz acknowledged,
especially in such fields as telecommunications, which ``change so
fast, there is no time'' to ``want great advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   And quality is frequently a runnerup to productivity, Ms. Salz
said, particularly now that technology enables work to be produced
faster.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers and agencies must remember, she added, that ``ideas
are still created the old-fashioned way, in people's minds and
emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted in April for Salz Consulting by Thurm
Marketing and Consulting Inc. in Princeton, N.J. Salz Consulting
sponsors training seminars in agency relations and advertising
development for marketers like Clorox Co. and IBM Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
