<HEADER>
A4524 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALL-LIST-TEX     08-20 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-LIST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S TOP 10 FAMILIES 
WITH BASEBALL EXTRA PACKAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Waner _ Paul ``Big Poison'' and Lloyd ``Little Poison'' Waner
played side-by-side in the Pirates' outfield for 13 years. Paul had
a career batting average of .333; Lloyd hit .316. They are the only
two players from the same family in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   2. Alou _ On Sept. 15, 1963, the San Francisco Giants had an
outfield of Jesus, Felipe and Matty Alou. All three had good
careers as solid-hitting outfielders. Matty won a batting title in
1966 with the Pirates. Felipe is an excellent manager with the
Expos, and his son, Moises Alou, is an All-Star with the Astros.
Felipe is also the uncle of Mets reliever Mel Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   3. DiMaggio _ There were three brothers from San Francisco,
including Joe, one of the greatest players ever. Dom, who played
for the Boston Red Sox, was almost as good as his brother, but
didn't have his power. Vince, who played for the Pirates, was the
Pete Incaviglia of his time, often leading the league in
strikeouts. He could have been a great opera singer.
</P>
<P>
   4. Boone _ A three-generation All-Star family starting with Ray
Boone, a shortstop with the Indians and Tigers. His son Bob won
seven Gold Gloves as a catcher, and grandson, Bret, was an All-Star
second baseman for the Reds this year. Bret's brother Aaron is also
with the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   5. MacPhail _ They never played, but they had huge impacts as
executives. Larry MacPhail was the original architect of the great
Dodgers dynasty while introducing night baseball and games
broadcast on radio. His son, Lee, recently was inducted into the
Hall of Fame and was the original architect of the great Orioles
dynasty as well as American League president. Grandson Andy won two
World Series as the Twins' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   6. Perry _ There have been many great pitching brothers in
baseball _ the Deans, Niekros, Coveleskis _ but Gaylord and Jim are
the only two who both won Cy Young awards.
</P>
<P>
   7. Griffey _ Ken Griffey Sr. was an All-Star for the Reds. Ken
Griffey Jr. might be the best player of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   8. Bonds _ Bobby and Barry Bonds are the only father-son
combination in history to both be compared to Willie Mays.
</P>
<P>
   9. Alomar _ Sandy Alomar was an All-Star second baseman for the
California Angels, then was followed by two outstanding sons,
catcher Sandy Jr. and Roberto, one of the best second basemen in
baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   10. Stottlemyre _ Father Mel and son Todd have combined for 284
victories (through Wednesday), the most by any father-son
combination. Mel was one of the best pitchers in Yankees history,
but had the misfortune of playing for them in the bleak years of
1964-74 when the franchise was unusually ordinary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
