<HEADER>
A4527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TIMING-1STLD-     08-20 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TIMING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING OF CRUISE MISSILE ATTACK COMES UNDER FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: Adding two paragraphs at the end from RNC chairman and Steve
Forbes) (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG and MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most lawmakers, even ardent foes of President
Clinton, rallied behind his decision Thursday to attack suspected
terrorist targets in Afghanistan and Sudan. But at least two asked
whether it was a calculated effort to change the subject from an
improper sexual relationship to national security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the president's personal difficulties this week, it is
legitimate to question the timing of this action,'' said Sen. Dan
Coats, R-Ind., a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee and
a longtime Clinton critic.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise missile strikes, retaliation for the Aug. 7 terrorist
bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, occurred less
than three days after Clinton reversed seven months of denials and
admitted to a relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky that he said ``was not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The admission was a turning point in Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr's investigation of whether Clinton committed perjury and
obstructed justice in an effort to cover up the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Coats said of the military attack that took place as Lewinsky
was completing her second appearance before a federal grand jury
here: ``Once the president has broken the bond of trust with the
American people, as he has done with his repeated lies, it raises
questions about everything he does or does not do.''
</P>
<P>
   Coats said the attack could be an effort to divert attention
away from the Lewinsky matter by a chief executive ``desperately
trying to hold onto his job.'' He added, ``The timing of this was
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said he supported the president but
stressed, ``I want to know more about the reasons and especially
the reasons for doing it now. ... Questions will be raised around
the world on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen rejected the notion that the
timing of the attack was a diversionary tactic like the one
depicted in the Hollywood film ``Wag the Dog.'' In the movie, a
fictional president embroiled in a sex scandal allows his aides to
manufacture a military crisis to divert public attention and win
reelection.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, asked about a possible analogy to the movie, said at a
news conference that ``the only motivation driving this action
today was our absolute obligation to protect the American people
from terrorist activities. That is the sole motivation. No other
consideration has been involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Most GOP lawmakers supported Clinton's decision and didn't
question the timing.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said the action was ``the
right thing to do at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said, ``The United
States has an absolute duty to attack terrorism where it lives and
breeds, in order to prevent future attacks on American citizens
around the world. The American people stand united in the face of
terrorism. The men and women who undertook this mission deserve our
praise and prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., one of the Senate's most respected
voices on defense issues, called the strikes a ``welcome response''
to the Aug. 7 embassy bombings that killed 257 people, including 12
Americans, and injured more than 5,000. ``The president did the
right thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, often a harsh Clinton critic, praised the
military action as ``clearly designed to strike at the heart of a
terrorist network that has the blood of American citizens on its
hands and which was planning further attacks on U.S. nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said, ``Thank you, Mr. President. ...
Let's wage a war against terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., called the retaliation ``bold and
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   But a strong Clinton critic outside Congress, conservative
politician and Reagan administration official Oliver L. North,
said, ``Given what we know about this commander-in-chief, one has
to wonder if the theme song for this operation comes from the score
of `Braveheart' or `Wag the Dog.'''
</P>
<P>
   However, Stephen Hess, a senior fellow at the nonpartisan
Brookings Institution who has often criticized Clinton, said, ``I
don't feel particularly cynical about this. We just have to give
the president the benefit of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Other longtime Clinton critics, Republican National Chairman Jim
Nicholson and GOP presidential candidate Steve Forbes, also
supported the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that America's enemies understand that the
American people are united in the fight against international
terrorism,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
