</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS HAS ANGELS WINNING, NOT WHINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Houston Astros went looking for a manager before the
1994 season, they asked one particular question to every candidate.
</P>
<P>
   What would you do if the club had to cut payroll and trade away
all our best players?
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates mumbled and stumbled around the question. Terry
Collins, so the story goes, looked his future employers in the eye
and said, ``I'd win.''
</P>
<P>
   Such bravado might seem trite, but Collins is doing exactly that
as manager of the Anaheim Angels. Their ownership seems
indifferent, the general manager has been almost ineffectual, their
best player (Tim Salmon) has a bad foot, their second-best player
(Darin Erstad) recently came off the disabled list and three-fifths
of the starting rotation has been on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Angels continue to hold off the Rangers and cling to
first place in the American League West. There is no sign of an
imminent collapse despite rumors of discontent when the Angels
failed to make a deal on the July 31 nonwaiver trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they heed their manager, who keeps saying, ``We can sit
here and pout or we can go out and get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels did receive some good news Wednesday when Jack
McDowell made his first start in three months and pitched seven
scoreless innings in a 2-0 victory against the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels couldn't have been happier if Disney had announced
they were trading the merchandising rights to Grumpy, Dopey and
Sneezy to the Blue Jays for Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no telling how Jack will feel two days from now or
five days from now.'' Collins told reporters after Wednesday's
game. ``But you can't ask for anything more from a guy who hasn't
pitched in almost three months than what he gave tonight. He did it
on guts and savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad news, though, continues to follow the Angels. Pitcher Ken
Hill, who had elbow surgery earlier this year, was supposed to come
off the disabled list and pitch Sunday. But he was forced out of
his last medical-rehabilitation start with more pain in the elbow,
and the Angels don't know when he'll be ready to return.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels need him and all the pitching they can muster up
because they are heading into the most crucial stretch of their
season, one even worse than the Rangers' recent road trip. The
Angels, starting Monday after an all-night flight from the West
Coast, are looking at a 10-game road trip through New York, Boston
and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The jaunt starts with five against the Yankees, including two
makeups of games postponed in April when a beam fell through a
ceiling at Yankee Stadium. While the Angels are enjoying the
sights, sounds and smells of New York City, the Rangers will be
starting a nine-game stretch against the Tigers and White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Logic says the Angels will get the stuffing kicked out of them
in the East, while the Rangers will swat aside those Central
Division losers and soar gracefully off to a division title. Then
they can focus on their real mission, which is to finish with a
better record than the AL Central-leading Cleveland Indians and
avoid the Yankees in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are better than the Angels. They should be better
than the Indians, whose best hitters are either slumping or
injured, and whose best pitchers are suffering from tired arms.
</P>
<P>
   But, as 26 years have proved conclusively, nothing ever comes
easy for the Rangers. A six-game winning streak after the
acquisition of Todd Zeile, Todd Stottlemyre and Royce Clayton
seemed to indicate they were on their way, then they turned around
and lost eight of 10. They have a losing record since the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Collins is not going to let the Angels die. The Rangers will
have to fight this one to the finish and could easily blow it if
they're not careful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
