<HEADER>
A4540 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROBE-LEWINSKY-BOS &LR;      08-20 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROBE-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY SPENDS FIVE MORE HOURS TESTIFYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica S. Lewinsky Thursday answered questions for
five hours before a federal grand jury that is examining whether
her sexual relationship with President Clinton went farther than he
acknowledged. Prosecutors focused on whether Clinton committed
perjury when asked about the former White House intern in a January
deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, making her second appearance before the grand jury,
was expected to expand upon her earlier testimony, reportedly that
Clinton touched private parts of her body, which would contradict
the president's sworn denial of such action. Some Republicans have
said Clinton should resign or be impeached if it is proven he
committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, prosecutors Thursday obtained samples of Clinton's
DNA, which will be compared to a stain found on one of Lewinsky's
dresses. The possibility that investigators would find a match
apparently played a role in convincing Clinton to admit Monday that
he had an inappropriate relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton's DNA matches the dress stain, it could provide
further evidence that the president had a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky and contradict his earlier testimony that he couldn't
recall meeting with her privately.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, wearing a gray dress and looking somber, did not talk
to a large press gathering at the federal courthouse before or
after her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``She answered all questions truthfully and completely,''
Lewinsky spokeswoman Judy Smith said about Thursday's testimony.
``Ms. Lewinsky is really looking forward to beginning the process
of rebuilding her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his address to the nation on Monday, indicated that
he did not commit perjury in his January deposition because his
denial of sexual relations with Lewinsky was ``legally accurate.''
Clinton aides have said that means the president had some type of
sex with Lewinsky, reportedly oral sex, that did not fall within
the definition of sexual relations used in the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   While White House officials decry this intense focus on the
nature of the sex between Clinton and Lewinsky, legal analysts said
Clinton ensured the matter would come under scrutiny by saying
Monday night that his initial denial of sexual relations was
legally accurate.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the definition of sexual relations as defined during
Clinton's deposition in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit:
``contact with genitalia, anus, groin, breast, inner thigh, or
buttocks of any person with an intent to arouse or gratify the
sexual desire of any person.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Clinton's aides suggested that if Clinton
received oral sex from Lewinsky but never touched certain parts of
her body, that would be outside the definition of sexual relations
used in the deposition. But in her Aug. 6 testimony, Lewinsky
reportedly said Clitnon touched her breasts and other parts of her
body.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, such as Representative Bill McCollum of
Florida, have said that if Clinton lied in the Jones deposition
about his sexual contact with Lewinsky, then he should be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   But others, mostly Democrats, have said if Clinton lied about
his sexual contact with Lewinsky in the Jones deposition, it would
not amount to perjury because the judge ruled that testimony
regarding the former intern was not ``material'' to the Jones
lawsuit and dismissed the case.
</P>
<P>
   This has led to some awkward explanations of Clinton's possible
defense. Representative Martin Meehan, the Massachusetts Democrat
who sits on the House Judiciary Committee that hears impeachment
cases, said Clinton could have lied without committing perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lying and perjury aren't the same thing from a legal
perspective,'' Meehan said earlier this week. ``Perjury requires it
be a material fact to a judicial'' proceeding. ``That doesn't mean
he didn't lie. He admitted that he lied to the American people. But
you would have to look and see what the standard was in the
deposition. Legally, by definition, perjury requires that there be
a material lie to a material fact.''
</P>
<P>
   While there remains much argument over whether Clinton's
statement in the Jones deposition could be perjury, there is
widespread agreement that the president would be in danger of
impeachment if he lied before the grand jury on Monday. Thus,
Starr, in recalling Lewinsky before the grand jury, wanted to
examine Clinton's statements.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in addition to focusing on whether Clinton lied about the
nature of his sexual relations with Lewinsky in the grand jury
testimony, wanted to explore Lewinsky's knowledge of whether the
president tried to cover up their relationship. The grand jury, for
example, has examined whether Clinton urged Lewinsky to return
gifts to presidential secretary Betty Currie in order to conceal
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton testified Monday that he did not order Currie to obtain
the gifts from Lewinsky, The New York Times reported Thursday. The
gifts, which included a dress, gold brooch and hatpin, had been
subpoenaed as exhibits in the Jones case. Lewinsky testified that
Clinton told her that if she no longer had the gifts she couldn't
turn them over, The Times said. The day after that conversation,
Currie telephoned Lewinsky and said she understood Lewinsky had
some gifts to return, the newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
