<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Aug. 21. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S. (Washington) _ Ledeall on the attacks: President
Clinton returns to Washington, announces the attacks on the
terrorist bases. How and when the decision was made. By James
Bennet. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   The stories are running under a 4-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   With satellite photos, maps showing attack targets, timeline
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ In her second and likely final
appearance before a grand jury here, Monica Lewinsky offers more
specifics about her sexual relationship with President Clinton as
prosecutors sought to draw distinctions between her testimony and
that of the President. By Richard L. Berke and Don Van Natta.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ The evidence the administration
had for attacking the Sudan installation and bin Laden's base in
Afghanistan. By James Risen. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The most cherished axiom of
American diplomacy is that politics stops at the water's edge,
meaning that the opposition party supports the president when
missiles are flying. Today it worked, more or less. The bulk of
congressional leaders, from Speaker Newt Gingrich to such reliable
Clinton critics as Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina, rallied
around the commander-in-chief, with Gingrich declaring: ``I think
based on what I know that it was the right thing to do at the right
time.'' But in the surreal and cinematic atmosphere that suffused
Washington this week, a handful of voices on Capitol Hill cried
foul. By Todd S. Purdum. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-BINLADEN (Washington) _ How Osama bin Laden, the youngest
son of a construction magnate from Yemen, became the world's most
feared sponsor of terrorism. The religious and ideological roots of
his rage lie in the 1980s, when he worked side by side with the CIA
backing the Afghan rebels. When that battle was over, he and his
fellow holy warriors, past and present _ having defeated the
British in the 19th century and the Soviets in the 20th _ went to
work on the United States. By Tim Weiner. (The story has moved in
``i'' news file.) With map.
</P>
<P>
   UNABOMBER-REWARD (Washington) _ The Justice Department gave a $1
million reward to David Kaczynski for turning in his brother,
Theodore, as the Unabomber. By James Brooke. (Scheduled to move by
9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-1918-FLU (Spitsbergen, Norway) _ Six coal miners who have
been buried in permafrost since falling victim to the Spanish flu
of 1918 are being carefully exhumed this week. Scientists plan to
take ``core samples'' from the bodies, in hope of building a
genetic profile of the mysterious virus that killed 20 million to
40 million people before vanishing. By John Noble Wilford. (The
story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
