<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-ALBANIA-NYT &LR;      08-20 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-ALBANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AGENTS SAID TO THWART BOMB PLOT AGAINST U.S. EMBASSY IN
ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S., ATTACK-BINLADEN, ATTACK-CONGRESS,
ATTACK-SECURITY, ATTACK-U.S., ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-MILITARY,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-ASSESS, ATTACK-WAG) (JT) 
 By JOHN KIFNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ In a series of lightning raids with the
Albanian secret police this summer, American intelligence agents
appear to have thwarted a bomb plot against the American Embassy
here. They also seem to have broken up a ring of Egyptian Islamic
terrorists using this nation's anarchy to set up a base.
</P>
<P>
   The raids netted five suspects wanted in Egypt, some of whom
were facing death sentences. At least two of them have been
extradited to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   The raids, which began in June and ended last week, after the
terror bombings in Africa, seized material that included plans for
bombing the embassy here, according to Albanian security officials.
</P>
<P>
   Acting after the bombing of their embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania, American officials responded to the threat by destroying
embassy communications equipment last week, one of the steps
mandated when an embassy might be attacked by terrorists, an
American security agent said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether the planned attack here was part of, or
even provoked, by the African terrorism, but like the embassies in
Africa, Albania offered a soft target, since the country has a
fragile infrastructure in which the Americans were seen as friendly
to the government.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the United States sent in some 200 Marines, 10 Navy
Seals and a number of other plainclothes security men to evacuate
dependents and nonessential personnel and guard the handful
remaining in the gated American residential compound, a tiny slice
of suburbia amid the brutal peasant poverty here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told there is a high threat out there,'' said Maj.
Frank Carroll, the commander of the marines from the 22d Marine
Expeditionary Unit who were diverted from a planned NATO training
exercise last Friday night to protect the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged terrorists operated under cover of an infusion of
Islamic proselytizers from Egypt, Saudi Arabia and other Arab
countries, many of them fundamentalists. They have flocked here to
build hospitals, schools and orphanages, under condition that they
can also build mosques.
</P>
<P>
   Albania is nominally two-thirds Muslim as a heritage of the
Ottoman Empire, but there are also substantial Roman Catholic and
Greek Orthodox populations. But the nation historically has not
always taken religion seriously. A local proverb translates
roughly, ``Religion follows the sword,'' or political power.
</P>
<P>
   And Albania virtually fell apart in March 1997 when the collapse
of a pyramid scheme bankrupted much of the population, leading to
rioting, the dissolution of the army, looting of weapons and the
collapse of the government.
</P>
<P>
   In that milieu, officials here say, Islamic Jihad and other
groups took the opportunity to set up operations in a place with
porous borders and few, if any, internal controls.
</P>
<P>
   The news of the raids here and of their American direction was
discovered broken by the scuffling police reporters of the
country's two biggest newspapers. The Albanian authorities,
embarrassed and worried about retaliation, have clammed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct told me the story was really a big story,'' said
Alfred Peza, editor of Gazeta Shqiptare, savoring the moment at
Fideli's, a crowded cafe. ``The police regretted it the next day.
Maybe in the excitement of telling the story of the good work they
had done, they went too far. The next day, the police bosses
cracked down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, neighbors at one of the sites of the raids, an
alley off Myslym Shyri Street, near police headquarters, confirmed
the details of American supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Several English-speaking foreigners carrying walkie-talkies
stood in the alley directing the operation while the Albanian
secret police searched the upstairs apartment, said the neighbors,
none of whom, after decades of the Communist rule, would give their
names.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Albanian secret police, known as Shik,
declined a request for an interview Thursday, indicating that the
Americans, with whom he was still working closely, had forcefully
expressed the position that too much had been said already.
</P>
<P>
   But in an earlier interview with an Albanian newspaper, the
secret police chief, Fatos Khosi, described the issue of Islamic
fundamentalism as ``a very delicate theme.''
</P>
<P>
   But he told the daily Koha Jone that Albania was vulnerable to
infiltration, saying: ``It is a poor country, ready to accept aid.
Its borders are relatively easy to cross, and this has made it a
relatively comfortable country for people that are wanted in their
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous government of President Sari Berisha, a casualty of
the pyramid scheme collapse, had what was known as a ``cracked
door'' policy in which even people with dubious or forged
credentials could enter Albania in hopes of bringing currency into
the poorest country of Europe. Albania was totally isolated for
nearly half a century under the late dictator Enver Hoxha, a
Stalinist decades after Stalin, whose legacy is crumbling circular
concrete barriers _ against anybody _ scattered every few hundred
yards all over the landscape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
