<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBINGS-EXPERTS-HNS &LR;      08-20 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBINGS-EXPERTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY BOMBINGS WILL COMBAT TERRORISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RICK KARLIN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Thursday's bombings of targets in Sudan and
Afghanistan represents a new paradigm for how the United States
will combat terrorism, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes are a clear demonstration that the United States
can, without the slow coalition-building of the Gulf War, reach
deep inside foreign borders and up the ante in a war of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have with the terrorist groups is a major change in
the nature of war,'' said Tom Kelly, a Siena College history
professor who follows military issues. By launching missiles from
sea with no risk to U.S. troops, the strikes sent a message to the
effect that ``we can kill a whole bunch of you without risking any
of our own people,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the post-Cold War era now,'' said Steven Hoffmann, a
Skidmore College political science professor. Terrorism, he said,
is ``the primary warfare that we in the U.S. have to worry about
right now.''Battling terrorists requires a shift in military and
political strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are trying to combat an amorphous opponent,'' said Abdo
Baaklini, director of the Center for Legislative Development at the
University at Albany's Rockefeller College.
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 7 bombings of U.S. embassies in Tanzania and Kenya
represent a new style of terrorism-driven warfare, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``In (most of) the 20th Century, the nation-state had a monopoly
on organized violence. Now we are looking at organized violence by
ethnic groups, religious groups and terrorists groups,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
<P>
   Osama bin Laden, suspected of masterminding the embassy
bombings, embodies this kind of post-Cold War enemy.
</P>
<P>
   The embassy bombings represent what military tacticians call an
``asymmetric'' strategy in which the attacker doesn't try to match
the enemy in pound-for-pound firepower or troop strength, said
Hoffmann.
</P>
<P>
   This shift requires a change in the way the United States fights
back. The U.S. airstrike against one of bin Laden's suspected bases
sends a message that it won't be easy to hide and that the U.S.
will strike back wherever it can, despite the lack of clear battle
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says, `they cannot hide and we're not going to wait until a
court proves who is responsible,' '' noted Baaklini. ``When you are
trying to combat an amorphous opponent ... you widen the circle
sometimes, and you narrow it other times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've done is the only thing available,'' Kelly said of
Thursday's attack. ``They have said to him, `yes, we can touch you
and, yes, we can defend ourselves.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly added that military and intelligence planners have long
known that the factory in the Sudanese capital of Khartoum was
suspected of harboring chemical weapon components.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they satellite-viewed this for a long time,'' Kelly
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
