<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WARNS AMERICANS ABROAD TO BE MORE CAUTIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S., ATTACK-BINLADEN, ATTACK-CONGRESS,
ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-U.S., ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-MILITARY,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-ASSESS, ATTACK-WAG.) (bl) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States on Thursday issued a new
worldwide warning to Americans and diplomatic personnel ``to
exercise much greater caution than usual'' following U.S. military
strikes against suspected terrorist targets in Afghanistan and
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. embassies, already on alert, were told of the raids and
warned to take precautions simultaneously with the cruise-missile
strikes themselves, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As military planning accelerated over the last week, U.S.
officials, concerned about reprisals, were already removing
non-essential personnel and family members from vulnerable U.S.
embassies in Albania, Pakistan, Eritrea and other possible targets
for retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the measures were ordered, Aug. 11, four days after
the East Africa bombings, U.S. officials said they were responding
to threats and to protect less-secure U.S. embassies that had not
been brought up to current standards because of budgetary
constraints. But that was also the day of a meeting of top Cabinet
officials in the White House to discuss the evidence against the
alleged terrorist ringleader Osama bin Laden and military plans to
attack him.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said Thursday that the embassy staff reductions,
and the suspension of some embassy operations, were part of the
military planning process, to limit U.S. vulnerability should Mr.
bin Laden and his allies try themselves to retaliate. Other
embassies affected included Malaysia, Uganda, Egypt and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the time said they could not recall a similar
instance when several U.S. diplomatic installations, which often
get diffuse threats, suspended operations simultaneously. And U.S.
non-diplomatic personnel working with charities and other
non-governmental organizations in Afghanistan were also advised to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   As the week went on, intelligence showed planning for new
attacks. ``We had very specific information about very specific
threats with respect to very specific targets,'' said National
Security Adviser Samuel Berger on Thursday. ``You will have noted
over the past week that we have closed certain embassies, we have
drawn other embassies down, we have taken other measures to protect
American citizens abroad, so that in addition to the general
expressed intention of this organization to perpetrate terrorist
incidents against the United States, there was very specific
information and very reliable information.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing everything we can to protect Americans
everywhere,'' said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said,
without providing details. But she emphasized that Thursday's air
strikes are only ``a part of a long-term battle against terrorism
and the terrorists who have, in fact, declared war on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Albright said: ``What I think is very important for the
American people to understand is that there may in fact be
retaliatory actions. We are very concerned about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials said Thursday that in addition to obvious
messages and cautions, U.S. intelligence, law enforcement and
military officials have also been working with other countries to
disrupt plans for attacks on U.S. embassies _ Albania in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials were reluctant to identify other countries,
saying they did not want to give terrorists either ``a game plan''
or ``an indication of what we know,'' one senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   New drawdowns are expected from U.S. embassies in Central Asia
and the Caucasus, like Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan,
Azerbaijan, Georgia and Tajikistan, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's worldwide caution intensified earlier warnings of
Aug. 16 and Aug. 7. Thursday's announcement urged Americans to take
``additional and enhanced precautions'' in Afghanistan, Iraq, Iran,
Libya and North Korea, where there are no American diplomatic
posts.
</P>
<P>
   It reminded Americans that embassy operations have already been
suspended in Somalia, Sudan, Guinea-Bissau and the Congo, currently
ripped by a rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the recent U.S. military strikes against terrorist
targets in Afghanistan and Sudan, and possible threats to Americans
and U.S. interests overseas, the State Department urges U.S.
citizens traveling or residing abroad to review their security
practices, to remain alert to the changing situation and to
exercise much greater caution than usual,'' the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are in a very sober mood here and throughout the
government,'' one administration official said. ``You heard
Albright saying it isn't over and retaliation is possible, and the
American people have to understand that. This is not the end of the
story and people are keenly aware of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Unocal, a U.S. oil company with worldwide interests, itself took
defensive steps Thursday, announcing that it would suspend all
activities involving a proposed natural-gas pipeline that would
link Turkmenistan to Pakistan through Afghanistan. The action was
taken ``in light of U.S. government actions Thursday,'' said a
Unocal representative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
