<SLUG> BC-ARNOLD-CENTURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD LOSES CENTURY 21 ACCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Arnold Communications, Boston's biggest advertising
agency, lost one of its biggest clients Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Century 21 Real Estate Corp., a New Jersey-based company that
spends about $40 million a year on advertising, said Thursday it
had parted ways with Arnold and hired Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS of New
York as its new agency of record,
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, which had estimated billings of about $750 million in
1997 and whose big clients include Volkswagen of America, regional
franchise cooperatives of McDonald's Corp., and Ocean Spray
Cranberries Inc., was hired as Century 21's ad agency last
September.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Arnold could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going forward, we need to uniquely position the Century 21
System in the minds of consumers such that the brand is
differentiated, thus gaining a real competitive advantage,'' said
Steve Savino, Century 21's senior vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In an informal ad agency review, Lowe &AMP; Partners ``was chosen as
a result of their strength and track record in managing brands for
change,'' Savino said.
</P>
<P>
   Savino said he assumed his job at Century 21 six weeks ago. At a
previous job with Heublein Inc., the wine-and-spirits company,
Savino said he enjoyed a three-year relationship with Lowe &AMP;
Partners between 1993 and 1996; during that time, he said he had
become an admirer of the agency's work.
</P>
<P>
   Of his new job at Century 21, Savino said: ``When I took this
job six weeks ago, I took a clean sheet of paper to look ahead and
see where we should be going.''
</P>
<P>
   Savino said he concluded that Century 21 ``needed a different
approach to how we advertise our brand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were happy with Arnold's `More power to you' campaign,'' he
said. ``But after we seeded that message, we felt we needed more of
an image-building campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   With $740 million in billings, Lowe &AMP; Partners is part of the
Lowe Group, which is owned by the Interpublic Group of Cos., a New
York holding company that recently acquired Hill Holliday Connors
Cosmopulos of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Clients of Lowe &AMP; Partners include Mercedes-Benz, Coca-Cola Co.,
and Gillette Co. brands Braun and Oral-B.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Arnold was acquired by Snyder Communications Inc. of
Bethesda, Md.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
