<HEADER>
A4578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENVER-BY-THE-SEA-NYT     08-20 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENVER-BY-THE-SEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OCEAN _ SOME VERSION OF IT, ANYWAY _ MOVES INLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Tenn., N.M.)  (smw) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With the Rocky Mountains looming to the west, plumbers
at Ocean Journey, a $93 million aquarium scheduled to open next
summer, are installing the ultimate faux beach: an acrylic
walk-through tube that will be pounded with waves of salt water
while floors vibrate and hidden atomizers spray sea scents.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, beach volleyball enthusiasts are flocking to The
Island _ a newly opened warehouse filled with 10,000 tons of
imported sand and decorated with palm trees and seascape murals.
And just north of Denver, about 4,000 visitors frolic daily in 3.5
million gallons of water at Water World, one of the nation's
largest water parks, spread over 64 acres of once-arid plains.
</P>
<P>
   Denver, landlocked and 1,000 road miles from the nearest ocean,
has always suffered from a mild municipal inferiority complex. Yes,
it is the gateway to some of the nation's most dramatic mountains,
but where is the beach? This year, the Mile High City is fighting
back against geographic determinism.
</P>
<P>
   In early August, Ocean Journey received its first shipment of
1,000 tropical fish, probably the largest number of salt water fish
seen here since 65 million B.C., when an inland sea covered this
patch of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For kids who have never been to the ocean, this is going to be
great,'' Judy Petersen-Fleming, one of the founders of Ocean
Journey, said recently as she led visitors through the three-story
shell of the aquarium, on Water Street. ``There will be coral in
front of them, sharks overhead.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver appears to be leading a heartland trend toward creating
ersatz oceans. Half a million people, or one out of four residents
of greater Denver, are expected to swim, sun and play this summer
at Water World, which calls its latest attraction the Colorado Wave
_ ``the world's first dual ocean wave surfing simulator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Best water park I've been to, and I've been to about 20,''
said Jim Anderson, a local resident, after a day at the park with
his 8-year-old son, Mark. Anderson, who vacationed in Hawaii last
May, said he preferred the park's big, simulated waves over the
real thing. ``You get a great one every five minutes _ that's
better than the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, attendance at the nation's water parks has
doubled, to 61 million last year from 30 million in 1987. Initial
figures for this summer show a continued increase, according to the
World Waterpark Association, a trade group in Overland Park, Kan.,
near the nation's geographical center.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the water park boom has taken place in the nation's
interior, said Marci McNeal, spokeswoman for the group, which
represents the nation's 964 water parks. Similarly, aquariums are
moving inland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, aquariums tend to be in coastal settings,''
said Charles Redmon, a senior partner for Cambridge Seven
Associates, the world's largest aquarium design firm. But in recent
years, Redmon said, his company has designed an aquarium for
Chattanooga, Tenn., a river city, and conducted studies for
aquariums in Denver and the Great Lakes area. It is now working on
a rain forest garden for Des Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an aquarium opened in Albuquerque, N.M. In Salt Lake
City, planners are studying a proposal for a $40 million aquarium
that would open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the sand and the waves have come to Denver,
marketers are very aware that many residents can still be lured to
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``United Airlines is thrilled to help bring the ocean to
Colorado,'' said Roger Gibson, the airline's regional vice
president, when he gave Ocean Journey a $1.8 million check. What
the executive of Denver's dominant airline left unsaid was that
United would also be thrilled to pack its nine daily direct flights
to San Diego, the nearest beach city to Denver, slightly over two
hours by jet.
</P>
<P>
   At Ocean Journey, visitors will follow the trail of the Colorado
River, from drops dripping from icicles on Colorado's Continental
Divide to the warm waters of Mexico's Sea of Cortez. Thus, it is no
accident that the Sea of Cortez exhibit is sponsored by Mexicana
Airlines, which maintains direct flights between Denver and three
Sea of Cortez resort towns: Los Cabos, Mazatlan and Puerto
Vallarta.
</P>
<P>
   So although people fly from around the nation to ski in the
Colorado Rockies every winter, a small counter-movement of
Coloradans fly 1,100 miles south to Mexico's Pacific beaches.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some of Mexico's Pacific resort villages are starting
to look like Denver-by-the-sea, with Coloradans having their own
condominiums and volleyball tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people who visit the beach each year, but
live in the mountains,'' said Tom Davenport, who started The Island
after taking ``volleyball vacation'' groups to the beaches of
Puerto Vallarta and Ixtapa.
</P>
<P>
   To give barefoot players a tropical feeling in the depths of a
Colorado winter, The Island will use gas heaters to warm the air
and infrared heaters to warm the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``People wanted to do 12 months a year, what they could do only
4 months a year,'' Davenport said.
</P>
</TEXT>
