<SLUG> BC-BARON-BEAR-STEARNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDER HALTS TESTIMONY IN CASES ON BARON'S COLLAPSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prosecutors have been granted a court order that
temporarily halts witness testimony in cases regarding the failure
of the A.R. Baron brokerage firm, a signal that a grand jury
investigation into the role that Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. played in the
collapse is reaching a critical point.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morgenthau, the Manhattan district attorney, applied on
Wednesday for the order, formally a stay, and Justice E.J.
McLaughlin of New York state Supreme Court granted it. The order
expires Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Under the stay, neither the New York Stock Exchange nor the
National Association of Securities Dealers may take or allow
testimony of witnesses in a variety of securities arbitration cases
concerning the 1996 failure of A.R. Baron, whose founders stole $75
million from investors from 1991 to 1996. Calling the firm a
criminal enterprise, Morgenthau's office won convictions of 14 A.R.
Baron employees last year.
</P>
<P>
   The clearing of Baron's customer trades and its back-office
administration were handled by a Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. subsidiary,
Bear Stearns Clearing Corp. As Baron's clearing firm, Bear, Stearns
also guaranteed customers' trades at Baron.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's stay applies to all arbitration cases involving
Baron, and all that name as respondents Bear, Stearns and Hanifen
Imhoff, another firm that had acted as clearing agent for Baron.
The district attorney could seek to extend the stay on Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bear, Stearns declined through a spokesman to comment on the
stay.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal and securities lawyers said applying for such an order
was significant. ``When a prosecutor's office seeks a stay in
testimony in related civil matters, it is significant to the extent
that it indicates a serious government prosecution is ongoing,''
said Andrew Levander, a partner at Swidler, Berlin, Shereff and
Friedman in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It also indicates that the district attorney's office has
information that it does not want to share with adversaries, such
as Bear, Stearns. Had the arbitration proceedings not been stayed,
Bear, Stearns would have access to much of the information that
prosecutors have secured in testimony, even perhaps from former
Baron employees who are cooperating with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, court documents filed by John Moscow, an assistant
district attorney, stated that if the cases were not stayed, ``it
would adversely, and seriously, harm the prosecution of future
indictments.'' The documents also say that the grand jury
investigation is continuing into the activities of other people and
organizations involved with Baron and that a determination as to
who, if anyone, should be charged is expected before the end of
October.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow could not be reached to comment further on the stay.
</P>
<P>
   A.R. Baron's collapse shed a spotlight onto the immensely
profitable but secretive business of clearing securities
transactions, a business that Bear, Stearns had dominated. Clearing
firms not only process securities transactions and other paperwork,
but they also provide capital to small brokerage houses, allowing
them to do business on a relatively small deposit.
</P>
<P>
   After Baron's fall, Morgenthau's office and other securities
regulators began to scrutinize clearing firms' roles in
small-capitalization stock fraud at brokerage houses. A.R. Baron,
for example, had had many run-ins with regulators, yet Bear,
Stearns continued to clear its trades.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers close to the investigation into Baron say that
settlement talks between Bear, Stearns and the district attorney's
office have been continuing. That the stay expires at the end of
October may be a signal from prosecutors that any settlement must
be reached by then.
</P>
</TEXT>
