<HEADER>
A4588 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-N     08-20 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE OVER QUESTIONING DELAYS MICROSOFT ANTITRUST TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sm) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge Thursday pushed back the starting
date of the antitrust trial against Microsoft Corp. by two weeks,
to Sept. 26, while lawyers for the company and the Justice
Department bickered over where and how pretrial questioning of Bill
Gates, Microsoft's chairman, would take place.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a lawyer representing several news
organizations, including The New York Times, asked for an expedited
review of an appeals court order on Wednesday that the deposition
of Gates be taken behind closed doors. Wednesday's order stayed a
ruling by the trial judge in the case that under federal antitrust
law, depositions had to be taken publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matter is still very much in doubt,'' said Lee Levine, the
news media lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is hearing the
government's case against Microsoft in U.S. District Court here,
reluctantly ruled that a federal antitrust law left him no
alternative but to open the depositions to the news media and the
public.
</P>
<P>
   That stalled the pretrial preparations, particularly the taking
of depositions from Gates and 16 other Microsoft executives,
leading both the government and the software maker to request a
two-week delay in the start of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Because the appeals court had stayed his ruling until the court
could consider how an antitrust law enacted in 1913 applied to
depositions in this case, Jackson agreed Thursday to delay the
trial and ordered the two sides to resume taking depositions as
soon as possible. A Microsoft lawyer, John Warden, told him, ``We
have offered Gates for tomorrow, but the offer was respectfully
declined.''
</P>
<P>
   David Boies, a Justice Department lawyer, responded that
Microsoft had told him that Gates would not be available ``until
next week sometime, but, strangely, after the Court of Appeals
decision, he suddenly became available for tomorrow morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden jumped up to rebut that assertion, but Jackson held up
his hands and declared, ``I don't care.'' Then the Justice
Department said it was willing to question Gates this weekend _ but
here, not in Seattle. A Microsoft spokesman said the company had
not made up its mind whether Gates would agree to travel to
Washington to be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Because this dispute seemed likely to bring a further delay in
the Gates deposition, Levine said he might ask the appeals court to
speed up its review of the open-deposition issue so that the
questioning of Gates might be opened to the news media after all.
</P>
<P>
   In the order issued on Wednesday, a three-judge panel of the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia also scheduled a
hearing on the question of whether the depositions should be
public. But it set the hearing for a date in September well after
all the depositions will have been taken. The appeals court said
videotapes of the depositions could be made public at that point,
if the court so ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Levine said Thursday his clients might ask the Supreme Court to
intervene or might ask the appeals court ``to expedite its
hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, Jay Brown, another lawyer in Levine's office,
said the news organizations had decided to ask the appeals court to
hold its hearing and to make a decision before the trial, so that
videotapes of the depositions could be available to reporters and
others before the trial began.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to The New York Times, the news organizations
involved in the case are The Seattle Times; the cable television
and online news units of Ziff-Davis, a computer trade publisher
owned by Softbank Corp.; and two news services, Reuters and
Bloomberg News.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
