<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-CONGRESS-2TAKE     08-20 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-CONGRESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST MEMBERS OF CONGRESS RLLY AROUND CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S. with photos, map and graphic,
ATTACK-BINLADEN with map, ATTACK-SECURITY, ATTACK-ALBANIA,
ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-MILITARY, ATTACK-ASSESS,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-SUNDAN with map, ATTACK-MEDIA,
ATTACK-WAG.) 
(bl) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The most cherished axiom of U.S. diplomacy is that
politics stops at the water's edge, meaning that political
opponents support the president when missiles are flying. Thursday,
it mostly worked, but the challenge of President Clinton's latest
crisis crystallized when some critics uncharacteristically cried
foul.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of Republican congressional leaders, from House Speaker
Newt Gingrich to such frequent Clinton adversaries as Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., rallied around the commander-in-chief, with Gingrich
declaring: ``I think, based on what I know, that it was the right
thing to do at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the surreal and cinematic atmosphere that suffused
official Washington all week, some voices that would usually be
reliably hawkish suddenly sounded just plain shrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger here is that once a president loses credibility
with the Congress, as this president has through months of lies and
deceit and manipulations and deceptions, stonewalling, it raises
into doubt everything he does and everything he says, and maybe
even everything he doesn't do and doesn't say,'' said Sen. Dan
Coats, R-Ind., who less than 72 hours earlier had called for
Clinton's resignation over the Monica Lewinsky issue.
</P>
<P>
   Coats added, ``I just hope and pray the decision that was made
was made on the basis of sound judgment and made for the right
reasons, and not made because it was necessary to save the
president's job.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., was only slightly softer in
questioning Clinton's air strikes in Afghanistan and the Sudan,
insisting: ``I'm not going to suggest ulterior motives,'' but
adding, ``I especially want to know the reason for doing it now. I
want to know what the evidence was.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the city, there was an inescapable sense Thursday that
the timing of the raid might have been dictated by politics rather
than intelligence information. Among the questions that Defense
Secretary William Cohen faced at the official Pentagon briefing on
the air strikes was whether he had seen ``Wag the Dog,'' the
satirical film in which a president concocts a war to deflect
attention from a sexual encounter with a teen-age girl. He did not
bother to answer, instead insisting, ``The only motivation driving
this action today was our absolute obligation to protect the
American people from terrorist activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said, ``I think that's pure
malarkey,'' when he was asked about any connection between the
cruise-missile strikes and Clinton's political and legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that such questions came up at all was seen as an example
of the damage the Lewinsky matter has done to Clinton's overall
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing people think about is `Why did the president
do this; is it to divert attention from other problems that have
been plaguing the White House?''' asked Rep. Rod Gramms, R-Minn.
``That just shows how much damage has been done to the institution
of the presidency.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even many of those who voiced support of the president reflected
the toll of the Lewinsky matter, taking pains to discount any link
without being asked. ``I know some are suggesting this was a
decision made for other reasons, because of the Monica Lewinsky
investigation,'' Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., told reporters
without prompting. ``To those people I have one thing to say:
Either put up or shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   More typical was Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah _ who had dismissed
Clinton's Monday speech on the Lewinsky matter by saying, ``What a
jerk!''_ said Thursday, ``Now I want to applaud the president. I
want to give him credit for being willing to take this action at
this time. Some people have been critical. The fact is, I doubt
that he would have taken this action without an awful lot of
intelligence backup.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars who have studied the links between past presidents'
foreign policy actions and public opinion found none of that
surprising Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never discovered any kind of factors that negate these
things from happening,'' said Larry Hugick, director of media and
political surveys at Princeton Survey Research Associates in
Princeton, N.J., who has studied presidential approval ratings in
foreign policy crises from Harry Truman to George Bush. ``In a
legitimate crisis where a president is using military force and
it's widely known to the public here, there's a tendency for his
approval rating to rise, and I would expect it would here.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bardes, a professor of political science at the
University of Cincinnati, agreed that presidential performance
ratings have risen for everything from Ronald Reagan's 1986 air
strikes on Libya in retaliation for the bombing of a West Berlin
night club, to his invasion of Grenada, to Bush's invasion of
Panama and his handling of the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is how do you prove success in an atmosphere in
which there is some suspicion of the administration's
forthrightness,'' Professor Bardes said. ``That makes this a
riskier proposition than those other moves. There was an underlying
confidence in the Gulf war that the smart bombs went down the
chimney, and then later we found out it wasn't quite that good. But
now we're in a very funny time period, a very tenuous
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugick noted that even failures, like John F. Kennedy's
disastrous invasion of the Bay of Pigs in 1961, or Jimmy Carter's
failed rescue mission for the Iranian hostages in 1980, have caused
temporary rises in approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his administration, Clinton's policies have often
been driven by polling, though his aides have always been loath to
ascribe any political motives to his foreign policy moves. But when
Clinton finally intervened in Bosnia, after temporizing for his two
years in office, his aides acknowledged that the president began to
appreciate the unilateral power he had over foreign policy even as
a Republican Congress stymied many of his domestic plans, and he
had always hoped that foreign policy would play a more prominent
role in his second term.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., urged Clinton on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration for the last seven months has neglected
compelling national security threats besides this _ Saddam
Hussein's ejection of our inspectors, North Korea building nuclear
weapons again in violation of an agreement, Middle East peace
process stalled, thousands of people being ethnically cleaned in
Kosovo,'' McCain said. ``I hope that the president will not confine
his activities to just this, but to address the other very
compelling problems that also affect our nation's security problems
long-term.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
