A4594 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USSTRIKES-SUDAN-0821-     08-20 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USSTRIKES-SUDAN-0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUDAN:WHAT IT IS, WHAT IT'S LIKE
 &HT;    With USSTRIKES-MAIN-0821.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Africa's largest country is also one of its most
troubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sudan is buffeted by civil war, chronic political instability,
adverse weather, high inflation, a drop in remittances from
(Sudanese living) abroad and counter-productive economic
policies,'' the Central Intelligence Agency reported in 1996. Two
years later, that evaluation still stands.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger is widespread, especially among the Christians and
animists in southern Sudan, a tropical area controlled by a shaky
coalition of anti-government forces who call themselves the
National Democratic Alliance. The northern region, containing the
capital city of Khartoum and most of the Islamic population, is a
flat, sandy area that this month was devastated by floods.
</P>
<P>
   Sporadic negotiations have failed to end the 15-year civil war,
in which 1.5 million have died from fighting or famine.
</P>
<P>
   The long-simmering war has complicated relief efforts by Save
the Children and World Vision Sudan Relief, which last month alone
collected more than a half-million dollars from Americans to help
Sudanese. One German group is thinking of avoiding road blocks by
dropping packages of food out of low-flying cargo planes.
</P>
<P>
   The United States placed Sudan on its list of
terrorist-harboring countries in 1993, and protested further by
moving its embassy operations to neighboring Kenya in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``America incarnates the devil for Muslims,'' according to
Hassan Turabi, an Islamic leader who appears to be the power behind
the transition government's president, Omar Hassan el-Bashir. The
lengthy ``transition'' grows out of a military coup in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The government's policy of waiving visa rules for any visiting
Muslim has made the country a special favorite for people in
political or criminal trouble in their home countries. One of them
was Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born millionaire who has endorsed
terrorist causes, and lived in Sudan before he moved to
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Some facts to keep in mind about Sudan:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Neighbors: In northeast Africa, across the Red Sea from Saudi
Arabia, Sudan has porous borders. East are Eritrea and Ethiopia;
South are Kenya and Uganda; West are the Congo, the Central African
Republic, Chad and Libya; and to the North is Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Size: At roughly 2.5 million square kilometers, Sudan is
one-fourth the size of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Population: Like California, Sudan has about 33 million
residents.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ethnic groups: Black 52 percent, Arab 39 percent, and Beja 6
percent, plus 3 percent foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Languages: Arabic is the official language. But many African
languages and dialects are spoken, and the former British colony
still has many English speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
