<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4603 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS &LR;      08-20 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEMMI IDENTIFIES FBI AGENT WHO WARNED BULGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On the witness stand in federal court Thursday,
gangster-turned-informant Stephen Flemmi explained for the first
time Thursday how his longtime criminal sidekick James ``Whitey''
Bulger was able to leave town before the law came calling: he was
tipped off by FBI supervisor John Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Answering the question that has lingered since last summer _
when Flemmi first claimed in an affidavit that someone in the FBI
gave him and Bulger a head start _ Flemmi laid the blame for at the
feet of Morris, a now-retired agent who earlier this year admitted
taking payoffs from the criminal partners.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly four hours, the career criminal whose double life
exposed the shadowy world where lawmen and outlaws collude
described three decades of being alerted to investigations and
indictments _ the price, he claimed, for helping the FBI bring down
the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be protected and we would not be prosecuted for
anything we did on their behalf, at their behest,'' said Flemmi,
who was unmasked as an informant last spring, shortly before he
dragged the murky methods of the FBI into the glare of the
courtroom to try and get charges against him dropped.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowning defense witness in months-long hearings, Flemmi
hopes to convince federal judge Mark L. Wolf to drop extortion and
racketeering charges brought against him, Bulger and the local
Mafia hierachy in 1995 because of the deal they had with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In April, testifying under immunity, Morris denied he warned
Bulger and Flemmi about the January 1995 indictments. But he
confessed to taking $7,000 in payoffs from the criminal pair,
admitted he warned Flemmi to avoid a bookmaker under investigation,
and helped Bulger and Flemmmi dodge indictments for fixing horse
races.
</P>
<P>
   But Flemmi said Morris, who retired from the FBI at the end of
1995, was not the only bureau agent or supervisor looking out for
him. Among Flemmi's claims Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   _ Former FBI organized crime supervisor James Ring, &UR;  &LR; Morris'
successor, phoned Flemmi at his mother's house in December 1984 to
let Flemmi know his phone and that of his associate, George
Kaufman, were going to be tapped as part of an investigation by the
US Drug Enforcement Administration and Quincy police. The
investigation collapsed four months later after Bulger found a bug
in his car.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ring, according to Flemmi, told Bulger in October 1986 that
Boston police Lt. James Cox &UR;  &LR; who was cooperating with the FBI in a
probe of police corruption was ``wired'' _ a warning for Bulger to
stay away.
</P>
<P>
   -- Former FBI agent H. Paul Rico phoned Flemmi early one morning
in September 1969 and told him he was about to be indicted for
blowing up the car of a Boston attorney, Flemmi said, ``and
suggested that me and my friend leave immediately.'' After four
years on the lam, Flemmi said, Rico convinced him to return to
Boston. A federal fugitive warrant for him was withdrawn, Flemmi
said, through the efforts of a former FBI handler, Dennis Condon.
</P>
<P>
   -- Former agent John Connolly, Flemmi's longtime handler,
confirmed to him that he and Bulger were targets in a South Boston
drug investigation in 1988 and 1989. Connolly also allegedly shared
the identity of other informants with Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bulger learned about a listening device planted in a garage
near North Station where they conducted criminal business from
Connolly, who Flemmi said conveyed the message from Jeremiah O'
Sullivan, then the head of the New England Organized Crime Strike
Force. Flemmi said he also learned about the bug from now-deceased
State Trooper John Naimovich, who was acquitted in June 1989 of
leaking confidential information to an informant.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone Thursday, Ring, who testified for 10 days
earlier this summer, had no comment on Flemmi's testimony. He said
the ``appropriate, professional response'' was to say nothing since
Wolf had not yet ruled in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But Flemmi's allegations, both revived and new, brought a swift
and united response from US Attorney Donald K. Stern and Barry W.
Mawn, the special agent in charge of the Boston office of the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Stern and Mawn had requested an investigation into Flemmi's
claims by the Justice Department and the FBI when they first
surfaced last summer. That report has never been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a federal prosecutor from Connecticut has been named
to investigate whether present or past FBI officials engaged in
criminal misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Stern continued to insist that the actions of rogue agents did
not provide Flemmi or his co-defendants with a valid legal basis
for challenging the charges brought against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a court were to bar such a prosecution, it would be saying
that such a deal, if it was made, was one which the law should
recognize,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very frustrating,'' said Mawn, who took over the
Boston office of the FBI two years ago. ``It does anger us
somewhat'' because ``this is activity that's gone on in the past
... coloring all the good the Boston FBI has done for the last 20,
30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi, who traded in the black and white jogging suit that he
wears to court on most days for a herringbone sport jacket, white
shirt and tie, corroborated much of what Morris and others
testified to earlier this year: the cozy dinner parties, the
exchange of Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   But he contradicted some testimony. Flemmi said Morris's bribe
was only $5,000, but he failed to mention an extra $1,000 Morris
said was hidden at the bottom of a case of wine and another $1,000
given to him to fly his girlfriend to an out-of-state conference.
</P>
<P>
   And he maintained that Morris had told him and Bulger they could
``do anything as long as you don't clip anyone.'' Morris denied
making that statement.
</P>
<P>
   After Morris made that remark, Flemmi testified, ``I asked if we
could shake hands. We shook hands and Jim Bulger shook his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   But Flemmi denied that former Massachusetts Senate President
William Bulger, Whitey Bulger's brother, had wandered into a dinner
meeting that his brother and Flemmi were having with their FBI
handlers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
