<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOVELL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVELL'S NET SLIGHTLY EXCEEDS ESTIMATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing its recovery, Novell Inc. reported earnings Thursday
that modestly exceeded Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   For its third quarter, which ended on July 31, Novell reported
earnings of $26.6 million, or 7 cents a share fully diluted, in
contrast to a loss of $121.6 million in the corresponding period a
year earlier. At $272 million, sales were more than three times the
$90.1 million reported in the third quarter of the 1997 fiscal
year. Sales in the 1997 quarter were depressed by a one-time
inventory reduction carried out at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected Novell to earn 6 cents a share, according to
First Call. Novell reported its results after the close of the
market. In Nasdaq trading, Novell shares closed unchanged at
$10.875.
</P>
<P>
   Novell said its third-quarter 1998 results included $30 million
in operating profit, up from $16 million in the second quarter.
``We've clearly stabilized the business,'' Eric Schmidt, Novell's
chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.``We're beginning
to grow, it's just not clear how fast we're growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said the company's performance in the third quarter was
the more surprising because it did not include Version 5 of its
flagship Netware network operating system software, which is
scheduled to ship by the end of summer. ``We have to get to an
impressive Internet product, which we will do with Netware 5.0,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
