</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-SUDAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-SUDANESE TENSIONS FINALLY ERUPT INTO OPEN WARFARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: ATTACK-U.S. with photos, map and graphic,
ATTACK-BINLADEN with map, ATTACK-CONGRESS, ATTACK-SECURITY,
ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-MILITARY, ATTACK-ASSESS,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-MEDIA, ATTACK-WAG) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The air strike against a drug factory in Sudan
on Thursday marked the first act of open warfare in a
long-simmering cold war between the United States and the Islamic
regime in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has been at odds with the governing National Islamic
Front in Sudan almost from the moment it seized power in a 1989
coup and set up a theocratic state ruled along conservative Islamic
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past nine years, the United States has repeatedly
accused the Khartoum regime not only of supporting Islamic
revolutionaries in neighboring countries but also of harboring
various Arab terrorists who hate America and Israel, among them
leaders of the Palestinian group Hamas, the Cairo-based Islamic
Jihad and the Egyptian Muslim Brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important of these figures is Osama bin Laden,
the Saudi businessman whom U.S. investigators maintain was behind
the bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden, who is believed to finance a network of Islamic
terrorists around the world, lived for several years in the Sudan
and still owns several major businesses there, including a
construction firm and company that exports gum arabic.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech justifying the air strikes Thursday, President
Clinton said the drug factory U.S. missiles destroyed about 12
miles north of the Sudanese capital was ``associated with the bin
Laden network.'' He said the plant was manufacturing chemicals used
in nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afghanistan and the Sudan have been warned for years to stop
harboring and supporting these terrorist groups,'' Clinton said.
``But countries that persistently host terrorists have no right to
be safe havens.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, bin Laden was forced to leave the Sudan in 1996 after
western intelligence organizations said he was linked to an
assassination attempt against Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. The
United States stepped up political pressure on the Sudan,
threatening to cut off diplomatic ties if bin Laden was not
expelled. He migrated to Afghanistan, where the Talieban militia
have allowed him to set up several training camps for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Osama bin Laden has left the Sudan for over two years and he
has nothing to do with Sudan,'' Sudanese Interior Minister
Abdel-Raheem Hussein told the BBC on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Still, U.S. officials say bin Laden has maintained close ties
with senior members of the Khartoum government, many of whom share
his aggressively anti-American views. He continues to finance
terrorist groups within the Sudan, these officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In May, bin Laden issued a call for a religious war against the
U.S. and promised a campaign of terror.
</P>
<P>
   But bin Laden is not the only bone of contention between the
United States and the Sudanese.
</P>
<P>
   Khartoum has long charged that Washington supports the rebellion
in the mostly Christian and animist south of the country that has
cost more than 1 million people their lives and has led to three
famines in the last decade, the latest this year in Bar el Ghazal.
</P>
<P>
   The southern rebels have been struggling against Khartoum for 15
years, but their movement has been crippled by tribal divisions and
factional infighting. They maintain they are fighting for more
autonomy for southern states, a secular government and religious
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration denies it supports the rebels
directly, but it acknowledges giving non-lethal military aid to
Uganda, Eritrea and Ethiopia, who have in turn have funneled arms,
radios and other equipment to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have also made it plain the U.S. supports the
rebellion's goals. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright even took
the bold step of meeting with the main rebel leader, John Garang,
last December during a visit to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the leaders of the Sudanese government, however,
blame the U.S. for the continuing war, which has sapped the economy
and demoralized northerners. Many in Khartoum see the rebellion as
part of a U.S. strategy to destabilize Sudan and eventually force
the government to fall.
</P>
<P>
   The endless war also serves U.S. goals in the Middle East. It
weakens Khartoum's ability to support Islamic militants opposed to
the government in Egypt, the most important U.S. ally in the Arab
world and a counterbalance to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Sudan's political elites have taken pains to
show the world they have turned over a new leaf since the early
days of their coup, when they openly professed a desire to spread
Islam to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   A new constitution has been adopted this year guaranteeing the
freedom of religion and association, opening the door a return to
party politics, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, they maintain they have tightened immigration rules
to keep out terrorists and expelled many known Islamic militants,
including bin Laden himself. They also point out they have reached
peace agreements with all the major rebel leaders except Garang's
and are in negotiations with him.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. diplomats have dismissed many of these reforms as
cosmetic. U.S. intelligence officials say Sudan continues to
provide a haven to terrorist organizations and the National Islamic
Front's leaders still have an iron grip on power.
</P>
<P>
   As rescue workers struggled Thursday night to ferry wounded
workers to hospitals and to put out the fire at the Al-Shifa drug
factory, Sudanese officials portrayed themselves as the victims of
naked aggression.
</P>
<P>
   Information Minister Ghazi Salah-Eddin said the plant had been
opened two years ago and produced nothing but medicines. ``This is
a crime,'' he said. ``There is no justification for this attack.''
</P>
<P>
   But Salah-Eddin said the attack was predictable, given the
recent history of the two countries. In a sense, he suggested, the
simmering conflict between the United States and the Khartoum
government had finally come out into the open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to remind people that this is a very old battle
between right and wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway across the world, President Clinton appeared on national
television to voice a similarly bellicose sentiment, painting the
air strikes in Sudan and Afghanistan in black and white terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a long ongoing struggle between freedom and
fanaticism,'' he said. ``Between the rule of law and terrorism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
