<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-PROFITS-MARKETPLACE-ART-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SEEING CORPORATE EARNINGS FROM DIFFERENT
PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of corporate profits is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sm) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the stock market struggles to get back on its
feet, investors are focused on corporate earnings, buoyed by
reports that profits among the biggest companies are still rising,
albeit slowly.
</P>
<P>
   But a gauge of corporate profits produced by the government
paints a darker picture.
</P>
<P>
   As measured in the National Income and Product Accounts,
corporate earnings declined in the fourth quarter of last year and
in the first quarter of 1998. And next week, when the Commerce
Department releases that report for the second quarter, analysts
expect a decline in corporate earnings for the third consecutive
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   There have been six declines of at least three consecutive
quarters since 1960. And five of those times, the Dow Jones
industrial average fell at least 15 percent from its peak ahead of
that profit decline.
</P>
<P>
   In those five stock spills, the average Dow drop was 23.4
percent. The average earnings decline of three quarters or more was
11.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   From the Dow's recent peak through last Friday, the index had
dropped nearly 10 percent, and it remains down about 8 percent from
its high. If, as expected, corporate earnings fell 4 to 5 percent
in the second quarter, the total decline will be about 10 percent
over the last nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, history is not a good predictor of financial markets.
But a look at these corporate data _ which many stock analysts
dismiss as inadequate _ may indicate a weaker earnings environment
than described by Wall Street, an upbeat place anticipating more
profit growth in the second half of this year. And it may help
explain why so many stocks, especially small ones, have fallen
sharply. According to Merrill Lynch, 74 percent of all stocks had
fallen 20 percent or more from their 1997-1998 highs as the Dow
neared its recent low.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the differences, start with Wall Street's most
common measure of corporate profits, the earnings from continuing
operations of the 500 companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's index.
Using this Wall Street measuring stick, profits rose 8.2 percent in
the fourth quarter of 1997 from their level a year earlier, 1.2
percent in the first quarter of this year, and 3.4 percent in the
second quarter, based on nearly final data.
</P>
<P>
   The National Income and Product Accounts, gleaned from income
tax and other government data, show changes from quarter to quarter
instead of from year to year. The data form the basis for official
government reports on economic growth, including the gross domestic
product, personal income and several broad measures of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   They also provide an official tally of corporate profits from
thousands of companies, filling in a gap left by the S&AMP;P 500, which
accounts for about three-quarters of corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, the quarterly government data reflect what companies
report in profits to the Internal Revenue Service. These numbers
are not adjusted for extraordinary items _ like financing of
company pension plans _ that accountants strip out. Nor are they
altered by one-time charges, like restructuring or acquisition
costs, that Wall Street analysts deduct to produce what they call
operating or continuing earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The government data reflect these extraordinary and other costs
as they occur. The S&AMP;P figures, based on quarterly earnings
reports, allow companies to take such costs all at once. Companies
generally prefer to take a one-time hit so earnings growth can
quickly recover.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, there can be a sharp disparity between the
government profit report and the S&AMP;P 500 report. Just look back to
1991. S&AMP;P 500 operating earnings, after adjustments by Wall Street,
fell 21.8 percent, 24.2 percent and 17.9 percent, respectively, in
the first, second and third quarters, from the periods a year
earlier, according to First Call, an investment research company
that tracks analysts' estimates. The government report showed that
corporate profits rose 4.5 percent, before slipping 1.3 percent and
1.9 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thomas Galvin, the chief investment officer at Donaldson, Lufkin
&AMP; Jenrette, said he did not rely on the government profit report.
Writeoffs are very much accepted today, he said, and investors are
always looking forward. For that reason, they prefer continuing
earnings, which try to reduce the volatility caused by one-time
writeoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Clough, the chief investment strategist at Merrill
Lynch &AMP; Co., has a lot of confidence in the government data. ``You
can't manipulate them,'' he said. ``They are earnings you can write
a check with.''
</P>
<P>
   And the current decline in this measure has him worried. Falling
corporate profits are going to put a squeeze on corporate
investment, which has been ``the key to the Goldilocks economy,''
Clough said.
</P>
<P>
   The government report, however, is not a good predictor of stock
market turns. The market is a leading indicator, not a lagging
indicator, of economic activity. In the five times that profits
fell for three quarters and the stock market fell, the market
peaked before profits began to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the report may be an indicator of where Wall Street's
favorite measure is headed. Total corporate profits declined from
the second quarter of 1984 through the first quarter of 1985,
compared quarter to quarter. But the S&AMP;P operating profits,
measured year-over-year, did not turn negative until the fourth
quarter of 1984. In that episode, the Dow peaked on Nov. 29, 1983,
and fell 15.6 percent to a low of 1,086.56 on July 24, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The government profits measure also fell from the second quarter
of 1969 through the second quarter of 1970. But the adjusted S&AMP;P
measure began to show a decline only in the fourth quarter of 1969.
The Dow, from a peak of 985.21 on Dec. 3, 1968, fell 35.9 percent
to a low of 631.15 on May 26, 1970.
</P>
<P>
   But the profits gauge is not foolproof as an indicator of market
weakness. Total corporate profits _ and S&AMP;P 500 operating profits _
did not fall in the quarters around the 1987 crash. In the 1973-75
downturn, when the Dow fell 45 percent, the government profit
measure fell sharply, but for only two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   And there was one instance, in 1989, when total corporate
profits declined for three consecutive quarters and the Dow
industrials did not truly plunge. The stock market index remained
on an upward course despite a one-day 6.9 percent free fall on Oct.
13.
</P>
<P>
   What did follow was a three-quarter decline in operating
earnings in the S&AMP;P 500, Wall Street's favorite measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
