<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0474 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MINORS-DANVILLE-M     08-20 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MINORS-DANVILLE-MGR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Master of Minor Management
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Va. _ Slowly yet surely, he's mastered the fine art of
managing in the minor leagues. Not that it's been easy to subjugate
winning to the greater good of the organizational flow chart. Even
as a kindergartener, Paul Runge was so competitive, so
temperamental, he insisted on having a Monopoly monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My competitive nature started when I was 5 years old,'' said
Runge, who grew up in a New York household of eight kids who loved
the Yankees and revered the Mick. ``We'd sit in the kitchen and
play Monopoly. Once I was eliminated, I'd turn the board upside
down and run out of the kitchen. If I couldn't play, no one else
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years later, at least Boardwalk and Park Place are
safe. ``Even when we play games, if I win we've got to play
again,'' said Runge's wife, Rae Ellen. ``If I find a game I'm
better at than he is, he doesn't want to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   That stubbornness and fierce drive enabled him to last parts of
eight seasons as a utility infielder with the Atlanta Braves. Now
in his sixth season of micro-managing in the lower minors, Runge
can recite the Skipper's Creed: It's not whether you win or lose,
it's how (ITAL)they(END ITAL) play the game that counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always competitive. But over the years, I've learned to
sort through the winning and losing and the player development
going on,'' said Runge, who manages the struggling Danville 97s,
Atlanta's advanced Class A affiliate in the Carolina League. ``The
ideal scenario? Have both going on at the same time. Unfortunately,
the world doesn't always work that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned to differentiate as a manager. You've got to
learn patience and always know in the back of your mind that the
bottom line is (to) see players improve from beginning to end and
prepare them for the next level when you turn them over. We all
play our little part.''
</P>
<P>
   When he first passed through here in 1994 to manage the Danville
Braves of the rookie Appalachian League, Runge got to bench a kid
center fielder for loafing and insubordination long before Bobby
Cox ever disciplined Andruw Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real fiery when I started managing, a Sgt.
Carter-type,'' Runge said, referring to Gomer Pyle's TV drill
sergeant. ``When you first start, you're real gung-ho. You holler
and scream. I was a sore loser and real fiery, because I wanted
everybody to do well every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lot different now,'' said Glenn Williams, an Australian
bonus-baby shortstop when he first played for Runge in '94 and now
a second baseman. ``His fuse was a little bit shorter then.''
</P>
<P>
   It burned to a crisp one night when Runge was ejected for
arguing, returned to the dugout, then flung his cap out on the
field. Dozens of D-Braves fans did likewise on Cap Night. That
summer, Runge went into the stands after the final out to confront
a season-ticket holder who'd been screaming all night about
Danville's lack of aggressiveness on the basepaths.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``He's almost two different people,'' said Tim Cahill,
general manager of both Atlanta farm clubs playing here this year
and the GM in '94 when Runge managed the D-Braves. ``His biggest
adjustment is being content with playing .500 ball. His biggest
credit is he wants to see his players do well. There's some
managers who just want to win, play .600 ball so they can move to
another level. Then there's others who genuinely want to see
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Braves slugger Darrell Evans was fired as manager of
Kansas City's first-place Wilimington farm club in the Carolina
Leauge for ``philosophical differences'' _ winning too much at the
expense of developing prospects. Bill Plummer suffered a similar
fate after winning the first-half title in 1996 while managing
Detroit's Jacksonville Suns affiliate in the Class AA Southern
League.
</P>
<P>
   Runge has avoided that pitfall. Although he's never had a
winning record as a minor-league mananger, he's never lost sight of
the big picture _ the big leagues, the best prospects' destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job basically is to make sure those guys are out there
every day and get a chance to experience a lot of things on a
trial-and-error basis,'' Runge said. ``And also with a lot of
instruction.''
</P>
<P>
   At a lot lower volume, though. ``I found out through my
experiences (that) you don't have to holler and scream to get your
point across,'' Runge said. ``I found out everybody's different.
Some guys need a little pat on the back, some a little nudge.''
</P>
<P>
   Runge can still nudge. After a sloppy late-July home loss after
a long road trip, he gave the 97s a wakeup call. He called a 9 a.m.
practice for the next day. Their first morning-after workout of the
season, purportedly to work on defensive fundamentals, also was a
group lethargy session.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lethargic from travel and the daily grind of the
schedule,'' Runge said. ``But there's no excuse for lackluster
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even with a kinder, gentler, OK, more patient manager.
``He's high intensity,'' said pitcher Rob Bell, a right-handed
starter who is 6-7 but one of Atlanta's top-10 prospects. ``He's a
high-control guy, wants to control everything he can, night-in,
night-out. The guy wants to win. He wants guys to take extra BP, do
everything they can to make it to the major leagues. That's a
reflection on him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also the bold-faced section of Runge's job prescription.
Some lower-level minor-leaguers, of course, are more equal than
others. Runge must gear his managing toward nurturing the more
talented, and more expensive _ such as Williams, 21, who signed in
1993 for a $925,000 bonus; minor-league managers make between
$25,000 and $60,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is a career .224 hitter, and he's batting less than
that this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy gets a chance, but there's going to be some guys who
get more of an opportunity because of the money invested,'' Runge
said. ``The real true prospects in the organization are going to be
in the lineup every day. They won't be pinch-hit for. The starting
pitchers are going to be in the rotation every five days,
regardless of how they're doing. Those guys are going to get their
at-bats and innings (pitched).''
</P>
<P>
   If, say, Bell has a no-hitter going in the seventh inning but
has reached his pitch limit, he's done. ``We know the importance of
a young pitcher and his arm,'' Runge said. ``When a guy has a
chance at a complete game, a shutout, even a no-hitter, it means
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The 97s have no complete games this season; Bell is only starter
to pitch into the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a player like Williams _ once a switch-hitter, now
solely right-handed after a shoulder separation _ is a lineup
fixture. ``He's going to get every opportunity to show what he can
do, regardless of game situations,'' Runge said. ``You can pretty
much throw out stats in the lower minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I pinch-hit for him with the bases loaded and he's been
struggling? No. Even if he'd already struck out four times, that
one at-bat might turn his career around.''
</P>
<P>
   So, damn the competitor within, tough as that may be. Just
develop, baby. ``I'm trying to protect the kids' interests and the
money invested in them,'' Runge said, ``and trying to get them
ready to play for Bobby Cox one day.'' And continue Atlanta's
monopoly on the postseason into the next millenium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
