<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-CLINTON-TV-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TV PERFORMANCES THIS WEEK A STUDY IN CONTRASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday, a somber, resolute and slightly torqued private man
spoke from the dimly lit Map Room of the White House. On Thursday,
a somber, resolute and very decisive president spoke from the
klieg-washed Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's necktie: act-of-contrition blue. Thursday's:
in-your-face red and gold.
</P>
<P>
   Packaging sells.
</P>
<P>
   But if television is just radio with pictures, the words must
still be important, right?
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and his wordsmiths think so. Consider the
first person's use of the first person.
</P>
<P>
   Careful writers are always aware of it. Too much of the first
person singular makes the user seem self-absorbed, inward-looking.
Liberal use of the first person plural, on the other hand, is
extremely disarming and collegial. (Ever notice how news anchors
almost never use ``I,'' even during the mindless chitchat
segments?)
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's unprecedented mea culpa to the masses, the president
wanted us to focus on him, and him alone. He spoke for about four
minutes and used the words ``me,'' ``my,'' ``myself'' and ``I'' 46
times _ a staggering pace of once every five seconds. There was no
mistaking the intensely personal nature of those remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, in his afternoon address to the nation to discuss the
strikes against terrorist targets, Clinton spoke twice as long but
made only 15 such personal references. Just enough to be
presidential, as in: ``I want to speak with you'' and ``I decided
America must act.''
</P>
<P>
   In high contrast, the president used the all-inclusive ``we''
and ``our'' 52 times, a brisk six or seven per minute. ``We have
high confidence,'' the president said. ``We must take extraordinary
steps.'' ``We will not yield to this threat.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he was a lonely figure caught in a lie. (And if he
had stopped before taking aim at Ken Starr, he might have elicited
more sympathy.)
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he was one of us again. The captain of the team.
The go-to guy at crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   If asked to vote on the matter, actors will always say an
effective performance begins with the writing. In the president's
case, you could see it in his ``I's.''
</P>
<P>
   To reach John Levesque, call 206-448-8330, or send e-mail to:
tvguy(at) &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
