<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MINORS-STANDINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Development, not winning, key in minors
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winning definitely isn't everything in the minor leagues.
Developing players for the majors is the priority, with team
won-loss records often an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   That was never more obvious than in 1996, when Baseball America
magazine named the Atlanta Braves the organization of the year
despite a composite minor-league winning percentage that ranked
28th among 30 major-league franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Other systems had the wins, but they didn't have players like
Andruw Jones _ minor-league player of the year two seasons in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' farm system _ also voted No. 1 in 1991 _ has kept a
steady flow of young players coming to the majors despite having
only three winning records this decade and none since 1993. This
year, Atlanta's composite winning percentage of .430 is the worst,
just behind Los Angeles. No Braves farm team has a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here for only one reason _ to get players ready for the
big leagues,'' said Deric Ladnier, Atlanta's director of minor
league operations. ``Winning is nice, but it's not our emphasis. We
are very careful with our young pitchers, and we don't sign a bunch
of career minor-leaguers to fill out rosters.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Atlanta owns all but two of its farm teams, the Braves
also don't have to worry about complaints from owners trying to
fill seats with a winning team.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' only team likely to make the postseason is Class A
Macon. The M-Braves were 30-40 in the first half, but are 32-28 in
the second and lead the South Atlantic League's Southern Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are one of the youngest teams in the league and struggled
at first,'' Macon manager Brian Snitker said. ``But some of our
players have grown up, and we are playing much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Atlanta concentrates on drafting and signing high school
players, Braves' farm teams are usually younger than their
opponents. Teams with most of their players from college have a big
edge in the lower minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we think players taken out of high school have more
potential,'' said Paul Snyder, the Braves' director of scouting and
player development. ``They can learn the game our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves' composite minor-league record
</P>
<P>
   Year Won-Loss Pct. Rank
</P>
<P>
   1990 459-452 .504 15th
</P>
<P>
   1991 429-333 .563 2nd
</P>
<P>
   1992 373-389 .490 19th
</P>
<P>
   1993 404-361 .528 7th
</P>
<P>
   1994 363-385 .485 20th
</P>
<P>
   1995 346-417 .453 26th
</P>
<P>
   1996 354-407 .465 28th
</P>
<P>
   1997 369-395 .483 25th
</P>
<P>
   1998 289-383 .430 30th
</P>
<P>
   Source: Howe SportsData International
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
