A4635 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WNBA-COX     08-20 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WNBA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WNBA more successful marketing than playing
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even when they lose _ and the Washington Mystics
have set a new low-water mark for futility in professional
basketball _ the WNBA expansion franchise is still a winner.
</P>
<P>
   After a 110-65 loss Monday to the defending champion Houston
Comets, an MCI Center crowd of 15,758 warmly applauded the Mystics,
even after they were on the short end of league records for most
points surrendered in a game and margin of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has gone through a coaching change, and wholesale
personnel moves are expected for a team that finished 3-27 with a
.100 winning percentage, poorer even than the woeful 1972-73
Philadelphia 76ers, whose .110 figure on a 9-73 record, has been
the Mendoza line of pro hoops for the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate this, but it's great that our fans have loved us all
along and keep coming out no matter what,'' said Mystics guard
Nikki McCray, a former Tennessee All-American who was the first MVP
of the rival American Basketball League.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most symbolic of the WNBA at the end of its second
summer is that its worst team has its best attendance mark. The
Mystics averaged 15,898 fans in 15 home games, well above the WNBA
average of 10,729, and have attracted three of the five top
single-game crowds in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all these people,'' Houston coach Van Chancellor said
during a timeout with the score 87-44. ``There ain't nobody going
for dinner, ain't nobody going for nachos. They're staying to watch
a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, many were waiting for the last free pair of Nikes to
be thrown into the crowd and an incredibly loud playing of ``YMCA''
to blast forth from the sound system.
</P>
<P>
   Which prompts a question: Is this a rock concert or a basketball
game?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the entertainment business,'' said Chancellor, the
folksy former Ole Miss coach who admits that he doesn't listen to
the ``modern music'' that constitutes a WNBA game atmosphere.
``It's more than a basketball game. It's a happening.''
</P>
<P>
   League attendance is up 11 percent from last season, and the
WNBA's marketing and merchandising prowess continues. With exposure
on three networks and a summer season away from the cluttered fall
and winter sports docket, the 10-team WNBA has made more strides
toward its goal of becoming what commissioner Val Ackerman calls
the ``fifth major league.''
</P>
<P>
   But only Houston has been dominating on the court. The Comets,
who romped to a 27-3 regular season record, play Saturday afternoon
at Charlotte in the first of a best-of-three semifinal series. In
the other matchup, Cleveland plays Saturday night at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Mystics undertook a large direct-marketing effort to tap
into a fan base that identifies with female athletes and looks for
affordable entertainment options. Mystics, Wizards and Capitals
president Susan O'Malley talked up ``Girl Power'' to appeal to
young females, and families happily have scooped up $8 tickets.
There is never a quiet moment during games, with giveaways, dancing
and music blaring in a whirlwind of a relentlessly hip pop-culture
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a lot of fun,'' Mystics spokeswoman Julie Demeo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're a player on a team with expectations of winning.
Reigning MVP Cynthia Cooper of Houston is feeling some effects of a
concussion sustained two weeks ago. And Comets point guard Kim
Perrot might miss the playoffs with a badly sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is on us to prove that our record is
legitimate,'' Cooper, 35, said. ``We like the position we're in.
We're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor is wary of two close calls against Charlotte this
season and that Cleveland and Phoenix have dealt Houston two of its
three losses: ``In a short series, anything can happen to
anybody,'' he said. ``Anybody can win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's ``Big Three'' _ Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes and forward
Tina Thompson _ provides the only postseason star quality, with New
York and Los Angeles, featured more prominently on television, both
out of the playoffs. ``If we have a Chicago Bulls in the WNBA right
now, it is certainly in Houston,'' Ackerman said this week. ``In
some respects, they are our glamour team.''
</P>
<P>
   Other matters behind the scenes are vexing for the league. On
Thursday, the NBA Players Association accused WNBA management of
delaying an election by players on the question of unionizing. The
average league salary is $35,000, with only a handful making the
maximum of $80,000 and earning endorsements and related income.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
