<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-WALLACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace confident coming to Bristol
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Va. _ Every time Rusty Wallace comes to Bristol Motor
Speedway, he has good reason to sing its praises.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace sat on the pole the last two races, led a ton of laps,
won one race and had another in his pocket until he ran over debris
and hit the wall.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, he spent more time talking about Jeff Gordon's
4-0 streak than his own 0-50 streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what everybody wants to hear, and I understand that,''
Wallace said. ``I promise you that streak will tame down at one
point, because this stuff goes in cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon makes a run at ``modern-era'' NASCAR history Saturday
night in the Goody's 500, when he tries for his fifth consecutive
victory. NASCAR started its modern era in 1972, when R.J. Reynolds
signed on as sponsor and NASCAR trimmed its Winston Cup schedule to
30 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four wins is a lot of wins, but when you're in a zone
everything starts clicking,'' Wallace said. ``It all comes to an
end, but you got to ride it all you can, because everybody's up.
And when you go to the track, you feel like you can't be beat. I'm
sure that's the feeling he's got right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace should know a little of how it feels. He hasn't won four
straight, but he won 10 times in 1993 and 16 races 1994-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a zone during that period, where every time I went to
the track I felt like I was going to win,'' Wallace said. ``What
happens is, you go to these tracks and look around at other guys,
and you know they can't beat you. And that feeling gets stronger
and stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace would like to feel it again during today's qualifying
and Saturday's race. Bristol is the type of track that should give
Wallace confidence; he has been racing here since 1986, when he won
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the fact that Bristol is where I first won gives me a
fondness for the place,'' Wallace said. ``But it's more that that.
I love that area of the country. The fans are some of the best
around. This is a track that every time I come here, I expect to
win, expect to run up front all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was doing just that in March. After winning the pole,
his fourth at Bristol, he dominated the race, leading on six
occasions for 220 of the first 397 laps. Then trouble hit. He ran
over debris from Ricky Rudd's car, punctured a tire, slammed into
the wall and eventually finished 33rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the race everybody wants to talk about,'' Wallace said.
``We had that in our grasp before we ran over something. You can
say we definitely have some unfinished business to take care of
Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
