<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4638 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-LONG-WAR-NAT     08-20 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-LONG-WAR-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      REPUBLICANS SAY WAR ON TERRORISM IS JUST BEGINNING; 
 &HT;      DISPUTE ``WAG-THE-DOG'' ANALOGY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Ronald F. Eckstein  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, August 20 -- The American war on terrorism is just
beginning, according to Congressional Republican leaders, and
despite distinct similarities between the Thursday's bombing of
suspected terrorist bases and a recent Hollywood movie, leading
Republicans defended President Clinton's motives and actions.
</P>
<P>
   On a conference call to update Republican congressmen about U.S.
military action in Afghanistan and Sudan, House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., and House Intelligence Committee Chairman Porter
J. Goss, R-Fla., said they were briefed and consulted about ``every
level of detail'' for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was approached by the Clinton administration (about
retaliatory action) on the day of the bombings in Africa,''
Gingrich said. ``I have been briefed on every level of detail. I
felt, at all times, that I had input.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss added that the administration ``has been very faithful in
keeping us appraised'' since the attacks on the American embassies
in Kenya and Tanzania last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he is ``very comfortable with the planning'' that
went into the American retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was driven entirely by national security considerations,''
Gingrich said firmly. ``If you saw the television coverage of the
embassy bombings, if you saw the caskets coming home, you know this
is real. ... There should be no question by anyone that this is
being exploited in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a very dirty, very nasty little war on
terrorism ongoing for some time, but it is clear it has
escalated,'' Goss said. ``We are having a war and people need to be
behind it and support the president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a long campaign -- six months, two years, three
years -- and there will be casualties,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Goss said public officials must stress the ``nature of
ugliness'' of terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't care about suicide. They don't care about the
targets they take. They would prefer to attack softer targets like
women and children because it is easier,'' Goss warned. ``We need
to remind the American people that this will be ongoing.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Conference Chairman John A. Boehner, R-Ohio,
organized and hosted the briefing. Gingrich estimated that more
than 100 Republicans listened in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
