<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CENTRALFLA-COX     08-20 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CENTRALFLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loyalty pays off big for Culpepper, UCF
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ Everything Mike Kruczek ever needed to know about
Daunte Culpepper, he learned in Culpepper's first college game.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1995 and on Culpepper's first play as Central
Florida's quarterback, he was sacked by Eastern Kentucky. Culpepper
got up, dusted himself off and proceeded to drive the team 84 yards
for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive, he completed five passes in a row, checked off to
another play four times and capped the march with a 24-yard scoring
pass. Culpepper would go on to complete his first 12 passes and 20
of 25 in a 40-32 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just raised my arms and thanked God,'' said Kruczek, the
former Steelers quarterback and now head coach at UCF. ``I knew we
had something very, very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything Nebraska's Tom Osborne needed to know about Culpepper
took place in one unforgettable half last September in Lincoln.
Central Florida was a 42-point underdog but on the game's first
possession, Culpepper drove the Knights 69 yards for a touchdown.
Culpepper ended the drive with a 10-yard scoring run in which he
bowled over two Cornhusker defenders.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Culpepper had completed 12 of 17 passes for 186
yards, and UCF led 17-14. The score sent shock waves through
football stadiums across the land.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska came back and won 38-24, but against a team that would
finish 13-0 and share the national championship, Culpepper
completed 24 of 35 passes for 316 yards and a TD. He ran for 34
yards and another score.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not know about Culpepper now,'' Osborne said
afterwards, ``but the whole world will find out about him, because
he'll be making big noise on Sundays.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything the fans of Central Florida needed to know about
Daunte Culpepper they learned earlier this year when he decided to
pass on pro ball and return for his senior year. If Culpepper had
left school, he probably would have become an instant millionaire,
like fellow quarterbacks Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper's bandwagon already was pretty full with grateful fans
and excited NFL scouts. Now it is overflowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like this program needed me right now more than
the NFL,'' said Culpepper, who threw for 3,086 yards and 25
touchdowns last season. ``If I take care of business this season,
the money will still be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loyalty,'' he added, ``Is a pretty big thing with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper knows that loyalty is one of the cornerstones for a
successful life. He knows because Miss Emma taught him.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 29, 1977, Emma Culpepper was confronted by a desperate
teenager who had given birth just the day before. She had no means
of support and begged Emma, a worker in a halfway house for
troubled teens, to adopt her baby. Emma was 50 years old and
already had raised 15 children _ some belonging to relatives,
others she had adopted on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I had the energy to raise one more,'' she said.
But Emma Culpepper agreed to take the baby boy.
</P>
<P>
   That baby was Daunte.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Culpepper, said Daunte, took him in and taught him right
from wrong. She was loyal to him in good times and bad. And there
was plenty of both. He wanted to take the NFL's money and buy her a
new house. She said no. Stay and get your degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the person who instilled in me the right way to do
things,'' said Culpepper, who at 235 pounds and 6-foot-5, now
towers over Emma. ``If God blesses me and I stay healthy, I will do
anything for her.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was loyalty that brought Culpepper to UCF when the
South's more established football powers came calling.
</P>
<P>
   As a junior at Vanguard High in Ocala, it appeared Culpepper did
not have the right academic stuff to play Division I football. Once
they took a look at his transcript, almost all of the major
football schools backed away.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Lounsberry, the offensive line coach at Central
Florida, stuck around and helped Culpepper put together an academic
plan for his senior year. He would retake some courses and for the
first time, work hard in every one. It paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thought I could make it, but (Lounsberry) did,'' said
Culpepper, who earned all A's and B's as a senior and met the
NCAA's entry requirements. ``He told me if I could just discipline
myself, I could do it. Nobody else believed in me like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, all the schools that had backed off recruiting
Culpepper suddenly reappeared. They told him that if he went to
Central Florida, he would never reap the glory that he deserved. He
would never play on national television. He would never get the
proper attention from the NFL scouts.
</P>
<P>
   But Culpepper, Florida's Mr. Football as a senior, stood firm.
UCF had stuck by him. He would stick by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never regretted my decision for one minute,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Culpepper and a memorable 1997 season, UCF's football
program has received a huge dose of national exposure. Not only did
the Knights play toe to toe with Nebraska, they also threw some
major scares into Ole Miss (a 24-23 OT loss), South Carolina (a
33-31 loss), and Mississippi State (a 35-28 loss).
</P>
<P>
   Because of what happened last season, Culpepper's exploits will
make the weekly highlight shows. He'll get some Heisman
recognition, particularly if UCF can win a big game, such as
against Purdue on ESPN on Sept. 19. But even Culpepper concedes his
Heisman candidacy is a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heisman is really not a big thing on my list right now,''
Culpepper said. ``... I'm more concerned about this team having a
good season.''
</P>
<P>
   With 10 offensive starters returning and an easier schedule, a
winning season is possible. If that happens, his star power might
be strong enough to get the Knights an at-large bowl bid. It would
be, he said, the best farewell present he could give the school
that gave him so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my goal,'' Culpepper said. ``If I can help this team
get to a bowl, it will have all been worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming Saturday: Florida State
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
