<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QB Leaf trying to revamp bad image
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Maybe it was because June Jones was within
earshot. Perhaps he was feeling pretty good about himself after
shredding a secondary during a seven-on-seven drill.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Ryan Leaf already is tired of being portrayed as the
spoiled-rotten brat of this year's NFL rookie class.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the rationale behind his sudden flirtation with
civility, a sweaty Leaf was trying hard recently to straighten his
lopsided halo.
</P>
<P>
   His replies were cliche-ridden but polite and measured. What he
lacked in introspection, Leaf compensated for with patience. And on
cue, he lauded the work of a rebuilt offensive line and even his
suspect receivers.
</P>
<P>
   As a teammate cooled his heels, waiting to ferry Leaf to a
nearby watering hole, the punky quarterback, whose talent is
matched only by his attitude, tried to turn on the charm. ``Lots of
this stuff that's being said is just an absolute crock,'' Leaf
concluded before heading for a hot shower and then a frosted mug.
``Just because I'm a little bit of a free spirit and don't toe the
line on everything, ... that shouldn't make you a bad guy. People
who don't know me, some who haven't even met me, are making these
judgments, and it isn't really fair. Some of these accusations,
like that I'm self-absorbed or an enigma ... Geez, I don't even
know what those things mean. I know I'm no choir boy, but ... ``
</P>
<P>
   Many of Leaf's new teammates and coaches contend the bad-boy
image is false. Yet in a six-month reign of terror that doesn't
begin to account for some of his college escapades at Washington
State, the Chargers' first-round draft choice seemingly has managed
to tick off about half the league.
</P>
<P>
   Regarded by some of his college teammates as petulant,
egotistical, overbearing and arrogant _ ``There were guys in his
own huddle who flat-out hated him,'' said former Philadelphia scout
Steve Crosby, now an assistant coach at Vanderbilt _ Leaf already
is threatening rookie records for boorish behavior. At the combine
sessions in February, he infuriated Indianapolis Colts general
manager Bill Polian and coach Jim Mora by blowing off a scheduled
interview and compounded the situation by failing to leave them a
message.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two months ago, Leaf was fined $10,000 by the league for
departing a day early from the mandatory rookie symposium in
suburban Denver.
</P>
<P>
   _ While participating in the made-for-TV ``NFL Quarterback
Challenge'' this spring, he tried to put the moves on an attractive
spectator. The lovely lady, it turned out, was the wife of
Cincinnati Bengals quarterback Neil O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several training-camp practices have included spats with
Chargers linebacker Junior Seau, who has his own ego and still is
acknowledged as the team's spiritual leader and a person not to
mess with. After last Tuesday's practice, Leaf yelled across the
locker room, ``Hi, buddy,'' to Seau as the linebacker undressed.
Seau, his voice dripping with sarcasm, replied: ``Yeah, hi,
buddy,'' and then quickly ducked into the shower.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leaf maintains that his friendship with Peyton Manning, begun
last fall when the former Tennessee star telephoned him, remains
solid. But he chafes at the suggestion that the Colts rookie is
better prepared to handle the cerebral end of the game. In an
interview last week with the Los Angeles Times, Leaf derisively
referred to Manning as ``The Golden Boy'' and ``Perfect Peyton.''
The two will square off for the first time Saturday night in a
preseason game so hyped it's now hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's got an evil twin running around or something,
huh?'' Chargers center Roman Fortin said. ``Really, I think the
guy's been great to deal with. He throws the hell out of the ball.
and if he keeps doing that, his image won't matter very much.''
</P>
<P>
   If Chargers owner Alex Spanos thought that image is everything,
he wouldn't have paid an $11.25 million signing bonus for Leaf, who
once gave the finger to a crowd that jeered him during a
high-school basketball game. If he remains more flippant than
forthcoming, it might be excused if he continues to throw the ball
as well as he did in a camp practice against the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   On consecutive attempts, he completed 12-yard slants, one to
Charlie Jones, a pass delivered so hard that 49ers safety Merton
Hanks was frozen. He connected with Bryan Still on a deep inside
hook, the pass leaving Leaf's hand even before the wide receiver
throttled down in the intermediate zone. He then lofted a deep ball
up the left sideline, just over the fingers of San Francisco corner
Marquez Pope and into the outstretched hands of speedy Tyrone
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   One personnel director from an NFC team just whistled and shook
his head in admiration. A scout from an AFC West franchise said
that Arizona Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill, even with the
charismatic Jake Plummer at quarterback, could rue the day he
swapped the rights to Leaf to the Chargers. After the workout,
several 49ers defensive backs stopped by to shake Leaf's hand.
``Every pass,'' Pope said, ``was right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has played down his impressive preseason
performance, Leaf is far more comfortable discussing his passing
than his personality. And his coaches now turn the conversation
away from his arrogance and more toward his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is there: strength, release, touch. He's pretty
rare,'' June Jones said. The former Atlanta Falcons coach is
serving as Leaf's tutor, guardian angel and probation officer. Leaf
conceded that he doesn't plan on being just mediocre in the NFL.
Noting that he was ``hardly surprised'' that Gilbride installed him
as the starter so early, Leaf said the Chargers might have the
savior the franchise so desperately needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting through all the (nonsense),'' he said, ``I think I'm
going to be something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
