<HEADER>
A4641 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USSTRIKES-CONGRESS-08     08-20 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USSTRIKES-CONGRESS-0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON RECEIVES BIPARTISAN SUPPORT FROM CONGRESS, SOME GOP
MEMBERS QUESTION TIMING
 &HT;    With USSTRIKES-MAIN-0821.
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a surprise break with tradition, some senior
congressional Republicans questioned the timing of President
Clinton's decision Thursday to strike at terrorist facilities in
Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Newt Gingrich strongly defended the move,
saying it delivered a much needed message to terrorists
contemplating future attacks on Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was exactly the right thing to do,'' said Gingrich,
R-Ga., in a telephone interview with the Cox News Service. ``It
says to every country in the world: if you are the host to a
terrorist, you are a target.''
</P>
<P>
   The military strikes, which appeared to have overall bipartisan
support among congressional members, were aimed at ripping a hole
in the heart of the terrorist regime of Osama Bin Laden, a Saudi
multi-millionaire and chief suspect in the recent bombings of U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania -- which killed 257 people and
injured 5,500 others.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans, however, questioned the timing of the
strikes, noting that it came four days after the president stunned
the nation by admitting that he had an ``inappropriate
relationship'' with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky after
denying it for seven months. It also came on the very day that
Lewinsky was to return to the grand jury investigating whether the
president committed perjury or obstructed justice in an attempt to
conceal the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the president's personal difficulties this week, it is
legitimate to question the timing of this action,'' said Indiana
Republican Daniel Coats, a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee. ``Once the president has broken the bond with the
American people, as he has done with his repeated lies, it raises
questions about everything he does or does not do.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Republican Arlen Specter raised an eyebrow as well.
``I think we have to raise certain concerns and look for evidence
because those questions will be raised around the world. . . . the
president's current problems have to be on the minds of many
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Specter offered support for Clinton's actions, saying he
had more time to evaluate the purpose of the strikes and added that
``the president acted appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike at Bin Laden coinciding with the developments in the
Lewinsky scandal caused some to compare the current climate in
Washington with the plot in the film ``Wag the Dog,'' in which the
president is caught having sex with a young woman and tries to
distract the nation's attention by fabricating a war with Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Those assertions were quickly refuted by the White House. ``The
only motivation driving this action today was our absolute
obligation to protect the American people from terrorist
activities,'' said Secretary of Defense William Cohen, a former
Republican senator from Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The president's troubles should have nothing to do with his
military actions, said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
``Our response appears to be appropriate and just . . . this
Congress will vigorously support the president in full defense of
American's interests throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich agreed: ``Anyone who saw the bombings in Kenya and
Tanzania, anyone who saw the (12 American) coffins come home, would
not ask such a question.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich was briefed about the strikes by the president's
national security advisors on Wednesday. Attempts to reach Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., were also made, but he is traveling
in Europe. However, other key Republicans such as South Carolina
Senator Strom Thurmond, chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee were not notified until just minutes before Clinton told
the media.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   And that unleashed a cool response from some members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not advised of today's operations until shortly before
President Clinton made his public statement regarding the
strikes,'' Thurmond said. ``Such military operations are certainly
risky and it is my sincere hope that there were no injuries or
fatalities among the American personnel involved.''
</P>
<P>
   While he strongly endorses removing terrorists, Georgia
Republican Rep. Bob Barr, said there was ``a mighty big coincidence
in the timing'' of the bombings. Barr, who has pushed for the
impeachment proceeding of Clinton over the Lewinsky affair, added
that he ``hoped the actions taken by the president were taken based
on sound intelligence reports.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, most members of the Georgia congressional delegations
showed support for the president's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation has taken action against very deadly terrorists
opposed to the most basic principles of American freedom,'' said
Georgia Sen. Paul Coverdell, a member of the Foreign Relations
Committee. ``This action should serve as a reminder that no one is
beyond the reach of American justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., urged his Republican colleagues to stop
attacking the president during a time of national crisis. For
Republicans to play politics with national security issues such as
a military strike, ``is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone to be questioning the actions of the president, is
playing politics,'' Lewis said. ``We cannot play politics when the
interests and lives of Americans have been threatened. Combative
terrorism is not a partisan issue.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Max Cleland, a Vietnam veteran, said that he strongly
supported Clinton's decision. The bombings should be viewed as
another example of the stern way America will deal with attacks in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrorism is a great threat, not only to the U.S. but also to
the peace and security of the entire world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
