<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4642 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      08-20 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACK AIMED 70 MISSILES AT TARGETS 2,500 MILES APART 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S. with photos, map and graphic,
ATTACK-BINLADEN with map, ATTACK-CONGRESS, ATTACK-SECURITY,
ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-ASSESS,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-SUNDAN with map, ATTACK-MEDIA,
ATTACK-WAG.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States attacked targets in Afghanistan
and the Sudan with roughly 70 cruise missiles fired from Navy ships
in the Arabian and Red Seas timed to strike their targets
simultaneously, senior administration and military officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The missiles struck at precisely 1:30 p.m. ET, after dark
settled over their targets, themselves more than 2,500 miles apart,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority struck six separate targets within a sprawling
camp near Khowst, Afghanistan, that President Clinton called ``one
of the most active terrorist bases in the world.'' A smaller
barrage struck a pharmaceutical plant in the Sudanese capital,
Khartoum, that the administration maintained produced important
components for making chemical weapons, particularly VX nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
   As the attack began, Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered
every American military base in the world to heighten its state of
alert, increasing security in the event of retaliation from
supporters of Osama Bin Laden, the Saudi exile whom the United
States accuses of sponsoring terrorism, including this month's
embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   There were no American casualties, the officials said. They said
it was not immediately clear how much damage the strikes caused in
Afghanistan and the Sudan, nor whether there were casualties on the
ground. Reports from Sudanese television in Khartoum said there
were injuries there.
</P>
<P>
   A senior military officer was told less than an hour after the
attacks that the cruise missiles had struck the factory in
Khartoum. The Sudanese television images showed heavy damage, smoke
and fire at the factory, which is in an industrial area northeast
of the city center.
</P>
<P>
   Military and intelligence officials said the extent of the
damage in Afghanistan would not be clear until Friday at the
earliest, but that the targets there included an array of buildings
clearly visible in satellite photographs shown at the Pentagon
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry
Shelton of the Army, declined to discuss details of the strikes, as
did Clinton's other senior national security advisers. But Cohen
said the raids would ``reduce the ability of these terrorist
organizations to train and equip their misguided followers or to
acquire weapons of mass destruction for their use in campaigns of
terror.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, senior officials later said the United States
timed the attack when it did because of ``credible evidence'' that
there would be more than the usual number of terrorists at the
camps in Afghanistan. At the same time, Cohen and other officials
said the attack was launched at night to minimize casualties among
civilians, especially in Khartoum. Cruise missiles launched at sea
posed much less of a risk to American forces than an attack by
warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan was to attack these sites with sufficient power to
certainly disrupt them and hopefully destroy them,'' Cohen said.
``Some of these are solid structures; others are less so, but we
believe that given the targeting that was done with the capability
that was unleashed, it would cause sufficient damage to disrupt
them for some time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
