<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RATPACK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO'S `RAT PACK' CAN'T GET UNDER THE SKIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They researched the facts and worked on the characterizations,
but the makers of ``The Rat Pack'' ultimately lose their way.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, Sammy Davis Jr. and their cronies,
in real life, formed the Rat Pack for the joy of it.
</P>
<P>
   They were rodents, but (set ital)fun(end ital) rodents.
</P>
<P>
   If the cosmos was one big cocktail lounge in the early 1960s,
then life in it was a perfect martini. Shaken (set ital)and(end
ital) stirred.
</P>
<P>
   The HBO movie, showing Saturday, takes an occasionally spirited
stab at reconstituting the old fizz.
</P>
<P>
   Its art direction and sort of cuckoo-crazy musical interludes
are right on the verge of getting it, rather like a slick retro bar
that serves up highballs and jiggers of attitude.
</P>
<P>
   But breezy, boozy fun is not a natural quality in the 1990s. We
can't even fake it convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra (Ray Liotta) pins Martin (Joe Mantegna) on the phone and
says, ``Listen, Dean, I got it all planned out. We take the plane,
we catch Sammy's show. We'll grab some ring-a-ding, and we'll take
the chopper to the Springs for a midmorning clambake, and I'll have
you back to the Oasis by show time. It'll be a gas.''
</P>
<P>
   And it would be a gas _ for them, back then. Today it would be
bogged down by worrisome business calls on the boys' cell phones,
fear of the diseases that go along with the ring-a-ding and calorie
counting at the clambake, whatever a Rat Pack clambake may have
been.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you can't have a productive business meeting with a
hangover. And if you live in a time when time is money, you have a
hard time imagining a time when time was merely time.
</P>
<P>
   So the ``Rat Pack'' actors can only pretend to have fun; the
real thing is probably the stuff of cultural archaeology.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, director Rob Cohen and screenwriter Kario Salem see
their film as a tragedy. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Rat Pack, the Kennedys and the Mafia again, with the
usual side dish of Marilyn Monroe (Barbara Niven).
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra provides Jack Kennedy (William Petersen) his women.
Kennedy provides the giddy Sinatra with a bit of presidential
panache. The Kennedys and the mob communicate through the Rat Pack.
</P>
<P>
   All of this makes Kennedy in-law and ex officio Rat Packer Peter
Lawford (Angus Macfadyen) miserable. He comes across as a spineless
errand boy who's deathly afraid of all his patrons.
</P>
<P>
   (Sinatra to Lawford: ``Don't squirm, Peter. I hate it when you
squirm.'')
</P>
<P>
   Dean Martin is the sensible cynic here, careful not to run afoul
of anyone. Joey Bishop (Bobby Slayton) is mainly a nonpresence. And
Don Cheadle, a rising star who is cast as Sammy Davis Jr., just
about sneaks off with the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Davis is configured as the most tragic rat of all,
unless you count Sinatra finally getting jilted by the Kennedy
clan.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tears-of-the-clown turn. Davis patiently endures
Sinatra's stage antics, which reduce Davis to little-black-mascot
status. Also, his interracial love affair and eventual marriage to
the Swedish actress May Britt brings him heaps of unwanted
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The oddest scene in the film is a fantasy sequence in which
Davis dances and sings ``I've Got You Under My Skin'' to a mob of
brown-shirted demonstrators outside his hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Cheadle projects Davis onto the street and does the number in
front of a big neon ``N_'' sign, adorned with Stars of David. It's
audacious _ way out there. It's also foolish in a rather
spectacular way. Cheadle manages to recoup his character's dignity,
but the scene leaves a lingering (set ital)huh?(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The central character of Sinatra, as opposed to the real
Sinatra, is a tough read in this movie. Salem's script probably
does the right thing in violently mixing Sinatra's conflicting
traits _ insecurity, an explosive temper, generosity, vanity,
arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   But whoever Frank Sinatra was, he was not Ray Liotta. The
baby-faced Liotta has said he could handle the role because ``I'm
from Jersey, I got blue eyes. It's close enough.'' It isn't close
enough. He's all wrong physically, and he doesn't have a whisker of
Sinatra's ratty charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are all the voices. There's a fake voice subbing for
The Voice in ``The Rat Pack.'' The Sinatra family didn't confer its
authorization on this movie, and Sinatra's voice is never heard in
it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, dealing with three well-known singers, the movie tries
to get by with swinging instrumentals, several lip-synched voice
imitators and, here and there, actual vocalizations by Mantegna and
Cheadle.
</P>
<P>
   If Martin had been Mantegna, Dino would have been fino long
before 1960. And Cheadle can't wheedle an authentic note from his
throat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
