A4650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORISM-CHANGE-BOS &LR;      08-20 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-CHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW' TERRORISM AMORPHOUS, PRIVATELY FUNDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The terrorist bombings in east Africa -- and the swift US
military response to them Thursday -- dramatically represent a new
era of world terrorism and the challenges faced by the US faces in
fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists say terrorist groups in recent years have mutated
into amorphous, trans-national entities which target the United
States through private funding sources centered around a single
belief: righteous killing in the name of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case marks major changes in direction of terrorism, an
increasing willingness to inflict mass casualties without claim of
responsibility from a trans-national group, aimed at expelling the
West rather than drawing attention to a specific cause,'' says
Jerrold Post, the former head of the CIA's center for analysis of
personality and political behavior in terrorism, and the author of
the 1997 book ``Political Paranoia: the Psychopolitics of
Terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of their lack of organizational structure and intense
religious zeal, these new groups are willing to attempt massive and
indiscriminate acts of terror -- unlike their more traditional and
more organized predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amid the confusion of vague claims and uncertain leads,
multiple possible suspects and a web of tangled motives, one aspect
of the tragic events in East Africa seems clear: A new era of
terrorism has begun, with a potential to be both bloodier and more
destructive than any experienced before,'' according to Bruce
Hoffman, author of the book ``Inside Terrorism'' and director of
the Center for the Study of Terrorism and Political Violence at St.
Andrew University, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Scott, a retired special operations commander in the US
Army responsible for terrorism response throughout the 1980s, says,
``What has changed in ten years is a change from politically
motivated terrorism to religiously motivated terrorism. And these
groups are emerging out of failed states, such as Sudan and
Afghanistan, which are attracting largely trans-national, adhoc
terrorist groupings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The old form of political terrorism was perhaps deterrable,''
he adds. ``What we are finding now is that the new religious
terrorism may not be.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, terrorism was practiced by members of identifiable
organizations with ``a defined command-and-control
</P>
<P>
   apparatus,'' according to an analysis of modern terrorism
published this week in the Los Angeles Times by Hoffman, regarded
as one of the world's leading experts on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   These groups included the Japanese Red Army, the Red Army
Faction in Germany, the Red Brigades in Italy, as well as
ethno-nationalist terrorist movements like the Palestine Liberation
Organization, the Irish Republican Army and the Basque separatist
group, ETA.
</P>
<P>
   These organizations had more defined objectives, he writes. They
generally issued communiques taking credit for, and often
explaining in detail, their actions. They engaged in ``highly
selective and mostly discriminate acts of violence,'' Hoffman
explains, choosing traditional targets such as embassies, banks,
and national airline carriers that symbolized their hated foes.
They kidnapped and assassinated persons whom they blamed for
economic exploitation or political repression to attract attention
to themselves and their causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were somewhat more rational goals, if we can use that
word, to describe terrorism,'' adds Richard Shultz, director of
internaional securities studies program at the Fletcher School of
Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, who has studied the changing
face of terrorism through the twentieth century.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see today in this case and others is a larger
ideological context of Islam against the West. Terrorism is
becoming more religious, and the goals are therefore more grandiose
and less specific, and the targetting more random,'' Schultz says.
</P>
<P>
   This newer brand of terrorism was evident in the 1993 World
Trade Center bombing and a subsequent foiled plot to blow up other
targets in New York. Those two conspiracies brought together
terrorists from the Sudan, Egypt, and Palestinian refugees from
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The two U.S. embassy attacks this month clearly fit this
virulent pattern. For starters, the operations do not appear to
have been executed by an established and identifiable terrorist
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The new terrorism, experts say, has its roots in Afghanistan in
the 1980s, when the US-backed Mujahadeen brought together Muslim
volunteers who fought in the name of Islam against the Soviet
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   But these fighters eventually turned against the United States.
Intelligence agents have a name for the phenomenon when individuals
who once were allies of the United States are now alienated by the
country. They call it ``blow back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the active figures who have emerged in this shadowy
trans-national terrorism come out of Afghanistan. Certainly that is
the case with (millionaire Saudi terrorist leader Osama) bin
Laden,'' says Post.
</P>
<P>
   Although accurate intelligence helped the US military locate and
attack the infrastructure of the bin Laden operation, military
experts fear that this new terrorism will be very difficult to
combat.
</P>
<P>
   US Army Lt. Col. Stephen Gotowick of the Foreign Military
Studies Office wrote in the May/June issue of Military Review:
``The likelihood of preventing or defeating terrorism through
conventional military means is remote.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Scott adds that while the US responded properly Thursday,
the future will not be as clear. ``In addition to immediate strikes
based on solid intelligence, there has to be a diplomatic dimension
to counter terrorism, and the UN and all world organizations have a
role in that,'' he says. ``These failed states, such as Sudan and
Afghanistan, have to be clearly advised that if they want to be
part of the world they cannot harbor terrorism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
