<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4656 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-EVIDENCE-NYT &LR;      08-20 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-EVIDENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ATTACKS BASED ON STRONG EVIDENCE AGAINST BIN LADEN GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S. with photos, map and graphic,
ATTACK-BINLADEN with map, ATTACK-CONGRESS, ATTACK-SECURITY,
ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-MILITARY, ATTACK-ASSESS,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-SUNDAN with map, ATTACK-MEDIA,
ATTACK-WAG) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton ordered strikes on
terrorist-linked facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan after
obtaining credible evidence that leading members of the
international terrorist network sponsored by Saudi exile Osama bin
Laden, who U.S. officials believe was behind the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in Africa, would be gathering Thursday at a
terrorist camp in Afghanistan to plan further attacks against the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. strike also came after U.S. intelligence and law
enforcement agencies had gathered what officials described as the
strongest evidence ever obtained in a major terrorist case, proving
that bin Laden was behind the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Senior U.S. officials said the fact that the United States had
gathered such compelling evidence linking bin Laden to the embassy
bombings, coupled with information concerning the scheduled
terrorist conference, led Clinton to plan the strikes for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a confluence of events,'' said a senior U.S.
official.
</P>
<P>
   By targeting the meeting, the United States hoped to badly
damage the ``infrastructure'' of bin Laden's terrorist network.
U.S. officials said they won't be able to assess the damage done at
the terrorist camp until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said that the U.S. counter-terrorism
center, based at the CIA, ``feels strongly that there is as much
and as rich evidence from a wide variety of sources on this case as
they have ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``Our information was convincing, and we had a
high confidence level that these bombings were planned and carried
out by bin Laden's network. And we had compelling evidence that bin
Laden and his organization were planning further attacks. If we
didn't take action, we were going to get hit, there's no doubt in
our mind.'
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that bin Laden's network was planning attacks at
several sites around the world, including against the U.S. embassy
in Albania. There was also a threat against U.S. interests in
Pakistan, officials added.
</P>
<P>
   The Zhawar Kili terrorist camp, near Khost, Afghanistan, where
the terrorist conference was expected to be held, was hit by U.S.
sea-launched cruise-missiles Thursday. U.S. officials said that bin
Laden had held a similar conference in Afghanistan in January,
apparently to plan attacks against the United States. Bin Laden's
networks have issued new terrorist threats against the United
States since the embassy bombings, and so U.S. officials believe
that the Thursday meeting was to plan future attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had information that something in the camp was going to
take place today,'' said a senior U.S. official. ``It's possible
the meeting was to plan further attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   But one U.S. official said that since May, bin Laden has become
increasingly cautious about his personal security. Prior to that
time, he stayed largely in one place outside Kandhar, Afghanistan
but since then he has been moving frequently, perhaps out of a fear
that his terror campaign would make him more of a target, a U.S.
official said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the U.S. struck a pharmaceutical plant in Khartoum,
Sudan, which U.S. officials said was making a precursor element
used in the production of VX, a poison gas.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said that bin Laden has been working with
the Sudanese government since 1995 or 1996 to try to develop a
chemical weapons capability. U.S. officials believe that bin Laden
has been working hard to obtain chemical weapons for use in his
terrorist campaign against the United States, although they don't
believe he yet has that capability.
</P>
<P>
   The Al-Shifa pharmaceutical plant in Khartoum, struck by U.S.
cruise missiles Thursday, was operated by the Sudanese
military-industrial complex, which has been financially supported
by bin Laden. Officials noted that companies owned and operated by
bin Laden have helped the Sudanese acquire dual-use technology for
use in developing biological and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that Bin Laden has worked with Sudan to test poisonous
gases and to finance simpler methods of manufacturing and
dispensing gas, methods which would be less time-consuming and
expensive than prior Sudanese efforts,'' a U.S. intelligence
official said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials declined to provide a detailed accounting of the
evidence linking bin Laden to the embassy bombings, but they have
strongly suspected his involvement since the day of the attacks.
And they say that as their investigation gained momentum in the
days following the bombings, the links to bin Laden quickly began
to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to other recent major terrorist cases, which have
required months or years to solve, the evidence against bin Laden
in the East Africa bombings came together with remarkable speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had early indications, and over time the information got
better,' a senior U.S. intelligence official said. `We had multiple
sources, and the picture was extremely convincing. You have to be
careful how you weigh early information, but in this case it was
very compelling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely do numerous sources converge so uniformly and
persuasively as they did in the course of our investigation into
the responsibility for these terrorist acts,'' added National
Security Adviser Samuel Berger.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence against bin Laden and his operatives in the East
African bombings is considered conclusive by U.S. officials, yet
the United States intelligence community has been convinced for
years of bin Laden's financial support and involvement in a long
series of attacks against U.S. interests, including the bombings of
U.S. military facilities in Saudi Arabia in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Clinton also revealed a series of other failed attacks
against U.S. or other international interests by bin Laden's
network, including a previously undisclosed plot to kill Pope John
Paul II. A U.S. official said that ``on one of the pope's recent
overseas trips, there were indications that bin Laden operatives
were trying to surveil routes with the intent to cause harm'' to
the pope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
