<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-PEPSI-COX     08-20 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-PEPSI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola, Pepsi attorneys take debate to court's cafeteria
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Attorneys for Coca-Cola didn't have to go far to make
their point.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi flows freely in the very courthouse where Pepsico
attorneys argued Thursday that Coca-Cola's ``classic monopolistic
behavior'' has effectively locked out its beverages from the U.S.
fountain soft drink market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Places like the 8th floor cafeteria downstairs that serve
Pepsi have to get that product from someplace,'' attorney Jonathan
M. Jacobson stressed to U.S. District Court Judge Loretta A.
Preska, as he summed up why Coca-Cola Co. thinks Pepsico's
antitrust lawsuit should be thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi is seeking unspecified monetary damages, plus a
restraining order to stop Coca-Cola from barring independent food
service distributors from delivering Pepsi products if they also
carry Coke brands.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, who closed the two-hour hearing in lower Manhattan
with the promise, ``You will have word shortly,'' did not rule on
Coca-Cola's motion to dismiss the suit Thursday. A decision is
expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed May 7, accuses Atlanta-based Coca-Cola of
using unfair trade practices to control prices and exclude
competition in the fountain soft drink arena, which makes up
roughly $15 billion of the $54 billion U.S. soft drink business.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico's complaint centers on the growing number of
restaurants, movie theaters and other retailers that get the syrup
for their fountain soft drinks from independent food service
distributors. This group of retail customers _ the so-called market
on which the case hinges _ accounts for about $2 billion in annual
wholesale syrup sales, said Pepsico attorney Richard M. Steuer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a shrinking market,'' said Steuer, explaining that
in recent years fountain customers have increasingly turned to
independent food service distributors to get one-stop delivery of
everything from soft drink syrup and cups to buns, hamburger
patties and condiments.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola historically has used such distributors to deliver its
syrup to fountain customers, but only recently began enforcing its
policy of working only with suppliers who didn't also deliver Pepsi
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico contends this started in 1997, when the Purchase,
N.Y.-based company spun off its KFC, Pizza Hut and Taco Bell
divisions and started more actively pursuing contracts for
restaurant fountain accounts. That's also when Pepsico started
trying to farm out its fountain syrup delivery to independent food
service distributors, only to be blocked by Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Steuer told the judge Coca-Cola's message to those distributors
was, ``If you ever let a drop of Pepsi go through your system,
we're going to cut you off.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico contends that Coca-Cola has contracts with companies
that service more than 90 percent of the market that takes fountain
syrup delivery through independent distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of an independent food service distributor's customers
wants Pepsi and the distributor honors that request, the
distributor would lose his Coke connection and all of his other
delivery customers unless he can convince those customers to also
switch to Pepsi,'' Steuer said. ``That could be difficult, if
impossible,'' he said, because fountain customers sign lengthy
contracts to carry a given company's beverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vicious cycle. It's a chicken and egg (cycle) that can
never be broken,'' he said. ``Coca-Cola has tied up all the
distributors. The food service distributor is a conduit, and
Coca-Cola has contracted with that conduit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson said Pepsico's argument was flawed, given that there
are other ways to get syrup to the market rather than by using
independent distributors. Among examples he cited are vending
companies, beverage specialists, dedicated commissaries or the
beverage company's own bottling network.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other selling opportunities. Those can't be ignored,
the same way the 8th floor cafeteria can't be ignored,'' Jacobson
said. ``The restaurant has a choice. Does it go to food service
distributors or does it not? They've only focused on the
restaurants that choose to use food service distributors, ignoring
those that don't.''
</P>
<P>
   And because the market at issue represents just $2 billion of
the total U.S. soft drink market by Pepsi's measure _ a figure
Jacobson disputes _ there are questions of whether the submarket is
``economically significant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we've got a $2 billion market,'' Jacobson told
the judge. ``We could have six years of discovery and a
20-year-long trial to debate that.''
</P>
<P>
   Preska quickly piped in: ``No you can't!''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit deals only with fountain sales, excluding soft
drinks sold in bottles or cans.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts estimate Coca-Cola has two-thirds of the U.S.
fountain business, compared with Pepsi's estimated 24 percent.
Coca-Cola has a 43.9 percent total share of the U.S. carbonated
soft drink market, compared with Pepsi's 30.9 percent share.
Globally, Coca-Cola's market share is 49.7 percent, compared with
Pepsi's 20.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Chief Executive M. Douglas Ivester in June called the
lawsuit _ and others Pepsi has filed against the company over
business in India and France _ ``the tactic of the month'' designed
to hurt Coke's business.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico spokesman Brad Shaw says the company is merely trying to
promote freedom of choice while protecting its right to a level
playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
