u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT-     08-20 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOST MIDEAST GOVERNMENTS REMAIN SILENT ABOUT U.S. ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S. with photos, map and graphic,
ATTACK-BINLADEN with map, ATTACK-CONGRESS, ATTACK-SECURITY,
ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-MILITARY, ATTACK-ASSESS,
ATTACK-SUNDAN with map, ATTACK-MEDIA, ATTACK-WAG.) 
(js) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel was quick to congratulate the United States
on Thursday night for its missile attacks on suspected terrorist
bases, but the early reaction from most other governments in the
Middle East was a notable silence.
</P>
<P>
   And while Israeli officials hailed the American operation as
courageous, television reports in parts of the Arab world featured
irate calls from viewers who denounced the strikes as unjust and
immoral.
</P>
<P>
   Those contrasts seemed to point to the depth of conflicting
emotions that the American attacks had already begun to stir.
Israelis, who have suffered more recent terrorist attacks than any
other country, saw the operation as vindication of their own calls
for confrontation toward Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said the American raids had
underscored the fact that ``the war against terror everywhere is
never-ending and necessary in order to ensure stability and
security around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Arab governments that have fought long battles against
terrorism seemed cautious about adopting a similar public stance.
Many Arab leaders have criticized what they call the imbalance in
American policy in the region and may be attuned to the possibility
that their citizens may regard the American raids less as strikes
against terror than as attacks on Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Among Arab countries, Egypt may have been typical in that its
state-run television station broadcast news about the American
attack without any comment from the Egyptian government. The raids
were launched on the eve of the Muslim holy day, and in Jerusalem
Israeli authorities said they were concerned that Friday prayer
gatherings in the walled old city could become the setting for
anti-American demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Only Libya, itself the target of a 1986 American air raid that
was characterized as retaliation for terrorism, was explicit in
condemning American attacks on targets in Sudan and Afghanistan.
The Libyan leader, Muammar Gadhafi, whose own home was hit in the
1986 raid, was reported by Libyan state television to have
telephoned President Omar Hassan al-Bashir of Sudan to express
support in this ``fight against aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Thursday evening, Libyan television had interrupted
its regular programming to begin carrying live broadcasts from
Sudanese television showing flames rising from a factory hit in the
American raids. American officials said the factory had produced an
ingredient necessary to make chemical weapons, but Sudan's
information minister, Ghazi Salah Eddin, said it had been nothing
more than a medical installation.
</P>
<P>
   But a more telling gauge of the hostility with which ordinary
Arabs were responding to the operation could be heard on some
Arabic-language television call-in shows, including one broadcast
by Sudan television. In a portion that was broadcast live by CNN on
Thursday night, a number of callers expressed solidarity with Sudan
and denounced the United States and an American president whom some
suggested was trying to turn attention away from personal and
political problems involving his relationship with a former White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Several callers identified themselves as being from Saudi
Arabia, whose government is a close ally of the United States but
where many citizens have deep misgivings about those ties. One
caller who did not give his name but said he was calling from
Riyadh, the Saudi capital, said of Clinton, ``The way out for him
was basically to carry out an operation that would divert attention
from his own lies and problems by attacking sites in Sudan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that the strongest power on earth is being led
now by a liar,'' the Sudanese host agreed. ``How would we know that
what he says isn't a lie?''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Thursday night, American officials took pains to
try to muffle Arab protests. Clinton declared that ``our actions
were not aimed against Islam,'' and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said she had been in touch with other world leaders _
including Arabs _ and that they had been ``very supportive of our
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to echo American assertions made earlier this year
that there was broad Arab backing for a possible military attack
against Iraq. In that instance, however, concern about a possible
public backlash against a strike on brother Muslims led most Arab
leaders to publicly warn against such an attack, and the United
States ultimately opted to find a way out of the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for Arab unhappiness with American policy in the
Middle East remains a perception that the United States is leaning
too far toward Israel in negotiations aimed at forging a broader
Arab-Israeli peace.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Israeli officials sometimes complain that their
American counterparts are not sufficiently sensitive to their
country's security concerns, and to the importance of retaliating
swiftly and ruthlessly to acts of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night, Israeli officials were repeating with
evident satisfaction what has long been their mantra. ``If we let
our fear of retaliation by the terrorists rule our action or
inaction, we will have handed terrorism the ultimate victory,''
said David Bar Illan, the spokesman for Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
</TEXT>
