<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-RESPONSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US MILITARY RESPONSE TO TERRORISM UNUSUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By unleashing missile attacks on two terrorist centers Thursday,
the United States made an uncharacteristically bold assault on
international terrorism, departing from a long history of seeking
out suspects through other means.
</P>
<P>
   Previous terrorist attacks _ from the 1988 bombing of Pan
American Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, to the 1996 bombing
of US Air Force barracks in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia _ have prompted
US investigations and manhunts. But rarely has the US swooped into
a foreign country so quickly to retaliate _ in part, because of the
elusive nature of terrorism itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been times when we simply haven't had the
information to respond,'' said retired Rear Adm. Eugene Carroll,
deputy director of the Washington-based Center for Defense
Information. ``Terrorists have gone to great lengths to conceal
their means and their modalities. I think that's the reason we
haven't done anything about (the 1996 attack on the Saudi) Khobar
Towers until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after President Ronald Reagan's 1986 condemnation of Libyan
support for terrorist attacks _ ``If we can find them, we will kill
them,'' he vowed _ direct military retaliation has been rare.
</P>
<P>
   Within the last 15 years, at least eight terrorist explosions
have killed hundreds of Americans. New York's World Trade Center.
The embassy and military barracks in Beirut. US military training
camps in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only one _ the bombing of a Berlin nightclub on April 5,
1986 _ brought a reaction as massive as Thursday's.
</P>
<P>
   In that instance, in the wake of an explosion that killed two US
airmen and injured another 230, and following reports that Libyan
terrorists planned to attack again, Reagan ordered an air strike on
Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force F-111s and Navy jets strafed Libya just 10 days after
the Berlin explosion, in a military response hailed by some as the
only appropriate choice.
</P>
<P>
   US officials acted immediately because they were able to ``get
the information and intelligence as to the perpetrator,'' said
Michael O'Hanlon, a fellow at the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We responded and retaliated through military reprisal, not too
much unlike'' Thursday, O'Hanlon said.
</P>
<P>
   But there were severe repercussions as a result of that
full-scale approach.
</P>
<P>
   The residence of Libyan leader Col. Moammar Khadafy was bombed
during the raid, killing his adopted baby daughter and injuring two
of his sons.
</P>
<P>
   One official said at the time that it was ``the price he's going
to have to pay for continued terrorism,'' but two years later, Pan
American Flight 103 was blasted out of the sky, in an apparent
retaliation that was far worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took great solace and pleasure in announcing to the world
that we had put Khadafy in his place,'' Carroll said. ``And bang,
there goes an airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of the two suspects in the plane crash, Abdel Basset
Ali Al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, was far quieter, as
investigators and intelligence officials traced their steps and
fought to bring them to trial.
</P>
<P>
   But fear of retaliation has been only one concern, US experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason: United Nations regulations, which permit ``self
defense'' or ``prevention,'' but not eye-for-eye retaliation,
according to Andrew Winner, a senior staff member at the Institute
for Foreign Policy analysis in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest obstacle to fighting terrorist violence with
violence, however, is the great difficulty connected with
indicting, then tracking, terrorists _ especially those who, like
Osama bin Laden, are not officially sanctioned by any state.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got groups that are fragmented and small, it's
very difficult to know where they are,'' said Jeswald Salacuse,
professor of international conflict and law at Tufts' Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy in Malden, Mass. ``When you've got a
group that's not affiliated with a state and that is mobile, it's
very difficult to go after them.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of those limitations, the US record is ``respectable,''
said O'Hanlon, the Brookings defense expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a grade B, or B-minus, not terrible, not great,'' he
said. ``We have gotten some people and not others. ...Overall, our
record is respectable in that we have gotten some people and not
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Said one senior intelligence official said during a Pentagon
briefing Thursday: ``Rarely do numerous sources converge so
uniformly and persuasively as they have in this instance. After
following many terrorist events, rarely have we come to some
conclusions as fast as we did; rarely has been the quality of what
we collected as high as it has been.''
</P>
</TEXT>
