<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TESTIFIES AGAIN BEFORE GRAND JURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim; also, times are cq) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky appeared before a federal grand
jury again Thursday as questions arose over possible conflicts
between President Clinton's testimony and information provided
earlier by the former White House intern and other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, the woman at the heart of the presidential sex
scandal, spent about four hours with the panel responding to
questions about her 18-month affair with Clinton, including details
from their trysts and what the president may have done to hide
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old former White House intern ``answered all
questions truthfully and completely,'' said Judy Smith, a Lewinsky
family spokeswoman who indicated that Thursday's grand jury
appearance probably would be Lewinsky's last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Lewinsky is really looking forward to beginning the
process of rebuilding her life,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a poll released Thursday indicates that public
opinion of the president has slipped in the wake of his nationally
televised appearance Monday night in which he confessed an improper
relationship with Lewinsky and lying about it for the past seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Americans surveyed by ABC News believe Clinton has
obstructed justice and three-fourths of Americans say he is not
trustworthy and does not have high moral standards. The survey was
conducted before the president ordered military strikes against
terrorist facilities in Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's announcement of the strikes eclipsed plans by some
television news networks to broadcast Lewinsky's departure from the
courthouse, which happened at 2 p.m., EDT. Wearing a gray
double-breasted suit and sunglasses, Lewinsky left the building as
she arrived just before 9 a.m., EDT _ in a sports utility vehicle
and without commenting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky was called back to the grand jury to address
inconsistencies prosecutors reportedly found between her testimony
Aug. 6 and what Clinton said during his unprecedented appearance
before the panel Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's testimony is critical to the investigation by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr into whether Clinton lied under
oath when questioned in January as part of the sexual harassment
lawsuit filed against him by Paula Jones. Starr also is examining
whether the president or his associates obstructed justice by
trying to cover up his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest to Starr's prosecutors, said a source
familiar with Lewinsky's appearance Thursday, were specifics from
her sexual encounters with Clinton and how she came to return gifts
he had given her.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky reportedly told the grand jury two weeks ago that she
performed oral sex on the president and that they engaged in
intimate touching.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the first president to testify before a grand jury
investigating his actions, read a statement confessing to an
improper, 18-month relationship with Lewinsky that included
intimate physical contact. When questioned by prosecutors, he
balked at providing details.
</P>
<P>
   Citing sources familiar with Clinton's testimony, both The
Washington Post, The Associated Press and several television news
organizations reported that during his testimony Clinton
specifically acknowledged that Lewinsky performed oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a source familiar with Clinton's testimony said the
president never specifically acknowledged any sexual conduct
involving Lewinsky. Instead, each time he was asked, the president
would reply that he had ``already said it was improper,'' referring
to his statement in which he contended that the type of sex he had
with Lewinsky did not fall under the definition of sex used in
Jones' lawsuit, said the source who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual relations was defined in the Jones case as an instance
``when the person knowingly engages in or causes ... contact with
the genitalia, anus, groin, breast, inner thigh, or buttocks of any
person with intent to arouse or gratify the sexual desire of any
person.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a source familiar with Lewinsky's Aug. 6 testimony,
she told grand jurors that she and Clinton met privately Dec. 28,
nine days after she had been subpoenaed to testify in Jones'
lawsuit and to turn over any gifts he had given her. At the meeting
they discussed returning the gifts to him through his personal
secretary Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky and Clinton reportedly testified that he suggested that
she would have to turn over any gifts still in her possession.
According to The Washington Post, Lewinsky on Aug. 6 told the grand
jury that Currie showed up at her Watergate apartment to pick-up
the gifts, which included a T-shirt, a pin, a book of poems and an
autographed copy of a State of the Union speech.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton adviser familiar with his testimony said the
president knew nothing about Currie retrieving the gifts and did
not direct her to do it. ``The gifts just aren't an issue as far as
we're concerned,'' the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   During his televised speech Monday, Clinton said he did not
``ask anyone to lie, to hide or destroy evidence or to take any
other unlawful action.''
</P>
<P>
   Currie, who has testified before Starr's grand jury five times,
turned the gifts over to his investigators.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
