<HEADER>
A4671 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TERROR-AZR &LR;      08-20 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TERROR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANTI-TERROR STRIKE WAS DIFFICULT, BUT RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - So much for the experts.
</P>
<P>
   The pundits proclaimed the Clinton administration was on the
ropes, the president about to collapse in the far corner of the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   But never - ever - count Bill Clinton out.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the fates handed him an opportunity for some redemption in
presidential leadership, and he did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   In retaliation for the bloody embassy bombings in East Africa
two weeks ago, in which 12 Americans and nearly 300 Kenyans and
Tanzanians lost their lives, Clinton ordered U.S. forces to attack
terrorist camps in Afghanistan as well as a chemical plant in Sudan
linked to terrorist Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reminded the nation that bin Laden publicly vowed to
wage a terrorist war against America, saying, ``We do not
differentiate between those dressed in military uniforms and
civilians. They are all targets.``
</P>
<P>
   The terrorists' mission was murder, said the president, and
their history is bloody.
</P>
<P>
   So Clinton did the correct but difficult thing. Difficult?
</P>
<P>
   It is always difficult to order military action, if only because
of the possibility for collateral damage to innocents. But this
time, the president had the extra burden of the ``Wag-the-Dog``
syndrome - a skeptical public cynically wondering whether this
action was a calculated diversion to send the public's attention
skipping off to an international crisis and away from that
DNA-stained dress.
</P>
<P>
   The president, whom we now know to be a dishonest man, created
this cynicism with his own actions.
</P>
<P>
   But he is, after all, the president. And yesterday, at long
last, he acted presidential, striking against terrorism with
stealth and finesse.
</P>
<P>
   This strong act of resolve comes in the wake of an embarrassing
retreat from a tough stand against Saddam Hussein when the Iraqi
dictator refused to allow United Nations weapons inspectors access
to sites that might be used for nuclear, chemical or biological
weapons development.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Secretary of State Madeleine Albright recently acknowledged
that she had urged U.N. weapons inspectors to discontinue
unannounced U.N. inspections in Iraq. Wouldn't want to upset
Saddam, you see. U.S. resolve had atrophied and Saddam Hussein knew
it.
</P>
<P>
   But then ... the United States struck back in Afghanistan and in
Sudan. Suddenly the U.S. had a commander in chief - allowing us to
be proud, however briefly, once again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
