A4672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-MOVIE-ANALYSIS-BOS     08-20 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MOVIE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERTAINMENT, REALITY COLLIDE IN STRIKE ON TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The line between fantasy and reality, between Hollywood and
Washington, has blurred into invisibility in this decade of
cynicism and disillusionment, in this culture of entertainment
above all else. But it snapped clearly back into view Thursday in
the wake of President Clinton's decision to bomb terrorist camps in
Afghanistan and the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   That a Hollywood movie should figure in any discussion of
Thursday's events shows only how skewed our collective sense of
so-called reality has become. One element of Thursday's reaction
consisted of cynical analogies between the US actions and the
political satire ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Wag the Dog,'' Robert De Niro's spin doctor and Dustin
Hoffman's Hollywood producer stage a phony war to divert attention
from a presidential sex scandal. They fill TV screens and
newspapers with faked images of pathos and made-up heroics of a war
America is told is taking place in the Balkans, but in reality is
unfolding on a sound stage. In doing so, they minimize coverage of
the president's peccadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the splash made by ``Wag the Dog,'' now available on
video, was the fact that it had just gone into wide release when
the Monica Lewinsky story broke in January. Clinton and those who
stand by his actions say the bombings were not politically
motivated, that the current scandal was not the reason for the air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Senator Dan Coats (R-Ind.) questioned the timing
of the air attacks, given the president's personal difficulties.
Senator Arlen Specter (R-Pa.) seconded him, adding in a milder vein
that the president's problems have to be on the minds of many
people. When special prosecutor Kenneth Starr was asked if he had
seen the movie, he laughed and said he shouldn't comment, but yes,
he had.
</P>
<P>
   Most members of Congress, including the President's severest
critics, closed ranks behind him. And a newly sobered America will
decide how much weight should be given to the skeptical
questioning, how appropriate it is to push the parallel between
fact and fantasy, whether the links between ``Wag the Dog'' and
Thursday's events represent oracular revelation or a conspiracy
theorist's wildest dreams come true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
