<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VIAGRA-WARNING-NY     08-20 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VIAGRA-WARNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA URGED TO STRENGTHEN VIAGRA WARNING LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Viagra, the impotence pill, may be dangerous to more
people than previously reported, a finding that has prompted two
cardiology groups to urge doctors to exercise caution when
prescribing the drug.
</P>
<P>
   In light of this and other information, Public Citizen, a
consumer group, petitioned the Food and Drug Administration on
Thursday to review Viagra's side effects and strengthen its warning
label.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is reviewing the request, said Brad Stone, an agency
spokesman. ``We've just gotten the letter and haven't gotten a
chance to analyze it fully,'' he said. ``On the basis of the best
data we have, we still believe that Viagra is a safe and effective
drug when used as labeled.''
</P>
<P>
   Viagra's label warns against prescribing the drug to people who
are taking heart medicine containing nitrates because of the
potential for developing life-threatening low blood pressure. The
FDA has reported 39 deaths of American men who have used Viagra.
Six of the men were taking nitroglycerine, a nitrate drug, and the
others had one or more risk factors for coronary artery disease.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement issued on Aug. 10, the American College of
Cardiology and the American Heart Association said Viagra was
``potentially hazardous'' to several groups of patients who were
not taking these drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The groups include patients with these conditions: active
coronary ischemia, which is insufficient blood flow to the heart;
congestive heart failure; borderline low blood pressure and
borderline low blood volume. Others at risk are people with
hypertension who are taking more than one drug, and those who are
taking drugs like erythromycin or Cimetidine, or who have
conditions, like kidney or liver disease, that can delay Viagra's
breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Adolph M. Hutter Jr., co-chairman of the committee that
developed the statement, said that Viagra could cause a dangerously
sharp drop in blood pressure in these patients. Hutter said he did
not think the drop would be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   Hutter said the committee had not based its statement on actual
cases, but on a review of the scientific literature on Viagra. He
said that the committee was still studying the drug's effects and
would issue a complete report this year.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at Public Citizen conducted a separate review of the
literature and of FDA documents on Viagra and found several other
possibly dangerous side effects that had not been made public. The
group's petition said that facts about these dangers ``are either
not discussed or misrepresented in the FDA-approved labeling for
Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   The petition said that the label did not mention animal studies
that found that Viagra caused perarteritis, a severe inflammation
of blood vessels. Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of Public Citizen's
Health Research Group, said that the FDA pharmacology review of
Viagra concluded that this finding ``may be a cause for concern''
in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Viagra label states that a side effect is ``blue''
vision, the petition said that the drug may cause more severe
vision problems. Viagra suppresses levels of one enzyme,
phosphodiesterase, to maintain high levels of cyclic guanosine
monophosphate, which causes erections. But, Wolfe said, studies
have shown that inactive phosphodiesterase and an accumulation of
cyclic guanosine monophosphate can lead to rapid degeneration of
the retina. The petition urged the FDA to determine whether
repeated use of Viagra could cause such deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen contends that questions exist because Viagra was
rushed to market last March in response to publicity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
