<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0501 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4678 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-MOTIVES-NAT     08-20 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-MOTIVES-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  GIBBONS QUESTIONS CLINTON'S MOTIVES
</P>
<P>
   By Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 20 -- Rep. Jim Gibbons, R-Nev., questioned the
timing of President Clinton's decision to launch simultaneous
missile attacks against terrorist bases in Afghanistan and Sudan
Thursday, saying it might be an attempt to shift focus away from
his personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction today with military force raises some very serious
questions as to whether or not this was based on some attempts to
cloud (Clinton's) personal problems, or if it truly involved
national security,'' said Gibbons, a member of both the House
Select Intelligence Committee and House National Security
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly have doubts about today's strike,'' Gibbons said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons was not alone in questioning Clinton's decision, three
days after the president admitted to an extra-marital affair with
former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind., and Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., also
suggested Clinton called for the missile attack to divert attention
away from his personal problems. Specter later said he supported
the president's decision after talking with U.S. military advisors
during an appearance on CNN's Crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   But Nevada's two Democratic senators and Republican Congressman
said the president's timing was appropriate in response to the
recent two U.S. Embassy bombings in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev., a member of the Senate Select
Intelligence Committee, said he supported the president's decision
to strike against the terrorist bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has the duty to take action, and he did,'' Bryan
said. ``I don't think the (missile strike) was unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., said, ``This is not about the
president. This is about national security. It is ridiculous and
insulting to make the assumption that the Secretary and Defense and
Joint Chiefs of Staff would ever act for political purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions appear that they were absolutely necessary,'' said
Rep. John Ensign, R-Nev. ``I support them.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. strike began at about 1:30 p.m. EDT when long-range
cruise missiles were launched at an alleged chemical weapons plant
in Sudan and six terrorist bases in Afghanistan. U.S. aircraft were
not used in the strikes, which helped to keep the mission a secret
until after it happened, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the sites are linked to Osama bid
Laden, a wealthy Saudi millionaire and a well known terrorist
supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Osama bid Laden is widely suspected of orchestrating two
bombings that took place minutes apart two weeks ago that killed
257 people including 12 Americans and leveled two U.S. Embassies in
Tanzania and Kenya. Osama bid Laden, who is also linked to the
World Trade Center Bombing in New York City and a handful of other
terrorist acts in the past six years, apparently survived the air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Reid and Ensign who are battling one another in this year's
Senate race appear to agree on how the U.S. should deal with
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said, ``We cannot afford to let rogue states and
organizations attack Americans and American property,'' Reid said.
``Protecting our national security must be the nation's first and
foremost concern at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ensign said U.S. citizens must band together to overcome the
terrorist threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This terrorist organization has declared holy war against the
United States, and we as Americans must join together to win it,''
Ensign said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
