<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELLION-NYT &LR;      08-20 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HELP ARRIVES, CONGO OFFICIALS REJECT TALKS WITH REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sm) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ A day after several African governments
pledged to help President Laurent Kabila repel an attack on his
government, a leader of the rebellion said he was willing to
negotiate a cease-fire in the 18-day war that is increasingly
becoming a political battleground for rival African nations.
</P>
<P>
   But while the government had not officially responded to the
offer Thursday night, aides to Kabila said they would hold no talks
with the rebels, who control eastern Congo and are advancing toward
the capital here from the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   In Goma, a city on the eastern border with Rwanda, which is
backing the revolt, Wamba dia Wamba, a leader of the rebels, said
they were prepared for a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready for negotiations with Kabila because we believe
the problems of the Congo are political and beg a political
solution,'' dia Wamba said, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   government officials rejected meetings with the rebels, although
they left open the possibility of direct talks with the Rwandan
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would we negotiate with them?'' a member of Kabila's
Cabinet said, referring to the rebels. ``To discuss? To discuss
what?''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels came under political pressure Wednesday after several
countries, including Zimbabwe, Kenya and Angola, said they would
supply military assistance to Kabila's forces. State television
showed foreign troops arriving at the airport here Thursday night,
but did not specify their country of origin.
</P>
<P>
   The South African government is also pressing both sides to
resolve the conflict peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting, meanwhile, continued in the region southwest of
the capital. In their march toward Kinshasa, the rebels claimed to
have seized Mbanza-Ngungu, an important city about 75 miles
southwest of the capital to which the government had sent troops
and military equipment. The aides to Kabila denied the rebels'
assertion, which could not be confirmed independently.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday in Kinshasa, electrical power returned briefly for a
few hours for the first time since Monday. But by nightfall, the
rebels, who control the enormous Inga hydroelectric dam on the
Congo River, cut off power again, leaving Kinshasa and nearby
Brazzaville, in the neighboring Congo Republic, in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   War preparations could be seen all over the city Thursday in
ways large and small. On Avenue de la Victoire, a 13-year-old boy
approached a businessman talking to a reporter and asked for change
to take the bus. The boy did not want to be late for work; he had
to report to his army unit or risk suspicion that he had deserted.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, where major airlines have not landed in days,
two military helicopters touched down in the afternoon. Small
airplanes shuttled passengers who wanted to leave the country
across the Congo River into Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
   Officials canceled the return visas of foreigners flying out of
the city. And soldiers forbade a dozen women trying to leave the
country from entering the airport, saying they were ethnic Tutsi.
The Congolese Tutsi, who are concentrated in eastern Congo, are
believed to be leading the war against Kabila along with the
Rwandan Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
   The Tutsi, with Uganda, are the forces that put Kabila at the
head of the rebellion that ended the 32-year dictatorship of Mobutu
Sese Seko. When Kabila assumed power 15 months ago, his ties to the
Rwandans made him extremely unpopular among his countrymen. But he
eventually cut himself off from the Rwandans, setting the stage for
this conflict.
</P>
<P>
   As the fall of Kinshasa appeared inevitable early this week,
Kabila flew to other countries, searching for military support and
exposing through his actions the continent's national rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda's competitors, led by Zimbabwe, said they
would supply arms, men and other military equipment to Kabila. At
the same time, though, South Africa pressed for negotiations
between both sides, saying it disagreed with the actions of its
diplomatic rival, Zimbabwe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2042EDT &QL; 
