A4689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIG-SUNAMERICA-BOS &LR;      08-20 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIG-SUNAMERICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN INTERNATIONAL TO BUY SUNAMERICA IN $16.7B DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Insurance giant American International Group Inc. has
agreed to buy SunAmerica Inc. in an $16.7 billion stock deal that
represents a big bet on the financial needs of the nation's aging
population and poses a stiff new challenge to firms like John
Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the second largest ever in the American insurance
industry after Berkshire Hathaway Inc.'s $22 billion purchase of
General Re Corp. in June, and is the latest in a string of
megamergers designed to consolidate the nation's financial services
sector and focus it on individuals rather than corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a demographic play,'' said Jeffrey Hopson, an analyst
with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Co. in St Louis. ``People are getting older.
They have unfunded liabilities, whether it's health or retirement,
and they need financial services.''
</P>
<P>
   The purchase marks the first big step that AIG has taken into
the US consumer market and, as such, is a mirror-image of other
recent megamergers, like the Citicorp-Travelers Group deal, which
were designed to extend the reach of US-based companies around the
world. Although AIG is headquartered in New York, it makes most of
its money overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will bring together two of the financial industry's
most strong-willed executives, AIG chairman and Maurice Greenberg
and SunAmerica chairman and Eli Broad. The prospect of competing
against the pair had other insurance executives speaking in hushed
and respectful tones Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two of the smartest, toughest guys in the
business,'' said Hancock president David F. D'Alessandro. ``What
other companies in this business should fear is that the combined,
low-cost structure will cause product prices to drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Insurance industry analysts said the purchase solves problems
for both companies, providing AIG with a popular product and a US
sales network and helping SunAmerica to expand overseas.
</P>
<P>
   AIG now sells business and individual life insurance in 130
countries, many in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   SunAmerica specializes in variable annuities, a kind of hybrid
insurance policy-mutual fund. The product has been the
fastest-growing segment of the US life insurance business in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg was quoted by Bloomberg News as telling analysts he
believes that variable annuities are the financial product of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this wil be one of the fastest-growing businesses
that exist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts expressed surprise at the roughly $75-per-share
price that AIG has agreed to pay for Los Angeles-based SunAmerica,
saying it is steep by current standards and out of character for
Greenberg, who until now has been willing to pay only
bargain-basement rates for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of investor displeasure, AIG shares fell 7 1/8
Thursday to 87 1/2, their largest decline in 10 years and a tumble
that shrank AIG's market value more than $7.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the purchase could end up looking like a smart
move if, as some predict, Congress passes legislation that permits
banks to buy insurance companies for the first time since the
Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens and there's a feeding frenzy, Hank Greenberg
will look like he got a steal,'' said one observer, who asked not
to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   AIG has tried to enter the US consumer market in the past by
building its own sales network and by buying other firms. Earlier
this year, it lost out to now-crippled Cendant Corp. in bidding for
Miami-based American Bankers Insurance Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   AIG has made its mark in the financial industry by entering
businesses like aircraft leasing that others shunned.
</P>
<P>
   Under Broad, SunAmerica has expanded rapidly by building a sales
force of 9,500 agents and offering 20 mutual funds as part of its
variable annuities. According to Bloomberg, its stock has risen an
average of 49 percent a year for the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Broad, 65, and SunAmerica vice chairman Jay Wintrob, 41, are
expected to join the AIG board when the purchase is completed later
this year or early next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
