<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING HISPANICS SUCCEED IN CORPORATE AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Teresa McUsic 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Just Because I'm Latin Doesn't Mean I Mambo: A Success Guide
for Hispanic Americans''
</P>
<P>
   By Juan Roberto Job
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine Publishing Group
</P>
<P>
   $22.95, 241 pages
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   One of the nation's biggest minorities is getting ready to flex
its economic muscles in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic community is ``where the action is,'' according to
author and speaker Juan Roberto Job.
</P>
<P>
   And their numbers are starting to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics are the fastest-growing segment of the U.S. population
and are projected to become the largest minority in 2005. By 2050,
one out of four Americans will be Hispanic, outnumbering all other
minorities combined.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers translate into more dollars for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics annually buy $190 billion in goods and services
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that economic influence, corporate America is still
reluctant to embrace this emerging market, Job says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although mainstream America is starting to acknowledge the
importance of the Latino community, we are not easy to categorize
or understand,'' Job said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Latinos come in all shapes and sizes, from lots of
different backgrounds. We have many things in common but are
extremely diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   That richness and diversity of culture can be difficult to
market to, Job writes. It can also go against the conservative,
traditional grain of corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   Even though companies such as Sears, Coca-Cola and Office Depot
have had Hispanics in top executive positions, only 249 Hispanics
executives are at the level of vice president or above out of the
Fortune 1,000 companies last year.
</P>
<P>
   And although there are 2 million Hispanics with college degrees
in this country, the national Glass Ceiling Commission found that
most chief executives of major corporations think that only a few
Hispanics are eligible for top executive positions, Job writes.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the Hispanic community for the opportunities and
requirements of corporate America, Job has written ``Just Because
I'm Latin Doesn't Mean I Mambo: A Success Guide for Hispanic
Americans'' (Ballentine Publishing Group, New York, 241 pages,
$22.95) The book offers a frank discussion on what it takes to
succeed in corporate America and offers practical advice on
overcoming the stereotypes that may stand in the way of getting
there.
</P>
<P>
   Many Hispanics will be entering unknown territory as they embark
on a corporate career, Job writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Latinos grow up in environments removed from the world of
business. Our fathers might be civil-service workers or mechanics.
Our mothers might be teachers or full-time homemakers,'' he writes.
``We have to learn about corporate America from observing and
listening to others.'' The key is adapting to the new environment,
Job suggests. And that may mean changing ingrained habits and
behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hispanics are traditionally a modest group, Job
says, yet self-promotion is vital to a successful corporate career.
Extended family ties are also traditional to most Hispanics, yet
corporate careers can mean long hours at the office and extensive
travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cultural paradigms of corporate America tend to reflect
the Anglo-Saxon model,'' Job writes. ``As a result, Latinos who
want to pursue a business career often face tough personal choices
about values.'' Ultimately, everyone must decide on his or her own
priorities and ability or willingness to compromise, Job writes.
</P>
<P>
   This books discusses other issues relating to corporate life,
including education, unwritten rules and codes, career advancement
strategies and mentoring. A list of Hispanic professional
organizations and employee associations is provided in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous stories and quotes by Hispanics in the business world
help bring this book to life.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   COVER BLURBS
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning Every Day''
</P>
<P>
   By Lou Holtz
</P>
<P>
   Harper Business, $25
</P>
<P>
   Former Notre Dame coach Lou Holtz gives readers his ``game plan
for success'' in this book. If you love sports analogies in
business, this is your book. Holtz is now a popular motivational
speaker. His tape is the top-selling motivational video of all
time, and he was named best motivational speaker in the country for
two years, appearing before nearly all of the Fortune 500
companies. Now he has put his speech on paper. He offers 10
strategies for career and life.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping Your Job While Your Bosses are Losing Theirs''
</P>
<P>
   By Marylou Hughes
</P>
<P>
   William Neil Publishing, $16.95
</P>
<P>
   Marylou Hughes is a psychotherapist and employment assistance
counselor who addresses the tumultuous workplace and provides
survival skills in this book. After three wrenching experiences
with difficult bosses, Hughes came up with a strategy different
from just turning and running to another job. She offers her own
experience, as well as drawing from myriad management sources, to
offer alternatives to quitting in the face of bad bosses.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``365 Sales Tips for Winning Business''
</P>
<P>
   By Anne Miller
</P>
<P>
   Perigee, $11
</P>
<P>
   Anne Miller is president of a New York City-based sales
communications company with clients such as Time and GTE. Her book
offers practical business-creating ideas in 10 areas of selling
from investigating and listening to closing and following through.
Creative thinking and motivational ideas are also included. The
book is easy to read and provides a good check list of reminders
for those in the selling game.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
