</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-U.S.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. BOMBS SITES IN AFGHANISTAN AND SUDAN LINKED TO TERROR GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphics are
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See ATTACK-BINLADEN with map, ATTACK-CONGRESS, ATTACK-SECURITY,
ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-MILITARY, ATTACK-ASSESS,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-SUDAN with map, ATTACK-MEDIA,
ATTACK-WAG.) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dozens of U.S. cruise missiles struck targets in
Afghanistan and Sudan on Thursday in what President Clinton
described as an act of self-defense against imminent terrorist
plots and of fearsome retribution for the bombings of U.S.
embassies in East Africa two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes were launched from ships in the Arabian Sea and Red
Sea, executed under the cover of darkness with no U.S. casualties.
With 75 missiles aimed to explode simultaneously in unsuspecting
countries on two continents, the operation was the most formidable
U.S. military assault ever against a private sponsor of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The targets were identified by Pentagon officials as an
extensive terrorism training complex in Afghanistan, 94 miles south
of Kabul, and a factory for the building blocks of chemical weapons
near Khartoum, Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his national security team linked both sites to
Osama bin Laden, the exiled Saudi millionaire tied by U.S.
intelligence to the twin bombings on August 7 in Kenya and
Tanzania, which killed 12 Americans and nearly 300 Africans. Bin
Laden, who is in Afghanistan, apparently survived the attack, which
officials insisted was not aimed at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let our actions today send this message loud and clear,''
Clinton said in an address from the Oval Office. ``There are no
expendable American targets. There will be no sanctuary for
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The president made no apologies for ordering the strikes without
permission from Afghanistan or Sudan, saying that ``countries that
persistently host terrorists have no right to be safe havens.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton returned to the White House this afternoon from his
vacation on Martha's Vineyard, where he was trying to repair family
relations damaged by his admission Monday of an intimate
relationship with a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said they had no immediate estimate of damage
or casualties, although Defense Secretary William Cohen said the
strikes were designed to ``cause sufficient damage to disrupt them
for some time.'' Sudanese television this afternoon broadcast
images of a ravaged, burning factory under a night sky stained
orange.
</P>
<P>
   The president presented several reasons for the decision to act
swiftly and forcefully, rather than to try to punish bin Laden
through means of diplomacy and law enforcement. Repeatedly, he said
that bin Laden presented an imminent threat, quoting his vow this
week to wage a war in which Americans were ``all targets.'' He
added that ``key terrorist leaders'' were believed to be gathering
at the compound in Afghanistan on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had ``convincing'' intelligence that bin Laden's
terrorist network was behind the embassy bombings. And he accused
groups tied to bin Laden of a host of murderous attacks and foiled
plots, from killing international peacekeepers in Somalia to
planning to assassinate the pope.
</P>
<P>
   But, while the Republican leadership rallied to support the
raids, some congressmen reacted suspiciously, noting that the
action followed by just three days Clinton's acknowledgement to the
public and a grand jury of his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Administration officials scorned talk of any connection.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton's motorcade abruptly left the borrowed estate where
he was secluded with his wife and daughter, reporters and
photographers idling at the entrance assumed he was going to play
golf. They reluctantly abandoned the movie that they had begun to
watch, ``Wag the Dog,'' about a fictional president who
manufactures a phony war to distract the nation from an adulterous
liason.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton made a brief, dramatic appearance to announce
the strikes. Then, in a feat of unparalleled one-upsmanship after a
summer of jaw-dropping juxtapositions, Clinton flew to Washington
for his Oval Office address as Ms. Lewinsky was testifying for a
second time before the grand jury here.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that planning for the mission
began nine days ago, shortly after the embassy bombings August 7.
Clinton was first informed of the planning in the White House
situation room Aug. 12, and on Aug. 14 he gave tentative approval
for a mission. He gave the final go-ahead in a telephone
conversation at 3 a.m. Thursday morning with National Security
Adviser Samuel Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials denied any plan to assassinate bin Laden,
saying that they intended only to damage his network. But asked if
bin Laden was a legitimate military target, Cohen said, ``To the
extent that he and his organization have declared war upon the
United States or our interests, then he certainly is engaged in an
act of war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
