<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MOVIE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTERTAINMENT, REALITY COLLIDE IN STRIKE ON TERRORISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The line between fantasy and reality, between Hollywood and
Washington, has blurred into invisibility in this decade of
cynicism and disillusionment, in this culture of entertainment
above all else. But it snapped clearly back into view Thursday in
the wake of President Clinton's decision to bomb terrorist camps in
Afghanistan and the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   That a Hollywood movie should figure in any discussion of
Thursday's events shows only how skewed our collective sense of
so-called reality has become. One element of Thursday's reaction
consisted of cynical analogies between the US actions and the
political satire ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Wag the Dog,'' Robert De Niro's spin doctor and Dustin
Hoffman's Hollywood producer stage a phony war to divert attention
from a presidential sex scandal. They fill TV screens and
newspapers with faked images of pathos and made-up heroics of a war
America is told is taking place in the Balkans, but in reality is
unfolding on a sound stage. In doing so, they minimize coverage of
the president's peccadilloes.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the splash made by ``Wag the Dog,'' now available on
video, was the fact that it had just gone into wide release when
the Monica Lewinsky story broke in January. Clinton and those who
stand by his actions say the bombings were not politically
motivated, that the current scandal was not the reason for the air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Senator Dan Coats (R-Ind.) questioned the timing
of the air attacks, given the president's personal difficulties.
Senator Arlen Specter (R-Pa.) seconded him, adding in a milder vein
that the president's problems have to be on the minds of many
people. When special prosecutor Kenneth Starr was asked if he had
seen the movie, he laughed and said he shouldn't comment, but yes,
he had.
</P>
<P>
   Most members of Congress, including the President's severest
critics, closed ranks behind him. And a newly sobered America will
decide how much weight should be given to the skeptical
questioning, how appropriate it is to push the parallel between
fact and fantasy, whether the links between ``Wag the Dog'' and
Thursday's events represent oracular revelation or a conspiracy
theorist's wildest dreams come true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0508 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4699 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERROR-AZ-AZR &LR;      08-20 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-AZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA GOP LAWMAKERS SUPPORT AIR STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER AND ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Republican congressmen from Arizona supported
President Clinton's order of air strikes on terrorist targets in
Afghanistan and Sudan, but had different takes on whether the
president's domestic foibles helped prompt the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain predicted most Americans would support
Clinton's move. He rejected the notion that the cruise missile
strikes were designed to distract the public from the Monica
Lewinsky scandal and Clinton's admissions about it earlier in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, and unless confronted with evidence to the
contrary, I am sure, that the president of the United States acted
simply in the United States' national security interests,'' said
McCain, a former Navy pilot and current member of the Senate Armed
Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe he would place American lives in danger for
domestic political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said he was disturbed that the president did not
consult congressional leaders before the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Although he backed Clinton's move, McCain chided the president
for ``neglecting compelling national security threats'' in the last
seven months, including Saddam Hussein's ejection of U.N. weapons
inspectors from Iraq, a nuclear weapons build-up in North Korea,
the stalled Middle East peace process and the ethnic Albanian
revolt in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he hoped Clinton would address those issues, and
said he doesn't know if the Lewinsky matter was the cause of the
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can say unequivocally that they have been neglected,''
McCain said, ``and to the detriment of our interests and the
possible future risk in loss of American lives and treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain compared Thursday's ac tion to an attack on terrorists in
Libya in 1986 - a reprisal for a West Berlin bombing that killed
three U.S. servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Libyans have been quieted ever since,'' McCain said. ``I
hope that that will have the same effect on this group of
terrorists, although they are obviously very committed and very
zealous.''
</P>
<P>
   While calling Clinton's action ``fully justified,'' Sen. Jon Kyl
had his own spin on how the timing of the strikes was affected by
allegations that Clinton lied about an affair with Lewinsky while
she was a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Several other senators had said they were suspicious that
Clinton ordered the action to divert attention from his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If his own political difficulties gave him a little more
courage to do this at this time, then all the better. His actions
have not often been characterized by decisiveness and courage,''
Kyl said. ``Perhaps his own political difficulties screwed that
courage up a bit, but the important thing is he did the right thing
in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl, chairman of a Senate subcommittee on terrorism, said he was
briefed on the twin strikes just prior to the president's
announcement of the air strike's from Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   During the briefing, Kyl was told of other threats against U.S.
facilities made by the terrorist groups targeted in the attacks,
but he said he could not provide further details.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Kyl were echoed by Republican Rep. Matt Salmon. He
praised the strikes, although he has called for Clinton's
resignation over the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am supportive of this president,'' he said. ``If you commit
acts of terrorism against U.S. citizens, you will be dealt with
harshly.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said any suggestions of an ulterior motive ``bring out
the worst in us, and I certainly don't want to engage in any such
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anybody that makes accusations of that kind is putting
politics ahead of national security,'' Salmon said. ``It's
irresponsible to be making those kind of accusations. It only harms
our ability to send the right message to terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., also supported the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military action we undertook today sends a strong message:
If you attack American citizens, you will pay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this story. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
