<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN coverage faster than a speeding missile
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Less than three hours after the United States launched
Tomahawk missiles against Sudan and Afghanistan, CNN brought up a
live feed from Sudanese television. It appeared to be a ``Larry
King Live''-style talk show, with a guy at a desk taking phone
calls from Sudanese viewers, who ranted against President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a president who has more than 100 girlfriends,'' said a
caller, as a video backdrop showed a building in flames, and
wreckage and rubble in the streets of Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   What used to be a visionary concept _ the global village _ is
now a given. And we've become used to the speeding-up of the news
cycle, the round-the-clock giddyup mentality that's at the core of
CNN and the Internet, and increasingly the rest of the media.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday was a quantum leap forward, as television whipped
the news along at the speed of a Tomahawk missile. Even during the
Persian Gulf War, it was frequently 24 hours or more before CNN
viewers in America saw what American bombs had done.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sense of warp-speeding events was driven by TV news,
while for some of it, TV just hung on for the ride. President
Clinton had not even managed the brief flight from his Martha's
Vineyard vacation home back to the White House before Congressional
Republicans were questioning his motives in the timing of the air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   CNN jumped to a live press conference with Sen. Dan Coates
(R-Ind.), who took after Clinton for trying to divert attention
from the Monica Lewinsky scandal. That was right about the time
when Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich called CNN to support the
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Wag the Dog'' scenario _ named for the fictional movie in
which a president enmeshed in a sex scandal diverts the country
with a fake war _ made it onto TV with frightening swiftness. By my
wristwatch, it was a whopping two minutes after the end of
Clinton's first speech (a brief announcement at 1:55 p.m. at
Martha's Vineyard) that ABC reporter Mike Von Fremde speculated
about a connection between the air strikes and the president's
grand jury testimony and speech Monday in the Monica Lewinsky
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ABC anchor Forrest Sawyer slapped Von Fremde down almost
immediately, saying the comment was ``very unfair. I don't think
Mike meant that.'' (Von Fremde's journalistic sin was not waiting
until Coates and other Republicans put the ``Wag the Dog'' scenario
into play.) Then only a half hour later, an unidentified reporter
at Secretary of Defense William Cohen's press conference asked him
if he had seen the movie and if this was a real-life ``Wag the
Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The smoke is probably still rising on sites that were
targeted, and the motives of the president are being questioned,''
said CNN senior analyst Jeff Greenfield. (Every time Greenfield is
on, it's clear that hiring him away from ABC for his fair and
thoughtful comments is one of the best moves CNN has ever made.)
</P>
<P>
   In a strange contrast, the TV news day on Thursday began like a
different movie, ``Groundhog Day,'' replaying the same sequence
over and over. The scene was of Lewinsky getting out of a car and
stepping into the courthouse in Washington, where she testified
again before Kenneth Starr's grand jury. CNN showed it live shortly
before 9 a.m., then replayed the same Monica-enters-the-building
video snippet seven times in two hours, sometimes in slow-motion.
</P>
<P>
   From slow motion to breakneck speed. There are times when
television is so much the same you want to scream, and times, like
Thursday, when it is extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer is a television critic for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
