<SLUG> BC-WAGDOG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Wag the Dog' _ Some believe it's a movie whose time has come
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Right in the middle of a press conference discussing
Thursday's U.S. bombing of Afghanistan and Sudan, Defense Secretary
William Cohen was asked about a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Had he seen ``Wag the Dog,'' director Barry Levinson's film
about a fictional spin doctor (Robert De Niro) and a Hollywood
producer (Dustin Hoffman) who stage a mock war to divert America's
attention from a sex scandal involving the president and a young,
female White House visitor?
</P>
<P>
   Cohen was quick to respond. He said the only motivation for
Thursday's maneuvers was ``our absolute obligation to protect the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it ```Wag the Dog' Strikes Back.''
</P>
<P>
   A switchboard operator at Levinson's Baltimore Pictures sounded
harried Thursday afternoon. ``Are you calling for a quote?'' she
asked, adding, ``It's been crazy here.''
</P>
<P>
   The phone had rung all afternoon, with journalists questioning
(once again) the connection between the Hollywood comedy and
Washington politics.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. bombings, coming only three days after President
Clinton's confession of an ``inappropriate relationship'' with
White House intern Monica Lewinsky, may look to some like Hollywood
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in seven months, the line between show biz
and politics had grown fuzzy. Three weeks after ``Wag'' opened last
December, allegations of Clinton's liaison with former intern
Monica Lewinsky hit the news.
</P>
<P>
   As for the unfortunate parallels between the movie and the
military action, it has struck more than just journalists. ``The
connection did come to mind,'' said Jerry Rubenstein, owner of
Movies Worth Seeing in Atlanta on Thursday afternoon. But that
doesn't mean there was an instant rush on the tape. ``I haven't
seen any response like that, but it may be too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, ``Wag the Dog'' probably doesn't need the extra plug.
In video stores since the end of June, this week it ranked No. 6 on
the national list of top tape rentals.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray is a film critic for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
