<HEADER>
A4704 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-RAUSCHENBERG-2TAK     08-20 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-RAUSCHENBERG-2TAKES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAUSCHENBERG'S REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH BAKER  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Robert Rauschenberg did not foresee that he
would pose for a photographer in front of his 1954 painting
``Collection'' at the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art last
Friday. Yet he happened to wear a sand-colored suit, red silk shirt
and orange tie of the same hues that permeate the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Serendipity has marked equally Rauschenberg's work and his life,
which took him from a poor boyhood in Port Arthur, Texas, to being
a world figure in art, which he became when he got the grand prize
at the 1964 Venice Biennale. His idea that art is reality
reshuffled pervades our cultural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Rauschenberg was so colorfully dressed, he explained over an
ice-choked glass of wine, because he had lunch with Phyllis Wattis,
the 94-year-old SFMOMA trustee who funded the museum's recent
purchase of more than a dozen early pieces from Rauschenberg's
cache of his own work. His drawl slowly lengthened as the wine
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 93-year-old mother,'' he said, ``so I know it helps
to wear bright colors so they can see where you are.''
</P>
<P>
   At 72, Rauschenberg himself is no longer the lithe figure who
combined dance, painting and stage design in the '50s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   He moves stiffly now, his posture hunched, his hair mostly gray.
But mischievous energy still flashes in his eyes, his smile and his
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wonders why Rauschenberg agreed to let SFMOMA acquire
his pivotal early works, including the 22-foot-long ``Automobile
Tire Print'' (1953) and the famous ``Erased de Kooning Drawing''
(1953), a crayon-and-ink drawing that Rauschenberg coaxed from the
abstract expressionist master, then laboriously effaced. Every
modern art museum in the world covets these objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal was shocking,'' Rauschenberg admitted. ``At first
I couldn't imagine living without the `Tire Print' or the `Erased
de Kooning.' The anticipation was that they would go to the Museum
of Modern Art in New York. When San Francisco was interested, I had
a little difficulty switching over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I had assumed that they'd end up in New York
was because most of them were made there, and New York is the
gateway to Europe. But San Francisco is the door to the other half
of the world. I, of all people, should have realized this more
quickly because I've done a lot of work in Japan, in Indonesia, in
China. Yet the only way I could really separate myself from these
things in good conscience was to form a partnership with a museum
to make a continuing in-depth survey of my work.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether that meant that the San Francisco museum would get
other important early works, he sidestepped the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the essence,'' he said of the pieces SFMOMA has just
acquired. They are now traveling with his mammoth retrospective but
will be shown here sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything is going to be more painful to part
with in the future,'' Rauschenberg said. ``Yet I knew rationally
that I wanted them someplace where they could be seen by people. I
didn't want them to be part of somebody else's ego or somebody's
profit. They are not just objects, they are evidence of events.''
</P>
<P>
   Rauschenberg is unfazed by criticism of his retrospective for
being overstuffed. It filled three venues in New York and three in
Houston. It opens in November at the Guggenheim Museum Bilbao in
Spain, its final stop.
</P>
<P>
   What bothers him is its air of finality and its emotional toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``De Kooning was very superstitious and refused (New York) MOMA
a retrospective time and time again because he knew too many people
who had died right after theirs,'' Rauschenberg recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm a little superstitious, too, so I just want to get out
of this and recover from it. I'm involved in every aspect of my
retrospective. I have been experiencing emotional fatigue from
having to deliver over and over again moments of my past. I'm
feeling very skittery about the work I'm doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the studio, he is currently working with vegetable dye
transfers of computer-enlarged, composite photographs, most of
which he has taken himself.
</P>
<P>
   The most moving aspect of his retrospective, Rauschenberg said,
``is the international appreciation, not of me as a personality,
but of individual objects. This is what I thought of when I started
ROCI'' _ the now-dissolved Rauschenberg Overseas Cultural
Interchange _ ``that images go beyond translation, no matter how
exotic or controversial they are in a given setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Under ROCI, which lasted from 1984 to 1991, Rauschenberg and his
assistants traveled around the world at his expense, collaborating
with artists and craftsmen largely in countries where democracy was
still a distant prospect. Whatever these travels did for artists
elsewhere, they netted Rauschenberg a lot of new work and some
criticism that he was grandstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``ROCI was dissolved when I ran out of money,'' he said. ``I had
to sell my Twomblys, my Johnses, my Warhols, and I ran out of
people to buy my Rauschenbergs. But ROCI still echoes around the
world. In Beijing, if somebody says they're an artist, they ask,
`Pre-Rauschenberg or post-?' Same thing in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rauschenberg continues to fund Change Inc., a foundation that
helps artists with small sums for non-art needs such as emergency
medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Rauschenberg retrospective's tour has not been untroubled.
The day it opened in Houston, police seized several important
pieces, including a couple purchased by SFMOMA, as a lien against
damages awarded to two Austin, Texas, art consultants who sued the
artist and two of his representatives for breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not supposed to talk about that,'' Rauschenberg said.
``Legally, we have what's called an amicable resolution. The works
were back on the wall the next day. It's the first time I've had
all the press on my side. I can't say it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rauschenberg acknowledges seeing his artistic influence
everywhere, but he thinks that critics misrepresent things when
they place him in confrontation with the generation before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't working against anything,'' he said of his early
career. ``People tried to insist that Jasper Johns and I did the
kind of work we did because we were against abstract expressionism.
But I used Vermeer, Leonardo, Ben Shahn, anything in history. If
you need it, it's what you do. I've never accepted the aesthetic
limitation of doing something to the exclusion of something else.
That's negative, there's no energy there. I just backed off from
abstract expressionism because they had their space and I didn't
feel at home in it, even though I didn't have a home.''
</P>
<P>
   The current critical fashion is to discover ``gay content'' in
Rauschenberg's early work that could not be acknowledged openly in
the '50s. The most famous example is Robert Hughes' reading of
Rauschenberg's ``Monogram'' (1955-59), a painted canvas on its
back, surmounted by a stuffed Angora goat with an old tire around
its midriff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one asks why it became so famous,'' Hughes writes of
``Monogram,'' ``the answer can only lie in its power ... as a
sexual fetish. The lust of the goat, as William Blake remarked, is
the glory of God; and this one, halfway through the tire, is an
image of anal sex, the satyr in the sphincter.''
</P>
<P>
   After Rauschenberg read this, he recalled, ``I ran into Hughes
on the street, and said, `If you feel that way about auto tires, I
don't know how you live in New York. How do you cross a street?'''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretation ``just gets carried too far,'' Rauschenberg
complained. ``With the concepts of Freudian sexual symbolism and so
forth, you almost can't look at anything for what it is. I find
myself inhibited by trying avoid symbolism that really isn't in the
picture. If I wanted a penis in a picture, I'd put a penis in a
picture. I don't leave anything to the imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   The current project that excites Rauschenberg most is a
commission from the Vatican to decorate a cathedral designed by
Renzo Piano, a shrine to the Franciscan healer Padre Pio, who is
soon to be canonized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having to go back to working on silk,'' Rauschenberg said,
``because of the requirements of the space _ 150 feet wide by 45
feet high. They are insistent that the piece be reverent of Padre
Pio's healing work, but the first assignment I've got is the
Apocalypse, which is a natural for me, but not a natural for
healing. Frankly, I'm having trouble with the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Rome recently, I made a trip to the Vatican and
checked out the competition and thought, `That's not it.'''
</P>
<P>
   He is still struggling with the details. ``It has to be done a
week before the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
