<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0520 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WAG-HNS &LR;      08-20 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WAG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME QUESTION TIMING OF ATTACK, SEE SIMILARITIES TO `WAG THE DOG' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ The eerie similarities struck 16-year-old
Brad Chaffee immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night he and his vacationing family watched a video of
``Wag the Dog,'' the movie about a president embroiled in a sex
scandal who stages a phony war to distract the public.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon Chaffee stood in an elementary school
gymnasium watching President Clinton, embroiled in a sex scandal,
announce the bombing of suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan
and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walks in here after he announces the scandals and he says
we're attacking a terrorist base,'' an excited Chaffee said. ``It
parallels the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager wasn't the only one to notice the connection
between President Clinton's personal crisis and an international
crisis and wonder about the timing and its impact. And the
administration found itself having to answer questions about the
motivation for its military action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only motivation driving this action today was our absolute
obligation to protect the American people from terrorist
activities. That is the sole motivation. No other consideration has
been involved,'' said Defense Secretary William Cohen, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, military action generates public support for
presidents,
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that at this point we rally around the president
unless we have reasons not to. We have to assume the president of
the United States, the secretary of defense, the chairman of the
joint chiefs of staff, the director of the FBI are acting in our
interests,'' said Stephen Hess, a presidential scholar at the
Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have room to get cynical later if for any reason we learn
things that we don't now know,'' Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   The president made a surprise appearance before reporters here
just hours after Monica Lewinsky resumed her testimony before a
Washington grand jury, providing more details about her 18-month
affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement of the U.S. retaliation came just as Clinton
appeared to hit his own political nadir. Politicians and pundits
panned his address to the nation Monday night in which he admitted
to an ``inappropriate relationship'' and expressed regret, but did
not say he was sorry. The president's job approval ratings have
remained strong in public opinion surveys this week, but his
personal standing has fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (White House) political types did not have a clue (about
the impending bombing). This whole operation was out of
Washington,'' said a senior aide traveling with the president.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said, ``I think the merits of the
issue and the need to go in speak for themselves. The facts will
stand on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Republican leadership voiced strong support for the
decision strike back at the terrorists, others were not as
generous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the timing here is extraordinary,'' said Sen. Daniel
Coats, R-Ind. ``The reaction of the president is so
uncharacteristic of anything he has done in his six years of a
presidency that it raises legitimate questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., noted the U.S. retaliation came the
same day of news reports that the White House staff was attempting
to refocus attention away from Clinton's personal problems and onto
his presidential duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an obvious question that will be raised
internationally ... as to whether there is any diversionary motive
involved,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Judiciary
Committee and a leading critic of Clinton on the Lewinsky affair,
voiced support for Clinton's decision and urged others to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to applaud the president. I want to give him credit for
being willing to take this action at this time,'' Hatch said.
Earlier this week, Hatch called Clinton ``a jerk'' for criticizing
independent counsel Kenneth Starr during the president's address to
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement gave the vacationing president the opportunity
to take full advantage of his presidential trappings.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House spokesman, had just began a daily
press briefing at the Edgartown School gym, describing the coconut
birthday cake and the blue sweater the president received for his
52nd birthday Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The press pool that always follows the president had just
settled under a white tent at the edge of the estate where the
Clintons are vacationing and ordered a pay-per-view movie from the
satellite hook-up.
</P>
<P>
   The movie? ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to reporters at the school, McCurry was killing
time. He received first a paged message and then a note that
Clinton had left the estate, cueing him to inform reporters that
the president would be in the filing center in 10 minutes to make a
national security announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton swept into the area that also included the Chaffee
family, who came just to glimpse the White House press corps and
McCurry in action. The president dramatically announced the U.S.
military action and that he was interrupting his vacation to return
to the White House for a national security briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, the national security adviser, said
``operational secrecy'' made it imperative that none of Clinton's
foreign policy team be seen on Martha's Vineyard, an island off the
Massachusetts coast.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three hours later, Clinton made a nationwide address from
the Oval Office to explain the reasons behind his action.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
