<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS SIGN JOHNSON TO 5-YEAR, $25 MILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ With each new signing, NFL owners seem to
move one step closer to the guaranteed problems that plague Major
League Baseball and the NBA. Thursday the Patriots inched pro
football nearer to the kind of guaranteed contracts that have made
NBA and MLB players all but unmanageable. They signed middle
linebacker Ted Johnson to a five-year, $25 million contract
extension that includes $8 million in guaranteed bonuses and an
option that all but weds the team to him until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The total deal is worth $25.4 million because it includes the
$403,000 salary Johnson was already contracted to receive this
season. It also includes a two-tiered signing bonus in which he
receives $3 million immediately and another $5 million next year,
when the extension kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   That bit of creative accounting allowed the Patriots to offer
Johnson the kind of money he and agent Jack Mills were seeking and
stay under the salary cap. The Patriots now can prorate the value
of the $3 million bonus over six years ($500,000 in cap value per
season) and the additional $5 million over five years (an added cap
value of $1 million a year beginning in 1999), a feature that made
the deal cap-friendly for the team.
</P>
<P>
   Those concessions were helpful for the Patriots, who still hope
to sign cornerback Ty Law before he becomes a free agent next
February. But to get them, New England had to agree to a deal
structure that makes it virtually impossible to release Johnson
before the end of the contract because of the acceleration onto the
cap of the bonus money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a two-year deal with an option for four more
years, but the economics are such that they can't afford not to
extend,'' Mills explained. Thursday ``If they don't exercise the
option, they have to buy out the rest of the contract. It wouldn't
make sense to pay us $5 million to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, this contract is pretty high as far as guaranteed
money goes. We have more guaranteed money than (Levon) Kirkland
(the Pittsburgh Steelers' All-Pro linebacker, who has $4.8 million
of his $28 million deal guaranteed, according to Mills). You still
don't see many guaranteed deals out there. The preferred way by NFL
owners is to guarantee bonuses, but the higher the bonus you get,
the more cap money on the books if they try to release the player.
It's a built-in protection.''
</P>
<P>
   If New England fails to exercise the option, it would take a $5
million hit on its cap next season, a figure it would be virtually
impossible to absorb and still keep players like Law, safety Lawyer
Milloy, and center Dave Wohlabaugh. Hence the belief that for all
intents and purposes, Johnson, a fourth-year veteran, now has a
contract that will pay him into his ninth professional season and
possibly beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted is very likely to collect all this money, and it could be
more,'' Mills said. ``If he's in prime time, I'd expect they'd come
and renegotiate it at some point. If he's still playing well, I
don't think they'll want him to become a free agent in his ninth
year.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, it would be a financial moot point because Johnson
would be set for life, even if his play had begun to slip, as did
that of his predecessor, Vincent Brown, once knee injuries plagued
him. While the Patriots could probably swallow letting Johnson go
with a year remaining on the deal if neccessary, anything more than
that seems problematic, a problem similar to what Mills said the
Dallas Cowboys now face with running back Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do that, you've got to be prepared to take a pretty big hit
on your cap,'' Mills said. ``That's the situation the Cowboys find
themselves in. They thought they were being really creative. Now
they're seeing they can't afford to let Emmitt go. It could blow
your cap apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, both Johnson and the Patriots believe this is not a
concern. It is their shared belief that he is just beginning to
emerge as one of the AFC's top inside linebackers after leading the
team in tackles the past two saeason and being named a Pro Bowl
alternate a year ago. Barring injury, they believe they are on safe
ground with the 25-year-old Johnson despite the guaranteed nature
of his newly signed deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A while back, when these discussions came up, I supported this
move all the way,'' said Patriots coach Pete Carroll. ``We were
real strong about it. There was no doubt what we wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clear statement that we're making an investment with
people of his character who stand for everything we believe is
important. We can see where he's going. He's becoming a master at
his position.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson does, his contract will be a bargain down the road.
If he doesn't, it could become an albatross. That is the gamble NFL
owners are now taking more and more as they sign young athletes to
contracts that are not guaranteed by law but are fully guaranteed
by the league's new accounting process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
