<SLUG> BC-US-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US BLASTS TERRORIST TARGETS IN AFGHANISTAN, SUDAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ US forces launched a pair of night missile attacks
Thursday on what officials described as a ``terrorist university''
in the hills of Afghanistan and a terrorist-sponsored chemical
plant in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes were in direct retaliation for the bombings of two
US embassies in Africa two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The action came as US intelligence officials reported that key
terrorist leaders from across the region planned to gather Thursday
at the Afghanistan training facility, considered a preeminent
terrorist matrix in the world. It also followed intelligence gained
by US officials anticipating a fresh round of terrorist attacks on
American targets, possibly more overseas embassies.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton gave final orders for the attacks around dawn
Thursday from his borrowed vacation compound on Martha's Vineyard,
made a hasty announcement in Edgartown, Mass., on the island, early
Thursday afternoon, then rushed back to Washington for meetings in
the White House situation room to deliver an Oval Office address.
The operation had been planned in secret in the prior two weeks,
senior officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we have struck back,'' Clinton said in the makeshift
briefing room at the Edgartown School before he left. He added:
``Terrorists must have no doubt that in the face of their threats,
America will protect its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   From the Oval Office, Clinton said, ``Let our actions today send
this message loud and clear: There are no expendable American
targets. There will be no sanctuary for terrorists. We will defend
our people, our interests and our values.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke from Martha's Vineyard and shuttled back to the
White House, former intern Monica Lewinsky appeared again before
the federal grand jury investigating her relationship with the
president -- in a stark contrast that prompted two Republican
senators, Dan Coats of Indiana and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania,
to openly question Clinton's motives in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an obvious issue here of whether there were any
diversionary motives involved,'' said Specter.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican and Democratic leaders, who had been kept
apprised of the plans by White House national security officials,
offered universal and strong support for the operation, as is
customary in the wake of US military strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US did exactly the right thing,'' said House Speaker Newt
Gingrich. ``We cannot allow a terrorist group to attack US
embassies and do nothing. We cannot afford to have people think
they can kill Americans without any consequence. This was exactly
the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the timing of the strikes, Secretary of Defense
William Cohen said, ``The only motivation driving this action today
was our absolute obligation to protect the American people from
terrorist activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the US targeted terrorist operations and sites
financed by Osama bin Laden, a multimillionaire Saudi exile who has
openly declared war on the United States and is the main suspect in
the twin embassy bombings in the capitals of Tanzania and Kenya on
August 7 -- attacks in which a dozen Americans and over 200
Africans were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's strikes, using Tomahawk cruise missiles with 1,000
pound warheads launched from ships in the Red and Arabian seas,
were aimed against a sprawling paramilitary training center in
Afghanistan operated and funded by bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   The second target was the Shifa Pharmaceutical plant in Sudan's
capital city of Khartoum. The facililty is suspected of making the
chemical agent used in the production of a deadly nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know with great certainty it produces the penultimate
chemical that goes into VX nerve gas,'' said Samuel (Sandy) Berger,
Clinton's national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The first missiles rained down at about 1:30 p.m. EDT, which is
7:30 p.m. in Sudan and 10 p.m. in Afghanistan. The attacks
continued for about an hour, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sudanese television footage showed the Shifa plant engulfed in
flames, with significant damage. Bloodied men were carried out on
stretchers, though there was no definitive estimate of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they intentionally bombed the
plant, located in an industrial complex, in the evening in order to
minimize casulualties among workers.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said they are uncertain how much damage the
missiles caused at the Afghanistan training sites, which included a
storage facility, a weapons training center, administrative offices
and housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bases provide refuges for terrorists and train
terrorists for tactics and use of international weapons,'' said
General Hugh Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how many terrorists, if any, were killed in the
raids, which were launched under the cover of darkness. US
officials stopped short of declaring the mission a success, and
they admitted they did not know if bin Laden had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea of bin Laden's whereabouts or whether he was
in the camp at that time,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Taliban, the ruling party of Afghanistan,
said bin Laden was not at the site at the time and was not killed.
After the attacks, the FBI immediately warned all local law
enforcement agencies to be on a heightened level of alert for
possible terrorist retaliation on US soil. Embassy officials abroad
were also warned, as were US travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, most US diplomats and their families fled the
embassy in Pakistan out of a fear for another embassy bombing. This
move came as US officials gathered key intelligence data that
showed more attacks were planned in the terrorist world, officials
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was executed with such extraordinary secrecy that
no US troops or ships were moved in the attack for fear of calling
attention to the plan. Also, no senior US national security
officials traveled to Martha's Vineyard this week to meet Clinton
so as not to alert news reporters covering the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0524 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-USSTRIKES-CHEMICA     08-20 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-USSTRIKES-CHEMICAL0821 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTACKS FOLLOWED GROWING CONCERNS ABOUT PRODUCTION OF DEADLY VX
GAS IN SUDAN
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH and ANDREW ALEXANDER
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. attack on a chemical plant in Sudan
Thursday followed reports of growing concern among Western
intelligence agencies that facilities for the production of deadly
VX nerve gas had been secretly shipped to Sudan from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Jane's Intelligence Review, published by the authoritative,
London-based weapons information company, reported earlier this
week that United Nations arms inspectors and U.S. intelligence
officials believe equipment for production of VX that disappeared
from Iraq in mid-1995 and wound up in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Besides striking purported terrorist camps operated in
Afghanistan by renegade Saudi businessman and self-described
terrorism sponsor Osama bin Laden, U.S. Tomahawk cruise missiles
were used to bomb a ``Shifa Phamaceuticals'' chemical plant in
Khartoum, the Sudanese capital.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen and a senior intelligence
official told reporters Thursday the facility was turning out
precursor chemicals for VX production.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence official also told reporters at a Pentagon
briefing that the plant was part of a Sudanese enterprise formally
known as ``the Military-Industrial Complex,'' which has been
financially supported by Bin Laden. Sudanese officials insisted the
plant produced only pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   VX is an abbreviation for a 62-letter chemical term (which
contains no Vs and no Xs). Colorless and odorless, the chemical is
the most toxic nerve agent known, many times deadlier than hydrogen
cyanide gas. By blocking an enzyme that regulates nerve impulses,
it causes uncontrolled spasms and within minutes, death.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do know is that this facility that was targeted in
Khartoum produced the precursor chemicals that would allow the
production of a type of VX nerve agent,'' Cohen said. The
intelligence official at Cohen's briefing went further:
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we know that Bin Laden has made financial contributions
to the Sudanese Military-Industrial Complex. That's a distinct
entity of which, we believe, the Shifa pharmaceutical facility is
part. We know with high confidence that Shifa produces a precursor
that is unique to the production of VX. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Butler, chairman of the United Nations Special
Commission that oversees the destruction of Iraqi weapons, has said
he believes 20 shipping containers with VX production equipment
disappeared from Iraq in mid-1995.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne's Intelligence Review reported Monday that U.S.
intelligence officials believe these containers were taken to
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also reported on minutes of a two-day secret
meeting in Khartoum last October at which Sudanese officials
purportedly were assured of financial support from Bin Laden for
construction of a ``chemical and bacterial weapons factory'' in
Kubar, a suburb of Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the meeting agreed that the plant should be
brought into production ``as soon as possible,'' the magazine said
minutes of the meeting showed.
</P>
<P>
   Javed Ali, principal author of Jane's ``Chemical and Biological
Defense Guidebook,'' said VX has been around for about 50 years,
but only two countries, Russia and Iraq, have ever acknowledged
producing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not cutting edge technology,'' Ali said in an
interview. ``The British first developed the chemical in the late
1940s.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the chemicals that become VX when mixed together are
widely produced for peaceful reasons in many countries, especially
in the manufacture of pesticides, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob May, a farmer from eastern Arkansas who is in Sudan with a
group of Americans studying Christianity there, said Thursday that
he believes the factory was used exclusively to manufacture
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have met some doctors here and they say the plant provides
90 percent of all medicines in this country,'' said May, who was
reached by phone in Khartoum several hours after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   May said the mood in Khartoum Thursday night was one of
puzzlement more than anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question in the Sudanese peoples' minds is: 'What in the
world does this have to do with Osama bin Laden?''' Why would the
U.S. direct an attack on this city (when) in fact they exiled him
from Sudan two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's attack is ``going to get the people aroused'' in the
coming days, he said. ``I think it may have been a mistake. It's
certainly put a lot of puzzlement on people's faces. ``
</P>
<P>
   But a security official at a downtown Khartoum hotel suggested
otherwise. Asked in a telephone interview what was produced at the
factory, he said: ``Between you and me, chemicals. They could be
used for chemical weapons. I know because I have very wide eyes. I
can tell when I look.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in recent years Libyans had worked at the factory,
ostensibly producing insecticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very clever here,'' he said, suggesting that the
insecticide production was a cover. ``They can hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a curious coincidence of names caused the chairman of
a Syrian pharmaceutical manufacturer to announce following the
bombing that he would attempt to sue the Sudanese pharmaceutical
company for ``stealing our name.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard of these people because we export drugs to Iraq
under U.N. approval,'' said Imad Sabouni, chairman of Shifa
Pharmaceutical Industries of Aleppo, Syria. ``They also attempted
to sell to Iraq and that is when we learned that they also use the
name Shifa.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabouni also said in a telephone interview that his company had
no relationship with Bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God! Oh, my God! What is going on?'' Sabouni cried when
told that a pharmaceutical company with the same name as his
company's had been bombed for producing nerve gas precursors.
``Really, we do not have any relation with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabouni said that in Arabic the word ``Shifa'' means ``cure from
illness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are sick, they lie in bed and cry, 'Please, God,
give me me Shifa,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
