<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0525 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4728 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USSTRIKES-MAIN-0821-C     08-20 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USSTRIKES-MAIN-0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. ATTACKS TWO SITES LINKED TO TERRORIST BOMBINGS
 &HT;    With USSTRIKES-CHEMICALS-0821; USSTRIKES-CONGRESS-0821;
USSTRIKES-SUDAN-0821; USSTRIKES-AFGHANISTAN-0821;
USSTRIKES-INTERNET-0821.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In mounting twin strikes at what President Clinton
called ``terrorist-related facilities in Afghanistan and Sudan,''
the United States on Thursday launched a hail of cruise missiles as
a lethal message to fundamentalist Islamic terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the missiles were aimed at the terrorist network
run by Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born multi-millionaire said to be
behind the deadly truck bombings of two American embassies in East
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans on Capitol Hill, as well as critics abroad,
questioned whether Clinton, as commander-in-chief of the world's
only remaining superpower, had also sought to defuse his political
problems by approving the military attacks just three days after
having admitted he had ``misled people'' about his adulterous
affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   As independent counsel Ken Starr summoned Lewinsky to appear for
a second time before the grand jury that is looking into whether
Clinton had perjured himself, White House officials bristled at the
notion that the military strikes might have been timed by a
domestic political need to draw public attention away from the sex
scandal,
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reason to believe that a gathering of key terrorist
leaders was to take place (at bin Laden's Afghan base) today, thus
underscoring the urgency of our actions,'' Clinton asserted in a
speech from the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen days after the twin bombings in Kenya and Tanzania
killed 263 people, including 12 Americans, the president responded
by ordering nearly simultaneous strikes from naval vessels and a
submarine poised in both the Arabian and Red Seas.
</P>
<P>
   The Tomahawk missiles hit the bin Laden camp, about 95 miles
south of the Afghan capital of Kabul, and the El Shifa
pharmaceutical plant, in an industrial section of Khartoum, the
Sudanese capital, causing extensive damage and casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Denouncing the raid as a ``terrorist crime,'' Sudanese officials
said the privately owned factory manufactured only children's
medicines and malaria drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton interrupted his vacation on Martha's Vineyard to deliver
his seven-minute Oval Office address declaring an open-ended war on
Islamic ``fanatics.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave final approval for the raids, which began at 1:30 p.m.
EDT, shortly before dawn in Edgartown, Mass. And he was the first
to announce them, some 25 minutes after they began.
</P>
<P>
   In returning without his family to the White House -- shortly
after announcing the strikes in a terse speech at Edgartown --
Clinton also met with his top national security team and conferred
by phone with various world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is convincing information from our intelligence
community that the Bin Laden terrorist network was responsible''
for the recent carnage in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also said there was ``compelling evidence that the
Bin Laden network of terrorist groups was planning to mount further
attacks against Americans and other freedom-loving people.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither the president nor any of his national security
advisers made public any specific information linking the
41-year-old bin Laden, who was said to have escaped injury, to the
embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, all but essential U.S. personnel have been
evacuated from U.S. embassies in Islamabad, Pakistan, and Tirana,
Albania, indicating that both sites could serve as fresh terrorist
targets.
</P>
<P>
   In a White House briefing that came almost immediately after
Clinton's Oval Office address, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said ``high-threat warnings'' have been issued to some
unspecified U.S. embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Albright added: ``We are very concerned about what is going on
internationally, which is why we are gathering international
support and why the president believed the seriousness of the
moment was one that required him to come back to Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger, who shared
the podium with Albright, revealed that the ``FBI has issued an
alert to all local law enforcement officials about the heightened
degree of concern (over terrorism) that they ought to manifest in
their work.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger also told reporters that the strike against the Sudanese
plant, from two ships in the Red Sea, was timed for the early
evening, in an effort, made at Clinton's specific request, to
minimize the loss of civilian life. He declined to give a number of
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   CIA Director George Tenet said that Bin Laden, who had been
ejected from Sudan at U.S. urging in May 1996, wanted chemical
weapons and that the Khartoum plant -- which Sudanese officials
claimed was being used solely to produce antibiotics and other
medicines -- could produce components for the deadly nerve agent
VX.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials place the Afghan camp -- comprising six sites,
including training and storage areas -- in another category: It was
deemed to be fair game as a military target.
</P>
<P>
   They said they had no information what damage, if any, the 50 or
so Tomahawks hurled against that complex, from four ships and a
sub, had caused. Nor, they said, did they know whether Bin Laden
had survived the U.S. raid.
</P>
<P>
   But Abdul Hai Mutmaen, a spokesman for the Islamic Taliban
movement, which rules most of Afghanistan, and which has been
harboring Bin Laden, said the terrorist chief had escaped the
strike without harm.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes were backed by several key lawmakers, including
House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia, one of the three top
congressional leaders who was informed beforehand of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think based on what I know that it was the right thing to do
at the right time . . . and I think it's been done in a methodical,
professional way,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., a member of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, told reporters in Philadelphia that ``there
is an obvious issue, which will be raised internationally, about
the response here as to whether there is any diversionary motive
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter cited earlier reports that the administration had been
negotiating with Afghan officials over turning over Bin Laden and
that the FBI ``has been conducting an investigation which might
lead to a prosecution if individuals were taken into custody.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said he saw no connection
between the timing of the strikes and Clinton's personal woes, he
added: ``However, it does remind us of the importance of the
president's credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
