<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBICLES-SIDE20-COX     08-20 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBICLES-SIDE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The evolution of the cubicle
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1950s _ Hamburg consultants Eberhard and Wolfgang Schnelle,
known as the Quickborner team, study the effect of office settings
on productivity. Theory develops that office workers are relatively
capable and do not need to be surveyed constantly.
</P>
<P>
   1960s _ A new breed of employee joins the U.S. work force: the
``professional,'' needing more space than a clerical worker but
less than a supervisor. IBM, Ford and DuPont experiment with office
designs: free-standing screens for privacy, desks arranged in
clusters. Bob Propst of Herman Miller in Zeeland, Mich., designs
the first ``cubicle.''
</P>
<P>
   1970s _ Quickborner theory takes off in America and leads to
primitive cubicles. In 1976, the power-equipped panel is invented
(where your phone and machinery are hooked up). Sales soar.
</P>
<P>
   1980s _ Economic boom brings heady times to cubicles.
Hierarchies flourish; some companies have as many as 14 grades of
cubicles _ the more powerful the employee, the better the cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   1990s _ Corporate down-sizing hurts cubicle diversity. Some
companies cut back to one standard cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   Cubicle chatter
</P>
<P>
   Cubicle design experts at Haworth Inc., in Holland, Mich.,
coined these terms for what we do in our cubicles:
</P>
<P>
   Chunking _ The way we remember things by association. A chunking
device would be a box to deposit papers you don't have time to do
something more meaningful with.
</P>
<P>
   Churn rate _ The speed by which employees are put on and taken
off teams.
</P>
<P>
   Hot desking _ Moving to a different work space each day because
you don't have an assigned desk. A downside of hot desking is that
you don't have the benefit of ``cognitive artifacts'' _ that is,
the little notes, ``in'' piles and other reminders you place around
your work space.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0532 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBICLES20-COX     08-20 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBICLES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cool cubicles, islands in a sea of conformity
 &HT;    (EDS: Photos available from New York Times News Service)
 &HT;    By Michele Chan Santos
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the cubicles everyone in the office knows about.
They're the ones that show up on unofficial tours, attract kids
visiting the office, and offer a giggle, a smile or just a ``Hey,
that's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   In a desert of charcoal-colored panels, they stand out like
oases, cheerful and funky reminders of the world outside.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 percent of white-collar workers _ that's 40 million
Americans _ work in a cubicle every day. In the Austin area, where
109,000 high-tech workers and 128,000 government workers are
employed, that percentage may be even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, in the hands of creative Central Texans, even the
most sterile of spaces comes vividly to life.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Somerville and Warren Alverson
</P>
<P>
   What they do: Software engineers, Smart Technologies
</P>
<P>
   What makes their cubicles cool: A thatched rattan-and-bamboo
roof. Somerville and Alverson's cubicles are side-by-side, and the
bright lights on the ceiling were giving them headaches as they
worked on their computers. (They were first inspired by fellow
engineer Craig Dunn, who has his cubicle enclosed with a roof and
dark green shower curtain.) Somerville devised the screen, using
mats and real bamboo, and built it over the course of three
weekends. The structure shades their area, makes the work easier on
their eyes, and gives their office a ``Gilligan's Island'' kind of
style.
</P>
<P>
   Why they did it: ``We work too much to not pretend we're on
vacation,'' Somerville says of the 8-to 20-hour days he and
Alverson log at their desks. ``We need a hammock.''
</P>
<P>
   So if their office is Gilligan's Island, who is the Skipper and
who is Gilligan? ``We both want to be the Professor,'' Somerville
says.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McAfee
</P>
<P>
   What he does: Vice president and creative director, GSD&AMP;M
advertising agency
</P>
<P>
   What makes his cubicle cool: His desk. It combines an old Jack
in the Box restaurant booth with a fish-shaped table. The collage
on the surface of the table incorporates pictures of floating doll
heads, cupids, sharks, flowers and eyeballs. Mounted on top of the
green-and-yellow restaurant seats are miniature plastic nuns and
hula girls, waving on tiny springs. McAfee got the desk from
friends who used to own ``Studio Suave'' on 29th Street. He'd
noticed it in their kitchen and always liked it. Artist Aletha
Reppell created the collage. The booth was ``too intense'' to put
in his home, but it went well with the bright and colorful interior
of GSD&AMP;M's offices. ``I like the idea of unique office spaces,''
McAfee says. ``It's amazing how important the atmosphere you work
in is.''
</P>
<P>
   What else is in his office: Black and white photos of friends,
prints from his mom.
</P>
<P>
   What he's thinking of adding: A love seat.
</P>
<P>
   Peggie Laser
</P>
<P>
   What she does: Project Manager, Management Information Systems,
Texas Department of Human Resources
</P>
<P>
   What makes her cubicle cool: Her pet rose-haired tarantula,
``Red Hot Chili Pepper,'' or ``Chili,'' for short. Chili lives in a
glass aquarium on Laser's desk. Every two weeks, Laser feeds Chili
a dozen live crickets or grasshoppers. Chili sinks her fangs into
them, paralyzes them, and sucks their insides out. Feeding time is
a popular attraction among Laser's co-workers. Every six months,
Chili sheds, leaving behind a skin that ``looks like another whole
spider,'' Laser says. There's a drawing in the office to determine
who gets to bring Chili's old skin home _ great for the kids'
show-and-tell.
</P>
<P>
   What else is in the cubicle: A photo of Willie Nelson and George
Strait at a golf tournament, signed by Strait; a plastic floating
eyeball; a picture of Laser with Darrell Royal; autographed photos
of Houston Astros players; a black plastic spider and black plastic
ants.
</P>
<P>
   If her pet at work is a tarantula, what's her pet at home? Two
cats, a cockatiel and a black shark that's more than a foot long,
named Black Bart.
</P>
<P>
   Merry Wade
</P>
<P>
   What she does: Mainframe computer operator, Texas Rehabilitation
Commission
</P>
<P>
   What makes her cubicle cool: Every square inch of it is covered
with magnets, comic strips, stickers, inspirational quotes,
photographs or buttons. The messages range from the amusing
(``Blonde jokes are short so men can remember them'') to the
serious (``Life's most persistent and urgent question is, 'What are
you doing for others?' '' _ Martin Luther King Jr.) Strips from
Garfield, Peanuts, Calvin and Hobbes, For Better or Worse, Frank &AMP;
Ernest, Mutts and B.C. all make an appearance. There is a profusion
of plants, too. ``You half expect to smell potpourri, be served
tea, and hear a little bell ringing when someone comes into the
office,'' says Wade's supervisor, Russell Smith. Wade works at
night; during the day, when she's gone, her co-workers will take
their coffee breaks at her desk because it's so entertaining. Wade
knows an item belongs in her cubicle if it ``gives me a giggle,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Samanthi Martinez
</P>
<P>
   What she does: Finance manager, Enterprise Customer Financial
Services, Dell
</P>
<P>
   What makes her cubicle cool: Martinez and her co-workers
decorated their area of the office in a beach-party theme. Colored
plastic leis, inflated beach balls and miniature inflatable killer
whales hang from the ceiling. Decorating the office is a popular
pastime at Dell _ another division, Martinez says, once dressed up
their area in a jungle theme, complete with camouflage netting. In
her cubicle, Martinez also has several art prints, photographs of
her family and postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Why decorating is important: ``It helps with morale,'' Martinez
says.
</P>
<P>
   Douphitt Briggs
</P>
<P>
   What he does: Consultant, new products and services, Texas
Guaranteed Student Loan Corp.
</P>
<P>
   What makes his cubicle cool: Elvis. The desk is arrayed with a
deck of Elvis playing cards, a ticket from Graceland, an Elvis
pop-up book, a copy of the ``Love Me Tender'' CD (the CD itself is
shaped like Elvis), an Elvis postcard and a copy of the ``Got
Milk?'' ad featuring Elvis impersonators. Shiny gold foil covers
the wall of the cubicle and flashing Christmas lights line the
edges. There's a bottle of Elvis cologne with the $1.99 price tag
still attached. The window is festooned with a piece of
gold-colored poster board, cut out in the shape of a light-- ing
bolt, with ``TCB'' at the top. This was the symbol Elvis gave to
his bodyguards, also known as the ``Memphis Mafia.'' ``TCB'' stands
for ``Taking Care of Business.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Elvis? Last Halloween, everyone in Briggs' department
decorated their cubicles in a ``Dead Rock Star'' theme. Briggs left
his cubicle decorated, and as the months went by, his co-workers
gave him more Elvis items.
</P>
<P>
   What really makes his cubicle classy: The fake jaguar fur
covering the desk. Almost as nice as the rhinestones on the coffee
mug.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Chan Santos writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0533 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USSTRIKES-CHEMICAL-08     08-20 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USSTRIKES-CHEMICAL-0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTACKS FOLLOWED GROWING CONCERNS ABOUT PRODUCTION OF DEADLY VX
GAS IN SUDAN
 &HT;    With USSTRIKES-CHEMICAL-0821.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH and ANDREW ALEXANDER 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. attack on a chemical plant in Sudan
Thursday followed reports of growing concern among Western
intelligence agencies that facilities for the production of deadly
VX nerve gas had been secretly shipped to Sudan from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Jane's Intelligence Review, published by the authoritative,
London-based weapons information company, reported earlier this
week that United Nations arms inspectors and U.S. intelligence
officials believe equipment for production of VX that disappeared
from Iraq in mid-1995 and wound up in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   Besides striking purported terrorist camps operated in
Afghanistan by renegade Saudi businessman and self-described
terrorism sponsor Osama bin Laden, U.S. Tomahawk cruise missiles
were used to bomb a ``Shifa Phamaceuticals'' chemical plant in
Khartoum, the Sudanese capital.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen and a senior intelligence
official told reporters Thursday the facility was turning out
precursor chemicals for VX production.
</P>
<P>
   The intelligence official also told reporters at a Pentagon
briefing that the plant was part of a Sudanese enterprise formally
known as ``the Military-Industrial Complex,'' which has been
financially supported by Bin Laden. Sudanese officials insisted the
plant produced only pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   VX is an abbreviation for a 62-letter chemical term (which
contains no Vs and no Xs). Colorless and odorless, the chemical is
the most toxic nerve agent known, many times deadlier than hydrogen
cyanide gas. By blocking an enzyme that regulates nerve impulses,
it causes uncontrolled spasms and within minutes, death.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do know is that this facility that was targeted in
Khartoum produced the precursor chemicals that would allow the
production of a type of VX nerve agent,'' Cohen said. The
intelligence official at Cohen's briefing went further:
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we know that Bin Laden has made financial contributions
to the Sudanese Military-Industrial Complex. That's a distinct
entity of which, we believe, the Shifa pharmaceutical facility is
part. We know with high confidence that Shifa produces a precursor
that is unique to the production of VX. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Butler, chairman of the United Nations Special
Commission that oversees the destruction of Iraqi weapons, has said
he believes 20 shipping containers with VX production equipment
disappeared from Iraq in mid-1995.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne's Intelligence Review reported Monday that U.S.
intelligence officials believe these containers were taken to
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine also reported on minutes of a two-day secret
meeting in Khartoum last October at which Sudanese officials
purportedly were assured of financial support from Bin Laden for
construction of a ``chemical and bacterial weapons factory'' in
Kubar, a suburb of Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
   Participants at the meeting agreed that the plant should be
brought into production ``as soon as possible,'' the magazine said
minutes of the meeting showed.
</P>
<P>
   Javed Ali, principal author of Jane's ``Chemical and Biological
Defense Guidebook,'' said VX has been around for about 50 years,
but only two countries, Russia and Iraq, have ever acknowledged
producing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not cutting edge technology,'' Ali said in an
interview. ``The British first developed the chemical in the late
1940s.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the chemicals that become VX when mixed together are
widely produced for peaceful reasons in many countries, especially
in the manufacture of pesticides, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob May, a farmer from eastern Arkansas who is in Sudan with a
group of Americans studying Christianity there, said Thursday that
he believes the factory was used exclusively to manufacture
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have met some doctors here and they say the plant provides
90 percent of all medicines in this country,'' said May, who was
reached by phone in Khartoum several hours after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   May said the mood in Khartoum Thursday night was one of
puzzlement more than anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question in the Sudanese peoples' minds is: 'What in the
world does this have to do with Osama bin Laden?''' Why would the
U.S. direct an attack on this city (when) in fact they exiled him
from Sudan two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's attack is ``going to get the people aroused'' in the
coming days, he said. ``I think it may have been a mistake. It's
certainly put a lot of puzzlement on people's faces. ``
</P>
<P>
   But a security official at a downtown Khartoum hotel suggested
otherwise. Asked in a telephone interview what was produced at the
factory, he said: ``Between you and me, chemicals. They could be
used for chemical weapons. I know because I have very wide eyes. I
can tell when I look.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in recent years Libyans had worked at the factory,
ostensibly producing insecticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very clever here,'' he said, suggesting that the
insecticide production was a cover. ``They can hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a curious coincidence of names caused the chairman of
a Syrian pharmaceutical manufacturer to announce following the
bombing that he would attempt to sue the Sudanese pharmaceutical
company for ``stealing our name.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard of these people because we export drugs to Iraq
under U.N. approval,'' said Imad Sabouni, chairman of Shifa
Pharmaceutical Industries of Aleppo, Syria. ``They also attempted
to sell to Iraq and that is when we learned that they also use the
name Shifa.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabouni also said in a telephone interview that his company had
no relationship with Bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God! Oh, my God! What is going on?'' Sabouni cried when
told that a pharmaceutical company with the same name as his
company's had been bombed for producing nerve gas precursors.
``Really, we do not have any relation with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabouni said that in Arabic the word ``Shifa'' means ``cure from
illness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are sick, they lie in bed and cry, 'Please, God,
give me me Shifa,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
