<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TELLS JURY MORE DETAILS ABOUT SEX AND GIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In her second and probably final appearance before
a grand jury here, Monica Lewinsky on Thursday offered more
specifics about her sexual relationship with President Clinton and
the gifts he gave her as prosecutors sought to draw distinctions
between her testimony and that of the president only three days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   During the five-hour session, prosecutors bore in on the series
of events that led Ms. Lewinsky to return gifts from the president
that had been subpoenaed in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
lawsuit last December, lawyers close to the case said.
</P>
<P>
   The events surrounding the gifts are potentially the most
serious for the president because prosecutors are trying to
determine whether he obstructed justice by telling Ms. Lewinsky to
turn the gifts over to his secretary, Betty Currie, rather than
give them to lawyers for Mrs. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky told prosecutors Thursday that she told Clinton
last December that the Jones subpoena demanded gifts he had given
her, a lawyer familiar with her account said. The president told
her that she could not turn over the gifts if they were not in her
possession, Ms. Lewinsky has told prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The day after her discussion with the president, Ms. Lewinsky
received a phone call from Ms. Currie, who told her, ``I hear you
have something for me,'' she told the grand jury. Ms. Lewinsky said
she assumed that Ms. Currie was referring to the gifts, according
to lawyers familiar with her account. Later that day, Ms. Currie
went to Ms. Lewinsky's apartment to retrieve the gifts, lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   But this account differs in some respects from Clinton's own
testimony last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the prosecutors that he told Ms. Lewinsky in
December 1997 that she had no choice but to turn over gifts he had
given her to the Jones lawyers, according to lawyers familiar with
his testimony Monday. When asked about the role of Ms. Currie, he
said he could not recall telling her to call Ms. Lewinsky about the
gifts. Prosecutors are also investigating whether Clinton kept some
of the gifts given to him by Ms. Lewinsky that had been subpoenaed
by lawyers in the Jones case, according to lawyers close to the
case.
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's grand jury testimony Monday, prosecutors also
asked him whether he deliberately wore a necktie, given to him by
Ms. Lewinsky, during a Rose Garden appearance Aug. 6, the day she
first testified before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he did not believe the gold and royal blue tie had
been a gift from her. He was then informed she had testified she
gave it to him and the prosecutors asked if he had worn it that day
as some kind of a ``signal'' to her, perhaps to influence her
testimony. Clinton said again he could not remember if the tie came
from her. But he insisted that he had no intention of sending Ms.
Lewinsky any kind of message that day.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky offered many more specifics of her sexual
encounters with the president than she gave in her original
testimony two weeks ago, according to her friends and associates.
The specifics of their physical contacts are also central to the
prosecutors' case as they try to determine whether Clinton
committed perjury in a deposition in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, these people said, told the panel that Clinton
caressed her breasts and touched her genitals during their affair
inside the White House. Her account was far more detailed than the
president's testimony Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Before he began Monday, Clinton admitted to the grand jury in a
statement supplied by his lawyers that he had had ``inappropriate
intimate physical contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors continue to try to determine whether Clinton lied
in his January deposition in the Jones case, lawyers on both sides
continue to wrangle over what constitutes sexual conduct. In his
Monday testimony, Clinton argued that the type of relationship he
had with Ms. Lewinsky did not meet the definition of sex used by
Mrs. Jones' lawyers, according to lawyers close to the case. Three
lawyers said he was implying that he had oral sex with Ms. Lewinsky
without testifying to that directly.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors are expected to argue that the acts described by
Ms. Lewinsky on Thursday fall within the definition of ``sexual
relations'' used by the Jones lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the testimony, prosecutors have obtained a sample of
Clinton's genetic material to determine if it matches a semen stain
on a dress Ms. Lewinsky turned over to prosecutors, according to
lawyers close to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI crime laboratory has determined that the stain on the
blue dress was semen, two officials briefed on the results said
Thursday. If the DNA in that stain matches the DNA sample from the
president, they would have forensic proof that the 52-year-old
president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky was sexual.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said administration officials turned over the
tissue? sample from the president at some point before he testified
Monday, presumably over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to the president said Thursday night that the DNA
sample was requested from Clinton last Friday and provided over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with Clinton's testimony Monday said
prosecutors asked him several questions about the dress.
Prosecutors apparently considered it important to obtain forensic
proof of the relationship as well, perhaps anticipating that
Clinton would likely maintain that his contacts with Ms. Lewinsky
did not fit the definition in the Jones case.
</P>
</TEXT>
