<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ANTITTRUST LAWSUIT POSTPONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government's antitrust lawsuit against Microsoft Corp. was
postponed for two weeks Thursday to allow for delays incurred while
news organizations sought access to depositions of company
executives, including chairman Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court ruled Wednesday that pretrial
depositions could resume without reporters present. Wednesday the
district judge overseeing the case agreed to postpone the trial
until Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson also said he would hear oral
arguments Sept. 8, the day the trial had been scheduled to start,
on Microsoft's motion for a summary judgment dismissing the case
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The company filed that request last week, saying the
government's claims were based on a false assertion that it had
``foreclosed'' the ability of Netscape Communications and other
competitors to supply Web browsing software to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... The undisputed facts show that no such `foreclosure' has
occurred,'' Microsoft said.
</P>
<P>
   In the antitrust case filed May 18, the government's main
allegation is that Microsoft forced computer makers to accept its
Internet browser software if they wanted to license its Windows
operating system, which controls the computer's basic look, feel
and operation.
</P>
<P>
   Windows so dominates its market that computer makers have no
real alternative to it, so Microsoft's action was an abuse of
monopoly power, the government asserts.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Microsoft argues that it has integrated the browser
technology into Windows in ways that benefit both consumers and
software vendors _ and that comply fully with antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking access to the pretrial depositions, the news
organizations cited a 1913 law that, while obscure, was nonetheless
plain in requiring the sessions to be open, Jackson ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft quickly appealed, saying it feared the disclosure of
highly sensitive business information if reporters and the public
attended the sessions.
</P>
<P>
   It also argued that procedures for trials and depositions have
changed substantially since 1913, and that the old law may be
superseded by newer federal rules authorizing judges to decide who
may attend depositions.
</P>
<P>
   In the handful of cases that cite the old law, ``none purport to
analyze in any depth'' the apparent conflict between it and the new
rules, one legal scholar wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court, in its ruling on Wednesday, said it would
hear legal arguments later and gave the parties until Sept. 29 to
file briefs on the matter. To keep the case from stalling, it said
depositions could be taken under an earlier protective order set up
to allow testimony to be made public without compromising
Microsoft's trade secrets or other sensitive information.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Ward Brown, a lead attorney for the news organizations said,
however, that they would file a motion Friday asking the appeals
court to issue a decision before Sept. 23, when the trial is to
start.
</P>
<P>
   Most or all of the depositions will have been taken by then,
Brown said, but if the news organizations prevail, they will become
public sooner than they would under the schedule set on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The depositions of Gates and other Microsoft executives will be
taken ``as quickly as we can get them scheduled,'' spokesman Jim
Cullinan said, but the times and places will not be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the protective order already in place, the person giving
testimony answers all questions and each side has a certain number
of days afterward to designate portions of the testimony
``confidential'' or ``highly confidential'' and ask that access to
it be restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the nature of the information, the restrictions can
bar disclosure not just to the public and news reporters but to
officials of the companies involved and their in-house attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, in its motion to keep the sessions private, noted
that some of the depositions taken so far include information so
sensitive that it ``cannot be seen even by the Microsoft in-house
lawyers who are involved in the preparation of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   If reporters and the public ultimately win access to any
depositions, sensitive information would still be protected.
</P>
<P>
   The news organizations ``have never contended that the statute
requires disclosure of Microsoft trade secrets,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the order Jackson issued last week saying the depositions
would be open, attorneys for Microsoft, the government and the news
organizations were negotiating a set of procedures for handling
sensitive information, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Those procedures have not been made public, but lawyers said
they would likely have called for supervision by the judge or
frequent conferences with him as specific issues came up during
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't clear what status the news organizations would have in
those conferences, Brown said, but they would have a ``greater
chance'' of avoiding overly broad restrictions if the sessions were
public from the outset.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
