u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-LOPEZ-COL-HNS &LR;      08-20 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LOPEZ-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gymnastics bosses &QL; 
just code-blooded
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ You see Kim Zmeskal sprint across the floor, pumping
her legs, twisting and leaping, and realize this is where the
search for Olympic magnificence should continue.
</P>
<P>
   Here, amid the haze of chalk and din of squealing pre-teen fans,
lots of talented girls and a handful of superstar young women hope
to succeed the ``Magnificent Seven,'' the 1996 U.S. women's
gymnastics team that dazzled the world.
</P>
<P>
   Zmeskal, 22, is in terrific shape. Dominique Moceanu, 16, looks
to make it back to the Games, this time as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   But for Zmeskal and Moceanu, two of the greatest athletes
Houston has produced and among the biggest names in the sport, it's
going to be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   This meet is where we should see Zmeskal begin an amazing
comeback story and Moceanu prove she might be taller than two years
ago but she's still among the best. This should be a meet where the
next generation learns from the golden generation and together they
head to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere between Atlanta and here, international gymnastics
powers decided to forget everything good that came out of the 1996
Games, instead stumbling backward and revisiting a dangerous time.
</P>
<P>
   A ghastly past
</P>
<P>
   The lowest era this sport has known was from 1989-1992. Just
being thin was not in. Being emaciated was in. Pushing it to the
brink of disaster was not considered abuse. It was training.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, after watching a 14-year-old Olympic hopeful struggle
through a training session, her face drawn and tired, I asked,
``What did you eat yesterday?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two bowls of rice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't talking about breakfast, lunch or dinner. She was
talking about the entire day. It was a sign of the times.
</P>
<P>
   But overzealous coaches, star-struck parents and children who
knew no better were only partly to blame. The biggest reason for
the embarrassment was something known as ``the code,'' a golden
carrot of sorts that federation officials hung out in front of
kids.
</P>
<P>
   It is the International Gymnastics Federation Code of Points, a
scoring standard for routines that athletes must attempt if they
want to earn high scores. The vaults Mary Lou Retton used to become
the world's darling in 1984, for example, would have started out
with a value of only about 9.7 based on the 1992 code.
</P>
<P>
   The international federation was force-feeding extreme
difficulty into routines, thereby starving athletes and blinding
coaches from doing reasonable things. The message was clear: Find
athletes who can tumble faster and higher, twist stronger and
tighter, but still score 10.0s. Kids, basically.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. coach Bela Karolyi looked at the stick-like girls on the
Chinese Olympic team in 1992 and joked about them having ``their
milk teeth.'' But it was no joke.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, after enduring criticism for the eating problems and
injuries, the code became reasonable and minimum-age requirements
were implemented. Nutritional programs were developed, too.
</P>
<P>
   It was all good. It also was why we saw Shannon Miller,
Dominique Dawes, Kerri Strug and Co., polished, proven and grown
up, thrill the world in Atlanta. The difficulty was there, but so
were mature athletes who looked like women and entertained massive
TV audiences.
</P>
<P>
   It should have been the moment that opened the federation's eyes
to what the world wants to see. It should have led to the likes of
Zmeskal _ proven veterans, not stick-girls _ having a chance of
making it to Sydney. But remarkably, the international federation
again raised the code of points to unkind levels for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Difficulty levels increased
</P>
<P>
   Today, the memorable vault that launched Strug to superstardom
two years ago would start out with a value of just 9.8. As much as
Moceanu looks terrific here and Zmeskal is tumbling strong, they
are having trouble keeping up the difficulty levels to the current
standards. At a time when the sport should ride a wave of
popularity that its stars provided, the federation has made it more
difficult on those same stars.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Probably fewer than 10 percent of Olympic TV viewers can
tell you the difference between a pike and a tuck. People want to
see 9.9s and 10.0s, not the falling-down 9.2s that opened
Thursday's national championships.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries are piling up. Some athletes again look 16 going on
12. Two of Houston's other top 2000 hopefuls, Kendall Beck and
Lindsay Wing, will not compete here. Beck tore an anterior cruciate
ligament in her knee practicing a vault. Wing is taking time off
because of what doctors diagnosed as food allergies.
</P>
<P>
   And how can the federation ignore the horrible accident that
left China's Sang Lan, 17, paralyzed after missing a vault at the
Goodwill Games?
</P>
<P>
   They didn't just raise the bar. They greased it. Unless the code
is adjusted downward, which the federation has shown no inclination
to do, athletes will crash to the mats from here to Sydney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0537 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIG-SUNAMERICA-ART-60     08-20 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIG-SUNAMERICA-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN INTERNATIONAL GROUP ACQUIRES SUNAMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md.)  (ART ADV: A graphic detailing the AIG acquisition of SunAmerica is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a merger of insurance giants, American International Group, a
world leader in corporate insurance, agreed Thursday to buy
SunAmerica Inc., one of the pioneers in selling investments for
retirement, for stock valued at $17.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, one of the largest in the financial services industry,
vaults American International Group into the rapidly growing
business of variable annuities _ mutual funds with insurance that
protects against market dips _ and gives SunAmerica a springboard
to worldwide expansion through American International Group's
offices in 130 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also brings together a pair of chief executives _
Maurice ``Hank'' Greenberg of American International Group and Eli
Broad of SunAmerica _ who are among the most respected and admired
in the insurance business. Both hold large stakes in their
companies and are among the world's wealthiest people with fortunes
exceeding $1 billion each.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg is to continue as chairman and chief executive and
Broad will become a member of the board of the merged company.
Broad, whose personal wealth would jump more than $250 million in
the transaction, will continue to direct SunAmerica from its
headquarters in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrific fit,'' Alice Schroeder, an analyst at Paine
Webber, said. ``It fills the biggest hole in AIG's product lineup
and offers a platform that SunAmerica can instantly plug into its
globalization strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms, SunAmerica shareholders will get 0.855 of one
AIG share for each SunAmerica share. Based on AIG's closing price
of $94.625 Wednesday before the announcement, the deal is worth
$17.8 billion. The purchase price comes to more than five times
SunAmerica's book value of $2.966 billion at a time when shares of
leading competitors are trading at about four times their book
value.
</P>
<P>
   AIG's stock dropped 7.5 percent to close at $87.50 Thursday
while shares of SunAmerica rose 11.1 percent to close at $71.375.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are sort of giving a thumbs down to the price,''
said Eric Berg, an analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   But Berg and others described SunAmerica as ``an exceptional
company,'' worthy of an exceptional price. ``You can't buy a good
franchise at a bargain price,'' said Ms. Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Greenberg said he felt confident the price was not
excessive. There is an enormous market for SunAmerica's variable
annuities and other retirement investments around the world, he
said, and the combined company will go after that. ``The need is
global,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of huge new overseas markets has been a driving
force in several recent financial services megamergers, notably the
combination of Citicorp and Travelers Group. Like AIG and
SunAmerica, partners in the Citicorp-Travelers deal hope to exploit
each other's strengths to sell products around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the AIG-SunAmerica deal, first reported
Thursday in The Wall Street Journal, could look less promising if
the stock markets fell and investors began to shy away from
variable annuities, which have been SunAmerica's main engine for
growth. ``That's maybe a near-term implication,'' said Jay Cohen,
an analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``But long-term, I don't see a lot of
downside.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts cautioned that the merged company might find it
difficult to introduce American-style retirement products in some
countries. Introducing new products to each other's sales forces
for so-called cross-selling, the analysts noted, has proved
daunting to some companies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg and Broad, who have been friends for nearly a decade,
said they believed that their personal styles and their corporate
cultures would integrate well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Hank and I and our people are Type A people,'' Broad
said. ``We like to win. We're very competitive. We believe in doing
things in a quality way and we're owner-operators.''
</P>
<P>
   While the two companies are publicly owned, Greenberg, 73, and
Broad, 65, have run them rather like entrepreneurs, avoiding layers
of committees and leaving no doubt where power resides.
</P>
<P>
   Broad literally built SunAmerica from the ground up. While
running a successful construction business, he bought Sun Life
Insurance Co.of America, an old-line life insurance company in
Baltimore, as a hedge against a downturn in housing. But in 1989 he
spun off the construction business. Perceiving great demand for
investments aimed at providing money for retirement as the American
population aged, Broad abandoned the sale of traditional life
insurance and began to sell insurance only in connection with
mutual funds and other investments. He took the company public in
1989 and owns nearly 42 percent of it.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg was not a founder of AIG but is responsible for the
company's extraordinary growth by taking it public in 1969, nine
years after he joined the company and one year after he became
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Back then it had a market value of about $300 million. Today it
operates 300 subsidiaries, in businesses ranging from its signature
corporate coverage to automobile and life insurance, and has a
market value of about $92 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg's son, Evan Greenberg, in his mid-40s, is president
and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, AIG, with assets of $164 billion, reported net income
of $3.3 billion on revenues of $30.6 billion. Net income for
SunAmerica, with assets of 35.6 billion, was $379 million on
revenues of $5.3 billion. For the last decade, SunAmerica's stock
has been one of the best-performing issues on the New York Stock
Exchange, rising an average of 42 percent a year. In the last five
years, AIG's stock value has more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   AIG plans to use the pooling method of accounting in the merger,
which shields the merged company from some one-time charges that
would reduce future earnings. The swap of stock for stock also
means SunAmerica shareholders will not be liable for taxes from an
increase in the value of their investment until they decide to sell
their new AIG stock.
</P>
<P>
   Domestically, Broad said, the merger would give SunAmerica
entree to scores of blue-chip corporate clients of AIG. And Larry
Mayewski, a senior vice president and analyst at AM Best &AMP; Co., a
rating agency, said SunAmerica's nationwide network of
broker-dealers would become an outlet for such AIG products as auto
and life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were generally effusive about the merger. ``This is a
great deal in every way,'' said Michael Frinquelli, a principal in
Renaissance Fund Advisers, a hedge fund specializing in insurance.
``Most importantly you're marrying the two smartest guys in their
respective businesses. Ask anybody in property and casualty who
their idol is and it's Hank Greenberg. Ask anybody in the annuities
business and it's Eli Broad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
