<SLUG> BC-UAW0821-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strike-affected UAW workers will receive unemployment
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ About 30,000 United Auto Workers in Dayton and
across Ohio who were laid off earlier this summer because of two
crippling strikes against General Motors Corp. will receive
unemployment benefits for the time they missed work.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Bureau of Employment Services on Thursday ruled that
the Ohio workers did not participate in the strikes at two GM parts
plants in Flint, Mich. between June 5 and July 28. The workers at
nine plants in Dayton, Lordstown, Mansfield, Parma, Defiance,
Toledo, Columbus and Sandusky were sent home because of a shortage
of parts.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was a section of Ohio law that prohibits benefits for
workers whose unemployment is due to any labor dispute other than a
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The workers claimed they were exempt under a provision that
allows benefits for workers who are not financing or taking part in
a strike. They did not get strike benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had faith we would get the benefits all along, we think our
the people deserve them,'' said Gary Hill, president of UAW Local
696, which represents 3,400 hourly workers at two Dayton brake
plants.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the strike settlement with the UAW, GM promised not
to sell or close the two Delphi Chassis brake plants in Dayton
before January 2000. The plants have lost more than $40 million
over the last two years and Local 696 has been battling GM for the
plants' survival.
</P>
<P>
   GM had maintained that as dues-paying UAW members, the workers
are helping to finance the strike. And because the agency assesses
GM for unemployment benefits and keeps the money in a trust fund to
pay to workers who qualify, the company would have to replace any
money that is paid out to its workers.
</P>
<P>
   David Garick, OBES spokesman, said the benefits covered under
Thursday's ruling would be granted retroactively.
</P>
<P>
   The agency declined to offer further comment because the matter
may be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed in the decision,'' said Gerry Holmes, GM
spokesman. ``We thought we had a strong case ... that this was a
UAW-orchestrated situation.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
