<HEADER>
A4765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISS-KLAN-TRIAL-1STLD     08-20 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-KLAN-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS PAINTS KLAN AS CHARITABLE ORGANIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (corrects to `heads' sted `hands' in 2nd graf)  (smw) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ Spectators here at the trial of a former
Klansman accused of ordering the murder of a respected civil rights
leader were surprised, to say the least, when another former
Klansman described the White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan of
Mississippi as a benevolent organization that existed to give money
to the rural poor and pass out fruit baskets at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the older black people in the courtroom shook their
heads, some of them snickered and a few laughed out loud when
Deavours Nix, a defense witness and former Klansman, testified that
he never even heard the defendant, Samuel F. Bowers, use a racial
slur.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, the Imperial Wizard who led the Mississippi White
Knights when the violent organization was linked to killings,
church burnings and beatings in the 1960s, stands accused for the
fifth time of ordering the murder of Vernon Dahmer, a black grocer
who was killed when his home was firebombed by Klansmen on Jan. 10,
1966. Both the prosecution and the defense wrapped up their cases
Thursday, with closing arguments scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nix, who held the Klan title of ``State Investigator'' though he
said he does not know what that title means and he attended only
three or so Klan meetings, described Bowers, now 73, as a
``patriot'' who was respectful to ladies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not used profane language and I never heard him use a
racial slur,'' said Nix, who is accused of taking part in the
firebombing that killed Dahmer, a NAACP leader who was helping
blacks register to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Nix suffers from cancer and heart and lung ailments and
testified in a wheelchair with an oxygen bottle attached. He and
another former Klansman, Charles Noble, are expected to go on trial
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nix testified Thursday that to his knowledge, Bowers was never
the leader of the Mississippi Klan, that the Klan did not stand for
violence and that he, himself, was never that much involved in it,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He only joined, he said, because he heard that the Klan ``did
some benevolent work, such as delivering baskets of fruit at
Christmastime to people that was needy.'' He never had a robe, he
said. He did not hear racial slurs at the Klan meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But three former Klansmen who became government informers have
testified that Bowers planned and ordered Dahmer's murder at Klan
meetings in 1965. Bowers walked free, three decades ago, after
juries in four trials deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
   This trial has boiled down to the word of two factions: those
former Klansmen who described Bowers as a coldly racist leader who
masterminded the execution of Dahmer, paired against people who
were either members of the Klan or had Klan ties.
</P>
<P>
   The lead prosecutor, Robert Helfrich, picked apart Nix's
testimony one statement at a time, showing gaps in the truth that
had the courtroom laughing. For example, there was this exchange:
</P>
<P>
   ``What color was your robe,'' Helfrich asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have no robe,'' Nix said.
</P>
<P>
   Helfrich handed him a picture, from an FBI file, that showed a
man identified as Nix wearing a robe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look like that might be a robe?'' Helfrich asked.
</P>
<P>
   Nix said it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got a hood on it?'' Helfrich asked.
</P>
<P>
   Nix acknowledged that it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holding a gun?'' Helfrich said, referring to the man in the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Nix did not deny any of it. Instead, he just said of the man in
the picture:
</P>
<P>
   ``That ain't me.''
</P>
<P>
   Helfrich asked Nix if he remembered something his wife said at
the time FBI agents seized the picture, in the spring of 1966.
According to court documents, Helfrich said, Nix's wife walked up
to him and said: ``They found that silly picture of you with the
pointed hood on.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of courtroom guffawed.
</P>
<P>
   Nix's credibility has already been questioned. After he was
arrested in May when state officials decided they had enough
evidence for one more trial, he told the presiding judge that his
health was bad and that he needed regular treatment. Several days
later, a news photographer took a picture of ``his backswing'' at a
golf course, Helfrich said.
</P>
<P>
   When Nix was ordered back before the judge, he had five golf
tees in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many fruit baskets did you deliver for the Klan?''
Helfrich here Thursday, sounding disgusted.
</P>
<P>
   Nix said none.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was interrupted at one point when Nix was apparently
having trouble breathing, presumably because his oxygen bottle had
to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   But when a private nurse carried the bottle from the room, it
hissed loudly from the pressure of the escaping oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   `` Nix,'' Helfrich asked him at one point in his testimony, ``do
you know what perjury is?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
