s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-AMAZON-ART-$AD     08-20 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-AMAZON-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS DID IT FOR AMAZON, BUT WHAT'S NET?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many an eye, on Wall Street and Main Street alike, is trained on
the Internet, seeking signs that its much-hyped promise as a
channel of retail commerce is beginning to be realized.
</P>
<P>
   The big breakthrough so far, the bookseller Amazon.com,
demonstrated that ordinary products not composed of chips and bits
can be successfully retailed over the Internet. And, perhaps more
important, it showed that investors see no need to wait for
consistent operating profits before betting heavily on a company
that may have found the key.
</P>
<P>
   So the old question of whether Internet retailing can work is
giving way to a new question: In which retail categories will the
next Amazons emerge?
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters say the stakes are high. Forrester Research, a
market research firm in Cambridge, Mass., expects the on-line
retail market to mushroom from $4.8 billion in sales in 1998 to
more than $17 billion in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But Forrester expects 86 percent of that trade to be in just
five categories, all of them already established on line:
Computers, software, entertainment, books and travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those industries that are most susceptible to on-line
retailing are already obvious,'' explained David Alschuler, an
electronic-commerce analyst at Aberdeen Group, a consulting firm in
Boston. The best candidates are those where consumers do a lot of
research before buying and want information that traditional sales
channels have a difficult time supplying, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Internet experts have already spotted opportunities for a
new round of on-line retailers.
</P>
<P>
   One company that may have its toe on the escalator is Etoys, a
year-old on-line toy retailer still in the venture-capital stage.
It sells about 3,000 products, according to Kate Delhagen, director
of on-line retail strategies at Forrester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Etoys has built up a good, customer-friendly front end of the
business,'' Ms. Delhagen said. ``And they've done a good job
matching inventory to logistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Another category that analysts are calling ripe for Internet
retailing is consumer electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Bajarin, president of Creative Strategies Inc., a consulting
firm in Campbell, Calif., sees Amazon's recent deal to acquire the
Junglee Corp. as giving it an important leg up in the field. For
comparison-shopping on the World Wide Web, Junglee offers consumers
a powerful search engine, one of the few ways to research consumer
electronics prices.
</P>
<P>
   The demographics certainly seem right. Consumer electronics
shoppers tend to be men with relatively high incomes _ among the
people most likely to use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But traditional electronics retailers like Circuit City and Best
Buy have so far been slow to step into cyberspace. And Nicole
Vanderbilt, director of digital commerce at Jupiter Communications,
an Internet consulting company in New York, said start-ups have a
difficult time breaking in because they lack the buying power of
larger retailers and must deal with a raft of distributors.
</P>
<P>
   So despite the large volume of computer products now sold on
line, ``no one yet has come forward and positioned themselves as a
category killer'' in other consumer electronics, Ms. Vanderbilt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some electronics retailers are moving ahead. In mid-June, Tops
Appliance City linked up with Cybershop International, a publicly
traded on-line retailer of luxury merchandise like Coach bags and
Mikasa crystal, to develop a new Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Bajarin saw rich opportunities for retailers of cameras.
``There's an amazing amount of comparison-shopping among
photography shoppers,'' he said, yet Web sites are often so
primitive that consumers must phone for prices.
</P>
<P>
   Discount buying clubs are another area that analysts say can do
well on the Internet. The leader so far is Net Market, a Cendant
subsidiary. But a competitor, Value America, has attracted
attention lately with heavy advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts also see apparel as gaining momentum on line,
despite clothing manufacturers' traditional slowness to adopt new
technology. Ms. Vanderbilt said one company with an early,
interesting niche is Pivot Rules Inc., formerly a maker of golf
clothing. In May it switched gears and began developing a Web site
called Bluefly, offering designer apparel at deep discounts.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief executive, Kem Seiff, said the off-price
apparel business frustrated many consumers with hit-or-miss
excursions to stores full of chaotic clothing racks. And catalogue
companies struggle with the unpredictable availability of off-price
apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are divided over the prospects for selling mundane
items like groceries over the Internet, offering widely divergent
revenue forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will grow into billions of dollars eventually, but
not soon,'' said Ms. Delhagen of Forrester. ``And that's because
there's a very powerful dynamic at work. Even though we say we hate
grocery shopping, it's still very easy to do'' and typically does
not require a lot of research, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Peapod Inc., a pioneer in on-line grocery sales,
may expand nationwide only gradually because so many of its wares
are perishable. By contrast, Net Grocer Inc. concentrates on longer
shelf-life products and is expected to gain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-July, America Online agreed to make Netgrocer Inc. the
exclusive supermarket delivery service for its customers in
exchange for a $15 million fee over the next three years, a share
in ad and transaction revenues and warrants to buy Netgrocer stock.
This month, Netgrocer filed a registration statement with the
Securities and Exchange Commission to go public.
</P>
<P>
   It's a short leap from groceries to drugstore sundries, and, so
far, the best-capitalized on-line entry seems to be Drugstore.Com,
a privately held company founded by a former Microsoft executive,
Peter Neupert.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vanderbilt of Jupiter thinks on-line sales make sense for
basic supplies that consumers often need to restock, like toilet
paper and soap. But drugstores' best profits are from goods that
are hard or impossible to sell on line: prescription drugs and
impulse purchases like cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart and Netgrocer already offer some drugstore items on
line, Ms. Vanderbilt said, but the selection is limited, and, in
Wal-Mart's case, not heavily promoted. ``We think there's an
opportunity here for a category killer like Amazon,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
