<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNDRAISING-GORE-ART-     08-20 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTES SUGGEST GORE WAS LESS THAN CANDID ON PHONE CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The notes of a senior aide say that at a November
1995 White House meeting where the distinction between hard and
soft money was apparently discussed, Vice President Al Gore told
the others present to ``count me in'' on making fund-raising
telephone calls that are now the subject of a Justice Department
review on whether to seek the appointment of an independent
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's comment was recorded in handwritten notes by his deputy
chief of staff, David Strauss, that appear on several pages of a
White House memorandum that discussed the Democrats' ambitious
fund-raising strategy for the 1996 Clinton re-election campaign.
The memorandum was turned over to the Justice Department by the
White House about a month ago and has prompted prosecutors to begin
the process of deciding whether to seek an outside counsel to
investigate campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The notes suggest that Gore may not have been candid in his
public statements on the subject of the phone calls. He has said
that he did not realize that some of the large contributions he
solicited in the fund-raising calls for use only for general
campaign purposes by the Democratic Party, such as registration
drives, would be diverted to ``hard money'' accounts which directly
financed such Clinton-Gore re-election devices as television ads.
</P>
<P>
   But Strauss' notes indicate that Gore may have known that there
was a distinction between ``hard money'' and ``soft money''
contributions because the subject appears to have been discussed at
the Nov. 21, 1995, meeting attended by President Clinton, Gore and
senior campaign officials.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss wrote ``65 percent soft, 35 percent hard,'' an apparent
reference to the division of contributions between hard and soft
money accounts. In his small neat hand, Strauss jotted a shorthand
definition of soft money as ``corporate or anything over $20K from
an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly narrow question of whether Gore knew the
distinction between hard and soft money is significant because
Attorney General Janet Reno has said that telephone solicitations
for the reelection effort, or hard money, by the president or vice
president were subject federal campaign finance laws and could be
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Reno refused to seek an outside prosecutor to
investigate Gore's phone calls, in effect clearing him of
wrongdoing because she had found no evidence that he had known that
money from any of his calls had been diverted to hard money
accounts. But early this month the notes forced her to reconsider
her decision, law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that Gore was recently questioned for about a
half hour by Justice Department investigators. But his aides said
he would ultimately be exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever this process ends and at whatever stage, we are
confident that it will show that everything the vice president did
was legal and proper,'' said a Gore spokesman, Christopher Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has until the end of the month to decide whether to advance
from a 30-day initial review of the Gore telephone calls to a more
intensive 90-day inquiry that will determine whether she refers the
case to an independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials are said to be divided about the
importance of Strauss' notes, a few sentences written on the
five-page memorandum. Some doubt that the notations alone are
sufficient to prompt Reno to seek an independent prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But, the officials said, the notes are likely to be considered
as part of a larger independent-counsel review under way at the
Justice Department as a result of a report to Reno by Charles La
Bella before he left as head of her campaign finance investigative
team.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella urged Reno to reconsider her refusal to refer the
campaign finance case to an independent prosecutor. He argued that
the Justice Department could not credibly investigate political
fund-raising efforts made on behalf of an incumbent president. La
Bella based his conclusions on a review of the evidence amassed
during the Justice Department's 18-month-old grand jury inquiry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
