<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; CHEVRON  &LR; _ As industry experts mull British Petroleum's plan to buy
Chicago's Amoco Corp. for $49 billion, one thing seems clear: It's
only a matter of time before other big oil companies seek merger
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Whether San Francisco's Chevron Corp. will be a player is less
certain, but many analysts think it will. By Kenneth Howe
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTODESK &LR;  _ Design software-maker Autodesk Inc. yesterday
agreed to buy movie special effects wizard Discreet Logic Inc. in a
deal worth about $531 million. The acquisition, expected to close
by the end of the year, will merge Montreal's Discreet Logic, which
helped sink the Titanic in this year's movie blockbuster, with
Kinetix, the Autodesk subsidiary that bedeviled television's Ally
McBeal with an animated 3-D baby.
</P>
<P>
   Reports second-quarter earnings. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREET &LR;  _ Talk about thin-skinned. In the rare event that you
were looking for more absurdity wrought by mega-bank merger mania,
try this on for size. NationsBank President Kenneth Lewis plans to
cancel his bankholding company's subscriptions to the American
Banker because the trade paper ran an article that audaciously
suggests how it should handle its community reinvestment
obligations in California.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Fire the messenger. By columnist Mark Veverka
</P>
