<HEADER>
A4783 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTODESK-SFCHRON &LR;      08-20 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTODESK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Autodesk to Buy Discreet, Maker Of Movie Magic &QL; 
 &QL; 
By Benny Evangelista &QC; 
 &QL; 
Design software-maker Autodesk Inc. yesterday agreed to buy movie
special effects wizard Discreet Logic Inc. in a deal worth about
$531 million.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, expected to close by the end of the year, will
merge Montreal's Discreet Logic, which helped sink the Titanic in
this year's movie blockbuster, with Kinetix, the Autodesk
subsidiary that bedeviled television's Ally McBeal with an animated
3-D baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are executing our strategy to broaden our business and
expand beyond the traditional design software category,'' Autodesk
chief executive Carol Bartz said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   Autodesk, the world's fourth-largest PC computer software-maker,
is best known for computer-aided design programs used by architects
and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday it reported net income of $9.1 million (18 cents per
share) on revenues of $186.6 million for the second quarter ended
July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the San Rafael company increased 21 percent from
$154.1 million in the second quarter of 1997, but net income was
down from $17.8 million (34 cents) due to a onetime charge related
to Autodesk's acquisition of German software-maker Genius in May.
</P>
<P>
   Autodesk agreed to issue 0.525 share of its own common stock in
exchange for each share of Discreet Logic stock.
</P>
<P>
   Both the earnings and the acquisition were announced after the
market closed. Shares in Autodesk rose 13 cents to $32.63, while
Discreet Logic shares rose $2.38 to $16. Both companies are traded
on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will expand Autodesk's reach into the entertainment
world, said Jim Guerard, vice president and general manager of
Kinetix.
</P>
<P>
   Kinetix has 130 employees worldwide including about 100 in San
Francisco. In addition to developing the computerized dancing baby,
it also designed software used to create special effects on films
like ``Lost in Space`` and graphics for CBS' television coverage of
the Nagano Winter Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Discreet is a 350-employee company that makes hardware systems
and software used for post-production movie special effects on
blockbusters like ``Titanic,'' ``Independence Day'' and ``Forest
Gump,'' said analyst Byron Berry of Yorkton Securities in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was a positive move for the companies and should allow
Discreet to eventually branch into lower cost systems aimed at the
consumer market, Berry said. For example, if the price came down
enough, consumers might use the company's products to edit their
own videos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The new subsidiary will be called Discreet Logic and be
headquartered in Montreal. Current Discreet Logic President Richard
Szalwinski will head the merged operation.
</P>
<P>
   Guerard said the company plans to keep the present employees of
both Discreet and Kinetix located in Montreal and San Francisco
respectively, but acknowledged the merger may cause some
reductions.
</P>
<P>
   He said the companies have worked together for the past year on
different projects and the merger ``is a natural evolution of the
path we've been on for nine to 12 months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
