<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0561 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON &LR;      08-20 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Chevron could be jumping on the merger bandwagon   By Kenneth Howe  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
As industry experts mull British Petroleum's plan to buy Chicago's
Amoco Corp. for $49 billion, one thing seems clear: It's only a
matter of time before other big oil companies seek merger partners.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether San Francisco's Chevron Corp. will be a player is less
certain, but many analysts think it will.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd better be looking or they'll be left behind,'' said
Fadel Gheit, oil analyst with Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gheit and other analysts believe that last week's deal _ which
would be the biggest foreign acquisition of a U.S. firm _ is a
signal that the oil industry is about to undergo the same
consolidation sweeping the telecommunications, banking, auto and
entertainment industries.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Chevron is mum about its plans. To those who ask,
the nation's fourth-largest oil company issues a purposely vague
statement: ``The BP/Amoco merger does not change our plans and will
not have any impact on our ability to execute those plans and
deliver value to our shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   The company refused to disclose whether its plans include
looking for a merger partner.
</P>
<P>
   But many industry watchers think Chevron will indeed seek a
partner and may have to move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The logic behind Chevron jumping on the acquisition bandwagon
goes something like this. The proposed merger of BP and Amoco
creates a tier of three so-called ``super major'' oil companies,
based on proven oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
   At the top is Royal Dutch Shell with 19 billion barrels,
followed by BP Amoco with 14.6 billion and Exxon at 13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Lagging far behind are second-tier companies such as Mobil and
Chevron at 6.9 billion barrels and 6.2 billion respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, these experts believe, only the super majors will
have the financial wherewithal to take on new oil discovery and
development projects.
</P>
<P>
   And even these super majors will be pitted against an emerging
new player, the state-owned oil company. From Brazil's Petrobras SA
to the Chinese National Petroleum Co., state-owned oil companies
are beginning to venture outside their borders to compete for
projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they aren't careful, the second-tier oil companies are
going to find they aren't big enough to get invited to the party,''
said Gheit.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think Chevron may have to move fast as the search
for merger partners heats up. For example, Texaco would be a
logical partner for Chevron. But Mobil, another possible partner,
may already be considering joining forces with Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron and Texaco are already 50-50 partners in Caltex
Petroleum Corp, a refining and marketing joint venture that covers
Asia, the Pacific, the Middle East and southern and eastern Africa.
</P>
<P>
   None of the companies would comment on its plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, whatever Chevron decides to do, it won't be out of any
particular financial weakness. One of the world's largest oil
companies, and one that traces its origins in California back to
1879, Chevron and its 34,000 employees pulled in revenues of $40
billion last year earning $3.3 billion, a 25 percent increase from
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, lower oil prices hurt profits during the past
quarter and Chevron's stock price has slipped somewhat. It traded
yesterday at $80.50, down 19 cents, well below its 52-week high of
$90.19.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers think that Chevron is more likely to be an
acquirer than a target. That's because it is so large that few
other oil concerns could afford to buy it. Those that are big
enough, such as Exxon Corp., have made it clear in public
statements that they are not interested in expanding further.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts don't see that the strategic choices for
Chevron in such stark terms as a big acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mergers are going to happen, but getting bigger isn't
essential,'' said Matt Sagers, head of the energy division for
PlanEcon Inc., a Washington, D.C., consulting group.
</P>
<P>
   Sagers said companies like Chevron may start fine tuning their
operations. They may shed under-performing division, much as
Chevron said it would do earlier this week when it announced it
would sell its Pittsburg &AMP; Midway Coal Mining Co. subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Or, Sagers added, oil companies may form other strategic
alliances such as last year's deal to merge Royal Dutch/Shell's
U.S. refining and marketing operations with those of Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lure to merge can be compelling, said Severin
Borenstein, director of the Energy Institute at the University of
California at Berkeley, though he wasn't speaking specifically
about Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein noted that oil prices are at their lowest level in a
decade with Brent crude in London at under $12 a barrel, compared
with nearly twice that a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been that the value of oil company assets _ the
crude they hold in the ground _ has gone down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these companies are taking a wealth hit, just as
consumers would if the price of their house declined,'' Borenstein
said. ``So they are thinking long and hard about efficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The response to lower crude prices by many oil companies has
been to cut costs. And one way to do that is merge and consolidate,
which can lead to large staff reductions from overlapping
operations.
</P>
<P>
   One industry rule of thumb, according to Gheit of Fahnestock is
that, on average, each employee laid off can save a company
$100,000 in salary, benefit and overhead costs such as travel,
training and office space expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies will salivate over those kinds of cost savings,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
