<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN TURMOIL DRIVES INVESTORS FROM DOW TO TREASURIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that tilde in parentheses has been used in the
second graf instead of the actual tilde character, which is
non-transmittable to some newspaper systems.) 
(smw) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Turmoil in overseas economies sent investors fleeing
stocks for the safety of bonds Thursday, pushing the yield on the
30-year Treasury bond to another new low.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that Russian bank failures were imminent and that
Venezuela might be forced to devalue its currency, the
bol(tilde)ivar, to combat a growing budget deficit, and persistent
concerns about a similar move by China buoyed the Treasury market.
All of these things added to investor concerns that the financial
crises among emerging markets might be spreading.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an announcement by President Clinton that the
United States had bombed suspected terrorist camps in Afghanistan
and the Sudan in retaliation for the bombings at U.S. embassies in
East Africa earlier this month contributed to a strong rally in
Treasuries in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of disturbing things going on around the
world,'' said Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko Securities
Company International. ``In that type of environment, the Treasury
market is the best place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The migration to the Treasury market hurt stock prices, which
fell for a second day after a rally earlier in the week. Analysts
cautioned that further declines were possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the dollar fell for the fourth consecutive day
against the yen, reflecting fears that the Japanese government
would sell dollars to defend the yen's value.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 81.87 points, to 8,611.41.
Financial services companies like American Express and J.P. Morgan
led the declines. The drop in those shares reflected investor
concerns that Venezuela's plight might hurt other Latin American
economies and jeopardize bank holdings of emerging-market debt as
well as repayment of loans made to those countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 6.46 points, to 1,091.60.
The Nasdaq, led by declines in the chip-related stocks Intel and
Applied Materials, lost 10.24 points, to 1,832.45.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury bond's price rose 21/32 to 99 28/32, which
means bond investors gained about $6.56 for each $1,000 of bonds
they held.
</P>
<P>
   The yield, which moves in the opposite direction of the price,
fell to 5.51 percent from 5.55 percent. The yield is now at its
lowest level since the Treasury Department began issuing the bonds
on a regular basis in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The strength in the bond market may last a while. Analysts said
one sign of its stamina is that long-term bond yields have been
below 5.60 percent for six consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, many analysts say that bond yields can fall
further, causing the Treasury yield curve to flatten even more as
the spread between long-term yields and those on shorter-term
Treasury securities narrows. A flattening yield curve can be an
indication that interest rates will fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually expect that to happen,'' said Kathleen Camilli,
director of economic research at Tucker Anthony, a regional
brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Camilli says the long bond's yield could fall to 5 percent
this year. At that level, the yield would fall below the current
Federal Funds target rate, a benchmark for short-term interest
rates, now at 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move might prompt the Federal Reserve to lower short-term
interest rates, she forecast.
</P>
<P>
   At present, yields on shorter-term Treasury securities, like the
10-year and 2-year notes, are already below 5.5 percent. Ms.
Camilli and several other economists said that indicates that
investors believe that the next move by the Federal Reserve will be
to lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   If Treasury yields fall further, it might send investors rushing
back to stocks, said Anthony Conroy, a managing director at Bankers
Trust Global Investment Management. At much lower yield levels,
investors might decide that they can get a higher return by
investing in stocks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lower interest rates also translate into lower borrowing costs
for corporations and ease pressure on corporate profit margins, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
