<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0565 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-AFC-VS.-NFC-TEX     08-20 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-VS.-NFC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL AFC TEAMS HAVE LEGITIMATE CHAMPIONSHIP HOPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past decade and a half, the AFC's Powers That Be haven't
been powers at all _ at least not come Super Bowl time.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with the Denver Broncos providing a one-game winning
streak, the AFC contenders can consider their chances for a ring
that represents more than just a conference title. For the first
time in seemingly forever, the Powers That Be in the AFC are actual
powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you come in and say you want to get there, but it's
not very realistic,'' New England Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe
says. ``Every team in the NFL is optimistic this time of year. But
I think we have reason to be optimistic. The Super Bowl is a very
realistic goal for us.''
</P>
<P>
   And realistic for at least five AFC clubs, each of which has a
reasonable chance _ based both on what underdog Denver did to NFC
power Green Bay in the Super Bowl and on how strong they look on
paper _ of outperforming any club from the traditionally stronger
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The argument making the rounds this preseason seems to be that
beyond the Packers, the five best teams in the AFC (Denver,
Pittsburgh, Jacksonville, Kansas City and New England) are more
potent than their counterparts in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   The mighty have fallen from the 33-19 interconference record in
1991 to a 32-28-1 AFC advantage last season. The mighty _
traditional powers Dallas and San Francisco _ are in transition,
and the rest of the hopefuls (the New York Giants, Tampa Bay,
Minnesota, Detroit, Washington, Atlanta and Philadelphia) remain
essentially unproven.
</P>
<P>
   But before anointing a team such as the Steelers as a power,
perhaps it's best to ask the Steelers themselves about the shift in
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one of the best teams,'' says running back Jerome
Bettis. ``But we have too many questions. Until we answer those
questions, we can't be ``the'' team.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions? Yeah, like the departures of wide receiver Yancey
Thigpen, linebackers Chad Scott and Greg Lloyd, tackle John Jackson
and safety Myron Bell. Still, Pittsburgh watchers must have
confidence the holes will either be patched by coach Bill Cowher
(fives AFC Central titles, three AFC Championship Games and a 64-32
regular-season record) or hidden by the talent of quarterback
Kordell Stewart. Stewart is entering his fourth season but just his
second as a full-time starter.
</P>
<P>
   Says Pittsburgh assistant-turned-Cowboys head coach Chan Gailey
of Stewart:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've come close to seeing what he can and will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's true of Stewart, it might also be true of Stewart's
team.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Steelers aren't the AFC team to beat, who is?
``Denver is that right now,'' Bettis says, ``because they've won a
Super Bowl and they have most of their team intact.''
</P>
<P>
   True, but the last AFC Super Bowl champion to defend its title
came 19 seasons years ago with quarterback Terry Bradshaw's
Steelers. That was a younger team; the same cannot be said for the
Broncos, who relied on 16-year quarterback John Elway and 18 other
players with eight or more seasons of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose you can make the argument against us based on age,''
says Broncos cornerback Ray Crockett, who starts his 11th season.
``On the other hand, John's one of the elder statesmen in the NFL,
and when he considered retirement it shook up the whole league.
Would you rather we be a younger team and not have John Elway?''
</P>
<P>
   Would you rather be the Chiefs? Kansas City is the only team in
the NFL to finish first or second in its division in each of the
last nine seasons and have posted the NFL's best record in two of
the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The '97 club started a new quarterback in Elvis Grbac and four
'96 draft picks on defense yet finished 13-3. Now comes the
maturity of those players, plus newly acquired wide receiver
Derrick Alexander and veteran defensive linemen Chester McGlockton
and Leslie O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Says Alexander of the organization's aspirations: ``It's like
we've failed here if we don't get to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksonville Jaguars have quickly elevated themselves to a
similar level of expectations. In just its fourth year of
operation, the expansion club boasts a premier offensive line
featuring tackles Tony Boselli and Leon Searcy, a
scrapheap-turned-Pro Bowl tandem of receivers in Jimmy Smith and
Keenan McCardell, a defense that should improve pass pressure with
the addition of Bryce Paup, and the franchise QB in Mark Brunell.
Brunell may be the best combination of polish and innovation this
side of Brett Favre and Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Patriots, an organization still stinging from
the widely held suspicion that the '96 edition qualified for the
Super Bowl on the solitary strength of departed coach Bill
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's an unfair criticism of New England's talent
to say that any team Parcells coaches is probably going to be a
contender,'' says NFL scouting guru Gil Brandt. ``For me, New
England isn't at the same level as the Pittsburghs and Denvers. I
think it's fair to say Parcells got the most out of that bunch when
he was there, and now they've lost both their coach and their star
running back.''
</P>
<P>
   Runner Curtis Martin is gone (painfully for the Pats, he has
followed Parcells to another AFC East outpost, the New York Jets)
but not forgotten _ no matter how hard coach Pete Carroll tries.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is whispering that rookie Robert Edwards is not only a
better running back than Martin, but that Edwards compares
favorably with Denver star Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Carroll's forecast goes unrealized, New England has an
edge over the other members of the AFC's Big Five: The Pats don't
have the sort of divisional shadow that Denver and Kansas City and
Pittsburgh and Jacksonville represent for one another _ unless ones
counts the track record of the Jets' Parcells and the Miami
Dolphins' Jimmy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is achievable,'' says Dolphins linebacker Zach
Thomas. ``People might not see it right now because we haven't done
anything yet. But nothing is too far out of reach.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be the slogan for the AFC this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
