<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4802 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AIRSTRIKES-HN     08-20 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AIRSTRIKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON: U.S. STRIKES `BACK' WITH MISSILE ATTACKS IN AFGHANISTAN,
SUDAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ American forces launched a missile attack at
suspected terrorist facilities in Afghanistan and Sudan on Thursday
in retaliation for bombings at U.S. embassies in Africa and to
pre-empt what President Clinton said were other planned attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In a pair of live television appearances, Clinton said he had
ordered the simultaneous attacks on terrorist organizations
affiliated with dissident Saudi millionaire Osama bin Laden
``because we have convincing evidence these groups played the key
role in the embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With compelling evidence that the bin Laden network of
terrorist groups was planning to mount further attacks against
Americans and other freedom-loving people, I decided America must
act,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and Pentagon sources said the U.S. strikes were
carried out by Navy ships in the Red Sea and Arabian Sea that
launched up to 100 Tomahawk cruise missiles. The weapons targeted a
bin Laden terrorist complex in Afghanistan and a pharmaceutical
plant in the Sudanese capital of Khartoum suspected of producing
chemical weapons agents.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon and White House officials refused to release details of
the attacks, but said three targets in the terrorist complex
located 94 miles south of Kabul, Afghanistan, and the plant in
Khartoum were hit. The assault began about 1:30 p.m., EDT, and
lasted about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials were still waiting for damage reports
on the targets late Thursday night. But based on television reports
from Sudan showing the gutted and still burning Shifa
Pharmaceutical Plant, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
declared the missile strikes ``a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudanese officials claimed that the plant was actually a private
medical facility. But Albright said there was clear evidence that
it produces agents that could be used to make VX nerve gas and is
heavily guarded by the Sudanese military.
</P>
<P>
   The missile strike on the plant in Sudan touched off a massive
demonstration in front of the U.S. embassy in Khartoum, which has
been closed for nearly two years. Dozens of protesters stormed the
high fence surrounding it, but found only a few of their
compatriots who had been hired to look after the facility. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Clinton called the base in Afghanistan ``one of the most
active'' in the world, and blamed bin Laden, long suspected of
being a major sponsor of terrorism, for financing, planning and
executing the bombings in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam on Aug. 7 that
killed 263 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we have struck back,'' the president declared.
</P>
<P>
   His dramatic announcement stunned the nation and caught most
lawmakers off guard. A few Republican critics questioned ``the
timing,'' of the attack, coming just three days after his public
admission that he had an ``inappropriate'' relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we may have a president who is desperate to hold on to
this job,'' said Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind. He repeated a call he made
earlier this week for the president to resign.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the Republican leadership rallied to Clinton's side
in a show of unity. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi and House Speaker Newt Gingrich of Georgia both praised
Clinton for taking military action.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said it would be ``sick'' for anyone to suggest that
Clinton's personal problems had driven him to take action. ``Based
on what I know, I think it was the right thing to do at the right
time,'' Gingrich told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sens. Jesse Helms of North Carolina, who heads the
Foreign Relations Committee, and John McCain of Arizona, a member
of the Armed Services Committee, also stood behind the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton interrupted his vacation on Martha's Vineyard to
announce the missile strikes, then flew to Washington for a
briefing by military and national security officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a second televised appearance late Thursday afternoon, the
president said his primary motivation for ordering the strikes was
to prevent other attacks on U.S. targets, which he described as
``an immediate threat.''
</P>
<P>
   He said U.S. intelligence sources had also uncovered evidence
that ``a gathering of key terrorist leaders was to take place
today'' at the Afghanistan complex ``thus underscoring the urgency
of our actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said later
that FBI and U.S. intelligence officials investigating the bombings
in Kenya and Tanzania had obtained ``very reliable information''
that other U.S. embassies and facilities were about to be hit by
elements supported by bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very specific information about very specific threats
in respect to very specific targets,'' Berger added, noting that a
number of U.S. embassies, including one in Albania, had been closed
in recent days because of the threats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton indicated that the military strikes may be the first
step in what could be a prolonged U.S. campaign aimed at wiping out
key terrorist cells. He said bin Laden, who he described as the
``pre-eminent organizer and financier of international terrorism in
the world today,'' was also responsible for assassination attempts
on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let our actions today send this message loud and clear: There
are no expendable American targets,'' Clinton said. ``We will
defend our people, our interests and our values.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said they were fairly confident that the
heavy missile attack on what they described as bin Laden's
``terrorist university'' in Afghanistan had severely damaged his
ability to train and support his operatives and those connected
with other terrorist groups he backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facilities we struck today in Afghanistan and Sudan are
important parts of the bin Laden network terrorist groups,'' said
Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. He said
the bases not only provide ``refuge for terrorists'' but also serve
as ``the key command and control'' center for terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
   A Taliban spokesman said bin Laden was unharmed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   But Defense Secretary William Cohen said the intent of the
mission, which was unanimous approval of all Clinton's national
security advisers, was to destroy bin Laden's ability to support
terrorist acts and not necessarily to kill bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that these strikes will not eliminate the
problem, but our message is clear,'' said Cohen. ``There will be no
sanctuary for terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
