r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      08-20 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 NationsBank Hated American Banker Story, Plans to Cancel   By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Talk about thin-skinned.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the rare event that you were looking for more absurdity
wrought by mega-bank merger mania, try this on for size.
NationsBank President Kenneth Lewis plans to cancel his bankholding
company's subscriptions to the American Banker because the trade
paper ran an article that audaciously suggests how it should handle
its community reinvestment obligations in California.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Fire the messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Just because Lewis didn't agree with an opinion piece submitted
to the American Banker by the Greenlining Institute, a San
Francisco advocacy group for minorities and low-income folks, he
thinks he's going to punish the publishers of the paper by
scrapping his bank's 250 or so subscriptions, according to an
internal memo signed by Lewis, which was obtained by Chronicle
banking reporter Peter Sinton. NationsBank, BankAmerica and
American Banker officials declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. This Lewis is a tough guy. Boy, that kind of hardball
tactic is really going to make those editors at the American Banker
shake in their boots, hey?
</P>
<P>
   How silly. With mature and enlightened leadership like that
waiting for us back in Charlotte, N.C., it's no wonder BankAmerica
customers are concerned that commitment to low-income neighborhoods
will wane after their bank becomes part of Hugh McColl's banking
empire this fall.
</P>
<P>
   And when you hear what the crux of the op-ed column was about,
Lewis' overreaction is going to seem even sillier. Essentially, the
piece by Greenlining's John Gamboa and Mary Ann Mitchell,
chairwoman of the National Black Business Council, suggests that
NationsBank should follow the example set by Washington Mutual. The
authors applauded the Seattle-based thrift for the way it handled
the buyouts of some good-size California savings and loans.
</P>
<P>
   What they liked most and recommended &UR;  &LR; that NationsBank emulate
was Washington Mutual's willingness to draft a community
reinvestment agreement. As opposed to some rather loosey-goosey
pledge of $350 billion as NationsBank is wont to have, Wamu (as
they say in banking circles) outlined specific goals on how it
would serve and lend money to less fortunate communities. Gee, what
an offensive idea.
</P>
<P>
   How did Lewis, the NationsBank executive, react to this
constructive input? Not very well, needless to say. In a memorandum
dated August 4, Lewis wrote: ``I am sure that you are as offended
and angry as I am about an industry newspaper doing such a thing.
Given that we are very focused on expense savings, couldn't we do
without this newspaper?''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, terrific. The bank can extract some of the $1.3 billion in
economies of scale expected from swallowing BankAmerica by
canceling its newspaper subscriptions. Without knowing what kind of
a deal the bank has with the paper (let's just use the bank's
discounted annual subscription rate of $795), that might just save
NationsBank a whopping $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's what I call high finance. No wonder Lewis gets paid
the big bucks. Shareholders are coughing up at least $1.2 million a
year before stock options for this kind of executive acumen. (His
stock grants are currently worth more than $14 million.)
</P>
<P>
   To say the least, Lewis really knows how to slice the marble off
the cow, doesn't he?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pour Some More  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt that the Internet offers investors far more
access to government filings and real-time information than ever
before. But sometimes it isn't always presented in context, and
that can cause some minor confusion. At least, that may have been
what happened with Golden State Vintners.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of readers responded to Wednesday's column, saying that
insider selling may have driven down the wine stock's shares
shortly after going public in July.
</P>
<P>
   That probably wasn't the case. In fact, some federal filings on
July 27 show that about 1.1 million shares of common were sold at
an average price of $15.88 a share by a group of insiders,
including directors.
</P>
<P>
   But venture capitalists didn't just impulsively dump shares on
the market. These were ownership shares sold to the public as part
of the offering. It happens that there is a three- to five-day
settlement period that follows an initial offering before the
transactions get posted with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, explains Golden State chief financial officer Brian
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   The company's IPO ``was always intended to provide liquidity to
certain shareholders (and) I can understand how there might be some
confusion'' from the filings, Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   Did the postings contribute to the stock's slide that began a
few days after the IPO?
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't believe so,'' Thompson says.
</P>
<P>
   Insider trading expert Bob Gabele concurs.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State shares ``were sold in the deal,'' which means there
were existing shares as well as newly created shares in the
offering, says Gabele, editor of Maryland-based CDA Investnet's
Insiders' Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that unusual to see selling in the deal,'' Gabele
says.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Bob.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., SF
94103, by phone at 415-777-8444 or by e-mail at mveverka(at
sign)sfgate.com.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
