<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0573 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-BASEBALLS     08-20 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-BASEBALLS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES UNDER INVESTIGATION FOR SELLING PERFECT-GAME BASEBALLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Major League Baseball is investigating the possible role of
American League umpires in the sale of baseballs used in the
perfect game that David Wells of the Yankees pitched against the
Minnesota Twins May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials confirmed the investigation Thursday, but
declined to identify the umpires. Others, however, including a Long
Island sports memorabilia dealer who said he bought 14 balls, named
Al Clark as the umpire who was directly involved in the
transaction. Two baseball officials also said Clark's name had come
up in the investigation as having been involved in the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lewis, the dealer, said Clark provided a letter
authenticating the balls, each of which bore Wells' signature and a
hand-written notation that it was used in the game. Clark was not
part of the umpiring crew that worked the game at Yankee Stadium,
but Lewis said Clark's letter revealed he obtained the balls from
John Hirschbeck, who was the first-base umpire that day.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck denied Thursday that he gave any balls to Clark and
said he had no idea why Clark would say that he did.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, an American League umpire since 1976, was on his
in-season vacation, and attempts to reach him through the American
League and Richie Phillips, the head of the umpires union, were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's policy on the sale of paraphernalia by umpires is not
clear-cut. Gene Budig, the American League president, said Thursday
that both leagues have distributed to their umpires guidelines on
various matters. One policy, he said, dealt with autographs,
memorabilia and tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting from the instructions about memorabilia, Budig said:
``There is to be no asking players, managers, coaches or other
field personnel for autographs. If you need an item or an autograph
for a charity event or other special/unique reason, please contact
the league office and we will contact the club on your behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the policy covers the sale of the so-called items, such
as baseballs, Budig declined to say. He also declined to comment on
the investigation, saying only, ``The league is aware of the matter
and it is being reviewed by appropriate staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hallinan, baseball's chief security official, said the
American League had asked him to look into the matter, but he
declined to comment on his investigation except to say, ``We
haven't targeted Al or anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the policy Budig cited, umpires often ask players for
autographs and memorabilia. Players have long hated the practice,
but they feel they can neither refuse the requests nor complain
about them because they fear the umpires will retaliate with their
calls in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the issues players raise with us with frequency,'' said
Donald Fehr, head of the players association, ``is requests by
umpires for players to provide memorabilia, which in many cases the
players expect will be sold.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a subject under discussion between clubs and the
players union.
</P>
<P>
   Wells declined to talk about the sale of the balls from his
perfect game, but a baseball official said the pitcher learned from
a friend that the balls were being advertised for sale. Lewis, the
dealer, said in a telephone interview that Wells called him and
questioned the authenticity of the balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He questioned whether the umpires got the balls from the ball
bag because he thought he received all the balls from the ball
bag,'' related Lewis, who Thursday was at Shea Stadium prepared to
pay $10,000 to the fan who caught Mark McGwire's 50th home run.
</P>
<P>
   The ball bag in question contained balls that were used in the
game or rubbed up for use in the game. The home-plate umpire keeps
several balls in a bag hanging from his waist, and when he needs a
fresh supply, the ball boy brings balls to him from the ball bag.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck, in denying any role in the sale of the balls, also
questioned their authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how they can be legitimate,' he said by telephone
from Youngstown, Ohio, where he had just played a round of golf on
his vacation. ``I know the ball bag never came to our locker room.
They came to Wells.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck, an American League umpire since 1984, said that Tim
McClelland, who was the plate umpire that day, had four balls in
his ball bag at the end of the game. ``David Wells signed those and
Tim gave one to each of us,'' Hirschbeck said. ``I still have
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he agreed to buy 14 balls from a man representing
Clark whom he identified as Rich Gressle, a New Jersey resident.
The dealer said he paid $300 a ball for the first six balls and
quickly sold four for $1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, he said, he was visited by Ed Petersen,
Hallinan's assistant in baseball's security department. Once he
learned the matter was under investigation, Lewis said, he asked
the buyers to return the balls, and he gave back their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reputation was on the line because there was a question,''
Lewis said, explaining his move. He added that Gressle asked for
all of the balls back and sent him a check for $1,800. However,
Lewis added, Petersen asked to borrow a ball for baseball's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis also said if the balls turn out to be legitimate and
remain available, he would buy them again.
</P>
<P>
   He said they had Wells's signature with the date on what he
called ``the sweet spot'' of the ball. Underneath the signature, he
said, was a notation that the balls were ``game-used.'' He said
Clark's letter said the notation was made by the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck said he did not understand why Clark wrote in the
letter that the balls came from him. He said the only contact he
has had with Clark this season was at a series he worked in New
York, when the Yankees played the Boston Red Sox. Hirschbeck said
he substituted for Jim McKean, the crew chief, in that series that
began 11 days after the perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck said he was in New York when he heard that balls from
the game were for sale and met with Wells to tell him that neither
he nor any other members of the umpiring crew had anything to do
with the advertised balls.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he has received many other items from umpires for
sale but declined to identify any of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
