<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVENT-ACCOUNTING-ART     08-20 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-ACCOUNTING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVENT DREW IN A NEW TEAM DESPITE JUGGLING EXPENSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Canada)  (Eds: Also filed in ``e'' category.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN and GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Behind the curtain at Livent Inc., the corporate theater
producer, the flamboyant impresario Garth Drabinsky did not just
produce Tony Award-winning Broadway musicals. He also created a
brilliant but mythical setting for his business, a world where much
of his famously lavish spending was visible on stage but somehow
rarely hurt the company's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   One of Drabinsky's props was Livent's financial books, which are
being investigated by securities regulators. The company's new
owners, Michael Ovitz and Roy Furman, say the books appear to have
been doctored.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many musicals that have ``angels,'' or private investors
who carefully track how a producer is spending their money,
Drabinsky's shows did not get such scrutiny. Livent, a public
company, produced many shows at once, lumping expenses together,
and disclosed few details on which ones _ if any _ were making
money.
</P>
<P>
   Other theater executives wondered how long the company could
afford extravagances such as a cast of 67 performers for
``Showboat'' and the dozens of double-page color newspaper ads
promoting its shows. One associate of Cameron Mackintosh, the
highly regarded producer of ``Miss Saigon,'' ``Phantom of the
Opera'' and ``Les Miserables,'' for example, remembers that
Mackintosh bet him four years ago that Drabinsky's company would
fail. Mackintosh could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, did Ovitz, the former talent agent and former
president of Walt Disney Co., put $20 million into Livent, and why
did Furman, a co-founder of the Wall Street firm Furman Selz, agree
to put up $2 million and become chairman? Furman, who had sold his
firm to ING Group last October, said, ``We wanted to be able to
look back and say that we were the people who proved to the public
that theater was profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love theater,'' he said. ``It is very important that theater
be done properly.'' He said that they thought they could change a
``financial model that was wrong.'' Ovitz declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Livent said that the two men knew before they
took control that the company had some financial problems, though
they did not anticipate what they call accounting irregularities.
Just last week, Furman and his new management team announced that
they had discovered those irregularities and that they were
suspending Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb, the company's vice
president and a co-founder with Drabinksy.
</P>
<P>
   The company has released few details, but some executives say
privately that Drabinsky kept ``a second set of books.'' They say
it appeared that the two men had run out of ways to keep their
spending from hurting the company's profits and had inappropriately
moved the costs to other accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Drabinsky and Gottlieb have denied any wrongdoing and any
knowledge of a second set of books. And on Thursday, a spokesman
for the two questioned why so many accusations were being hurled at
them. He said that the new management had been given ``ample
opportunity during a protracted due diligence process to ask any
questions they had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are concerns being raised now?'' the spokesman asked.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the new team had not discovered any irregularities,
warning signs that Drabinsky's high-spending ways would eventually
catch up with Livent had been popping up for years.
</P>
<P>
   _ The company's debt was labeled ``junk'' last year by Wall
Street bond-rating agencies because of worries that the company
would not be able to make interest payments that amount to nearly
$13 million each year. The company's debt now exceeds $130 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ The company, which is based in Toronto, used Canadian
accounting standards, which are looser and allow companies to
record profits sooner than the rules in the United States. For
example, the $29 million loss that Livent reported last year using
Canadian accounting would have shown up as $38 million using
American standards, according to the company's financial
statements.
</P>
<P>
   _ Analysts complained about an accounting method that the
company adopted in 1996 that in essence allowed Drabinsky to spend
as much as he wanted on a musical for costs such as advertising,
costumes and scenery without deducting them immediately from the
bottom line. Unlike most other Broadway productions, Livent was
able after changing its accounting methods to show a profit on a
musical even before ticket sales covered the costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accounting was aggressive,'' said David McFadgen, an
entertainment industry analyst with Griffiths McBurney and Partners
in Montreal. ``It just made no sense.'' McFadgen has long been
critical of the company's financial reporting and recalls how
Drabinsky once yelled at him on the phone for issuing a negative
report.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Livent's vendors had been complaining for years
that the company took months to pay its bills. For example, the
owners of shoemaking shops and fabric stores in Toronto, where
Livent creates most of its musicals, complained about Drabinsky's
slow bill-paying habits to one costume designer who was trying to
buy attire for another producer's show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every place I went, they would say, `You're not with Garth
Drabinsky, are you?''' said the costume designer, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. ``His reputation was the worst.'' A
spokesman for Drabinksky declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   What shocked several veteran Broadway producers and executives
was the company's high-spending ways. For example, the cast of 67
performers for Livent's revival of ``Showboat'' was
``unprecedented,'' one Broadway executive said. ``And the company
was spending massive amounts of money on advertising,'' this person
said, including double-page color ads in major newspapers,
including The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
