<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0577 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4816 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-BIRNBAUM-LADN     08-20 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-BIRNBAUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY TO DISTRIBUTE FUTURE BIRNBAUM FILMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Walt Disney Co. has announced that it has
signed a distribution deal with high-profile producer Roger
Birnbaum for up to five movies a year through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment giant said Thursday the deal with Birnbaum's
newly formed Spyglass Entertainment calls for Spyglass to finance
the projects with Disney handling distribution in the United
States, United Kingdom, Australia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reflects Disney's strategy of spending less on
live-action movies, which have provided lower profits than most
other operations, while continuing to send a full pipeline of
product to multiplexes. ``As we reduce our investment in our
release slate we look forward to distributing first-tier,
independently financed films,'' Disney studio chief Joe Roth said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is pretty consistent with what Disney has said it
wanted to do,'' said Stewart Halpern, an analyst with ING Barings
Furman Selz. ``It's a way to make a low-risk profit and maintain an
appropriate volume for its distribution infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   The pact calls for Birnbaum's Caravan Pictures to stop
operations following release of New Line's ``Rush Hour'' and two
upcoming Disney movies _ ``Simon Birch'' and Eddie Murphy's ``Holy
Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Spyglass' major upcoming projects include ``From Alice to the
Ocean'' with Julia Roberts as a producer and star; ``The
Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy,'' based on Douglas Adams'
best-selling novel; ``Cosmo Cop'' with Murphy; and remakes of ``The
Errand Boy'' and ``Old Dark House.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0578 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4817 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVENT-ACCOUNTING-ART     08-20 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVENT-ACCOUNTING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: York Times. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some critics also said that given its financial state, the
company had spent too much to build theaters _ $35 million for the
Ford Center for the Performing Arts in Manhattan alone _ and to
promote shows in a notoriously unpredictable business. They noted
that even producers of mega-hits showed more restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Even Livent's biggest hit before ``Showboat'' and ``Ragtime,''
the Tony-Award-winning ``Kiss of the Spider Woman,'' had reported a
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the financial woes they inherited, Ovitz and Furman
are said to think that by tightening financial controls, they can
turn the company around. One person who knows Ovitz well said he
compared the enterprise to a movie studio that can release several
films at a time and let the profits from the blockbusters carry the
rest of the company.
</P>
<P>
   And some entertainment executives said privately that the two
men might have found the Livent deal appealing because both are at
personal crossroads in their careers and both like the
entertainment business. Furman, 59, apparently wanted a new
challenge after selling his investment firm. And Ovitz, once
referred to as the most powerful man in Hollywood, has been without
a focus since he left Disney. ``Where else could Ovitz get control
of a highly visible company for $20 million,'' asked one industry
executive, who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Furman is a veteran investor in the entertainment business.
Furman Selz had taken large stakes at one time or another in Time
Warner, MCA, Carolco, New Line Cinema and others. He has also
headed the Film Society of Lincoln Center and is an avid
theatergoer.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were so enamored of show business, apparently, that
they were willing to set aside Drabinsky's checkered stewardship of
another company, Cineplex Odeon, the movie theater chain, nearly a
decade ago. That company was also criticized for its aggressive
accounting methods. In 1989, Drabinsky was ousted in a fierce
battle with MCA, one of Cineplex Odeon's largest shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   However, neither Furman nor Ovitz had extensive financial
experience in the arcane world of live theater. And Furman had
never run a public company. Not only that but, for now at least,
they must rely on several of the same creative executives who
worked for Drabinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Associates said one of the main protections they saw for their
investment was the value of the real estate: Besides its New York
theater, Livent owns two in Toronto, one in Vancouver, British
Columbia, and one in Chicago. One person close to the company
estimated their value at up to $200 million, though a theater
industry expert, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, gave a
lower estimate of about $120 million, not enough to wipe out the
company's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Furman also sees plays as ``software'' that could generate pay
television, pay-per-view and video rights, one of his associates
said. One pay-television executive who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said there was no recent history of Broadway shows
selling to pay TV or pay-per-per view because there was not much
interest in buying such projects. Revenues from home-video sales
have been slim.
</P>
<P>
   Livent clearly has a long way to go. It has said it will take
additional write-offs that have nothing to do with the accounting
irregularities and that possibly relate to the North American tour
of ``Showboat.'' And despite the near-sellout of ``Ragtime'' in New
York, it is doing relatively mediocre business on tour. Though
Livent plans to open ``Ragtime'' in Chicago in October, its debut
in London has been postponed indefinitely. If it does open there,
Livent might try to cut costs by taking sets and props from an
existing production, a person close to the company said.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, ``Ragtime'' and other Livent shows will have to
lure audiences without the huge advertising budgets for which
Drabinsky was famous. That makes the new owners' bet on which plays
to produce and which performers to hire all that more crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, those were the things that Drabinsky, now gone, did best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
