<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers agrees to go on DL
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark Wohlers returns to the Atlanta Braves today,
though maybe only on paper.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, in an arrangement worked out between the club and
Wohlers' agent, will recall Wohlers from his optional minor league
assignment in Class AAA Richmond, but only to place him on the
major league club's disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers, who has been in Richmond since Aug. 11, is expected to
spend only two or three days in town and then return to Richmond on
a medical rehab assignment. Asked how the Braves would specify
Wohlers' malady for placing him on the DL, general manager John
Schuerholz said the reliever's inability to pitch is justification
enough, under baseball rules.
</P>
<P>
   The move saves the team from having to demote another reliever.
The Braves have to send down somebody today when it activates
reliever Russ Springer off the DL. The move also keeps Wohlers from
losing any major league service time, which became an issue during
the right-hander's first optional assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had been in touch with Wohlers and his New York-based
agent, Seth Levinson, to solve what had become a sticky roster
situation, particularly since playoff rosters must be turned in
Aug. 31. Moreover, the team saw no reason for Wohlers to try to
pitch in Atlanta, though as a five-year veteran he has the right to
claim his roster spot after his minor league assignment was up.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not about just wanting (Wohlers to stay down),''
Schuerholz said Thursday. ''It's really the only viable, meaningful
thing to do right now, so that he can keep pitching on a regular
basis, which is why we did it in the first place and why he
accepted. It's not as if we're forcing him to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hail El Presidente
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will salute Dennis Martinez and his 244th career win
before Sunday's game with Los Angeles. The club is flying in the
43-year-old right-hander's family from Miami, as well as Nicaraguan
ambassador Aguirre Sacasa from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The club is also trying to arrange a video presentation with
Juan Marichal, the ex-San Francisco great whose record Martinez
broke as the game's winningest Latin American pitcher. A CNN camera
crew is currently on assignment in the Dominican Republic and the
team is trying to set up a video shoot to be replayed on the Turner
Field scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher in the slump
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez took a 4-for-28 slump into Thursday night, a result,
he says, of home-run fever. After hitting homers in three straight
games two weeks ago, Lopez has skewed his swing trying to reach the
fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impatient, that's the word,'' said Lopez, who has driven
in only one run since Aug. 8. ``I'm not swinging at good pitches.
Each time I feel like my swing is there but the pitch I'm swinging
at is no good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch, ouch, etc.
</P>
<P>
   One notable factor in Andres Galarraga's setting the modern
franchise record for most times being hit by pitches: he needed
just 120 games to get hit 21 times while Jeff Blauser, who set the
record of 20 last season, did so in 151 games. The record-breaker,
which came off San Francisco's Julian Tavarez Tuesday night,
occurred right after Tavarez had intentionally walked Chipper Jones
and loaded the bases. Galarraga, who has been hit 133 times in his
career, cannot remember being plunked right after an intentional
walk before. His next target: the all-time record of 29, set by
Boston Beaneater Tommy Tucker in 1891.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like this record,'' Galarraga said. ``You can have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, since he began wearing his padded guard on his
left arm, he has been hit 11 times. Just once has the ball hit the
guard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
