<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leyritz on Wohlers: It's mental
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The man widely credited with transforming once-potent
Mark Wohlers into a struggling minor-league pitcher wants no part
of that distinction.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres' Jim Leyritz admits to turning the 1996
World Series, but Wohlers' problems, he insists, have nothing to do
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Mark, it's all mental,'' said Leyritz, whose three-run
homer as a New York Yankee off Wohlers in the eighth inning of Game
4 erased a three-run deficit. The Yankees went on to win that game
and the Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the talk that I'm the reason he's had it bad
lately, and I don't believe it at all,'' the Padres' part-time
catcher said Thursday night. ``I watched him the next year after my
homer mow down the entire National League (33 saves, 3.50 ERA). If
it was my hit, he wouldn't have had the year he did in '97. I'm
sure it's a mental thing with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz has seen a case similar to Wohlers' up close and
personal. And it is that experience that lets him know Wohlers'
troubles are in his head. In 1992 and '93, Leyritz caught a
promising young Yankee prospect named Sam Militello. The youngster
was brought up in the second half of the '92 season and started
nine games. He was projected as the next great Yankee hurler.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``he got hurt in spring training the next year,''
Leyritz recalled, ``and rushed back and was never the same. He got
mentally screwed up. You could catch him in the bullpen and he'd
throw the ball right to the spot. But as soon as you put a batter
in there, he was throwing to the backstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Militello was never heard from again. Wohlers, meanwhile,
continues his quest to find the strike zone and his confidence in
Class AAA Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he gets over it,'' Leyritz said. ``He's a good guy, a
great guy, which makes it harder to see him go through this. That
home run I hit will always be a burden for me and him. But I don't
think it affected him mentally to the point where he's struggling
so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, a virtual unknown until he jettisoned Wohlers' slider
at old Atlanta Fulton County Stadium, called his bomb a ``burden,''
but it's really been the identifying play of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That home run was big for both of us,'' he said. ``It was the
moment of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
