<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZERS OF YOUTH MARCH SUE CITY IN EFFORT TO HOLD RALLY IN
HARLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The organizers of a planned Million Youth March sued
the city in federal court Thursday, saying that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's refusal to grant them a permit to hold the event in
Harlem next month was both unconstitutional and reflective of the
mayor's discriminatory treatment of the city's black residents.
</P>
<P>
   The court action came as Harlem's most prominent black minister,
the Rev. Calvin O. Butts 3d, threw his support behind the march,
saying it was a perfect opportunity for young blacks to call
attention to issues that affect them, like unemployment and the
high cost of health care. Other civic leaders in Harlem have also
stepped up their support for the march in recent days, saying the
Mayor's resistance is an affront to their community.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have said they denied the permit because the
neighborhood cannot safely accommodate the one million participants
the organizers had said they expected.
</P>
<P>
   But the organizers, appearing before Judge Lewis Kaplan in
federal district court, said the city had refused to grant a permit
to hold the rally along Malcolm X Boulevard on Sept. 5 only because
of Giuliani's ``dislike for one of the conveners of the rally,''
Khalid Abdul Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   They said it made no sense for the city to reject their permit
application, since the city regularly grants permits for even
larger rallies and parades. ``The only issue is whether or not the
Constitution applies to the people of Harlem,'' said Roger Wareham,
a lawyer for the march organizers. ``The city's policy is totally
arbitrary about who they grant permits to and when.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad and other organizers have billed the event as a show of
unity among young blacks from across the country, much like the
Million Man March that was held in Washington in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani has denounced it as a ``hate march,'' citing
anti-Semitic and anti-white remarks by Muhammad, a former top
official in the Nation of Islam. The mayor has repeatedly condemned
Muhammad and criticized the organizers' plan to invite gang members
to the rally.
</P>
<P>
   In court Thursday, lawyers for the city questioned why the march
organizers waited so long _ their permit application was rejected
in February _ to take their case before a judge. They said
Giuliani's opinion of Muhammad had nothing to do with the denial of
the permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor did not decide whether the permit should be granted
or denied,'' said Michael Hess, the city's corporation counsel.
``This did not turn on the words of Mayor Giuliani one way or the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
