<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4825 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-JOB-TENURE-$ADV2     08-20 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-JOB-TENURE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOB-HOPPERS HAVE YET TO CONQUER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.Y. Calif.)   (af)  
 By SUSAN J. WELLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contrary to the popular belief that corporate downsizing and
job-hopping have eroded job stability, private studies and
government data show that average job tenure has changed remarkably
little in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   And workers, especially women, are generally feeling secure in
their jobs, with many enjoying the one-company careers widely
regarded as anachronisms, the studies suggest.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent study conducted by Watson Wyatt Worldwide,
a management consulting firm in Bethesda, Md., the average job
tenure at midsize and large companies was 13.4 years in the most
recent period _ 1995 to 1997 _ up from 12.6 years from 1990 to
1992.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined the employment records of one million workers
at 59 companies at the beginning and end of three different
five-year periods _ 1990 to 1995, 1991 to 1996 and 1992 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the portion of workers who stayed with the
same employer for at least 10 years had risen significantly _ from
54 percent for 1990-92 to 57.6 percent in the most recent period.
The number of workers with 20-year tenure also climbed, from 25.6
percent to 26.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rush of concern over people losing or changing jobs due to
downsizing or layoffs or what have you would give the impression
that there's less stability than ever,'' said Sylvester Schieber,
director of research at Watson Wyatt. ``But this conventional
wisdom is simply not borne out by our research.'' The company said
its study was the first this decade to review employment records to
determine job tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for rising tenure is an aging work force. The
average age of employees in the Watson Wyatt study, for example,
rose to 41.9 years in the most recent period, from 40.7. ``The
older a person is, the more likely she is to stay with the same
job,'' Schieber said.
</P>
<P>
   Over a longer term, government data also show a slight increase
in median job tenure for workers. The median number of years that
workers had spent with their current employers rose from 3.5 years
in 1983 to 3.8 years in 1996, the most recent data available, the
Bureau of Labor Statistics reported.
</P>
<P>
   Differences show up, however, between the sexes. The job tenure
of men age 16 and older declined slightly, from 4.1 years in 1983
to 4.0 in 1996. But tenure for women has risen consistently, from
3.1 years to a record 3.5 years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, job tenure could rise in coming years, as the effects
of downsizing ebb. In a survey released last week, the bureau found
that a smaller percentage of workers had been laid off in the last
three years _ eight million, or one of every 15 jobholders _ than
in any other period this decade. But layoffs are still
significantly higher than they were in the 1980s and could rise
again if the economy slows.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the trends, Henry S. Farber, an economist at Princeton
University who studies job-tenure patterns, said: ``There's just no
basis for the idea that the great American job is dead. The answer
is that long-term jobs in the United States are as common as ever.
The difference is in who holds them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenure rates tend to move with the business cycle, decreasing in
strong economic times, for example, as companies expand _ thus
increasing their hiring and diluting their average tenure rate.
During good times, experienced workers also have more opportunities
to change employers and take better jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But tenure can rise in weak or recessionary times, as older
workers tend to be the last to be let go, leaving companies with a
higher proportion of longer-term employees.
</P>
<P>
   In some industries, like the labor-starved high-technology
sector, high tenure rates can even be frowned upon. In an survey of
250 companies by Towers Perrin, a consulting firm in New York,
those that rated technology as key to their businesses _ one-third
of the respondents _ generally reported the highest levels of
turnover. And some technology businesses actively recruit workers
who have moved from company to company, seeing such job-hopping as
essential in keeping skills up to date, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Dudley Brown, managing director of Bridgegate LLC, an executive
search consulting firm in Irvine, Calif., said it was easier for
technology workers to move from job to job because of the
industry's focus on product development cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Once a new software product is completed, for example, the
project's employees might prefer working on new products at other
companies to sticking around and developing upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   While companies ``don't necessarily see a lot of job-hopping on
a resume as desirable'' he said, ``in our experience, people don't
tend to stick around beyond five years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're probably most valuable to the company during your first
year or two, when you're still thinking out of the box, trying to
change and improve things,'' Brown added. ``Companies want that
freshness _ especially in tech people.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line in his business, he said, is that ``people buy
resumes the same way they buy cereal: if you've come out of a No.
1, 2 or 3 firm, you're a hot commodity, you're popular and everyone
wants to try you.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Long-term workers are more expensive for
employers to keep. Not surprisingly, the Watson Wyatt study found
that costs for pay and benefits _ like health insurance, pensions,
401(k) plans and paid time off, were substantially higher in
companies with higher average tenure.
</P>
<P>
   If the trends continue, will employers have to look for ways to
shave the costs of high-tenure staff? ``It should be a wake-up
call,'' Schieber said. ``Older workers may be more expensive to
maintain on the payroll, but companies cannot afford to simply let
so much talent go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
