<HEADLINE>
CLINTON JUGGLED PERSONAL, POLICY AFFAIRS OVER WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton informed his wife of his
extramarital affair with Monica S. Lewinsky and prepared his
unprecedented testimony before a federal grand jury last weekend,
he also gathered his senior national security advisers and plotted
his strategy to do battle with terrorist forces abroad, aides said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This combination marks a breathtaking juxtaposition of policy
and personal life. Since Monday, when the nation became transfixed
in the aftermath of his televised confession, Clinton and a few
elite aides harbored a secret: they planned to lob more than 100
cruise missiles at suspected terrorist sites in Sudan and
Afghanistan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive meeting to strike came in the White House last
Friday, officials said, after Clinton's national security adviser
Samuel R.Berger and CIA Director George Tenet concluded that Saudi
millionaire Osama bin Laden was responsible for the deadly bombings
of two US embassies in Africa on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, Tenet, Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen and Joint
Chiefs of Staff Chairman Hugh Shelton gathered with Clinton in the
White House to lay out their proposal for a missile attack that
would involve no troops and put no Americans at risk. The targets
were a suspected chemical weapons plant in Sudan that US officials
believe was financed by bin Laden, and his sprawling terrorist
training center in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   At the Friday meeting, Clinton approved the proposal with one
caveat: He wanted the ability to halt the operation until 6 a.m. on
the morning of the attack, when he would be secluded in a
beachhouse outside of Edgartown on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was perhaps most notable for its secrecy.
Virtually no White House political or domestic aides were apprised
of the plans, except for Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles. Members of
the congressional intelligence committees were intentionally kept
out of the loop. Only Clinton's most senior national security
aides, as well as the four highest-ranking congressional leaders,
were kept informed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Martha's Vineyard, Clinton worked the telephones overnight
Thursday, talking repeatedly with Berger in Washington and placing
a call to Vice President Al Gore, who was vacationing in Hawaii. At
3 a.m., Clinton gave final orders for the plan, and the 6 a.m.
deadline passed without any decision to halt.
</P>
<P>
   The operation began at 11:30 a.m., with missiles fired US ships
in the Red Sea and the Arabian Sea. Targets were struck at 1:30
p.m. The missile fire continued for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   At the press filing center in the Edgartown School, press
secretary Michael McCurry was briefing the gathered members of the
news media on Clinton's birthday celebration from the prior night
when his pager vibrated. He looked at the message, then told the
group: ``I need to do a very important piece of business. In about
10 minutes, the president will be here. He has an announcement he
has to make on a national security matter.''
</P>
<P>
   On the drive between the house and the school, Clinton
telephoned House Speaker Newt Gingrich to inform him of the
strikes. At the school, he ducked into an office and placed another
call to Senate majority leader Trent Lott. He also reached Senate
minority leader Tom Daschle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0587 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4830 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-POWER-COMPANIE     08-20 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-POWER-COMPANIES-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSMISSION-ONLY COMPANIES MAY FIND A MIDDLE NICHE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)   (af)  
 By MICHAEL PARRISH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One reason for the spikes in electricity prices this summer was
a series of bottlenecks in the nation's transmission system _ the
towers and high-voltage lines that carry power from generation
plants to utilities and, increasingly, between sellers and buyers
in the fledgling wholesale power market.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators now require utilities that own sections of the
transmission grid to transport power produced by any source, even
competitors. However, they can decline to do so if the extra
electricity threatens to overload their stretch of the system.
Several utilities with transmission lines feeding the Midwest used
that argument this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities' refusal to allow some power over their lines
``impeded the flow of power,'' said Edward J. Tirello, a utilities
analyst at BT Alex. Brown. ``You have to have physical
deliverability of the assets.''
</P>
<P>
   The summer's problems have intensified the debate over how to
restructure the transmission business. Utilities in California, New
York, New England and elsewhere have created independent system
operators, or I.S.O.'s, nonprofit administrators of regional chunks
of the grid. But critics within and close to the industry see ISOs
as bureaucratic halfway measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``ISOs are going to end up being a transitional mechanism,''
predicted Steven M. Fetter, managing director of the global power
group at Fitch IBCA, the credit-rating firm.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the critics propose a lucrative new kind of utility,
called a transco, that could be attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   A transco would be a pure transmission company and would hold a
monopoly in its region. It would be likely to be regulated, at
least in the beginning. It would receive financial incentives from
regulators based on how much power it carried, which would
encourage efficiency and expansion of the grid to meet rising
demand.
</P>
<P>
   Some utilities are already positioning themselves for transcos,
said Daniele M. Seitz, energy analyst at Warburg Dillon Read, as
they see money to be made in the middle. Just as pipeline companies
have been big winners under natural-gas deregulation, she noted,
``the large electric companies are definitely saying, `Hey,
transmission could be a good business.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Companies widely expected to transform themselves into transcos,
if the concept develops, include the Entergy Corp., with operations
in four states; the American Electric Power Co., which already owns
22,000 miles of high-voltage transmission lines; the Northern
States Power Co., and possibly the Firstenergy Corp. and Utilicorp
United Inc.
</P>
<P>
   James J. Hoecker, chairman of the federal energy regulatory
commission, who expects to release the commission's analysis of
June electricity shortages in about two weeks, agreed that the ISOs
and other new industry institutions ``are a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that bottlenecks were not the only problem in
the Midwest and that transcos, as monopolies, could introduce
drawbacks. ``When you have monopoly facilities,'' he said, prices
often tend to go higher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
