<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-GINGRICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHEAST REPUBLICANS WARM UP TO GINGRICH 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1996, Democratic candidates across the nation
were reading from the same play book. Attack the Contract With
America. Call every Republican a radical conservative. And whenever
possible, accuse opponents of being foot soldiers in Speaker Newt
Gingrich's rebel brigade.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was not a rousing success in much of the country.
But in the left-leaning Northeast, it was instrumental in defeating
six Republican members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   So it is one of this year's political oddities that across the
Northeast, Republicans are unrepentantly embracing Gingrich, even
as Democrats prepare to bash them for it and opinion polls show
that the speaker remains about as popular up north as Sherman is
down South.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato of New York, who castigated
Gingrich for hurting the party in 1996, traveled to Georgia for a
$1,000-a-head fund-raiser with the speaker as host at a country
club in Gingrich's hometown of Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gingrich visited the Hudson Valley town of New
Windsor to speak at a fund-raiser for Rep. Sue W. Kelly,
R-Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   And before Election Day, Gingrich, his party's most prolific
fund-raiser, is expected to venture into the region several more
times to stump for candidates in tight races, Republican officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are pleasantly puzzled that Republicans are not
fleeing from Gingrich in an election year. But moderate Republicans
offer several reasons why they stay close to their speaker. It is
not just that he is an extremely effective fund-raiser, they say,
but also because he is arguably the only top Republican leader who
listens to their concerns. And, they proudly contend, he needs
them, both to remain speaker and to build support for a possible
presidential campaign in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond such politicking, centrist Republicans like Christopher
Shays from Connecticut, Sherwood L. Boehlert from New York and
Robert D. Franks from New Jersey, all of whom decry their party's
conservative drift, call Gingrich a visionary, a mesmerizing
speaker and a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I care?'' said Ms. Kelly when asked how she felt that
Gingrich may be burned in effigy by New York Democrats again this
year. ``No. Because Newt is also a symbol of rebirth in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it is not as risky for moderates to cozy up to Gingrich
these days because he is not as politically radioactive as in 1995
and 1996, when a budget-related government shutdown and an ethics
investigation into his finances made Gingrich a useful Democratic
symbol of Republican excesses.
</P>
<P>
   But members of Congress and many political analysts say another,
more symbiotic dynamic is at work here. Moderates genuinely like
Gingrich, they say, because he alone among the House's conservative
upper echelon listens to them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people he's our link to the decision-makers,'' said
Boehlert, who has clashed famously with Gingrich and House
conservatives over environmental policies. ``He is the guy who will
listen to the moderates. He doesn't always agree, but he listens.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert, who is from Utica, said he was amazed to sell out a
fund-raiser with Gingrich during a snowstorm in 1996, when the
speaker's popularity was plumbing new depths. ``I had to return
checks,'' Boehlert said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gingrich needs the moderates to stay in power.
Centrist Republicans like Rep. Nancy L. Johnson of New Britain,
Conn., cast crucial votes in 1989 to elect Gingrich as House whip,
his stepping stone to becoming speaker. And moderates like Shays
warned Gingrich last year about a coup by conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts also say that if Gingrich is serious about
running for president in 2000, he must mend his tattered image in
the Northeast, a goal that moderate Republicans could help him
achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican and Democratic politicians said they thought
Presidential motivations were behind Gingrich's offer to do a
fund-raiser for D'Amato, who already has $12 million in campaign
money in the bank. D'Amato is the paramount leader of New York's
Republican Party, and his support, or at least lack of opposition,
could be essential to Gingrich's presidential aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a large electoral-vote state,'' said Johnny
Isacson, an Atlanta real estate broker who ran for governor as a
Republican in 1990. ``Senator D'Amato is an influential senator. It
doesn't hurt to have done a fund-raiser for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's 50-minute speech at Ms. Kelly's fund-raiser last
month had the feel of an old-fashioned stem-winder. The speaker
took a few well-aimed shots at liberal Democrats and then went into
a recitation of bipartisan themes: trimming government waste,
saving Social Security, cutting taxes, fighting drug abuse and
improving schools.
</P>
<P>
   There were lots of broad ideas, few nagging details and almost
none of the harsh oratory that peppered his speeches in 1995. More
than a few of the self-described Republican moderates in the crowd
left impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came expecting to see a man with horns,'' said Fred
Paschkes, 73, an insurance broker from Pound Ridge, N.Y. ``I will
look at him more closely from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to both Gingrich and D'Amato denied that presidential
positioning was behind the Georgia fund-raiser. Other Republicans
suggested that D'Amato, making a small concession to Gingrich's
unpopularity in New York by traveling to Georgia, accepted the
speaker's assistance because he never thinks he has enough money
for a campaign and because Atlanta is home to regional banks and
credit unions that are regulated by the Senate Banking Committee.
D'Amato is chairman of that committee.
</P>
<P>
   Though Democrats are not gearing up to attack Gingrich as
lavishly as in 1996, many candidates are gleeful that their
Republican opponents remain close to the speaker, noting that
Gingrich's approval rating remains below 35 percent in many
Northeastern states.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still have Democrats whose only applause line in this
state is conjuring up Newt Gingrich,'' said John Zogby, a pollster
from Utica. ``It still works.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment that news of the Georgia fund-raiser became public,
all three of D'Amato's major Democratic opponents, former Rep.
Geraldine Ferraro, Rep. Charles Schumer and Mark Green, the New
York City public advocate, released statements attacking D'Amato as
a Gingrich Republican.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
