<HEADLINE>
CLINTON JUGGLED PERSONAL, POLICY AFFAIRS OVER WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton informed his wife of his
extramarital affair with Monica S. Lewinsky and prepared his
unprecedented testimony before a federal grand jury last weekend,
he also gathered his senior national security advisers and plotted
his strategy to do battle with terrorist forces abroad, aides said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This combination marks a breathtaking juxtaposition of policy
and personal life. Since Monday, when the nation became transfixed
in the aftermath of his televised confession, Clinton and a few
elite aides harbored a secret: they planned to lob more than 100
cruise missiles at suspected terrorist sites in Sudan and
Afghanistan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive meeting to strike came in the White House last
Friday, officials said, after Clinton's national security adviser
Samuel R.Berger and CIA Director George Tenet concluded that Saudi
millionaire Osama bin Laden was responsible for the deadly bombings
of two US embassies in Africa on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, Tenet, Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen and Joint
Chiefs of Staff Chairman Hugh Shelton gathered with Clinton in the
White House to lay out their proposal for a missile attack that
would involve no troops and put no Americans at risk. The targets
were a suspected chemical weapons plant in Sudan that US officials
believe was financed by bin Laden, and his sprawling terrorist
training center in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   At the Friday meeting, Clinton approved the proposal with one
caveat: He wanted the ability to halt the operation until 6 a.m. on
the morning of the attack, when he would be secluded in a
beachhouse outside of Edgartown on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was perhaps most notable for its secrecy.
Virtually no White House political or domestic aides were apprised
of the plans, except for Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles. Members of
the congressional intelligence committees were intentionally kept
out of the loop. Only Clinton's most senior national security
aides, as well as the four highest-ranking congressional leaders,
were kept informed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Martha's Vineyard, Clinton worked the telephones overnight
Thursday, talking repeatedly with Berger in Washington and placing
a call to Vice President Al Gore, who was vacationing in Hawaii. At
3 a.m., Clinton gave final orders for the plan, and the 6 a.m.
deadline passed without any decision to halt.
</P>
<P>
   The operation began at 11:30 a.m., with missiles fired US ships
in the Red Sea and the Arabian Sea. Targets were struck at 1:30
p.m. The missile fire continued for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   At the press filing center in the Edgartown School, press
secretary Michael McCurry was briefing the gathered members of the
news media on Clinton's birthday celebration from the prior night
when his pager vibrated. He looked at the message, then told the
group: ``I need to do a very important piece of business. In about
10 minutes, the president will be here. He has an announcement he
has to make on a national security matter.''
</P>
<P>
   On the drive between the house and the school, Clinton
telephoned House Speaker Newt Gingrich to inform him of the
strikes. At the school, he ducked into an office and placed another
call to Senate majority leader Trent Lott. He also reached Senate
minority leader Tom Daschle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
