<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ROYALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOUREK DEBUT LEAVES RED SOX BEHIND ROYALS, 8-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There was a time when Pete Schourek was
mentioned in the same breath as Greg Maddux and nobody blinked an
eye.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, after he was pinned with an 8-2 loss to the Kansas
City Royals Thursday afternoon in his first start for the Red Sox,
Schourek's name remains linked to the company of Kid Korea, the
Dominican Mystery Man, and other pitchers who have faltered in
their auditions at the tail end of the Boston rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't exactly the start I envisioned,'' said Schourek,
who took the mound with a 2-0 lead fashioned by Mike Stanley's
third home run in two days but was unable to hold it for more than
two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek gave up a three-run homer to Terry Pendleton, who
hadn't gone deep in more than three months (April 30) and probably
will retire at the end of the season. The lefthander was then
touched for two more runs on three singles and a sacrifice fly in
the fourth, his final inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can pitch better than that,'' Schourek said, ``and,
obviously, longer than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, winners of three in a row and looking for thier
ninth victory this season against the Royals, which would have
matched their high against Kansas City since 1969, instead
succumbed to Royals righthander Hipolito Pichardo and three
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, who own the worst home record in the American League
and were in the midst of being auctioned off even as they prepared
for Thursday's game, ended a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's homer, which came with two outs and Mo Vaughn aboard,
was followed by singles by Troy O'Leary and Darren Bragg. The Red
Sox appeared intent on putting the Royals away early, just as they
had done the night before in their 11-1 win at Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But with Nomar Garciaparra on the bench getting a rare day off,
the Red Sox managed just two more singles and a total of three more
runners the rest of this searing afternoon. Pichardo lasted only
through the fifth because of a bad elbow, but he set down the last
11 batters he faced, a succession of outs that grew to 15 until
Bragg's one-out single off Scott Service in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   No Boston runner advanced as far as third after Stanley's 27th
homer, a career high for the recycled Sox veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pichardo pitched good against us,'' said Red Sox mnanager Jimy
Williams, whose team began the day seven games ahead of the Orioles
in the American League wild-card race. ``It was hot out there. They
got going and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek had no illusions about what was at stake in his first
start in three weeks, his duties with the Red Sox having been
limited to two relief appearances since he came from Houston. ``I'm
disappointed with it,'' said the lefthander, who just three years
ago was runner-up to Maddux for the National League Cy Young Award.
``Obviously, we're in the wild-card race, we need wins. Since I've
been here, I've been in three games and I've got two losses. That's
not exactly the impression I wanted to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek set down the next eight Royals in order after
Pendleton, the 35-year-old third baseman who last season played
with Schourek in Cincinnati and before that had hit him at a .429
clip, turned on a first-pitch fastball and hit it over the
left-field fence to make it 3-2. Schourek struck out three in that
span, including the Royals' Nos. 3 and 4 hitters, Jose Offerman and
Dean Palmer, in succession.
</P>
<P>
   But after Palmer went down swinging, Pendleton blooped a single
over the head of rookie second basemen Donnie Sadler, Jeff Conine
grounded a single off Sadler's glove, and Jermaine Dye followed
with another ground-ball hit through the right side that made it
4-2. A fifth run scored on Sal Fasano's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals strung together four straight singles in the fifth
off reliever Derek Lowe, including a bunt on which Lowe and Stanley
crossed signals, and broke it open with three more runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hadn't started in three weeks, he was out of whack from his
routine, so we knew the probability existed that he would have a
rough first start,'' pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said in his
critique of Schourek. ``But once he gets into our program and our
routine, I think he'll be fine. I think he'll help us a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan, who has watched would-be starters Jin Ho Cho and
Robinson Checo, among others, fail in situations similar to
Schourek's, blamed himself for Pendleton's homer. He failed to
inform rookie catcher Jason Varitek that Pendleton likes to swing
at the first pitch with runners in scoring postion. The worst thing
Schourek could do was throw him a fastball inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``That home run was the killer for us,'' said Kerrigan. ``We had
momentum going on our side from the night before, we jump ahead
today, and Pendleton hits the home run. My fault.''
</P>
<P>
   While Varitek may be a rookie, Schourek is hardly a babe in the
woods. He admitted he knew of Pendleton's tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I hadn't faced him in a while,'' he said. ``I left it over
the plate a little too much. Especially beating them the way we did
last night, to give them three runs back like I did knocked the
wind out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's on to the dome in Minnesota, under the big top, where
there is no wind and no heat. Except the kind being generated from
Baltimore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
