u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-RECAP-NYT &LR;      08-20 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-RECAP-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; U.S. ATTACKS TERRORIST BASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times has moved the following stories about U.S.
missile attacks on suspected terrorist sites in Afghanistan and
Sudan. This recap expands upon the previously-filed
ATTACK-ADVISORY, with more-detailed story summaries and art
information.
</P>
<P>
   Lede story: ATTACK-U.S. (Washington) _ Dozens of U.S. cruise
missiles struck targets in Afghanistan and Sudan on Thursday in
what President Clinton described as an act of self-defense against
imminent terrorist plots and of fearsome retribution for the
bombings of U.S. embassies in East Africa two weeks ago. By James
Bennet. WITH PHOTOS and GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-BINLADEN (Washington) _ How Osama bin Laden, the youngest
son of a construction magnate from Yemen, became the world's most
feared sponsor of terrorism. The religious and ideological roots of
his rage lie in the 1980s, when he worked side by side with the CIA
backing the Afghan rebels. When that battle was over, he and his
fellow holy warriors went to work on the U.S. By Tim Weiner. WITH
MAP.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-CONGRESS (Washington) _ A cherished axiom of U.S.
diplomacy is that the opposition party supports the president when
missiles are flying. Thursday it worked, more or less. Most
congressional leaders, from Speaker Newt Gingrich to such reliable
Clinton critics as Sen. Jesse Helms, rallied around the
commander-in-chief. But in the surreal and cinematic atmosphere
that suffused Washington this week, a handful of voices on Capitol
Hill cried foul. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ASSESS (Undated) _ In the war against terrorism,
experience suggests that any operation, whether an assassination or
the sort of strike launched by the United States, has the quality
of damned-if-you-do-and-damned-if-you-don't. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SECURITY (Washington) _ The U.S. on Thursday issued a new
worldwide warning to Americans and diplomatic personnel ``to
exercise much greater caution than usual'' following U.S. military
strikes against suspected terrorist targets in Afghanistan and
Sudan. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MILITARY (Washington) _ The U.S. attacked targets in
Afghanistan and the Sudan with roughly 70 cruise missiles fired
from Navy ships in the Arabian and Red Seas timed to strike their
targets simultaneously, senior administration and military
officials said.The missiles struck at precisely 1:30 p.m. ET, after
dark settled over their targets, themselves more than 2,500 miles
apart, the officials said. By Steven Lee Myers. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ Arrests in Albania show links to the
African embassy bombings: In a series of lightning raids with the
Albanian secret police this summer, U.S. intelligence agents appear
to have thwarted a bomb plot against the U.S. Embassy here. They
also seem to have broken up a ring of Egyptian Islamic terrorists
using this nation's anarchy to set up a base. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ President Clinton ordered strikes
on terrorist-linked facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan after
obtaining credible evidence that leading members of the
international terrorist network sponsored by Saudi exile Osama bin
Laden, who U.S. officials believe was behind the bombings of two
U.S. embassies in Africa, would be gathering Thursday at a
terrorist camp in Afghanistan to plan further attacks against the
U.S. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-SUDAN (Nairobi) _ U.S.-Sudanese tensions finally erupt
into open warfare. The air strike against a drug factory in Sudan
on Thursday marked the first act of open warfare in a
long-simmering cold war between the U.S. and the Islamic regime in
Khartoum. By James C. McKinley. WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MEDIA (Undated) _ After a week of what felt like nonstop
talk about sex, ties and audiotape involving President Clinton and
Monica Lewinsky, television screens were overtaken Thursday by news
of a different shock value. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT (Jerusalem) _ Israel was quick to
congratulate the U.S. night for its missile attacks on suspected
terrorist bases, but the early reaction from many other governments
in the Middle East was a notable silence. British Prime Minister
Tony Blair was alone among European leaders in expressing strong
support. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-WAG (New York) _ Is life imitating art? `Wag the Dog'
springs to many minds. Beginning with a reporter's question early
Thursday afternoon to Defense Secretary Cohen about the film ``Wag
the Dog,'' we cast a wide net in search of reaction. By Frank
Bruni. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-GAS (Undted) _ VX, the chemical nerve agent that the U.S.
alleges Sudan was preparing to make, is one of the deadliest nerve
agents known, especially when applied to the skin. A 10 mg drop on
the skin can kill an adult in 15 minutes. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-YORK (New York) _ Once they received word that the U.S.
had bombed targets in Afghanistan and the Sudan, New York City
officials immediately tightened security in a routine that Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani acknowledged has become all too familiar in recent
years. By Dan Barry.
</P>
