<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-FOCUS-BOS &LR;      08-20 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FOCUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US STRIKE: REQUIRED MOVE OR MEDIA PLOY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As news of US military attacks on terrorist sites
abroad spread Thursday, so did questions about whether the White
House may have timed the operation to change the subject dominating
the news: President Clinton's affair with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Dan Coats, an Indiana Republican, called the timing of
the military missions ``suspect.'' Senator Arlen Specter, a
Pennsylvania Republican, said it was fair to ask ``whether there
was any diversionary motive involved'' in the US attack.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials denied it. But certainly the
juxtaposition of a humiliated president retreating to a secluded
vacation spot on Martha's Vineyard Tuesday with the return Thursday
of a take-charge commmander in chief did not disappoint Clinton
image-minders.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did they lament that for a day, at least, the newspapers and
newscasts would feature foreign affairs rather than domestic ones.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton stepped into the media center on Martha's
Vineyard to make his surprise announcement of the military attacks
at the same time that Lewinsky, a former White House intern, was
testifying to a grand jury in Washington for a second time about
her sexual relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the president or the White House has been
particularly following her business today,'' White House spokesman
Michael McCurry told reporters on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a reporter asked Defense Secretary William Cohen
if the timing of the military attack was influenced at all by the
president's problems at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only motivation driving this action today was our aboslute
obligation to protect the American people from terrorist
activities,'' Cohen answered. ``That was the sole motivation. No
other consideration has been involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most lawmakers from both parties, House Speaker Newt
Gingrich supported the president, saying it was ``sick'' to suggest
there was any motive other than national security that drove the
president's decision. ``It was the right thing to do at the right
time,'' the GOP leader said.
</P>
<P>
   By last evening, Spector said he had talked to administration
officials and was convinced that the attack was justified.
</P>
<P>
   But Coats, a member of both the Senate Intelligence and Armed
Services committees, wondered why the operation hadn't come last
week or next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is extrordinary, coming when the president is in
political extremis. People are raising legitmate questions about
the attacks, here and around the globe,'' Coats said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin Meehan, a Massachusetets Democrat, said
the senators' statements were ``unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one thing for a radio talk-show host to bring up such
things, but for a US senator to do it is outrageous,'' Meehan said.
``The bombing of our embassy was very real. That 260 people were
murdered in Kenya and Tanzania was real. The movie was fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``movie'' most talked about Thursday was ``Wag the Dog,'' a
recent film in which Robert De Niro and Dustin Hoffman, portraying
two operatives in the White House, concoct a phony military
operation to divert attention and restore the popularity of a
president whose future is imperiled by a sexual encounter with a
Girl Scout.
</P>
<P>
   To some, a ``Wag the Dog'' scenario seemed just too cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with a spin machine like the one in this White House, I
would be very wary of jumping to any conclusions like that,'' said
Howard Kurtz, the Washington Post media critic and author of ``Spin
Cycle: Inside the White House Propaganda Machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my opinion that it is not within the realm of possibility
that the president would engage in a Hollywoodized version of
reality, or send young men and women into battle, in order to cover
his embarrassment,'' said Marvin Kalb, director of the Shorenstein
Center on the Press, Politics, and Public Policy at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the fact that people would even raise the issue of `Wag
the Dog' is a sad testimony to the cynicism which exists in the
American population, particularly after the president has been
lying to the people for seven months,'' Kalb said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam War gave Americans good reason to challenge the
Pentagon on its judgment and veracity, and ever since Watergate
Americans have been skeptical about whether their president was
telling the whole truth at all times.
</P>
<P>
   But fresh from a public admission that for months he lied to his
family, friends, and the country about an ``inappropriate
relationship'' with Lewinsky, the president was sure to face
credibility problems as he led the nation into an unexpected and
uncertain military operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything the president does from now on will be subject to
this kind of skepticism, and all you can say is that he has brought
it on himself,'' said Stephen Hess, a presidential scholar at the
Brookings Institution, a private group.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gaffney, director of the Center for Security Policy, a
private group, said, ``Given what is at stake here, which is
nothing less than the security of the United States, I hope that
the president is acting in a sober way, that his intelligence was
good, and that it was done for a cause, not `Wag the Dog' effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, critics of the US action from the Sudan to Iran said
Clinton was trying to divert attention from the Lewinsky story. A
state-controlled Iranian radio broadcast monitored by the British
Broadcasting Company suggested that the military move was ``aimed
at covering up and overshadowing his problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative commentator Arianna Huffington said she would not
be surprised if Harry Thomason, the Hollywood producer who has
helped the Clintons with scandal damage control and appeared before
the grand jury himself last week, had a hand in the orchestration
of the operation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to pass judgment on its military necessity, but
I do say with absolute certainty that we can't have a person people
can't trust making life-and-death decisions and sending our
children to war,'' Huffington said. ``He needs to resign and leave
these decisions to someone we can trust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
