<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-YORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON ALERT, NEW YORK CITY TIGHTENS SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S. with photos, map and graphic,
ATTACK-BINLADEN with map, ATTACK-CONGRESS, ATTACK-SECURITY,
ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-MILITARY, ATTACK-ASSESS,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-SUDAN with map, ATTACK-MEDIA,
ATTACK-WAG, ATTACK-TRAVEL-ADVISORY.) 
(smw) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once they received word Thursday that the United
States had bombed targets in Afghanistan and the Sudan, New York
City officials immediately tightened security in a routine that
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani acknowledged has become all too familiar in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is the normal thing that we would do when
there is an international incident, which unfortunately we face
more often now than maybe we did in the past,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and Police Commissioner Howard Safir declined to be
specific, other than to say that security had been increased at
what Safir called ``specific targets'' like public buildings,
religious institutions, embassies and consuls. As the two officials
spoke inside City Hall, police officers outside were shutting off
public access to City Hall's parking lot. ``It's because of the
bombings,'' an officer said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the mayor said the city had ``no intelligence that
suggests there would be any target here,'' city officials say that
New York is generally considered to be a primary target for
terrorists. The city endured one of the worst acts of terrorism on
American soil, the bombing of the World Trade Center in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the city had to respond to false reports of
an impending anthrax attack. It was later reported that the city
had quietly begun an effort to counter any chemical or germ
attacks. That effort included the creation of a $15 million crisis
center in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Similar precautions apparently were being taken by the Federal
Aviation Administration and the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey at airports in the area. ``We would suggest that passengers
heading for the airports tonight and tomorrow leave extra time,'' a
spokesman for the port authority said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Safir said they had called a news conference to
express their support for the Clinton administration's actions, as
well as to ease any local concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
