<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-SECRET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON JUGGLED PERSONAL, POLICY AFFAIRS OVER WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton informed his wife of his
extramarital affair with Monica S. Lewinsky and prepared his
unprecedented testimony before a federal grand jury last weekend,
he also gathered his senior national security advisers and plotted
his strategy to do battle with terrorist forces abroad, aides said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This combination marks a breathtaking juxtaposition of policy
and personal life. Since Monday, when the nation became transfixed
in the aftermath of his televised confession, Clinton and a few
elite aides harbored a secret: they planned to lob more than 100
cruise missiles at suspected terrorist sites in Sudan and
Afghanistan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decisive meeting to strike came in the White House last
Friday, officials said, after Clinton's national security adviser
Samuel R.Berger and CIA Director George Tenet concluded that Saudi
millionaire Osama bin Laden was responsible for the deadly bombings
of two US embassies in Africa on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, Tenet, Secretary of Defense William S. Cohen and Joint
Chiefs of Staff Chairman Hugh Shelton gathered with Clinton in the
White House to lay out their proposal for a missile attack that
would involve no troops and put no Americans at risk. The targets
were a suspected chemical weapons plant in Sudan that US officials
believe was financed by bin Laden, and his sprawling terrorist
training center in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   At the Friday meeting, Clinton approved the proposal with one
caveat: He wanted the ability to halt the operation until 6 a.m. on
the morning of the attack, when he would be secluded in a
beachhouse outside of Edgartown on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   The operation was perhaps most notable for its secrecy.
Virtually no White House political or domestic aides were apprised
of the plans, except for Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles. Members of
the congressional intelligence committees were intentionally kept
out of the loop. Only Clinton's most senior national security
aides, as well as the four highest-ranking congressional leaders,
were kept informed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On Martha's Vineyard, Clinton worked the telephones overnight
Thursday, talking repeatedly with Berger in Washington and placing
a call to Vice President Al Gore, who was vacationing in Hawaii. At
3 a.m., Clinton gave final orders for the plan, and the 6 a.m.
deadline passed without any decision to halt.
</P>
<P>
   The operation began at 11:30 a.m., with missiles fired US ships
in the Red Sea and the Arabian Sea. Targets were struck at 1:30
p.m. The missile fire continued for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   At the press filing center in the Edgartown School, press
secretary Michael McCurry was briefing the gathered members of the
news media on Clinton's birthday celebration from the prior night
when his pager vibrated. He looked at the message, then told the
group: ``I need to do a very important piece of business. In about
10 minutes, the president will be here. He has an announcement he
has to make on a national security matter.''
</P>
<P>
   On the drive between the house and the school, Clinton
telephoned House Speaker Newt Gingrich to inform him of the
strikes. At the school, he ducked into an office and placed another
call to Senate majority leader Trent Lott. He also reached Senate
minority leader Tom Daschle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0597 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-TRAFFIC-BREAKDOWN     08-20 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-TRAFFIC-BREAKDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER GLITCH LEAVES FLIGHTS OVER N.E. UNTRACKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For 37 agonizing minutes, air-traffic controllers
covering flights over New England and upstate New York Wednesday
night scrambled to keep planes safely separated after their
computer system failed, forcing them to exchange information with
each other on hand-written notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was chaos,'' said William Johannes, local president of the
National Air Traffic Controllers Association. ``Controllers were
having to ask airplanes where they were at, saying `Say your
position,' and one aircraft replied `Position to what?'''
</P>
<P>
   The outages at the Boston Center, located in Nashua, N.H.,
occurred at 6:50 p.m., one of the busiest times of the day. Some 75
controllers were following about 300 planes when all information
identifying the flights, including their altitude, air speed,
route, and destination, was lost.
</P>
<P>
   All that remained on the screen were the blips that inform
controllers that there is a plane in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea where some of the planes were,'' said Johannes.
</P>
<P>
   A backup computer system was used and, while it normally is able
to retain much of the information about each flight, it could not
do so in this instance because of the type of computer failure
involved. Jim Peters, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, said, however, that the backup system ``worked
within its parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's breakdown, one of many equipment problems to plague
the nation's air-traffic control system in general and the Boston
Center in particular, highlighted the need for upgrades of the
antiquated system, controllers say.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest incident, the mainframe computer failed, and the
backup could not reload all of the information and instead went
into a so-called ``dumb'' mode, according to FAA officials.
Controllers had to manually re-enter information into the system
and write information about each flight on strips of paper and pass
the notes along as they handed planes off from one controller to
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety was not compromised,'' said Peters. ``Anytime we have a
failure we are concerned. But there were, as in other times,
redundancies that are built into the system and they worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Radar problems and computer outages are frequent problems for
controllers. The radar screens at the Boston Center _ which
controls more than 160,000 square miles of air space from the
Atlantic Ocean to western New York, and from the Canadian border to
south of Long Island _ have been failing with distressing
frequency, according to controllers.
</P>
<P>
   The Computer Display Channel, installed in 1972, which takes
information from IBM mainframe computers known as the HOST, has
been causing much of the trouble in the Boston Center. The channel
has been breaking down frequently, and at one point this spring,
the Globe reported, outages were occurring on almost a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that problem, the Boston Center was given a higher
priority by the FAA for a new computer display system. Preparation
work is expected to begin within two weeks, and the new system is
expected to be operating in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the mainframe computer, or HOST, that failed
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   For controllers, it meant their radar screens went from having
detailed data blocks containing the airline and flight number, the
type of aircraft, the altitude, airspeed, flight path and
destination, to having blips with no identifying information.
</P>
<P>
   By punching a few buttons, controllers are able to use the
backup system if it is available. But when the backup system, known
as DARC, kicked in, it showed no information.
</P>
<P>
   Using notes, talking with controllers in New York, and asking
pilots to ``squawk and ident,'' controllers were able to
reconstruct the data that had been lost.
</P>
<P>
   When a controller asked, for example, American Airlines Flight
123 to ``squawk and ident,'' the pilot was able to manipulate a
radio transponder in the airplane that changes the radar blip on
the controller's screen from a slash to three horizontal lines.
With that identification, the controller could then type in next to
that radar blip ``AA123.''
</P>
<P>
   Delays occurred along the coast as Boston Center controllers
informed their counterparts in other centers that planes should not
enter the New England airspace. Flights waiting to take off from
Logan were delayed as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
