<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- ATTACK-WAG, 8-20 --
Pedestrians watch the large zipper in Times Square broadcast the
news Thursday that the United States had bombed terrorist targets
in Afghanistan and Sudan. Thursday's events make it easy to make
comparisons with the movie ``Wag the Dog,'' in which the
president's handlers invent a war merely to distract public
attention from his sexual transgressions. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- BBO-UMPIRES-BASEBALLS, 8-20
-- Major League Baseball is investigating the possible role of
American League umpires in the sale of baseballs used in the
perfect game that David Wells of the Yankees pitched against the
Minnesota Twins on May17. Baseball officials confirmed the
investigation Thursday but declined to identify the umpires.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- FUNDRAISING-GORE, 8-20 --
Attorney General Janet Reno telling reporters Thursday that she
will brief the Judiciary Committee this week on the campaign
finance inquiry. Reno has until the end of the month to decide
whether to advance from a 30-day initial review of Vice President
Al Gore's fund-raising telephone calls to a more intensive 90-day
inquiry that will determine whether she refers the case to an
independent prosecutor. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- BBN-METS-CARDS, 8-20 --
Mark McGwire - the man the fans came to see - signing autographs
before Thursday's doubleheader at Shea. McGwire became the first
player in history to hit 50 home runs in three consecutive seasons
Thursday night with a towering shot in the seventh inning of the
St. Louis Cardinals' 2-0 win over the New York Mets in the first
game. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
