   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- ATTACK-WAG, 8-20 --
Pedestrians watch the large zipper in Times Square broadcast the
news Thursday that the United States had bombed terrorist targets
in Afghanistan and Sudan. Thursday's events make it easy to make
comparisons with the movie ``Wag the Dog,'' in which the
president's handlers invent a war merely to distract public
attention from his sexual transgressions. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- BBO-UMPIRES-BASEBALLS, 8-20
-- Major League Baseball is investigating the possible role of
American League umpires in the sale of baseballs used in the
perfect game that David Wells of the Yankees pitched against the
Minnesota Twins on May17. Baseball officials confirmed the
investigation Thursday but declined to identify the umpires.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- FUNDRAISING-GORE, 8-20 --
Attorney General Janet Reno telling reporters Thursday that she
will brief the Judiciary Committee this week on the campaign
finance inquiry. Reno has until the end of the month to decide
whether to advance from a 30-day initial review of Vice President
Al Gore's fund-raising telephone calls to a more intensive 90-day
inquiry that will determine whether she refers the case to an
independent prosecutor. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- BBN-METS-CARDS, 8-20 --
Mark McGwire - the man the fans came to see - signing autographs
before Thursday's doubleheader at Shea. McGwire became the first
player in history to hit 50 home runs in three consecutive seasons
Thursday night with a towering shot in the seventh inning of the
St. Louis Cardinals' 2-0 win over the New York Mets in the first
game. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- MILLION-YOUTH-MARCH, 8-20
-- Malik Zulu Shabazz, a coordinator of the Million Youth March,
speaking at the Federal courthouse in Manhattan on Thursday with
Roger Wareham, left, a lawyer, and Talib Abdul Muhammad, an
organizer. The organizers sued the city, saying that Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's refusal to grant them a permit to hold the event in
Harlem next month was unconstitutional. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) DENVER -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- DENVER-BY-THE-SEA-2, 8-20 --
Residents of the Denver area, landlocked and 1,000 miles from the
nearest ocean, have acquired a love of water sports. At Water World
near Denver, some of the 4,000 daily visitors play in a pool.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) DENVER -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- DENVER-BY-THE-SEA-1, 8-20 --
Yes, it is the gateway to some of the nation's most dramatic
mountains, but where is the beach? This year, the Mile High City is
fighting back against geographic determinism. At Water World near
Denver, a surfer rides waves in a pool that creates them. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- LIVENT-ACCOUNTING-2, 8-20
-- Garth Drabinsky, chairman of Livent Inc. Behind the curtain, the
company's flamboyant impresario did not just produce
Tony-award-winning Broadway musicals. One of Drabinsky's props was
the company's financial books, parts of which now appear to have
been made up and which are now being investigated by securities
regulators. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- LIVENT-ACCOUNTING-1, 8-20
-- ``Ragtime'' at the Ford Center for the Performing Arts in
Manhattan - one of the Tony-award-winning Broadway musicals
produced by Livent Inc. The public company produced many shows at
once and disclosed few details on which ones - if any - were making
money. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ACTON, Mass. -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- HOLOCAUST-SURVIVOR-BOS,
8-20 -- Tatiana Benharbone follows her dog, Ms. Kitty, into her
cab. Ms. Benharbone is one of the few Holocaust survivors still
actively working in the Boston area, a reminder of an era fast
fading from public memory. ``There's this terrible hole inside
you,'' she says. ``Acton isn't home. I don't think anyplace is
home.'' (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) CARVER, Mass. -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- HOME-PROJECT-BOS, 8-20
-- Ralph Weaver's stone house in Carver. ``A mason told me about
the old stone houses in New England that are much admired today,''
says Weaver, a retired policeman who will turn 50 next November.
``They were built by farmers who knew nothing when they started.
So, why not me?'' (John Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- INDIA-PHOTO-REVIEW-2, 8-20
-- Sunil Janah, whose photographs chronicle India's history. Now
more than 300 of his photographs, many never exhibited or published
anywhere before, are on view in ``Sunil Janah: Photographing India
1942-1978,'' at the Gallery at 678 in the East Village. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- INDIA-PHOTO-REVIEW-1, 8-20
-- A partial view of ``Sunil Janah: Photographing India
1942-1978,'' at the Gallery at 678 in the East Village. His work
during World War II, the struggle for independence and the postwar
years in India is little known in the United States but highly
regarded in his native land, where a limited number of images have
been shown repeatedly. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- NY-OUTDOOR-SCULPTURE-2,
8-20 -- An oversize, inflatable teddy bear in ``Percutaneous
Delights'' at PS 1. The run in outdoor sculpture this year is from
celebrated talents like Auguste Rodin and Tony Smith to a single
quirky placement by the English sculptor Rachel Whiteread in SoHo;
from a playful show in the courtyard of PS 1 in Queens to a more
conventional convocation at Long Island University's Brooklyn
campus. (J. Emilio Flores/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- NY-OUTDOOR-SCULPTURE-1,
8-20 -- Christine Koch's ``Cosmic Bosom'' at Socrates Sculpture
Park in Long Island City. No one can say that New York is outdoor
sculpture-challenged. If you travel around the city in summer, in
addition to the time-honored monuments that appear at every turn,
you will find many a new work or works ensconced on temporarily
sites. (J. Emilio Flores/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BOSTON -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
ACKLEY-ART, 8-20 -- Clifford Ackley, the curator of prints,
drawings and photographs at the Museum of Fine Arts, stands amid
his exhibition ``PhotoImage: Printmaking 60's to 90's.'' For
``PhotoImage,'' at the museum through Sept. 27, Ackley has turned
his galleries into a montage of images that all make use of
photographs. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- TWELFTHNIGHT-TESORI-2, 8-20
-- Jeanine Tesori drew on eclectic instruments, played by six
musicians, for her incidental music and songs accompanying
Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night'' at the Vivian Beaumont. ``I
surround myself with people who believe in the theater the way it
was: that is, if you tell a great story, audiences will come, and
if you make music that comes out of your heart, people will
listen,'' she says. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- TWELFTHNIGHT-TESORI-1, 8-20
-- A scene from Shakepeare's ``Twelfth Night'' at the Vivian
Beaumont, a play whose fantasy elements nudged the composer toward
elemental but mystical music. Paul Rudd, fourth from left, is duke
Orsino. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- NY-KAYAK, 8-20 -- Manhattan
aglow, seen from a kayak, can be an exhilarating experience. The
trip around the island offers physical challenges as well as
peaceful moments to enjoy the sights and sounds. (Philip
Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HERSHEY, Pa. -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- CHOCOLATE-VACATION-2,
8-20 -- Attractions in Hershey include Hersheypark, with rides and
water slides, restaurants with you-know-what themes and candy
characters for children to meet and pose with. What is known as
``the sweetest parade on earth'' consists of 14 of these
characters, each a trademarked Hershey's product, marching
triumphantly through the park shortly before dark. (Sal DiMarco/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) HERSHEY, Pa. -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- CHOCOLATE-VACATION-1,
8-20 -- Spinning along in Hersheypark, the amusement park in
Pennsylvania. The experience is wholly commercial, with every
feature linked to promoting the Hershey image, or occasionally
other corporate sponsors who have rented space. (Sal DiMarco/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NASHVILLE, Tenn. -- Aug. 20, 1998 --
LEAGUEOFTHESOUTH-2-COX, 8-20 -- Michael Hill, 46, the president of
the League of the South, in front of a statue of Nathan Bedford
Forrest, a slave trader and grand wizard of the Ku Klux Klan.
``There can be no peace until we are a separate and free people
again,'' Hill said recently. ``The day of apologizing for the
conduct of our Confederate ancestors is over.'' (Jim
Auchmutey/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BIRMINGHAM, Ala. -- Aug. 20, 1998 --
LEAGUEOFTHESOUTH-1-COX, 8-20 -- At the League of the South's annual
conference in Birmingham, items promoting the league's cause were
available for purchace. The Alabama-based organization that claims
almost 7,000 members and wants the former Confederate states to
finish what they started in 1861 by revisiting the option of
secession. (Cathy Seith/Atlanta Journal-Consitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
PLYMPTON ANIMATOR, 8-20 -- Bill Plympton as seen through the mouth
of one of his film props. A retrospective of Plympton's career that
includes screenings of ``Sex and Violence'' and ``The Exciting Life
of a Tree,'' two of his more recent shorter works, as well as the
New York premiere of his second full-length animated feature, ``I
Married a Strange Person,'' is being presented at the American
Museum of the Moving Image in New York. (Chester Higgins Jr./New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
STUPID-KIDS-THEATER-1, 8-20 -- James Carpinello, top, and Keith
Nobbs in ``Stupid Kids.'' The play, which originally opened
off-Broadway in June to a shaky start at the WPA Theater, where it
received several mixed reviews, reopens Tuesday at the Century
Theater.(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23 --
STUPID-KIDS-THEATER-1, 8-20 -- Keith Nobbs, the 19-year-old actor
in ``Stupid Kids,'' waits for a booth at a Manhattan diner. Written
by John Russell, who died of AIDS in 1994 at the age of 31,
``Stupid Kids'' begins a commercial run Tuesday at the Century
Theater on East 15th Street with a gilt-edged pack of producers
behind it. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LENOX, Mass. -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23
-- TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL-2, 8-20 -- Visitors bask in shade and
solitude on the lawn in front of the Koussevitzky Music Shed at
Tanglewood. This summer's festival at Tanglewood, which is nestled
in the Berkshire Hills, was once again memorable. (Alan E.
Solomon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LENOX, Mass. -- Aug. 20, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 23
-- TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL-1, 8-20 -- Seiji Ozawa, the longtime music
director of the Boston Symphony, at the Serge Koussevitzky Music
Shed at Tanglewood. Veterans of past summers at Tanglewood attest
that with Ozawa, who studied at the center in 1960, more closely
involved in its activities than ever before, this has been one of
the most rewarding festival seasons in recent memory. (Alan E.
Solomon/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
