<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4875 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-W     08-20 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: grand jury.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton said he did not believe the gold and royal blue tie had
been a gift from her. He was then informed she had testified she
gave it to him, and the prosecutors asked if he had worn it that
day as some kind of a ``signal'' to her, perhaps to influence her
testimony. Clinton said again he could not remember if the tie came
from her. But he insisted that he had no intention of sending Ms.
Lewinsky any kind of message that day.
</P>
<P>
   The former White House intern, stone-faced and businesslike,
said nothing to reporters this morning as she climbed out of a
Toyota Land Cruiser and walked briskly into a side entrance of the
federal courthouse in Washington, ignoring a reporter's question
about whether Clinton should apologize to her. Friends have said
Ms. Lewinsky was deeply hurt by Clinton's address to the nation
Monday, especially since he did not apologize to her in it and
because she thought he was dismissive of their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Lewinsky's appearance drew a crowd of tourists and
gawkers, it was not as intensively covered by the news media as
when she first testified before the grand jury two weeks ago. But
her testimony was crucial as prosecutors search for discrepancies
between her account and the president's.
</P>
<P>
   She emerged from the courthouse just before 2 p.m., wearing dark
sunglasses, leaving her spokeswoman, Judy Smith, to meet with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She answered all questions truthfully and completely,'' Ms.
Smith said. ``It is our expectation that today's appearance
concludes her grand jury testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, Ms. Smith added, ``is now looking forward to
beginning the process of rebuilding her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, 25, had agreed to answer questions in exchange for
immunity from prosecution. In a deal worked out with prosecutors,
she is vulnerable to prosecution only if she lies in her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Whitewater Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, spoke out Thursday
for the first time since Clinton accused him in a nationwide
address Monday of needlessly prying into his private life.
Responding to reporters' questions in Little Rock, Ark., Starr
would not say whether he felt vindicated by the president's
admission that he misled the American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is one of law, gathering facts and assessing them
and making professional judgments, as it should be,'' Starr said.
``A legal process should above all be aimed at achieving and
vindicating the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the legal maneuvering, debate has intensified at the
White House over the political fallout from the Lewinsky matter.
Many of the president's political advisers have complained that the
president was not properly apologetic in his nationwide address
Monday, and that his tone prompted harsh responses from Democrats
and Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers have also complained that Clinton's lawyers have
been uncooperative and that they had wrongly assured them early
this year that Clinton's defense did not rely on specific
definitions of sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an effort to unite the legal and political teams,
David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, met Wednesday evening with
political advisers including deputy chief of staff John Podesta,
White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said that in discussions that took place
before American cruise missiles struck targets in Afghanistan and
Sudan, aides also weighed whether Clinton should agree to a major
interview or another public appearance to tamp down criticism of
his speech Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who has had many run-ins with the
White House related to the Starr investigation, Thursday reaffirmed
her confidence in Clinton as the leader of the administration. ``In
all my dealings with the president, he has been to me a person
dedicated to the issues of government,'' she said in response to a
reporter's question.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, White House officials did their best to play down Ms.
Lewinsky's testimony. ``I don't think that the president or the
White House has been particularly following her business today,''
said White House press secretary Mike McCurry.
</P>
</TEXT>
