A4888 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-RODRIGUEZ     08-20 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RODRIGUEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE THE STATS, PUDGE WON'T REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ At this point in the baseball season, even
those of us who consider Pudge Rodriguez worthy of his $8 million
paycheck, are forced to register a disclaimer.
</P>
<P>
   When Rodriguez is overworked, he does become overpaid. Army
mules couldn't carry Pudge's load. And neither can Pudge. His
dedication is commendable, but not baseball profitable for either
Rodriguez or the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   No calendar is necessary at The Ballpark in Arlington. For any
Rangers' fan, the passage of spring and summer months can be
clearly marked by charting Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   April, May and June _ going so good like we knew he would. The
bat and step are lively; the arm is forever deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Early July brings the All-Star Game. They couldn't play that
thing without Pudge. He's as automatic at the ballot box as a South
American dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Then, however, here comes the season's second half, bringing
with it a slump. July doesn't lie. There are telltale signs that
the load becomes heavier.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the elephant shows up, looking for a ride. And Pudge
can't seem to get the big fellow off his back or his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the steady fade of statistical numbers tells us September
is near.
</P>
<P>
   This is simply how Pudge Rodriguez's great career in Arlington
is defined. Every season it happens with the same certainty.
Managers may come and go, but the workload doesn't change, nor does
Rodriguez' steady decline.
</P>
<P>
   Pudge, for his part, resists change, even if catcher is the most
demanding position both physically and mentally. And his immense
talent as a hitter is best illustrated by this being the fourth
consecutive season his average will be better than .300.
</P>
<P>
   But what could his average and his run production be if
Rodriguez didn't hit 40 points less for his career after the
All-Star break, and if his runs batted in didn't fall dramatically
in the same span? Both declines have, of course, begun this season,
along with a defensive slide. Pudge has two RBI in his past 12
games, hasn't homered in a career-high 69 games, and since late
July is only a .260 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up another great idea from me, although not exactly
original.
</P>
<P>
   Would somebody please rest this guy?
</P>
<P>
   And right now would not be too late to start, although Pudge
taking off one game a week behind the plate starting back in April
seemed the best plan.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Johnny Oates thinks often over the course of a season about
doing just that, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The next day's lineup I write down the night before and leave
it on my desk,'' said Oates. ``I'll have Pudge not playing. I'll go
home, get to thinking about it, and then the same thing usually
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates returns to the ballpark the next afternoon, tears up his
lineup card, and makes a new one with Rodriguez catching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge is a hard guy to leave out because of everything he can
do, and because there's Pudge's attitude to also consider,'' said
Oates. ``Ivan Rodriguez is a real unique bird.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my business, we've got guys you have to hit with a 2-by-4
to get them to play every day. But with Pudge, you have to use a
2-by-6 to get him out of the lineup. I love him for that, but I
also understand the wear-and-tear process he puts himself
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Regular rest is obviously not a subject Rodriguez wants to
discuss. ``If they decide to do that, I'd take the rest,'' Pudge
said, shrugging, before Thursday night's game against Cleveland.
This was his 106th start of the season behind the plate, an
American League high. Last season he led the majors in games caught
with 139.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get tired because I try to play the game hard,'' added
Rodriguez. ``What I do, however, is come to play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates, a former catcher, believes that as long as Pudge is at
the position, his offensive numbers will slide in the second half,
even with spotted rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mental grind gets you as much as the physical grind,'' he
said. ``Who is to say his numbers would be any better? A lot of
good catchers have eventually been moved to other positions just to
give them offensive relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Oates admits ``it's a fight'' to convince Rodriguez to
take a rare off day.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, nothing will change, despite what the career
offensive numbers show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday, however, picture Pudge as a third baseman,'' added
Oates. ``The quick hands and feet, the arm ... think about that and
think about what he'd hit without the burden of catching.''
</P>
<P>
   Only then apparently could Rodriguez's July and August follow
his April-May-and-June pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
