<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOCOLATE-VACATION-AR     08-20 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-VACATION-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HERSHEY, Pa.: gastronomic ghettos.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hershey's mansion was not remote; it was across the street from
the chocolate factory. At the suggestion of his wife, Kitty, the
childless couple devoted almost all their personal fortune to
caring for orphans on farms surrounding Hershey, an initiative that
the family's foundation continues, although today's beneficiaries
are not necessarily parentless.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast and Dessert
</P>
<P>
   The infomercials ended. It was bedtime, particularly as the only
feasible alternative was clearly the Cartoon Network. It was then
we experienced our second disappointment: no York Peppermint Patty
on the pillow. I had sort of expected it.
</P>
<P>
   Upon waking up, we were thus especially eager to get to
breakfast in the lodge's Lebbie Lebkicher's Eatery and Pub, named
for a man who lent Hershey some money after one of his failures. It
is decorated with old posters for nickel-and-dime candy bars. The
waitress asked the boys whether they wanted chocolate milk or hot
chocolate. She gave them crayons in a tin candy container.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to eat more chocolate than you've ever eaten in
your life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I had coffee and four succulent chocolate muffins, but the
children ate healthily. To be sure, the waitress had point-blank
refused Guy's request to give them plates of whipped cream. A
Reese's Peanut Butter Cup, with a human inside, came by. Guy said,
``It's fun shaking your favorite candy's hand, right, Dad?''
</P>
<P>
   After grabbing a handful of free Hershey Kisses for the road, we
waited in front of Hershey Lodge for Suzanne's flute teacher, who
lives nearby and with whom she has kept up all these years. The
hotel is oriented to families and conventions, and had seemed more
our kind of place than the hilltop Hotel Hershey across town. This
was not just because it is cheaper, but because it also had
miniature golf, several swimming pools and a video arcade.
</P>
<P>
   A friendly crowd. There were lots of people in Nascar and
motorcycle T-shirts; a huge woman wearing an ``I'm a chocoholic''
tank top; a couple with triplet babies in a single stroller, and
people carrying five-foot-high stuffed animals they had obviously
won at the amusement park. Pointing to the prizes, Roy gasped,
``Those kids are talented, Mom.'' (He believed this deeply, it was
to emerge in tearful moments later on.)
</P>
<P>
   Youthful Memories
</P>
<P>
   But before visiting Hersheypark, we went for a ride with
Suzanne's teacher, Bish, and her husband, Karl. Suzanne's four
years in a nearby town, Cleona, seven miles down the road from
Hershey, was the longest she lived anywhere as a child. We saw her
high school and other required sights We also went to places to
sample fresh-made soft pretzels and Lebanon bologna.
</P>
<P>
   Most compellingly, we marveled at the chocolate factory, with
the giant logo Hershey Cocoa spelled out in shrubbery, as well as
the towering silos full of cocoa beans. We saw Hershey Hotel, with
the magnificent fountains and stone lions in the lobby, and the
stunning gardens outside. Reverently, we paused at the intersection
of Chocolate and Cocoa and whiffed the air wafting over from the
factory. Yes, Virginia, it smelled divinely of chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   What was once the centerpiece of a Hershey visit, a factory
tour, has not been offered for years. Suzanne remembered seeing
huge vats of bubbling chocolate and savoring a chocolate milk on
factory tours of her youth. By the early 1970s, the tour was
drawing a million people a year, ultimately making it too crowded
for the workers.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was Hershey's Chocolate World, a Disney-like tour
of chocolate, with visitors riding automated cars. The attraction
has just been spruced up in honor of its 25th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   For the brief ride, about 10 or 12 minutes, one sees the world
from the perspective of a cocoa bean. From being cut with a machete
in an unidentified rain forest, you are shipped in containers to
the Pennsylvania promised land for roasting, milling, refining and
any number of other things. A Donald Duck-sounding voice provides
commentary. The cars never stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``So cool, man,'' Roy intoned as we went through the roaster
oven where the enveloping odor was you-know-what. The Hershey's
Kiss machine would have been anti-climactic, had it not been so
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   The final message, from an eminently sincere recorded voice,
was: ``No matter where you go, no matter how far, you're always
near a Hershey's Bar.'' As if to prove it, you are then given a
free candy bar before exiting into a really big gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, you pass an expansive wall plaque with a lot of
names on little gold sheets. It is labeled the Hall of Fame of the
National Confectionary Salesmen's Association. That seemed
intriguing. Who were these men prowling the highways and byways of
America to bring chocolate to those in need? I'll never know,
because Roy and Guy had made a beeline for the gift shop. We raced
to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
