<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0619 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOCOLATE-VACATION-AR     08-20 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-VACATION-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HERSHEY, Pa.: keep up.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best part of the shop was the giant made-to-order candy bars
they were selling that you could put any message on: ``Thanks for
watching the house,'' was the suggested one. I briefly thought of
provocative inscriptions I might have written to that long-ago
girlfriend, when my attention was suddenly seized by a toddler
stumbling by in a daze. ``Chocolaty, chocolaty,'' he kept
repeating.
</P>
<P>
   The Early Factory Days
</P>
<P>
   We each had a hot fudge sundae at an ice cream stand near the
gift shop. Then it was a short walk on to Hershey Museum, mostly an
eclectic collection of things Hershey picked up here and there _ an
American Indian section, Pennsylvania Dutch furniture, artifacts of
Victorian America and lots on the history of the Hershey family,
town and business. The Hershey stuff was best.
</P>
<P>
   Roy loved the re-creation of the factory locker room, where he
put on the chocolate-brown uniform of a worker and punched a time
clock. In the Discovery Room, the boys time-traveled to the 1800s
and pretended to buy things at a general store and cook on a wood
stove. What they liked best was playing checkers, a game that has
not changed. Parents sit on chairs at the edge of the room as
spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Intriguingly, a small exhibition hinted that things were not
always simple and easy, even in the world's sweetest town. In 1937,
there was a pretty brutal sitdown strike, the result of workers'
discontent with wages and an organizing campaign by the Council of
Industrial Organizations. The strikers shut down the plant and
barricaded themselves inside. Workers loyal to Hershey, local dairy
farmers and the American Legion fought with the strikers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, neither the Council nor a company union got
bargaining rights. Hershey promised not to discriminate against any
participants. Chocolate town returned to cozy comfort.
</P>
<P>
   One wondered, though. One object in the display case, with no
accompanying explanation, riveted my attention: a wooden club with
a leather strap. And according to another exhibition at the museum,
life on the world's sweetest assembly line was relentlessly
demanding piecework. Payment on the ``Kiss line'' was a dime for 20
dozen Kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Shake-ups
</P>
<P>
   The time for Hersheypark had come. Suzanne and I have kind of an
ambivalent feeling about amusement parks. It might be because
neither of us much likes spinning out of control at high altitudes.
Or it might be an aversion to seeing the rubes, particularly
ourselves, fleeced on the Midway. What we like about amusement
parks is the atmosphere, somehow nostalgic and challenging at the
same time. We like Coney Island. Sometimes we think we should take
the boys to Disneyworld, but we've never quite gotten around to it.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering, we were measured to determine which rides we
could handle. Roy was tall enough to be a ``Twizzler,'' a Hershey's
candy that, alarmingly, contains no chocolate. That meant he could
ride almost anything. Guy was a Hershey Bar, which barred him from
a ride or two. Suzanne was ``Cookies `N' Creme.'' At 6 feet 3
inches, I was waved through.
</P>
<P>
   We began bravely enough by marching straight to the Comet, the
biggest roller coaster in the United States when it opened in 1946.
We waited in line for about 45 minutes, which is standard for most
of the big rides on the weekend. I rode with Roy. We screamed and
complained and promised to ride each of the park's other five
coasters, then somehow forgot to get around to it.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne and Guy found the experience sinister. She made Guy
close his eyes throughout the ride. She feared she was going to fly
out of the car, and sank so deeply into her seat her knees and back
hurt. She said it was awful. Guy let it be known that his teddy
bear (and alter ego), who had just been named Teddy Fudge in honor
of our expedition, would ride no more roller coasters. That meant
Guy wouldn't either.
</P>
<P>
   We soon found ourselves absorbed in the fantasy world of the
park. We drank big lemonades, lots of them, and ate popcorn and
cotton candy and funnel cake. Roy and I did a really great water
slide, Pistol Pete's Plunge, and also Tidal Force, a ride in which
you slowly climb a 100-foot hill in a 20-passenger boat, then shoot
down at a 43-degree angle to hit the water with an enormous splash.
The boys and I loved yet a third water ride, Canyon River Rapids,
which gives the experience of white-water rafting. But on a hot
afternoon, we had to wait for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne and Guy tackled the Rodeo, an innocuous enough looking
ride compared with all the killer coasters _ particularly the new
Great Bear, on which riders sit in ski chairs with their feet
dangling down through 60-mile-an-hour corkscrew turns and
360-degree loops. But she was white as a sheet after revolving and
rotating, at the same time, on the Rodeo. Roy studied the map and
said, ``I've got a good ride for Mom _ the bathroom or the
telephone booth.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went, through two sunny days and one neon-seared night.
Fear, laughter and time moving at a little different speed. A
spectacular antique carousel went round and round and round. The
boys cried bitterly after unsuccessful tries at tossing balls in
milk cans and other Midway games, but were thrilled to win stuffed
animals when a barker could not guess either of their weights.
</P>
<P>
   They frolicked in the misting sprinklers the park has placed at
strategic locations. They laughed a little too loudly when a
toddler threw up his Twizzlers. At ZooAmerica, which began with
Hershey's personal animal collection and is included with admission
to the park, we walked on a bridge to a quieter, wooded world. The
animals are exclusively North American. We liked the bears.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what to think? The experience is wholly commercial,
with every feature linked to promoting the Hershey image, or
occasionally other corporate sponsors who have rented space. What
is known as ``the sweetest parade on earth'' consists of 14
characters, each a trademarked Hershey's product, marching
triumphantly through the park shortly before dark. Having your
picture taken with one or another candy bar is one of everyone's
favorite activities.
</P>
<P>
   Well, why not? For better or worse, Hershey in this very place
made chocolate accessible to the masses. By definition, chocolate
is happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we ate too much chocolate,'' Guy mumbled as we were
leaving, a Hershey's Kiss firmly in his mouth. ``But this  &UR; is &LR;  a
special chocolate place.''
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEY LODGE, West Chocolate Avenue and University Drive, (800)
533-3131. Open year round. Nightly rates start at $89 a person for
adults, based on double occupancy, during the summer season. Room
rates vary significantly according to season and specific package.
Call for details and reservations.
</P>
<P>
   HOTEL HERSHEY, Hotel Road, (800) 533-3131. Open year round.
Nightly rates start at $129 a person for adults, based on double
occupancy during the summer season. Room rates vary significantly
according to season and specific package. Call for details and
reservations. Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   LEBBIE LEBKICHER'S EATERY AND PUB, at Hershey Lodge, West
Chocolate Avenue and University Drive, (717) 533-3311. Open daily:
7 to 11 a.m. for breakfast, 11:30 a.m. to 11 p.m. for lunch and
dinner. All major credit cards accepted. Attractions
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEYPARK, (800) 437-7439. Hours: through Sunday, 10 a.m. to
11 p.m.; Monday through Labor Day, Mondays through Thursdays 10
a.m. to 8 p.m., Fridays through Sundays 10 a.m. to 10 p.m.; Sept. 8
to 20, open Saturdays 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. and Sundays 10 a.m. to 8
p.m.. Park closed after Sept. 20 until the spring of 1999.
Admission: $29.95, ages 9 to 54; $16.95. ages 3 to 8 or 55 and
older; $18.95 for consecutive day (keep previous day's ticket
stub); $15.95 late-day admission (call for specific hours); free
for children 2 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEY'S CHOCOLATE WORLD, Park Boulevard, (717) 534-4900.
Hours: 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. daily; 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. on Labor Day; after
Labor Day, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. usually, but hours can vary and
visitors should call. Free.
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEY MUSEUM, 170 West Hersheypark Drive, (717) 534-3439.
Hours: 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily through Labor Day; after Labor Day,
10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission: $5; $4.50 for the elderly; $2.50 for
ages 3 to 15.
</P>
<P>
   HERSHEY GARDENS, Hotel Road (across from Hotel Hershey), (717)
534-3492. Hours: 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily; to 8 p.m. on Fridays and
Saturdays before Labor Day. Admission: $5; $4.25 for those 62 and
over; $2.50 for ages 3 to 15; members and children under 3, free.
</P>
