<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINATRA-FILMS-NYT &LR;      08-20 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINATRA-FILMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY FACES OF SINATRA: FROM FLUFF TO `ETERNITY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Critic's Notebook) 
(smw) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the more unlikely romantic couplings to be
found in a 1950s Hollywood movie was the pairing of Frank Sinatra
as a gaunt, impoverished young composer from New York City and
Doris Day as his indefatigably chipper apple-cheeked Connecticut
dream girl. Ms. Day's character, who is engaged to another man
throughout much of the film, is the singer with a family orchestra
whose perky togetherness and taste for kitsch vaguely suggest a
tacky Connecticut equivalent of the Von Trapps.
</P>
<P>
   The Sinatra character, an Italian-American who has changed his
name to disguise his origin, moans on and on about how the fates
have conspired against him in both his career and his love life.
When he sings ``One for My Baby'' near the end of the film, the
song becomes a summation of all the self-pitying complaints that
have gone before. Throughout the movie, Ms. Day's goody-goody, who
finds herself strangely drawn to him, is tireless (to the point of
obnoxiousness) in her efforts to cheer up this self-proclaimed
loser who, unbeknownst to her, has been nursing a case of
unrequited love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young at Heart,'' which will be shown Sept. 4 to Sept. 6 at
Walter Reade Theater as part of the Film Society of Lincoln
Center's ``Salute to Sinatra,'' is a musically enhanced remake of
``Four Daughters,'' the 1938 movie in which John Garfield made his
screen debut. In the remake Sinatra fills Garfield's shoes, playing
the same vulnerable ``ethnic'' outsider pressing his nose to the
glass and peering with longing at a preposterously idealized vision
of WASP gentility.
</P>
<P>
   The 1954 movie, whose title was taken from the hit song that
commercially revitalized Sinatra's recording career after a long
slide, is miles away from the best film he made. But what it
captures, perhaps more purely than any of his other movies, is the
essence of his screen charisma and the mannerisms that embellished
it.
</P>
<P>
   There is the raised left eyebrow arched to the point of no
return, expressing a deep quizzical sadness that in later films
shaded into a combative cynicism. There is the tilted fedora that
seemed to float on the side of his head like a more grown-up,
rakish version of the askew sailor hat he sported in 40's movie
musicals. There is the cigarette dangling so precariously from one
side of his upper lip that you begin to wonder if the butt hasn't
been glued on.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there are the eyes that seem to spin like blue
pinwheels, alternately searchingly lonely and penetratingly
observant. As Sinatra aged, that aura of loneliness and wonder
steadily gave way to a harder glare seething with a tough, often
accusatory carnal knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that ``A Salute to Frank Sinatra'' forcefully
demonstrates is that Sinatra didn't have to sing to be a movie
star. Singing may have gotten him into the movies. But after his
1953 comeback in ``From Here to Eternity,'' he wouldn't have had to
sing another note to continue on screen as long as he cared. As the
series also shows, after ``From Here to Eternity,'' the period in
which Sinatra cared didn't last too long.
</P>
<P>
   At his most convincing, he embodied and carried forward his own
version of Garfield's up-from-the-streets outsider tradition,
mixing it with some of Humphrey Bogart's
hard-as-nails-but-still-vulnerable tough guy. To these archetypes
he brought an extra dimension of waifish vulnerability. More than
any other male movie star, with the possible exception of
Montgomery Clift, Sinatra wore his nerve endings on his sleeve. But
where Clift's characters seemed terminally neurotic, Sinatra's were
scrappy outsiders fighting their way in.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra's physique had a lot to do with it. In an era of fleshy
male stars, he was skinny, and as a bobby-socks idol had been
ridiculed for it. Thinness, of course, has always been equated with
hypersensitivity (think of the expression thin-skinned), and
Sinatra's tender imploring ballad style of those early years was
nothing if not sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   With Maggio, the Academy Award-winning role in ``From Here to
Eternity'' that turned his career around (and for which he was paid
a measly $8,000), all the chemical ingredients of Sinatra's screen
and vocal persona came together. The wiry, high-strung outsider
whose self-martyring refusal to buckle to authority costs him his
life is a version of the same personality who could prostrate
himself totally to a self-destructive passion in a song like ``I'm
a Fool to Want You.'' But that scrappy outsider could also swing
out with a feisty aggression that on a good night could best an
opponent twice his size.
</P>
<P>
   But could Sinatra really act? It depends on what you mean by
acting. Even in his most ``serious'' performances, you are never
less than 100 percent aware that what you're watching is Sinatra
giving a performance. And when the shoe fits, that performance can
be impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his finest moment after his triumph as Maggio came in
``The Man With the Golden Arm,'' Otto Preminger's black-and-white
1955 adaptation of Nelson Algren's novel, in which Sinatra plays a
heroin-addicted cardsharp and aspiring drummer fighting to survive
on Chicago's mean streets. The scenes in which his character goes
cold turkey with the help of Kim Novak (as a sympathetic bar girl)
are still harrowing to watch. As his character goes through the
shakes and cold chills, his nerve endings aren't just on his
sleeve, they're emitting stinging lightning flashes from all over
his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Salute to Sinatra,'' which begins Friday and runs through
Sept. 8, features 19 of the 57 films he made. All phases of his
career are represented, from the 40's musicals to the '50s dramas
(excluding ``Suddenly,'' the well-regarded film in which he played
a presidential assassin) to his Rat Pack capers (only one,
``Ocean's 11'') and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Sinatra maintained a certain stubborn integrity.
If his taste in songs began to waver in the 1960's, his taste in
movie roles more than wavered; it plummeted. But even if Sinatra
walked through a role or riffed crudely on a pop song (``How's your
bird, Mrs. Robinson?'' he once interpolated), he was always nothing
more or less than himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
