<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TREASURY BOND YIELDS FALL AS INVESTORS FLEE STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   Turmoil in overseas economies sent investors fleeing stocks for
the safety of bonds, pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond
to 5.51 percent, another new low. The Dow Jones industrial average
fell 81.87 points, to 8,611.41.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that Russian bank failures were imminent and that
Venezuela might be forced to devalue its currency, the bolivar, to
combat a growing budget deficit, and persistent concerns about a
similar move by China, buoyed the Treasury market. All of these
things added to investor concerns that the financial crises among
emerging markets may be spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan stocks plunged 9.5 percent, the biggest one-day drop
in nearly four years, as the market was rattled by worries that the
government might devalue its currency. Other Latin American markets
also declined. Mexico's chief market index fell 2.93 percent. In
Brazil, the Sao Paulo stock exchange's Bovespa index fell 6.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   BARNES &AMP; NOBLE UNIT TO GO PUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Barnes &AMP; Noble rose 7.5 percent, or $2.8125, to
$40.0625, after the bookseller said it planned to sell 20 percent
of its on-line venture to the public. Barnes &AMP; Noble also announced
that its loss for the second quarter tripled, primarily because of
a $23 million loss by the on-line venture.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT TRIAL IS DELAYED 2 WEEKS
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge has pushed back the starting date of the
antitrust trial against Microsoft until Sept. 26. Lawyers for the
company and Justice Department were also bickering over where and
how pretrial questioning of Bill Gates, chairman of Microsoft,
would take place.
</P>
<P>
   FED GROUP VOTED 10 TO 1 ON RATES
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policy makers voted 10-1 at their meeting on
July 1 to leave the overnight bank lending rate unchanged at 5.50
percent. The lone dissenting vote was from Jerry Jordan, president
of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG BOUGHT STOCKS AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong government bought stocks for the fourth time in a
week and intervened in the futures market for a third session as it
continued to try to hurt currency and stock speculators.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN SALES BOLSTER HONDA PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Honda Motor reported a 26 percent profit gain in the latest
quarter, largely because of sales in Europe and the United States.
Those overseas sales once earned Honda criticism, but now many
Japanese business executives are praising the benefits of
globalization. Hiroyuki Yoshino, the new president of the auto
maker, predicted that the overseas expansion would protect Honda
from the consolidation sweeping the automobile business.
</P>
<P>
   NOVELL BEATS EARNINGS ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Third-quarter profit at Novell beat analysts' expectations by
one cent as the maker of networking software cut costs and improved
sales by selling new Internet-based products. Net income was $26.6
million, or 7 cents a diluted share. The company had been expected
to earn 6 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   AUTODESK BUYING DISCREET LOGIC
</P>
<P>
   Autodesk, a maker of software for engineers and designers, plans
to buy Discreet Logic, a maker of special effects for movies and
television, for about $520 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   IRS SET TO PERMIT USE OF PLASTIC
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service will accept payments of Federal tax
bills by credit card next year.
</P>
<P>
   STRAINED RELATIONS IN ADVERTISING
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between ad agencies and advertisers is
deteriorating, according to the 1998 Salz Survey of
Advertiser-Agency Relations. The surveys for 1996 and 1997 had
brought surprisingly better responses from executives at agencies
and client companies when asked about the nature of their
relations. But that era of good feelings proved brief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
