<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFGHAN AND SUDANESE IMMIGRANTS DOUBT MERIT OF AIR STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: ATTACK-U.S. with photos, map and graphic,
ATTACK-BINLADEN with map, ATTACK-CONGRESS, ATTACK-SECURITY,
ATTACK-ALBANIA, ATTACK-EVIDENCE, ATTACK-MILITARY, ATTACK-ASSESS,
ATTACK-MIDEAST-REACT, ATTACK-SUDAN with map, ATTACK-MEDIA,
ATTACK-WAG, ATTACK-TRAVEL-ADVISORY.) 
(smw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yes, they thought that the embassy bombings in East
Africa constituted a crime of the lowest order. And yes, they
thought that Osama bin Laden, a wealthy Saudi who has publicly
threatened a holy war against the United States, came across as a
shady character with an inordinate amount of power.
</P>
<P>
   But in the New York metropolitan region Thursday, immigrants
from the Sudan and Afghanistan reacted to bombings by the United
States on their respective homelands with surprise, horror and
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others, the immigrants wondered about the timing of
the strikes, suggesting that President Clinton was aiming not so
much to punish bin Laden as to divert attention from the Monica
Lewinsky case. But they also criticized what they said was a
foolhardy strategy of going after one man accused of terrorism by
picking on two countries that have been mired in misery for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the floods and the earthquakes and the wars and threats
of attacks from Iran,'' said Maryam Miazad, an Afghan immigrant
living in Westbury, N.Y., ``this was the last thing Afghanistan
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the two immigrant groups, the Afghans are by far the more
numerous and visible in the New York region. According to official
figures, there are more than 5,000 Afghans in New York City;
community leaders, though, say that there could be as many as
40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most Afghan-Americans moved to the United States after the
Soviet invasion in the late 1970s and early '80s. It was a tragic
time, said Yusuf Mohammed, an Afghan immigrant who lives in New
York City. He added that the invasion was the latest example of
Afghanistan's suffering at the hands of rapacious invaders, first
Alexander the Great, then the Chinese, then the British.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said some of the immigrants, come the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is a superpower,'' said Mohammed, an employee at the
Afghan Kebab House near Times Square. ``The Afghan people don't
have food to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Historical indignities aside, many Afghan-Americans said they
were irritated, even dumbfounded, at Washington's strategy for
capturing, or killing, bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't bombard one area, maybe kill hundreds of people,
just for one person,'' said Mohammed Yusufi, imam of the Afghan
Immigrants Islamic Center in Flushing, Queens. ``Everyone was
surprised by this. Everyone was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people questioned Clinton's motives for the strikes.
Some Republican senators, including former presidential candidate
Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, hinted that Clinton's troubled
personal life was the rationale behind the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what everyone else thinks,'' Ms. Miazad said. ``Monica
Lewinsky testified today, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who were willing to give the United States the
prerogative to vigorously defend its citizens said they were
disappointed with the military action. They said the Taliban, the
fundamentalist Muslims in control of the Kabul government, have
yearned for world-stage recognition from other nations,
particularly the United States. So it followed, the
Afghan-Americans said, that the United States might have had some
leverage in giving the Taliban recognition, money and food in
exchange for bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``America had a good chance to talk to these guys,'' said Bashir
Saleh, who operates a coffee cart in Times Square. ``America could
have used diplomacy. But now, America strikes in Afghanistan, and
the Taliban are going to say, `We're going to defend this guy till
our last drop of blood.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
