<SLUG> BC-NY-DISABLED-HOUSING-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SHIFT, PATAKI PROPOSES MAJOR EXPANSION IN HOUSING FOR RETARDED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two months after 26 retarded adults were found to be
living in homeless shelters at the Westchester County Airport, Gov.
George Pataki has proposed a major expansion of a housing program
for developmentally disabled people, one that is intended to place
thousands of them in group homes around New York State.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's proposal calls for spending $230 million over the next
five years to create housing for 4,900 people and represents a
significant departure for the governor, who during his first three
years in office added fewer than 900 beds for developmentally
disabled people. Currently, the state houses 32,000 mentally
retarded people in group homes and supervised apartments; about
6,500 are on waiting lists for housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the right way to do the right thing for people who
need our help here in New York State,'' Pataki said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But critics charged that Pataki was embarrassed into making the
election-year proposal after it was disclosed in June that retarded
adults in Westchester were living among a homeless population that
included drug and alcohol abusers and ex-convicts. Advocates for
the homeless said that their subsequent inquiries led them to
estimate that about 8,000 developmentally disabled people were
living in homeless shelters statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became an enormous political problem for the governor,''
said Assemblyman Richard Brodsky, D-Greenburgh. ``At the same time,
it was apparent that on a human basis, he had to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Maul, commissioner of the state Office of Mental
Retardation and Developmental Disabilities, denied that the plan
had anything to do with the Westchester situation. He said the
proposal was meant to address a chronic housing shortage that has
its roots in a 1975 federal court order that forced the state to
close institutions for mentally retarded people because of
deplorable living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal and what happened in Westchester are two
separate issues,'' said Deborah Sturm Rausch, a spokeswoman for
Maul. ``Anyone can go to a shelter if they need help. The question
is what happens after they get there. Do they remain or do the
providers refer them elsewhere? What we're doing here is responding
to a need.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Westchester County shelter, officials said
that many of the retarded adults wound up there after living with
aging parents who could no longer care for them.
</P>
<P>
   While advocates for the mentally retarded are thrilled with
Pataki's announcement, the plan could lead to a backlash in
neighborhoods where the group homes would be situated. Though 6,600
group homes have opened in New York state since the 1975 court
decree, some homes were put into service only after vociferous
debates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Families of people with mental disabilities welcomed the plan,
although some expressed skepticism about its timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled when I heard about the governor's announcement,
but then I realized he is running for office,'' said Rochelle
Kessler, a 61-year-old widow living in Greenburgh, who cares for
her 33-year-old developmentally disabled son, Stuart. ``I'm not
going to be around forever and I've got to get him used to a group
home before I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the plan are still being worked out, said Ms. Rausch
of the office of mental retardation, though it had been decided
that the beds would be operated by private, nonprofit agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Brodsky questioned the timing of the proposal, saying Pataki had
come under fire for recent decisions involving the developmentally
disabled. In particular, Pataki was criticized during the last
legislative session for vetoing a proposal that would have added
175 beds to the system.
</P>
<P>
   But Maul's spokeswoman said Pataki vetoed the item because it
would have served only as a Band-Aid on a worsening problem and he
wanted to come up with a long-range plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
