<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOWER-MANHATTAN-PARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVER PARKS OFFER MANHATTANITES A BACK YARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kate Young lives in the East Village but likes to
walk over to the meticulously kept lawn outside Battery Park City
to read. Marilyn Smith makes weekly visits to the esplanade from
her Greenwich Village home. And Daryl Richardson of Chelsea says he
likes the chain of parks along the Hudson in lower Manhattan better
than Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   For park-starved lower Manhattanites, the rapidly expanding
stretch of parkland from Battery Park to Chambers Street is
becoming what Central Park is for uptown residents: the closest
thing they have to a back yard. And as a hybrid of public-private
parkland, the series of parks is a model of what the future may
hold for the Hudson River shoreline as developers team up with the
city to turn neglected land into recreational space.
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of visitors who have been descending on the parks
are drawn by a wealth of attractions: magnificent Hudson River and
harbor views framed by finely landscaped lawns, whimsical
sculptures, a variety of restaurants and a regular schedule of free
events like concerts and storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is spectacular,'' said Ms. Smith, a retired
secretary. ``I feel like I'm in San Diego.''
</P>
<P>
   But as crowds have flocked to the parkland in lower Manhattan
over the last few summers, there has been grumbling that what was
once a downtown oasis is becoming overrun by those people, many of
whom live outside the immediate area and don't pay directly to
support the parks. On a recent Sunday, scores of Roller-bladers
whirled crazily about, weaving around bicyclists and baby
carriages. At one playground, security guards sometimes make
children and their parents line up to be admitted only when someone
else leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten to the point where a lot of people, myself
included, are afraid to take their children into the playground,''
said Paul Goldstein, district manager of Community Board 1, who
lives nearby. ``You almost have to take a number to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   The parks' popularity, no doubt, is a symptom of success _ a
success backers say is rooted in having the private sector actively
involved in running parks as government support becomes scarcer.
The chain of parks along the lower Manhattan shoreline saw its
genesis in 1985, when the Battery Park City Authority opened the
esplanade as the first new waterfront park in the city since the
opening of the Brooklyn Heights promenade in 1954. The idea was to
give beauty and texture to the new residential community nearby,
while enhancing real estate values.
</P>
<P>
   Since the esplanade was constructed, other areas have been
turned into parkland, from the heavily used Rockefeller Park in the
north, to the picturesque South Cove and the intricately landscaped
Robert F. Wagner Park in the south. And all the parks are marked by
a painstaking attention to detail, in both their planning and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   But perfection comes at a price. The $4 per square foot in
annual maintenance costs is more than 10 times the amount that New
York City spends on an average square foot of parkland. Those
expenditures are shielded from the traditional uncertainties of
spending on parks: because the city ceded management but not
ownership of Battery Park City's open spaces to the authority, the
river park is completely protected from any cuts in city spending.
</P>
<P>
   The quasi-private nature of the parks has left some nearby
residents with a proprietary feeling, signaling that an effort to
reduce city government's role in parks management could have its
pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Elli Fordyce, a jazz singer who has lived in Battery Park City
for 11 years, says the crowds that jam the park on weekends
sometimes make it feel like Coney Island or Jones Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of rowdiness, necking and drinking and stuff,''
she said. ``It's just as not as pleasant when it's crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   Tessa Huxley, the executive director of the Battery Park City
Parks Corp., the subsidiary of the Battery Park City Authority that
runs the 30 acres of parkland connected to the housing complex,
said that in the early years of the development, residents tended
to react more like those in gated communities. ``People felt
shocked and angered to see strangers here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she says, the cocoon mentality has largely receded, though
the principal support of the park is still assessments paid by
owners and renters that average $270 a year per unit. She said
residents have become used to crowds streaming to the parks, as
well as to the new Museum of Jewish Heritage and the World
Financial Center's Winter Garden, with its stately indoor palm
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Others who live in the complex say they they do not mind sharing
their back yard with visitors, who help support the many
restaurants and shops in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if it were all ours, but that's not
realistic,'' said an executive recruiter who lives in Battery Park
City and was out teaching her 4-year-old daughter to ride a bike.
``That sort of resentment is just unjustified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
