<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5030 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-COLUM     08-20 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD IS GORDON'S IF HE AVOIDS ROUGH STUFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Will he or won't he?
</P>
<P>
   With Jeff Gordon in position to set NASCAR history Saturday with
a fifth consecutive Winston Cup victory at the Goody's 500, it's
time to examine the facts, pore over the data and make a
prediction.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the clues are contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   Those who think Gordon has a great shot at becoming the only
modern era (post 1971) driver to win five straight point to his
record.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has he won his past four races this season, he has also
won the past four Food City 500 races, the annual spring event at
the Bristol Motor Speedway, site of Saturday's race.
</P>
<P>
   And having cut his teeth on short tracks in the Midwest, Gordon
knows well that the key to winning on the half-mile Bristol course
is contained in an old racing axiom: To finish first, first you
have to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary concern at Bristol is finishing the race and
keeping all four fenders on,'' Gordon said. ``If we're in position
at the end, then we'll think about going for the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who think (hope?) Gordon won't get No.5 Saturday also have
supportive data.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has never won the Goody's race at Bristol, which is held
at night in the heat of summer. And they point to last year's race
as an example of what could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon had led 184 of the 244 laps and was running near first
when a collision with Jeremy Mayfield on the short, tight-cornered
crowded track knocked him out of the lead. And by lap 365 his car
was done and he had to settle for a 35th-place finish that enabled
Mark Martin to overcome him in the season points race.
</P>
<P>
   Short-track racing is notorious for bump-and-shove racing. Look
for Gordon's competitors to scratch up his paint job a bit as they
try to bring his team back to earth.
</P>
<P>
   Can he survive the rough stuff and win?
</P>
<P>
   I think he will.
</P>
<P>
   Holy cow stat of the week: Gordon has made 91 pit stops this
season. In all but eight of them, his pit crew has gotten him back
on the track in the same position or better compared to other cars
pitting at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   See ya: Wood Brothers racing is looking for a driver to replace
Michael Waltrip, who announced Monday that this season will be his
last in the No.21 Winston Cup Citgo Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip, who finished 14th in 1996, 18th last year and is 15th
so far this season, said both parties agreed a change was needed
after a recent spate of poor finishes. Waltrip has finished out of
the top 20 in seven of the past nine races.
</P>
<P>
   The younger brother of Darrell Waltrip, Michael Waltrip has
never won a Winston Cup event in 383 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Another parting: Scott Pruett, one point out of fifth place on
the CART tour this year, will end a five-year relationship with
Patrick Racing and join Arciero-Wells next season.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-year CART career, Pruett has developed a reputation for
consistency if not domination. He has been a top-10 finisher in
season points five times and has two series victories.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Gordon will not be back with Arciero-Wells, despite a
longstanding friendship with co-owner Frank Arciero. Gordon is
seeking other options.
</P>
<P>
   Movin' on up: Winston Cup driver John Andretti _ nephew of Mario
and cousin of Michael _ has five top-10 finishes in his past six
races and has moved from 21st to 11th in season points.
</P>
<P>
   Speedy Boat: &UR; !off! &LR;  Indy Racing League driver Billy Boat was
slowed by crutches anytime he left his car at the Radisson 200 in
Colorado last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the wheel, he was plenty fast, winning the pole and
setting a track record of 178.571 mph in qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   In his first race back since fracturing his femur at the IRL
race in New Hampshire on June 28, Boat had to settle for a
ninth-place finish when his car ran out of fuel with two laps to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Women's road-racing tour formed: An eight-race road-racing tour
featuring women drivers is being planned for 1999 by the American
Le Mans Series.
</P>
<P>
   The series will be called the Women's Global GT Championships
and is being headed by longtime open-wheel driver Lyn St. James.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a platform to highlight women as drivers,'' St. James
said. ``... My objective is to provide a venue for them to get
their names out as good candidates for careers in racing.''
</P>
<P>
   St. James said the series would be a stepping-stone to GT-3 or
GT-2 racing. Drivers will race identically prepared Panoz GT-RA
cars. The organization is looking at both Sears Point and Laguna
Seca as possible race sites.
</P>
<P>
   Shafer off and running: North Hollywood's Jeff Shafer finished
fourth at the Texaco Havoline 200 KOOL Atlantic race last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of what Jeff did, coming in fourth in just his
third race,'' said team co-owner Cal Wells III. ``He got the rookie
of the race award. I look forward to having him race again for us
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Shafer, who has been running a limited schedule for the team,
started eighth behind teammate and pole- and race-winner Anthony
Lazzaro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one of the fastest cars on the track,'' Shafer said.
``... It was the best run I've had and I just hope to keep taking
it forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Next on Shafer's calendar will be a KOOL Toyota appearance in
Vancouver, British Columbia, Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Woodside slips: Valencia's Sean Woodside finished eighth in
Saturday's Coors Light 200 at Monroe, Wash., and lost a few more
points to season points leader Kevin Harvick, who finished third,
in the NASCAR Winston West season points race.
</P>
<P>
   Woodside now trails Harvick, of Palmdale, by 34 points.
</P>
<P>
   Nuts and bolts: CART season points leader Alex Zanardi has put
off any announcement of his 1999 plans for two weeks. Zanardi, who
may leave CART to return to Formula One racing and his native
Italy, said he expects to make his decision by Sept. 1.... When
Jimmy Hensley came from his 30th starting place to win last week's
Federated Auto Parts 250 in Nashville, it was Hensley's first win
on the NASCAR truck series and the first time a provisional
qualifier won a series race.... Michael Schumacher's victory in
last week's Hungarian Grand Prix was the 32nd of his career, moving
him past Nigel Mansell into third place on the all-time victory
list.... Formula One racing is negotiating a return to South Africa
in 2001.... When he coasted to victory in Sunday's Radisson 200 at
Pikes Peak International Raceway Sunday _ his car out of gas _
Kenny Brack became the second driver in the Indy Racing League's
short history to win back-to-back events.... Ted Musgrave, recently
bumped from the No.16 Primestar Ford in favor of Kevin Lepage, will
drive Jimmy Spencer's No. 23 Winston No Bull Ford on Saturday and
perhaps for the rest of the season. Spencer is recovering from a
concussion suffered at Watkins Glen. Steve Grissom will drive
Spencer's Busch Grand National ride tonight.... Winston Cup driver
Joe Nemechek _ 24th in season points _ signed a three-year contract
extension with Team SABCO to drive the No. 42 BellSouth Chevy Monte
Carlo.... Palmdale's Ron Hornaday Jr. continues to lead the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck points race. Hornaday, the 1996 champion and
all-time series win leader has a 70-point advantage over Jack
Sprague.... Lance Hooper, also of Palmdale, was 30th in Saturday's
Busch Grand National Pepsi 200.... Craftsman Truck driver Bryan
Reffner _ 12th in the season points _ and his crew chief, Les Back,
were fired by Phelon Motorsports Tuesday.... John Myers, a
three-time NHRA pro stock bike motorcycle champion, was killed in a
motorcycle accident near his home in Birmingham, Ala., on Aug. 9.
He was 40.... Al Bignotti, a mechanic for A.J. Foyt, Graham Hill,
Al Unser Sr. and Gordon Johncock, died Aug. 11 at the age of 89.
</P>
</TEXT>
