<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-20 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSISSIPPI: SECOND THOUGHTS ON PRIVACY RIGHTS  
 ARIZONA: A TEST OF WILLS OVER DRUG LEGISLATION  
 WYOMING: SURPRISE SHOWDOWN LOOMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of years back, Gov. Kirk Fordice of Mississippi was
seriously injured in a car wreck while traveling from Memphis to
Jackson. He recovered but questions about the crash and
circumstances leading up to it dogged him and were making headlines
and talk shows long after he returned to work.
</P>
<P>
   Area papers reported that at the time of the crash, the
governor, a Republican, was not accompanied by his usual state
police escort. They said that a few hours before the crash he was
seen sipping wine in a Memphis-area restaurant with a woman who was
not his wife. Mrs. Fordice, they noted, was out of the country,
representing the governor and the state on a cultural mission.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to shed some light on all this, Fordice said, repeatedly,
that there was nothing to say because he could remember nothing
about the accident and, anyway, he was entitled to his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   That said, on Tuesday the governor had something to say about
the Clinton-Lewinsky matter and the president's confessional of the
night before. Addressing a gathering of Mississippi Republicans in
Jackson, he called for Clinton's resignation, declaring it would be
``the best thing for the country, without question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know he's a liar,'' Fordice said. ``Other horrors and
much worse are to follow and impeachment will surely follow and the
United States doesn't need that.''
</P>
<P>
   Character counts in politics, the governor went on, adding:
``When folks enter public office, they're due all the scrutiny they
get.''
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: A TEST OF WILLS OVER DRUG LEGISLATION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was called Proposition 200 and it seemed straightforward
enough when it appeared on Arizona ballots in the fall of 1996.
Backed by a well-financed grass-roots organization that called
itself Arizonans for Drug Policy Reform, it proposed allowing
doctors to prescribe marijuana and other illegal drugs for medical
use by grievously ill and dying patients.
</P>
<P>
   Voters approved it.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Legislature, one of the most conservative in the
country and in no mood to have the Grand Canyon State join other
states like California and Washington in the much-debated national
push to legalize illegal drugs for medical use, saw the proposition
as a legislative end run by a special interest group that had
considerably more in mind than just compassion for the sick.
Legislative leaders said that although marijuana was the drug most
talked about for medical use by Proposition 200's proponents, the
measure, if allowed to stand as written, also would permit doctors
to prescribe other illegal drugs like heroin, LSD and PCP.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature amended the measure, as Arizona law permits,
adding a rider that said Arizona doctors could not, under any
circumstances, prescribe a drug not on the federal government's
list of approved drugs. That amendment effectively gutted the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight did not end there.
</P>
<P>
   Arizonans for Drug Policy Reform, having renamed itself The
People Have Spoken, now has another drug proposal for Arizona
voters to consider. Labeled Proposition 300 and scheduled to be on
this fall's ballot, it would restore Proposition 200 to its
original form and instruct the legislature not to modify it again.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting back, state lawmakers are making sure that this time
around, the official ballot description of the proposition is
worded so that voters will understand that they are deciding not
only whether to legalize the use of marijuana for medical purposes
but also the use of many other illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, The People Have Spoken, whose main supporters
include George Soros, the international investor involved in
several social issues, asked a judge to throw out the lawmakers'
description of the measure, arguing that it was unfair for the
legislature to be in a fight in which it alone wrote the rules of
engagement. The court refused and the pamphlets are being readied
for distribution.
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING: SURPRISE SHOWDOWN LOOMING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wyoming is one of the nation's most Republican states, with the
Grand Old Party enjoying a 2-to-1 registration edge over Democrats.
So the odds are that the state's Republican governor, Jim Geringer,
will handily win a second term this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the aftermath of Tuesday's primaries in the Cowboy
State, the race now merits watching.
</P>
<P>
   Geringer safely won renomination, but in doing so, some
weaknesses were exposed. As a result the Democratic nominee, state
Sen. John Vinich, who also readily won nomination, probably has a
better shot at the governor's job than he originally had reason to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took office three years ago, the governor has struggled
to get the Wyoming economy moving, but with little success. With
its small population, limited job base and vast remoteness, the
state is the rare economic exception in this era of boom, and
throughout the primary season the governor's critics were quick to
put the blame on him.
</P>
<P>
   His main challenger in the primary, Bill Taliaferro, a sheep
rancher, hammered him relentlessly on the matter. But the governor
also had to contend with the issue and its political fallout when
one of the state's highest-ranking Republicans, Secretary of State
Diana Ohman, announced that she too was unhappy with his leadership
and approved a last-minute write-in campaign for the nomination on
her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   She did not cut very deeply into the governor's support. But her
campaign underscored the divisions within the Republican Party
under his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all for the governor, when the primary was over,
Taliaferro, who pulled 29,000 votes, or about a third of the entire
Republican vote, announced that he would not automatically throw
his support to the governor in the fall but instead might consider
supporting the Democratic nominee, Senator Vinich.
</P>
<P>
   Taliaferro said he would try to make his supporters ``players''
in the contest by urging them to go with the candidate who offered
them the most. Then he called on the governor to institute
wide-ranging economic reforms to solidify the Republican vote and
avoid any defections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 29,000 votes out there,'' he went on. ``Who wants
them? Vinich or Geringer?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
