<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT SORTS OUT OFFENSIVE LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE _ USC coach Paul Hackett set his starting lineup for the
Pigskin Classic on Thursday, with a couple surprises along the
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Junior-college transfer Matt Welch will start at right tackle,
despite the fact Hackett had nearly exclusively mentioned veterans
Ken Bowen and Rome Douglas as the challengers for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen, last year's starter, has a hyperextended elbow and was
expected to have a magnetic resonance imaging test Thursday. But
Hackett said Welch was named the starter before Bowen even got
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Welch) won the job for one game,'' Hackett said. ``It can
change at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch (6-foot-6, 295 pounds), of Santa Ana Junior College,
orally committed to UCLA last year before changing his mind in
January and signing with USC.
</P>
<P>
   The center position also underwent a change, as Eric Denmon beat
out Matt McShane. Junior Jason Grain has won the left guard spot,
with Donta Kendrick behind him. Sophomore Brent McCaffrey will
start at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the offensive line will continue to see a lot of
movement,'' Hackett said. ``The big thing is finally there's a
settling of the offensive line but I hate to say it's rock solid.''
</P>
<P>
   The new lineup means junior Travis Claridge is the only
returning starter from last season who will start the season opener
against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're inexperienced and we're limited,'' Hackett said. ``And
the game is won and lost in the trenches.''
</P>
<P>
   At fullback, Brennan Ochs will start but split time with Ted
Iacenda. Mike Van Raaphorst will start at quarterback, and as
expected, freshman Carson Palmer will be No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Morton will start at tailback and Malaefou MacKenzie will
back him up, but freshman Frank Strong is going to be in the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   At cornerback, Ken Haslip will start but share time with Antuan
Simmons. Lawrence Larry of Littlerock has won a defensive end
position.
</P>
<P>
   Woods update: Hackett still has not heard from quarterback
Quincy Woods, who left camp Monday, but a close friend said, ``He's
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, upset that he had no chance to start or back up at
quarterback, left camp Monday night to ponder his future and is now
expected to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   He had already considered a transfer to a Division I-AA school
last year and would probably go that route if he seeks his release
from USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk to Quincy, I'll talk to you,'' Hackett said.
``I've not talked to Quincy and I have nothing to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Cusano questionable: Hackett is hoping linebacker Mark Cusano
(hamstring) will play in the Pigskin Classic, but said sophomore
Zeke Moreno will start at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how much Mark will play in the opener,'' Hackett
said. `I hope a lot. I'm disappointed in Mark's injury. After
seeing him today, he might be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Marvin Powell's chances of being ready for the opener
are also in doubt as he recovers from a twisted knee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980820.0634 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-SAFETY-500&AMP;ADD-N     08-20 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA ACTS TO BAR GAGS IN DEFECT CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California motorists who obtain restitution from
automakers for defective vehicles may no longer have to promise
they will stay quiet as part of their settlements.
</P>
<P>
   California lawmakers passed a bill this week that would bar
automakers from imposing gag rules in agreements to repurchase cars
or trucks that are deemed defective under the state's lemon law.
The bill, the first of its kind in the nation, awaits the signature
of Gov. Pete Wilson; an aide said Wilson was likely to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Vows of silence over the settlement terms of a court case, or
details of a matter resolved privately, are common in disputes
involving medical malpractice, product liability and corporate
malfeasance. Increasingly, consumer advocates say, these secrecy
clauses are being written into automakers' agreements to buy back
badly flawed vehicles. Some regulators say the gags erode their
oversight by making it hard for them to track vehicles that have
been branded as lemons.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler Corp.'s reselling of 116 such defective vehicles is
central to a two-year legal fight between the company and
California's Department of Motor Vehicles. In June, a Superior
Court judge ordered the dispute to be reconsidered again, and, in
effect, reinstated the proposed penalty _ the harshest by any state
for violations of lemon laws. The penalty, which has yet to take
effect, would bar Chrysler from shipping cars or trucks to the
state for 45 days. Chrysler has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Annually, about 100,000 vehicles are repurchased by auto makers
because of defects, including 5,000 to 10,000 in California, said
Clarence Ditlow, director of the Center for Auto Safety in
Washington. He said consumer complaints often prompted
investigations by federal safety officials. ``If the gags are
widespread, you're going to dry up the source of complaints,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Charles Calderon, the Whittier Democrat who
co-sponsored the bill with Assemblyman Kevin Shelley, D-San
Francisco, said he expected Wilson to approve the legislation.
``Where the state has a responsibility to monitor safe products,
then secrecy makes no sense,'' Calderon said.
</P>
<P>
   In a Senate hearing last June, Mark Krause, a lobbyist for
defense lawyers, testified that the proposed legislation would
generate more litigation and work against consumers, making
automakers less likely to negotiate. ``By having a gag clause, it
sweetens the pot,'' he said. ``It makes it easier for manufacturers
to settle.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rosemary Shahan, president of Consumers for Auto Reliability
and Safety, an advocacy group in Sacramento that asked law makers
to introduce the bill, argued that ``gag clauses interfere with
agencies that are supposed to protect us.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the state Senate voted 21 to 12 to approve the
legislation, adding an amendment that permits secrecy on a
settlement's financial terms. On Tuesday, the state Assembly, which
had already endorsed the bill, approved the amendment 42-28.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Besides the Association for California Tort Reform, several
automakers also opposed the legislation. Ray Buttacavoli, regional
manager for General Motors Corp. in Sacramento, said most lemon-law
repurchases were voluntary. ``We feel we ought to be able to impose
conditions on those buybacks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Gomez, 48, a Moorpark, Calif., avocado grower, felt
vindicated when arbitrators deemed her 1996 Jeep Cherokee a lemon.
In its first year on the road, the car's drive shaft fell out
twice, once when Ms. Gomez' teen-age son was driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we returned the car, the very first thing they did was
shove a gag order in our face,'' Ms. Gomez said. ``It was
intimidation without legal representation; it was a threat to drag
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   A Chrysler representative eventually released a check to Ms.
Gomez, but only after she declared her intention to seek the help
of a consumer advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gomez's experience is typical, said Steven Solomon, a
Burlingame, Calif., lawyer who specializes in vehicle fraud. Most
consumers see a gag provision only in the final flurry of paper
signing, not during negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In defending the use of gag clauses, Jonathan Sasser, a lawyer
for the Dupont subsidiary Conoco in Raliegh, N.C., told the
American Bar Association Journal in April that disclosing
settlement amounts will raise litigation costs by heightening
expectations of lawyers and their clients. ``It will raise the
value of settlements in the future and raise the costs of defending
these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates are hopeful that California's ban on gag
clauses will be copied in other states. Yet the bill does not
establish a broader precedent that could be used to argue against
gag clauses in other consumer product settlements, said Judge
Thomas Whelan, presiding judge of San Diego Superior Court. ``The
statute is limited in its application,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of public furor over secrecy in some high-profile cases,
in the early 1990s San Diego's judges took the unusual step of
banning gag clauses in all cases in the local courts, permitting
them only by court approval. ``We look with disdain on secret
settlement agreements,'' Whelan said. ``Once they get us involved,
we aren't going to seal a court file.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
