<HEADER>
A5056 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-W     08-20 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY TELLS JURY MORE DETAILS ABOUT SEX AND GIFTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating for all needing)  
 (expands story by about 600 words; clarifies when Lewinsky told
jury about Currie phone call; adds more details about Lewinsky
testimony, activity outside the courthouse, new material about the
dress, statement issued by Starr from Little Rock, reaction from
White House and Reno, etc. story is now 2 takes)  (bl) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In her second and probably final appearance before
a grand jury here, Monica Lewinsky offered more specifics Thursday
about her sexual relationship with President Clinton and the gifts
he gave her as prosecutors sought to draw distinctions between her
testimony and that of the president only three days ago, lawyers
close to the case said.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-and-one-half-hour session, prosecutors bore in
on the events that led Ms. Lewinsky to return gifts from the
president that had been subpoenaed in the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct lawsuit last December, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The events surrounding the gifts are potentially the most
serious for the president because prosecutors are seeking to
determine whether he instructed Ms. Lewinsky to turn the gifts over
to his secretary, Betty Currie, rather than give them to lawyers
for Mrs. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky testified Thursday that she told Clinton last
December that the Jones subpoena demanded gifts he had given her, a
lawyer familiar with her account said. The president told her that
she could not turn over the gifts if they were not in her
possession, Ms. Lewinsky has told prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The day after her discussion with the president, Ms. Lewinsky
received a phone call from Ms. Currie, who told her, ``I hear you
have something for me,'' Ms. Lewinsky told the grand jury Thursday,
lawyers familiar with her account said. Ms. Lewinsky said that she
just assumed that Ms. Currie was referring to the gifts, the
lawyers said. Later that day, Ms. Currie went to Ms. Lewinsky's
apartment to retrieve the gifts, the lawyers said in their account
of her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But this account differs in some respects from Clinton's
testimony last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the prosecutors that he told Ms. Lewinsky in
December 1997 that she had no choice but to turn over gifts he had
given her to Mrs. Jones' lawyers, lawyers familiar with his
testimony said. When asked about the role of Ms. Currie, he said he
could not recall telling her to call Ms. Lewinsky about the gifts,
the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are also investigating whether Clinton kept some of
the gifts given to him by Ms. Lewinsky that had been subpoenaed by
lawyers in the Jones case, lawyers close to the case said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky offered more specifics of her sexual encounters
with the president than she gave in her testimony two weeks ago,
her friends and associates said. The specifics of their physical
contacts are also central to the prosecutors' case as they try to
determine whether Clinton committed perjury in a deposition in the
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, these people said, told the panel that he
intimately caressed her breasts and touched her genitals during
several encounters inside the White House. Her account was far more
detailed than the president's testimony Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Before he began Monday, Clinton admitted to the grand jury in a
statement supplied by his lawyers that he had had ``inappropriate
intimate physical contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky in the White House.
But the president repeatedly declined to discuss specific sexual
acts with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   As prosecutors continue to try to determine whether Clinton lied
in his January deposition in the Jones case, lawyers on both sides
continue to wrangle over what constitutes sexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Monday, Clinton argued that the type of
relationship he had with Ms. Lewinsky did not meet the definition
of sex used by Mrs. Jones' lawyers, lawyers close to the case said.
Three lawyers said he was implying that he had oral sex with Ms.
Lewinsky without testifying to that directly.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors are expected to argue that the acts described by
Ms. Lewinsky on Thursday fall within the definition of ``sexual
relations'' used by Mrs. Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the testimony, prosecutors have obtained a sample of
Clinton's genetic material to determine whether it matches a semen
stain on a dress Ms. Lewinsky turned over to prosecutors, lawyers
close to the investigation said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI crime laboratory has determined that the stain on the
blue dress was semen, two officials briefed on the results said
Thursday. If the DNA in that stain matches the DNA sample from the
president, prosecutors would have forensic proof that the
president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky was sexual.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to the president said tonight that the DNA sample was
requested from Clinton last Friday and provided over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with Clinton's testimony Monday said
prosecutors asked him questions about the dress. Prosecutors
apparently considered it important to obtain forensic proof of the
relationship as well, perhaps anticipating that Clinton would
likely maintain that his contacts with Ms. Lewinsky did not fit the
definition in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's testimony Monday, prosecutors also asked the
president if he deliberately wore a necktie, given to him by Ms.
Lewinsky, during a Rose Garden appearance Aug. 6, the day Ms.
Lewinsky first testified before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he did not believe the gold and royal blue tie had
been a gift from her. He was then informed she had testified she
gave it to him, and the prosecutors asked if he had worn it that
day as some kind of a ``signal'' to her, perhaps to influence her
testimony. Clinton said again he could not remember if the tie came
from her. But he insisted that he had no intention of sending Ms.
Lewinsky any kind of message that day.
</P>
<P>
   The former White House intern, stone-faced and businesslike,
said nothing to reporters this morning as she climbed out of a
Toyota Land Cruiser and walked briskly into a side entrance of the
federal courthouse in Washington, ignoring a reporter's question
about whether Clinton should apologize to her. Friends have said
Ms. Lewinsky was deeply hurt by Clinton's address to the nation
Monday, especially since he did not apologize to her in it and
because she thought he was dismissive of their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Lewinsky's appearance drew a crowd of tourists and
gawkers, it was not as intensively covered by the news media as
when she first testified before the grand jury two weeks ago. But
her testimony was crucial as prosecutors search for discrepancies
between her account and the president's.
</P>
<P>
   She emerged from the courthouse just before 2 p.m., wearing dark
sunglasses, leaving her spokeswoman, Judy Smith, to meet with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She answered all questions truthfully and completely,'' Ms.
Smith said. ``It is our expectation that today's appearance
concludes her grand jury testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, Ms. Smith added, ``is now looking forward to
beginning the process of rebuilding her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, 25, had agreed to answer questions in exchange for
immunity from prosecution. In a deal worked out with prosecutors,
she is vulnerable to prosecution only if she lies in her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Whitewater Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, spoke out Thursday
for the first time since Clinton accused him in a nationwide
address Monday of needlessly prying into his private life.
Responding to reporters' questions in Little Rock, Ark., Starr
would not say whether he felt vindicated by the president's
admission that he misled the American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is one of law, gathering facts and assessing them
and making professional judgments, as it should be,'' Starr said.
``A legal process should above all be aimed at achieving and
vindicating the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the legal maneuvering, debate has intensified at the
White House over the political fallout from the Lewinsky matter.
Many of the president's political advisers have complained that the
president was not properly apologetic in his nationwide address
Monday, and that his tone prompted harsh responses from Democrats
and Republicans alike.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers have also complained that Clinton's lawyers have
been uncooperative and that they had wrongly assured them early
this year that Clinton's defense did not rely on specific
definitions of sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an effort to unite the legal and political teams,
David Kendall, Clinton's private lawyer, met Wednesday evening with
political advisers including deputy chief of staff John Podesta,
White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also said that in discussions that took place
before American cruise missiles struck targets in Afghanistan and
Sudan, aides also weighed whether Clinton should agree to a major
interview or another public appearance to tamp down criticism of
his speech Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who has had many run-ins with the
White House related to the Starr investigation, Thursday reaffirmed
her confidence in Clinton as the leader of the administration. ``In
all my dealings with the president, he has been to me a person
dedicated to the issues of government,'' she said in response to a
reporter's question.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, White House officials did their best to play down Ms.
Lewinsky's testimony. ``I don't think that the president or the
White House has been particularly following her business today,''
said White House press secretary Mike McCurry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
