<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MCGWIRE-NYT </SLUG>
   MCGWIRE MAKES FANS MANEUVER AT SHEA  
(Eds: See also BBN-METS-MCGWIRE, BBN-METS-CARDS) 
(mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hopeful fans began stationing themselves in the
suddenly precious seats in the left-field loge section and the even
more precious perches in the picnic area in left center field more
than one hour before Mark McGwire was scheduled to take batting
practice at Shea Stadium Thursday. They arrived early because
finding a seat at Shea from which to corral one of McGwire's homers
is almost as difficult as sneaking into the bullpen for an inning.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Shea has a capacity of 55,775, only a fraction of
those seats are in fair territory behind the fences, so that made
those areas especially desirable for the spectators who attended
Thursday's doubleheader and who wanted a piece of history.
Normally, the sections next to left field and the picnic area are
empty for batting practice. Thursday, they were filled with fans
who then stood on their toes when McGwire batted against Willie
Blair in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some time, we have had people asking for seats in fair
territory on all levels,'' said Bill Ianniciello, vice president of
ticket sales and services. ``The phones have been very busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it McGwire mania. The man who has 51 homers _ connecting
off Blair in the opener and off Rick Reed in the second game in his
pursuit of Roger Maris' 37-year-old record of 61 homers in a season
_ is a bigger attraction than Beanie Babies and a team pushing for
a wild-card spot, at least in Flushing. Ianniciello said the
doubleheaders Thursday and Friday were expected to attract around
40,000 fans apiece and outdraw Saturday's game with the Arizona
Diamondbacks, in which the Mets are giving away a Beanie Baby named
Curly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three games have been selling comparably,'' Ianniciello
said. ``But, for the last three or four days, Thursday and Friday
have been outselling Saturday. As the games have gotten closer,
it's been McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   All McGwire, all the time. He was cheered when he signed about
100 autographs along the left-field line, cheered before he struck
out against Blair in the first and cheered when he gave his broken
bat to a young girl after lining out in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine was asked whether he would rather watch
a team pursuing a wild-card spot or watch McGwire hammer homers if
he were a fan. He offered an answer that would make a politician
gleam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd watch the Mets,'' Valentine said. ``When it got to
59, I'd go watch the Cards.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reason the Mets even discussed the slim possibility of a
sellout Thursday was McGwire's chase. Ianniciello admitted it and
Valentine conceded that the people who came probably wanted McGwire
to blast two homers and wanted the Mets to sweep. ``I think, for
the majority of the fans, that would be a perfect day for them,''
Valentine said before McGwire hit one and the Cardinals won, 2-0,
in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect day for a fan would include catching a McGwire homer,
which, once again, is not easy at Shea. Ianniciello said there are
about 1,300 seats in left, 1,300 seats in right field and another
600 seats in the picnic area that are in fair territory where a fan
could catch a possible homer.
</P>
<P>
   But there are far fewer fans who actually have a legitimate
chance for a home run ball because McGwire is unlikely to hit one
to right. He is unlikely to pound a ball into the upper deck, since
the Mets' Tommie Agee is the only player to have hit one there, and
the ball would need a compass and a map to reach half the seats in
the mezzanine and loge sections in left.
</P>
<P>
   The best place for camping under one of McGwire's homers at Shea
is the picnic area, which is usually available only for group
sales. But the Mets had groups who returned more than 200 tickets,
so the team offered them for sale and Ianniciello said most of them
were immediately scooped up. ``The picnic area would be my choice
to catch a ball,'' Ianniciello said.
</P>
<P>
   That was the perfect choice. McGwire lifted a 2-1 pitch off
Blair into the first row of the picnic area in the seventh for his
50th of the season. A fan in a T-shirt caught it, had it pop out of
his hands and then fought others to caress it to his chest. In the
first inning of the second game, McGwire homered into the loge
seats in left.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, after Mike Piazza whacked some long homers
in batting practice, McGwire, who was stretching beside the batting
cage, teasingly asked him, ``Can you give me a tip or what?'' It
caused Piazza, who ignored the cheering fans, to smile and imitate
McGwire's stance. McGwire laughed and then showed why no one can
really imitate him.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire clubbed two into the picnic area, hit four straight
homers at one point and finished the session with eight. As McGwire
was escorted to the third-base dugout after his show before the big
show, he softly flipped a baseball into the stands and watched the
fans turn into rugby players to scuffle for it. It was not a
McGwire home run ball. One of those came seven innings later and
another came early in the second game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
