<HEADLINE>
ELECTRIC SYSTEM LICENSED TO SCHWINN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Small, young Currie Technologies Inc. has given
bicycle giant Schwinn the power to pedal into the emerging market
for electric bikes.
</P>
<P>
   Currie, co-founded about two years ago by former Hughes Aircraft
Chief Executive Officer Malcolm Currie, has signed a licensing
agreement granting the Boulder, Colo.-based bicycle maker exclusive
use of its propulsion module system.
</P>
<P>
   The technology gives an otherwise ordinary bike a burst of power
with the flick of a thumb control and comes in handy, say, on one
of those pesky hills that can sap the energy of even the hardiest
cyclist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bike first, an electric bike second, and it gives you
all the power you need,'' said Richard Mayer, the company's
co-founder and executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Schwinn Cycling &AMP; Fitness had been looking for just the right
technology to propel it into the electric bike market, said Gregg
Bagni, vice president of marketing for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be our very first electric bicycle,'' Bagni said.
``The way we look at it is we now have access to what we think is
the most innovative ... electric bicycle on the market today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagni isn't the only one enthusiastic about the marriage between
Currie and Schwinn.
</P>
<P>
   This team could be the one to charge up the market for electric
bicycles in the United States, said Gary Coffrin, owner of San
Jose, Calif.-based Coffrin Group, which provides industry research
and consulting services to bicycle manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Electric bikes _ which emerged in Japan in 1994 _ are becoming
increasingly popular in some countries overseas, but have barely
rolled into the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 253,000 of the total 8 million bicycles sold in
Japan last year were electric bikes, he said. In the United States,
by contrast, only 8,000 electric models were sold out of 11.5
million bikes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And in Europe, just two or so years ago there were no
manufacturers or suppliers of electric bikes, Coffrin said. Now
there are 64.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the electric bikes produced overseas that derive their
energy through pedal power, Coffrin said, Currie's technology
depends on a throttle that, flicked on, provides the bike with the
power the rider wants when he or she wants it.
</P>
<P>
   That makes the bike more versatile, and potentially more
attractive to consumers _ particularly the 76 million aging baby
boomers who are likeliest to buy the bike, and who grew up in an
era when Schwinn was synonymous with bikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could speed up America's acceptance for the electric bike,
and the visibility of the electric bike, by a solid year or two,''
Coffrin said about the team. ``The reason I believe that is that of
all the names you can put on the product to appeal to the aging
boomers, the number one name, I believe, by far is Schwinn.''
</P>
<P>
   Currie had already been selling another version of its
technology, the U.S. Pro-Drive electric bike, through independent
dealers and Sports Chalet, Currie Vice President Jack Pentlarge
said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the current Pro-Drive inventory is depleted, other bikes
produced by the company will carry the Schwinn name, Mayer said.
Currie and its dozen or so employees will remain in Van Nuys, a Los
Angeles suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schwinn will have a technologically advanced propulsion
system,'' he said. ``It is exclusive to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Currie has come up with a system that answers
most of the objections that have been raised'' about electric
bikes, Schwinn Chief Executive Officer Tom Mason said, pointing out
that Currie's system is lightweight, operates in all weather and
can be easily serviced at bike shops.
</P>
<P>
   Under the licensing agreement, Schwinn will essentially be
funding Currie, Mason said. ``We can turn that to an equity stake
in the future, if we wish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schwinn plans to showcase the bike at the Interbike Trade Show
in Las Vegas on Sept. 11, according to Bagni. The bikes should be
on the market around year's end and sell for about $900. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
