<HEADLINE>
LOPEZ FORMIDABLE, EVEN TO TOP FIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ In boxing there are lists of the top boxers
and lists of the boxers the top boxers will not fight. Among
welterweights, Jose Luis Lopez, ranked No. 2 by the World Boxing
Association, is at the top of both lists.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar De La Hoya, the World Boxing Council welterweight
champion, said that Lopez is the fighter he would least like to
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a logical way of thinking,'' Lopez said after a workout
at Marciano's Gym here Wednesday afternoon. ``He knows I am one of
the toughest opponents he will face and I will beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   He added later: ``No one has really punched him the way he needs
to be punched. No one has put the pressure on him the way he needs
to be pressured. No one has fought him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez (41-3-2 with 32 knockouts) does not lack confidence, but
with two nuclear warheads at the end of both arms, he should not.
Lopez will meet Ed Goins on the undercard of the Arturo Gatti-Ivan
Robinson show at Bally's Park Place in Atlantic City on Saturday
night as part of HBO's Boxing After Dark series. Fernando Vargas,
the brilliant young junior middleweight, will fight Darren
Maciunski on the same card.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said he does not know anything about Goins, and that is
one thing that veteran trainer Lou Duva likes about Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only fighter I've handled who doesn't care who he's
fighting,'' said Duva, who co-manages Lopez. ``He'll fight anybody,
whether it's De La Hoya or Trinidad.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez put Ike Quartey on the canvas twice during their world
championship bout last Oct. 17 at Foxwoods Casino in Connecticut,
and fought to a 12-round draw. He calls it a wasted opportunity.
Two months later at Foxwoods, Lopez scored a five-round TKO against
Ronnie Johnson, but tested positive for marijuana. In his next
fight, on May 9 in Sacramento, he scored a second-round TKO over
Sammy Fuentes.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez presented a piece of paper with Spanish writing, showing
that he was clean during a test for marijuana that was conducted at
a lab in California on Aug. 14. Lopez said he is voluntarily taking
the test to show his promoters, Main Event, that he is clean and is
giving his all to win a championship.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hamed Has New Opponent &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prince Naseem Hamed and his London-based promoter, Frank Warren,
have ditched Kennedy McKinney as the opponent for Hamed's Oct. 31
bout in Las Vegas, Nev. Wayne McCullough, a native of Belfast,
Northern Ireland, who lives in Las Vegas, has replaced McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   It's a raw deal for McKinney, who has been waiting for eight
months through on-and-off negotiations and delays to fight Hamed.
The July 18 bout between the two was postponed, because Hamed was
said to have hurt his hand in training. But many believe he put off
the fight because he wanted to spend time with his new baby.
McKinney was to earn $750,000 for the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prince is scared of Kennedy McKinney or Frank Warren is
the worst individual I've met in this game,'' said Murad Muhammad,
McKinney's promoter. ``It's got to be one or the other. I can't put
any intelligence to anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the match is a strange move considering that Hamed's
stated reason for fighting here was to face America's best
featherweights. A bout between Hamed of Sheffield, England, and
McCullough, who won a silver medal in the 1992 Olympics, in London
or Dublin would have been a major box office draw in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quartey Loses Title &LR;   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ike Quartey's headaches got worse Wednesday. The World Boxing
Association stripped him of his welterweight title, because he
could not make his mandatory defense against No. 1 contender Andrei
Pestriaev of Russia. Quartey of Accra, Ghana, was supposed to fight
Pestriaev Thursday, but pulled out of the fight because malaria was
diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   A vacant title could open the way for Pestriaev and Jose Luis
Lopez, the No. 2 contender, to fight for the championship. Quartey
has a Nov. 14 date with Felix Trinidad, the International Boxing
Federation champion. If it does not come off, it won't be because
Quartey doesn't have his title. It will be because a Federal judge
in Manhattan would not grant Trinidad an injunction against the
promoter Don King.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad and King are involved in a legal wrangle over the
validity of Trinidad's contract with the promoter. Trinidad
recently signed a contract with Main Event as his promoters and
with HBO.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
