<HEADLINE>
COLLECTOR MARKET GETS A HIGH-PROFILE LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (See also CARS-SAFETY) 
(js) 
 By KEITH MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEREY, Calif. _ The stock market may be gyrating, but the
classic car market is rocking and rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Each August, the eyes and wallets of the collector car world are
focused on the Monterey Peninsula in California. Over three days
there is a whirl of car activities, including the historic races at
Laguna Seca Raceway (where Porsche was the featured marque this
year), the Concours at Pebble Beach (which featured the
long-defunct Belgian manufacturer Minerva) and a series of
collector car auctions that set the tone for the vintage market for
the rest of the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the two companies that held auctions here, Rick Cole
Auction Co. and Christie's, sold 176 cars between them for a total
of $14 million. This year, the auction landscape was altered by the
sale of one company when Rick Cole was bought by Rob Myers' RM
Productions of Toronto and became the Monterey Sports Car Auction,
and the entrance of another when Robert Brooks, a British auction
house, made its U.S. debut. Market watchers worried that the
continuing collapse of Japan's vintage car market would depress
sales; others felt that with the uncertainty surrounding the stock
market, some big collectors might not buy. All were concerned that
Brooks' entry into the already crowded weekend would dilute sales
for everyone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the last hammer had fallen on Sunday night at
the Christie's sale, the market had gathered new steam. The three
auctions sold a total of 253 cars for nearly $30.5 million _ more
than double the amount a year earlier. The average price per car
jumped to $120,000, from $79,500.
</P>
<P>
   At all three auctions, it was the big-ticket cars that broke
sales records, while prices of regular production cars remained
within the expected price ranges. Each auction company had its
star. For Brooks, it was a 1908 French-built Mors Grand Prix
two-seater with a 775-cubic-inch engine _ equivalent to
one-and-a-half Dodge Viper motors. One of the earliest surviving
Grand Prix cars, it sold for $690,000 including buyer's commission,
nearly $300,000 above the low end of the pre-auction estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The Monterey Sports Car Auction had two spectacular racing
Jaguars. A 1959 D-type, one of 77 built, sold for $952,300. An
unrestored 1963 factory-built lightweight XKE competition roadster,
one of 16, brought a monumental $872,000, nearly $300,000 above the
low end of the estimates and a testimony to the appeal of original,
unrestored cars. The XKE had covered just 2,600 miles since it was
made and was discovered in a garage after 35 years of storage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christie's had three show-stoppers. The first was a somewhat
mundane 1989 Jaguar XJ-S V12 coupe, in excellent condition and
driven fewer than 10,000 miles, that had been owned by Frank
Sinatra. Estimated to sell at $10,000 to $15,000, the final price
including commission was an astounding $178,500. Another Jaguar, a
rare 1957 XKSS roadster, was one of only 18 made. It had been
driven fewer than 12,000 miles, and the auction catalog asserted
that it still had the original, 1957 air in the tires. In
extraordinary unrestored condition, having been stored since 1967,
it brought $1,014,500 _ $300,000 above the low estimate.
</P>
<P>
   A 1967 Ferrari 275 GTS/4 NART Spyder brought Christie's the
weekend's top price, $2,092,500. But the loudest cheers in the
auction tent were reserved for the buyer of a striking 1935 Alfa
Romeo 8C-35 Grand Prix car. Painstakingly restored, though not
completely original, it went for $1,322,500, some $300,000 above
the low estimate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
