<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PILOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERING EXITS FOR SAMPRAS AND RAFTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (smw) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Tennis icons do not usually have to deal with
heckling, but there was plenty of it on the stadium court Thursday
at the Pilot Pen International. Faithful fans who had waited a
decade for Pete Sampras to make a second appearance at this
beleaguered event watched in indignation as the top-seeded player
came to a virtual standstill instead of standing up to the spoiler,
100th-ranked Leander Paes of India.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more vocal spectators harangued Sampras to at least
make a pretense of caring about his performance, earning a
condemnatory stare from the player. Others booed Sampras when he
left the court after displaying little resistance during the 6-3,
6-4 throttling he received. Sampras said he did not lose the match
intentionally, but admitted he did not even begin to rise to the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't the player that I am usually out there,'' said
Sampras, who has not won any of the three hardcourt events he
entered this summer to prepare for the United States Open, which
begins Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the swan song of Sampras, whose passivity prompted
suspicion about his motivation, second-seeded Patrick Rafter's exit
on the overcrowded grandstand court prompted compassion rather than
catcalls. A fan favorite here, where he was runner-up to Yevgeny
Kafelnikov last year, Rafter was apologetic after he and his
career-best 11-match winning streak ran out of steam, flummoxed,
7-6 (10-8), 6-3, by the clever returns and passing shots of
48th-ranked Guillaume Raoux of France.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to lose sometime, so there's no use crying about
it,'' said Rafter, ``but I tried everything and he came up with
every answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to panic because I wasn't making any inroads on his
serve; when I was coming in he was hurting me, and when I stayed
back he was hurting me,'' said Rafter, whose zinc oxide mask had
melted away from the prolonged heat of the moment even before Raoux
ended the excruciating first-set tie breaker with a cruel backhand
drop volley on his fourth set point.
</P>
<P>
   So each in his own way, and with a very different reception from
the crowd, the two titans now chasing Marcelo Rios and his No. 1
ranking, Sampras the Wimbledon champion and Rafter the Unites
States Open champion, found themselves chased out of the third
round by a pair of pretenders who were rewarded for having humbler
goals: Paes and Raoux simply wanted to make it to the
quarterfinals, and did.
</P>
<P>
   Raoux knew that what constituted dream victories for Paes and
himself represented a box office nightmare to Butch Buchholz, the
tournament director. ``To the tournament director, I'm sorry, and
Leander's sorry; tell him I have some pills if he's afraid of not
sleeping tonight,'' Raoux joked.
</P>
<P>
   Buchholz, who rescued this event from limbo and hopes to
transform it into a coed blockbuster in the image of his Lipton
Championships at Key Biscayne, Fla., was sufficiently rattled by
the day's twin upsets to hold a brief news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Besides denying that the loss of Sampras and Rafter would
cripple the tournament, Buchholz took pains to deny the rumor that
he and the rest of the Pilot Pen's organizers were furious at
Sampras for surrendering without a serious fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete tried; I don't think Pete tanked,'' said Buchholz, who
was instrumental in persuading Sampras to play here instead of
Indianapolis. ``After all, you do have bad hair days.''
</P>
<P>
   But Buchholz was hard pressed to expand his defense of Sampras,
the 11-time Grand Slam champion who is chasing Roy Emerson's record
of 12.
</P>
<P>
   Buchholz instead took a realistic view of what transpired.
``Pete's in a stage right now where, well, at 21 or 22 you might
dig a little deeper,'' he said, ``but today he's on a quest to
pass, or to catch, Emerson, and probably doesn't have the same
intensity he might have had here at 21, 22.''
</P>
<P>
   Paes, whose only career title came this year on the grass at
Newport, had to survive last weekend's qualifying to earn a berth
in this event.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people pay good money to see me play, and they expect to
see me win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm playing well it looks like I'm a genius, and when I'm
not, I'm tanking.''  &QL; 
MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov defeated 11th-seeded Gustavo
Kuerten, 6-4, 6-4, fourth-seeded Richard Krajicek crushed Harel
Levy, 6-2, 6-4, and Goran Ivanisevic, who later chastised the
linesmen for being ``too old'' to see the ball, dismissed Nicolas
Kiefer, 6-3, 7-5. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-20-98 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
