<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SPLIT DOUBLEHEADER WITH CARDS AND MCGWIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark McGwire was the main attraction on a glorious
baseball stage in New York Thursday night and was expected to
perform like some sort of home run-hitting robot. Push a button,
then watch him swing his bat and blast another homer. And, oddly
enough, McGwire somehow made it look that simple against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire pounded two more homers for his 50th and 51st of the
season as the Cardinals grabbed the first game, 2-0, before
succumbing to the Mets, 5-4, in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone who bought a ticket to Shea Stadium wanted
to see McGwire go deep and see history, and that they did.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire exhibited a rare display of emotion following his first
homer of the day, off Willie Blair in the opener, as he became the
first player in major league history to drill 50 homers in three
straight seasons, eclipsing Babe Ruth's record of two straight
seasons, which Ruth accomplished twice.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire pumped his fist twice, clapped his hands twice and
shouted something to himself as he rounded the bases and received a
rousing ovation from the enemy-turned-envious fans.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire was more subdued when he homered off Rick Reed in
the second game, the red-headed superstar with the tight end's
frame continued to add to the notion that he will surpass Roger
Maris' 37-year-old record of 61 homers in a season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire had said the chase would become serious if a player
reached 50 by Sept. 1. He has hit 51 with 11 days to spare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamt of being in this position,'' McGwire said
before smashing the two homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dreamt about being a big leaguer,'' he added. ``Things
happen for a reason. Hard work pays off.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire uncorked his powerful swing off Blair's 2-1 slider in
the seventh inning of the opener and gazed toward left field as the
ball soared in that direction. There were more than 40,000 pairs of
eyes gazing into the blue sky with McGwire, but his eyes were the
most expressive. He could not stop looking at the ball. No one
could as it landed 369 feet away in the left-field picnic area.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's historic homer followed Brian Jordan's homer and
helped St. Louis roll in the first game, which turned into a
footnote. Even the fans who were hoping the Mets could maintain or
improve their one-half game lead over the Chicago Cubs for the
wild-card playoff spot stood and cheered as McGwire retreated to
the dugout. He peered at the fans and waved.
</P>
<P>
   It obviously bothered manager Bobby Valentine that the fans
treated McGwire as if he had ``NY'' on his cap, but the Mets
regained some support in the second game by erasing a 4-1 deficit
with two runs in the fourth on Mike Piazza's 464-foot homer and two
more in the seventh on Rey Ordonez's run-scoring double and Tony
Phillips' RBI groundout. The Mets made sure the night was not all
about McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis first baseman ignored the growing attention,
scoffed at the mounting pressure and did exactly what virtually
everyone in Flushing wanted him to do by plastering his 50th. It is
hard enough to hit a round ball 400 feet with a round bat, and it
should be even harder when everyone is expecting it. But McGwire
made it a night to remember for his newfound friends by injecting
his 51st for those among the crowd of 45,308 who were tardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hits his 50th homer, that would be a good memory in 20
years,'' Valentine said before the contest. ``That would be a
cherished memory, rather than I was at a doubleheader when the Mets
did whatever we do tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words were uttered before Shea became Busch Stadium East.
It was respectful to applaud McGwire, but the first setback dropped
the Mets into a tie with the Cubs and the reaction disappointed
Valentine. When he was asked about the fans cheering an opponent,
Valentine said, ``I don't have any comment on that,'' with an
expression that said much more.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, who was impressive in allowing two runs and three hits in
his first Mets start, was not upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the first player to ever hit 50 in three straight
years,'' Blair said. ``It's a great feat. He deserves it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who was one for 15 with nine strikeouts off Blair
before the homer, said that it is uncomfortable when everyone in
the world is watching him, but he handled the attention with aplomb
by carrying his own marker to sign autographs and then supplying
the highlight everyone hoped for. Donovan Osborne no-hit the Mets
for five and one-third innings and finished with a four-hitter
through eighth innings, and his results were superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   With McGwire unavailable to reporters between games, the
Cardinals released a statement in which he said: ``It's nice to be
part of major league history and to have done so in such a historic
baseball city as New York. I broke Babe Ruth's record just across
town from the stadium he played in.''
</P>
<P>
   Then McGwire accentuated it by pummeling Reed's 3-2 pitch into
the left-field screen in the first inning of the second game, a
385-foot shot. McGwire whiffed for the third time this year against
Turk Wendell with the Cardinals down by a run in the eighth, but it
was still an unforgettable night in his robot-like pursuit of
Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like him to do it,'' Blair said. ``If anybody does it, I'd
like to see him do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
