<HEADLINE>
SOCCER'S RISE MARKS ROTHERNBERG'S REIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Truth be known, Alan Rothenberg was thrust upon a U.S. Soccer
Federation that didn't know him, didn't want him and had no say in
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later his imprint on American soccer is indelible,
his presence towering over the sport, his fingerprints on
everything that has gone toward the tremendous growth it has
enjoyed here during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic and incisive, Rothenberg whose presidency ends this
weekend has guided U.S. Soccer, and through it the sport as a
whole, through a renaissance that created a landscape not thought
possible in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Without him, none of it would have been.
</P>
<P>
   When Rothenberg took charge of USSF, it was a mom-and-pop-styled
organization working with a $3 million budget and about a
half-dozen full-time employees. It had limited power, fewer
resources, no place within America's sporting culture ... and the
right to put on the 1994 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg, it turned out, was part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Criticized worldwide for its 1988 decision to award the Cup to
the United States and more than a little fearful of the
consequences, FIFA the world's governing body for soccer
hand-picked the Beverly Hills attorney, with whose handling of the
1984 Olympic soccer tournament it had been impressed, and gave the
federation a mandate: Make Rothenberg your president, or we'll take
away the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The choice wasn't simple Rothenberg was derided as a
``carpetbagger'' within the fiercely provincial soccer community
but it was easy, and the payoff has been immense:
</P>
<P>
   --The 1994 World Cup, which brought the sport into the American
conscious, demonstrated to the world that we were ready to play
(ITAL) its (ITAL) games, paved the way for a professional league,
and made a cool $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. Soccer's growth from an inconsequential group into a huge
organization with a $38 million budget, hundreds of employees, a
nine-figure Nike deal, an expansive television contract, successful
national teams (playing before big crowds in big stadiums), a
relationship with the disenfranchised ethnic communities and plans
to create a developmental program designed to win a World Cup in
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   --Major League Soccer, which provides plenty of jobs for
American soccer players, plenty of soccer for American fans and
lots of exposure for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   --The U.S. Soccer Foundation, which dispenses the capital off
the '94 Cup money to develop the sport in America, funding programs
to build fields, take the game to inner cities and making better
players, coaches and referees.
</P>
<P>
   --The Women's World Cup coming to these shores next summer which
wants to do for women's soccer what the '94 Cup did for soccer in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he's brought key people USSF Secretary General
Hank Steinbrecher, former national team coach Bora Milutinovic, MLS
Deputy Commissioner Sunil Gulati and national teams general manager
Tom King into the American game and created a model, certain to be
followed, for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was elected, my plan was to do five things,'' said
Rothenberg, 59, who is in Hawaii for U.S. Soccer's Annual General
Meeting and Saturday's election. ``Professionalize the federation,
bring some unity to the disparate forces in (American) soccer,
build the national teams program, put on a successful World Cup,
and start a professional league. We accomplished all of them, and
we did all of them well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan is certainly a charismatic guy,'' Steinbrecher told
Soccer America. ``I think whoever the new president will be will
have very, very big shoes to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg's influence will continue to be felt. He remains on
U.S. Soccer's executive board and on the foundation board and
chairs its marketing board, he's a CONCACAF vice president, is
chairman of the Women's World Cup organizing committee and is
expected to play some role in new FIFA president Sepp Blatter's
organization. He also heads a group that paid $25 million for MLS's
San Jose Clash.
</P>
<P>
   There also is talk that Rothenberg would retain the real power
should Dr. Robert Contiguglia, a Denver kidney specialist, be
elected president on Saturday he's running against retired
D.C.-area lawyer Larry Monaco; Rothenberg has endorsed Contiguglia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't intend to leave the sport,'' Rothenberg says. ``I'll
be very active, but I won't be the guy who has to do it day in and
day out. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, (ITAL) never (ITAL) realized what I was getting into.
I had no idea what was in store. Only half-jokingly I've said if I
had known the amount of work involved, I probably wouldn't have
run. I'm glad I didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``These have been exciting times and I'm proud to have been
apart of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
